<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
This acquaintance most pleasurable
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Dale Robertson
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Overwhelming? Not quite. Overpowering? On a number
of occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Overjoyed? Actually, the thin man himself wasn't. But his
awestruck new teammates had every reason to be.
</P>
<P>
   Unit-ed stood the Astros behind the most exciting acquisition
made by Houston's long-thwarted baseball franchise since Nolan Ryan
came home. On a glorious Sunday afternoon in Pittsburgh, where our
town's favorite memories had been of epic Oilers-Steelers
confrontations, the Randy Johnson mini-era began exactly as it
should have.
</P>
<P>
   With a called strike, 94 mph, to Kevin Polcovich. A `W' followed
ultimately, with lots of K's and grand promise for _ finally _ a
happy ending in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``A special day,'' Jeff Bagwell called it, admitting he couldn't
fully believe Johnson, the most dominant pitcher in the game as
recently as about this time last year, was a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were so enthralled by the erstwhile Mariner, their
would-be World Series lottery ticket, their hoped-for means to the
end of a nearly four-decade stay in purgatory, they almost forgot
to do what they do best, which is hit.
</P>
<P>
   It's Astros bats, after all, that made going after Johnson, the
scraggly-haired, fierce-eyed 6-10 lefthander who has posted numbers
that are Koufax-esque, well worth the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the guys might have been trying a little too hard to
impress him,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``Everybody really
wanted to give Randy some support today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, 6-2 winners, scored five of their runs following
Johnson's 116th and last pitch, an 84 mph sinker that Jason Kendall
popped up to Bill Spiers near third base to end the seventh inning.
Kendall wound up being the only Pirate the Big Unit _ Mister Big
Unit to you _ didn't whiff en route to his 12-strikeout, six-hit
victory. It was a masterful debut, considering how his life was
torn asunder over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A towering fixture in Seattle for most of 10 seasons, and maybe
a Mariners lifer if he hadn't scared them by needing spinal surgery
in 1996, he was traded to the Astros right before the waiver
deadline Friday night. Although he knew he was gone _ to somewhere
_ he didn't swallow the news well, and nobody was sure what his
frame of mind would be Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' Bagwell said. ``I didn't want to bother him,
because I know most pitchers would rather be left alone before they
pitch. But I thought I should at least go over to shake his hand
and say hello.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, for his part, kept his distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't find Randy,'' he said. ``He must have uncovered a
quiet spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Johnson surfaced in time to warm up, then promptly
showed the Pirates what quaking AL hitters have been suffering
through for years.
</P>
<P>
   He made only one inarguably bad decision all day, leaving an
intended 0-2 sinker in the fifth inning dangerously close to the
plate's fringe. Aramis Ramirez, his eyes as large as small meteors,
poked it over the left-field fence, albeit barely above the glove
of a leaping Moises Alou.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Johnson's strikeouts _ no Astro had fanned more in a
game all season _ were polished off with 97-98 mph heaters,
although his slider also began to baffle the Pirates in the sixth
inning, when he fanned the side after a first-pitch single by
Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   Three Pittsburgh hits came off first pitches as the young
Pirates, every one of them batting right, gamely dug in on
anticipated fastballs. Guesswork, that's all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give a good effort, and I feel I did,'' Johnson
said with discernible relief afterward, probably talking more in
one postgame gab session than he had over the entire previous month
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He practically couldn't stop talking. Clearly, a burden had been
lifted, now that his fate, short-term at least, had been
determined. First, with glistening eyes, he thanked his new
teammates and his old fans. Then he thanked his old teammates and
his new fans, saying he was eager to pitch in Houston, in domed
surroundings that will hardly feel foreign to him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson next starts against the Phillies either Friday or
Saturday night. Whichever date is agreed upon _ Dierker is leaning
toward using him in the series opener _ he solemnly promised to
pitch better than he did here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have very good command of my sinker,'' he said, ``and
my fastball was just so-so.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Brad Ausmus would admit his hand was no more raw than
when Billy Wagner, the Astros' diminutive flamethrower, is his
batterymate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with Randy,'' Ausmus said, ``the ball definitely comes in
from a higher place.''
</P>
<P>
   The catcher was, I assume, referring to the pitcher's physical
stature, not his spiritual presence. Either way, though, Johnson
does seem a godsend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
