<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: WARY LOOK AT LIFE WITHOUT PIAZZA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Piazza's life should be so much fun right now.
He is living every 11-year-old's dream as a major-league player, he
is being paid $8 million this season and he is healthy. It is
ludicrous to expect anyone who paid $1.50 for a subway token to
sympathize with Piazza when he is verbally trampled by fickle fans
and treated like Mel Rojas in a catcher's mask, as he was again
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When Piazza reported for work at Shea Stadium, he had the worn
look of a man who had to mow lawns for the next eight hours. He
never lifted his eyes when some fans behind the dugout screeched
his name. After batting practice, Piazza continued staring at the
dirt while fans pleaded for an autograph, a smile or a wave.
</P>
<P>
   Even General Manager Steve Phillips was basically given the
silent treatment by Piazza before the Mets cruised past the
Dodgers, 9-3. Sitting in the dugout with his two young sons,
Phillips asked Piazza how he had hit. Piazza gritted his teeth and
said ``good'' before vanishing into the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Get a close look at Piazza wearing those black Mets jerseys
because there are increasing indications that the marriage between
Piazza and the club will end after this season. Piazza is intent on
becoming a free agent and pursuing a $100 million contract, and
Phillips has expressed his doubt about having Piazza back in black.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have options behind the plate,'' Phillips said. ``Whether
we're able to work out Mike's deal or not, we have options.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a revealing statement from the cautious Phillips.
Usually, he is careful to avoid saying anything too substantial.
But there he was in the middle of the chase for a wild-card spot
admitting that Todd Hundley _ who is at least a month away from
placing his surgically repaired right elbow behind the plate _ and
Jorge Fabregas were candidates to replace Piazza in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing black sunglasses to fend off some television camera
lights Sunday, Piazza looked perturbed after going 1-for-4 with a
run batted in to finish the three-game series against his former
team with one infield single in 11 at-bats. He also continued in
his unfair role as the Met Most Likely to Be Booed, which will
surely influence his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm not even thinking about that,'' Piazza said. ``I have
a job to do. I'm going to play as hard as I possibly can.
Everything else, I'm not even thinking about next week, never mind
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the berating must have robbed some of baseball's fun from
Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they embrace me or not, they're entitled to that,'' Piazza
said. ``They pay for a ticket to get in. They can boo me or cheer
me. Unfortunately, it's part of the territory that we have to deal
with. I just hope that the big picture isn't lost, the fact that
we're playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is too savvy to utter something so intriguing about
Piazza without reason. He could be laying the groundwork for
lessening the sting if and when Piazza relocates to Anaheim, to
Boston, back to Los Angeles _ anywhere but Flushing. Since a person
close to the 29-year-old catcher has said it will not matter how
lavish an offer the Mets may make because Piazza wants to test free
agency, Phillips could say the Mets pushed for the postseason with
Piazza and have no control over his choices. It would be a weak
excuse, and those who booed Piazza will howl to get him back if
Fabregas starts next year. That could happen.
</P>
<P>
   By obtaining the left-handed-hitting Fabregas from Arizona, the
Mets have set up a safety net if Piazza departs and Hundley cannot
catch again. Why else would they want or need a left-handed-hitting
catcher who is signed for 1999 when Hundley, a switch-hitter, is
better from the left side?
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Piazza, who rejected a six-year, $84 million contract from the
Dodgers and then was traded to Florida in May, had a forgettable
weekend. He forgot to back up first base in the first inning
Sunday, and Rey Ordonez's wild throw rolled into the dugout,
leading to a run. He had a sacrifice fly in the first, but missed a
meaty 3-1 pitch before grounding out in the third. He swung at ball
four while striking out in the fifth, secured an 80-foot single in
the seventh and was booed after bouncing out to third in the
eighth. The Mets were leading, 9-1, and were poised to win for the
10th time in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips speculated that Piazza was ``trying too hard,'' but
Piazza disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have an excuse for it or anything,'' Piazza
said. ``I'm just going out and playing. I really think the whole
thing has been overdone, a little too much drama for me to worry
about that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   On what should have been a blissful day for Piazza, he did
notice an 8-year-old boy on crutches outside the clubhouse and
asked him, ``Do you want a bat?'' T.J. McGuinness happily accepted
Piazza's bat. About five minutes later, someone told Piazza that he
had made the boy's day and the Met did not even nod. Piazza just
walked away, which might prove to be a fitting metaphor for his
days with the Mets.
</P>
</TEXT>
