<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT JOHNSON, FIVE PITCHERS BEAT CONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Paul Spoljaric drew the unfortunate assignment of
replacing Randy Johnson in the Seattle rotation Sunday night,
circumstances that begged for inevitably unfavorable comparisons.
And Spoljaric had to pitch against the Yankees and David Cone, the
team and the pitcher, respectively, with the major leagues' best
record.
</P>
<P>
   But Spoljaric and four relievers limited the Yankees to nine
hits and won, 6-3, as Cone was done in by a series of bloop hits,
lapses on defense and one very bad pitch. The Yankees (77-28),
having won two of three games against the Mariners, move on to
Oakland to play the final four games of their West Coast road trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, trailing by three runs in the fourth inning,
crawled back to trail by 4-3. But Cone allowed a bloop double with
two outs in the seventh, after striking out both Ken Griffey Jr.
and Edgar Martinez. Even as Cone neared 120 pitches, his slider and
curveball were electric, and he had 11 strikeouts _ the sixth time
this season he had had 10 or more strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Jay Buhner, however, Cone hung a slider and Buhner
walloped it; Cone drew both hands up to his head and pulled off his
cap in frustration, turning away as the ball rocketed toward the
left-field stands. Then Cone (15-4) kicked at the dirt. It had not
been a good day.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the Yankees were to begin batting practice
Sunday, their hitting coach, Chris Chambliss, strolled purposefully
over to the wall where the lineup was posted, carefully stripped
away the white medical tape holding the cardboard sheet and
replaced the early lineup. Joe Girardi was out at catcher because
of back spasms, and Jorge Posada was in. It would not have been
particularly noteworthy except that Cone was pitching, and Girardi
always catches when Cone pitches. Posada and Cone had not worked
together in a regular-season game since May 18, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, too, was missing from the lineup, because the
left-handed Paul Spoljaric was Johnson's temporary replacement in
the Seattle rotation, and Martinez had always struggled against
Spoljaric. Shane Spencer, a right-handed-hitting rookie, who has
been an outfielder most of his career, made his major league debut
at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the ball seemed to seek out both Posada and Spencer
in the early innings. With a single and a walk separated by a
strikeout, Seattle rallied in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cone struck out Russ Davis on three consecutive sliders for the
second out of the inning. Catcher Joe Oliver, however, bounced a
hit through the left side of the infield. The ball quickly reached
a charging Chad Curtis, who executed his patented throw-and-roll in
an effort to cut down Edgar Martinez at home plate. Curtis' throw
reached the plate area well ahead of Martinez, but on a short hop,
and Posada could not hang on. Martinez's run tied the score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Alex Rodriguez poked a one-out double. Cone
threw a high fastball to Griffey, and Posada let it glance off his
glove. Cone _ often angry and animated when he pitches _ got
another baseball and walked back to the mound, mumbling to himself.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Griffey and walked Martinez, filling the bases. David
Segui hammered a low line drive directly at Spencer, who gloved the
ball at his midsection and then dropped it; all the runners were
frozen for an instant, and had Spencer thrown home, he would have
retired Rodriguez easily.
</P>
<P>
   But Spencer rose and threw to second for a forceout. Derek
Jeter's return was too late for a doubleplay, and a run scored.
Buhner hit a run-scoring single and Cone, not accustomed to losing,
was turning a fiery red. The Yankees trailed by 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Cone struck out the first two batters in the fourth inning,
before Joey Cora chopped a weak grounder toward shortstop. Jeter
charged and threw offbalance, the ball sinking in the dirt _ and
Spencer could not come up with the short hop.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez beat out another infield single, Griffey fought off an
inside pitch, looping it over second base, and Seattle had four
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Spoljaric, who has pitched in middle relief most of this season,
was replaced in the middle of the fifth inning when Mariners
Manager Lou Piniella began mixing and matching against the
right-handed and left-handed batters in the Yankees lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees still came up with a run in the fifth, however, on a
run-scoring double by Scott Brosius. Curtis hit a high and long
home run with one out in the seventh, cutting Seattle's lead to
4-3.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, who officially requested a trade from the Toronto
Blue Jays last week, reportedly said that the Yankees' principal
owner, George Steinbrenner, told his agents he would be willing to
extend Clemens' contract if the pitcher was traded to the Yankees.
Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said he was unaware of
any conversations between Steinbrenner and Clemens' agents, but did
say Toronto General Manager Gord Ash did give the Yankees
permission to speak to Clemens' agents before the July 31 trade
deadline. It's now unlikely the Yankees could discuss a trade for
Clemens until after the season, because Clemens would have to clear
waivers. Cashman intends to ask other club officials if there's
reason to have an interest in the free agent reliever Norm
Charlton, recently released by the Baltimore Orioles. ... Second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch had two hits in his last 29 at-bats, and
Yankees Manager Joe Torre, has talked to Knoblauch informally about
the high number of flyouts he has generated recently, since a burst
of home runs last month. Knoblauch's batting average is down to
.246, his lowest since May 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
