<SLUG> BC-NY-FIRE-HOMELESS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FIRE LEAVES MORE THAN 100 PEOPLE HOMELESS  (js) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 100 people were left at least temporarily
homeless Sunday after a fierce, smoky fire tore through an
apartment building in upper Manhattan, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire marshals labeled the fire suspicious, in part because of
the speed with which it engulfed the top floor of the six-story
building and burned through the roof of the structure. ``It was
deemed suspicious, and the cause is still being investigated,''
said James Spollen, a fire department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the fire had been brought under control at 6:30
a.m., 22 firefighters and five residents had suffered minor
injuries, mostly from smoke inhalation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 128 people _ including 17 children _ were forced from
their apartments by the fire, Robert Wingate, a spokesman for the
Red Cross, said. Many made plans Sunday to stay with relatives and
friends, but two busloads of people were sent to two local hotels
for emergency housing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Commissioner Thomas Von Essen, who visited the scene, said
that battling the blaze was made difficult by the age of the
building and the many layers of renovation that had been added over
the years. ``It was very difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wingate said the Red Cross would work with residents as the city
and the building's landlord decided whether the apartments would be
inhabitable again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
