<HEADLINE>
CONTRIBUTORS TO NYC POLITICAL CAMPAIGNS NOW LISTED ON THE
INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a milestone in the effort to inform the public
about the political process, the New York City Campaign Finance
Board unveiled a new feature Monday on its Internet site that
allows users to search a list of campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Web site can examine the names of donors and the
amount they gave to the campaigns of more than 175 candidates who
ran in the 1997 city elections, from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to
losing contenders for the city council. The records for candidates
who plan to seek office in the next city election, in 2001, are
also available at the site (www.cfb.nyc.ny.us).
</P>
<P>
   Since it was established in 1988, the board has required most
candidates who take part in the city's voluntary campaign finance
system to submit their disclosure records on computer disk. Members
of the public were then able to obtain copies of the records on
disk or view them at a terminal at the board's offices.
</P>
<P>
   But the board had not put the records on its Internet site. The
new feature includes information on the names, occupations and
employers of contributors, as provided by the campaigns. It also
includes the date when the donations were received.
</P>
<P>
   ``By visiting the board's Web site, the public can now follow
the money that funds New York City campaigns right from their own
homes, 24 hours a day,'' said the board's executive director,
Nicole Gordon. ``No other jurisdiction in the country offers all
the public disclosure resources that the Campaign Finance Board now
provides.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates in the city's campaign finance system obtain money
from the city treasury for their campaigns in return for agreeing
to limits on their fund-raising and spending, as well as increased
disclosure rules.
</P>
<P>
   The state does not disseminate information on computer for the
finances of campaigns for state offices. It plans to change that
after the November elections, when it begins a new disclosure
system that is supposed to be similar to the one in the city, with
information available at an Internet site.
</P>
</TEXT>
