A4647 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN     08-03 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI WINS MERCEDES-BENZ CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A Los Angeles TV announcer had just offered a
hearty welcome back to Andre Agassi after Sunday's Mercedes-Benz
Cup final, and Agassi responded in kind: ``Thanks, it's nice to be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about playing in L.A. But the world's one-time
No.1 player might just as well have been talking about his
re-emergence as a tennis power.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-seeded Agassi won his second consecutive tournament
title _ and fourth of the year _ with a 6-4, 6-4 defeat of No.2
seeded Tim Henman of England. After falling to as far as No.141
last November, Agassi is on the verge of breaking the top 10 for
the first time since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's win pushed Agassi to No.11. He's won 11 consecutive
matches and 23 sets without a loss. He hasn't faced set point at
any time during the streak.
</P>
<P>
   Nice to be back, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a tough climb, but Agassi is enjoying the ascent
without saying much about where this storied comeback is supposed
to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about getting anywhere,'' he said. ``I get a lot of
fulfillment and satisfaction out of the road back, so I don't want
to minimize the importance I put on just every day....
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy playing well, bringing entertainment, bringing a great
level of tennis to fans. All that is wonderful. But Grand Slam
titles is what you shoot for, what I shoot for. There's no feeling
like it. I want more of that, that's the pinnacle. But there's a
lot in between that's still left for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like breezing through ATP tour stops. Between now and the U.S.
Open, Agassi will continue a nonstop schedule of warm-ups, looking
to extend his streak in Toronto, Cincinnati and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's comeback train ran right through Henman, the
23-year-old Wimbledon semifinalist with a big serve. Clocked at up
to 142 mph this week, Henman's serve can be a killer. But Sunday it
killed only Henman, who committed seven double faults _ twice on
break point _ while chalking up eight aces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played OK. I don't think I played my best tennis,'' said
Henman, who could drop a spot from his No.12 ranking. ``But to beat
someone like Andre, you have to play to the top of your game. And
that never really happened for me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman seemed to lose his concentration at key moments,
including all three break points he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi broke Henman's serve twice in succession in the second
set, both on double faults. The second time was particularly
damaging, coming just after Henman had broken Agassi for the first
time. That gave Agassi a 4-3 edge as he took back the serve.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi also broke Henman in the third game of the first set,
when Henman smashed an Agassi lob into the net. Moments earlier,
Henman was rattled in mid-serve, by a ringing mobile phone in the
crowd of 7,027. That serve also ended in a double fault.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with the intensely focused Agassi, who had a serve
interrupted by a baby's loud coo late in the second set. He
promptly re-tossed and won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just felt the pressure of having to make some first
serves today, because I felt like I returned pretty solidly,''
Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   And so Agassi's big-picture return rolls on, gaining momentum
with every match added to a streak that shows no signs of slowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every match you win, it starts becoming more important
that it continues,'' Agassi said. ``It has a double impact. It's
like letting it ride on the blackjack table. You know letting it
ride, it's going to get bigger and bigger. That's the way it feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just get out there and let it ride. Every game doubles
your confidence, doubles your focus, your intensity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
