<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-TRUMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TRUMP'S LOSS IS A VICTORY FOR TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He's been down before.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for example, that bleak moment back in the early '90s
when, as sympathetic New Yorkers will remember, he had to sell his
yacht and accept a $450,000-a-month allowance.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was all the trouble with Ivana, followed by all the
trouble with Marla, much of which got splashed on the front page of
The New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all in all, these last couple of weeks haven't been good
ones for the Donald. In Atlantic City, N.J., he was frustrated by
an old lady who beat back his efforts to condemn her house. In
Washington, the federal government small-mindedly insisted that,
no, public parkland could not be offered as collateral for mortgage
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in New York, Donald Trump lost the Coliseum site
at Columbus Circle.
</P>
<P>
   He had been eyeing the site for nearly 15 years. Back in 1985,
he had tried to raise there a truly magnificent Trumpaleum, a
137-story wonder in the shape of a spaceship. This time around he
played it safer, proposing to put up only 72 floors. He offered
more money for the site than anyone else, and threatened to sue if
he didn't get it. Still, the seller, the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   That such a prize should have slipped from Trump's vigorous
grasp was, understandably, a sharp disappointment to him. ``I had
the best building at the highest price,'' he lamented in an
interview from his car phone last week. ``I had the worst political
consultants.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the cosmic scheme of things, too, his loss of the site
was kind of surprising: just think of all the damage he could have
done with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trumpification'' is in urban design circles a term of art, and
not on the whole a complimentary one.
</P>
<P>
   From the site on Columbus Circle where Trump won't get to build,
a short walking tour takes the student of contemporary architecture
to no fewer than three Trump properties, all steps on what one
prominent architect calls a ``trail of tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Right across the circle is the Trump International Hotel, which
the developer created out of the old Gulf and Western building. In
the process he took a decidedly undistinguished building and still
managed, in the opinion of many, to ruin it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original building was nothing,'' said James Steward
Polshek, a former dean of the Columbia University School of
Architecture. ``It became less than nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks away, on Central Park South, is Trump Parc, the
former Barbizon Plaza Hotel, which Trump had hoped to tear down. In
the end, he had to settle for bolting a huge gold-colored awning to
the front of the Art Deco structure.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Fifth Avenue at 56th Street, is Trump Tower, once home
to Trump himself, as well as to a two-story indoor waterfall, acres
of peach-colored marble and enough gold chrome for every faucet in
Beverly Hills. Among architects and critics, it is generally held
to be Trump's least bad bad building. Paul Golberger, the
architecture critic for The New Yorker and formerly for The New
York Times, even confessed to a certain grudging fondness for its
``warm vulgarity.''
</P>
<P>
   A slightly longer walking tour would include Trump's latest work
in progress, Riverside South, which the developer prefers to call
Trump Place. According to the cool appraisal of Polshek, the
complex overlooking the Hudson River expresses ``an architecture so
grotesquely banal that it is an embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   His many detractors note that Trump has, over the years, brought
in some of the biggest names in the business _ among them Philip
Johnson and Robert Stern _ to work on his projects. And yet, no
matter what he builds or whom he gets to design it, the results,
they say, reflect the same esthetic. His buildings are inevitably
big, shiny and profoundly self-absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything he's done that has any lasting urban
or esthetic value,'' said Carter Wiseman, an architecture critic
formerly with New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Trump suggested that the reason he lost the Coliseum site last
week was his own disproportionate success. He ticked off all the
properties he owns in the neighborhood, including the recently
acquired General Motors Building, saying, ``Perhaps that played a
role.''
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't discouraged. He has already bid, he said, on
another slice of Columbus Circle _ the old, and still only
moderately ugly Cultural Affairs Department building.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
