<HEADER>
A4655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MEXICO-TROUBLES-     08-03 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEXICO-TROUBLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TROUBLE IN THE OTHER MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 3:
</P>
<P>
   The poor, heavily Indian state of Chiapas in southern Mexico is
a world apart from cosmopolitan Mexico City. It is also home to the
four-year-old Zapatista rebellion for Indian autonomy, land reform
and a new Mexican political order. President Ernesto Zedillo has
mishandled relations with the Zapatistas since peace talks
collapsed in 1996, abandoning dialogue and trying to impose his own
solutions. As an elected leader, Zedillo is responsible for
preserving constitutional order. But he can better do so by
compromise than by confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere in Chiapas has recently grown more violent. Last
Christmas, a paramilitary force aligned with Zedillo's party
massacred 45 Indians in the village of Chenalho. Zedillo responded
with a credible investigation and removed negligent officials. But
in June, the government raised tensions anew by sending the army
and police to reassert control over Zapatista-run communities. The
Zapatistas, meanwhile, have turned from guerrilla violence to
political organizing, deepening their support. Zedillo must make
greater efforts to coax them back to the bargaining table .
</P>
<P>
   The peace talks broke down after the Zedillo government backed
away from several constitutional reforms to which its own
negotiators had unwisely agreed. The government was right to reopen
these questions. But instead of trying to create an atmosphere for
resumed negotiations, its actions have been highhanded and
provocative.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, implacable government hostility forced the bishop
of Chiapas, Samuel Ruiz Garcia, to abandon efforts to mediate the
conflict. Then the government overturned a longstanding policy of
tolerating the parallel administrations set up by the Zapatistas in
33 villages. That led to a clash in which eight Indians and two
police officers were killed. Zedillo speaks with pride about his
commitment to a new, more pluralistic Mexico. Regrettably, that
vision seems not to apply to Chiapas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4657 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      08-03 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ASTRO JOHNSON IS A RELIEVED PITCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Putting on the new uniform was a little funny.
</P>
<P>
   You might expect something like that when you're 6-foot-10, legs
longer than a heron's. You don't just go and pull something off the
rack.
</P>
<P>
   So Randy Johnson tugged and tugged at his knees, trying to
stretch the pants of his new Houston Astros' uniform down far
enough to reach his ankles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel like the size pants I wore when I was in Little
League,'' Johnson said Sunday, tugging some more and grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's right: Grinning. Smiling. Pleasant. Thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's almost perpetual glower of 1998 was gone _ except on
the pitching mound, where it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson showed it doesn't matter if it's the American League or
National League or maybe even the American Legion or the Japanese
League _ anything to get out of that dead-end job with the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, instead of pitching as scheduled at the Kingdome,
instead of making his start against the Yankees and all those pesky
New York lefties, Johnson was the new ace on a first-place team in
the National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   In his Astro debut, he struck out 12, walked only one, and beat
the Pirates, 6-2, at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   His new teammates are glad to have him. Just ask Astros'
second-baseman Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding me? A horse like that who can chew up a bunch
of innings? To get a guy like him ... my God,'' Biggio gushed,
drooling at the Astros' chances of reversing their fortunes against
the mighty Braves this October.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's good fortune was an absurd and embarrassing
trade-deadline deal, Johnson for three minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Mariners feel bad. Believe me, we've been there
before, losing 98 games,'' Biggio said. ``But they didn't do too
bad. The pitcher they got, Freddy Garcia, he's really good. The
shortstop, (Carlos Guillen) he's OK, too.''
</P>
<P>
   After telling his new employers he would rather stick to his
work schedule, Johnson was moved from a scheduled debut Monday
against the Florida Marlins in Miami into the lineup against the
Pirates. He pitched seven strong innings, giving up six hits,
including a home run to Pittsburgh's Aramis Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new team I had to face today. I wasn't really pleased
with the way I threw but I'll take it because the team won,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   We all know he's human, after all. But even when not at his
best, he's basically overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear so much about him, then you face him live and you
realize, hey, it really is true. He's really as good as everyone
says,'' said Kevin Polcovich, the Pirates' leadoff hitter and one
of Johnson's strikeout victims. ``He's just so tough to hit. And
he's so big, it looks like he delivers the ball to the plate by
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   So now there will be all these new National League hitters to
dazzle. Or is it the other way around?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell if I'll be the one who has the advantage
since they don't know me,'' Johnson said. ``I don't know the
hitters, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also now must bother with having to hit. He didn't have
much success at the plate Sunday, although he did make contact in
two at-bats before pushing through a bunt attempt for strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee I won't be ripping the cover off any baseballs
this season,'' he said. ``But I do need to put in a bat order.''
</P>
<P>
   For his short-notice debut, the Houston equipment manager
scrounged up a loaner bat that looked like a matchstick against
Johnson's giant frame. An old friend and former teammate, Astros'
pitcher Doug Henry, lent him a batting helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make do,'' Johnson said, amused and light-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   He is now a man relieved, or at least a man who is free. Free
after nine months of misery on a team he insists he never wanted to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to have been a Mariner forever and finished
my career there,'' Johnson said. ``There are a lot of memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Without rehashing the entire, tired scenario, Johnson said the
Mariners did not do the right things to make him feel wanted. Some
incidents are minor, showing Johnson's immense over-sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Mariners did make one gigantic blunder last season.
Johnson was 100 percent recovered from back surgery, yet the
Mariners failed to pick up his option for 1998. Instead of feeling
some measure of thanks for his Cy Young and post-season
accomplishments in 1995, he felt unappreciated and financially
unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the starting pitcher for the (1997) All-Star Game. I was
something like 12-2. I thought that would have been the time,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it doesn't matter what did or did not happen. The
divorce and the reasons are history _ though far less memorable
than the history Johnson created for the Mariners and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   His only regret is the way it ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for a lot of people. The Seattle fans. My teammates
in Seattle. My family and myself. I just felt like this was a
little drawn out and much like the Lewinsky-Clinton deal. No one
wants to hear about it, but all we kept hearing about in Seattle
was when or who is going to get Randy,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   They say baseball is a business. That is why Randy Johnson is no
longer a Mariner, since someone, somewhere decided Johnson was one
Mighty Mariner they could not, would not afford.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball is also a daily psychology lesson. And Sunday, when
Johnson became a winner in the National League for the first time
since the Expos traded him to the Mariners in 1989, he seemed
satisfied with one very important element:
</P>
<P>
   The Astros want him.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners did not. So he just wanted to say one more thing:
</P>
<P>
   ``For nine years, the fans in Seattle treated me very nicely.
They always gave a nice ovation. There are probably some things I
did that I would not have been able to do without the fans'
encouragement. So I just want to say again that I'll miss my
teammates back there in Seattle and the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   He said to tell everyone ``Hey.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
