<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONNECTICUT-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: CONNECTICUT POLITICS _ IT ISN'T BRAIN SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Connecticut used to be known as ``The Land of Steady Habits,''
but that was before an ad agency came up with ``Connecticut, We're
Full of Surprises.'' The earlier nickname was better. While it is
true that the state did go through a disquieting period when large
structures were collapsing left and right _ a hotel here, a bridge
there _ it really does not like all that much excitement. I covered
the capitol for a long time, and the only surprise I can remember
was the day the state Senate, caught in a violent battle between
fans of the deer and fans of the whale, dyspeptically voted to name
the human being official state animal.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's incumbent governor, John Rowland, a Republican,
may be familiar to out-of-state residents for his starring role in
tourism promotion commercials. (Americans who plan their vacations
on the basis of the local elected officials' affinity for water
sports will remember that Rowland is the one in the canoe with his
wife, while New York's George Pataki was the guy teaching a little
boy to fish.) Rowland's opponent this fall will be Rep. Barbara
Kennelly of Hartford. As surprises go, it was at least a bit of one
that she would give up her very safe seat to make the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've virtually got to have a lobotomy, and you could still
get re-elected if the economy's good if you're the governor,'' said
Bill Clinton at a Kennelly fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a remark designed to bring the party faithful to
their feet cheering. ``He was just having too good a time,'' said
someone who sat with the president at the $5,000-a-plate luncheon
catered by Martha Stewart. Clinton caught himself in time to assure
the crowd that he was not trying to suggest that John Rowland had
had a lobotomy. But he obviously did mean that Barbara Kennelly
would have a tough time winning even if surgeons disconnected the
frontal lobe of the governor's cerebrum between now and November.
The president couched this as a tribute to Mrs. Kennelly's
political courage, but it was pretty dispiriting all the same.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland has been talking a lot about cities and schools and
doling out tax cuts, but it is not as if there is nothing to carp
about. Like New York, Connecticut's economic upturn is lagging
behind the nation's, and the state labors under a disproportionate
amount of debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no economic development strategy. Where we've given
publicly subsidized economic development aid, 86 percent of the
jobs never materialized,'' said Bill Curry, who ran against Rowland
in 1994. Curry, obsessed with policy, wanted to try again this
year, but party elders seemed to feel voters would prefer Mrs.
Kennelly's warm persona to an analysis of Rowland's privatization
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the congresswoman, having made the jump, seemed to sink like
a stone. She turned out to be a terrible speech maker, as well as a
teller of truths who grimly assured reporters that yes, the polls
did matter. Deconstructing Rowland's administration began to look
like a better idea, and a former state legislator who is known as a
policy whiz was grafted onto the ticket as the candidate for
lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, making a local visit, told Mrs.
Kennelly's staff to keep her away from big speaking engagements and
get her in close to the voters, where she is most impressive. At
the Martha Stewart lunch, someone complimented the president on his
wife's knowledge of Connecticut politics. ``We've been talking
about this race,'' said Clinton, launching into a dissection of
local politics. You would have thought that he came from the Lower
Naugatuck Valley. Then the greatest campaigner of our generation
walked up to the dais and delivered the lobotomy speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
