<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' TOP PICK SIMMONS OUT 2-4 WEEKS WITH KNEE INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Just when things were going so well for Anthony
Simmons, the Seahawks' first-round draft choice could be sidelined
up to a month with torn cartilage in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, a linebacker from Clemson, was injured in Friday
night's preseason opener at Dallas and is scheduled to have
arthroscopic surgery Monday in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that happens,'' Simmons said Sunday.
``It's really nothing you can prevent, but it's something that you
can deal with. Right now, I just have to deal with it and take time
to heal up.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury was originally called a bruised knee and not
considered serious. Now Simmons will miss at least two weeks, but
more likely four.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons was just one of several players injured in the 20-19
victory over the Cowboys, and he was not the most serious.
</P>
<P>
   Backup center Frank Beede is expected to miss the season with a
torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee, coach Dennis
Erickson said. Additional tests to determine the extent of the
damage will be made when the swelling in the joint subsides.
</P>
<P>
   Also injured were starting middle linebacker Dean Wells, who
strained his right calf muscle; backup linebacker Michael Barber,
who has a bruised back; and reserve safety Eric Stokes, who
aggravated his left hamstring, which he pulled last summer and
forced him to miss most of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Barber and Stokes are scheduled to return to Seattle _ Barber to
have a magnetic resonance imaging test; Stokes to have blood
drained from his thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve center Greg Bloedorn (sprained knee ligament) and backup
running back Steve Broussard (strained calf muscle) already were
sidelined with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always concerned about injuries,'' said Erickson, who
lost 17 starters for a total of 72 games last year. ``But that's
part of the game. Every team gets guys hurt. You just hope it's not
serious enough that you lose somebody for the whole season. That
happened to one of our players (Beede). That's bad, but that's part
of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wells, Simmons and Barber all standing on the sideline,
outside linebacker Jason Kyle worked in the middle during Sunday's
90-minute practice. But Wells and Barber are expected to play in
Saturday night's preseason home opener against the Indianapolis
Colts at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   As for the center position, backup guard Chris Gray becomes No.
2 and Washington State rookie Jason McEndoo is No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons wasn't just in camp on time _ only the second Seahawks
first-round pick to do so since 1982 _ he was having a good camp.
The rookie linebacker was using his speed and play-making ability
to contribute on special teams while learning the defense. He was
drawing praise from his coaches and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Now Simmons is sidelined with the first knee injury of his
career, and he can't even recall the play in happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a setback for him. He needs to practice. He really needs
it badly,'' Erickson said. ``It's going to set him back some. He
just needs to study and mentally be in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 0053EDT &QL; 
