<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS RELIEVER-TURNED-STARTER RATTLES YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He struck out the side in the first inning, fanned two
more in the second and another in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad Randy Johnson impersonation on Sunday by Paul
Spoljaric.
</P>
<P>
   With 47,872 fans at the Kingdome wondering just how the Mariners
are going to replace the departed Johnson, who was traded to the
Houston Astros on Friday, Spoljaric set the tone for the Mariners'
6-3 victory over the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander pitched into the fifth inning, exited with a
two-run lead and the Mariner bullpen maintained the edge as Seattle
ended a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buhner's two-run homer off Yankee starter David Cone (15-4)
in the seventh inning put the Mariners ahead by three runs, and
Mike Timlin secured his sixth save despite a scare in New York's
three-hit ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the spotlight was on Spoljaric.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work as a starter for the first time this season and
felt a little uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little too excited in the first inning after (striking
out) the first two batters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill rocked the reliever-turned-starter with a home run,
and Spoljaric promptly walked the next two batters before striking
out Jorge Posada to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got out of the first inning, I relaxed and did what I
wanted to do and actually felt comfortable out there,'' he said.
``It was an adrenaline rush, but I just ran out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoljaric departed two outs too early to qualify for the win.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't wind up with any outrageous expectations, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Randy Johnson and will never be Randy Johnson,''
Spoljaric said. ``Maybe someday I will be as successful as him, but
I won't be a strikeout pitcher. As long as you make the pitches
against any team, even a team as good as the Yankees, you can
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella said Spoljaric earned further starting
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched very well before getting a little tired in the
fourth inning, and rightfully so,'' Piniella said. ``He threw more
pitches (last night) than any game this season. It's not easy doing
what he did, but he seemed very relaxed and smooth out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Used primarily as a setup reliever in 41 appearances this
season, pitching just 442/3 innings, Spoljaric threw a season-high
76 pitches against the Yankees, who lost for only the 28th time in
105 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said the plan is to increase Spoljaric's running
routine to build stamina and give the left-hander another start in
about two weeks when a fifth starter is again needed.
</P>
<P>
   Timlin, meanwhile, has emerged as Seattle's main man at the end
of games and has six saves in seven save opportunities. But Sunday
the right-hander deflected the attention he was getting toward
Spoljaric, whose locker is directly across the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Almost one year ago, they were involved in a trade-deadline deal
bringing them from Toronto to Seattle for outfielder Jose Cruz Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has good stuff and can do the job as a starter or
reliever,'' Timlin said of Spoljaric. ``To me, he is capable of
giving this team quality innings.''
</P>
<P>
   As the shock of the Johnson trade begins to wear off, Timlin
said it was important for the team to treat the former ace's
departure as an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we have to look at it (is) as him going on the
disabled list, like he blew out his back or something,'' Timlin
said. ``There is no reason for us to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners gave up an early run Sunday but retaliated in the
second inning when catcher Joe Oliver singled home Edgar Martinez
from second base.
</P>
<P>
   They took the lead for good in the third, thanks to a botched
play by Yankee first baseman Shane Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and one out, David Segui lined a shot at
Spencer, who dropped the ball and was able to get only a force out
at second base. The botched double play enabled Alex Rodriguez to
score from third to break a 1-1 tie, and Buhner followed with a
run-scoring single to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, 4-for-15 with two home runs lifetime against Cone going
into the series finale, provided the clinching blow with his eighth
homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The three RBIs give Buhner 22 in 21 games since the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   New York, boasting the best record in major league baseball,
continued to play longball against the M's. The Yankees hit two
more homers, by O'Neill and Chad Curtis, and now have 18 this
season against Seattle pitchers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
