A4664 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-ANALYSIS-SPI &LR;      08-03 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-ANALYSIS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME MARINER OWNERS FOR RANDY JOHNSON TRADE BUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There is a lesson for Mariner owners in the Randy
Johnson trade: Stay out of the way when it comes to baseball
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The M's ended up with much less for Johnson than they were
offered back on June 2, when a still unnamed owner blocked a
proposed trade with the Los Angeles Dodgers that would have netted
experienced right-handed starting pitcher Ismael Valdes,
infielder/outfielder Wilton Guerrero and a minor-league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Sources on and off the team say the owner was Nintendo of
America executive Howard Lincoln. Whether he blocked the deal and
why remain closely guarded secrets; the owners aren't willing to
discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the decision forced Woody Woodward, the vice
president of baseball operations, to play a high-stakes poker game
as Friday night's non-waiver trading deadline approached.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the best pitcher in franchise history, already had made
it known numerous times that he wouldn't return to Seattle next
season, and if he wasn't traded, the M's would have had to offer
the unhappy left-hander salary arbitration just to get two draft
choices next June.
</P>
<P>
   The closer the deadline, the less room Woodward had to maneuver.
By Friday, his only hope for leverage was a bidding war between the
New York Yankees and Cleveland Indians. And that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the Yankees said owner George Steinbrenner's
only interest in Johnson now was to make sure he didn't join the
Indians. Steinbrenner wanted to keep his own powerful team intact
for a probable World Series appearance and planned to pursue
Johnson in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Indians general manager John Hart concluded that he
had virtually no chance of signing Johnson to a long-term contract,
so he wasn't willing to deal players with major-league experience
and, according to those familiar with negotiations, never made a
concrete offer.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking competition from Cleveland, the Yankees began
subtracting from a list of available players that originally
included pitcher Hideki Irabu, second baseman Homer Bush, reliever
Ramiro Mendoza, outfielder Ricky Ledee and minor-league infielder
Mike Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   With the clock ticking toward the 9 p.m. PDT deadline, Woodward
called other teams that had expressed interest in Johnson _ the
Houston Astros, San Francisco Giants and Baltimore Orioles. He
eventually settled for three Astro minor-leaguers _ pitcher Freddy
Garcia, infielder Carlos Guillen and a player to be named later,
possibly within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners now have a blueprint on how not to handle a similar
situation. In the future, when a player in the final year of a
contract says he doesn't want to play for the team, they should
trade him long before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership should have realized Johnson was a short-timer two
years ago when he told an Arizona Republic reporter in spring
training that he wanted to be the starter when the expansion
Arizona Diamondbacks played their first game. He sent the same
message last August in Chicago when he and his agents told the
Mariners not to offer him a contract extension because he wouldn't
be back.
</P>
<P>
   What the M's couldn't have known was Johnson's reaction when
they announced in November that no extension would be offered.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson acted hurt. And instead of using his option year as a
springboard toward a lucrative deal elsewhere as a free agent, he
did not consistently show the fire or focus that made him the most
dominating pitcher in the major leagues during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   He's gone now, but shouldn't be forgotten _ especially by the
owners who let him go at too low a price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 0054EDT &QL; 
