<HEADLINE>
MCIVER COULD BE NEAR RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS AND DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Guard Everett McIver could practice as
early as Wednesday, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said. McIver didn't
play in the preseason game against the Seahawks because of a neck
wound suffered in a dormitory incident at Midwestern State that
Cowboys coaches termed ``horseplay.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jones nor Cowboys coach Chan Gailey would comment on
Saturday's Star-Telegram report that wide receiver Michael Irvin
was involved in the incident. ``We've said all we are going to say
about it,'' Jones said. When asked about the report after practice,
Irvin had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   McIver was not at practice and could not be reached for comment.
Don't blame Cunningham
Cowboys coach Chan Gailey took the heat off kicker Richie
Cunningham, who drew some criticism from fans for missing an extra
point and a 46-yard field-goal attempt during the loss to the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said those misses came when backup center Steve Scifres
was the snapper. Scifres' snaps were a bit slower than those of
regular snapper Dale Hellestrae.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not bad snaps,'' Gailey said. ``It's just not the
same rhythm. So your stride is a little bit off _ just enough to
make you miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellestrae was the snapper when Cunningham converted 25- and
20-yard field goals and an extra point against Seattle. But Gailey
wanted to also give Scifres some playing time, just in case he's
needed in a critical situation during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when \RHellestrae\S might get an injury, and
you might not have the first-team snapper,'' Gailey said. ``That's
something Richie has to see and know and make a little adjustment
on his part, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cunningham took the blame for what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really got no excuse missing those kicks,'' he said. ``I
just came up too fast on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cunningham was the second-most accurate kicker in the
NFL. He was 34 of 37 on field-goal attempts _ 91.9 percent _ and
was 24-of-24 on extra-point kicks.
Mills shut out
Free-agent signee Ernie Mills was supposed to be the front-runner
to start at wide receiver opposite Michael Irvin. But Gailey found
himself explaining why no passes were thrown to Mills against
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't have anything to do with him or anything,'' Gailey
said. ``He played the same as he had. It just worked out that we
didn't have any passes called that way during the course of the
ballgame.''
He's No. 3
Despite a rock-solid performance by rookie free-agent Danny
Gonzalez against Seattle, he is not about to unseat Jason Garrett
as the No. 2 quarterback. At least that's what Gailey said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was 9-of-12 passing for 105 yards against the Seahawks.
His totals included eight consecutive completions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did surprise me,'' Gailey said. ``And that's not fair to
him for it to surprise me, because I had really no basis except
practice. He'd had limited reps at practice, so I'd never seen
that. \RBut\S I love those kind of surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie free-agent wide receiver Jeff Odgen also surprised Gailey
when he ran the wrong route on one play, but still wound up making
a reception from Gonzalez. Odgen finished with a team-high four
catches for 60 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the passes \ROdgen\S caught, he wasn't in the right
spot, but he caught it,'' Gailey said. ``What's bad is he and Danny
were obviously on the same page.''
Woodson-Sanders up in air
The Cowboys have not decided whether Pro Bowl safety Darren Woodson
and Pro Bowl cornerback Deion Sanders will play in Thursday's
scrimmage in El Paso against the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson (shoulder, triceps) and Sanders (ankle) were held out of
the Seattle game for precautionary reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said: ``We need to see where they are with the injuries,
and the rehab stuff.''
They said it ``''I've never seen nothing like that before.''''
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Strickland
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker discussing the third-quarter drive by Seattle when
the Cowboys were flagged for having 12 men on the field three
different times.
</P>
<P>
   ``''I was pleased with the way I played, but we've got a few
things to work on.''''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Warren
</P>
<P>
   Backup running back who rushed for 32 yards on six carries
against the Seahawks.
</P>
</TEXT>
