<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMPAIGN REFORM'S FINEST CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Mass., N.J., N.Y., Tenn.)   (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 3:
</P>
<P>
   The House stands Monday on the threshold of approving the most
sweeping overhaul of election fund-raising laws since Watergate.
Few in Washington gave campaign finance reform any chance earlier
this year. But last Thursday and Friday, the House dramatically
rejected 16 amendments designed to kill off reform legislation.
Dozens of Republicans defied Newt Gingrich in those votes. If
pro-reform lawmakers stay together on Monday, the House can approve
the Shays-Meehan bill banning unlimited ``soft money'' donations to
political parties, the very donations at the center of the recent
fund-raising scandals.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill needs to win by the widest possible
margin. That is because of unusual parliamentary rules crafted by
Gingrich, in which any bill that gets the most votes this week
wins. If the Shays-Meehan measure is approved, Gingrich will
probably lobby immediately for a watered-down version in order to
trump it. A separate measure backed by a bipartisan group of
freshman members would, for example, ban soft-money contributions
to national party organizations but permit them for state parties,
opening a huge loophole. Approval of the Shays-Meehan bill on
Monday, and the quick dispatch of competing versions, would clear
the way for final passage by the end of the week. The bill would
then go to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The cynics say reform has no chance in the Senate even if it
passes the House. These same experts said House Republicans would
never defy their leadership and join with Democrats to back reform.
But under pressure from Christopher Shays of Connecticut, they did.
In New York, Sherwood Boehlert, Amo Houghton, Sue Kelly, Michael
Forbes, James Walsh and Benjamin Gilman voted again and again to
reject killer amendments. Nancy Johnson of Connecticut joined with
Marge Roukema, Bob Franks, Rodney Frelinghuysen and Frank LoBiondo
of New Jersey to do the same. Tom Campbell and Zach Wamp,
Republicans from California and Tennessee, showed particular
courage. Also impressive were the efforts of Richard Gephardt and
David Bonior to help Martin Meehan of Massachusetts keep Democratic
votes in line.
</P>
<P>
   By banning soft-money donations to parties and curbing
fund-raising for campaign ads by single-issue advocacy groups, the
Shays-Meehan bill would drastically reduce the role of
special-interest money in elections. Why would anyone allow such
corruption to continue now that the opportunity for reform is here?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
