<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE HELPS SELE SETTLE DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DONALD EMMONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The evening started out precariously for
Rangers right-hander Aaron Sele last night.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up two runs on two hits in the first inning against the
Chicago White Sox and appeared on his way to remaining winless in
seven outings since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sele settled down as the Rangers rolled to a 12-3
drubbing of the White Sox before 28,175 at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled a little bit early, but I kind of gritted my teeth
and came back and pitched well,'' said Sele, who earned his 13th
decision of the year, tying a career high for a season. ``It was
just a matter of making some changes to get the ball down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele (13-8) pitched eight innings, allowing three runs on 10
hits while striking out two and walking two. After allowing the
White Sox to score another run in the second, he had little trouble
the rest of the game, until he was replaced after throwing 110
pitches, 78 of them strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The decision ended an 0-3 showing over four games for Sele, who
hadn't won since July 4. It also helped to restore his
earned-run-average that had ballooned to 4.51 over his previous six
outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron bounced back after struggling with his command in the
first and second innings,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``After that, I thought he made a lot of quality pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Oates considered Sele's first victory in nearly a month
a product of sound pitching and a sure-gloved defense inspired by
two newcomers _ third baseman Todd Zeile and shortstop Royce
Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   Acquired in trades, Zeile and Clayton each made fielding plays
that helped kill potential early scoring opportunities for the
White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our pitcher saw a couple of plays \Rby Zeile and
Clayton\S made tonight that gave him confidence,'' Oates said.
``The pitchers see we can take care of the ball and score some
runs. That can spread all over.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RSele\S started getting the ball down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who said he never got down on himself during the recent
winless period, also credited his defensive support _ particularly
a revamped left side of the infield _ for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy that the first inning didn't turn into a bigger
inning \Rfor the White Sox\S,'' Sele said. ``I was able to stay out
there and they did the rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
