<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOMB-FUGITIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE RUNNING MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., N.C.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 3:
</P>
<P>
   He has a scar on his chin and regular features. His manner is
polite. He leaves money for the groceries he steals and a
handwritten note naming the owner of the vehicle he took. The press
regularly calls him an ``outdoorsman,'' an honorific with overtones
of class demarcation. He has lived in isolation long enough to
remain unspecific in the eyes of his neighbors in western North
Carolina. His childhood was blurred, to outside eyes at least, by
his family's strange beliefs, his manner withdrawn even in ninth
grade, when he wrote a school paper denying the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   But when Eric Rudolph, 31, is finally captured and if evidence
warrants his indictment for the fatal January bombing of a
Birmingham, Ala., abortion clinic _ and if he is charged too for
the 1996 bombings at Olympic Park in Atlanta _ the shadows will
begin to fall away. Rudolph has been on the run for six months and
is believed to be hiding in North Carolina's Nantahala National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   As a fugitive, Rudolph has elicited sympathy among a few
residents of the area. A number of things make this possible, if
perverse. His belief in a militant white separatism that is
anti-abortion, anti-homosexual and anti-government finds echoes in
a region where white separatist organizations are known to have
taken refuge. In a place full of ``outdoorsmen,'' what some
residents seem to be feeling is something akin to the respect a
hunter feels for his prey. The implicit absence of that respect at
the FBI _ its determination simply to get its man in a businesslike
manner _ merely adds to the unpopularity of a strong government
presence where government has never been particularly welcome. The
search itself embodies the conflict between terrain, on the running
man's side, and technology, on the FBI's.
</P>
<P>
   But what really enables even this limited expression of local
sympathy is vagueness. The cruelty and indecency of the Birmingham
bombing has been echoed, so far, by nothing in Rudolph's words. No
one has heard them. It is easy enough to imagine oneself in
Rudolph's place, on the run, for his predicament is far better
known from movies and television than he is. It is much harder to
imagine just who and what kind of person could have detonated the
bomb at the New Woman All Women Health Care Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
