<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WHEATON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
F.H. WHEATON JR., 85, HEADED GLASS WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Fla., N.H., Conn., Nev., Va.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Hayes Wheaton Jr., who served for three decades as head of
Wheaton Industries, a Millville, N.J., glass manufacturer founded
by his grandfather, died on July 21 at the University of
Pennsylvania Hospital in Philadelphia. He was 85 and a lifelong
resident of Millville.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton Industries, formerly the Wheaton Glass Works, was built
into the country's largest family-operated glass company by his
father, and Wheaton expanded its operations overseas. Wheaton makes
everything from fine crystal to table glassware to plastic bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton entered the family business in 1935 after attending
Boston College. He became chief executive in the mid-1950s and
served until dissatisfied family members replaced him in 1991. The
company was later sold to Alusuisse-Lonza Holding Ltd. of Zurich,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton was president of Wheaton Village, a glass museum in
Millville that he founded and endowed. A boating enthusiast, he
also served as president of Dorchester Shipbuilding Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton is survived by his wife, Mary Bainbridge Wheaton; a son,
Frank H. III, of Jacksonville, Fla.; three daughters, Mary Edith
Smith of Newington, N.H., Susan Ball of Greenwich, Conn., and Nancy
Wheaton of Gardnerville, Nev.; a brother, Laur Don Wheaton of Rose
Hill, Va.; 13 grandchildren; and 11 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
