<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOLLEYBALL-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL IS THE REIGNING POWER IN BEACH VOLLEYBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gold medalists were Brazilian. The runners-up were
Australian. The sand was Canadian. The Goodwill Games women's beach
volleyball final at Wollman Rink Sunday further proved that the
sport no longer belongs to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The power has shifted to the beaches of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil,
where there are more than 200 volleyball nets along a two-mile
stretch of sand. The top players have their own coach, their own
trainer and their own masseuse _ the same luxuries afforded soccer
star Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder Brazil rules the beach? Shelda Bede and Adriana
Behar continued the bullying on a sparkling afternoon in Central
Park Sunday, dispatching Australia's Pauline Manser and Kerri
Pottharst by 12-9, 12-5 in front of 2,800 spectators. The victory
gave Brazil a sweep of the men's and women's events at the games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming a familiar scene. Another Brazilian women's team
won the 1997 world championships and the 1996 Olympics. Bede and
Behar lead the world professional tour and would appear to be the
early favorites for the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have lots of confidence,'' said Holly McPeak of the
United States, who earlier teamed with Lisa Arce to defeat Italy's
Laura Bruschini and Annamaria Solazzi, 12-11, 12-3, for the bronze
medal. ``It's a confidence knowing you can perform every game.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-5-inch Bede and the 5-9 Behar wear down opponents
with well-placed serves and consistency. They dive for balls that
would land for winners against less agile players. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our opponents make mistakes before we do,'' Bede said through
the translation of her teammate. ``We are calm and concentrated.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behar said she and Bede practice jump-serving an hour a day, a
ritual unheard of elsewhere. In the second game, Bede served three
aces in a row between the tall, muscular Australians to give Brazil
a 6-1 lead and little hindrance to a $30,000 payday. The
Australians will share $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for McPeak and Arce, the once top-ranked duo must find a way
to improve without a domestic tour, which collapsed last year.
Their solution? Move temporarily to Brazil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
