<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ With their 8-7 loss to the Boston Red Sox Sunday night
at Edison Field, the Angels fell out of first place and nobody in
the home clubhouse was very happy about it. In fact, the Angels
made a couple of roster moves after the game, and manager Terry
Collins promised there would be more to come _ soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox ran off to an 8-0 lead and held off an Angels rally
before 35,763 fans, completing a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have lost five of six on the homestand, with the AL
Central-leading Cleveland Indians in town for three games beginning
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   They fell one game behind Texas in the AL West, a spot in the
standings that seems more fitting for a team that has lost 20 of 29
since June 30. The Angels had held first place in the division for
all but six days since June 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels managed to make this one interesting after the Red
Sox scored four runs in the first, one in the third, one in the
fifth and two more in the sixth on a Mo Vaughn homer to go up 8-0
against Angels starter Jason Dickson (9-9). But the Angels rallied
in the bottom of the sixth off Red Sox starter Tim Wakefield
(13-5), who sailed through five innings, allowing only one hit.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, the Angels sent 11 batters to the plate and scored
six runs. They got five hits, including Garret Anderson's two-run
homer (No. 12), three walks, a sacrifice fly and an error by
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra to make a game of it.
</P>
<P>
   They scored another in the ninth off Red Sox closer Tom Gordon
but came up short when Anderson grounded out to first with the
potential tying run on first. Anderson, whose hitting streak was
snapped at 28 games Saturday, had three hits Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say Anderson isn't going anywhere, but the same
isn't true for others. After the game, the Angels sent second
baseman Justin Baughman and left-handed reliever Mike Holtz to
Triple-A Vancouver, called up left-handed reliever Trevor Wilson
and activated second baseman Randy Velarde.
</P>
<P>
   Other moves are coming, Collins promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make some changes,'' he said. ``Shake things up
here. We've got to find the right mix, find a way to get it done.
We need to start getting people's attention and getting it done on
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have not been happy with the production of Dave
Hollins (.244, 10 homers, 36 RBI) or Cecil Fielder (.241, 17
homers, 68 RBI). Even though Fielder has decent power numbers and
leads the team in RBI, he has struggled in key situations, hitting
just .169 with runners in scoring position and two out.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are trying to find a spot on the roster for Todd
Greene, and releasing a veteran might be the only way to do it.
However, Hollins is making $1.9 this season and is guaranteed $1.9
next year. Fielder is making $2.8 million this year and is owed
about $900,000 for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh really?'' Angels DH Tim Salmon said when told changes would
be made. ``There's no question we have to do some things to shake
things up a little bit. . . . Yeah, I think I'm going down. Just
joking. I'm not going to speculate on who they will be. But this
team needs to do something to turn it around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to a point where everybody knows how badly we need
to win. Sometimes you lose focus on what it takes to get a win. You
focus so much on the end result, you forget what it takes in
between, doing the little things. We need to focus on each at-bat
and playing defense each inning. And at the end of the game, cash
in and see where you're at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
