<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-CAYARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TO THE KENWOOD CUP WITH A NEW PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Driving across the Golden Gate Bridge recently on his way to
work, Paul Cayard gave way to idle reflection. He was an hour
behind schedule at his San Francisco office. And, trying as he is
to begin an America's Cup campaign, each of his calendar hours
looks more like a week of commitments. Not a good time to be
running late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was late,'' the 39-year-old yachtsman said recently.
``But I was thinking, `I'm not in a hurry.' A year ago, I would
have been completely stressed out. But the Whitbread race has put
everything in perspective. Alone in the Southern Ocean, the way we
were, there were those moments where you are really scared. And
that really makes an impression on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The adrenaline-charged reports that Cayard sent by satellite
from the 60-foot EF Language are history. Regarded at its finish
last May as a stunning victory for a team of mostly round-the-buoy
sailors, the achievement by the EF crew in the Whitbread Round the
World Race was a personal triumph for Cayard.
</P>
<P>
   But now it is back to rounding orange buoys, and the next event
on the list is the 11th biennial Kenwood Cup, which is scheduled to
begin today off Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard has agreed to sail as tactician on Illbruck-Pinta, a One
Design 48 being chartered for the Hawaii series by an aspiring
around-the-world team from Germany. The Germans are so committed to
the next equivalent of the Whitbread in 2001-2002, which will be
called the Volvo Ocean Race, that they purchased EF Language and EF
Education, both former Whitbread competitors _ for training
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In charge of Illbruck-Pinta will be John Kostecki of San
Francisco, the regular Illbruck skipper who also happens to have
signed on with Cayard for the America One 1999-2000 America's Cup
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard is struggling to find the $20 million or more in
corporate sponsorship that he and most of the other 15 cup
challengers are still seeking. In addition, Cayard has lost several
key members of his team.
</P>
<P>
   The first defection came last year when Laurent Esquier,
Cayard's veteran cup manager, took a job with Prada, the Italian
challenger. Last spring, Steve Erickson, a longtime friend and
sailing cohort in the Whitbread Round the World Race, also took a
position with Prada. Then last week, Kimo Worthington left America
One. Worthington is expected to sign on with Young America, the New
York Yacht Club team.
</P>
<P>
   For Kostecki, a vital member of the America One effort and still
loyal to Cayard, sailing with his America's Cup boss is a two-way
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, adding Paul Cayard to our Illbruck-Pinta crew is a
nice bonus for the Kenwood Cup,'' Kostecki said recently.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-day Kenwood series includes eight day races: four ocean
triangles and four windward-leeward courses of about 10-12 nautical
miles each. On Friday is a 150-mile middle-distance race from
Honolulu to Maui, and on Aug. 11, a 376-mile race from Oahu to Maui
and back.
</P>
<P>
   America's Cup teams are revving up their intensity now, with
many sailors choosing to hone their skills in the Kenwood Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the One Design 48 yachts have been transported to Hawaii
for the regatta. Their presence is being felt by Ken Morrison,
Kenwood's race director for the last 20 years. Since its inception
as the Clipper Cup in 1978, the biennial regatta has featured team
racing based on handicap rules for differently designed boats.
</P>
<P>
   But that mix is eroding. A weak Asian economy this year has
reduced the number of handicap entries from Japan, Australia and
New Zealand. In 1982, there were a record 82 boats; now there are
about 30.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, the six 1D48 yachts are not competing in the
long-distance race because of a tight shipping schedule. That
leaves 24 boats to sail the last and most important race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look very closely at the proliferation of One
Design 48's,'' Morrison said about realistic prospects for a
greater one-design fleet in the Kenwood Cup 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
