<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VELARDE SET FOR SECOND COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ No, the Angels didn't make a trade, but they will have
some ``new faces'' today.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Velarde will rejoin the team tonight and start at second
base after completing a rehabilitation assignment at Triple-A
Vancouver. It will be Velarde's second ``comeback'' of the season.
Following reconstructive elbow surgery in April of 1997, Velarde
came back and played in games May 13 and 14, going 3 for 5.
</P>
<P>
   However, he suffered a stress fracture in the elbow and had to
shut it down again.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins said Velarde won't necessarily
start every day. Instead, he will monitor the condition of the
second baseman's elbow daily.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Velarde on the roster, the Angels sent rookie
Justin Baughman to Vancouver. Baughman hit .245 with one homer and
20 RBI in 57 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want Justin Baughman sitting on the bench,'' Collins
said. ``He's too good a prospect to not be playing every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also called up left-handed pitcher Trevor Wilson
(5-9, 3.62 ERA at Vancouver), replacing struggling reliever Mike
Holtz. Holtz is 2-1 with a 5.33 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Holtz needs to go pitch and get his confidence back,''
Collins said. ``He lost the feel for his curveball. It's not as
sharp. He has one of the toughest jobs in the game. He had to come
in and face Ken Griffey Jr., Mo Vaughn, the best lefties in the
game. It's not like he has to face me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nature of the business,'' Holtz said. ``You don't do
your job, you start over. That's what I'm going to do. You can be
bummed out, and I'm certainly not happy. But the best way I can
help this team is to go down, work hard and get back to what got me
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Add call-ups: Catcher Charlie O'Brien also will join the team
today. O'Brien, acquired in a trade from the White Sox for two
minor leaguers last Thursday, has been out with a broken right
thumb. He is eligible to come off the disabled list today, but he
won't be activated for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Hill feeling fine: Pitcher Ken Hill (elbow) threw Sunday and
felt fine. He'll throw again Wednesday before beginning a rehab
assignment Sunday at Cedar Rapids because the Angels will be in
nearby Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``How he feels is going to be the No.1 thing, but we plan to
have three (rehab starts) scheduled,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Matchup for the ages: When third baseman Troy Glaus, who
celebrates his 22nd birthday today, faced Dennis Eckersley, 43, of
the Red Sox in the eighth inning Sunday, one could say there was a
definite generation gap. In 1976, the year Glaus was born,
Eckersley went 13-12 with a 3.44 ERA in 36 games (30 starts) for
the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Against Eckersley, Glaus hit a comebacker and was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Projecting Erstad: Darin Erstad continues to play at a
record-breaking pace. His projected season totals in hits (203),
doubles (49), total bases (345) and extra-base hits (81) would be
Angels records.
</P>
<P>
   With 19 homers and 19 stolen bases, Erstad has a chance to
become only the second Angel ever to have a 30-30 season. In 1977,
Bobby Bonds hit 37 homers and stole 41 bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
