<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRIVALS HELP GIVE RANGERS NEW ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Two scenes keep running through the head, as
the Rangers get adjusted to Todd Zeile's .833 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   The first involves the Rangers' former shortstop, who possessed
a perpetual California tan and, alas, a terminal California
attitude. The 1996 Rangers had just returned from their potentially
calamitous September swing through Seattle and Anaheim. Their
season-long division lead was shriveling. Their throats were
clenching. Concern was the order of the day in the silent Rangers
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Except at Kevin Elster's locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' a smiling Elster tried to explained, ``the important
thing is that we're having fun. This is just a game, and we're
still having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. Whoopee cushions and Hootie and the Blowfish tickets for
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   The second memorable scene comes from the 1993 World Series. The
mayor of Philadelphia, Frank Rizzo, looking to disparage the
opposing Blue Jays, makes a politically incorrect reference to
Toronto pitcher Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after the Jays had won the Series, Stottlemyre took the
microphone and, in front of citizens from two nations, suggested
that His Honor can kiss his posterior.
</P>
<P>
   The word is attitude. And the Rangers would like to think
they've dealt themselves a whole new one.
</P>
<P>
   The feisty Stottlemyre may be the social antithesis of the man
he must replace, lefty Darren Oliver. Darren's easygoing style was
once mistaken for a strong stoicism.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out he had the competitive fire of a refrigerator light
bulb.
</P>
<P>
   The equally breezy Elster, while well-liked, was showing as much
range at shortstop as that other Hollywood infielder ... Rosie
O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to be done. The Rangers looked like a tired,
uncertain bunch for a six-week stretch in June and July.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, whether it was waiting for the ink to
dry on the new owner's bill of sale or for the starting pitchers to
actually get someone out, this team lost its edge. Its confidence
vanished in a week, while losing back-to-back home series in June
to the Angels and the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the heat. It was the futility.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's dramatic dealings, therefore, were a wakeup call long
overdue. It was management's way of applying its shoes to the rear
of the players' pants.
</P>
<P>
   The response has been, for lack of a better word, electrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, the new third baseman, has enjoyed a Roy Hobbs debut.
After a three-hit, three-RBI opening game, he came back last night
and missed a two-homer game by inches.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton, Elster's successor at shortstop, has brandished
an active bat and a hustling attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Attitude. That word again.
</P>
<P>
   And the best may be yet to come, Tuesday night when Stottlemyre,
Philadelphia's once-favorite son, takes the mound against his old
team, the Blue Jays. Stottlemyre has the demeanor, as well as the
pitching goods, to assume the staff's No. 1 role for the remainder
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver couldn't. His lackluster spring was followed by a blase,
inconsistent summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had to move on.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny. Without so much as a timely base hit, the Rangers
were seen Friday night _ the major-league deadline for trades
without waivers _ as surging past both the Angels and Seattle
Mariners. The Angels, adrift in Disneyland, will play out the
season with a pat hand. The Mariners, on the other hand, bungled
the Randy Johnson trade and then passed it off as creative
rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   How times change. Before the season, the Mariners were hailed by
some as this year's World Series champions. Now they're in the
throes of rebuilding, with a lion's share of their own once-feisty
attitude, Johnson's, gone to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Since the new guys have arrived, the Rangers have played like
the caffeine has finally kicked in. Zeile won't stop getting on
base. Clayton runs out ground balls like a rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it was only the Chicago White Sox and, last night in
particular, the weekly burnt offerings known as Jaime Navarro. But
it beats what the Rangers have been parading out for the past six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new attitude in town. Management hopes that it's
contagious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
