<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS, PHILS PLAY BRAWLBALL 
BY HENRY SCHULMAN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ ``Dear Miss Manners, is it a breach of etiquette
to steal second base when your team is leading by seven runs in the
fifth inning? Sincerely, the San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia
Phillies.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. A simple letter like that could have spared
these two teams a lot of heartache Sunday. But ballplayers being
ballplayers, they settled it differently, with two bench-clearing
brawls that resulted in three ejections, bruises on Barry Bonds'
forehead, a certainty that the National League will suspend Bonds
for charging the mound and enough angry words to call this city's
nickname into question.
</P>
<P>
   One positive thing the Giants took from the City of Brotherly
Love Sunday was an explosive 15-3 victory. The win, their third
straight, was highlighted by back-to-back-to-back homers in the
second inning by Ellis Burks (with two aboard), Bonds and Jeff
Kent.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange way, the Giants also viewed the fisticuffs as a
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want things to get stirred up like that with
possible suspensions, but this doesn't put a damper on the game,''
manager Dusty Baker said. ``Sometimes something like this brings
guys closer. You're defending one another. That doesn't make it
right, but it's August, we've played 100 games and it's the summer.
You see most riots occur in the heat of summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The unpleasantness began in the fifth inning, after Bonds ripped
his fourth hit in four at-bats to right field, driving pitcher Kirk
Rueter home for a 9-2 lead. With first baseman Kevin Jordan holding
him on, Bonds stole second.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, stealing a base with a seven-run lead is viewed as
pouring it on. But since Bonds did it in the middle of the game,
not toward the end, and since the Giants' pitching staff had
squandered leads of 4-0 and 6-1 in the first two games of the
series before rallying back, Bonds felt he was justified.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, when Bonds led off the seventh against new pitcher
Ricky Bottalico, the hard-throwing right-hander fired his first
pitch at Bonds' right leg, hitting him above the kneecap. Bonds,
who had expressed frustration at being hit when he was plunked
twice in Montreal last week, bolted for the mound and took
Bottalico down at the knees.
</P>
<P>
   The benches emptied and jumped on the pile. Although a lot of
words were exchanged and somebody socked Bonds in the head from
above, there were few punches thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any cheap shots,'' Giants second baseman Kent
said. ``It was a pretty professional brawl, as those things go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants felt that Bottalico threw at Bonds deliberately in
retaliation for the stolen base. In fact, Baker accused Phillies
manager Terry Francona of putting Bottalico in the game for that
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was obvious,'' Baker said. ``He pitched two
innings yesterday, and a guy like that, you wouldn't figure he'd be
in a game like this, especially after he just had an operation. It
seems to me he was probably put in there to hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds defended the theft, his 19th of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as baseball has been around, in the fifth inning, the
game is not over,'' he said. ``You play the game for five innings.
Now, if the guy is not holding you on, or if it's the sixth inning
or later, you give them the courtesy (of not stealing). You don't
go out there and expect a team to lay down and die. That's
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team,'' Bonds said of the Phillies. ``They keep
scoring and keep coming back. You can't take anything for granted.
We haven't been able to hold them from scoring runs. We've had
six-run leads, and other teams have come back to tie us.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Phillies saw things differently.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Alex Arias, who would be a central player in the
second bench-clearing incident, was the most vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt he's a great player,'' Arias said of Bonds.
``But do you want to be a great player with stats that don't mean
anything? I'm sure half of his steals are like that. I never had
respect for the guy because of things like that. His own teammates
don't tolerate him. He's a stats guy. That's all he's worried
about.''
</P>
<P>
   During the brawl, Bonds and Phillies pitcher Curt Schilling
exchanged words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't saying anything to him that his own teammates weren't
saying about him on the field,'' Schilling said. ``He's a
first-ballot Hall of Famer, no doubt, but when you don't play the
game right bad things will happen. What he did was bull.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds knows he will be suspended, but he was not sorry he
charged the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only restrain yourself for so long,'' he said. ``You
try to handle things the best way you can. The suspension should
come to the person who started it. It shouldn't come for defending
myself. You can hit my kneecap and end my career. What am I
supposed to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds also took a swipe at Bottalico, who was ejected as well,
saying the pitch did not hurt much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got spanked worse than that,'' Bonds said. ``I'll take one
shot with a baseball over my dad spanking me for 20 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The other shoe dropped with two out in the bottom of the seventh
inning. Rueter, who allowed a two-run homer by Scott Rolen in the
fourth and a solo homer by Arias in the fifth, hit Arias with a
changeup or fastball, depending on your point of view. Arias
started toward the mound slowly, emptying both benches again.
</P>
<P>
   Giants catcher Brent Mayne restrained Arias and little else
happened, except for Arias shoving Giants first base coach Carlos
Alfonso as Alfonso tried to restrain him. That's a bad idea;
Alfonso is a martial-arts expert.
</P>
<P>
   Arias was ejected, but Rueter was not, because home-plate umpire
Jeff Nelson felt Rueter did not try to hit the batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a changeup,'' Rueter said. ``I tried to go inside and
it cut on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Arias said it was a fastball with purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing this game long enough to know it was a
fastball. There's no chance a left-hander is going to throw a
right-hander a changeup inside. I might be dumb, but I ain't
stupid,'' Arias said. ``A mistake? He hasn't made a mistake all
year. He was living on the outside corner all day, then he makes a
mistake inside? Have the decency to say you hit me and get on with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arias also was upset with Baker for the way the manager
restrained him, saying, ``A manager is supposed to calm things
down, not start anything. He pushed me. I don't thank that was nice
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded Baker, ``I don't care what he said. He was up in my
player's face. He was going to fight. He wasn't out there to paint.
He doesn't respect me? I don't care. Who is he in my life? Nobody.
If he don't like that, he can come up to my chest and tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an odd twist in the NL schedule, the Giants will stick
around and play the Phillies again Monday afternoon. As the man
used to say, hold on to your hats.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
