u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANTA-FE-OPERA-REVIEW     08-03 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-FE-OPERA-REVIEW-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUFFERING AS ILLUSION IN A SURREAL LANDSCAPE IN SANTA FE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ The Santa Fe Opera's second structure _ which
opened in 1968, after the first one burned down, and has just been
rebuilt _ was perhaps unique in the extent to which it welcomed in
a spectacular natural setting without sacrificing theatrical
integrity. But it was not the only feature that made the company
distinctive. Even as access to the great outdoors has been
curtailed this season in what is effectively a third theater, the
programming remains typically adventurous, with the last piece put
in place on Saturday evening: the American premiere production of
Ingvar Lidholm's ``Dream Play.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the theater has lost its character by any means, as
Colin Graham's production of ``A Dream Play'' showed. The rear of
the stage remains open to mountains and sky, and Derek McLane's
scenic design, with its low backdrop of fluffy clouds, seemed a
whimsical extension of the actual sky seen above, all in keeping
with the opera's surreality.
</P>
<P>
   The major change in the $19 million reconstruction is a new,
full roof, which closes the big gap that made audiences feel so
much a part of that natural setting, for good (on glorious starry
nights) and ill (during punishing downpours). The outdoor air still
wafts through in abundance, and the remarkable light shows
generated by the night sky are visible all around. In more
practical terms, the seating capacity has been expanded by 237, to
2,126, and theatrical capabilities have been enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   But practicality seemed remote indeed on Saturday, as Lidholm's
opera, which was first performed in 1992, in Stockholm, Sweden,
transformed the house into a weird dreamscape. The work's
surreality, which seems radical even today, especially in opera,
closely mirrors that of Strindberg's ``Dream Play,'' of 1901, which
argued that ``the world, life and human beings are only an
illusion, a phantom, a dream image ... a dream become reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In play and opera, the god Indra, beset by the complaints of
humanity, sends his Daughter to earth, to investigate the human
condition. As she lives human parts _ lover, wife, mother _ and
finds disappointment, frustration and tragedy everywhere, her
Candidean innocence gives way to an oppressive understanding of the
human lot, which is ultimately saved only by its being illusory.
</P>
<P>
   Lidholm, a Swedish composer born in 1921, fits all of this out
with a wonderfully flexible score. As in much of his music, he
draws heavily but imaginatively on Stravinsky: ``The Rite of
Spring,'' on which he based his ballet ``Rites,'' of 1960, but
also, strikingly at the end, the Symphony of Psalms. There are
touches of Britten's ``Peter Grimes,'' too, yet Lidholm speaks with
an individual voice. His handling of a rich harmonic palette is
masterly, especially in chords that mutate before the ear. He is
also a virtuosic orchestrator, though he does not hesitate to set
the instruments aside for long dramatic passages by the chorus
(here, the Santa Fe Desert Chorale).
</P>
<P>
   The work was performed in Graham's English translation of
Lidholm's Swedish libretto. The central role of the Daughter is a
splendid vehicle for a lyric soprano, and Sylvia McNair turned it
into a tour de force, showing as thorough an involvement in the
quirky drama as in the vocal flights. Among the Strindbergian alter
egos, Hakan Hagegard repeated the rough-hewn role of the Officer,
which he created in Stockholm; Thomas Barrett functioned smoothly
as the Lawyer, and Richard Stilwell was commanding as the Poet,
working through to the truth with the Daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Of the lesser characters, Judith Christin was especially
effective as the Stage Door Keeper. Hal France conducted the
orchestra, which rose beautifully to Lidholm's many challenges.
</P>
<P>
   This was a rewarding evening of musical theater if hardly an
easy one. Yet the audience, evidently long accustomed to adventures
cooked up the company's general director, John Crosby, showed
admirable gumption. Few patrons left at intermission, though many,
bemused, scurried off to buy a libretto at the newly expanded gift
shop.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another relative novelty, on Friday evening, presented no such
problems. Tim Albery's lively production of Berlioz's ``Beatrice
and Benedict,'' also sung in English, was clever (overclever at
times) and remarkably detailed (if overbusy at times): mostly a
delight.
</P>
<P>
   It was aided by an excellent cast, headed by Susan Graham,
lustrous of voice and deft in her comic timing. The other leads,
Gordon Gietz, Elizabeth Futral and Nathan Gunn, formed a fine
ensemble vocally and dramatically. Timothy Nolen stole several
scenes as the chorus master, and Nancy Maultsby added stature to
the role of an attendant. Edo de Waart conducted fluently, and the
orchestra played well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beatrice and Benedict'' is to be performed next on Thursday
evening, ``A Dream Play'' on Wednesday. On Monday, meanwhile, comes
Puccini's ``Madama Butterfly,'' which opened all three Santa Fe
theaters, starting in 1957, and on Tuesday, Mozart's ``Magic
Flute,'' in a new production by Jonathan Miller.
</P>
</TEXT>
