<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NEVER TOO SOON TO START WORRYING
</HEADLINE>
  By TIM KEOWN &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's going to be tough for the 49ers to recover
from Sunday's 14-13 win over the New England Patriots. All those
penalties, the costly interceptions, the short kickoffs _ it's just
way too much to dismiss with a wake-me-in-September shrug.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's early. First exhibition game, first week of August,
all that. But you know what? They always tell you it's early until
it's too damned late. Fact is, somebody has to sound the alarm for
sanity here: You let it slide and slide and pretty soon you're
laughing at those holding calls and taking bets on the next offside
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes an institutional thing, like the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mariucci knows. He's a coach, wears a headset, watches a
lot of film. After the game, he said, ``I told all the guys in the
locker room, whether you're handing out water or playing in the
game, that we've got to get better this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Great to see football again, isn't it? Five exhibition games for
everyone to savor. There's so much to worry about, and so much time
to worry. They say the exhibition season doesn't mean anything, but
we know that's not true. If it was, then try to explain why the
coaches still lament the amount of work left to do. Or why the
referees still take forever to explain the obvious. Or why the
cheerleaders still smile their cryogenic smiles.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition season is made for guys like 49ers third-string
quarterback Jim Druckenmiller. He played nearly three quarters
Sunday night, and the stage was his. Beginning in five weeks, it
would take injuries to both Steve Young and Ty Detmer for
Druckenmiller to make his way onto the field, but for now his
performance is going to be dissected with scientific intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Druckenmiller the perfect primer for the worrier's
training camp. You worry about him now, then work your way up to
worrying about Steve Young. It's a progressive thing, like jacks or
better to open.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci started the bidding, saying, ``We're nowhere near where
we need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's why they charge full price for exhibition games:
Druckenmiller played pretty well, but he threw two interceptions
near his own end zone _ one on a pass he never should have thrown
and another on a pass he never should have thrown so hard.
</P>
<P>
   And so afterward, when asked about his second interception,
Druckenmiller said, ``I guess the receivers have got to remember
that with Druck in there, it's coming at you like a howitzer.''
</P>
<P>
   This guy's priceless. It's obvious he needs to play more.
Somebody needs to circulate a petition or something. Promise them a
stadium, or a mall, anything to get this guy more playing time.
Young is thoughtful and articulate, always able to find the right
18-20 words to sum up the whole experience. But Druck _ Druck's in
a different league. Young can't compete with a guy who goes
third-person nickname on himself while in the act of verbally
puffing up.
</P>
<P>
   You remember what Bill Walsh said? He said take Jake Plummer.
Maybe Walsh knew Druck was in the wrong sport at the wrong time.
Druck should have been a baseball player in the '20s and '30s,
riding trains and calling his own shots.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibition games are for guys like Druck and Tony Blevins, a
free-agent cornerback from Kansas. Blevins knows the golden rule
for free-agent rookies: Do something spectacular and hope it comes
while the coaches are paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Blevins tried as hard as humanly possible
to keep a punt inbounds at the goal line, and he succeeded by
twisting his body in several unnatural directions. Frankly, whether
the Patriots started their drive at the 20 or the 1 was completely
immaterial to most everyone on the planet, but for Blevins it was
beyond important. If he does it enough times, they'll put the name
above his locker in something more permanent than tape.
</P>
<P>
   Blevins was no doubt one of the reasons Young said, ``It looks
like our team really likes to play football. I know that sounds
ridiculous, but being a football player you can tell the
difference. In the long run, we'll win games because we have that
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   That alone shouldn't be enough to stop anybody's worrying,
because 13 penalties for 112 yards is Raider football whether the
guys making the penalties like to play football or not. And even
though the first-team offense scored easily on its second
possession, and the first-team defense made Drew Bledsoe look like
Dieter Brock, you can never be too vigilant when it comes to
drawing conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   After all, even the guys who played well shouldn't be spared
your concern. You have to wonder whether some of them, like our
friend Druck, might be in serious danger of peaking too soon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
