<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS HE WILL NOT RUN FOR THE PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is not running for
president, at least for now. But he is not ruling it out, either.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a regular routine whenever he takes questions
from the national news media, Giuliani said Sunday that he was
focused solely on running the nation's largest city, and that he
did not have any plans to run for the nation's highest office in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention at this point of running for any other
office,'' Giuliani said Sunday on ``Fox News Sunday.'' ``When I
have that intention, I'll tell you about it.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he had ruled out such a run, Giuliani backed
away slightly, saying, ``I never completely rule anything out, but
the most important part is, I haven't ruled it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's remarks will likely do little to quash speculation
that he is interested in bringing his brand of moderate
Republicanism to a national stage. In recent months, Giuliani has
traveled to Arizona and other places to point up his record on
crime, welfare reform and civility campaigns. And in October, he
will go to New Hampshire, a state regarded as an early barometer of
presidential aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Giuliani repeated earlier statements about the intention
of the New Hampshire trip, saying that he hoped to broaden the base
of the Republican Party. Giuliani also said that he hoped to
persuade party members to seriously consider selecting New York as
the host of the Republican National Convention in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
