<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS_SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS TOP PATS, COLLECT FLAGS 
BY IRA MILLER
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ No one got seriously hurt and the starters
played at least respectably. On that basis alone, the 49ers'
exhibition opener Sunday was a success.
</P>
<P>
   That's not quite the same, however, as being ready for the
season to begin. Which, of course, they are not, the 14-13 victory
over the New England Patriots notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were called for 17 penalties, 13 of which were
accepted. Six of the penalties were called against first-string
players, five of them in the first quarter alone. ``It made the
game kind of sloppy,'' said coach Steve Mariucci.
</P>
<P>
   And backup quarterback Jim Druckenmiller threw two
interceptions, both of which killed possible scoring drives in the
red zone. In Druckenmiller's defense, one came on a scramble when
his arm was hit, the other off a dropped pass. But several of his
other throws were behind receivers, although he completed 10 of 14
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we can all get better at every phase of our game,''
said Mariucci, who didn't excuse himself, either, saying the 49ers
leaned more on their passing game, especially in the first half,
than he had intended.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci has made a point this summer of talking about how he
plans to open up the offense. But he didn't envision an 18-5
pass-run ratio for the 49ers' first five possessions, which is what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to throw the ball a little bit more, but not to
that extent,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young played only the first two possessions at
quarterback, handling 12 offensive plays and completing five of
nine passes for 64 yards. Young set up the first touchdown with a
perfect 28-yard pitch to reserve wideout Mark Harris on 3rd-and-15
that was just beyond the reach of Patriots cornerback Chris Canty.
A two-yard TD pass to Garrison Hearst followed.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Darnell Walker, who started 11 games for the 49ers
last season, scored the other San Francisco touchdown on a fumble
recovery in the end zone. Jeff Posey, a defensive end who was on
the practice squad last year, forced the fumble, by Scott Zolak,
New England's backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Chris Doleman had an interception for the 49ers,
when he dropped into coverage on a zone blitz. Among youngsters,
safety Lance Schulters, the fourth-round draft choice, made several
eye-opening plays including a near-blocked punt and a late-game
sack.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback R.W. McQuarters, the first-round pick, played much of
the game at right cornerback, but was hardly tested; the Patriots
threw only a couple of passes in his direction, to no effect.
Mariucci said McQuarters would be worked into the nickel and dime
specialty defenses this week in practice.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' first-string defense, missing only free safety Merton
Hanks, did not permit New England's starting offense to cross
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better than the first game last year,'' observed strong safety
Tim McDonald. ``I think our guys wanted to start fast. It was a
pretty solid effort by our starting unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people have taken it for granted that the defense would be
fine this season, and Sunday's performance did nothing to diminish
expectations. New linebacker Winfred Tubbs played effectively, and
new cornerback Antonio Langham did a good job a couple of times
forcing receivers off their routes and out of bounds, according to
defensive coordinator John Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the focus this summer, however, has been on the
offensive line, which seemed to get through the first game without
difficulty, even though it was missing two projected starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anybody get overwhelmed,'' said Bobb McKittrick,
the offensive line coach. ``So from that standpoint, I was pleased.
We've been through a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, though, have the 49ers been through worse with
penalties. To put the 13 accepted penalties in perspective, the
team record for penalties in a regular season game is 15.
</P>
<P>
   Starters flagged were Tubbs, Doleman, tackle Bryant Young and
end Roy Barker on defense and center Chris Dalman and left guard
Ray Brown on offense. The 49ers were called eight times for
offsides on defense, all by different players.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
