<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANGELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX HOLD OFF ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ At this rate, they should have full-color
brochures printed up and sent to travel agencies across New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for an alternative to a Caribbean cruise, a stroll down
the Champs Elysees, or a week in the Swiss Alps?
</P>
<P>
   For a really good time, take a West Coast tour with the Red Sox!
</P>
<P>
   What was once thought to be a nightmare excursion continued to
be a giddy joyride for the Sox, who leaped to an eight-run lead
against the Anaheim Angels, then held on for an 8-7 win that
assured them of a winning record on their spin around the Pacific
Rim.
</P>
<P>
   One of the newest passengers to hop on board, lefthanded
reliever Greg Swindell, joined right in the fun after the Angels
added a few late thrills. Swindell, acquired at the trading
deadline from Minnesota Friday night, struck out two in a scoreless
seventh inning that threw the brakes on the Anaheim comeback, which
began with six runs off Sox starter Tim Wakefield and reliever Rich
Garces and was abetted by a throwing error by Nomar Garciaparra
that allowed the sixth run to score.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Eckersley followed Swindell with an inning of vintage
Eck, fanning two in the eighth, and Tom Gordon rang up his third
save of the trip and league-leading 31st of the season despite
giving up a run on a couple of singles and a force out in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice,'' Swindell said after striking out Jim Edmonds,
retiring cleanup man Tim Salmon on an infield tapper, and striking
out Dave Hollins after Garret Anderson's two-out single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in there, and I was thinking, `Is there any reason for
me to be nervous? I've been playing this game since I was 7 years
old.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I couldn't get any spit in my mouth. First time for a new
team, it was very nerve-wracking. I wanted to do so well. I'm glad
it's over with, and I'll try to build on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who already had taken two of three from Oakland
before sweeping three from the reeling Angels, are 5-1 on this
trip, a season-best 21 games over .500, and have just two games in
Seattle before departing this side of the continent.
</P>
<P>
   They'll have one stop left before going home _ a four-day
dalliance in Texas against the Rangers, who Sunday passed the
Angels as the first-place team in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox also opened some serious distance between themselves
and their closest pursuers in the wild-card chase. Sunday night's
win put them 7 1/2 games ahead of the Angels, who are 9-20 in their
last 29 games, 4-13 in their last 17 at Edison International Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take advantage of this time,'' said Mo Vaughn,
whose two-run home run and 27th of the season in the sixth gave the
Sox an 8-0 lead and proved to be the margin of victory. The home
run also made it 10 straight games in which the Red Sox have hit at
least one homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing well,'' he said, ``but the main thing is, the
road trip is not over yet. We've done some things that have put us
in a pretty good stand, but we have to continue to do the things
we're doing. This team has got to be mentally ready.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one player more nervous than Swindell Sunday, it
was Vaughn, according to Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who has hit in all 10 games since he told a Toronto
newspaper he wanted to play for the Blue Jays next year, spent his
third straight game as Red Sox DH, with Mike Stanley playing first
base. The Sox dugout, Martinez said, was barely big enough to
contain him between at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so nervous,'' Martinez said with a laugh. ``He's jumping
and yelling at everybody. He doesn't know how to be on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who had outscored the Angels, 18-5, in the first
two games here, wasted no time in jumping on Anaheim Sunday night,
giving Wakefield a 4-0 lead before the Angels came to bat. Darren
Lewis singled, John Valentin doubled, and Nomar Garciaparra singled
home Lewis with a broken-bat single, giving him at least one RBI in
his last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary followed with a high chopper that Angels pitcher
Jason Dickson fielded and threw to a vacant first base. Garciaparra
scored from first and O'Leary, who was credited with a single,
wound up on third on the two-base error. Stanley's sacrifice fly
made it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox made it 5-0 without benefit of a hit in the third.
Valentin walked, advanced to third on two wild pitches by Dickson,
who also walked Vaughn, and scored on Garciaparra's infield out.
That was Garciaparra's second RBI of the night, and 16th in the
last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra reached on an infield hit with one out in the fifth,
took second when Stanley drew a two-out walk, and scored when
Darren Bragg shot a single through the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield checked the Angels on just one hit, a second-inning
single by Garret Anderson, through the first five innings, before
being knocked out in the sixth, when he gave up four runs, two on
Anderson's home run. But with his bullpen picking him up, Wakefield
was credited with his 13th win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good,'' said Eckersley, who has been unscored
upon in his last four appearances. ``But I don't want to get
carried away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot more relaxed. It's nice to pitch when we're
winning. That's all you can ask for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
