<HEADER>
A4731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     08-03 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO NEED TO PANIC JUST YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ OK, so they didn't look so good Sunday when it
counted, but before you head to the Tobin Bridge to do a Greg
Louganis, let me give you some advice from the old neighborhood:
``Fahgetta about it!''
</P>
<P>
   For just over the first quarter of their first exhibition game,
the first offense of the New England Patriots stayed on the field
at 3Com Park against a first-rate defense and looked like it had
never left Pittsburgh. The offense seldom moved, and when it did it
went in reverse as often as it went forward. Understandably, this
may have caused you some alarm, bad memories being the most
difficult ones to erase, but fear not.
</P>
<P>
   The performance shortfall applied to most everyone involved,
including quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who was a miserable 3 for 9
with an interception and a fumble; young running back Sedrick Shaw,
who fumbled once to set up the San Francisco 49ers' first touchdown
when he got stung by linebacker Winfred Tubbs; and a corps of wide
receivers who had only three receptions in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   So what did you expect? A juggernaut?
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are installing a new offensive scheme and although
you may have heard that more times than you'd like to the past few
years, Sunday it was a valid explanation for what was, at best, an
underwhelming offensive performance.
</P>
<P>
   New offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese's entire design is based
on timing, and timing comes only with time. Both the timing and the
time necessary to develop it clearly were still missing Sunday, and
so, predictably, there were problems. But thankfully they appeared
to be the kind that can be solved in the simplest of ways: by
returning to Smithfield, R.I., and practicing a few thousand more
snaps, as the Patriots will begin doing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think it's pretty clear we had first-game problems,'' said
coach Pete Carroll. ``We were not real clean with the throwing
game. We've got a lot of cleaning up to do on the offensive side.''
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly true of the running game, which was not much
in evidence, as Shaw and No. 1 pick Robert Edwards failed to do
anything to make you forget the best of Curtis Martin. Of most
concern was the fact that when the varsity was playing it averaged
just 3.3 yards a carry on 16 first-half tries, with Shaw handling
nine (for 34 yards and a 3.8 yard average) and Edwards six for 20
more (3.3 yards a carry). Things went downhill from there, believe
it or not, with New England ultimately rushing for just 88 yards on
32 carries, a 2.8 yards-per-carry average. That number was worse
even than last year's 3.7 yards a carry, which only goes to show
you that just when you think things can't get worse, you learn
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't see anything pop out,'' Carroll said of his
young backs. ``There was nothing to get lit up about.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite problems with field position created by its offense,
New England's defense remained stout. Even though it faced
situations where the Niners began drives at their 44, the New
England 35 twice, and then the 49er 41, the defense surrendered
only one touchdown, and that came only after the 49ers had
recovered Shaw's fumble at the New England 35.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted as well that that fumble came at the end of a
series in which the offense actually showed something by driving
the ball from its 6 to the 37 with some power running that produced
three first downs and reason for hope before Shaw's drop.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco would not score again until backup quarterback
Scott Zolak was sacked and fumbled the ball into the end zone. He
then illegally batted it forward in an attempt to get it back on
the playing field, but instead directed it into the hands of backup
cornerback Darnell Walker, who fell on it for a 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   This situation later would change admirably when the Patriots'
reserves came on in the second half and began to outplay the 49ers'
reserves, closing the lead to 14-13 before time ran out. What that
proved was that the Patriots who will seldom play this year are
better than the 49ers who will seldom play this year.
</P>
<P>
   This is a point that should not be minimized, especially on a
day when the Patriots who will play did not play as well as the
49ers who will play, because ready reserves are a goal of Carroll's
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Backup tight end Lovett Purnell, for one, had himself a day,
catching five passes for 54 yards. So, too, did rookie wide
receiver Tony Simmons, who made six catches for 67 yards. And the
defense's first impression was of a group that had not lost
anything from the way it was playing at the end of last season,
when it was among the stingiest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   So, all in all, this is no time for panic or even much
grumbling. There is plenty of time for the timing to improve.
</P>
<P>
   And even if it doesn't, there's plenty of time for panic later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
