u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-49ERS-BO     08-03 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-49ERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS VICTIMS OF BAD TIMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ Its time has not come.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the new passing game, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was way off. No question about it,'' said new
Patriots offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese. Drew Bledsoe echoed
that, saying, ``If we played like that in a regular-season game,
we'd get beat by any team in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps a college team or two.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots Sunday lost the first of their five exhibition
games in 1998, 14-13 to the San Francisco 49ers at 3Com Park, but
don't be fooled by the score. While the second team seemed to grasp
the Zampese offense much better than the first team, the goal is to
have that the other way around. The good news: Scott Zolak led the
Patriots on two impressive second-half drives against the 49ers'
second-team defense, pulling the team back from a 14-3 deficit at
the half. So New England appears to have some depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott did some good things,'' said coach Pete arroll. ``But he
made a play in the end zone that we can't have from an experienced
backup quarterback in the NFL.'' That came early in the second
quarter when 49ers linebacker Jeff Posey blasted past second-year
offensive tackle Ed Ellis as Zolak dropped back into his end zone
to throw, forcing Zolak to fumble. The 49ers' Darnell Walker fell
on the ball for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise Zolak, who wasn't available to the media after the
game, completed 18 of 34 passes for 181 yards. Six of those passes,
for 67 yards, went to rookie Tony Simmons, a prominent figure in
the two second-half scoring drives. One of the drives produced a
touchdown on 18 plays, the other a 31-yard field goal by Adam
Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll also was not bowled over by the Patriots' running game,
which produced 88 yards on 32 carries. Forty-eight of those yards
came from starter Sedrick Shaw, on 16 carries, a 3-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing really stood out,'' said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Robert Edwards had six carries for 20 yards, but he was
sidelined by a troublesome left groin.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said of his performance, ``I really don't know until I
watch the film.'' He certainly won't like viewing his first-quarter
fumble, when he was hit by linebacker Winfred Tubbs at the Patriot
39. That led to the 49ers' first score, a 2-yard pass from Steve
Young to Garrison Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sedrick had the fumble and that was unfortunate,'' said
Carroll. ``Those plays can really put a team in a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who was in for 25 plays, completed three of his nine
passes for 23 yards and threw an interception to defensive end
Chris Doleman in the first quarter. Terry Glenn caught no passes.
Ditto Vincent Brisby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to play well in this offense right from the
start,'' said Bledsoe. ``I don't think it's going to take five
games. You can't expect to turn the ball over like we did and beat
a team like the 49ers.''
</P>
<P>
   A positive was that the 49ers couldn't throw to Tebucky Jones's
side, as the first-round pick did a nice job in bump-and-run
coverage at right cornerback with the second-team defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I did OK,'' said Jones. ``I got some action and got
my feet wet out there. I wish we'd won. I just have to get better.
It was difficult out there today, but I think I held my own.''
</P>
<P>
   The second offense clicked immediately in the second half. Zolak
directed a 79-yard drive that consumed 8:27 of the third quarter,
culminating in a 1-yard run by Shaw. Nine of the 18 plays were
runs, while Zolak spread the ball in the air to Michigan rookie
Chris Floyd, Simmons, and Lovett Purnell. The touchdown got the
Patriots within 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   On the second drive of the quarter, Zolak directed the team from
its 15 to the 49er 13 before things stalled two plays into the
fourth quarter. Vinatieri booted the second of his two field goals,
a 31-yarder, to bring the Patriots within 14-13.
</P>
<P>
   But Zolak couldn't bring the Patriots all the way back, hindered
by poor field position in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real disappointed we couldn't win that game in the
fourth quarter,'' said Carroll. ``I think it's pretty clear we had
first-game problems. We were not real clean with the throwing game.
We've got a lot of cleaning up to do on the offensive side.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first quarter, Shaw rattled off runs of 6 and 9
yards, but on the second possession and on his third straight
carry, Shaw was nailed by Tubbs.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers went right at Chris Canty, burning him twice on a
drive that was finished with a 2-yard swing pass to Hearst for the
first score of the game.
</P>
<P>
   After Derrick Cullors returned the kickoff 41 yards to the 46,
Bledsoe, who seemed out of sync from the start, became confused by
the 49ers' zone blitz and threw the ball right at Doleman at the
49ers' 40.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Slade bailed out the Patriots by intercepting Jim
Druckenmiller at the Patriot 5, setting up Zolak's fumble.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots ran a decent two-minute offense at the end of the
first half, getting the ball at the 36 after a 29-yard return by
Canty. Vinatieri ended up kicking a 27-yard field goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
