<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA HAS DRUMMED UP SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ The young man who plays the role of the St. Joseph's
Hawk is admired by one and all in the world of college basketball.
Custom dictates that he begin flapping his wings the minute he
takes the floor and never stop until the game is over.
</P>
<P>
   That's impressive. But he does not bang a drum.
</P>
<P>
   Samson Shobowale does. He began banging his drum when the
Nigerian national team came onto the floor Sunday (or perhaps even
sooner), and he did not stop until a good 20 minutes after his team
had blown away South Korea by an 89-65 score, which was about 2 1/2
hours later. Shobowale banged during play. He banged during
timeouts. He banged during the entire halftime break. He banged and
he banged, and it would not have bothered him if the game had gone
four overtimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our tradition to play when the players play,'' he
explains. ``We always have to beat the drum. It is our
communication with the players. It lets them know we are behind
them. We do not get tired of beating the drum. We love doing it, so
why would we get tired?''
</P>
<P>
   Shobowale is an integral part of the best fan group at the World
Basketball Championships. There is some competition from the
ever-joyous Argentines and the colorfully clad Lithuanians, and
there is the obvious national pride being manifested on a nightly
basis by 18,000-plus Greeks. But for sheer joie de vivre, not to
mention sheer endurance, they are all tied for second place behind
the lovable Nigerians, who play music and sing nonstop in support
of their beloved Tigers (and don't ask why they are the Tigers,
since there are no such beasts in Nigeria).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans are great,'' says Obinna Ekezie, the Maryland
senior-to-be who has inherited the center spot from the injured
Yinka Dare (tendinits of the shoulder, or so they say). ``They give
us the extra energy to go out there and perform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are out there playing, you do not always hear them
because you are concentrating on the game,'' says guard Mohammed
Acha. ``But you hear them during a foul shot or a timeout, and they
give you a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Music is provided by three drums, two trumpet players (they get
a little break) and assorted noisemakers. Song and dance is
provided by everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sing songs to praise God,'' explains Shobowale. ``We sing
songs to praise the players. We sing songs to praise ourselves. We
sing songs to inspire our team. It is the music of inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is not going to win a medal, but Nigeria is not a bad
team. The leading scorer Sunday was none other than former Boston
University great Tunji Awojobi, who had 24 points on an assortment
of inside moves and a few face-up jumpers. He is one of seven
members of the 12-man roster who play professionally in Europe or
Asia. Ekezie, a Maryland starter, is one of three Division 1
American college players. Godwin Owinue played in the CBA last
year. And there is the perpetually underachieving Dare, whose
lackluster play in the team's first three games means he was not
missed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers are an amazing story because, in truth, they hardly
know each other. They congregated in Lagos for, depending on whom
you believe, somewhere between four and 10 days before coming here
for this tournament. Coach Ayo Bakare says the team had perhaps 20
practices, which is about 10 more than the players claim. But it is
evident that if this team had just a little more time together, it
could have made some noise in the championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just starting to become a team,'' laments Ekezie.
``Each of these players was a big man on his team. It is not easy
for some of them to give up a shot to another man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting better and better,'' says Bakare. ``We have had
an awesome improvement. With just a couple of more weeks together,
three, perhaps, we could be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   His immediate concern is an ever-shrinking roster. With the drug
suspension of center Julius Nowsu and a run of injuries, he
possibly will dress just seven men for Monday's 13th-place game
against Japan. ``The fans will help us get through this,'' says the
6-foot-7-inch Awojobi, who can expect to go 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria was in a tough bracket in which it lost close games to
Argentina and Australia, medal contenders both. This is Nigeria's
first trip to the World Championships, and with Sunday's victory
they have achieved the minimum goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't come in dead last,'' grins Ekezie, who says he never
had played basketball before learning the game at Worcester
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   They will play their final game at the 1998 World Basketball
Championships Monday, and they will not be doing it alone. ``We
will be there for them,'' says Shobowale, who, incidentally, is
Awojobi's brother, and who says he watched Tunji's great game
against Drexel two years ago live via satellite. ``When the team
sees us there, it can never go down. And if it does go down, it
will go down fighting. We fight for our team and for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentleman, commence banging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
