<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-TOUR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANTANI PREVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
 DE FRANCE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Marco Pantani took the winner's place on the Tour de
France podium here Sunday, marking the first time an Italian stood
there in 33 years. In second place was Jan Ullrich, of Germany, who
won the race last year. And right behind them, in third place, was
Bobby Julich of Glenwood Springs, Colo., the highest American Tour
finisher since Greg LeMond won it in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Tour de France should have been a celebration for
almost everyone. Instead, when the race came limping into Paris
there almost a sigh of relief from riders and spectators that it
was over. It hadn't been killed, but it had been so decimated by
dropouts and accusations of drug use it was far from the spectacle
it has been for the past 84 years. One team was kicked out during
the first week and more riders bailed out over the next two weeks,
leaving only 14 of the original 21 teams.
</P>
<P>
   So even though Pantani had dyed his goatee and mustache blond to
match his yellow jersey, it was clear the glitter has faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy because all the bad times I have are now
ended,'' said Pantani, 28, who crashed into a car during a race in
1995 and broke his leg in two places. ``But my first victory in the
Tour de France was most difficult because of all the doping stories
and the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantani only won two stages in the three-week event that started
in Dublin July 11. But his total time of 92 hours 49 minutes 46
seconds was more than three minutes ahead of Ullrich, and three
hours in front of last-place finisher Damien Nazon. Pantani will
collect $440,000 for his win.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, who finished third overall last year, won the ``Giro,''
or Tour of Italy, in June. He's the first winner of both Tours
since Miguel Indurain of Spain in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Julich, 26, seemed content with his third-place win that was
good for $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's from another planet,'' Julich said of Pantani. ``It's
something to tell your grandchildren that you raced in the same
pack with the winner of the Giro and the Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only fitting that a steady rain was coming down as the
riders started the final 92-mile race into Paris. But as they hit
the Champs Elysees the skies cleared, and the pack circled the road
from the Arc de Triomphe to the Place de la Concorde 10 times to
build up for a sprint to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Steels of Belgium jumped over the line first, claiming his
fourth stage win.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow jersey was passed around the first week, with
American George Hincapie coming within seconds of wearing it. But
when Ullrich took it over last weekend, it looked like the race
might be a repeat of last year.
</P>
<P>
   That was, until last Monday, when Pantani made his way up one of
the Tour's steepest mountains in the Alps, cutting through the rain
and fog to make a statement. He not only won the stage, beating
Ullrich by almost eight minutes, but he took over the leader's spot
and wore the yellow jersey until the end.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the Tour was marred by the police investigations for
drugs, and two interruptions _ one in which the protesting riders
delayed the start of a stage for two hours, and one in which they
rode so slowly the stage was nullified. Seven teams left the Tour,
and seven people have been placed under formal investigation for
doping-related charges, including one rider, Italian Rodolfo Massi.
</P>
<P>
   So as the daily headlines blared more about drugs than racing,
fans seemed to grow resentful. Some of the hundreds of thousands
who lined the route, which covered 2,400 miles, held signs that
read, ``EPO Gratuit, (EPO for free),'' referring to the illegal
blood-enhancer. One said, ``Il Tour Est Mort (The Tour is Dead)''.
</P>
<P>
   Others defended the race, however, and held signs that read,
``Tour '98: Injustice,'' or ``Viva le Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The riders had mixed emotions, too. Tyler Hamilton, of
Brookline, Mass., said of the drug investigation, ``I think a lot
of positives will come from this.'' But Laurent Jalabert, the
leader of both strikes, said racers were ``being treated like
cattle'' before he dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour went on, but without riders like Richard Virenque, who
was second in last year's race; No. 1 ranked Jalabert; Fernando
Escartin, who had been fourth overall; and Massi, who was seventh
overall and wore the climber's jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The US Postal Service team had something to cheer about _ sort
of. The squad was one of only two to have all nine riders cross the
finish line. But co-general manager Mark Gorski acknowledged that
it was an almost hollow victory in light of so many dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have to overlook whatever shadow might be over these
results and know that the Tour de France is going to happen next
year,'' he said. ``The sport is going to go on. The success and
continued existence of cycling may be clouded, and it's definitely
going to be impacted, but it's going to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Team member Jean-Cyril Robin, of France, placed sixth overall,
and Dariusz Baranowski 12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would J.C. have been sixth in the race if he hadn't been
impacted by some of these defections and dropouts?'' Gorski said.
``Probably not, but he may be top 10. So we've reached a lot of our
goals. We've got a great spirit on our team and I'm really proud of
that. The guys have gone through this experience and I think
they've probably learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who finished 51st overall, said he'll stay in Europe
to continue racing through the end of August before he heads back
to New England, where he'll probably compete in the Killington,
Vt., stage race in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had much to brag about, from Julich's third-place
finish to teammate Kevin Livingston's 17th-place finish to
Hincapie's near miss of the yellow jersey to Hamilton's near miss
of a stage win.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of it all was three-time Tour winner LeMond, who
was never seen at the finish but was leading a bike tour along
different stretches of the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   And it's no doubt that Julich, the new American on the racing
scene, felt the presence of the former champion. He is, after all,
following in LeMond's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked for this since I watched it on TV,'' Julich said.
``I knew right away that was my destiny, to be in the Tour de
France.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's not just in it _ he's at the top of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
