<HEADLINE>
VALDERRAMA DEAL STILL UP IN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ MLS commissioner Doug Logan expects Carlos
Valderrama to join the Revolution before Wednesday's game against
San Jose. But Valderrama said Sunday he might remain in Florida,
possibly returning to Tampa Bay, where he owns a house and where he
played in 1996 and '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things to consider about New England, such as
the cold weather,'' Valderrama said after playing the World team in
a 6-1 loss to the US in the MLS All-Star game Sunday. ``It is a
difficult decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan hoped to announce that Valderrama and a Miami domestic
player would be exchanged for Joe-Max Moore and a Revolution
foreigner. MLS deputy commissioner Sunil Gulati met with Valderrama
in an attempt to conclude the deal Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution apparently wanted to discard Dutchman Richard
Goulooze, who was signed to replace Francis Okaroh in central
defense and has failed to make an impact at other positions. But
the Fusion balked at taking Goulooze, a cousin of coach Thomas
Rongen's, who has a three-year contract, preferring David Nakhid.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's eagerness to part with Goulooze highlights the
apparent error in expecting him to replace Okaroh. And in a league
with a salary cap, such a mistake can be costly. The Revolution
have the worst record in MLS with 16 points in 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have told the league what player we want,'' Miami general
manager Leo Stillitano said. ``It is up to the league to make the
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami was also reluctant to part with defender Leo Cullen,
instead offering Matt Kmosko.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos wants to come to New England,'' Rongen said. ``If my
hunch is right he will be in a Revolution uniform. I made good eye
contact with him and his eyes had a sparkle in them. Carlos's eyes
speak volumes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rongen said the Revolution have made sacrifices to accommodate
the trade, which became a possibility after Valderrama clashed with
new Miami coach Ivo Wortmann.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two major players in the deal are Carlos and Joe-Max but
the two secondary players could be very important,'' Rongen said.
``We have given in other areas, giving up on getting another player
from another team. We have tried hard to make the deal happen.
There comes a point when it's got to make sense for both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Revolution acquire Valderrama, they must discard a
foreigner. They also hope to make a separate deal to sign Vladan
Vicevic, a naturalized Salvadoran from Yugoslavia. Vicevic, a
defensive midfielder, moved to El Salvador to play professionally,
then was recruited to the national team by former coach Milovan
Djoric. Vicevic joined El Salvador for World Cup qualifying and
played in a 4-2 loss to the US at Foxboro Stadium in November.
</P>
<P>
   The main ingredient, though, is Valderrama, who could not only
salvage the Revolution's playoff hopes but also Rongen's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a unique relationship with Carlos, in effect a
lifetime contract,'' Logan said. ``We respect him as a professional
and want him to finish his playing career in this league. I am
confident we will find a place for him, probably before the next
regular-season game (Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a problem with the new coach in Miami. Any time a new
coach comes in, there is a period of great tension and stress.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems all might have been solved if the league had simply
traded coaches _ Rongen for Wortmann _ which would have reunited
Rongen and Valderrama and returned Rongen to South Florida, where
he has had his greatest coaching success. But Logan said such a
deal ``will not happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
