<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NEWCOMERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWINDELL, MERCED ENJOY NEW SURROUNDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Greg Swindell was reading a bedtime story to
his daughters Brenna and Sophia late Friday night, after he'd come
back from the ballpark, when the phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the story? ``Where Do Bears Sleep,'' Swindell said,
``but I had to cut it short.''
</P>
<P>
   The Swindell kids may not have found out where bears sleep, but
they soon discovered that their daddy would be needing a pillow in
Boston, after he picked up the phone shortly after the midnight
trading deadline Friday and was told by Twins general manager Terry
Ryan that he'd been traded to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Swindell's teammate in Minnesota, Orlando Merced, already had
come back from the ballpark that night, too, convinced that his
request for a trade had gone unfulfilled. He said as much to his
wife, Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was about 90 seconds before the deadline, and I
looked at my wife and said, `Hey, baby, we're not going anywhere,
we might as well swallow it,''' Merced said.
</P>
<P>
   Merced had the TV on, he said, and ESPN was just announcing that
the trading deadline had arrived. Just then, his phone rang, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Terry Ryan, saying, `You're going to Boston,''' Merced
said. ``My wife started jumping all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   The newest members of the Red Sox were both in their new
uniforms Sunday. Merced, a lefthanded-hitting first
baseman-outfielder who has had just two at-bats in the last two
weeks, was not in the Sox' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Swindell, meanwhile, was on call, the latest candidate for a job
that has gone undone all season, a dependable lefthander out of the
bullpen. Swindell doesn't have the fastball with which he won 18
games for Cleveland in 1988, but it's still his weapon of choice.
``I always go to that if I'm in trouble,'' he said. ``It's the only
pitch I really rely on.''
</P>
<P>
   A starter for his entire career until signing with the Twins two
years ago, Swindell, 33, gestured across the Sox clubhouse, where
catcher Scott Hatteberg was sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started two games in spring training my first year with the
Twins,'' Swindell said, ``both against the Red Sox. Hatteberg got
me put in the bullpen. He hit two home runs in one game, and after
that, I went to the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The move has been a fortuitous one for Swindell, who was
released by both the Astros and Indians in 1996 and thought his
career might be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was almost ready to quit,'' he said, ``then January rolls
around and you get that feeling again.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this has prolonged my career. And hopefully, I'll get
in the playoffs this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Swindell, a jumbo-sized Texan (6 feet 3 inches, 230 pounds) who
followed Roger Clemens to the University of Texas, made his major
league debut 12 years ago for the Indians against the Red Sox, but
never has played in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Merced, meanwhile, was with Pittsburgh teams that lost to Jimy
Williams's Braves in both the 1991 and '92 National League
Championship Series. He hasn't been back to the postseason since,
and after having shoulder surgery last season, in his one year in
Toronto, Merced passed up a chance last winter to join the Red Sox,
signing a minor league contract with the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of his time in Minnesota, neither the team nor the
player was happy. ``No matter what I did,'' Merced said, ``I got in
the doghouse. I tried to hang in there, but the less I played, the
more frustrated I got.''
</P>
<P>
   Merced, who never had the reputation of being a problem player
for either Jim Leyland in Pittsburgh or Cito Gaston in Toronto, had
a major falling out with Tom Kelly in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   He said Kelly apparently became upset with him after he went
into the manager's office and asked if he could play more. ``I
never asked him to play me every day,'' he said. ``I wanted to see
if I could help the club more. But he shut me down. I guess he
didn't like me asking him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like Fidel Castro. I'm more pro-democrat. We never
really got along. I can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Merced, asked about an incident in Chicago in which he was back
in the clubhouse reading a newspaper in the ninth inning of a game
in which Kelly was looking for him to pinch hit, Merced said it was
common for him to go back to the clubhouse to prepare for an
at-bat. ``I already had stretched,'' he said. ``I was watching the
game on TV. Mentally, I was ready. It was a miscommunication
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he said, an incident in which he ripped up the lineup
card in Oakland a couple of days later was misconstrued. He said he
was leaning against the wall on which the lineup card was posted,
accidentally knocked it off the wall, and impulsively ripped it up.
Even his teammates took notice of that, Merced said, including
Swindell, who asked him about his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Greg, `If people think I was disrespecting my
teammates, I apologize,''' Merced said. ``But that wasn't it.
Everything I did, people were watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get out of there because I wasn't playing.''
</P>
<P>
   His wish granted, Merced said he was ecstatic to be with the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great situation, a great tradition,'' he said. ``I
want to thank the people responsible for getting me here.
Hopefully, I'll pick up where I left off before I quit playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
