<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ZOLAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOLAK TAKES BAD WITH GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scott Zolak's season normally is drawing to a
close right about now. Such is life as New England's backup
quarterback, especially when you're riding in Drew Bledsoe's
sidecar.
</P>
<P>
   Life as Bledsoe's second makes for a hot July, a busy August,
and standing sentry on the sideline for most of the autumn and
early winter.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday Zolak was one busy backup, moving in for an
ineffective Bledsoe in the second quarter, surviving some early
rough going, and getting the offensive game to percolate a little
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Scott battled well,'' said coach Pete Carroll. ``He
made that one terrible play in the end zone ...''
</P>
<P>
   The play in question came with just more than a minute remaining
in the first half, with the Patriots on their 5. Zolak dropped back
into the end zone and, under pressure by Jeff Posey, dropped the
ball around his feet.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, conventional wisdom would have called for a swat
of the ball. Zolak's wisdom prevailed, but his execution was
lacking. He swatted the ball, handball-like, only he knocked the
ball toward the goal line rather than out of bounds. What might
have been a safety, a 2-point hit for the Patriots, instead turned
into a touchdown when Darnell Walker pounced on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a desperation, garbage play,'' said Carroll.
``It's the type of play we can't have from an experienced backup
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Zolak is entering his eighth season in a New
England uniform. He has logged the years, but his experience as a
backup has dwindled significantly in the Bledsoe years. Witness: 10
passes, 7 completions for 68 yards the last two seasons. Inactivity
such as that leads to swatting balls in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak was among the first Patriots out of the dressing room
after the loss and security guards prevented media from approaching
the New England bus after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's appraisal of Bledsoe, agreeing that his No. 1
playcaller looked out of sync: ``It's just one thing or the other.
It just wasn't as clean as we would have liked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
