<HEADLINE>
TOO EARLY TOO TELL IF SHAW HAS LEGS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The coming weeks and months will tell us if more
than a pair of legs left town when Curtis Martin wandered away from
the Patriots to play under Bill Parcells's loving hand and kind
arm, not to mention Leon Hess's pile of cash.
</P>
<P>
   But as of Sunday night, 60 minutes into the
relevant-only-if-you-want-it-to-be exhibition season, Martin's free
agent walkaway had the Patriots' running game spinning its wheels _
wheels that went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was just average ... I didn't see anything
special,'' said Patriots coach Pete Carroll about the work of his
backfield in Sunday's 14-13 loss to the 49ers. ``No one got to the
hole clean, and the unfortunate part was Sedrick's fumble.''
</P>
<P>
   Sedrick Shaw, last seen as the Patriots' last hope when the 1997
season ended in Pittsburgh, finished with 48 yards on 16 carries,
which made him about half the New England ground game (32 carries,
88 yards). The second-year back, who didn't run for a yard in the
'97 regular season, opened the New England offense Sunday with two
carries that netted 8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But a decent start quickly turned into false hope. With the
Patriots on their own 37, on second and 9, Shaw got popped at the
line of scrimmage, lost the ball, and watched it fall into the
clutches of 49ers linebacker Lee Woodall. One drive. One turnover.
One large question mark hung over the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a good play, I'll just leave it at that,'' said Shaw.
``What happened? I won't know until I watch the film.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when he didn't look capable of running to daylight,
Shaw spent much of his brief time in a postgame interview telling
the media that he won't know what to say about his performance
until the lights are turned down low and he can watch tapes. Who
knows, maybe the movie will be better than the stat book. It's
often that way at the cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw scored New England's only touchdown, a 1-yard dive at 6:33
of the third quarter that helped cut San Francisco's lead to 14-10.
And overall, there was nothing dreadful about anything Shaw did,
just as there was not much bad to say about the work of Harold Shaw
(8 carries, 22 yards) or Robert Edwards (6 carries, 20 yards). On
the flip side, however, no one looked good lugging the ball, and
with a whole new passing game being implemented this season by
offensive czar Ernie Zampese, someone at some point is going to
have to seize the day on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is football, you are going to have your ups and
downs,'' said Sedrick Shaw, who saw slighty more of the latter in
his '98 debut. ``You are just going to have to try and show
consistency. I think I feel all right. I'll watch the film, take
everything to heart, and see what I have to improve on.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is, does Shaw have the speed, power, and quickness
to be an NFL running back? Based on 16 average-to-lackluster
carries Sunday, no one would have him labeled for Canton, Ohio.
That's precisely what Parcells once said about Martin, when the two
were cozying up, symbiotic-like, on Route 1. Who knew then that
Parcells had Martin pegged more for Fort Knox than the Hall of
Fame?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm taking it all in stride,'' said Shaw, repeating
his mantra. ``I'll have to watch the film. The system is real good.
It's simple, not very complicated. It's timing, basically, and
everyone has to get it together.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what interaction he had on the sideline with the coaching
staff, Shaw made it sound like there wasn't much to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running back is instinctive,'' said Shaw. ``Things are
happening out there ... it's hard to tell anybody what to look
for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
