<SLUG> BC-CAR-PENNZOIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE HAUL FOR HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
 200-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ There was a perfect symmetry to it all.
</P>
<P>
   After his father, Tommy, turned the first lap at New Hampshire
International Speedway in a Busch Grand National car in 1990, Andy
Houston made his first visit to NHIS as a NASCAR Craftsman Truck
Series rookie a triumphant one by winning the first truck race of
his career in Sunday's Pennzoil/VIP Discount Auto Centers 200.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Houston arrived in victory lane after laying down a few
victory doughnuts in his No. 60 Addington Racing Chevrolet, he was
greeted by his beaming father, who, in his glittering career that
spanned a record 417 Busch races, never won at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a really special moment, and I won't ever forget that
for a long time,'' Houston said of the victory lane meeting with
his father. ``He's just been retired from racing for a couple of
years now, and it's really hard for him. He's raced _ I don't know
_ for 30 years, and to be there standing in the pits and not being
behind the wheel was pretty tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me when I got to victory lane, `I knew that I was
going to get to victory lane again.' He said, `I might not have
been driving, but we're here.' So it was just a special moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tommy Houston, winner of 24 Busch Grand National races, ``I
have never won a race in my life that felt as good as seeing that
boy come down there for the checkered flag. He drove one heck of a
race. He drove a smart race.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, 27, a native of Hickory, N.C., became the first NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series rookie to win this season after outdueling
fellow rookie Greg Biffle in a dazzling last-lap duel. Biffle
finished runner-up in his No. 50 Grainger Racing Ford F-150 when he
surrendered the lead to Houston in the final turn of the 200-lap
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clean,'' said Biffle, who swapped paint with Houston in
a last-lap drag race down the backstretch into Turn 3. ``I was just
trying to keep him down on the bottom of the racetrack to keep him
from getting into the corner good. I was just trying to do all I
could.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time rookies finished 1-2 since Kenny Irwin,
Boris Said, and Rick Crawford finished 1-2-3 last June 6 at Texas.
Houston's victory, which was the first by a rookie since Irwin's
Texas triumph, vaulted him from 15th to 10th in the point standings
(1,768) and paid $44,575. ``It wasn't quite what Jeff Gordon
made,'' Houston joked, referring to Gordon's $1 million windfall
from his Brickyard 400 victory. ``But I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a race that was highlighted by green-flag pit stops _ a first
in series history _ Houston capitalized on a winning pit strategy
developed by crew chief Rick Ren that called for a ``short pit''
for right-side tires on Lap 73. Twenty laps later, Houston came in
for left-side rubber and, on a green flag stop on Lap 162, pitted
for right-side tires and fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would've been in trouble if a caution came out,'' said
Houston, who survived a spark plug problem at the start of the race
and a pit-row fender bender with race leader Ron Hornaday to lead
three times for 56 laps. ``We were banking on it going green the
whole way. But I think getting right-side tires and fuel was what
really helped us.''
</P>
<P>
   It enabled Houston to put some serious heat on third-place
finisher Joe Ruttman and, at the very end, on Biffle, who fell out
of the lead when he was tapped from behind by Houston in Turn 4 of
the last lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We touched from the middle of Turn 1 and 2 to the middle of
Turn 3 and 4,'' Houston said. ``Then we weren't touching anymore
and I was looking at the checkered flag.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dale Shaw, of Center Conway, N.H., battled battery problems on
the last lap to hold off a hard-charging Brad Leighton, of Center
Harbor, N.H., to win the Pennzoil/VIP Discount 100 Busch North
Series race. ``Another 50 feet of racing, and he would've caught
me,'' said Shaw, who pocketed $23,800 for his 13th career Busch
North victory. ``But I was just driving it as hard as I could at
the end.'' ... After crashing his primary car Saturday and starting
40th, Mike Stefanik, of Coventry, R.I., survived a crash-marred
Featherlite Modified Tour event _ which was stopped five laps from
the finish to clear an eight-car melee _ and outraced Reggie
Ruggiero on the last lap to take the checkered flag in the third
and final race of the Pennzoil/VIP Discount Auto Centers
tripleheader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
