<SLUG> BC-RAC-SPICY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNOVATE WINS TURF WAR AT ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
 LIVING HANDICAP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ How good is Innovate?
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old proved she was the champion filly over the
Rockingham Park turf course Sunday, winning the $75,000 Spicy
Living Sweepstakes Handicap to back up her victory in the Rock
Breeders' Cup July 5. The question now is: can the talented
daughter of Relaunch do some serious business against the heavy
hitters at Saratoga?
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Innovate, who is owned by Willam Clifton Jr., and
the Rudlein Stable and trained by H. James Bond, was more
impressive in the Spicy Living than she was in the Rock Breeders'
Cup, swinging out from behind three horses turning for home and
motoring to the wire 1 3/4 lengths in front of Hero's Pride. Local
standout Sandy Gator ran hard and had the lead in midstretch, but
finished third, a half-length farther back.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Innovate was the second choice at 9-5 ($5.60)
under Frank Lovato despite her heroics here in July. Hero's Pride,
from the outstanding turf barn of trainer Christophe Clement, was
favored at 7-5 with Chris DeCarlo, coming off a strong allowance
win at Belmont Park. But when the real running started, Hero's
Pride could not match strides with Innovate to the wire despite
Hero's Pride having gained the lead between calls. Innovate had
defeated another Clement-trained horse, Heaven's Command, to take
the Rock Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Gator, ridden by Rudy Baez, was part of a three-horse
entry (including Nana's Toy, who was fourth, and Tara's Reward,
sixth) trained by Jimmy Hartley. She tried her best, which wasn't
quite good enough. Innovate tallied in the fast time of 1:47 2/5
for the ``about'' one mile and one-eighth distance over the grass.
The course record is 1:45 4/5 (Kiri's Clown in 1995) and the stakes
record is 1:46 4/5 (Via Borghese, '93).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very concerned entering the stretch because I had two
horses in the entry (Tara's Reward, who set the early pace, and
Sandy Gator) in front of me and Clement's filly on the outside of
me,'' said Lovato. ``I was definitely concerned with the traffic
setup. Innovate was beautiful today. She was patient and it allowed
me to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I finally did get clear, I had to wake her and put her
into a dead drive. After three or four strides, she was gone. It
was unbelievable. I was shocked at how fast she finished that last
eighth. It was incredible. I think she'll fit in at Saratoga. Both
of the Clement fillies she's run against have been competitive up
there. She will be dangerous. She showed them she's got ability and
class. She's just getting to be her best.''
</P>
<P>
   DeCarlo made no mistakes with Hero's Pride, Innovate was just
too strong. ``I was surprised to see her go past me,'' said
DeCarlo. ``I left her at the three-eighths pole and she was boxed
in. My horse ran hard but the other horse was too good. I think the
ground might have been a little too hard for my mare,'' who
previously raced in Europe. ``But I knew Lovato was going to have
to track us. I went when the time was right. Innovate is just
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to Innovate's success was an operation to correct an
entrapped epiglottis that her camp discovered after she ran third
in a stakes race at Hialeah in May. Since the breathing problem was
corrected, she has authored the two fine efforts at Rock, and Bond,
who is based at The Spa, will be studying the Saratoga condition
book to find the right spot for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really ready for this race,'' said Carlos Correa, an
assistant to Bond. ``She was sharper for this one than the first
one. My boss was very confident in her and she ran the way she was
training. We have her good right now, that's the main thing. We
don't know how good she is. We'll give her a shot in the big time
now that we have her confidence up. Whatever her next assignment
is, it will be at Saratoga.''
</P>
</TEXT>
