<HEADER>
A4873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     08-03 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 9.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MEN GIVING MONEY, WOMEN YELLING: INTERSECTING STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alice Mattison. Quill/Morrow, $13.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the New Haven, Conn., teachers, lawyers and social
workers who populate these whimsical tales are domestic but hardly
domesticated, as they squirm in the intellectual and social shadow
cast by Yale. ``Mattison is a charmer,'' Dwight Garner said last
year in the Book Review. ``It's a joy to tune into her characters'
thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WOMEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Hilton Als. Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $11.
</P>
<P>
   Three quirky, highly personal portraits explore the themes of
racial and sexual identity by mixing memoir, literary criticism and
reflections on politics and psychology. The subjects are the
author's spirited mother, who moved to Brooklyn from Barbados;
Dorothy Dean, a brilliant but self-destructive fixture in New
York's gay scene in the '60s and '70s; and the Harlem poet and
dramatist Owen Dodson, who was Hilton Als's mentor and lover. In
1997 our reviewer, Andrea Lee, admired the ``almost magical
cohesiveness'' of these ``truly original'' essays, calling this ``a
book to read several times, noting how its application grows
broader and broader upon consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD BROTHER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Chris Offutt. Scribner, $12.
</P>
<P>
   After his brother is killed, Virgil Caudill tries to escape a
blood feud in his Kentucky hill town by fleeing to Montana, but he
can't shake the past or the psychological pull of his homeland.
Last year in these pages, Jo Ann Kiser called this ``a fine first
novel by a fierce writer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; T. REX AND THE CRATER OF DOOM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Walter Alvarez. Vintage, $13.
</P>
<P>
   A geologist describes how the discovery of a giant
65-million-year-old crater in Yucatan helped advance the once
scandalous theory that a comet or asteroid killed off the dinosaurs
(and nine-tenths of the planet's species at the time). Last year
our reviewer, Timothy Ferris, called this a ``deft and readable ...
account from the world's leading authority on death from above.''
In  &UR; DINOSAUR LIVES: UNEARTHING AN EVOLUTIONARY SAGA &LR; , by John R.
Horner and Edwin Dobb (Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13), a leading
paleontologist and bone collector explains his craft and uses the
fossil record to offer fascinating ideas about how dinosaurs lived
and evolved. ``We can't all study dinosaurs, but books like this
mean we can all enjoy the process and the results,'' Philip
Gingerich wrote here in 1997. Back in the Holocene, the creatures
described in  &UR; THE MODERN ARK. THE STORY OF ZOOS: PAST, PRESENT AND
FUTURE &LR; , by Vicki Croke (Bard/Avon, $12), benefit from the author's
close-up observation of their lives in captivity. Combining history
with vivid accounts of maulings, this is an ``absorbing,
provocative book,'' Carol Peace Robins said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CORNERSTONE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Zoe Oldenbourg. Translated by Edward Hyams. Carroll &AMP; Graf,
$14.95.
</P>
<P>
   The title of this somber historical novel, which has just been
restored to print, refers to Christianity in 13th-century France
and the struggle among the members of a landowning family in
Champagne to build spiritual values in the squalid, bloody age of
chivalry. The result, Elizabeth Janeway said here in 1955, is ``a
vital book, and a rich one'' by an author of ''very substantial
talent.'' Three hundred years later in the New World, the events of
 &UR; AZTEC AUTUMN &LR; , by Gary Jennings (Tor/ Tom Doherty, $6.99), unfold
during another brutal time, in the years after the invasion of
Mexico by the conquistadors. The hero is a young Aztec who plots
revenge after witnessing the death of his father at the hands of
the Spaniards. ``Jennings's fascinating if often gory novel is
guided by exhaustive research,'' Charles Salzberg said here last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOE IS I: THE GRAMMARPHOBE'S GUIDE TO BETTER ENGLISH IN PLAIN
ENGLISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia T. O'Conner. Riverhead, $11.
</P>
<P>
   With chapter titles like ``Death Sentence: Do Cliches Deserve to
Die?'' and ``Comma Sutra: The Joy of Punctuation,'' it's fair to
assume that this grammar book, written by a former editor at The
New York Times Book Review, is irreverent and reader-friendly. But
it's also surprisingly useful. In 1996 our reviewer, Daniel
Pinkwater, called the guide ``lighthearted and funny.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERONIMO REX &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Barry Hannah. Grove, $12.
</P>
<P>
   The author's audacious first novel follows the larger-than-life
comic exploits of Harriman Monroe as he romps through the South in
the 1950s and '60s. When it was first published in 1972, our
reviewer, Jim Harrison, called this ``a stunning piece of
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUNGRY GHOSTS: MAO'S SECRET FAMINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jasper Becker. Owl/Holt, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   A journalist re-creates in chilling detail the 1959-61 famine
that killed up to 30 million Chinese, a calamity caused by the
obstinacy of the nation's ruthless, ideologically driven leaders.
The book, with a new afterword on the current famine in North
Korea, is ``powerful and important,'' Nicholas Eberstadt wrote here
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXILES: THREE SHORT NOVELS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Philip Caputo. Vintage Contemporaries, $13.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in Micronesia, suburban Connecticut or Vietnam, the
misfit heroes in this collection are outsiders whose defects lead
them into trouble. Last year in these pages, David Haward Bain said
two of three stories displayed the author's ``extraordinary eye for
the exotica of locale and behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 0846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
