<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The enduring Castro
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 5, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There are some things that just won't go away. Examples:
nuclear waste, Monica Lewinsky's dress _ and Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Last week was a wickedly interesting period on the Castro front.
</P>
<P>
   He triumphantly toured three English-speaking Caribbean islands,
including Grenada, from where his ``workers'' were expelled 15
years ago by U.S. troops. Throughout the Caribbean, including the
three visited nations, calls echoed for the end of the U.S.'s
37-year-old embargo on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   As Castro reveled in a 21-gun salute in Grenada and sympathy for
the isolation of his island by the U.S., his enemies continued to
tear at each other, both in the U.S. and elsewhere. Liars called
liars ``liars,'' and the gullible stood by their gullibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban exile community, physically and emotionally scarred by
years of political doublespeak from no less than nine different
White House occupants and hordes of congressional types, and
cannibalized by internecine squabbling, seems more involved now
with putting out internal fires than figuratively lighting any in
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   And the media isn't helping matters much.
</P>
<P>
   Even The New York Times appears to have given too much credence
to a man who first claimed that the late Jorge Mas Canosa and the
Cuban American National Foundation (CANF) paid him to launch
terrorist attacks on Havana hotels last year.
</P>
<P>
   When the Times printed that story, an enraged Miami-based CANF
not only denied involvement in terrorism but threatened to drop a
libel suit on the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the story, an aging, admitted terrorist, now says
he lied to the Times reporter and that the reporter should have
done a better job of checking out his story. (Everyone, it seems,
complains about the media _ even the ones who corrupt them.)
</P>
<P>
   The Times, oddly, says it is standing by its story because that
is what the source told the paper. There's nothing like a direct
quote, even if it is a lie.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, and while Castro was polishing his belt buckle
for his trip to Jamaica, Barbados and Grenada, a woman stepped
forward to claim that she was part of a surgical team that treated
Castro for a brain disorder last year.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was El Nuevo Herald, the Spanish-language edition
of the Miami Herald, that was doing the reporting. Naturally, the
Castro government denied it. Then people within the Cuban exile
community began wondering about the woman. There were questions as
to how long ago she defected to Costa Rica and whether she really
was a doctor, and ultimately her ex-husband living in Colombia
reported the woman was a total fraud: not a doctor, not even a
nurse. He said she was a teller of tall tales.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban diaspora is particularly painful. U.S. presidents have
promised them an end to Castro but have not delivered. Instead,
they invoked U.S. neutrality acts and told the CIA-trained exile
operatives to behave themselves _ sell limes on street corners, or
insurance, but don't do what we trained you for.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, self-proclaimed militants would say they have
returned to Miami from raids on the Cuban coast when, in truth,
they never went anywhere other than the neighborhood coffee stand.
These fouled the deeds of the militants who actually performed
anti-Castro raids before the U.S. muscled them out of business.
</P>
<P>
   In the almost four decades of Castro's dictatorship, he has
successfully twisted the U.S. embargo to be the sole reason for all
that is wrong in Cuba. We gave him that opportunity, and continue
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And in Miami, those who years earlier felt his spiked heel
stagger in rumor, belief and disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   First Jack Nicholson turns up in Havana and praises Castro, then
a 21-gun salute for him in Grenada. ``This must be as good as it
gets,'' Castro probably is thinking to himself.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
