<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Death, yes; taxes, no _ so says Big Tobbaco
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you still have any doubts about just how cynically the
tobacco companies have been jerking you around with their megabuck
advertising campaign against federal legislation, check the report
just put out by the Centers for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   Since the cigarette companies' game has been to distract us from
the obvious, CDC has had to go to the bother of proving the
obvious. A CDC study finds that a sharp increase in cigarette taxes
would deeply slash sales, precisely the objective of recently
failed legislation that would have used a cigarette tax increase to
force up the price.
</P>
<P>
   The health agency calculates that a 50 percent increase in the
price of cigarettes would lead some 3.5 million smokers to quit and
far more to cut down. Overall, CDC figures 60 billion fewer
cigarettes would be smoked annually. The biggest gains against
smoking would be among low-income folks, minorities and young
people _ all of them prime targets of opportunity for the tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies would hate in particular losing the young. The
cigarette makers need young smokers to make up for the 400,000 of
us they kill with their product every year _ more than the deaths
from murder, alcohol, AIDS and traffic combined.
</P>
<P>
   It is to preserve the profits from this annual human slaughter
that the industry has flooded television with commercials
pretending cigarette companies are the good buddies of working guys
and gals.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard the pitch: Washington wants to get its hand on
smoking just so it can soak working folks for more taxes to pay for
more big government. In a series of commercials, all variations on
the same themes, the industry plays the hot buttons as if it were
the church organist pounding out a mighty hymn. Taxes _ bad.
Government _ bad. Working people _ good.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the industry cared about working people it would
stop selling them poison and go into bedding or insurance or
anything else less lethal. But the $40 million tobacco has spent so
far _ small change compared to the lost sales it fears _ fails to
mention that the biggest beneficiaries of the reduced smoking would
be exactly the same people it pretends to be protecting from taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason the CDC study counts as news is its currency.
We've known for years that smoking is price-sensitive with many of
tobacco's customers. Another study just last May found that the
proposed $1.10 tax per pack would cut teen smoking by 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's far more payoff than is likely from the scolding, just
say no-no ads the Republican Congress, having done tobacco's
bidding by quashing legislation, now favors as a politically
face-saving substitute.
</P>
<P>
   An unbought Republican, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, continues
trying to find a political opening that would let him bring back
his tobacco control bill. He is struggling upstream against a
torrent of industry advertising that has managed so far to convince
enough folks that a $1.10 tax on cigarettes is somehow a bigger
cost than those 400,000 lives and $50 billion in annual medical
expenses that we shell out to keep the tobacco companies rich.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
