<P>
   1. BRIDGES AND MAN'S WILL TO DOMINATE NATURE A major new bridge
is rising over the Oresund that will connect Sweden and Denmark,
giving inspiration to even more ambitious projects in Italy, Greece
and even Alaska. Inspired by fallen tree trunks and hanging vines,
the bridge-builders have proceeded to create masterpieces of
engineering as they strive to keep testing the limits of nature. By
Jvrg-Uwe Albig. From GEO magazine. 1,500 words. (English
translation available.) 2. SUPERBUGS For the past decade,
scientists have been waiting with dread for the emergence of
disease-causing bacteria that are resistant to our most powerful
antibiotics. The wait, alas, is over. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. From
The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words. 3. TODAY'S PLUGGED-IN
WORLD Checking in is our new pastime. We're fascinated by our
teletoys and the freedom they give us. Those old barriers of time
and space have vanished. We can check in from anywhere with anyone,
any time we please. We check in with the Internet and television
too, fingering our mouses and remotes, clicking and zapping. We
have become human hummingbirds, flitting and hovering, dipping in
our beaks for a quick taste, then zipping off. By John Powers. From
The Boston Globe Magazine. 1,800 words. 4. LABYRINTH OF SOLITUDE
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the mayor of Mexico City, is the second most
prominent man in his country, the son of one of its most beloved
presidents and Mexico's best hope for reform. Then why does he seem
so alone and helpless? By Paul Berman. From The New York Times
Magazine. 2,500 words. 5. AT CZAR NICHOLAS' BURIAL : THE COFFIN
TABLE COLLAPSES, AN IRPORT 'WELCOME' SIGN COMES DOWN AND 'THE
BOSS' SHOWS UP The state earmarked 5 million rubles for the
farewell ceremony. The important state event, solemn but without
pomp and circumstance, was a great success. Viktoria Voloshina, a
correspondent in the St. Petersburg bureau of Moscow News,
describes how the the Czar and his family were finally laid to
rest. 1,500 words. 6. From NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and
Spain. Embargo: 1800 GMT Wednesday August 5) A. Public Health - Too
Much Triclosan? A widely used antibacterial agent that is used in
toothpaste, kitchen utensils and toys could cause resistant strains
of bacteria to develop, in much the same way that
antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains are emerging. By Helen
Phillips. 600 words. B. Another Wet Weekend : Do you sometimes get
the feeling that it rains more at weekends? You could be right. It
seems the weekly cycle of human activity can influence regional
weather patterns. By Helen Phillips. 700 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
RAISING GRANDCHILDREN, RISING STRESS For many grandparents, joyful
dates with the grandchildren have been replaced by the
responsibility of full-time child care. And that is taking its
toll. They are suffering from problems like depression, anxiety,
high blood pressure, alcoholism and strokes that doctors link in
part to the stress of being parents all over again, this time under
far more difficult circumstances than the first time around. By
Susan Gilbert. New York Times Science Times. 1,350 words + photo.
