<HEADER>
A4967 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CHINA-REVIEW-600&AMP;AD     08-03 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CHINA-REVIEW-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1.) 
 TRYING TO CHANGE CHINA'S SYSTEM IN ORDER TO SAVE IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, Auguslt(The Week in Review) 
(mk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ever since the Communist Party took charge here in
1949, China's leaders have thrived on an unending cycle of
political campaigns. With quaint-sounding names like Let a Hundred
Flowers Bloom or the Cultural Revolution, campaigns were supposed
to sound noble. The realities were often horrific.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all was the Great Leap Forward, Mao Tse-tung's cockeyed
scheme of mass industrialization that destroyed the economy and
caused a famine that killed 30 million people around 1960. Yet even
in lesser campaigns, the same pattern was repeated: In public,
innocent victims were persecuted in the name of a bogus ideal; in
private, it was actually crass political jockeying that inspired
and directed a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that legacy, political campaigns continue in China
today. As in the past, they sound noble, but are purely political.
Most ordinary people are now wise enough to ignore them. But the
party itself is still clinging to its antiquated ways.
</P>
<P>
   Last month President Jiang Zemin unveiled China's latest
campaign. It targets smuggling, which reached epidemic proportions
in China years ago and is a trade dominated by the People's
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   True, in this case the target is hardly innocent, but as in
other campaigns, larger goals are being pursued. Jiang wants the
nation's military forces to relinquish their vast business
operations and, more important, he wants to reassert the authority
of the central government.
</P>
<P>
   That authority is being eroded by a variety of factors,
including the freer flow of information and insidious corruption.
Perhaps the biggest question facing China today is whether the
Communist Party is becoming vulnerable to an unexpected political
jolt strong enough to topple it. No one can predict such surprises
or their results _ like the failed Soviet coup in 1991 that yielded
the unintended consequence of propelling Boris Yeltsin to power _
but people can smell vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   They smell it today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a question of time,'' said a magazine editor in
Beijing, reflecting a popular sentiment. ``No one believes in
communism anymore, so how can there be any justification for a
Communist Party ?''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing utter dissatisfaction among wide sections of the
populace, and facing the potentially explosive danger of wide
unemployment as inefficient state-owned industries are overhauled,
Jiang is starting to tinker around the edges _ trying to change his
system to save it.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, newspapers and television programs were given mild
encouragement to report on egregious corruption cases. A handful of
university professors and scholars at research institutes have
started talking openly about the need for political reform.
Magazines with juicy stories of political intrigue, although highly
unreliable, are selling more openly on Beijing streets.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a small step toward greater openness when
President Clinton visited in June and, during a live national
broadcast, was shown publicly disagreeing with Jiang on sensitive
topics like the Tiananmen massacre of 1989 and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to take advantage of the marginally more tolerant mood,
some political dissidents have emerged in the past month to try to
announce the formation of a fringe party, still expressly
forbidden. Several have been detained and then released in a
merry-go-round of a legal procedure that reflects a minor softening
in Beijing's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   All these modest changes come at a time when the government,
with a new pro-reform prime minister, Zhu Rongji, is trying to
reduce the size of central ministries and undertake a vast reform
of China's outdated banking and housing systems.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jiang seems to be betting that a minuscule amount of opening
will help assuage the innumerable complaints that gurgle near the
surface all the time throughout China. It is a wager with sizable
risks, looming even larger if China's economy stalls.
</P>
<P>
   For there is a distinct possibility that steps toward openness
and accountability will only create even greater pressure on the
floodgates of popular discontent. As with Mikhail Gorbachev's
attempts to save the Soviet system by reforming it, letting in a
little sunlight can expose a void where political legitimacy should
be.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the military equation. Judging that the time is right for
change in China's political and economic culture, Jiang has ordered
the military to relinquish its business operations.
</P>
<P>
   The order was treated with incredulity at first, so deeply
entrenched is money-making in the contemporary culture of the
People's Liberation Army. Yet Jiang appeared to be serious, as
China's media went into full blitz to make the point that he was,
with army generals and senior officials emerging one after another
to say they were earnestly addressing the task of fighting
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Until last month, the worst-kept secret in China was that the
army operated an enormous smuggling racket. It was a stunning
political milestone for Jiang to say publicly (addressing a meeting
of top military officers no less) that China's military was deeply
involved in illegal activity.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than question the root of the problem _ an
authoritarian system that leaves the military unaccountable _ or
even reconsider the high import duties that make smuggling cellular
telephones, cigarettes and diesel oil so profitable, China's
leadership instead declared a campaign against smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   An expert political tactician, Jiang is unlikely to have
launched the anti-smuggling campaign, or to have ordered the
military out of business, without confidence that senior military
officers are on his side.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the main threat to the success of his campaign appears
to be not an outright rebellion by money-making officers but a
miasma of obfuscation and hidden transfers of ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Wei Jianxing, a senior official in charge of anti-corruption
efforts, alluded to that peril at a recent public meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army, armed police and law enforcement departments are
prohibited from hiding, relocating, transferring or selling
properties belonging to enterprises they run, or from distributing
funds and property belonging to firms held privately under any
name, from making false financial reports or rewriting, hiding or
destroying financial documents,'' Wei said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the larger issue is whether taking on the military _ until
now off limits to public criticism _ will provoke a deeper
examination of failings by the ruling authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army has always been sacred,'' said a retired Communist
Party official who is sharply critical of the current group of
leaders. ``It seems a very bold move to take on the army, no matter
how corrupt it has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what is the next step?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
