<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELA-BASSETT-IN-HOW-STELLA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELA BASSETT GETS IN THE GROOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 &HT;     Includes a color slide of Angela Bassett in a scene from ``How
Stella Got Her Groove Back.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``It's always the fear that holds you back,'' Angela Bassett
says.
 &HT;    In one sense, she's talking about Stella, her character in the
upcoming film ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' which opens Aug.
12. Stella is a business executive so caught up in her life that
she hardly has one _ until a quick-fix trip to Jamaica and a
romance with a younger man bring her a new perspective on life.
 &HT;    In another sense, though, Bassett is talking about herself,
because she knows all about being Stella.
 &HT;    ``I always had the `Good Girl Syndrome,''' she says. ``I'm a
good daughter, a good worker, a good sister, a good person. I'm all
about serious stuff. It can be exhausting.''
 &HT;    The man who helped her find her own way back was the actor
Courtney B. Vance, who recently starred in ``The Preacher's Wife''
(1996). Bassett had known him for years without ever contemplating
romantic involvement.
 &HT;    Her sense of him changed when, at a community playhouse, she
overhead him talking to a mutual friend who, suffering from
cerebral palsy, was facing the loss of her beloved dogs because she
could no longer walk them.
 &HT;    ```What if I came over every morning at 7 a.m. and walked them
for you?''' Vance asked.
 &HT;    ``At that moment, I fell in love,'' Bassett says, smiling.
 &HT;    She and Vance married last year.
 &HT;    ``I finally sat myself down and said, `You know what, Angela?
It's OK to let loose. It's OK to fall in love, because this life is
going to be rough any way you look at it,''' the actress recalls.
``At that moment, I found my groove.''
 &HT;    Right now, things are groovy indeed as Bassett enjoys a late
lunch at Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel. Dressed in a sky-blue,
beaded sun dress, her arm muscles rippling, she sways to a breeze
that offers some relief from the heat.
 &HT;    Speaking of heat, ``Stella'' is already being proclaimed one of
the year's most erotic films. But don't look for Bassett to do her
first nude scene _ she remains adamantly opposed to the idea.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to prove with this movie that you can be a lady and
still be sexy,'' Bassett says. ``I know people are looking for a
little titillation, whether it's violence or sexuality or whatever.
But I feel that nudity is gratuitous. I want no part of it.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, Taye Diggs, who plays Stella's Jamaican hunk,
does appear in the altogether in a romantic shower scene with a
clothed Bassett.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, I said, `It will be OK to take all your clothes off,
baby,''' the actress says, laughing. ``The poor guy had to wear a
sock over his private parts, and that was attached by an invisible
wire.
 &HT;    ``Unlike a woman, this man had no fat, so you could see the
wires burrowing into his skin,'' she adds. ``I felt real bad for
him, but in the back of my mind, I kept thinking, `Thank God it
isn't me.'''
 &HT;    Vance might have been thinking the same. The two married two
weeks into filming, and Bassett spent most of her early married
life making out with another man.
 &HT;    ``It was tough,'' Bassett admits. ``I was like, `Hi, how are you
today, honey? Oh, it was fine. Nothing went on today.'''
 &HT;    Jokes aside, Bassett says that what drew her to Stella was the
character's vulnerability.
 &HT;    ``You've seen me do my tough act,'' says Bassett, who battled an
abusive husband in ``What's Love Got to Do With It'' (1993), burned
her husband's car in ``Waiting to Exhale'' (1996) and harangued
Congress in ``Contact'' (1997). ``I wanted to show that I could
also be soft and loving onscreen.''
 &HT;    The older woman/younger man dynamic also resonated for Bassett.
 &HT;    ``At one point, my mother had a boyfriend who was pretty
young,'' she recalls. ``I remember being taken aback.
 &HT;    ``I was away at college and I came home on break, and this young
guy was at my home, just hanging out,'' she says. ``To what extent
it went, I don't know _ I don't need to know.
 &HT;    ``I was just like, `This is too weird for me. I'm going back to
school.'''
 &HT;    Bassett usually doesn't talk about her past in interviews, but
today she seems to be in the mood.
 &HT;    ``You don't want to talk about it when you grew up in the
projects,'' she says quietly. ``I grew up in a place where people
were selling drugs down the hall. My childhood was filled with
wondering if our apartment would be broken into when I got home.''
 &HT;    She was born in New York, but when she was 8 her parents split
up.
 &HT;    ``I remember the judge told my mother, `Take your children back
home to Florida, where you come from, or they're going into foster
care,''' she says.
 &HT;    Bassett, her sister and her mother wound up in the projects of
St. Petersburg. Even then, she says, she felt driven to perform.
 &HT;   ``As a kid, I would turn up the record player and scream, `Mom,
this is my favorite song,''' she recalls. ``Then I would do the
entire Temptations act. I would be all of the Jackson Five. I'd get
up and grab a brush and act it out until it was my sister's turn.''
 &HT;    The real turning point came when she was 15, however, on a visit
to Washington, when she and some friends went to see a performance
of ``Of Mice and Men,'' starring James Earl Jones.
 &HT;    ``I was crying my head off at the end,'' Bassett says. ``At that
moment, I knew if I could only make people feel like this, I would
be happy for the rest of my life.''
 &HT;    Bassett won a scholarship to Yale University. After earning
bachelor's and master's degrees, she headed for New York. She
admits to having had her doubts, however.
 &HT;    ``At the time,'' she recalls, ``if you saw a black woman in the
movies she was a prostitute, the maid or the neighbor, or some
other image I didn't like.''
 &HT;    Instead, she gravitated toward theater, and won parts in two hit
plays by August Wilson, ``Ma Rainey's Black Bottom'' (1984) and
``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' (1986).
 &HT;    She was on her way. Hollywood cast her as strong women in ``Boyz
N the Hood'' (1991), ``Malcolm X'' (1992) and ``What's Love Got to
Do With It.''
 &HT;    As her career ripened _ her ``What's Love Got to Do With It''
role as Tina Turner earned her an Oscar nomination _ her life
outside work was neglected, she admits, not unlike Stella's.
 &HT;    ``I didn't trust marriage,'' Bassett says. ``I would pray that I
wouldn't be fooled by a man. I can be quite gullible.''
 &HT;    Even when she started dating Vance, an old friend, she was still
ambivalent about it.
 &HT;    ``When we went out for the first time three years ago on a real
date,'' she recalls, ``I kept thinking, `I know him. God, I hope he
doesn't like me, because it would be too weird.'''
 &HT;    She got over it. When he proposed one day last year on the
streets of New York, Bassett said yes. She hasn't regretted it yet.
 &HT;    ``I love that my husband wants to make sure I am comfortable and
taken care of every second of the day,'' she says.
 &HT;    Looking at her own life, personally and professionally alike,
Bassett can't resist thinking that she's found her own groove.
 &HT;    ``It blows my mind to think about how far I've come,'' the
actress admits. ``I look around and see the people who inspired me,
and I want to yell, `Look at me now!'''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
