<SLUG> BC-DREW-CAREY-IN-WHOSE-LINE-IS-IT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREW CAREY'S NEW GAME IN TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Drew Carey with Kathy Kinney in a scene
from ``The Drew Carey Show.'' 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember those hazy, crazy days when networks used the summer
months to try out new shows?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, most of those series were forgettable filler, but there
were also some gems, including ``The Sonny and Cher Comedy Hour,''
``Melrose Place'' and ``Northern Exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   The tradition has now been resurrected with ``Whose Line Is It
Anyway?,'' which premiered Aug. 5 on ABC for a six-week run.
</P>
<P>
   The offbeat game show is actually a remake of a long-running
British series. The new version is hosted by the brushcut star of
``The Drew Carey Show,'' who also thinks the whole concept of
summer shows deserves a second look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I used to love watching new series in the summer,'' Carey
says wistfully. ``I never understood why the networks stopped doing
that. One of my all-time favorite shows as a kid was `The Ken Berry
Wow Show,' which was a summer-replacement series. I still remember
jokes from that show.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the way TV is so competitive right now, you really should
have original programming all year round,'' he adds. ``Hey, you
might as well try something new out in the summer. What have you
got to lose?''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, ABC has plenty to gain with ``Whose Line.''
They've slotted it in a promising niche _ right after reruns of
``The Drew Carey Show'' on Wednesday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea of me following me,'' Carey says, laughing.
``Hey, if I can't hold my own audience, I'm in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is a remake of the British version _ currently running
daily on the Comedy Network _ and has an undeniably distinctive
setup: Four comics perform unrehearsed skits and improvisational
scenes, based on suggestions from a studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   As host, Carey sets the scene for each skit and oversees the
proceedings. The entertainment value comes from each comic's
ability or inability to think quickly on his/her feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, when it comes to actual laughs per minute, I don't
think I've ever seen a funnier show,'' says Carey, who is
admittedly biased, since he's also an executive producer. ``The
humor is just, like, bang-bang-bang! It just keeps coming at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey's inspiration to adapt ``Whose Line'' for an American
audience clicked several months back, when he and his ``Drew Carey
Show'' castmates began trying some onstage improvisational scenes
at the Melrose Improv in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just felt right,'' says Carey, who had already become a fan
of the British show through the Comedy Central reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it helped matters that Ryan Stiles, who plays the
doofus Lewis on ``Drew Carey,'' had been a regular on the British
``Whose Line'' since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about redoing it here, and it just seemed like a
great idea,'' Stiles says. ``Obviously, it was also great having
Drew involved, because it meant we would have a lot more viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   After putting the television deal together, Carey and Stiles _
by this stage also an executive producer _ hooked up with Canadian
comic Colin Mochrie, Greg Proops and Brad Sherwood, all veterans of
the British version, and newcomer Wayne Brady to tape six shows at
the end of June. Studio-audience tickets were offered through Los
Angeles radio stations, and the response was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last week's taping, we had 700 ticket requests for 300
seats,'' Carey says. ``That's for a TV taping! Usually you have to
beg people to come to a new-show taping.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey doesn't make any great claims for his role on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the easiest job of all,'' he says. ``I do an improv
scene at the end, but mostly I just get to sit there and laugh my
head off.''
</P>
<P>
   The more difficult work falls to the comics, who have a split
second to make a random concept into something hilarious. After
almost a decade of annual treks to London to tape the British
``Whose Line,'' Stiles and Mochrie are the unofficial in-house
experts, and both notice differences between the two versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The improv stuff was the same, but the audiences were really
great here,'' Stiles says. ``They really got into it and were way
more responsive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mochrie agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British audiences were far more laid-back and polite,'' he
says. ``They were really whooping it up at the L.A. tapings, which
is great for the performers. Also, there isn't any censorship in
the British version, but in the U.S., we were told we couldn't use
certain words, like `erection.' And, of course, Drew is a totally
different host.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure. On the original British series, which recently
completed its 10th season, host Clive Anderson is a totally
refined, thoroughly composed Englishman. On the new show, Carey is,
well, Carey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of times,'' Mochrie recalls, ``when I
actually heard spit takes coming from the side of the stage, and I
would look over and I could see Drew was wiping water off his chin.
He was just killing himself at all the tapings. Believe me, Drew
and Clive have a completely different method of hosting this
show.''
</P>
<P>
   That Carey should be convulsed isn't too surprising: The entire
improvisational scene is virgin territory to him. He spent more
than a decade doing rapid-fire stand-up in clubs and on HBO
specials before landing his own hit sitcom, but never ventured into
improv.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole improv thing is a totally new world for me, but I
really love it,'' he says. ``It's harder than stand-up _ you have
to pay a lot more attention. But both Ryan and Colin told me that
they can't possibly imagine what it would be like to do straight
stand-up. So it depends on what you're used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Improv comedy is, indeed, an acquired art. The Toronto-based
Mochrie is a veteran of the Second City Stage Company and
innumerable television commercials, and says that it's particularly
difficult to transport his improv skills to television.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a club, you can take more time with the scenes,'' he says,
``but on a television show, it's faster, so it can sometimes become
a one-liner type of comedy. Basically, it's like a strange marriage
of stand-up and improv.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it's like a theater atmosphere,'' Styles adds,
``because we're really playing to the people sitting there in the
studio, not the home viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Carey fans, the big attraction to ``Whose Line'' may be
getting an hour-long dose of their favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Drew he should get a correspondent job on `20/20,' so
that way he could be on two hours in a row,'' Stiles jokes. ``I
think Drew would do a really good job on their more twisted
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, don't expect to see Carey sitting beside Hugh Downs and
Barbara Walters anytime soon. However, the big fella is hoping that
``Whose Line'' will catch on for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously, the best thing that could possibly happen would be
for this show to do well in the summer and get picked up for the
regular season,'' Carey says. ``If that happens, we'd do a show
every Saturday. I'd just have to show up three hours for the taping
_ no problem. I'd love every minute of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor of Canadian TV Guide, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
