<HEADER>
A4992 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VINCE-VAUGHN-IN-RETUR     08-03 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINCE-VAUGHN-IN-RETURN-TO-PARADISE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINCE VAUGHN: A `SWINGER' BRANCHES OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Vince Vaughn with Anne Heche in a scene
from ``Return to Paradise.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Everyone on the planet thinks Vince Vaughn is a huge star in the
making _ everyone, that is, but Vaughn himself.
 &HT;    The tall and winsome lead in the hip indie film ``Swingers''
(1996), Vaughn went mainstream as a dino-meal deluxe in Steven
Spielberg's ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' (1997).
 &HT;    Dodging dinosaurs was a switch for the 25-year-old Vaughn, who
was born in Minneapolis and raised in the well-heeled suburbs of
Chicago. He first made it onscreen in a ``Heartbeat of America''
television commercial for Chevrolet, soon followed by television
appearances on ``Doogie Howser, M.D.'' and ``21 Jump Street,'' and
then brief turns in the films ``For the Boys'' (1991) and ``Rudy''
(1993).
 &HT;    Then came ``Swingers,'' and all of a sudden Vaughn was a hot
commodity.
 &HT;    ``I don't pay much mind to the hype,'' he says. ``I get
recognized, but I have the same friends I've always had and,
really, I haven't been in big films like a lot of these other guys
you're hearing about.
 &HT;    ``I never got into acting to get this or that one day, or so I
could go back to my hometown and have a parade thrown for me,''
Vaughn adds. ``My thing has always been that I love to act for the
fun and the love of it.''
 &HT;    If that's the case, his current schedule qualifies as a love
feast. He has three films coming up and more in progress. In fact,
he's promoting his current ``Return to Paradise'' by telephone, on
a break from shooting the controversial remake of ``Psycho.''
 &HT;    ``Return to Paradise,'' a crisis-of-conscience drama starring
Vaughn, Joaquin Phoenix and David Conrad, is due to hit theaters on
Aug. 14.
 &HT;    The three actors portray Americans in Malaysia, who part ways as
pals after a month of partying and debauchery. Two years later,
desperate lawyer Anne Heche delivers stunning news to Vaughn and
Conrad: Phoenix has been imprisoned on drug charges for the past
two years, and will hang in eight days if the two don't agree to
jet to Malaysia, admit culpability and do hard time.
 &HT;    It's a hard-hitting drama, and despite its picturesque locales _
the cast and crew visited such diverse ports of call as Manhattan,
Philadelphia, Macao, Thailand and Hong Kong _ Vaughn says that it
was a difficult shoot. Jet lag, language barriers, homesickness and
jampacked scheduling all took their toll.
 &HT;    ``I'd never been to the Far East before and it was my third film
in a row, so I spent most of last year in hotel rooms,'' the actor
says. ``You get on a plane for a period of time, come down and your
whole environment has changed. You just don't have a balance. We
shot six-day weeks.
 &HT;    ``By the end of it I was really tired,'' he says. ``And I didn't
even have a chance to relax and see any of the places I was in.''
 &HT;    Vaughn did, however, find time to bond with Phoenix and Heche _
which is good, because he'll be working with both again, in the
upcoming ``Clay Pigeons'' and in ``Psycho,'' respectively.
 &HT;    It seems like a repertory company in the making, but Vaughn
swears it's just coincidence.
 &HT;    ``How about that!'' Vaughn says. ``I like both of them. Joaquin
is a really great actor, really giving, very genuine and he's
touched me in a way.
 &HT;    ``Anne is a brilliant actress, one of the best,'' he adds.
``She's a chameleon, and can take on a comedy or a drama or
whatever and just be excellent in it.
 &HT;    ``They both cared so much about `Paradise,''' he concludes,
``but didn't have to run around in dark moods, because they trusted
themselves to get to the place they needed to be.''
 &HT;    ``Clay Pigeons,'' due later this year, casts the actor as nutso
drifter Lester Long, who makes life hell for Montana gas-station
attendant Clay Bidwell (Phoenix). Georgina Cates, Scott Wilson and
Janeane Garofalo co-star in the October release, which Vaughn
describes as ``an indie punk-rock film, a dark comedy.''
 &HT;    After ``Pigeons'' comes ``A Cool, Dry Place,'' with Vaughn as a
young father raising a kid and trying to kick-start his life again.
Joey Lauren Adams, late of ``Chasing Amy,'' plays his girlfriend,
while Monica Potter is the ex-wife who re-enters the picture.
 &HT;    Then there's ``Psycho.'' The need for it has been questioned _
the original is one of Hollywood's all-time favorites _ but the new
version, though set in the 1990s and shot in color, adheres almost
word-for-word to Joseph Stefano's script for Alfred Hitchcock's
1960 classic.
 &HT;    Directed by Gus Van Sant, the remake hands Anthony Perkins' wig,
knife and mother complex to Vaughn. Janet Leigh's legendary shower
sequence goes to Heche, while Julianne Moore, William H. Macy and
Viggo Mortensen take on the roles originally assayed by Vera Miles,
Martin Balsam and John Gavin, respectively.
 &HT;    ``I'm showing up on the set, at the motel and I'm saying these
lines,'' says an obviously stoked Vaughn, who watched ``Psycho'' as
a teen and was as freaked by it as anybody. ``It's like an
out-of-body experience.
 &HT;    ``Truthfully, I was scared at first,'' he admits. ``I thought,
`Should I play this role?' because I thought people would compare
me to Perkins and ask why we're remaking `Psycho.'''
 &HT;    And indeed all that came to pass. Still, Vaughn says, he doesn't
regret his decision.
 &HT;    ``For me, it's a challenge,'' the actor says. ``It's an
interesting character. Van Sant is a really interesting director.
It's got great actors.
 &HT;    ``To let perceptions, or the fear of perceptions, stop me from
doing it would have been a mistake, would have been wrong,'' he
says. ```Psycho's' going great, and I hope it turns out great, but
regardless, I feel good about my reasons for wanting to be involved
in it.''
 &HT;    Actually, Vaughn feels good about most things these days. And
why not? He's working steadily, he isn't trapped in paint-by-number
would-be blockbusters and he has the chance to display his range by
breathing life into a gallery of swingers, serial killers and dads
in comedies and dramas alike.
 &HT;    ``I know how lucky I am,'' he says. ``Out here, entertainment is
the No. 1 industry. It's constantly around you _ billboards, trade
magazines, this and that.
 &HT;    ``It can be real hard if you're not lucky enough to crack
(Hollywood) in some way, as an actor, agent, whatever,'' Vaughn
says. ``I'm getting to do the roles and films I want to do now, but
I remember what it was like to be at home, not have an agent, not
have people returning your phone calls, to walk around the block at
3 in the morning putting together some kind of game plan.
 &HT;    ``To do what I'm doing now just feels great.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
