A4993 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOING-PLACES-STARBEAT     08-03 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOING-PLACES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOING PLACES' WHILE STAYING HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of James Avery in a scene from ``Going
Places.'' 
 By JAN BENZEL  
 c.1998 The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adventurous armchair travelers have always had plenty of
vicarious options, from the books of Lawrence Durrell and Margaret
Mead to television shows from National Geographic and Charles
Kuralt, not to mention the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   But what about those who don't have the vacation time _ or even
the inclination _ to canoe down the Zambezi alone or feast on yak
butter in Nepal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Going Places,'' a public-television series now in its second
season _ airing Mondays on PBS at 8 p.m. (EDT) _ aims to appeal to
the ordinary traveler whose idea of a good time is a little
history, a lot of scenery, some local culture, a tasty meal and a
comfortable bed.
</P>
<P>
   James Avery, probably best known for his role as a judge on the
NBC series ``Fresh Prince of Bel Air'' or as the star of the UPN
sitcom ``Sparks,'' is the new affable host, picking up where the
veteran weatherman Al Roker, the affable host for the first season,
left off.
</P>
<P>
   With hourlong video visits to popular and photogenic vacation
destinations including South Africa, Sydney, Ireland, Miami,
Ecuador and Las Vegas, the show has earned the rather specialized
distinction of being public television's highest-rated travel
series.
</P>
<P>
   The series doesn't have a formula, says executive producer
William R. Grant, so much as it has a loose concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's imagine that we're going to spend a week somewhere and
capture a variety of experiences, some traditional, some not in the
guidebooks,'' he says. ``Places you'd be pointed to by local
experts, a little bit of food, a little bit of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery introduces each show, does voice-over narration and is the
surrogate traveler on a couple of programs. In Florida, for
example, the camera follows him in his convertible, but also takes
a tour of the city's Art Deco buildings with a local authority and
keeps its eye on two 20-ish sisters in Miami for some chic fun,
including a foray on Rollerblades.
</P>
<P>
   ``What works in TV programs of all sorts is the people,'' Grant
says. ``Characters are everything. In these shows, the place is a
character and the people you meet there, whether they're the guides
or the other people you've traveled with. Tourists are stand-ins
for the viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Segments of the Ecuador trip are told through the experience of
a young, attractive tour group that does some trekking in the Andes
and stays in a remote lodge on the Amazon. The Australian author
Thomas Keneally provides colonial lore on a visit to Sydney. A show
called ``The Bloodiest Field'' documents Civil War re-enactments of
the Battle of Antietam in Hagerstown, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The programs cost about $200,000 each _ low for documentary
programming, Grant says _ and are shot in about 10 days. The eight
programs are among the 20 to 25 new hours of ``travels and
journeys'' programming shown on public television each year.
</P>
<P>
   An advance guard does some scouting before the camera crew
arrives. Still, Avery says, ``sometimes we have to change plans
when what was supposed to be a fascinating temple turns out to be a
hut in a ditch.''
</P>
<P>
   He is already taping next season's shows, and recently returned
from Bali.
</P>
<P>
   He loves travel, but wants his creature comforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a child of the '60s,'' he says. ``I've been through all
that, sleeping in the dirt. I'll do just about anything, but in
Bali they tried to get me to go to a cave with fruit bats. A dark
cave with a bunch of flying rats? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Practical advice is sprinkled in with the chats, scenery and
geography. A doctor interviewed about the dangers of drinking water
and eating vegetables in Ecuador urges ``caution, but not to the
point of obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a happy marriage of two electronic media, the show leaves
most of the service information to a well-thought-out ``Going
Places'' Web site, which can be found at www.pbs.org. Travelers
with an actual urge to leave their armchairs can go from television
to computer to find relevant phone numbers, maps, further facts,
figures and advice.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us can sit back and enjoy the ride.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jan Benzel reports on entertainment for The New York Times.) &LR; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
