EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Aug. 3, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HARRELSON-CONVICTION (San Antonio) _ Charles Harrelson, who
committed the biggest, boldest and most outrageous crime in San
Antonio history, is seeking a new trial for his conviction for
murdering a federal judge. By ROY BRAGG.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOV (San Diego) _ Despite all the sniping between Attorney
General Dan Lungren and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the first of a series
of debates in the race for governor was surprising in its focus on
issues. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-PRIMARY (San Francisco) _ With newly released records
showing that the primary for the California governor's race cost an
unprecedented $72 million, political experts predict November's
election might look cheap in comparison. By ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-IMMIGRANT (San Francisco) _ A New Zealand AIDS patient
plans to risk arrest by returning to the city this week, in
dramatic defiance of U.S. immigration policy barring HIV-infected
foreigners. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Houston) _ In today's world of retirement planning,
it pays to make a pest of yourself. This is especially true when it
comes to 401(k) retirement savings plans offered by employers.
That's because some employers are doing a lousy job of telling
their workers about their 401(k) programs. By PAMELA YIP
</P>
