   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HORSESHOES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Need some luck? Trying hanging a
horseshoe above your door, or spit on it and throw it over your
shoulder. But beware of finding a horseshoe without the nails still
in it, as that signifies bad luck. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-TOWERS (Hadley Mountain, N.Y.) _ Originally built to help
spot forest fires, lookout towers in the Adirondack mountains were
rendered obsolete by airplane observers and a sharp decline in
fires. Most towers have been abandoned, with some slated to be torn
down by the state. Now, though, a growing band of preservationists
is starting to restore these structures. By RICK KARLIN
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ Sometimes when potted plant leaves
turn yellow, we tend to overwater. But overly wet soil causes
leaves to yellow. However, inadequate water also causes yellow
foliage. Test for dryness with your fingers. By KATHY HUBER
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-IROQUOIS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Still at it on the cusp of
his 10th decade, William N. Fenton has capped his career as dean of
Iroquois studies with the engaging, revealing, and massive volume
``The Great Law And The Longhouse.'' By CHRISTOPHER RINGWALD.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RYAN-VET (Guilderland, N.Y.) _ His gait was slow and
measured as he left the theater, but Harold Ripps' clenched fists
and traces of moisture beneath his eyes revealed his true feelings
about the movie ``Saving Private Ryan.'' By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
