   FILM-CURTIS-PROFILE (Undated) _ Jamie Lee Curtis returns to the
scene of the screams in ``Halloween: H20,'' an anniversary sequel
to the 1978 horror classic. ``This film is a thank-you note to my
fans who have loved that movie and supported me for 20 years,''
Curtis said. The movie opens nationwide Wednesday. By BRUCE
WESTBROOK
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-ACADIANS (Lafayette, La.) _ Lafayette is very proud of
being the hub city of Acadiana. Brochures tout it as the ``Heart of
French Louisiana'' and everyone embraces the ``joie de vivre'' that
is life in the bayou. By JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-SACRED (Grand Coteau, La.) _ At the Academy of the
Sacred Heart, a shrine stands at the site of a miracle that
occurred more than 130 years ago. Besides the religious overtones
that attract pilgrims, the beauty and history of Sacred Heart draw
2,500 visitors in a town about half that size.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ The recent fire aboard Carnival's
Ecstasy cruise ship off the Florida coast should serve as a
reminder to all travelers that safety is no trivial matter _ at sea
or on land. By HARRY SHATTUCK
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-BLACK-JOCKEYS (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ History is taking
note of the early jockeys and trainers who happened to be black. On
August 10, the National Racing Hall of Fame will induct Ansel
Williamson, an ex-slave who trained the first Kentucky Derby winner
in 1875 and in 1873 the winner of Saratoga's Travers. The honor
comes as writers and museums recognize blacks in horse racing. By
JANE GOTTLIEB.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (Bassetts, Calif.) _ Some people get dizzy atop
the Sierra Buttes. Some get nervous, and others seem euphoric. It's
the thrill that makes this one of the best short hikes anywhere. By
TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
