<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ God's punishment for the liberal
Bay Area is liberals. That's right, it isn't earthquakes, fires or
possible comets. It's all those people with ``Commit random acts of
kindness'' bumper stickers, the ones who commit systematic acts of
guilt-tripping for the greater good. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ So powerful are the combat
scenes in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Veterans Administration
counselors across the country are bracing for a possible wave of
vets who see the film and rip open old emotional wounds. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ There are 38 state lotteries
in America and many, if not all, try to ensnare customers by hyping
the size of their jackpot. They don't talk about installment
payments or taxes. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Is the state of Texas sending
teen-agers mixed signals? Bill Lewis, a spokesman for Mothers
Against Drunk Driving, said a number of teen-agers attending a MADD
youth camp this summer detected an inconsistency. ``The kids were
asking why is all the attention being focused on banning tobacco
and tobacco ads, and beer companies are getting by with no
attention at all,'' he said. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-PLUGOLA (Beverly Hills, Calif.) _ Until now, little
evidence has supported the theory that tobacco companies use movies
as advertising vehicles. Newly released tobacco company files now
provide that evidence. By NANCY MARSDEN.
</P>
