<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5072 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUILDING-SICKNESS04     08-03 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILDING-SICKNESS04 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida government addressing problem of poor indoor air
quality; many workers sickened by fumes
 &HT;    By Lillian Weis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You can't see it. Some can't even smell
it or taste it. But you can feel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like chasing a ghost,'' Palm Beach County Facilities
Compliance Manager Dean Zehnter said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to pinpoint exactly what is in the air at the Palm Beach
County Sheriff's headquarters and many other buildings in South
Florida can be as daunting as solving a mystery. It has cost the
sheriff's office an estimated $26,000 in cleaning and consulting
fees since late June to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four of the sheriff's 77 dispatchers have seen doctors for
problems related to air quality in the building. A noxious odor
that caused eye and throat irritations and led to respiratory
problems forced workers to evacuate their office four times in the
past month. The only other time there was an air-quality complaint
there was in December 1995, at the crime lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say it's this one thing,'' assistant director
of administration Georgette Carroll said. ``There's nothing else
that can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The burden of proof is great for a science that's imprecise.
Even the most sensitive instruments used to test air quality can't
detect the low levels of chemicals that the human body can, said
Holly Bailey, president of Bailey Engineering Corp., a Palm Beach
Gardens-based company that has been testing indoor air quality for
about 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bodies are very sensitive, but they can't identify the
problem,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither can most experts. Everyone's sensitivity level to gases
released into the air is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know which are the bad compounds and how they
are going to react,'' said Gene Tucker, a senior research engineer
at the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's lab in Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   According to the EPA, people spend as much as 90 percent of
their time indoors. Indoor air pollution has consistently ranked
among the top five environmental risks to public health in recent
studies conducted by the EPA and the Science Advisory Board.
</P>
<P>
   But the EPA doesn't regulate indoor air because little data
exists on its pollutants and the effects they have on people, said
Garvin Heath, an employee at the indoor environments division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science is not there,'' Heath said. ``Without that kind of
data, you can't regulate anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Indoor air quality studies are under way at the Research
Triangle Institute in North Carolina and universities throughout
the country. Tucker, who has studied the sources of indoor air
pollutants and ways to control them since 1983, said progress has
been made in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to develop ways to measure the chemicals emitted
in buildings, and we're working with manufactures to learn how to
make products that limit the emissions of gases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts look for the usual suspects such as mold in air
conditioning units, which provide a wet environment where mold and
mildew thrive, and dust mites. Wil Spaul, a $200-an-hour certified
industrial hygienist hired by the sheriff's office, identified
those _ among other problems _ in the sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   County and sheriff's officials believe smoke from the wildfires
in Central Florida that led to health advisories here may have led
to some of the employees' complaints.
</P>
<P>
   All commercial air handler units in public buildings must
distribute a blend of outdoor air and recirculated indoor air, as
required by industry standards established in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no fix all at the present time that solves all indoor
air quality problems,'' Zehntner said.
</P>
<P>
   But the EPA, the National Institute for Occupational Safety and
Health and the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air
Conditioning Engineers have set industry standards and guidelines.
The key is maintenance and control of indoor air pollutants,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said most problems linked to a sick building surface soon
after construction is completed. The Martin County Courthouse was
closed for four years because toxic fungi growing in mold and
mildew made employees sick. It was deemed a sick building by
experts who found moisture and humidity problems.
</P>
<P>
   Martin County spent $27 million renovating the two-building
complex, relocating employees and litigating against builders and
designers of the complex, which reopened in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case with the Palm Beach County sheriff's
headquarters, which was first built 16 years ago and expanded in
1993. The problems are new and affecting only the communication
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had sick-building syndrome, we would all be sick,''
Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County, which owns and maintains the 1
million-square-foot complex, has 40 workers on site who follow a
maintenance schedule that includes checking the 26 air conditioning
units monthly. The sheriff's budget for maintenance and repairs
last year was $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   To identify the problem at the communications office, Bailey
Engineering first tested the temperature, relative humidity and
carbon dioxide levels, which were fine. They then searched for
another environmental cause by asking employees questions that
would determine what happened before they became ill.
</P>
<P>
   But isolating a specific chemical as the cause of an illness is
nearly impossible. Thousands of compounds exist naturally, adding
to synthetic ones that release chemicals into the air. Scientists
don't know what effects cumulative compounds may have on the body,
and that's why they say it's important not to discount any
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Carroll said, ``there's a level of anxiety going into
work when you are wondering if you'll get sick again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Weis writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
