<HEADER>
A5076 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN04-COX     08-03 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lying about sex: criminal or courteous?
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Martha Ezzard will be on vacation until Aug. 10)
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA- What is the impact of the Clinton sex saga on American
culture and politics? Or is this baby-boomer president as much a
reflection of today's culture as an influence on it? Either way, a
majority of the American people say they didn't want to know the
embarrassing details of the alleged Monica Lewinisky affair.
</P>
<P>
   If the recent leak of the Lewinsky deal with the special
prosecutor is true, either the president or Lewinsky may have lied,
but Lewinsky says (according to the leaks) that the president
didn't pressure her to lie under oath. That means he couldn't be
charged with the criminal act of obstructing justice and it's
doubtful perjury can be proved in a he says, she says conflict.
Despicable as the president's behavior may be, most Americans
understand that it doesn't endanger the nation. Clinton is
responsible to his wife and his God for his sins.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the independent prosecutor, is also a creature of
today's culture_ the socially conservative culture. Conservatism,
once defined as minimizing government and maximizing individual
liberties, now fosters government as the moral police. Starr has
also missed a lesson basic to every good prosecutor _ you don't use
all of the legal power at your disposal lest you fill the jails
with parking meter violators. Arranging bribes, endangering
national security, using public office for private gain _ that is
the stuff of a special prosecutor, not the sex lives of high
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office has become little more than a sieve for Illegal
leaks of grand jury testimony to media_ a matter serous enough to
cause a federal judge to ordered an investigation. Starr violates
the time-honored ``doctrine of clean hands,'' which says those who
disregard the tenets of justice cannot plead before the court for
it
</P>
<P>
   Starr has employed attorneys on his staff with less than clean
records.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Udolf, a former Georgia District Attorney, is a good
example. Udolf was found liable by a federal jury for violating a
Dawsonville carpenter's constitutional rights. Udolf tried to
coerce Ronald Reeves to testify against his employer in a drug case
Udolf was prosecuting. Udolf had Reeves thrown in jail on a bogus
stolen weapon charge. He didn't allow Reeves to call his wife or
lawyer for 24 hours, never scheduled a hearing , and grilled Reeves
about the drug case, not the gun charge. A federal judge fined
Udolph $50,000 for violating Reeves' constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   Udolf isn't my idea of the caliber of lawyer who should be
questionning the president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned the special prosecutor's press spokesman Charles Bakaly
to ask about Udolph's role in the investigation. After three calls
and five days, an aide left a message that Bakaly would need to
know my questions before he could talk to me. Even Star's
spokesperson doesn't seem to get the hang of his job.
</P>
<P>
   But in almost every corner of the nation, folks get the hang of
this unfortunate chapter of American politics: a president who
succeeds as a policy maker and fails as a moral model. A zealot of
a special prosecutor. And Americans find different ways to say why
they'd keep Clinton in office anyway.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly southern woman from an upscale Atlanta suburb put it
this way: ``If the president did have an improper relationship with
that young woman, lying about it was the gentlemanly thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta Journal
-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   EX
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
