A5077 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN04-CO     08-03 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sit first in judgment of ourselves
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Last month, speaking at the 89th annual NAACP
convention in Atlanta, the group's president and chief executive
officer, Kweisi Mfume, called the justices of the Supreme Court
hypocrites when it comes to matters of diversity. His comment that
the justices ``should be ashamed of themselves'' made headlines.
</P>
<P>
   In hiring law clerks, the justices reflect a decided bias for
whites from three Ivy League schools: Harvard, Yale and Columbia.
USA Today reported that of the 394 clerks the current justices have
hired, 4.5 percent were Asian, 1.8 percent were black, and 1
percent were Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Each justice hires three or four clerks a year, and they have
significant influence. Clerks screen most of the cases, thus
helping decide which ones the court will hear, and they draft most
of the rulings. Justice Antonin Scalia, who has consistently voted
against affirmative action, has never hired a black clerk during
his 12 years on the bench. During 26 years on the high court, 99
percent of Chief Justice William Rehnquist's clerks have been
whites and 88 percent have been males.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines aside, the part of Mr. Mfume's speech that impressed
me most was his plea to all Americans, individually and
collectively. He asked us not to retreat from the struggle for
civil rights into ``the comfort of our own existence.''
</P>
<P>
   His words struck a resounding chord with me because the NAACP
fought for the comforts of my existence, from equal pay as a
teacher to access to public accommodations. Another compelling
reason to reflect on Mr. Mfume's words is that he leads by example.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, this brother who transformed himself from
school-dropout street hustler to widely respected,
college-educated, urbane, respected politician had arrived at a
position of status longed for by many and achieved by few. The
former five-term congressman from Baltimore was comfortably
situated on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, however, he left Congress to run the NAACP, which at
the time seemed to be a dying organization. The nation's oldest
civil rights group was $4 million in debt, reeling from scandals
related to former CEO Ben Chavis and adrift without assertive
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the organization has a $2 million surplus. There is a new
emphasis on recruiting young members. Most important, Mr. Mfume has
brought the NAACP full circle, seeking to include all people who
want to eliminate racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP was founded by a coalition of blacks and whites. Mr.
Mfume would have those of us who have achieved sufficient economic
stability and a modicum of status step outside our comfort zones to
address prejudice and bigotry. Only with the involvement of those
who now feel no personal urgency to get involved in the struggle
can we create the kinds of coalitions that wield moral authority in
shaping this nation's future.
</P>
<P>
   As the hiring practices of the Supreme Court confirm, America is
still not sufficiently free of discrimination against blacks and
other minorities to abandon affirmative-action remedies. The NAACP
is committed to fight to change that reality. But, as Mr. Mfume
said, those of us who abhor prejudice and bigotry have an
obligation to step outside our insular status to open doors
undeniably closed against minorities except by government
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what would happen if all of us who deny we are
prejudiced put aside our stereotypical prejudgments of each other
to really get to know a person of a different race. Imagine if we
did this of our own volition, without being coerced by law. And
imagine what would happen if those of us who believe racial
prejudice can destroy this country acted on the job, in the home
and throughout the community to confront bigotry, whether directed
toward us or others.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect we would discover that that kind of affirmative action
is the only kind this nation needs.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
