<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5080 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX     08-03 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton's moral legacy
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Richard Nixon turned in the doorway of the Marine
helicopter and gave his two-armed victory salute just before he was
</P>
<P>
   whisked away from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   What will Bill Clinton do? Perhaps he will give his pretend
military salute. Maybe it will be a big wave with a big smile.
Should Hillary be
</P>
<P>
   there standing there by her man?
</P>
<P>
   These details need to be worked out. Clinton, after all, is
concerned about his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants to look good when future generations compare the
departures of America's two disgraced presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it remains an open question whether Clinton serves out
his presidency. But there is no question that Clinton's greatest
legacy to
</P>
<P>
   the nation will be lowered moral standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had to lower its adultery standards. Considering
the adulterous behavior of the commander in chief, there's no way
the
</P>
<P>
   military could kick some private out of the Army for violating
the Uniform Code of Military Justice ban on adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's treatment of women has lowered the standards by which
men treat women. Clinton and his supporters have no problem
trashing the
</P>
<P>
   reputations of women who complain that they were victims of
Clinton's crude and sexually harassing behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be unacceptable for men accused of sexual harassment
to defend themselves attacking the reputations of the complaining
women.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has made smearing the backgrounds of his accusers an
practiced art form.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's supporters have either defended his boorish actions or
kept silent. Either way, moral standards have been lowered.
</P>
<P>
   Feminist Gloria Steinem facilitated Clinton's legacy of
dumbed-down moral standards by defending him when White House
volunteer Kathleen
</P>
<P>
   Willey reluctantly reported that Clinton grabbed her, kissed
her, groped her breast and forced her hand on his genitals.
</P>
<P>
   Steinem said even if what Willey said was true Clinton was not
guilty of sexual harassment because he ``took 'no' for an answer.''
We now have
</P>
<P>
   the one-free-grope standard.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Clinton's legacy, Americans who used to demand only
the highest standards from their elected officials now defend
Clinton by
</P>
<P>
   saying that other presidents had adulterous affairs. Before
Clinton, standards set by the lowest common denominator were
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also has given us lowered standards on truthfulness. He
can look Americans straight in the eyes and lie, such as his
performance on
</P>
<P>
   60 Minutes when he lied about his affair with Gennifer Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Americans heard him on tape urging Flowers to lie about their
affair if questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Americans flocked to this new Clinton standard by saying, ``If
you can't lie about sex, what can you lie about?'' Har, har. Wink,
wink. Nudge,
</P>
<P>
   nudge.
</P>
<P>
   Now Clinton appears to be caught in a lie under oath when he
said he did not have sex with Monica Lewinsky, a 21-year-old White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Another new lowered moral standard is the argument that even if
the president did lie under oath in the Paula Jones case, it was a
civil
</P>
<P>
   case. Besides, the case was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   So, thanks to Clinton, the new standard is that Americans can
commit criminal perjury as long as it is committed on a civil case
that might
</P>
<P>
   get dismissed. Parents may have a difficult time teaching that
standard of criminal mendacity to their children.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legacy of lowered morality also has left parents with
the chore of explaining oral sex, semen-stained dresses and how
some daddies
</P>
<P>
   cheat on their mommies.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with this, thanks to Clinton and
his legacy to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
