<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marilyn Geewax's Business Commentary: Hitting the jackpot
without Powerball
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Becoming a millionaire is surprisingly easy. Any American
teenager with average intelligence and decent health can plan to
retire with more than $1 million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the August/September issue of The Futurist
magazine lays out the simple guidelines for retiring rich. To
guarantee ``future wealth,'' just get a solid education, work hard,
invest early, stay married and don't squander money on frivolous
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But could it really be that simple? Could a blue-collar worker
with no college degree or inheritance really retire as a
millionaire? Absolutely. Here's how, based on financial
calculations in The Futurist:
</P>
<P>
   Let's say a teenager finishes high school and gets a job. He
lives lean so he can put $500 a year into a savings account and
still spend about $3,000 over a few years to pay for the training
to become an auto mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Now at age 22, he has $2,000 in savings and lots of
opportunities to earn $30,000 a year as a mechanic. If he puts his
savings into a mutual fund paying a 10 percent compounded rate of
return (equal to the appreciation of the stock market over the last
50 years), he will collect $194,000 from that one-time investment
at age 70.
</P>
<P>
   Then assume our young mechanic can average a 2 percent annual
pay raise (after adjusting for inflation) throughout his career. If
he saves just a tenth of his income each year and invests it
conservatively for a 6 percent rate of return, he'll have $1.1
million at age 70. Throw in the $194,000 from his initial
investment, and he's living on a lake, golfing every day and
driving a big luxury car. If he stays married to someone who earns
and saves a similar amount, the couple will be multimillionaires,
and that's not even counting the equity they might have in a house.
</P>
<P>
   Without getting any inheritance, without worrying about Social
Security, without depending on his boss for a pension plan, our
mechanic will retire wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Powerball, the crack cocaine of state
lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, millions of Americans put on a dramatic demonstration
of why very few people will retire as millionaires. The
lottery-crazed gamblers took time off work, drove long distances
and wasted valuable hours in huge lines trying to buy a ticket to
instant riches.
</P>
<P>
   An individual's chances of winning the jackpot were less than
one in 80 million, slightly less than my chances of being crowned
Miss America this year.
</P>
<P>
   While one winning ticket did make a few people rich last week,
the rest of the country was made poorer. The news media were filled
with reports of people who skipped work and spent small fortunes on
gasoline trying to get to packed stores where they could throw away
more time and money on tickets.
</P>
<P>
   How many waitresses will struggle this week because their
customers squandered potential tip money on the lottery last week?
How many kids won't get a back-to-school sweater this week because
their mothers blew the budget on Powerball? How many trips to the
dentist will get put off because would-be patients lost their
meager savings?
</P>
<P>
   At least in Georgia, which does not participate in Powerball,
people have realistic chances of becoming millionaires from the
lottery. That's because lottery revenue goes into the HOPE
scholarship program.
</P>
<P>
   Losers buy the lottery tickets. The winners ignore the games and
focus on qualifying for the scholarship money. Those who use
lottery funds to get good educations can easily become
millionaires. In Georgia, those who throw their money down the
lottery rat hole make it possible for others to retire rich and
happy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-98 2258E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
