<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take a tour of the '60s and keep on truckin'
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- August marks the birthdays of a pack of '60s icons
including Andy Warhol and the Grateful Dead's late front man, Jerry
Garcia. In their honor, why not crank up your Web-based time
machine and take a closer look at the people and ideas that shaped
the 1960s?
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly as many sites for the Dead as there are bootleg
concert tapes, but any Grateful Dead Web journey should start at
the official home page at http://www.dead.net, which also offers
links to a variety of sites related to San Francisco, the sixties
and other influences on the band. One link leads to a site called
Sixties.com (http://www.sixties.com), a tribute to the legendary
Haight-Ashbury culture and birthplace of the band.
</P>
<P>
   As the historians and other folks who keep tabs on such things,
the '60s were also a time of political and social upheaval, some of
which is chronicled on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Psychedelic '60s: Literary Tradition and Social Change
(http://www.lib.virginia.edu/exhibits/sixties/index.html) is a
treasure trove of information on the music, poets and politics that
helped shape the decade. Once you get past the lofty-sounding
title, it's possible to spend hours here reading up on people such
as Timothy Leary, newspapers such as the long-defunct Berkley Barb,
or about the early origins of the women's movement. There's lots of
information here, well written and well organized. One small
complaint is a few more pictures would have been nice, but as a
'60s primer this is an excellent resource.
</P>
<P>
   For more of an immersion experience, try the Summer of Love Web
site at http://www.sftoday.com/enn2/summerlove.htm. ``Enter here
with flowers in your hair,'' beckons the start page referring to
the line from the song ``If You're Going to San Francisco.''
Visitors can be transported back to 1967 for a virtual tour guide
to San Francisco, ground zero for the legendary Summer of Love.
Learn about the famous Fillmore theater where concert promoter Bill
Graham booked bands such as Jefferson Airplane and the Grateful
Dead, page through the ``Hip Dictionary'' or read up on the Free
Speech movement and Yippie founder and counterculture guru Abbie
Hoffman. Music fans will love pouring over articles about the
Beatles' 1967 landmark album Sgt. Peppers Lonelyhearts Club Band,
which was released that summer, and the Monterey Pop festival.
</P>
<P>
   Warhol fans will find more than just soup cans at the site
designed by the Andy Warhol museum at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .warhol.org. In addition to documenting Warhol's life and works,
it also provides links to other aspects of Warhol's world including
a site devoted to Warhol's one-time musical proteges, Lou Reed and
the Velvet Underground (http://www.rocknroll.net/loureed/), whose
music has been cited as a major influence on many rock and
alternative bands working today. There's also another excellent
site devoted to the Velvets at
http://members.aol.com/olandem/vu.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-98 2251E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
