<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Child proof is proof enough for me
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ All that stands between me and relief are the
gel capsules inside that little bubble - the one I'm holding
between thumbs and forefingers. As I struggle, I remember reading
somewhere that what really separates humans from animals is the
fact that we have opposing thumbs. It made sense at the time, but
looking back on it, I'm not so sure. When was the last time you and
your opposing digits successfully ripped into a little silver
packet that instructed you to ``tear here''?
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   It's 3 a.m. and I'm sitting on the side of the bathtub,
shivering, swearing and trying my damnedest to ``tear here.''
Instinctively, I stick one corner of the bubble pack in my mouth
and begin to gnaw. Nothing happens.
</P>
<P>
   Fumble. Expletive. Vow: If I live, I'll never, ever, buy another
packaging miracle that has been tested by a bunch of sadistic
chimpanzees. And no childproof bottle caps either.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I'm feeling lousier by the minute. I'm thinking maybe
I'd better take my temperature, a serious sign because I haven't
seen a thermometer around the house since my son got out of grammar
school. I begin the search in the most logical place - the linen
closet. Of course, I can't reach anything in the three-foot deep
cabinet so I pull out the bottom drawer and stand on it - barefoot.
But not for long. A couple of seconds at a stretch is all my sick
soles can handle.
</P>
<P>
   I find it on the fourth pain-ridden try, in a jar with some old
plaid shoe laces probably left over from high school days - mine. I
try not to calculate their age (I feel lousy enough already) as I
struggle with the bubble-packaged thermometer. Methodically, I pull
at everything sticking out. Nothing happens. Next, I try pushing
and twisting at the same time. Still nothing. I'm reduced to
swearing as I fling it across the room.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it pops open and the thermometer rolls across the
floor with Biddy Bother, my Siamese nemesis, in hot pursuit. Shes
been taking in the whole show, without comment which is most
unusual for her. She's faster - but I'm bigger. ``If you don't give
me that thermometer,'' I find myself threatening, ``I'm going to
die right here on the spot and you'll miss breakfast because no one
will find my body until mid-afternoon which is probably when 'll
begin to stink.'' I crawl across the bathroom, grab the
thermometer, shake it down, and stick it in my mouth. Too late to
worry about germs. I lean against the toilet and wait.
</P>
<P>
   It's 102. I'm really sick. In fact, I'm feeling a bit like Fred
Sanford, staggering around with my hand on my chest declaring,
``This is the big one, Elizabeth.'' All of my survival instincts
are firing now and my focus is on that bubble packet. I go for the
scissors and begin trimming away the edges. Two snips, and I've
unintentionally disemboweled the blue gel caps and cold remedy is
running through my fingers onto the cat. Neither of us is happy and
now I have to wash off the cat so she doesn't overdose on flu
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In my fever-ridden stupor, I come to the conclusion that the AMA
and the pharmaceutical companies are in cahoots thereby ensuring
that packaging designs will thwart even the most agile sufferer,
and put patent remedies totally beyond the reach of the weak and
the digitally impaired. Result: a trip to the doctor AND a few
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning I visit the doc who listens to me
breathe, shakes his head, and tells me I've done it again -
pneumonia. He writes out a couple of prescriptions and suggests I
take it easy for a few days. I ask if I can have my pills in a
paper bag since only well people can get medicine bottles open.
</P>
<P>
   He's not amused. Okay, I'm sick...and so's my humor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
