<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHREPORT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TNotebooks have crisis of proportions
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- There is in human nature a battle between big and
small, the fascination with what is tiny vs. the awe of bigness.
</P>
<P>
   Some things get cooler as they get smaller. Wireless phones,
silicon chips, quarks, Thumbelina. And, of course, we want some
things to be as big as can be: pro football linemen, Godzilla, the
World Trade Center, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Technology -- natch -- is only too happy to oblige either
impulse.
</P>
<P>
   You want a sport-utility vehicle the size of a township? You
plunk down a few months salary and it's yours. You want a miniature
speaker for your stereo? No problem. Sometimes we want smaller,
sometimes bigger.
</P>
<P>
   But now, notebook computers seem caught between the competing
urges.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the very existence of notebooks seems proof that
people need smaller, lighter computers. The only limit to building
smaller ones seemed to be the size of people's hands -- keyboards
had to be large enough to give us a fighting chance at typing. And
you recall the original notebooks with their three lines of
semi-legible type.
</P>
<P>
   Yet now, notebooks are trying to grow at the same time they
maintain their portability. More specifically, many notebooks are
being made with larger screens -- up to 15.1-inch displays. The
user gets a better picture, often with souped-up sound and graphics
as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the result for those models -- increasingly defining the
high end of the market -- are notebooks that are larger and
heavier. Some even check in at 10 pounds or more.
</P>
<P>
   In the July issue of Mobile Computing &AMP; Communications,
reviewers took on 16 notebooks, each with displays measuring 13.3
inches or more diagonally. Among the machines tested:
</P>
<P>
   -- AMS Tech's Rodeo 3040ECX draws praise for speed and ability
to support several storage devices. However, sigh the reviewers, it
is large and heavy and the display is ``a bit dull.'' For
information on the $3,900 notebook, call the company (626-814-0782)
or visit its Web site (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .amstech.com).
</P>
<P>
   -- IBM's ThinkPad 600, a $4,934 notebook, is fast, thin and --
at 6.5 pounds -- light of weight in the large-display category,
according to reviewers. For more information, call the company
(1-800-426-7255) or visit its Web site (http://www.ibm.com
</P>
<P>
   /thinkpad).
</P>
<P>
   -- Hewlett-Packard's OmniBook 4100 also won generally good
reviews. The $4,274 machine is thin, performs well and offers both
good display and long battery life, reviewers say. For more
information, call the company (1-800-322-4772) or visit its Web
site (http://www.hp.com).
</P>
<P>
   -- VisionBook Pro 7590 from Hitachi costs $4,134 and performs
well, reviewers say. Unfortunately the keyboard is poorly designed
and the battery anemic by comparison to other Pentium notebooks.
For information, call the company (1-800-555-6820) or visit its Web
site (http://www.hitachipc.com).
</P>
<P>
   Using your thumb to travel
</P>
<P>
   Just how you get from place to place is a very personal,
idiosyncratic choice.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind whether you prefer car, bus, taxi, plane, train or
foot power. How do you navigate across the frontier of the screen
in your personal computer? Most PC users started with typing the
complex codes needed for DOS. Thanks to folks like Apple Computer,
the much quicker mouse with the more user-friendly interface became
common. (Although Xerox scientists are generally credited with the
invention.)
</P>
<P>
   A California outfit now suggests that the truly ``natural,
intuitive link between people and computers'' is really the
thumb-operated trackball.
</P>
<P>
   Logitech, which is based in Fremont, Calif., says its TrackMan
Marble is a more advanced cousin of the trackballs used in many
laptop computers. The device results from four years of research
and uses ``advanced optics and neural network logic'' to detect
movement and pass along the information to the computer, according
to Logitech. The result, the company claims, is a control of the
cursor that is fast and precise.
</P>
<P>
   The device also has three mouse buttons, which can be
customized, letting you assign a function to a button. Traditional
trackball technology is subject to problems with dust, as well as
chemical reactions between metal and oil or with the user's skin,
Logitech says.
</P>
<P>
   The TrackMan Marble works with IBM-compatible systems and
requires Microsoft Windows 95 or Windows NT for scrolling, although
it can be used as a standard mouse with Windows 3.1. Unfortunately,
TrackMan Marble is not yet engineered to be compatible with Apple,
the original user-friendly computer.
</P>
<P>
   Suggested list price for the device is $80.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the company's sales office in North
Miami Beach (510-795-8500) or visit the company Web site
(http://www.logitech.com).
</P>
<P>
   Code or Kierkegaard?
</P>
<P>
   Programming over Proust. That's the conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   It is assumed by many that the route to the techiest of the
high-tech jobs passes through a university's engineering or
computer department or some trade school equivalent. It does seem
logical, after all, that computer programming courses are the path
to computer programming.
</P>
<P>
   But Ellen Ullman, a software engineer and author, says that is
the exact wrong way to produce the next generation of great
techies.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion piece in The New York Times, Ullman argues that
the very idea of a computer science degree is relatively new and
may be misguided. She notes that no one can teach tomorrow's
programmers what the cutting edge will be, since it doesn't exist.
More importantly, she says old-style educations were well-suited to
training someone for an industry that was in constant flux and
frequent revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we knew was how to learn, which is all that one can hang
on to in a profession in which change is relentless. The generation
of programmers who followed us were, well, disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   They just didn't seem to have a clue about anything but
computers, she sighs.
</P>
<P>
   Ullman is author of ``Close to the Machine: Technophilia and Its
Discontents,'' whose title is itself a reference to a certain
well-known work read by many students in liberal arts. Ullman says
schools should stress subjects ``that foster a flexible and open
mind,'' rather than the latest skills, which will become obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Most important is education in the broadest sense, she wrote.
``Programmers seem to be changing the world. It would be a relief,
for them and for all of us, if they knew something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-98 2253E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
