<HEADER>
A5086 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLULAR-911-04-COX     08-03 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLULAR-911-04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    911 calls from cellular phones clogging systems; compensation
sought
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Stephanie Murray was impaled by a
steel rod as she rode in a van, the 13-year-old's mother spent
several crucial minutes with a testy Fort Lauderdale police
dispatcher trying to get the distressed family's location.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Murrays been home, dispatchers' screens would have
displayed their address and telephone number. But they were calling
from a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency and law enforcement managers in South Florida and
nationwide are pushing to make cellular phone users pay for the
technology 911 operators need as the phones boom in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   The phones make up a fourth of lines statewide and up to 30
percent in South Florida. And while projections 2 1/2 years ago
said there'd be more cellular phone numbers than wired lines by
2008, that milepost has already been moved up to 2003.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1996, the Federal Communications Commission ordered that
by April 1998, cellular telephones and systems would have to
provide dispatchers the caller's number and the location of the
nearest phone tower, which narrows the call to about a 5-mile
radius.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC also said that by October 2001, cell companies had to
have technology in place for dispatchers to locate callers within
about 400 feet.
</P>
<P>
   But the FCC said states must have a money source first.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, regular customers already pay up to 50 cents a month
per line for 911. Proposed legislation would charge cellular users
50 cents as well. They now pay nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular companies have balked at the extra expense to customers
but have bought into the idea within the past month, said Jim
Martin, the state's 911 coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefit for this service is enormous and well worth the
price,'' Jim Robinson, manager of advertising and promotions for
GTE Wireless, said from Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the companies have reacted to the 2001 deadline,
improvements in the technology and polls that show public support
for the idea. Some customers surveyed said they'd actually switch
to a company that had it.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators, wary of launching still another tax, have stalled
on the issue. But with phone companies signing on, the lawmakers
are expected to push the bill through the next session, said John
Ricco, governmental liaison for the Florida Association of
Counties, which has supported the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely momentum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said no sponsor has come forward but agreed the plan now
looks good for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Should the legislature approve the plans next spring, counties
would start collecting fees almost right away, but equipment
probably wouldn't be in place until 2000, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, the equipment will cost about $100,000,
said Mark Adler, the county's 911 coordinator. Running it would
cost about $75,000 a month, he said. Martin and St. Lucie counties
do not yet have estimates.
</P>
<P>
   So far, less than 2 percent of the nation's phones are in
compliance with the FCC rule, said Bill Stanton, executive director
of the National Emergency Number Association, a non-profit group
that supports 911 dispatch centers and educates the public.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC's ruling doesn't provide any penalty, state 911
coordinator Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Automatically knowing a caller's number could save time, money
and even lives if, for example, a motorist:
</P>
<P>
   Makes a prank call that keeps police from a real emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Is ill or being attacked and isn't able to give a location or
cell phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Gives a wrong number because he or she has new service or
doesn't often use it.
</P>
<P>
   Is in an unfamiliar area or a rural stretch with few exits,
landmarks or mile markers _ a problem aggravated by Florida's large
numbers of seasonal residents and tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Calls 911 but the call drops out; the motorist redials but has
crossed into another town and is connected to a different agency,
prompting confusion and overlapping efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are under the impression that we automatically know who
they are,'' said Joe Laviano, 911 manager for the Martin County
Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
