<SLUG> BC-MACNEWS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mac News: Ascend personal manager doesn't quite measure up
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ascend, based on a philosophy of life management, is a popular
personal information manager among PC users. The Mac version,
though, works and feels like an afterthought by the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   It's buggy and missing some major features now standard in most
Mac personal information managers such as Claris Organizer, Now
Up-To-Date (soon to be renamed Eudora Planner) and Consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those who value the emphasis on life goals might like
Ascend. The program holds true to that philosophy, which isn't the
case for any other personal information manager.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, the philosophy asks you to think deeply about
what's important to you and then prioritize your life accordingly.
That is, if you want to be a writer, focus on writing well and not
on how many things you write.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend is the software incarnation of this philosophy. The
program asks you to think about your values, prioritize them and
then come up with a plan to achieve them.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend translates your plan into a series of tasks you can check
off day to day and keep track of your progress toward the greater
goal.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the deeper look at scheduling, Ascend includes a
journal feature. It lets you record your daily thoughts and
feelings. This is not a feature unique to Ascend, since many other
personal information managers now include journals.
</P>
<P>
   Like all of today's personal information managers, Ascend
includes a calendar, a to-do list and an address file. To-dos and
notes can be linked to contacts and contacts linked to to-dos.
</P>
<P>
   The program also lets you store random bits of information such
as a Social Security number or a password. But this feature is not
well integrated into the rest of the program. You can't link these
tidbits of information to contacts or to-dos.
</P>
<P>
   What you won't find in Ascend is a menu bar icon that lets you
quickly enter new items without launching the program. Organizer,
Consultant and Now Up-To-Date all have this feature.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a number of annoying bugs. The calendar doesn't
open up on the current day, and the feature designed to let you
import addresses from another personal information manager doesn't
work at all.
</P>
<P>
   Published by Franklin Covey, Ascend 4.1 retails for about $100.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-98 2251E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
