A5090 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-COMPUTERVIRUS04     08-03 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-COMPUTERVIRUS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Infectious Technology
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Austin's status as one of the country's most wired
cities has a drawback _ a virulent one _ and this past week it hit
close to home.
</P>
<P>
   A computer virus infected personal computers at the University
of Texas last week, threatening to wipe out the hard drives of
thousands of machines. Then Monday, Microsoft Corp. and Netscape
Communications Corp. said that flaws in their popular Web-based
e-mail programs let programmers spread viruses over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more people log onto the World Wide Web, they become
increasingly susceptible to infection from a computer virus,
experts say. And those recent events have left users wondering how
to best protect their machines and files.
</P>
<P>
   One line of defense is anti-virus software, which scans all
files and programs _ new and old _ to check for any of the
thousands of viruses it recognizes. After users purchase the
program from an anti-virus software maker, they can download free
updates from company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virus protection software is only as good as the version
you're running,'' said G. Morgan Watkins, associate director of
Academic Computing and Instructional Technology Services at the
University of Texas. ``Viruses are nasty and can hit when you least
expect it, so get some life insurance _ it won't cost more than
$100. And it's a reality of the computer age.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 years ago, however, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet was still a fledgling community of computers, with
barely a dozen computer viruses running through the system. And
back then, the viruses packed more attitude than punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them just carried annoying messages,'' Watkins said.
``One gave me chills _ it had a `Welcome to your worst nightmare'
feel to it. Another one promoted legalization of marijuana. But
they were more irritating than malevolent.''
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed. In the span of a decade and backed by the
Internet's explosion into a vast global network, computer viruses
have become too numerous to count.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 1,000 new viruses are created each month, according to
Roy Jenevein of Austin-based HighPoint Technologies Inc., which
makes software that recovers data lost to viruses or other
malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   A virus is a string of computer codes that infiltrates a user's
software or memory. Most viruses stay dormant until the computer
tries to carry out a certain task _ and when it does, the virus
takes over and feeds the computer a series of harmful instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A successful virus _ one that does something really nasty _
wouldn't show its true self for some period of time,'' Watkins
said. ``That way, people are unaware that they're infected and it
spreads to more and more machines before being triggered.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, words in some documents might suddenly become
gibberish; at worst, the virus could block access to any files
saved on the machine or make it impossible to even start the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the so-called Win32/CIH virus in UT's computer system
put at risk years of professors' research, the dissertations of
graduate students and even the university's records. Gone
undetected, it could have rendered thousands of machines useless,
Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a day and a half to warn everyone _ that's not much
time,'' Watkins said. ``But I think we got people to read our
messages, and most people weren't affected. We were lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Viruses can attach themselves to specific programs _ like word
processing software or spreadsheets _ or can infect disk or CD-ROM
drives. Jenevein said they don't often eliminate data from
computers, but they hide it so the system can't access any files.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the most common way of spreading a virus is by
attaching an infected file to an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viruses are getting smarter and quicker,'' he said. ``And they
don't give you tips about their nature _ they hit abruptly, and
that's it. Once you've opened an (infected) e-mail, it's too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters are e-mail hoaxes that make it challenging
for users to differentiate between fact and fiction. One widely
circulated _ and, experts say, false _ e-mail claims that opening
any e-mail entitled ``Good Times'' will automatically erase that
computer's hard drive, and it cites Microsoft Corp.'s Bill Gates as
its source.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hoaxes out there, but unfortunately, there's
no way to really know,'' Jenevein said. ``If someone says to watch
out for a certain virus, and you aren't sure about it, the safe
thing is not to touch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the fact that computer viruses can grow and
multiply as fast as their biological counterparts, Watkins said
they're far from being users' most prevalent problem. Bugs in
software or hardware can freeze the screen, forcing users to
restart and lose any unsaved work.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins recommended that both home users and businesses take the
time to back up important files by either saving to diskettes, or
printing the documents.
</P>
<P>
   But, with a laugh, he noted that nothing, not even a computer
virus, is as deadly to data as a simple human error.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, you are your own worst enemy,'' he said. ``How many
times have we thrown something in the trash we wish we hadn't, or
deleted the wrong paragraphs? It happens all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've definitely learned that the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
