<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money Talk: Focused funds are mutuals' fad of day
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The people who sell mutual funds keep coming up with
seductive concepts to get you to invest. Some of those approaches
actually work. Some are no more than gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   But there are others that might well be both a good idea and a
good investment, which brings us to focused, or concentrated funds.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale behind focused funds is beguiling: Instead of
spreading a mutual fund's investments over scores or hundreds of
stocks, the manager concentrates the money in 20 or 30 stocks.
After all, the sales people say, nobody wants to buy the manager's
20 or 30 second-best ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Focused funds are the wave of the present. Morningstar, the
Chicago-based financial publisher, counts 100 diversified, domestic
stock funds that hold 30 or fewer stocks. A full one-third of them
were founded in the last 2 1/2 years. They are, says Morningstar
senior analyst Michael Stout, ``the fund fad of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Stout has studied the trend with great care, and his conclusions
are worth listening to:
</P>
<P>
   ``To sum it all up, if you want to buy a concentrated fund, you
better make sure the manager is a very good stock picker,'' he
said. ``You can't take a mediocre stock-picking strategy, slap a
focused format on it and expect it to do any better.''
</P>
<P>
   So how come they are becoming so popular, or at least more
numerous?
</P>
<P>
   Stout's theory is investors -- paying more attention as they
pour money into retirement funds and the like -- have come to
realize most funds don't do as well as the S&AMP;P 500. In turn, mutual
fund families are looking for ways to improve their performance and
lure those customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea of concentration with just a few super stocks has a
lot of intuitive appeal, and it's probably easy to sell,'' Stout
said. ``Fund companies are always looking for new fund ideas to
sell.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is a momentum factor. ``As fund companies see
other companies coming out with focused funds, they start their
own,'' Stout said. It helps, he added, that some of the focused
funds have impressive records.
</P>
<P>
   So how, then, do investors pick a good one?
</P>
<P>
   Stout's suggestion is to rank small-portfolio funds by 10-year
returns, checking how each fund's average annual results compare
with competitors with similar goals.
</P>
<P>
   The table shows the six funds that scored highest on that scale.
It excludes funds now closed to the public, and it excludes sector
and international funds.
</P>
<P>
   Note this is a first step -- a sorting rather than a selection.
``Now you have to research each of these funds,'' Stout said. ``You
make sure the fund manager is still there, and he's not 65 years
old. And look at the style of the fund, whether it is something
that appeals to you.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, top fund on the list, Oppenheimer Quest Capital
Value, has been managed by Jeff Whittington only since January
1996. Over the last three years it has returned 13.9 percent a
year, according to Morningstar. That's 14.9 points below the S&AMP;P
500. You might still like the fund, but it would behoove you to
look at it more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   A second consideration is Stout's methodology excludes a raft of
younger funds, some of them from well-respected managers and fund
families.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar's FundInvestor, a monthly magazine, reports Ralph
Wanger's Acorn fund family is opening the Acorn Twenty, a U.S.
fund, and the Acorn Foreign Fifty. The latter will spread itself
among 40 to 60 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, SunAmerica has started a Style Select Series Focus
fund, which will invest in the 10 top choices of Elizabeth
Bramwell, Sig Segalas and Tom Marsico.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-98 2259E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
