</P>
<P>
   ALI-PILGRIMAGE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Muhammad Ali arrived
last Tuesday from Canada to begin treatments with Jerry Jacobson, a
retired dentist and oral surgeon who lives in Jupiter. Inside an
office at West Boca Medical Center, Jacobson is surrounded by
acolytes. They are the parents of children with cerebral palsy and
brain damage, and they believe in his magic. They sing his praises.
They believe that the Jacobson resonator will deliver their
children. Ali, too, has come to be saved. Modern medicine, the
establishment's best and brightest, have failed him. (Belkin/War,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ August marks the birthdays of a pack of
'60s icons including Andy Warhol and the Grateful Dead's late front
man, Jerry Garcia. In their honor, why not crank up your Web-based
time machine and take a closer look at the people and ideas that
shaped the 1960s? (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING-SICKNESS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You can't see it.
Some can't even smell it or taste it. But you can feel it. ``It's
like chasing a ghost,'' Palm Beach County Facilities Compliance
Manager Dean Zehnter said. Trying to pinpoint exactly what is in
the air at the Palm Beach County Sheriff's headquarters and many
other buildings in South Florida can be as daunting as solving a
mystery. It has cost the sheriff's office an estimated $26,000 in
cleaning and consulting fees since late June to address the
problem. (Weis, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CELLULAR-911 _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Stephanie Murray was
impaled by a steel rod as she rode in a van, the 13-year-old's
mother spent several crucial minutes with a testy Fort Lauderdale
police dispatcher trying to get the distressed family's location.
At home, dispatchers' screens would have displayed their address
and telephone number. But they were calling from a cellular phone.
Emergency and law enforcement managers in South Florida and
nationwide are pushing to make cellular phone users pay for the
technology 911 operators need as the phones boom in popularity.
(Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ ATLANTA _ The people who sell mutual funds keep
coming up with seductive concepts to get you to invest. Some of
those approaches actually work. Some are no more than gimmicks. But
there are others that might well be both a good idea and a good
investment, which brings us to focused, or concentrated funds.
(Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-COMPUTERVIRUS _ As more and more people log onto the World
Wide Web, they become increasingly susceptible to infection from a
computer virus, experts say. And those recent events have left
users wondering how to best protect their machines and files.
(Cocks, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ Despite grumbling from old-time Internet
users, some of the best things on the Net are still free. Better
yet, some things that weren't free in the old days -- e-mail, for
instance -- are available from a number of sources without paying a
penny. Just to be clear, most of the free e-mail services require
you already have a way to connect to the Internet. There are
exceptions but, most commonly, these services are most often used
by people who already have access to the Net at school or work.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MACNEWS _ Ascend, based on a philosophy of life management, is a
popular personal information manager among PC users. The Mac
version, though, works and feels like an afterthought by the
publisher. It's buggy and missing some major features now standard
in most Mac personal information managers such as Claris Organizer,
Now Up-To-Date (soon to be renamed Eudora Planner) and Consultant.
Still, those who value the emphasis on life goals might like
Ascend. The program holds true to that philosophy, which isn't the
case for any other personal information manager. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
