<HEADLINE>
PUTTING A GUILT TRIP ON GUILT-TRIPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pat Robertson hasn't thought of this one yet,
but it occurs to me every day: God's punishment for the liberal San
Francisco Bay area is liberals.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, it isn't earthquakes, fires or possible comets.
It's all those people with ``Commit random acts of kindness''
bumper stickers, the ones who commit systematic acts of
guilt-tripping for the greater good.
</P>
<P>
   The following is one example: On a hot Saturday not too long
ago, I bought a carton of Coors on sale at Safeway. In the parking
lot, a woman getting out of an expensive, nonunion-made Japanese
car looked at the picture of John Wayne on the side of the Coors
carton and said, ``John Wayne beer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right, pilgrim,'' I said. ``It's on sale.''
</P>
<P>
   (I could have added that it's also good hot weather beer,
because it's the beer most like water, but I didn't.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Republican beer,'' she snorted, as she went into Safeway,
owned by Republicans who laid off thousands of workers after a
merger a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I drove home seething with smart comebacks I could have made,
then drowned my sorrows in the insipid product of right-wing
brewers.
</P>
<P>
   The anonymous grocery-store guilt trip is one of the basic
Bay-area interactions. You can get nailed by a stranger for
anything from not bringing your own cloth bag to buying red meat.
If you buy veal, the call probably goes out for guilt trip backup.
</P>
<P>
   Most guilt-tripping is done with the simple glare. However, many
strangers, like the woman who didn't like John Wayne or Joseph
Coors, have the effrontery to lecture you.
</P>
<P>
   These are people who won't even shush their screaming kids.
</P>
<P>
   I still don't have a good response to the grocery-store guilt
trip. All I can think of is: ``Do I know you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut up'' or ``Who are you, Jiminy Cricket?''
</P>
<P>
   Say this for right-wingers. They don't guilt-trip people for,
say, wearing Birkenstocks. They just laugh.
</P>
<P>
   For bigger sins, they call for comets from God _ which we can
deal with, as long as we have Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   There really aren't any conservatives or liberals anymore.
People are defined, not by coherent philosophies, but by who or
what they dislike.
</P>
<P>
   No one is open-minded, as liberals are supposed to be. So-called
liberals are just open about the things they mind.
</P>
<P>
   Like the woman yapping about Republican beer while at a
Republican store, they're maddeningly inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Wear a fur, and get lectured by someone in a jacket made by
slave laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Go hunting, and get shunned by people who buy meat wrapped in
plastic far from stinking feedlots.
</P>
<P>
   Light up a cigarette in your own home, and a neighbor will say
you're poisoning her children through the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Drive a BMW, of course, and you deserve everything you get.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, the list of things you have to feel guilty about
in the Bay area keeps getting longer.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have to feel guilty about sex, though. Perhaps that
explains why Bill Clinton has visited the Bay area more than any
place in the world except that infamous little room off the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Bay-area shoppers know enough to skip grapes, iceberg lettuce
and strawberries because it's better to be safe than sorry about
boycotts. Forget Hefty bags and other nonbiodegradable items made
from depleted fossil fuel resources.
</P>
<P>
   You buy that kind of stuff at Costco where nobody cares about PC
shopping, just good deals. You can engage in mass
crypto-consumption at Costco.
</P>
<P>
   And there was my most recent mistake. In a column last week, I
mentioned buying ``The Joy of Cooking'' at Costco, and a woman who
does publicity for an association of independent booksellers wrote
a full-page letter lecturing me for it. When I called her, she
lectured me more.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry, it was Costco, and the cookbook fell into my cart by
accident, like the other $200 worth of stuff I bought there.
</P>
<P>
   This woman was doing a great job of PR, and she was doing it the
Bay-area way, by guilt-tripping a member of the press.
</P>
<P>
   I love my independent booksellers, who have soul and titles
Borders doesn't have, so I won't add to their problems by saying
how much money I saved by buying ``The Joy of Cooking'' at Costco.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe guilt-tripping will save independent bookstores and fossil
fuels, and keep people from drinking watery Republican beer. It
probably will work in the Bay area, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In my Random House Historical Dictionary of American Slang, by
J.E. Lightner, the noun ``guilt trip'' first appears in literary
sources in the 1970s. One of the first appearances of the term is
in Cyra McFadden's ``Serial,'' set in our own Marin County. The
guilt trip is our trip.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the beer and book police got under my skin, and this is my
way of working it out.
</P>
<P>
   I guess there's only one thing I can say to all you
guilt-trippers: Don't you feel bad doing it? You ought to.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
