</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOS OF TRAGEDY AREN'T TAKEN LIGHTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Assembling a newspaper is not an exact science.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a science at all.
</P>
<P>
   Each day's product is the result of hundreds _ maybe thousands _
of individual decisions ranging from what ads go where to how many
pages are printed to what goes on what page and with which picture.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one page of the newspaper subject to great
discussion and, often, heated argument. That is the front page.
</P>
<P>
   The decision-making process begins early and continues until the
last available second. Editors from all editions are involved, and
depending on the issue, the executive editor may be called in to
arbitrate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the care, concern and discussion, I can count on a
few calls each week about the front page. Readers want to know why
some stories made it and others did not. Some call with a list of
stories that they think were more worthy than those picked by the
editors.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to the Fort Worth Star-Telegram of July 13 and a
picture on the front page that showed the grieving aunt of Edna
Rodriguez. The 8-year-old girl disappeared from her home July 11,
and her body was found the next day. The July 13 photograph was an
excellent picture taken by Joyce Marshall. But it also showed in
the far background the child's body covered by a sheet.
</P>
<P>
   There was much discussion before the picture was printed.
</P>
<P>
   There were only a few calls. No one argued that the story
belonged elsewhere, but they did believe that the picture was
invasive.
</P>
<P>
   I do not react well to such pictures, although over the decades
I've shot television footage of the same scene and directed
front-page placement of other, similar photographs. I also must
admit that I am more conservative in my present role than I was
when the decision to print belonged to me. But I am conservative on
this.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, I reacted to the tiny image of the child's covered
body in the background, which, for me, would have been the deciding
factor against front-page publication.
</P>
<P>
   I reported the reader conversations to the staff and questioned
whether these kinds of pictures are so common as to add little
information to the stories they accompany. Senior editors
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty in capturing a photo like this one by Joyce
Marshall is enormous,'' said Gregg Ellman, photo chief in the
Arlington newsroom. ``To begin with, you're dealing with a hostile
environment because of the crime involved, and carrying camera
equipment just makes you even more of a target for abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation was tragic,'' he said. ``As journalists, we are
supposed to cover the news. Unfortunately, more often than not the
news is not positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days we have to fight very hard with our own editors to
get high-impact photos in the paper because many of them are
running scared to put a photo of this caliber on their pages,''
Ellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Vetter, a Star-Telegram managing editor in Fort Worth,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had numerous discussions about sensitivity and invading a
woman's moment of grief before deciding that this was a wonderful
photo that captured the horror and emotion of a little girl's
death,'' Vetter said.
</P>
<P>
   The covered body in the background never came up because it was
a very small part of the image, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sensitivity should always come into play; in this case, we
chose a photo of the aunt with a hand over her face, which gave her
a small measure of privacy yet still conveyed the moment,'' Vetter
said. ``But we can't go overboard and be too cautious. Sometimes
the news should horrify and disturb people.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall is a thoughtful and sensitive photographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggle with taking the responsibility that comes with my
actions and the pictures I take and do not take,'' she said. ``I
weigh the cost the photo will have on the people involved and the
benefit to the reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am aware of my intrusiveness as a member of the media in
times of tragedy and emotional devastation and see too many times
the exploitation of this grief,'' Marshall said. ``I am glad that
we continue to question our decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   I found her description of the scene that day particularly
telling:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrived at the location where the child's body was
found, the first person I encountered was a very distraught
television reporter who had witnessed the scene as the police
discovered the body of the missing girl,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to tell a story with pictures, and that is what was
on my mind, while, through my own tears, I witnessed family members
collapse under unimaginable grief,'' Marshall said. ``Although I
stayed for several hours, I did not take many pictures or feel a
need to follow family members to their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   One surprising thing you learn as a journalist is that people in
grief often are willing, sometimes eager, to share their grief with
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very fine line between public moments and private
ones,'' Marshall said. ``Eleven years ago my ideas were challenged
by a family who at the very emotional funeral of a mother and two
children _ immigrants from India who died a violent death _ asked
me to record their grief in its most painful and direct form.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I would have backed off, they urged me forward, saying
they wanted their story to be told.''
</P>
<P>
   The decisions first to shoot and then to print photographs like
this one are taken very seriously. You may not agree with those
decisions, and when you do not, you should call or write because
that helps us the next time.
</P>
<P>
   But the decisions are not made lightly, nor are they made _ at
least in print _ just to sell papers.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is ombudsman for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
His e-mail address is harral(at)star-telegram.com. You may
telephone him at (817) 390-7692 or write him at P.O. Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX, 76102. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
