<HEADLINE>
NEED SOME GOOD LUCK? TRY A HORSESHOE, OF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Superstitions and folklore continue to surround
us, even in today's learned society.
</P>
<P>
   One superstition that has to do with good fortune or luck is
hanging a horseshoe over the door to a house, garage, barn or
business.
</P>
<P>
   The first horseshoe-manufacturing machine was patented in 1835
by Henry Burden of Troy, N.Y. Back then, you were likely to find a
thrown horseshoe on any country or city road. Today, they're only
found in those areas where there is still horseback riding.
</P>
<P>
   If you come upon a horseshoe, legend has it that you must spit
on it after you pick it up, and then hang the horseshoe over your
door for good luck.
</P>
<P>
   Horseshoes hung over doorways were believed to keep the devil
and evil witches away. Why the devil? Legend is that the sound of a
blacksmith hammering shoes on an anvil attracted his attention one
day. The devil bought a set of shoes for his hoofs, but the
blacksmith, knowing who he was dealing with, nailed on red-hot
shoes without first cooling them down in water. Instead of driving
the nails around the outside of the shoe and hoof, he drove the
nails straight through the center of the devil's hoof.
</P>
<P>
   The devil paid for his shoes and left. After walking several
miles and dancing and prancing, the shoes became pure torture. No
longer able to endure the pain, the devil tore the shoes off his
hoofs and threw them away.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, the story goes, every time the devil sees a
horseshoe, he turns and runs away.
</P>
<P>
   A horseshoe should be hung with the ground surface facing out
and the prongs pointing upward, supposedly so that your luck won't
fall out.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have the right size molding or room before the door
molding meets the ceiling, you can hang your horseshoe with the
prongs pointing downward. According to superstition, if a horseshoe
is hung with the heels hanging down, good luck will flow down on
all who pass through the door.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel that a horseshoe doesn't go with your decor, don't
worry about having to hang it up. Another old bit of wisdom states
that if you find a horseshoe, it will bring you luck if you spit on
it and throw it over your shoulder. But beware of finding a
horseshoe without the nails still in it, as that signifies bad
luck.
</P>
<P>
   Or you just may want to buy a decorative interpretation in
silver or brass, and forget the spitting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
