<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERIES MAKE LOSERS OF US ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ There are 38 state lotteries in America and many,
if not all, try to ensnare customers by hyping the size of their
jackpot. Lottery players throughout the country could care less
about the hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Lotto and the multistate Powerball, among others,
pull the same stunt. Last week, New York said its game offered a
$40 million first prize. The farther-reaching Powerball advertised
a $250 million prize and in the end exceeded that record-setting
amount by $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Should you have been the one singularly blessed to have
prevailed over supernatural odds _ 1 in 80 million for Powerball
and 1 in 12.9 million in New York _ your actual immediate winnings
would not have been the ballyhooed $250 million or $40 million, but
a sum in the range of half of that. To collect the full advertised
amount, you would have to wait 25 years, and take your winnings in
annual installments.
</P>
<P>
   As 50 percent of such a payout is serious money, even for those
already wealthy, the question is why lottery operators insist on
using the higher figure when the lower one is impressive enough.
The reason is self-evident: To incite the kind of lottery mania
that infected many people this past week as they traveled far from
their homes, to stand hours in line, to buy a chance at the
Powerball fortune.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the long-term payout doesn't come to the winner in
26 equal installments. If you grab the brass ring in New York, say
for an announced jackpot of $10 million and have opted for the
25-year payout, you would receive $250,000 the first year, before
taxes. Appreciably higher installments are not handed over until
the 15th year, when you would get $400,000, with subsequent annual
payments increasing by $10,000 each year.
</P>
<P>
   What New York state is doing is investing your winnings in an
annuity (something you rather might wish to do for yourself) and
dribbling out the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   But if, during the quarter of a century it takes to gain all
your promised winnings, your good fortune turns bad and you die,
your heirs inherit the high honor of paying up-front the taxes on
the remainder of the winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Since February 1996, however, players have been given the choice
of taking their prizes in a lump sum, generally amounting to about
half of the advertised prize. But it varies. For a time late last
year, it was down to about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   New York is only doing what every other lottery that offers a
lump-sum payment does, which means that it should be rather
uncomplicated for all to indulge in simple candor and trumpet their
jackpots for their value at the time the numbers are drawn. Why not
make the payout over 30 years, or even more, and thereby enormously
increase the size of the jackpot that could be used to attract ever
greater number of players?
</P>
<P>
   It's absurd. The stark fact is that despite the odds, so many
people play this game. At the beginning, in the late 1960s, $48.5
million in lottery sales were made in New York; during the last
fiscal year reporting period, that figure was more than $4 billion.
In fiscal 1997-'98, nearly $2 billion was paid in prizes.
</P>
<P>
   New York Lottery took in $34 billion between fiscal 1967, when
the games started, and this past fiscal year. That provided $15.5
billion in revenues to the state. Of that amount, New York Lottery
Division spokesman Rob Hayes said, 45 cents of each dollar goes to
an educational account in the comptroller's operation, for use by
the state's schools. Forty cents is awarded in prizes.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear just who plays the lottery, whether it attracts
players disproportionately from among those people for whom a buck
is consequential.
</P>
<P>
   New York Lottery says it aims its advertising at the average New
Yorker, and makes no attempts to target particular sub-groups.
Hayes points out that in 1996, Gov. George Pataki ``directed that
Lotto advertising reflect reality, and no longer show a winner in
his wading pool behind his huge mansion.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's directive came after criticism of lottery
advertising by state lawmakers and others.
</P>
<P>
   Raising money for education is a rationale that can serve more
than the state lottery, for it is a handy argument to extending the
scope of gambling under the battle cry of helping worthy causes.
The existence of lotteries, off-track betting parlors and Indian
reservation gaming halls paves the way for the introduction of
further activities, such as casinos.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, what is being shunted aside is the idea that
government ought to pay for its operations through progressive
taxation, whereby the wealthy pay more than the well-to-do, and
they in turn pay more than those who make less.
</P>
<P>
   There used to be a strong sentiment running in this country that
gambling reflected a weakness of character. Of late, we've stood
that proposition on its head. Not for our betterment.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
