<HEADLINE>
CAPTURING AUTUMN ON FILM: TIPS AND TECHNIQUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes photo of New England scene) 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By ROBERT WINKLER  
 c.1998 Robert Winkler 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No season brings out photographers like the fall.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only because autumn is the most colorful time of year.
Spring, summer and winter are, in their ways, every bit as
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   It's also because no other season reminds us so strongly yet
sweetly that another year has passed, and it is the photographer's
lot to capture its fleeting beauty and to try to stop time in its
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is doing so in a meaningful way. The fall is such
a popular subject that camera-laden tourists are as common as
squirrels. We are all familiar with this scene: a country road
winding into woods ablaze with golds, reds and yellows, and
somewhere in the picture, a weathered barn.
</P>
<P>
   Yet you need only take time to consider the pictorial variables
at your disposal--grouped here into five areas--to return with
photographs that are personal and unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Choosing Your Subjects &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the media abound with predictions of peak foliage
viewing times. These are always tempered by speculation that it
will be an early or late fall, or that the year's colors may not be
at their best, because of insect damage or unfavorable weather.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you choose your advice wisely, you would be mistaken to
equate fall with leaves alone. Fall is also a time for harvesting,
returning to school, migrating birds, changes in the weather,
preparing for winter, for towns and cities to reflect the season,
for outdoor portraits, for photographing lakes and fields--all
valid subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Foliage, nevertheless, is deservedly high on any photographer's
schedule, and if your touring takes you through the woods at other
than peak times--most leaf watching is done on weekends--consider
what you have to gain.
</P>
<P>
   If you're early, the palette will include much greenery, and
you'll be able to show trees and single leaves in transition to
their autumn finery. If you're late, leaves will cover the ground,
and trees in various stages of undress will hint more strongly of
winter, perhaps creating unexpected patterns and interesting
contrasts between the vibrant and the dormant.
</P>
<P>
   A consolation to any fall tourist is that all species of trees
do not show their best colors at the same time. No matter when you
go, you're bound to find enough variety to satisfy all but the most
color-hungry lens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finding the Best Camera Position &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Often, the best angle presents itself immediately. You'll know
you have a shot, and finding the best vantage point will verge on
being an unconscious process. At other times, the subject seems
eminently worthy, but deciding on the approach confounds the
imagination. Then there are shooting situations between these
extremes.
</P>
<P>
   If you're driving and a subject catches your eye, stop and
investigate on foot. Although photographing through an open window
does not preclude good pictures, restrictions on your movements
severely limit angles.
</P>
<P>
   Your first instinct usually will be to take head-on, eye-level
shots. This point of view is the most prevalent and often the most
natural. But remember that the possibilities range from a worm's to
a bird's-eye view.
</P>
<P>
   You can lie on your back and shoot straight up or lie prone for
a ground-level view. If you need more height, try shooting from the
upper stories of buildings; in the country, go to a mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Composing the Picture &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A photograph is a section cut from the world and rendered in two
dimensions. The borders of your viewfinder separate the desired
image; making the exposure takes the subject out of its natural
context and places it in the frame on your film.
</P>
<P>
   A ``natural'' landscape would follow the contours of the scene.
Edges of the frame would lie between distinct pictorial
elements--between trees or leaves--and the horizon would guide you
in leveling the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Details can be suggestive of the whole. A leaf can represent the
season just as well as a mountainside of trees. Blades of fading
grass, ripened fruit, an abandoned plow, a pile of apple
crates--you can show them close up or from a distance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Enhancing the Effect &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Choose 200-speed color film if you plan to shoot under bright
conditions; otherwise, go with the greater range of a 400-speed
film. For deeper colors, you can darken a blue sky and reduce light
reflections by using a polarizing filter over the lens.
</P>
<P>
   If your camera allows you to vary the aperture or f/stop
setting, overexpose slightly to bring out subtler hues, or
underexpose to give colors fiery prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Shutter speed may seem of little concern when your subjects are
rooted in the earth, but even a slight wind can set them in fast
motion. In that case, if your camera has variable shutter speeds, a
setting of 1/2SO of a second or higher may be warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Allow swaying tree limbs to paint a picture for you by placing
the camera on a tripod or other support and making an exposure of
1/4 of a second or longer. The crown of a large tree can extend 50
feet or more from front to back, so focus on the most important
element to put it in sharp relief.
</P>
<P>
   To create an unconventional but pleasing effect, throw the lens
out of focus. Colors will bleed indistinctly beyond their natural
borders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Creature Comforts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're planning long hikes through the woods, give some
thought to comfort and camera protection. Although you can slip a
compact point-and-shoot camera into a pocket, you might replace the
skinny plastic neckstrap that comes as standard equipment on most
full-size 35-mm cameras.
</P>
<P>
   With a somewhat wider fabric or neoprene strap, you'll have less
slippage and strain factors that grow in significance once you've
hiked for hours with a camera around your neck.
</P>
<P>
   A harness, consisting of a strap that goes around your back and
fastens to the camera, will keep the camera from bouncing around on
your chest and from getting tangled in branches.
</P>
<P>
   Among the non-photographic accessories you'll need are a
baseball cap with a broad sun visor, insect repellent and a
flashlight if your foray will begin late in the day. Wearing hiking
boots with soles that are not too worn minimizes the risk of a
fall, which can wreck your equipment even if it doesn't injure you.
</P>
<P>
   Stay off wet or slimy rocks, logs and roots, and don't cross
streams unless you can do so safely. As the season wanes, many
photographers go into hibernation until spring. So, while the
weather is still pleasant and the landscape full of life and color,
walk slowly and carry a loaded camera.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Robert Winkler is a nature columnist and photojournalist based
in Connecticut. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
