<SLUG> BC-PRESENTATION-QUIZ-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIZ YOURSELF: THE PROCESS FOR EFFECTIVE PRESENTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By VALERIE SOKOLOSKY  
 Copyright 1998 Valerie Sokolosky 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Giving an effective presentation to your boss, a school
committee or your own staff takes time for preparation and
following a process. Take this quiz to determine your thought and
planning procedure.
</P>
<P>
   1.) When making a presentation to any group, you should first:
</P>
<P>
   _A. Decide what topic you will present.
</P>
<P>
   _B. Analyze your audience.
</P>
<P>
   _C. Prepare an outline to fit the time allotted for the
presentation
</P>
<P>
   2.) As you analyze your audience, an important consideration is
to include different methods of delivery because:
</P>
<P>
   _A. People learn differently.
</P>
<P>
   _B. People will not be bored.
</P>
<P>
   _C. People will realize you are creative
</P>
<P>
   3.) Probable objectives for a presentation would include:
</P>
<P>
   _A. To inform, persuade or give a viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   _B. To showcase your department and its accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   _C. To practice getting over nervousness in front of a group
</P>
<P>
   4.) When deciding your objectives, it is important to:
</P>
<P>
   _A. Review existing data to determine what else is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   _B. Anticipate what is expected by your audience
</P>
<P>
   _C. Determine whether or not you desire to take a strategic
approach.
</P>
<P>
   5.) A tactical approach is called for when:
</P>
<P>
   _A. The step by step plan to achieve an end is needed.
</P>
<P>
   _B. You must have handouts with graphs and charts to prove your
points.
</P>
<P>
   _C. There are people in the audience who are more inclined to
listen to an analytical approach.
</P>
<P>
   6.) When gathering data for organizing your presentation, you
should:
</P>
<P>
   _A. Write everything down, avoiding evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   _B. Try to categorize your information.
</P>
<P>
   _C. Look only at pertinent facts relevant to what you are
presenting.
</P>
<P>
   7.) In preparing the content of your presentation, the opening
and closing should each be:
</P>
<P>
   -A. 5 percent of the entire presentation.
</P>
<P>
   _B. 10 percent of the entire presentation.
</P>
<P>
   _C. Whatever is required to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   8.) Handouts should be used to:
</P>
<P>
   _A. Provide a take away that details everything that you
present.
</P>
<P>
   _B. Reinforce and supplement your presentation.
</P>
<P>
   _C. Show your creativity by giving well-illustrated information.
</P>
<P>
   9.) When specifying a time for questions to be asked, you
should:
</P>
<P>
   _A. Tell people at the beginning when you will answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   _B. Open the floor at the beginning and let questions come
throughout the talk.
</P>
<P>
   _C. Tell people you will only take questions at the end of your
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   10.) If someone asks you a hostile question during the
presentation, you should:
</P>
<P>
   _A. Be firm and answer the questions in a direct manner.
</P>
<P>
   _B. Answer the question by mirroring the level of hostility of
the questioner.
</P>
<P>
   _C. Tell the questioner you will answer after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANSWERS &QL; :
</P>
<P>
   1.) B. Know things about your audience, like the culture of the
people in terms of race, language and religion. Understand the
attitude of the people attending as it relates to their reason for
attending and whether you are giving good or bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Know the size of the group, ages and experience in terms of
knowledge of your subject and position or status. This information
will guide you in knowing the level of detail you will need to give
as well as potential problems you should anticipate.
</P>
<P>
   2.) A. People have different learning and listening styles,
which include visual, kinesthetic (through experience) and/or
auditory. Those who learn visually like demonstrations, stories or
analogies, overviews at the first and an enthusiastic style of
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Those who learn kinesthetically like activities, opportunities
to ask questions, quizzes and participation. Those who have an
auditory style of learning like an organized talk with statistics
and facts. By including parts of your presentation that will reach
all learning styles, you will gain more buy-in from your audience.
</P>
<P>
   3.) A. Perhaps you are informing senior management on your
department's recent productivity levels. Maybe you are giving a
sales presentation. Or you might discuss recent losses to
competition with your view of the situation. Deciding the primary
objective helps you plan a targeted presentation.
</P>
<P>
   4.) C. There are times when a strategic approach is required,
such as developing a five-year strategic plan or presentations
targeted at long range objectives.
</P>
<P>
   5.) A. A tactical approach to a presentation is detailing the
ways to achieve an end result. It should include what skillful
methods you will use.
</P>
<P>
   6.) A. When you first begin gathering data you should find as
much material as possible without trying to judge what order,
category or relevancy it has.
</P>
<P>
   7.) A. A well-structured presentation should include an opening
that gets attention and a close that includes a call to action.
Both of these should not exceed 5 percent of your total allotted
time.
</P>
<P>
   8.) B. It is your choice whether to hand out papers before or
after your presentation. The decision is determined by whether or
not people need to take notes and follow along during your talk or
if the information can be reviewed later.
</P>
<P>
   9.) A. Tell the audience at the beginning of your presentation
whether or not you want to have them ask questions any time or if
you will take questions at the end. If you wait to answer questions
at the end of the presentation, be sure to prepare a statement to
bring closure to the allotted time.
</P>
<P>
   10.) A. When you are knowledgeable about your subject you can
give a credible, direct answer. Acknowledge a person's feelings in
order to defuse emotions implied in a hostile question.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCORE &QL; :
</P>
<P>
   If you have answered this quiz with a high score, 80 to 100, you
are thinking clearing and professionally. Your presentations are
well planned. I wish you continued success.
</P>
<P>
   If your score was 60 to 70, remember that giving a professional
presentation that gets the results you want calls for not only good
execution, but also careful planning ahead of time. Take note of
the questions missed and add the information next time.
</P>
<P>
   Below 60: Maybe you are not making many presentations at this
point in your career. Take note of the important concepts in this
quiz if you begin making more presentations and get started on the
right foot.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Valerie Sokolosky is a free-lance writer based in Dallas,
Texas.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Distributed by new York Times Special Features &LR; ) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
