<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEET-POTATO-BLUES-LI     08-03 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEET-POTATO-BLUES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD CLASS ROOT THAT CAN'T GET A BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a 150-word sidebar 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 BY JON MILLER 
 c.1998 Jon Miller 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ I like sweet potatoes, and always have. I like
their texture, their flavor and how they look. I like them baked or
boiled or cooked into pies, and I cringe when they are smothered in
marshmallows.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I consume, at best, two pounds of sweet potatoes a year. And
each time I reacquaint myself with their earthy charms, I ask
myself the same question: Why don't we do this more often?
</P>
<P>
   Finding myself in Lima, Peru, I decided to look for an answer.
Lima bills itself as the City of Kings, but to root-crop
cognoscenti it is better know as the Spud Capital of the World. Few
cities can compete with Lima for the quality and variety of its
underground provender.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the home of the International Potato Center (known as
CIP), where scientists from 26 countries look for ways to improve
and promote a range of nutritious roots and tubers.
</P>
<P>
   CIP sees the potato as an answer to some of the world's most
pressing food needs. It is high in energy and vitamins, and easy to
grow. Indeed it has been a lifesaver through the ages. Sweet
potatoes grown in backyard gardens in the Philippines during World
War II helped keep American and Filipino prisoners from dying of
malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese have repeatedly relied on sweet potatoes for famine
relief, especially after typhoons devastated rice crops. Sweet
potatoes saved millions of lives in famine-plagued China in the
early 1960s; in Uganda, where a virus is currently ravaging cassava
crops, farmers are banking on the sweet potato to keep hunger at
bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all else fails,'' says Peter Ewell, an American economist
who heads CIP's Africa program, ``the sweet potato is always
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumption is down almost everywhere. The reason is not
taste or texture, but image. ``All over the world, people think of
sweet potato as a poor man's food,'' complains plant physiologist
Noel Pallais.
</P>
<P>
   In Peru, farmers grow sweet potatoes as an off-season cover
crop, and feed much of the produce to cattle, pigs, or dogs. In
China, which grows more than 80 percent of the world's sweet
potatoes, more than three-fourths of the crop goes to livestock and
industry; only about 15 percent becomes human food, mostly for the
poorest sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers are always proud to tell us that they aren't eating
sweet potatoes anymore,'' says Zhang Dapeng, a CIP plant breeder
whose native Szechwan province leads the planet in sweet potato
production.
</P>
<P>
   In a hallway at the potato center stands a glass case with some
promising options. From Peru come sweet potato starch, flour,
bread, and chips. From the Philippines come ketchup, jam, bottled
juice, and powdered soup.
</P>
<P>
   From Brazil comes a spicy snack food and bricks of sweet potato
paste. But by far the most ingenious collection comes from Japan:
candied cubes, salty balls, caramels and toffees, dark syrup, two
kinds of snack sticks, four kinds of noodles, and a perfectly clear
liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even in Japan, sweet potatoes are losing their allure. Since
World War II, the land planted in sweet potatoes has plummeted.
Taiwan and Korea also saw production drop dramatically as their
economies boomed. Although the sweet potato still ranks seventh
among food crops worldwide, it's hardly at the top of its game.
</P>
<P>
   Except in Africa, where it is one of the few crops whose
production kept up with growth in population. In Rwanda, adults eat
about a pound a day. It was critically important in Uganda during
its recent civil war. ``You can drive tanks over it, you can leave
it for six months, and it's still there,'' says Ewell.
</P>
<P>
   Not to say people hold it in high esteem, however. ``It's a food
that you would never serve to guests,'' Ewell notes. ``It's the
macaroni and cheese of African cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Reynoso, a Peruvian plant breeder, says the potato is
high in Vitamins A and C -- nutrients in which millions of children
in developing countries are deficient. It provides half again more
energy, nearly twice the fiber and more than three times the
calcium of potatoes. The greens, which can be eaten by humans or
fed to animals, have a protein content about the same as alfalfa.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes grow low to the ground, making them virtually
invulnerable to hurricanes and typhoons. They require few
chemicals, minimal water and almost no weeding. And they are
extremely productive.
</P>
<P>
   North Americans mainly know the Jewel and Centennial varieties,
with their deep orange flesh and brown skin. China is dominated by
a creamy white variety called Xushu-18. But Papua New Guinea claims
no fewer than 5,000 different kinds. Indonesia boasts about 4,000,
the Philippines 1,000, and Uganda 700.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes range from white to purple; some have lovely
kaleidoscopic patterns when opened. They can be as small as golf
balls or large as watermelons. Some are moist and sweet, while
others are dry and virtually flavorless.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are drawing from CIP's sweet potato gene bank to
improve productivity and address nutritional needs. In Africa, a
priority is to boost the Vitamin A content of the white sweet
potatoes that most people prefer. In Latin America, researchers are
looking for ways to ward off the sweet potato weevil, the crop's
most tenacious pest.
</P>
<P>
   The worst enemies of sweet potatoes aren't genetics or insects,
though, but memory and culture. Even in America, sweet potatoes
remind many people of hunger and hardship (like Thanksgiving, a
symbolic remembrance of a humbler past). Yet perhaps someday the
tables will turn, and the sweet smell of roasting sweet potatoes
will move us to rejoice in the generosity of the earth. In the
meantime, they deserve at least some thanks and respect.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
 &UR; A YAM IT'S NOT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sweet potato and yam are unrelated. Yams have scaly skin,
sweet potatoes are smooth. Yams are tubers (like potatoes); sweet
potatoes are roots (like carrots). Yams rarely grow in temperate
countries. What Americans call yams are almost always sweet
potatoes. The confusion probably dates to slaves, who associated
the sweet potatoes in America with the yams they knew back home.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes can be found in more than 100 countries. In the
United States, more than half come from North Carolina and
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia and the Pacific, sweet potatoes have been used to combat
asthma, constipation, sore throat and delayed lactation. In China,
doctors are investigating their usefulness against kidney, spleen,
and stomach ailments and some forms of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Jon Miller is a free-lance writer based in in Lima, Peru.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
