<HEADER>
A5162 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETTER-HEALTH-SHORTCU     08-03 1927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTER-HEALTH-SHORTCUTS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
20 SHORTCUTS TO BETTER HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By TRISHA CALVO 
 c.1998 McCall's 
 North American rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't need a lot of time to boost well-being, ease stress,
maybe save your life. We looked at research on preventing illness
and found 20 strategies that each take ten minutes or less. What
are you waiting for?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Consider Popping a Vitamin-E Supplement &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The final word isn't in yet, but a steady stream of evidence
points to vitamin E as a potent weapon against major health hazards
like heart disease and possibly Alzheimer's disease and some common
cancers. Women who took 100 to 250 international units daily for at
least two years were able to cut their heart-disease risk nearly in
half, according to Harvard University researchers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Replace Road Rage With Good Manners &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to lose your cool when you're stuck in traffic and
someone tries to cut in front of you. But instead of blocking that
person, do something nice. ``Performing small kindnesses is almost
certainly a health-enhancing behavior,'' says Redford Williams, a
professor of psychiatry at Duke University Medical Center in
Durham, N.C. It helps you stay calm, preventing the release of the
stress hormone cortisol, which can raise blood pressure and
increase cholesterol levels, says Williams. With heart attacks as
the leading killer of women, you'll do yourself a favor when you
cut others some slack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Give Someone a Great Big Bear Hug &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A husband, kid, sister, friend. ``From birth on, humans need
touch,'' says Domeena Renshaw, a professor of psychiatry at Loyola
University of Chicago. ``It's a natural anti-depressant, and it
bonds one person to another.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Do Wall Push-ups for Muscle Tone &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many women have underdeveloped muscles in the upper body _ arms,
shoulders and chest. Upper-body strength training improves posture,
builds bone density (helping to prevent osteoporosis) and makes it
easier to accomplish everyday tasks like lifting a bag of groceries
or a child. Push-ups are effective, but many women can't do even
one. So try this modified version: Place your palms against a wall,
shoulder-width apart, and then step backward until the line of your
body from feet to shoulders is at a 45-degree angle. Bend your
elbows, and slowly lower your upper torso toward the wall until
your forehead is about an inch from it, then push back slowly until
your arms straighten. Repeat 9 times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Don't Just Brush Your Teeth _ Floss Them Too! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter what kind of floss you choose as long as you
use it daily, says Kenneth Burrell, senior director of the Council
on Scientific Affairs at the American Dental Association. Flossing
removes what brushing misses: plaque between teeth that causes gum
disease. To get into the habit, Burrell advises, try flossing at
the same time every day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For a Healthy Snack, Peel and Eat an Orange &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting your five fruits and vegetables a day? Oranges are
portable and nutritious, containing several nutrients most women
need more of like folic acid (plus a little calcium) _ all this for
only 65 calories per medium navel orange. They also supply vitamin
C.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Smooth on Sunscreen (Everywhere) for Skin Protection &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to ultraviolet light can prematurely age your skin and
cause most common forms of skin cancer. Protect yourself every day.
For mostly indoor days use a moisturizer that contains sunscreen.
For outdoor days apply sunscreen liberally to all exposed areas
(don't forget the tops of your feet) at least 15 minutes before
venturing out, to allow the product to be absorbed by your skin.
Reapply every two hours or after perspiring heavily. For added
protection on sensitive areas like nose and cheeks, you can put
zinc oxide over sunscreen. Whatever you use, make sure it's ``broad
spectrum'' and has a sun protection factor (SPF) of 15 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Help Your Diet Along by Walking Up the Stairs &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 135-pound woman burns about 15 calories in two minutes
climbing stairs, compared with three calories or so standing in an
elevator. That may not sound like much, but it adds up: if you take
the stairs five times a day, over the course of a year you'll burn
about eight pounds' worth of calories with very little effort.
What's more, you'll get a mini-workout that will strengthen your
thighs, calves and rear end in the process.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Down a Glass of Low-fat or Fat-free Milk &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An 8-ounce cup of skim milk supplies about 300 milligrams _ a
mineral that can reduce bone loss, helping to ward off
osteoporosis, in which bones become thin and prone to fracture. In
addition, research suggests that a calcium-rich diet may prevent
high blood pressure in some individuals. Don't like milk? Don't
worry. Non-fat yogurt has even more calcium per cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Throw Away Your Old Toothbrush &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bristles become worn and lose their cleaning power after about
three months of use. So buy several toothbrushes at a time _ look
for soft bristles and a head small enough to reach your back teeth
easily _ to have on hand for a quick switch when your current one
frays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Concentrate on Breathing &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stress, tension and anxiety tend to make breathing faster but
shallower, increasing your heart rate and raising blood pressure.
Simply becoming aware of your breathing can help you return to a
more balanced state, notes Elana Rosenbaum, clinical coordinator of
the Center for Mindfulness in Medicine, Health Care and Society at
the University of Massachusetts Medical Center in Worcester.
Whenever you have a couple of minutes _ standing in line, waiting
at a red light _ place your hand on your belly and just notice your
breathing pattern. Pay attention to the up-and-down movement of
your abdomen. When you find yourself in a tense situation, stop
what you're doing and ``go to your breath,'' recommends Rosenbaum.
If you focus on your breathing, whether slow or fast, you can quiet
yourself almost instantly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Give Yourself a Break From Your Computer &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staring at a screen for hours strains your eyes, wrists, neck
and, especially, your back. `'Sitting puts more pressure on your
back than standing or lying down does,'' says physical therapist
Benjamin Gelfand, supervisor of the Nicholas Institute for Sports
Medicine and Athletic Trauma at Lenox Hill Hospital in New York
City. At least once an hour, when you're working at the computer,
get up from your desk and walk around _ take a look out the window
_ or stretch. Try shoulder shrugs (raise your shoulders toward your
ears, hold for a few seconds and then slowly lower) and trunk
twists (stand up, gently rotate your upper body at the waist in one
direction, return to the center and repeat in the other direction),
Gelfand advises.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chat with a Friend &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You might think those who are around lots of other people come
in contact with a variety of germs and get sick - often. Actually
the opposite may be true. When researchers at Carnegie Mellon
University in Pittsburgh exposed people to cold viruses, those with
the widest social network were the least likely to come down with
the sniffles. Other studies have shown that having friends you can
count on leads to longevity. So spend some time with your pals. You
might get it back in the end.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Schedule an Appointment for a Pap Smear &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most doctors believe that every woman over age 18 should have
this test annually, yet one third skipped it last year, according
to a College of American Pathologists survey. The main reason: lack
of time. A pap smear can detect cervical cancer early, when it's
most curable. Death rates from this disease have dropped 70 percent
since the test was developed nearly 50 years ago, and today it's
mostly women who haven't had one in five years whose cases are
fatal. Don't put this test off another minute. (And if you're
worried about time, take some work with you to do in the waiting
room. Or try our two-minute breathing tip, and further improve your
health.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Whip Up a Quick and Tasty Meat Marinade &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marinating chicken before grilling can block the development of
potentially cancer-causing substances that form when meat is cooked
over high heat, find researchers at Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory in Lawrence, Calif. The recipe used in the study
combined olive oil, brown sugar, cider vinegar, lemon juice,
garlic, salt and mustard, but other studies have shown a variety of
alternate marinades will also work. Let your chicken marinate,
covered and refrigerated, at least four hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buy New Mascara &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We all know mascara lasts for ages, but if you use it for ages
you run the risk of getting an eye infection: Bacteria that are
normally present on the eyelids and eyelashes can be transferred to
the makeup container each time you reinsert the wand. Most brands
contain anti-bacterial preservatives, but these start to wear off
in three or four months. If you never use all of your mascara, try
getting a smaller tube or a trial size. Or buy your moisturizer
when mascare is offered as a free gift.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Always Buckle Up &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Halve your risk of dying or being seriously injured in a car
crash by wearing a seat belt each time you're in a car, says the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. If everyone
followed this advice, the number of lives saved annually by seat
belts would more than double, from 9,500 to 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Walk Around the Block &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walking briskly for ten minutes a day can help prevent heart
disease, high blood pressure, diabetes and some forms of cancer,
concluded a panel of experts from the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention and the American College of Sports Medicine. Walking
is easy and convenient: Do it instead of driving to the video
store, or make it a family outing before dinner. Aim to accumulate
30 minutes or more of walking a day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eat Whole-grain Cereal &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's faster than standing in line for a muffin and probably a
lot better for you. Women who ate the most whole-grain cereal
reduced their risk of developing diabetes by about a third compared
with those who ate the least, according to a study at the Harvard
School of Public Health. One reason is that the fiber in whole
grains helps keep blood-sugar levels in check. High-fiber cereal
also fills you up _ enough to reduce the number of calories you eat
at lunch, reports another study _ so having whole-grain cereal for
breakfast may help control weight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Microwave Your Kitchen Sponge &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You've cleaned up after cooking chicken. But now the sponge is a
perfect new home for salmonella. Don't toss it. Just rinse it and
pop it into the microwave for one minute. That's enough to kill
salmonella and other infectious bacteria, finds a study by Dean
Clever, professor of food safety at the University of California,
Davis. He suggests ``cooling'' your kitchen sponge daily. Make sure
it's damp first, and be careful when you take it out _ it will be
hot.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   ( &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &LR; )
</P>
</TEXT>
