<HEADER>
A5163 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-IROQUOIS-     08-03 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-IROQUOIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK EXPLORES THE INTRIGUING WORLD OF THE IROQUOIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER RINGWALD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In 1990, I visited the Tonawanda Seneca
reservation in western New York to interview several chiefs and
leaders for a newspaper series on the Six Nations of the Iroquois
Confederacy. Quite naturally, they wondered, ``Why should we talk
to you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just here for a few hours; how can you understand us,
our history, our culture?'' several continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``William Fenton, when he studied us back in the 1930s, he lived
here for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Inwardly I groaned. Two years! I had to get to my next
appointment. But this mention of the abiding ethnologist steered me
to a remarkable scholar whose career stretched so far back that I
first presumed he was deceased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I have been among the Iroquois people, I have been
told that I must see Fenton,'' reported Edmund Wilson, the critic
and scholar, in his 1957 classic ``Apologies to the Iroquois.'' He
called Fenton his guide and muse for the book.
</P>
<P>
   Now, still at it on the cusp of his 10th decade, William N.
Fenton has capped his career as dean of Iroquois studies with the
engaging, revealing, and massive volume ``The Great Law And The
Longhouse'' (University of Oklahoma Press, 786 pages, $70).
</P>
<P>
   Not all Iroquois respect Fenton's scholarship as did those
traditional Senecas. Many still smart over past disagreements with
Fenton, whose career included stints at the Smithsonian, as
director of the New York State Museum and as a professor at the
State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions always arise between the student and the studied,
particularly in ethnology and anthropology. Some Iroquois fault
Fenton for publicizing sacred ceremonies and betraying the trust of
his informants.
</P>
<P>
   But what is respect if not attention? Fenton's lasting
contribution, so evident in the volume at hand, has been to keep
looking at a people until he sees deeply into their culture and
history in order to explain those to outsiders. Further, past
Iroquois leaders have used Fenton's findings to renew ritual and
custom.
</P>
<P>
   With vivid images and direct language, Fenton brings the solemn
heart and soul of a people pulsing to life on the page, even for
the non-academic reader.
</P>
<P>
   In 1684, after an Iroquois force outwitted a French army, an
Onondaga speaker dictated terms in a famously brief and
distinguished oration. Fenton writes: ``In short, the speech, at
once satire, ritual sanction, and business, shoved the bateaux of
La Barre's sick soldiers off downriver to Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, he notes succinctly that ``cultures, like armies,
move on their stomachs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenton studs his accounts of even the smallest encounter between
the famed Iroquois diplomats and European invaders with details
from the diaries and letters of witnesses, as well as the memories
of descendants. When a female frontier prophet delayed certain
treaty negotiations with several hours of unwelcome prayer and
preaching, Fenton concludes, ``As an act of ill grace, nothing in
the annals of white and Indian affairs quite approaches Wilkinson's
performance before the Indian council during the Canandaigua
treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   When the same talks were almost postponed in order to mourn the
death of an Oneida ancient, the chiefs justified an exception since
the man had been almost dead for so long. Fenton's wry comment:
``Having decided that the Great Spirit would countenance this
breach of custom, they went on with the council.''
</P>
<P>
   The author surrounds each moment, seemingly, with the grand
history of the 17th and 18th centuries, when scores of Indian
tribes and French, English and Dutch forces clashed, made peace and
jockeyed for position, riches and survival.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he sweeps history right up to our own threshold. Fenton
recounts visits to the Six Nations Reserve, a traditionalist
stronghold in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my day, one could still sense the spirit of living history
as the old chiefs recounted the removal of their great-grandfathers
from New York state, how they looked around and discovered that
they numbered a majority of the (Iroquois) league chieftainships,
and how they rekindled the fire and reconstituted the league as a
local government on the reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His ethnological method, common to other experts, is both
profound and simple. Called ``upstreaming,'' it moves from the
obvious _ what can be learned from the living _ to historical
accounts. Similarly, Biblical archaeologists may ask a Galilean
shepherd the significance of an earthen mound before they excavate
it. This method worked well with the Iroquois, still famous for
their memories and oral traditions.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Fenton reports that contemporary Senecas still
recite guarantees _ recorded in diaries but not in the treaty _
made by U.S. representatives at Canandaigua in 1794. He verifies
the reliability of the oldest Iroquois beliefs and legends by
noting that the 1799 teachings of Handsome Lake, a Seneca prophet,
have been preserved for 200 years through periodic recitations.
Their accuracy can be checked against Quaker missionary journals.
</P>
<P>
   Given this record, he writes, ``it stands to reason that other,
similarly kept and validated traditions in the same culture merit
consideration as oral history.''
</P>
<P>
   The volume could have been shorter. Its occasional
repetitiveness and the exhaustive detail may deter readers who
want, and need, to learn more of this ancient and powerful people
who still walk among us. The undeterred will be rewarded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
