<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUISIANA-ACADIANS-HN     08-03 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-ACADIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BON VOYAGE: LAFAYETTE OFFERS A TASTE OF FRANCE IN SOUTH LOUISIANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAFAYETTE, La. _ Want to lose yourself in the heart of Cajun
country?
</P>
<P>
   Consider changing your name to Thibodeaux, Fontenot, Landry,
Breaux or Arceneaux. Or how about Guidry? There are six columns of
Guidrys in the Lafayette phone book. But Broussard has it beat with
12-1/2 columns in the residential pages.
</P>
<P>
   Lafayette is very proud of being the hub city of Acadiana.
Brochures tout it as the ``Heart of French Louisiana'' and everyone
embraces the ``joie de vivre'' that is life in the bayou.
</P>
<P>
   The Cajun people who settled this area in the mid-18th century
migrated from Nova Scotia after a forced exodus by the British
crown. Separated from loved ones, the Acadian exiles found a new
home in French Louisiana, mostly between 1765-81.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Wadsworth Longfellow immortalized the Acadian story in his
poem, ``Evangeline.'' Here in Lafayette you can drive the
Evangeline Highway (Route 90), stay at the historic Evangeline
Hotel or bet on the ponies at Evangeline Downs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cajun French language survives in Louisiana. A waitress may
call a customer ``cher'' (dear), a band sets up to play a dance
called a ``fais-do-do,'' while visitors might be invited to attend
a pig roast, ``boucherie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cajuns seem to love a party. Downtown Alive! is a weekend
festival that runs 12 Fridays in spring (April-June) and fall
(September-November). Downtown shopkeepers sponsor the street party
at Jefferson and Vermilion streets that features bands playing
Cajun, Zydeco, Swamp Pop, jazz, and rhythm and blues.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers _ such as Isaac and Bertha Broussard _ take to the
asphalt to cut a rug as the other partyers enjoy a cold one and
wipe away the sweat. The Broussards, who have been dancing together
for 60 years, are decked out in bright-colored clothes and sport
more than a few strands of beads, which they share with visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of beer and soda ``pay the band,'' says Wayne LeJeune,
events and marketing coordinator for Downtown Alive!
</P>
<P>
   The new Bayou Bullfrogs of the Texas-Louisiana League show up at
Downtown Alive! to drum up support among Lafayette residents. One
of their coaches is Ron Guidry, a former New York Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Lafayette is getting a face lift, including the
construction of a $30 million federal courthouse and an $8 million
street improvement project.
</P>
<P>
   The main streets are wide and cobblestone. Inviting storefronts,
shops and restaurants also are getting a face lift in downtown
Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the library is the Children's Museum of Acadiana,
which is housed in a 1930s grocery store. Everything is hands-on in
this ``learning by doing'' museum. Built in 1987, the museum is
truly a community effort, and the directors work with area teachers
to tie in exhibits with school lessons.
</P>
<P>
   To get a feel for the history of the Acadians who settled here,
explore the Acadian Culture Center, a unit of the Jean Lafitte
National Historical Park and Preserve. A film chronicles ``Le Grand
Derangement,'' the history of the Acadian exodus from Canada. It is
a poignant film with haunting narration and music.
</P>
<P>
   Acadia was former French colony along the Northeast coast of the
Atlantic, including what is now Nova Scotia, New Brunswick and
Prince Edward Island in Canada, and parts of Quebec and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The Acadian Culture Center features artifacts from everyday life
of the people who settled this swampy region in south-central
Louisiana, raising cattle, rice and various crops.
</P>
<P>
   At the center, you might run across park ranger and self-taught
accordionist Phil Rose playing Zydeco music on his squeeze box.
</P>
<P>
   There are two living history museum/villages in the area:
Vermilionville, which is set on 23 acres on the Bayou Vermilion;
and Acadian Village, a folklife museum representing 19th-century
Acadiana, surrounded by 10 acres of gardens and woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   Acadian Village, 200 Greenleaf Road, is open from 10 a.m. to 5
p.m. daily. Admission is $6. Costumed guides lead tours of
structures dating from 1803 to the 1860s, and visitors can watch
women spinning cotton, a blacksmith at work and a craftsman making
Mardi Gras masks as they did in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Vermilionville, 1600 Surrey St., is open from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
daily. Admission is $8 for adults, $6.50 for seniors, $5 for
students (6-18) and free for children younger than 6. In addition
to a guided tour, there's a restaurant, daily live music and Cajun
cooking demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to go wrong with a meal in French Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Check out Mulate's Cajun Restaurant, 325 Mills Ave., Breaux
Bridge, La.; (800) 422-2586 or (318) 332-4648. The restaurant/dance
hall is open from 11 a.m. to 10:30 p.m. and has a live band every
night. Everything is fresh and the specialties of the house are
catfish Mulate and stuffed crabs.
</P>
<P>
   The drive-in daiquiri bar is popular with locals, who don't
consider it an open container.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more information: Contact the Lafayette Convention and
Visitors Bureau, P.O. Box 52066, Lafayette, La. 70505; (800)
346-1958; World Wide Web: www.lafayettetravel.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
