A5169 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUISIANA-SACRED-HNS &LR;      08-03 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-SACRED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRACLES NEVER CEASE IN TINY LOUISIANA TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND COTEAU, La. _ Some people might say that miracles happen
every day. At the Academy of the Sacred Heart in the tiny town of
Grand Coteau, a shrine stands at the site of a miracle that
occurred more than 130 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrims are drawn to the Academy's second floor where they find
what is said to be the only shrine in the United States on the
exact location where a miracle has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   In 1866 a young postulant at the academy, Mary Wilson, was sick
in the infirmary. She offered up prayers to John Berchmans, a holy
priest who lived and died in the 17th century. Nearly blind,
hemorrhaging and probably within hours of her death, Wilson was
cured after having a vision of the priest. (She died 18 months
later of a fever, before taking her final vows.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides the religious overtones that attract pilgrims, the
beauty and history of Sacred Heart draw 2,500 visitors in a town
about half that size.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1821, the school's main building was built in the
1830s. The architecture is Georgian, with bricks created from local
soil and cemented in a pattern known as Flemish Bond. The window
glass, imported from France, still shows dimples and waves,
evidence of its hand-blown origins.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the building are formal gardens, which were restored
in the 1980s. An alley of oaks, called Oakdale, runs from the front
gate of the academy to Grand Coteau. The trees were planted to
provide shade for the priests who made a daily walk from St.
Charles College to the cloistered nuns at the academy.
</P>
<P>
   The site also attracts its share of Civil War buffs, according
to local tour guides. During the Civil War, Union troops were
stationed at Grand Coteau, which is just north of Lafayette, and
skirmishes were fought in the area including the Battle of the Red
River.
</P>
<P>
   During a particularly loud skirmish a nun was said to have sent
out word: ``Gentlemen, please move your battle. It's disturbing our
class.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy found a strange protector in Union Gen. Nathan
Banks, whose daughter attended a New York Sacred Heart school.
Banks supplied the academy with staples from the commissary and
issued orders protecting the academy and its residents.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 370 girls attending Sacred Heart, pre-school
through high school. Parents pay $16,300 a year for their
high-school age daughters to board and attend Sacred Heart.
Students come from all over, many from Mexico and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Coteau campus is the oldest continuous Sacred Heart
School in the world, according to development director Marie
Orgeron.
</P>
<P>
   Computers seem strangely out of place in classrooms that date
from the 1830s, but the girls still wear long white dresses and
march between the oaks during graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road from Sacred Heart, a newer business is making a
mark for the Grand Coteau economy. Catahoula's, named for the state
dog, is serving new Louisiana cooking in an old-fashioned, relaxing
atmosphere. The restaurant, which sits at Grand Coteau's only stop
light, is owned and operated by photographer John Slaughter and his
wife, Hilary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago (we) probably would have died on the vine
with this kind of restaurant,'' John Slaughter said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 minutes from Lafayette, diners don't have too far to
travel to sample chef Daniel Landry's specialities _ Gorgonzola
stuffed angus tenderloin with sauteed oyster shiitake mushrooms or
grilled gulf shrimp with three roasted pepper sauces.
</P>
<P>
   The breaded breast of chicken with corn macque choux over
Cheddar cheese polenta wins hands down over fried chicken and
cheese grits _ typical fare from a small-town Louisiana truck stop.
</P>
<P>
   To get there: Take Interstate 49 from Lafayette, exit 11 to
Sunset/Grand Coteau on Louisiana 93. Turn right at the stop sign
onto Martin Luther King Drive. Catahoula's is at the stoplight at
Church Street and King.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
