<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUYMOVIES-1200(2Takes     08-03 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUYMOVIES-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH-GUY MOVIES LIKE `PRIVATE RYAN' MAKE IT OK FOR GUYS TO CRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A male tear-jerker movie is pretty easy to spot. It generally
involves competition _ which is almost always the way men in movies
feel safest in expressing their feelings for each other _ or the
threat of death, or a manly sacrifice. Some observers believe that
the shameless king of the genre is ``Field of Dreams,'' in which
not only is there a sacrifice (the compromise of adulthood), but
also someone comes back from the dead, and the boys get to have a
soul-healing game of catch. ``Field of Dreams'' is the
I-love-you-man ethos of the Bud Light commercials of a few years
back, writ large.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ultimate men's tear-jerker film _ which happens to
combine at least two of these elements _ is ``Brian's Song,'' the
1971 TV movie. The defining moment is when Chicago Bear Gale Sayers
(Billy Dee Williams), tears streaming down his face, bellows ``I
love you, Brian Piccolo'' _ a tribute to his teammate (James Caan),
who died of cancer. It's probably still the fastest way to get a
group of guys to crumble into weeping.
</P>
<P>
   Such movies differ from traditional melodrama _ ``Gone With the
Wind,'' to use both a now-playing and classic example _ in that the
lump in the throat isn't directly evoked. The shell of masculinity
is preserved at all times, and the man's melodrama is usually set
in a macho line of work, such as those in the current bumper crop,
which includes ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Armageddon.''
Generally, the tears are massaged from a gesture or glance _ a
wounded Tom Hanks, raising a .45 to hold off an approaching tank in
``Ryan'' _ rather than the slow, satisfying build to Vivien Leigh's
``As God is my witness ...'' speech from ``Gone With the Wind.''
There is a riper, higher flow of adrenaline in both cases, but
standard melodrama is freer. Unlike the man's tear-jerker, the
situation doesn't always have to threaten the entire Free World.
</P>
<P>
   Ensemble tough-guy movies like ``The Magnificent Seven,'' ``The
Dirty Dozen'' and ``The Great Escape,'' in which the young stars
winked or grinned into the camera, upstaging each other in a show
of muscle and charisma before sacrificing their lives for the Good
of the Others, gave rise to the male tear-jerker in the '60s. These
movies could be looked upon as a kind of suspense film, because we
wondered who'd make it. And these films reinvented movie-star
hierarchy, changing the rules of who'd survive. In ``The Great
Escape,'' even Steve McQueen, self-contained cool embodied, doesn't
get out alive.
</P>
<P>
   The genre had vanished after John Wayne's constant single-handed
winning of World War II (and the old West for that matter) had
ceased to have meaning. When the war movie disappeared from the
scene, American movies shifted to a loner culture, and the nihilism
of the Vietnam era lent itself more to shock than pathos. The 1972
movie ``The Last Detail,'' starring Jack Nicholson as a lifer
sailor who awakens a part of himself after he transports a naive,
small-time criminal (Randy Quaid) to jail, borders on wresting
tears from us. But it strikes a deeper moral chord, and leaves us
to wrestle with a metaphor for self-denial.
</P>
<P>
   It took the '80s, and a repudiation of the on-screen code of the
leading man, to bring the real return of the men's tear-jerker
movie. The leading exemplar of this new male sob story is Mel
Gibson, whose combination of fragility and volatility finally
launched him into stardom in the ``Lethal Weapon'' movies. With his
clean-jawed good looks, Gibson had flirted with the big time with
such early-'80s movies as ``The Year of Living Dangerously,'' in
which his callow glibness and capacity for hurt made him seem the
first actor of his generation whose suffering didn't lessen his
machismo. When he stared at Sigourney Weaver in ``Year,'' he was
slightly awed by her. He didn't put on a passive male ingenue act,
gazing into the distance and waiting for her to come to him, like
the self-absorbed or overtly sensitive actors of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   He's better in ``Year'' than perhaps in any movie since. In it,
he shows a side that men rarely displayed. Gibson didn't withhold
his feelings, and he wasn't a man of few words, a pose which even
Method avatars like Robert DeNiro still often held. Volubility and
a quick temper burn through Gibson at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in ``Lethal Weapon,'' he wrapped his volcanic baritone _
no actor gets such shadings out of such a normally reassuring vocal
range _ around the role of flamboyantly suicidal cop Martin Riggs.
Watching ``Lethal Weapon'' once, on a plane, I heard the sniffles
as Riggs confessed his anger and shame over his feelings about his
dead wife _ sounds that probably went unheard in the theater when
the film first ran, as the Goobers-rattling explosions and gunplay
made anything below a certain aural range impossible to detect.
Gibson's rages and melancholy, and his attachment to his partner,
Danny Glover, created a bond that had men slapping choked
high-fives of acknowledgment.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
