<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRA-PUNISH-BOS &LR;      08-03 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRA-PUNISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CEASE-FIRE, RISING IRA VIGILANTE VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Andy Kearney was quick with his hands and didn't back
down from anyone.
</P>
<P>
   When he heard that the son of a woman he knew was beaten up,
Kearney went after one of the men who supposedly administered the
beating when he saw him in a bar. Kearney was not intimidated by
the fact that the man was a well-known senior figure in the Irish
Republican Army. In hindsight, perhaps he should have been.
</P>
<P>
   In the early hours of July 19, a group of eight reputed IRA men
appeared at the high-rise apartment Kearney shared with his
girlfriend and their 2-week-old daughter in the New Lodge section
of Belfast. The members of what is known here as a punishment squad
sealed off the perimeter of the building with military precision.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the men burst into the apartment, where they found
Kearney lying down with his infant daughter on his chest. They
ordered his girlfriend to take the baby into another room. Kearney
was marched out into the hallway and summarily shot in the legs.
</P>
<P>
   Before they left, the men ripped the telephone from the wall and
immobilized the elevator. In the time it took for his girlfriend to
run for help down the stairwell with their baby in her arms,
33-year-old Andy Kearney bled to death, one year to the day after
the IRA called a cease-fire it supposedly still observes.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet that destroyed an artery in Andy Kearney's leg has
also opened a furious debate over the sincerity of the IRA and
other paramilitary groups to honor their promises to end the
violence. The killing has embarrassed Sinn Fein leaders, who insist
that they cannot be held responsible for the actions of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant unionist politicians say that unless the IRA stops
its punishment shootings and beatings and declares unequivocally
that the war is over, its political representatives within Sinn
Fein cannot take their seats in the Northern Ireland Assembly
cabinet to be formed in September.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA, for its part, believes that its cease-fire is solid. It
will not attack police, soldiers, or so-called economic targets.
But the IRA is still in business, as are its Protestant loyalist
counterparts. These organizations engage in extortion and other
illicit money-raising ventures. And they act as judge, jury, and
executioner in kangaroo courts they assert are necessary to keep
order because the police are not acceptable alternatives in their
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA beats or shoots people for what it calls ``antisocial
activity,'' an elastic term used to describe drug dealers, social
misfits, or somebody like Andy Kearney, who had the misfortune of
beating up the wrong guy.
</P>
<P>
   Glyn Roberts, spokesman for Families Against Intimidation and
Terror, a Belfast-based lobbying group, said that through the end
of last week, the IRA had carried out most of the 30 punishment
shootings attributed to Catholic republican groups this year.
Roberts said the two main loyalist paramilitary groups, the Ulster
Defense Association and the Ulster Volunteer Force, had perpetrated
17 punishment shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the shootings, Roberts said, republicans have meted out
27 punishment beatings and loyalists have beaten 36 people this
year. Because punishment squads use cement blocks and baseball bats
with nails protruding from them, the injuries from punishment
beatings are usually worse than so-called kneecappings, whereby
victims are shot in the backs of their legs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the political progress in Northern Ireland, rough street
justice appears to be increasing. Some people suggest that such
vigilantism has become more important to the IRA as a way to
maintain morale and to exercise control now that its volunteers
have nothing else to do.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Catholic republicans shot a 79-year-old man in North
Belfast. He was believed to be the oldest punishment victim of the
Troubles. It was unclear whether the shooting was done by the IRA
or the Irish National Liberation Army, a small splinter group. The
reason was also unclear. Royal Ulster Constabulary chief Ronnie
Flanagan said it was a case of mistaken identity. But neighborhood
residents said that the man was a suspected pedophile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting a 79-year-old man cannot be justified, whatever the
alleged reason,'' said Roberts, whose group accuses the British and
Irish governments of turning a blind eye to the punishment beatings
and shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Kearney makes it impossible for the governments
to ignore the issue any longer. Under the terms of the Good Friday
agreement, which created the assembly and calls for cross-border
cooperation, any party linked to a paramilitary group can be barred
from holding office if that group violates the commitment to
nonviolence.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionists who before Kearney's death seemed almost
resigned to the fact that Sinn Fein leaders Gerry Adams and Martin
McGuinness would become cabinet ministers now point to the killing
as a reason to oppose them.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leaders say that they are opposed to punishment squads
but are powerless to persuade the IRA to stop them. Sinn Fein
leaders repeat that they are not part of the IRA and cannot be held
responsible for its actions. But that is an argument they lost last
winter, when Sinn Fein was expelled from the peace talks after the
IRA allegedly killed two men.
</P>
<P>
   The man Kearney is said to have beaten and is believed
responsible for the attack on Kearney is an infamous IRA figure who
has survived several assassination attempts by loyalist hit squads.
He was also shot by a British soldier but survived.
</P>
<P>
   There is support for punishment squads in the poor,
working-class neighborhoods where they flourish. But the support is
hard to measure, given the inherent intimidation that accompanies
them.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say the IRA keeps its neighborhoods from being
overrun by hoodlums and drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Kearney has a less charitable view of those who killed
her son. ``If they don't like you,'' she said, ``they dispense with
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUYMOVIES-2ndTake-TEX     08-03 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUYMOVIES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: of acknowledgment. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Willis evokes a similar masculine empathy. He broke
through in ``Die Hard,'' a precedent-setting action movie. Not just
for its plot, which has become the most imitated high-concept trope
of the last decade, but because it was the first action movie in
which the hero has to save the day, outwit sleekly outfitted
Eurotrash and reclaim the rights to his family. It's this
ingredient that the slavish copiers of the ``Die Hard'' formula _
including Willis himself in ``Die Hard 3'' _ neglect. It expanded
the threshold of masculine melodrama, because the battle with the
villains became an inadvertent metaphor for emotional maturation.
</P>
<P>
   Willis' anguish over rescuing his wife is as important a plot
segment as the Eagle Scout resourcefulness he shows in using
whatever's at hand to defeat the indistinct terrorists. It
redefines the ground rules of the adventure movie, because for the
first time, there's something real at stake: a man's future. This
introduction of melodrama to the genre let men in the audience risk
welling up as they watched, emboldened by the fearlessness of
Willis and his open access to his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gibson, Willis also used his popularity to take occasional
risks. He's better than you'd expect in ``In Country,'' playing a
whipped, dysfunctional Vietnam vet. He discards all the devices _
the half-smile that telegraphs craftiness, the gold-plated
smart-aleck delivery _ and creates real tension. He's unafraid to
show how lost he is. This wasted, adrift man, who's continually
aware of how weak he appears but can't hide it, still has a core of
dignity and resolve. There are glimmers of the tough, hopeful joker
he used to be. Willis is a limited actor, but he can bring
incredible power to a role because of his level of commitment. He
even shows a few hints in ``Armageddon,'' a movie so infatuated
with its own facility that there's barely a place for actors in it.
</P>
<P>
   It's when actors put their cool at risk that the male
tear-jerker really works. Robert Redford, who treats himself as if
he were Audrey Hepburn and uses the camera to dictate our responses
to him, isn't nearly as interesting or as affecting, not even in a
potential man's-man weeper like ``The Horse Whisperer.'' But Steven
Spielberg, working at the top of his form, builds a bigger, better
boys' melodrama with ``Saving Private Ryan,'' because it brings to
bear all those things _ competition, death, sacrifice _ that define
the genre. ``Ryan'' is so guileful _ barely a character or audience
member is left standing at the end _ that it may retire the male
tear-jerker for a while. No one, and no movie, could possibly
contend with it.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-LEWINSKY-BOS &LR;      08-03 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY CASE BUOYS REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH   AND DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans, who had begun to worry they could lose
control of the House this fall, now believe &UR;  &LR; the Monica S. Lewinsky
story has become serious enough to blunt the Democrats' momentum.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans remain deeply divided over whether to use the
Lewinsky matter to attack the Democrats, or whether such a maneuver
would backfire, according to interviews with party members and
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Republican analysts are predicting many
Democrats will be disgusted or disinterested enough to stay home on
Election Day, helping the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a dampening effect,'' Republican pollster Linda DiVall
said. ``It makes it difficult for Democrats to communicate their
agenda since the news is so focused on this. Secondly, as people go
to the polls on Nov. 3, they are saying to themselves, `I don't
really dislike this Republican (congressional) incumbent.' There is
not the animosity that there was in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats have proclaimed that the allegation that Lewinsky
had an affair with President Clinton will have no effect on the
fall campaigns. Democrats variously said that voters don't care
about the matter, that nothing has been proven, or that Clinton
isn't the person up for election.
</P>
<P>
   But privately, a growing number of Democrats are concerned that
the Lewinsky story will, at the very least, draw attention away
from the party's accomplishments and energize Republicans to turn
out on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   So far, independent analysts who track congressional races
cautioned that they have not seen an impact in any general election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year is too localized for it to make a difference,'' said
Jennifer E. Duffy of The Cook Political Report. ``These races are
all about local issues. There is no overarching national trend. The
people are more worried about landfills than Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans prepare to visit their constituents this month,
some are eager to go on the attack. Senator John Ashcroft of
Missouri, who is considering a presidential bid, has frequently
questioned Clinton's moral character, like many other GOP members.
</P>
<P>
   But others believe it is best to let Democrats stew in the
controversy with no help from Republicans, thus keeping the GOP
above the fray. Indeed, while some Republicans have already called
for Clinton's impeachment, others said they don't want to begin
such proceedings unless there is overwhelming evidence that the
president engaged in a coverup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here for this stuff,'' said Representative David
Weldon, a Florida Republican. ``I came here for budget reforms and
tax reform. I don't relish the idea of taking this up, even though
I am a Republican and I oppose Bill Clinton's policies. I don't
want to see a president impeached, even a president who has done
some of the things Bill Clinton has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Weldon said the issue hasn't come up among constituents except
``among the Republicans that are well-informed.'' The GOP lawmaker
added: ``In my opinion, the majority of voters have been concerned
with economic issues, tax reform, keeping the budget balanced, and
Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   While there were reports last week that some Republicans are
developing a campaign playbook that relies on the Lewinsky story as
a major issue, top party officials said they are not following such
a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is going to be a factor in the elections,''
Republican National Committee spokesman Mike Collins said, when
asked about the Lewinsky matter. ``I think that voters are going to
cast their ballots based on things they always do. They want the
issues that affect them personally _ things like tax cuts, the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   As Republican pollster Ed Goeas puts it, the best strategy for
the GOP is to ``just shut up and watch'' as the Lewinsky story
takes its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we enter into the fray, we do what the Democrats want,
which is to partisan-ize the whole process and give Democrats
someone to demonize,'' Goeas said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Republican strategy does not dismiss the possibility
that the report delivered to Congress by the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, will result in impeachment hearings. If that
happens, Collins said, Republicans will cast it as the fulfillment
of constitutional requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Foreshadowing a theme that will be used by Republicans
throughout the fall, Collins said: ``We as individuals and as a
party have been very careful to say this is not a political
investigation. We are standing up for the rule of law and the
people's right to know.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a midsummer snapshot taken during a mostly bad week
for the president may not be a good indicator of what will happen
in November. Indeed, it was just weeks ago that some analysts were
saying the Democrats had turned the corner and had a real chance of
retaking the House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold a 228-206 edge in the House, which has one
independent, and a 55-45 majority in the Senate. While Democratic
officials say they have little chance of regaining control of the
Senate, they note that it would take only an 11-seat swing to
retake the House.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Democrats, Representative Ken Bentsen of Texas said he
has had few questions about the Lewinsky story from constituents.
People are more interested in the economy, even the smoke from
Mexico, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that some voters have become wearied or numbed by the
frequent stories about the matter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This latest bombshell is just one in a long line of bombshells
since January,'' Bentsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Democrats who spoke on condition of anonymity said
the concern about the Lewinsky fallout is real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is watching it, but nobody is talking about it,''
said a Senate Democratic official. ``I know this is right
underneath the surface that people are worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Ruben Hinojosa, Democrat of Texas, sounded
pleased that Clinton has decided to give his testimony in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found a great deal of people saying they don't want
others messing with the president's private life,'' Hinojosa said.
``We have to respect that small percentage who are interested; this
is something that they have a right to know, and they will when the
president gives his testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Sosnick, counselor to the president, predicted that the
Lewinsky matter would not have an impact on the elections and
rejected suggestions that the president has been harmed politically
by the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the Democratic National Committee funding, direct
mail, the events the president does around the country,'' Sosnick
said. ``I think you see a lot of energy and enthusiasm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
