<HEADLINE>
WHY DO FIREFLIES FLASH AT NIGHT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why do fireflies light up at night?
</P>
<P>
   --M.T., Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I thought fireflies appeared in late June or early July. We
haven't seen one this year.
</P>
<P>
   R.W., Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. What puts the fire in fireflies? The same thing that causes
many species to put on flashy displays: the mating urge.
</P>
<P>
   Entymologist Jim Lloyd of the University of Florida at
Gainesville, who's been studying fireflies for 36 years, says males
are the flashier flashes. ``They're saying, `Would you like to mate
with me? I'm a male of species X looking for a mate.'''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of the flashes identifies the species. Some have a
double flash that repeats every three seconds. Some have one short
flash that repeats at 10-second intervals.
</P>
<P>
   The females flash too. But they light up only once. And they're
perched, not flying. A male determines which single flash is coming
from a female of his species by the timing of the response to his
query.
</P>
<P>
   But just because she answers the male's personal ad doesn't mean
a relationship is established. ``The first female flash says `Come
a little bit closer and light up again so I can check you out,'''
Lloyd says. The female then watches to see how quickly the male
arrives, how close he gets, and other signals that humans haven't
figured out before deciding if this fly is her guy.
</P>
<P>
   If she's satisfied, she flashes back again. Then the lights go
out and the mating begins _ for most species it continues for
several hours. The next day the female lays her eggs. Most species
repeat the find-a-mate ritual nightly. ``Lightning bugs,'' as we
used to call them, light up between mid-June and mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Not all species spell out their desires in lights. Some
fireflies don't rely on bioluminescence at all, including three of
the 20 species that live in Massachusetts. They fly around during
the day looking for mates, sending out chemical signals. Then
there's the deadly female photuris firefly. She'll signal back to
males of other species that she is a female of that species willing
to mate. The guy fly buzzes over in the dark expecting to become a
dad, but the photuris female instead flashes her light just as she
strikes _ and the male becomes dinner.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 2,000 firefly species worldwide, in all sorts of
habitats. There are no studies confirming that fireflies are in
decline, but ``observers all over the country tell me that's what
they're seeing,'' Lloyd says. He thinks light pollution at night
may be one reason. ``That's noise to them, and might be affecting
successful mating.''
</P>
<P>
   Biology professor Sara Lewis of Tufts University says habitat
disruption may be a key factor. ``They're very habitat-specific.
Some fly only under a tree canopy. Some fly only along stream beds.
Some are restricted to open fields. And they don't disperse well.
The larvae don't crawl very far and the adults don't fly very
far,'' she says. As a result, even minor changes in habitat can
destroy a firefly population.
</P>
<P>
   This was actually a good year for fireflies, Lewis says, the
best in several years, because the moist spring was ideal for
firefly larval development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
