<HEADLINE>
LEGAL CHAOS LEAVES CUBAN REFUGEES ADRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Immigration courts are filled with Cuban refugees. Jails
are packed with Cubans in legal limbo as judges, lawyers, and
prosecutors debate conflicting immigration rules. And while the
experts argue, scores of Cubans arrive by the boatload every month.
</P>
<P>
   All this might suggest that the immigration laws for Cubans need
sweeping reform. As it happens, though, sweeping reform caused much
of the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 30,000 Cubans arrived on rafts in the summer of
1994, the Clinton administration ended three decades of special
treatment for Cubans. No longer would anyone fleeing Fidel Castro's
Communist regime have an automatic right to become a US resident.
On the contrary, Cubans found at sea would be deported immediately,
just like Haitian ``boat people.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the theory. Most Cubans who are caught in the Florida
Straits these days are sent back in US Coast Guard cutters. The few
who make a strong argument that they face political persecution are
sent to the US naval base at Guantanamo, where they can seek asylum
in another country. Others, such as pregnant women who become sick
at sea, are often allowed into the United States. Still others, who
set foot on US soil, are usually allowed to stay and become legal
US residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration's intent was to say that Cubans are not
Martians, Cubans are not to be put on a pedestal _ they are
supposed to be treated no differently than anyone else,'' said
Jorge Dominguez, director of Harvard University's Weatherhead
Center for International Affairs. A Cuban immigrant himself,
Dominguez approved of the change. But decisions about who stays and
who goes seem to be arbitrary, he said. And advocates for the
exiles say that even as Washington is worsening conditions in Cuba
by tightening the US embargo, immigration agents summarily send
back those who escape.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Clara, in the middle of Cuba, Maria Elena Garcia could
not take it any longer.
</P>
<P>
   After years of trying, she had gotten pregnant and delivered a
girl in February. But the clinic that performed the caesarean
section had run out of surgical thread, and Garcia got infected.
Her husband, Roberto, could not afford to buy medicines on the
black market. His job as a gym teacher and basketball coach at a
school paid only 200 pesos, or $8, a month. Garcia's baby was
malnourished, her grandmother was sick from lack of vitamins, and
no one could earn a living wage.
</P>
<P>
   After secretly making preparations to leave, the family took off
from Cuba's northern coast on a 28-foot wooden fishing boat. The 17
passengers, who spanned three generations, carried the staples of
the Cuban diet of the '90s: bread, sugar, and water. These days,
getting out is easy because the Cuban border patrol boats rarely
have fuel. The Garcias knew that the United States no longer
welcomes boat people, but they didn't care. They had relatives in
Miami, including Maria Elena's brother, Juan, who had left in a
raft six years before and was doing well as a mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Elena Garcia recalls the adventure in fast-paced Spanish:
After puttering north for almost two days, the boat hit a rock and
water started to seep in. For hours, the passengers prayed for
help. Then they heard the buzzing of a powerful speedboat. It was
Juan, who had received a panicked call from Cuba saying his family
was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia acknowledges that the story sounds improbable, but she
says it is true. ``When we saw Juan, we all started crying,'' she
said. ``God is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Crammed with passengers, the boat ran out of fuel and was
spotted by the Coast Guard. Garcia and her infant daughter were
released to relatives in Miami because the baby was ill. The others
were sent back to Cuba _ except Juan, who was sent to a detention
center near Miami. He was charged with people-smuggling and,
because he was not a US citizen, he was also charged with illegally
entering the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smuggling! How much are you going to charge your own mother?''
Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   She is doing the paperwork that will allow her to stay legally
in the United States. But Juan, who worked long hours and never got
around to applying for US residency, faces deportation. Under
strict immigration laws enacted two years ago, noncitizens who
commit crimes must serve their time and then be deported. That
leads to a complication: Fidel Castro's government, which has
frosty relations with Washington, refuses to take back convicts.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Penalver, an attorney who works with imprisoned
immigrants, says 1,600 Cubans who have served their time are
scattered in American prisons, awaiting deportation to a homeland
that won't accept them.
</P>
<P>
   Because Cubans drifting in the Florida Straits on inner tubes
and rafts are no longer hailed as heroes risking their lives for
freedom, those fleeing the island want to make the 90-mile trip to
the United States as quickly as possible. Smugglers have responded
to the demand. Prosecutors say they have identified several
smuggling rings in south Florida that charge about $9,000 for each
adult they pick up on the Cuban coast or at pre-arranged locations
in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Cubans fleeing has accelerated this year because
drought and a low sugar harvest have heightened the sense of
desperation on the island. So far this year, the Coast Guard has
picked up 547 Cubans. Immigration officials say another 340 Cubans
have made it to shore _ often with the help of smugglers in
high-speed boats. Those numbers are more than twice the totals for
any year since the 1994 crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The smugglers pose a range of problems for US authorities. How
can prosecutors make a case if the only witnesses _ the passengers
_ are repatriated? Should there be a different standard for boat
captains who don't charge their passengers, such as a father who
fetches his children from Cuba?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many cases that we know in our heart of hearts are
good cases, but you pick these jurors and none of them want to
convict,'' said Wilfredo Fernandez, a prosecutor with the US
Attorney's office in Miami. ``Jurors say, `We've got violent crime,
we've got drugs, we've got kilos of cocaine falling out the sky,
and you're going to give me someone smuggling some poor people out
of Cuba?'''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Garcia lived the exile's dream. After arriving in Florida
on July 2, 1992, he went on a blind date with a woman who had the
same first name as his sister, Maria. They married and started
their own auto and boat repair shop. By working six and seven days
a week, they were able to buy a house with a pool. On July 2, 1996,
on the fourth anniversary of Garcia's arrival, Juan and Maria had a
son.
</P>
<P>
   The way the family tells it, Juan Garcia received the call from
Cuba about his missing relatives on June 26, a Friday. He set off
in a borrowed speedboat, trusting his instincts to find the
passengers, who included his mother, sister, and a 10-year-old
daughter from a first marriage.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to verify that account. At the US attorney's
office, Fernandez has heard too many miraculous-encounter-at-sea
stories. Most of these ``coincidences,'' he says, are actually the
result of a carefully planned rendezvous. Smuggling, in other
words.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia has not been told when he will face an immigration judge.
If he is found guilty, the authorities probably will say he has to
serve his time and return to Cuba. Of course, Cuba won't accept him
if the United States says he is a criminal, so he could be in limbo
for years. ``My husband would rather die than go back to Cuba,''
said his wife, Maria.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives who were deported are home in Santa Clara, worse
than ever. Roberto, the gym teacher, lost his job as punishment for
deserting the country. ``My family will not stay in Cuba, you can
be sure of that,'' said his wife, Maria Elena, as she held her baby
girl. ``They are going to keep trying and trying until they get
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
