<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEUKEMIA-OLDER-PATIENTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTERNATIVE LEUKEMIA TREATEMENT GIVES NEW HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Treating older patients with leukemia presents an
agonizing dilemma for physicians. Doctors can increase an older
patient's odds of a cure with aggressive treatment, such as a bone
marrow transplant, but the treatment itself can kill the patient.
</P>
<P>
   But in the future, older patients may not have to make such a
difficult choice.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center have
begun testing a new-generation bone marrow transplant procedure
that could one day be used for older patients who aren't eligible
for traditional bone marrow transplants, and for others who are too
sick to survive high-dose chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, six people have tried the new procedure, which is not
being done yet anywhere else in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic,'' said Gordon Aaby, 30, who had a transplant
with the new method a little more than five months ago and credits
it with saving his life.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a traditional bone marrow transplant, this process
involves no high-dose chemotherapy or intense radiation, the two
aspects of the conventional method that pose the most risk for
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the new procedure uses natural immune system cells,
called lymphocytes, along with new bone marrow from a donor to
``sneak up'' on the cancer and kill it without chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very novel, very experimental,'' said Dr. Rainer Storb,
head of the Clinical Research Division's Transplantation Biology
Program at Fred Hutchinson. Storb and principal investigator Dr.
Peter McSweeney are conducting a pilot study of the new treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Its promise is enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Once refined, it eventually could lead to what Storb termed a
``drive-through'' transplant, a non-toxic procedure with the
potential to cure or treat a wide variety of malignancies,
including acute myelogenous leukemia , and genetic blood disorders,
such as sickle cell anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional bone marrow transplants use high doses of
chemotherapy and radiation to kill cancer cells, irreversibly
destroying the body's blood-making machinery and immune system in
the process. The donor's bone marrow then essentially replaces the
patient's own system with a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically almost kill you and then bring you back from
the edge,'' said Tim Testu, 54, who seven months ago faced a choice
whether to get a bone marrow transplant with only 50 percent odds
of surviving it, or try the new procedure, which at that point had
only been used in animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be better off playing Russian roulette,'' he said of his
chances with the regular bone marrow procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Testu, a marine engineer living in Port Townsend, was diagnosed
in 1991 with chronic lymphocytic leukemia, a slow but fatal form of
blood cancer.
</P>
<P>
   After his remissions began lasting shorter periods, he sought
help at Fred Hutchinson. Because he was an older patient showing
signs of increased resistance to chemotherapy, he was told he only
had a ``shockingly few'' number of months to live. Maybe two years
at the outside, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His treatment options were limited. More conservative treatment
options promised greater near-term survival, but posed greater risk
of relapse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed me charts, kind of like investing in the stock
market,'' he said. ``You can choose aggressive and high risk with
the big return, or choose the sure thing, and not make as much
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he was told he was eligible for the new treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is cancer-free. ``I can't even believe my own good
fortune,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His doctors are excited about his long-term outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our point of view, we're remarkably optimistic about his
outcome,'' McSweeney said. ``The most encouraging thing is we can't
find any leukemic cells, even using our most sensitive tests, and
that's a prerequisite for being cured.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaby, a cook who lives south of Seattle, has had a similar
dramatic turnaround. He suffers from a congenital immune deficiency
condition, similar to the ``bubble boy'' disease. Five and a half
months ago he weighed only 80 pounds and his body was shutting down
little by little. He had violent chills and a running fever of 103
degrees. He could barely breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like I was watching him disappear before my eyes,''
said Toni Aaby, his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors believed that replacing his own defective bone marrow
with healthy cells from a donor might cure him, but doubted he
could survive the chemotherapy phase of a regular bone marrow
transplant. Instead, they told him about the new procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either that or nothing,'' Aaby said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the procedure, his health has been steadily improving.
He's now at normal weight and, as a side benefit of not having
chemotherapy, still has the long wavy ponytail he's been growing
for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go back to everything,'' he said. ``Jogging,
skiing, water sports, baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new treatment, which is done completely outside the
hospital, patients have their own immune systems slightly
suppressed with oral medications, just enough so that when doctors
slip in donor bone marrow cells , the body doesn't immediately
reject them.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the two bone marrow systems _ the patient's and the
donor's _ set up shop together, existing in a state referred to as
``mixed chimerism.''
</P>
<P>
   Once that state is achieved, doctors infuse th patient with
lymphocytes from the same donor. Lymphocytes are a type of immune
system cell that can attack and kill cancer. Because they come from
a donor, they are more aggressive in killing cancer than the
patient's own lymphocytes.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon is known as the ``graft-versus-leukemia''
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Because the patient already has some donor bone marrow in his
system, the donor lymphocyte cells aren't automatically rejected,
allowing them to do their work. Then, over time, the immune
suppression medication is removed, and the new, stronger donor
marrow gradually overtakes and eventually replaces the old bone
marrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be as if the patient were a personal computer,
plagued by some kind of virus, and they fix it by changing the
operating system from Win95 to Macintosh _ without tearing down, or
even turning off the machine,'' Testu said.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure hasn't worked for everyone. Two patients failed to
achieve the mixed chimeric state and rejected the donor marrow
before it could take hold. No patients who have undergone the
therapy have died.
</P>
<P>
   It will take two or three more years to refine a treatment
protocol for wider use, Storb said. Currently, it is considered
experimental and is not routinely covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   There is a need for advances that would allow high-risk and
older patients such as Seattle Public Schools Superintendent John
Stanford, 59, to get bone marrow transplants with reduced risks,
doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, only about 10 percent of (all types of cancer)
patients are cured by chemotherapy alone,'' said oncologist and
researcher Dr. James Bianco, who heads Cell Therapeutics Inc., a
Seattle-based biotechnology company working on cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer cells become resistant to repeated rounds of
chemotherapy, making them increasingly difficult to treat.
</P>
<P>
   And each time a patient undergoes chemotherapy, it reduces the
odds of success of subsequent treatments, such as a bone marrow
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   If an older patient with acute myelogenous leukemia, for
example, gets a bone marrow transplant as soon as possible in the
course of his disease, his odds of a cure are about 40 to 50
percent. The odds fall to less than 20 percent after multiple
rounds of chemotherapy, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   But with a traditional bone marrow method, ``anyone over age 65,
most would die'' from the treatment, Storb said.
</P>
<P>
   Between the ages of 50 and 60, there is a ``pretty high
mortality'' from bone marrow transplants, he said. In some cancers,
it's as high as 80 percent. For acute myelogenous leukemia, the
mortality rate from the bone marrow transplant itself is around 25
to 30 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Damage to organs and risk of infection are two main
complications that can lead to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ability to repair DNA damage is lessened when we age,'' Storb
said. Many centers around the world won't even attempt bone marrow
transplants in patients older than 55. At the Fred Hutchinson
Center, the cutoff age is 65.
</P>
<P>
   However, leukemia strikes many patients over that age. Half of
patients with chronic myeloid leukemia , for example, are older
than 67. This type of cancer is not curable with conventional
chemotherapy, but 80 percent of patients younger than 50 can be
cured with a bone marrow transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Patients with acute myelogenous leukemia, the aggressive type of
leukemia that Stanford has, would be eligible for the experimental
treatment only during a first remission, Storb said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the advanced stage of Stanford's disease, he would
not be eligible for the experimental transplant procedure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is currently undergoing tests in preparation for a
traditional bone marrow transplant.
</P>
<P>
   For Testu, the procedure has already given him a new shot at
life, and he hopes by being the first to try the treatment, it will
open the way for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hope here,'' he said. ``And a lot of
encouragement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
