<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-03 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WRITER BECOMES A CAM HAM
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   In a shameless effort to boost readership, this column will soon
be the focus of a Web-cam, which means that for a not-unreasonable
fee anyone may log onto the World Wide Web and watch the amazing
and hitherto closely guarded process of cranking out the stuff that
appears in this space.
</P>
<P>
   Web-cam sites are proliferating. A recent Globe Living/Arts
story reported that each day hundreds of thousands of Web surfers
check in to various candid camera Web sites to watch people
``cleaning, opening the refrigerator, cooking spaghetti, working,
giving birth, putting on makeup, sleeping, even imitating Austin
Powers.''
</P>
<P>
   My editors reasoned that while column writing is not as exciting
as giving birth or putting on makeup, it's probably more
interesting than sleeping, although that remains to be seen. It may
depend upon who's sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   I feel like a pioneer, in a way, because eventually everyone
will have his or her own Web-cam site. Someday, I'm sure, we'll be
able to log on and call up anyone's life, anytime. True, there's at
least one obvious disadvantage to Web-cam Nation, but a complete
and total loss of individual privacy is a small price to pay for,
say, the ability to see just exactly what our leaders and lawmakers
are up to every minute of the day and night.
</P>
<P>
   With public mistrust of journalists and politicians running
neck-and-neck in the polls, offering up my working life, such as it
is, for scrutiny seems the very least I can do for journalism _
apart from writing these columns, that is. I have selfish reasons,
too, for wanting to expose myself on the World Wide Web. It's the
only way I'll ever get a book contract.
</P>
<P>
   I have no horrible sins to confess, no shameful secrets waiting
to be told. That's what it takes these days, to be a successful
writer, the kind of writer who gets big advances, big reviews,
appearances on Oprah and Larry King. I have never murdered anyone,
never posed nude, never had an affair with a celebrity or even with
a blood relative, never taken enough alcohol or drugs to be really
interesting. I've never even had a complete mental breakdown,
although I'm not ruling out the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it may not be enough just to share my working life on
my own Web-cam site. I may need a gimmick, if I hope to get a book
out of it. It's far too late to lose my virginity on line, like
those two California teenagers threatened to do a couple of weeks
ago. That turned out to be a hoax. That Florida woman who gave
birth live on the Internet wasn't a hoaxer, unfortunately. But I'm
past the point of being able to have a baby on or off the Web,
although with the miracle of modern reproductive technology,
anything is possible. I'm thinking about cloning.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe readers will have some other ideas. A team of Web-cam
consultants has been called in at great expense to help focus this
project. They suggested that the columns should be interactive,
that I invite readers to share in the whole exciting process, from
the frantic search for ideas right up to and including arguments
with the copy desk. They also suggested that henceforth I wear some
sort of skimpy costume, possibly spangled. However, my editors
pointed out that the whole object of the Web-cam experiment is to
attract readers, not repel them. So I will continue to write
wearing my usual oversized garments.
</P>
<P>
   In preliminary tests, the consultant team noticed an increased
number of ``hits'' when I was at lunch and during bathroom breaks,
leading them to speculate that some Web surfers may prefer staring
at my empty chair to watching me work. I am not sure how to
interpret this. Maybe it's too early to draw any conclusions. See
you, or maybe not, at http://www.ohmygod.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
