<HEADER>
A5199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RICE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BO     08-03 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RICE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 STOCKTON, Calif.: ... in the preseason.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rice, in fact, is convinced that Mariucci will not allow him to
get in any of the exhibition games. Is he right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uhh ... '' said Mariucci, ``I'd say that's a high
probability.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can tell Rice anything about the position he plays, but
it's up to the likes of Mariucci and his surrounding medical
experts to remind him of the position he's in. He is aging, and
those aren't character lines, marks of distinction, that are now
etched around his left knee. The first operation alone easily could
have ended the career of a lesser athlete. The second cut almost
assuredly would have been a ticket to some network broadcast booth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Little about Rice's career has been ordinary. The son of a
bricklayer, born and raised in Crawford, Miss., he developed his
Velcroed hands while laboring at his father's jobsights. In the
sweltering summer heat of the Deep South, his brother Jim would
toss him two bricks at a time, and the wideout-superstar-to-be
would snare each one with a separate hand as they split apart on
their flight path up the scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rice would be irate if a brick came back his way, and Joe
Rice was a demanding father who liked to keep the job moving. The
workplace was no place to drop the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (toughness came) just from my parents,'' Rice
explained to the San Francisco Chronicle early in the '95 season.
``As a kid growing up, I had to work for everything. Nothing was
given to me. When I would go out and work with my father, he was a
very demanding father, and I had to do my job. I couldn't give 50
percent. It had to be 100 percent, and that's the way I look at
football. It's all about going out there and enjoying something
that you do, but also knowing that while you're out there, you're
jeopardizing everything. One blow can end your career, so why not
give 100 percent while you're out there?''
</P>
<P>
   When he went down with the knee injury last August, it was the
first time Rice would miss a game because of injury in his career.
He had played 189 consecutive games with virtually no significant
damage to his body, a stat that, in the violent world of pro
football, may be more amazing than any of his accomplishments that
are tabulated in the rec-ord book. Perhaps no one ever will
outcatch him. Perhaps no one ever will outcondition him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a relentless work ethic,'' said Young, who has
delivered 75 TD passes into Rice's clutches. ``He has put together
world-class athleticism with a world-class work ethic, and there
aren't many who do that. It's usually that blue-collar athlete
who's out there working and working, but Jerry's that rare case
that blends the two. I can tell Michael Jordan's like that, too.
And that, to me, is what brings guys to that next level. It's what
separates the world-class athletes from everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Hill is part of the formula. Rice's offseason conditioning
regimen is based, in part, on a grueling 2 1/2-mile run up wooded,
mountainous terrain of San Carlos, not far from Palo Alto. As
training camp draws near, he puts more emphasis on sprint work. But
The Hill is the centerpiece of his endurance and his longevity. It
is what helped him report here two weeks ago, a day ahead of
schedule, ready to resume running his pass routes.
</P>
<P>
   Only now he runs with the same legs and a different attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I stood here and said that I'm not afraid,''
Rice said in his first media session upon reporting to camp.
``After coming off an injury like this, you are going to have some
second thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon reporting to the 49ers' new training facility here, Rice
was unsettled to find a pair of knee braces waiting for him in his
locker. When the knee cracked in December, he was wearing a brace,
and he was convinced then that the brace made the knee more
vulnerable to such a fracture. That's not necessarily a medical
opinion, but that of a man who has lived the pain. Greater
flexibility upon impact, he believes, could have prevented the
fracture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was part of my trouble last time,'' said Rice, explaining
his reaction to seeing the braces again two weeks ago. ``I threw
'em in the garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing any injured player can do in training camp can truly
mirror what will happen in a game. Rice will spend the next month
preparing for the opener against the Jets, eventually immersing
himself in contact drills and offering up his head, shoulders, and
legs to the blows of what is often a beastly game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this time,'' said Rice, ``I can jump up and run
back to the huddle, and finish the entire game. ... Then I think
basically everything would be behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he jogs on the sidelines, works in the weight room, and
inches his way toward the day of reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   What awaits him is either an extension of his greatness or a
reminder, perhaps a final one, that all good things must end.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing about football,'' said Barton. ``There are no
graceful endings. It's not like baseball, where you play your last
game, hit a couple of homers, and wave goodbye with everyone
cheering you. In football, there's always this ugly hand ready to
grab you out of the sky and haul you down. It's nasty. And it
happens to everyone eventually, and I'm talking players,
management, everyone. It happened eventually to Thurman Thomas and
to Y.A. Tittle. It's just always there, ready to bring you down
with a crash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
