<SLUG> BC-BOOK-JUDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDE: QUIET APOSTLE SPEAKS TO OUR TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
JUDE 
A Pilgrimage to the Saint of Last Resort 
By Liz Trotta 
HarperSanFrancisco, 270 pp., $24  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writing about a religious figure who lived 2,000 years ago is
never easy. Sources of information can be scant and unreliable. And
when that person is St. Jude, perhaps the most revered but least
known of Jesus' 12 apostles, the challenge is even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Liz Trotta is both a skilled reporter and a
graceful writer. Her account of the fervent international devotion
inspired by Jude is an absorbing, even riveting tale. Trotta's
``Jude: A Pilgrimage to the Saint of Last Resort'' can be read as
religious mystery, spiritual quest, and inspirational literature.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling to New York, Baltimore, Rome, and a remote corner of
Turkey, Trotta tries to shed light on this ``mysterious man who,
without historical or theological proof, has been delegated the
amazing burden of retrieving lost causes.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotta wisely avoids writing a biography. After all, it would be
difficult to provide a very detailed sketch of an apostle who has
only one spoken line in the entire New Testament. Yet, as Trotta
shrewdly notes, it is Jude's elusiveness that has helped make him
such an appealing person in our media-saturated,
celebrity-worshiping age.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time of utter identification with the sound bite, he
stands in silence, mythless: Jude the Deliberately Obscure, the
guerrilla operating unseen in the mist, an apparition over the
horizon, the farthest out, remote _ yet hearing the weakest, most
desolate cries,'' writes Trotta, New York bureau chief for The
Washington Times and a former television network correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   She makes a convincing case that Jude is the right saint for our
times. He is the answer to our spiritual restlessness, to our sense
of unease even in times of material prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graduates of the `Me generation,' those who sought to be
`Masters of the Universe,' seem to have discovered in their middle
age, at last, that they are not lords of their own destiny,''
Trotta writes. ``It is a time of internal transformation, a hunger
for personal experience of a higher power. Prayer _ the final
sensation _ is back in fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotta is most compelling when she moves away from Jude to spend
time on vivid, humorous, and sometimes poignant portraits of the
people _ the sick, the dying, the lonely _ who follow the farmer
turned Christian martyr with ferocious passion. At a church named
in honor of St. Jude in Rome, Trotta meets Vitoria Ansini, who
believes Jude saved her life. In the early-morning hours of a day
in 1980, Ansini was hit by a bus. Though she lay in the street for
nearly two hours, Ansini tells Trotta, no other cars struck her.
Later, people who had been at the scene told Ansini that a
mysterious white light surrounded her body. Ansini is convinced it
was Jude's doing.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Judean stories of the famous. In the 1950s
Danny Thomas made public his appeal to Jude to give him the break
that would let him escape one-night stands in sleazy clubs. Thomas
got his break. In gratitude, he built the Saint Jude Hospital for
children in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Today, except for the Virgin Mary, there are probably more
churches in the United States dedicated to Jude than to any other
saint. Jude brings in millions of dollars every year from
supplicants who buy books, ornaments, prayer cards in the thousands
of Judean churches and shrines around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Jude's remarkable ascendancy from a virtually unknown
first-century Christian messenger into a worldwide religious
phenomenon is testament to the power of belief. This is the message
Trotta's fine book leaves us with. The Judean movement is not built
on historical documents. Jude doesn't belong to the scholars or the
princes of the church. Jude belongs to the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jude does not make his presence felt through history, or
iconography, or folklore, but by his endless indirect
manifestations to the millions who catch his invisible hand as a
first desperate clutch in their stretch toward God,'' Trotta
writes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
