<SLUG> BC-WASH-AFFIRMATIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFIRMATIVE ACTION BATTLE MOVES TO WASHINGTON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Advocates on both sides of the affirmative action
debate do agree on one point: Well-mannered, overwhelmingly white
Washington state is the perfect arena for a face-off.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only state where conservatives were able to place
the issue on the ballot this year. That puts Washington, better
known for cafe lattes and computer software, at the epicenter of
the ongoing effort to end so-called ``preferences'' for women and
members of minority groups. That also means that the outcome here
could have implications nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of preferences say their movement could be made _ or
broken _ by the November referendum, which will ask voters to ban
the practice in state and local government, colleges, and
universities. They have the money and the early momentum, along
with ballot language that critics consider misleading, although the
ballot was a winner in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, we will have pumped new life into the movement to
end preferences,'' said Ward Connerly, whose American Civil Rights
Institute pushed through the initiative in California in 1996 and
later paid to jump-start the effort in Washington. ``If we lose in
a venue tailor-made for us, we'll have to rethink whether it's
worthwhile pursuing initiatives in other states.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, supporters have a clear sense of what is at
stake, here and nationally. And they believe the votes should be
there to defend affirmative action in a state where, because of the
paucity of minorities, the greatest beneficiaries of the policy are
white women and white men who have served in the military.
Washington voters, also known for their political independence,
have also elected members of minority groups to high political
office, including the nation's only Asian-American governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can imagine that people will look to this state, which has a
reputation of being fairly liberal, and say, `If it's OK there,
it's OK here,''' said Carol Pencke, executive director of A
Territory Resource, a Seattle-based foundation that funds groups
that work to give women and minority groups equal opportunity and
opposes the ballot initiative. ``It'll be a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates on both sides of the measure known as Initiative 200
talk in terms of civil rights. But they disagree over the measure's
potential impact.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Initiative 200, among them Governor Gary Locke,
Starbucks, and the Boeing Co., the state's largest employer, say
minority enrollment at California's premier universities plummeted
after Proposition 209 barred preferential treatment. The Washington
initiative, they argue, would eliminate public recruitment programs
aimed at women and minorities and even those intended to interest
girls in math and science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doors of opportunity are going to be slammed shut for women
and minorities all across the state if this passes. ... We don't
take our challenge lightly,'' said Kelly Evans, who is managing the
``No!200'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But initiative supporters, including the Senate majority leader
and the speaker of the House, insist that it would simply ban
preferences based on race or gender. They take a very different
view of what has happened in California, noting that outreach by
state colleges there has increased, with deans themselves speaking
to minority students about the benefits of attending the system's
star campuses in Los Angeles and Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire idea of different rules for different people
doesn't work in America anymore.''said John Carlson, who is leading
the effort to undo affirmative action in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the initiative's interpretation could be key.
In Washington, as in California, the ballot title emphasizes the
elimination of preferences without mentioning affirmative action.
The wording reverberates with voters.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Seattle Times newspaper poll showed that 64 percent of
voters would support Initiative 200 as worded on the Nov. 3 ballot.
But when told it would effectively end affirmative action, while
leaving federal and private programs unaffected, support fell to 49
percent. Still, more white voters continued to support Initiative
200 than to oppose it, in the poll.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, minority opposition to the measure is
considered almost inconsequential, since minorities make up at most
10 percent of the electorate and less than 17 percent of the
population. Still, the fastest-growing group in the state is
Hispanics, followed by Asians, then blacks and native Americans,
according to the state Office of Financial Management. But
Washington's largest minority group, Asian-Americans, does not even
qualify for a number of the state's affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Initiative 200 ``are going to have to change a lot
of minds,'' said Stuart Elway, president of Seattle-based Elway
Research, which conducted the poll. ``Their task is to convince
people it's going to end affirmative action. For supporters, it's
to convince people that it's just about preferences. What is clear
is that it's not clear what the effect will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to voters is increasingly seen as a way for opponents of
race-based preferences to circumvent state legislatures that have
proven as reluctant as Congress to bar the practice. During 1996
and 1997, 13 states introduced such legislation; none of the bills
passed, according to the Southern Regional Council, an
Atlanta-based civil rights group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jesse Jackson was saying the same thing as we are, to treat
people equal, he'd be cheered,'' said Scott Smith, a state
representative who started gathering signatures for Initiative 200
after failing to force a bill out of committee. ``I don't see what
the difference is if I say it. People want this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet voters have also proven reluctant to end affirmative action.
In Florida, too few signatures were gathered to hold a referendum.
Washington's signature drive was stymied until Connerly's
California-based organization stepped in with matching funds last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves California and Houston, where voters passed a
similarly worded initiative, then sank a follow-up referendum that
included the words ``affirmative action.'' A judge recently ordered
a new election, saying the city's revised language did not reflect
the intent of voters who petitioned to put the issue on the ballot.
``They really got lucky with the ballot title, which is poorly
worded and quite vague,'' said Martha Choe, a Seattle city
councilwoman who opposes Initiative 200. ``It's deceptive, because
it says do away with something when it will do away with other
things, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Said House Speaker Clyde Ballard: ``Affirmative action is a good
program and it will continue. But people are against preferences.
They call them goals, but if you talk to them on the side, they
say, `Yeah, they're quotas.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Washington, said Tom McCabe, a building industry executive
in Olympia who has been active in several recent initiatives, those
are fighting words. The people here tend to have a ``go along, get
along'' attitude that makes marching in the streets or public
protests almost anathema. The debate surrounding Initiative 200, he
added, is particularly contentious and emotional at the campaign
level.
</P>
<P>
   But among the people of Washington, there appears to be little
talk at all of Initiative 200. With the vote more than three months
off, the pro and con campaigns are still gearing up to get out
their messages. Bill Gates and Microsoft have yet to take a
position. Many voters, whether planning to support or oppose the
initiative, say they are ambivalent about their decision.
</P>
<P>
   As a white male, business consultant Larry Hobbs says he may
have lost opportunities to members of minority groups. Still, he
has had plenty of success and plans to vote against Initiative 200.
Although she might benefit from affirmative action, Linda Hoder,
who works at a cellular telephone company, says people should not
get jobs or college admissions they do not deserve. She plans to
vote yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affirmative action isn't fair, but neither are people,'' said
Jim R. Allen, who sells real estate in eastern Washington. ``I
don't like it, but without it we'd lose too much of what we've
gained that has been good for the whole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
