<HEADER>
A5210 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUTURE-GAMES-ART-BOS &LR;      08-03 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-GAMES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR POINTS WAY TO PROTECTING WORLD'S RESOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Dennis Meadows, the director of the Institute for Policy and
Social Science Research at the University of New Hampshire, is
playing games with the future, _ and government, industry, and
educational leaders are playing along.
</P>
<P>
   According to the editorial board of Simon &AMP; Schuster's
``Encyclopedia of the Future,'' Meadows is one of the country's 100
most influential futurists.
</P>
<P>
   In his best-selling 1972 book, ``The Limits to Growth,'' which
Anthony Lewis of The New York Times decribed as ``a headline-making
report on the imminent global disaster facing humanity,'' Meadows
and a team of experts used a computer model to forecast global
population growth and its impact on economic systems and the
environment. They painted a bleak picture.
</P>
<P>
   But Meadows isn't satisfied with just crying wolf, he's created
a series of outdoor exercises and board games to help officials
contemplate large-systems management and reach solutions before the
environment is permanently damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows doesn't see himself as a ``futurist,'' because, he says,
``that term encompasses many different activities, like astrology
and science-fiction writing.'' A more apt term, he says, would be
``forecaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been creating a series of games to serve as models and
metaphors to help get people thinking about resource development
and the limits to growth,'' he said recently as he took a visitor
on a tour of the Browne Center at UNH, a 100-acre complex of
buildings and equipment devoted to outdoor education, experiential
learning, and team building.
</P>
<P>
   In his search for solutions to world problems, he has developed
several games that help focus thinking about resource development
and large systems management.
</P>
<P>
   The games include Fish Banks, which he developed to train
government officials in 1986. It has since been translated into 20
languages and has been used as a teaching tool throughout the
world. To play Fish Banks, participants are divided into teams to
catch fish, buy boats, and build fishing fleets that compete with
other teams in making money, while managing an imaginary fishery
without depleting it. In a training video for the game, he said it
was an attempt to develop ``a new kind of training method based on
computer-assisted role playing which conveys teamwork and managing
complex systems and containing substantive information about
real-world problems.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Strategem, which he developed to help players look at
the earth from a different perspective in an attempt to manage the
world's ``abundant but finite resources.''
</P>
<P>
   In Strategem, teams govern an imaginary country in an attempt to
build a balanced economy and manage renewable resources. The teams
consist of leader and Cabinet ministers responsible for population
growth, energy systems, social services, and other concerns.
</P>
<P>
   His eyes twinkled behind wire-rimmed glasses as he showed off a
wooden yurt that was recently contructed at the Browne Center
``without the aid of power tools.'' The yurt, which is lined with
benches and smells of freshly sawn wood, serves as a conference
room where participants in the outdoor education course discuss
lessons learned in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Browne Center is a component of the Institute for Policy and
Social Science Research at UNH. According to a mission statement,
it has two goals: ``to facilitate innovation in the teaching and
research programs of the University and help focus the intellectual
resources of the school on important problems of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the center opened in 1988, more than 8,000 students _
teachers, businessmen, and representatives of government and
private organizations _ have participated in the center's team and
consensus-building programs by playing games and meeting outdoor
challenges such as scaling a 13-foot wooden wall without outside
aid and traversing a telephone pole-sized log suspended 20 feet
above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows earned a doctorate at Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. He has taught at MIT and Dartmouth. He says he joined
the faculty at UNH in 1988 because of the university's commitment
to ``reach out to the community and seek practical solutions to the
problems that face it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem like a big leap from forecasting global population
in the year 2100 to prescribing steps for improved team
performance,'' he said, ``but throughout my professional life, I
have been a social engineer _ working to understand how to make
institutions work better in satisfying human needs. The difference
is that now I don't have to wait 100 years to see if my work is
useful.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a consultant to the Rockefeller Foundation, and has
trained US officials in large-systems management, as well as public
officials in Africa, Germany, and the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows has written several books in addition to ``Limits to
Growth'' and its 1992 companion volume ``Beyond the Limits.'' He's
working on a book titled the ``Systems Thinking Workbook.'' It will
consist of a series of games designed to assist in managing large
systems. When asked for an example, he quickly grabs a piece of
graph paper and a pen and offers to demonstrate. With a flourish,
he eagerly scribbles five marks on the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``What number does this represent?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   The visitor guesses five.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Four,'' he says, and quickly scribbles four more slashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What number does this represent?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Four.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Three,'' he says. ``Try again. And this time look at my
other hand.'' He quickly scribbles five lines while holding up
three fingers on his other hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three,'' the visitor says confidently.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' he says. ``The solution to a problem is often
found in a direction you're not looking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
