<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING THE HOUSING ISSUE ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It has driven me crazy,'' Joe Kennedy was saying the other day
about the country's disastrous and ridiculously gridlocked housing
policies.
</P>
<P>
   As well he might. And should. And has.
</P>
<P>
   Down the home stretch of his congressional career, there is no
subject _ for obvious reasons _ that gets this guy's juices flowing
like the condition of urban housing, both by itself and as a
metaphor for the cities' treatment by the national government.
</P>
<P>
   There is also no subject more important to the In-box of
Kennedy's successor. And while Kennedy has wisely kept out of the
campaign, it is at least interesting that the one candidate who
keeps housing front and center is his almost-neighbor, former state
Representative Susan Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing Kennedy or his Boston-centered constituents
don't experience (whether it's cost, availability, quality, or
homelessness) that is not a direct consequence of this scandalous
situation.
</P>
<P>
   I had noticed from mid-July on that, as usual, Kennedy was in
the forefront of several efforts in the House to avoid Newt
Gingrich-led assaults on urban working families' most immediate
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as usual since 1994, the votes weren't there for success
(that will come defensively via President Clinton's veto, if
necessary). But keeping the goal of a return to sanity alive is no
small task; it's one that Kennedy and a too-small band of
colleagues has been performing for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy likes to point out that a minimum-wage family in Boston,
in order to rent the average two-bedroom apartment, would need to
shell out more than 90 percent of its income. At twice the minimum
wage, that apartment still gobbles more than half the family's
take-home pay.
</P>
<P>
   Down here, in terms of national policy, it's important to
realize that fully 40 percent of the Draconian Reagan budget cuts
that still never came close to paying for those high income
focused, immense tax cuts back in 1981 came out of housing programs
for the less well-off.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to realize that while the opportunities lost
to Reagan's cuts were all restored and then some in education,
transportation, and most everywhere else, housing was the flagrant
exception.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, it's important to realize that Gingrich &AMP; Co. have
been trying to take another whack of 25 percent out of the system
since they won their majority four years ago, including the
programs to combat spreading homelessness. Only the voices of
people like Kennedy and Clinton's veto have blocked them.
</P>
<P>
   The president, however, deserves no special credit for that, and
as Kennedy points out, much responsibility for what he accurately
describes as a ``national abandonment'' stretching back to the
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite, dramatically damning Kennedy fact: Of the more
than 15 million low-income families eligible under the law for
assistance under the government's housing programs only 3 million
currently receive any. And the GOP majority in Congress proposes
that even fewer families receive any.
</P>
<P>
   In Kennedy's view this is why record numbers of people are
showing up at shelters in an amazingly prosperous economy;
government policies are literally creating homlessness at the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   But, also in his view, they are creating overcrowding, and
several other major problems. For tens of thousands of
modest-income homeowners, a lack of accessible capital is keeping
them from making needed improvements to maintain their dwellings.
And for still more tens of thousands, the expiration of
generation-old incentives to landlords with low-income tenants is
literally pushing people out of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   For the future, Kennedy has long supported and at various times
has proposed equalizing the tax breaks for renters that
mortgage-holders enjoy. The most common idea would make rent
payments tax deductible up to some moderate-income cutoff.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy worries that the politics of this is tough, and he's
right. However, at some point after this year's elections, tax cuts
are going to make it to the national table, and then the question
will be whether working families or the comfortable are targeted.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a passionate advocate of a new financing mechanism _
low-interest loans up to some reasonable maximum _ to help
homeowners make needed repairs and add rental units (a big deal for
the elderly).
</P>
<P>
   It will take a lot of tough, determined political work, and it
is impossible not to notice Susan Tracy's concentration on the same
theme. In Brighton, Kennedy's home is up a big hill they call the
Bigelow; Tracy comes from the hill right across Oak Square from it,
called the Breck.
</P>
<P>
   As an up-from-the-grass roots activist, housing is in her blood.
She ran Boston's home-less effort for a certain former mayor who's
also in this race. It's one of her central issues, from fighting
evictions in the buildings where subsidies are expiring, to taking
full advantage of funding for lead paint removal, to expanding the
new financing mechanisms for home-buyers at the community level.
And the tax deduction for renters is a cause she champions.
</P>
<P>
   There are all kinds of big issues in an urban district, from
health care to education to infrastructure. But housing hits people
literally where they live.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
