<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUTCHESON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND HOW ABOUT THE LINCOLN-FORD-MERCURY MEMORIAL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There's a lot of hand-wringing in Washington these
days about how to keep Social Security afloat when the baby-boom
generation hits retirement age. I'm pleased to report that I have
the answer: corporate sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   I got the idea from Ralph Lauren. You know Ralph Lauren. He's
the tan guy in a T-shirt who is always surrounded by beautiful
women. The New York designer recently shook off his entourage to
join President Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton at the
Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of American History.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren earned a spot on stage with the Clintons by pledging $13
million to restore one of the museum's treasures: the flag that
inspired ``The Star-Spangled Banner.'' Francis Scott Key wrote a
poem, which later became the national anthem, after the flag
survived the British bombardment of Fort McHenry in Baltimore
during the War of 1812.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Star-Spangled Banner was an inspiration to Francis Scott
Key, it's been an inspiration for me, and I want it to be an
inspiration for future generations,'' Lauren said in announcing his
gift.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Lauren doesn't write poems. He designs clothes, and
his flag sweaters are one reason that his company, Polo Ralph
Lauren, reported net revenues of nearly $1.5 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   The product tie-in is obvious, but just in case anybody missed
it, the president gave Lauren's sweaters a big fat plug at the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, most of us have _ well, maybe not most of us, but a
lot of us, including Hillary and me _ have those great Polo
sweaters with the American flag on it,'' the president said. ``I
wish I had one with the Star-Spangled Banner on it, because that's
the gift that he's given America today.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought you had to be tan, have tousled blond hair and live on
Cape Cod to wear those sweaters, but I think Clinton is on to
something with this cash-for-commercials program. He just didn't
take it far enough. How much do you think Lauren would have given
if Clinton had agreed to call the flag the ``Polo-Spangled
Banner''?
</P>
<P>
   We could do the same thing at the Washington Monument, where
Target is underwriting another restoration effort. Why not? Nearly
every sports facility in the country is already known by its
corporate sponsor. If we can have a United Center and a USAir
Arena, why can't we have a Target Washington Monument?
</P>
<P>
   Think about the possibilities. The Lockheed Martin Pentagon. The
Archer-Daniels-Midland Agriculture Building. The Excedrin/Maalox
Internal Revenue Service Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could announce the new corporate sponsors at a briefing
in the 1-800-FLOWERS Rose Garden, behind the Sherwin Williams White
House and near the Turf Builder South Lawn. (Victoria's Secret
might want to get in on the White House action, too, but I don't
think they'd make the approved bidders list.)
</P>
<P>
   Bidding on the Capitol would surely go sky high. Maybe we could
call it the NRA Dome in exchange for payments from the National
Rifle Association. If Democrats take charge, they could call the
entire Capitol complex Tort Village in honor of the Trial Lawyers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't just have to be buildings that get corporate
sponsorship. I'm sure the Walt Disney Co. would have picked up the
tab for Clinton's recent China trip if he had called it the Mulan
Tour. Guinness breweries and Stolichnaya Vodka could underwrite
forays to Ireland and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   If Saddam Hussein acts up again, we could launch Operation
Ex-Lax, the mother of all ... well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   As for that Social Security problem, that's not a problem _ it's
a marketing opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, anybody out there interested in sponsoring
a newspaper column?
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Hutcheson is chief of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's
Washington bureau. You can e-mail him at
rhutcheson(at)krwashington.com or call him at (202) 383-6000. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
