<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I WAS JUST THINKING ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not that it really matters, but:
</P>
<P>
   Did Howdy Doody die before Buffalo Bob and I just missed it?
</P>
<P>
   When the Clinton library is built, do you suppose there'll be a
special booth for phone sex?
</P>
<P>
   I can remember when Washington interns had difficulty getting
sublet apartments; now they get total immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Because Monica Lewinsky apparently doesn't believe in dry
cleaning, I'd be willing to bet she has really bad breath.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that we live in a time in which a 16-year-old
girl has to get a parent's permission in order to see ``Saving
Private Ryan'' but doesn't in order to get an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sick of athletes who claim to play within themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Were you surprised when ``Love Story'' didn't make the list of
100 best novels ever written?
</P>
<P>
   If I had one game to win, I'd want Bob Gibson on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   How come planes aren't made with the same indestructible
material used to assemble those black boxes that always survive
crashes?
</P>
<P>
   What do you figure the president's definition of safe sex is?
</P>
<P>
   TV news anchors pretty much bank on a short attention span when
they take a couple of minutes during the 5 o'clock news to tell us
what's coming up at 6.
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, everything in America will be owned by five people.
</P>
<P>
   I hate it when the person ahead of me in the ``12 Items or
Less'' line decides to pay for a pack of Tic Tacs by writing a
check.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't anybody use money anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Helms thinks a spy ring is a piece of jewelery.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Ruth candy bars rule.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be the first president to become a regular on Court
TV.
</P>
<P>
   I don't get it when guys over 40 think they're cool because they
wear an earring.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my idea of how to reform education, eliminate truancy,
and make school incredibly interesting for kids: Hire more teachers
like 32-year-old Julie Feil, who was convicted Friday of criminal
sexual conduct for doing the nasty with a 15-year-old boy in her
Hastings, Minn., high school class because she fell in love with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of the same kind of ``hands-on'' approach Clinton has
brought to government.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn is a lot more than the Red Sox first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra wears DiMaggio's number and plays like him,
too.
</P>
<P>
   You could eliminate 50 percent of courtroom backlog by
eliminating contingency fees for lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, wouldn't it be great if that spot on Monica's dress turned
out to be soy sauce and she was merely a fat slob?
</P>
<P>
   I never met a single soul who wanted to be born poor.
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me that living in poverty is the toughest job in
America.
</P>
<P>
   When liberals are told that a couple has been sentenced to jail
for forcing a 7-year-old to smoke cigarettes, drink liquor, and
have sex with an adult for money, they say: ``Cigarettes? That's
awful!''
</P>
<P>
   Someday I'd love to see the Pope appear on his balcony and
announce the baseball scores.
</P>
<P>
   You know things are good when people actually get angry over the
cost of a pay phone call going to 35 cents, a 2-cent hike in
stamps, and having to pay turnpike tolls.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the size and scope of the Big Dig, it's amazing
there is so little traffic disruption downtown.
</P>
<P>
   And if Bob Gibson couldn't start, I'd have Sandy Koufax out
there. With Tom Seaver and Whitey Ford in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   I saw Jimmy Bulger the other day sitting on a stool in a diner
out in Worcester where Elvis was working behind the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Malone is totally baked.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for her, Lois Pines came across as who she really
is during that attorney general debate.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary must be really proud, huh? I mean, think of the progress
we've made: Nixon was asked to produce a few tapes while Clinton is
going to be asked to produce a DNA sample.
</P>
<P>
   I buy eight rolls of toilet paper every time I go to the
supermarket even if I don't need them.
</P>
<P>
   I would have picked those same Powerball numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But I think you could get awfully rich even more quickly by
inventing a business where people could lease dogs rather than buy
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Barnicle is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
