<HEADLINE>
NEW AND RECOMMENDED RECENTLY REVIEWED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Whereabouts of Eneas McNulty'' &LR;  by Sebastian Barry
(Viking, $23.95). A graceful novel about the wanderings of an Irish
outcast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Hand'' &LR;  by Frank R. Wilson (Pantheon, $30). A
neurologist's provocative argument that the human hand, as much as
the human mind, has been the key to our evolution and our
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Explaining Hitler'' &LR;  by Ron Rosenbaum (Random House, $30).
Not a new account of the dictator but a sifting of what we can and
do know for sure about his life and what he stands for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Not Guilty!'' &LR;  by Betty Holcomb (Scribner, $25). An unabashed
partisan and a careful reporter, Holcomb acquits working mothers of
the charges of harming their children, their families, and their
society.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``A Beautiful Mind'' &LR;  by Sylvia Nasar (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
A biography of an extraordinary mathematician who went to madness
and back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``Angela the Upside-Down Girl: And Other Domestic Travels'' &LR;  by
Emily Hiestand (Beacon, $23). From Oak Ridge, Tenn., to Winthrop
and Cambridge.
</P>
