<HEADER>
A5232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LOLITA-BOS &LR;      08-03 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOLITA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW `LOLITA' RISKS OFFENDING FOR ART'S SAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's plenty of irony in the American fate of director Adrian
Lyne's ``Lolita.'' The movie, based on Vladimir Nabokov's 1954
novel about the love affair between a middle-aged man and a
12-year-old girl, was deemed too controversial for American cinemas
by the distribution companies. Then it was rescued from oblivion by
Showtime and given a home in the one medium that will make it
available to the greatest number of people: television. And then,
emboldened by Showtime's courage, the Samuel Goldwyn Co. last month
decided to widen the movie's potential audience even further by
bringing it to theaters after all, with a one-week run in Los
Angeles before its premiere on the cable network, followed by a
limited national release that includes Boston in September.
</P>
<P>
   So, in a manner familiar to the media age, a nice bit of
notoriety has given a huge boost to the prospects of ``Lolita.''
Fortunately, this movie mostly deserves the added attention,
despite a few tonal problems and a lag in pace about two-thirds of
the way through.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night at 9, Showtime will provide the country with its
first glimpse of Lyne's film. By the end, as Humbert hears ``the
melody of children at play'' in the distance and realizes he has
robbed Lolita of her youth, you may find yourself wondering what
the big deal was all about. Yes, Lyne's ``Lolita'' is more open in
its sexual theme than Stanley Kubrick's version ever could have
been in 1962. There are carefully choreographed scenes in which we
actually see Humbert and Lolita sexually engaged. But it is
nonetheless a profoundly bleak story in which Humbert's obsession
is taunting and destructive, a tragedy that doesn't glamorize his
relationship with his nymphet of a stepdaughter even as it explores
the fetishistic details of his attraction to her.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong: Lyne's ``Lolita'' is not an ``issue movie''
with plastic people that preachily condemns pedophilia;
screenwriter Stephen Schiff has not been co-opted by our current
awareness of child abuse, and those who won't accept anything other
than a screed will remain hostile to it. But there is certainly a
moral center in Lyne's adaptation, and that is more than you can
say for many of the blood-soaked movies sitting on top of the
weekly box-office returns.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this ``Lolita'' so risky, so potentially offensive,
and so artistically interesting is that Lyne and Schiff layer the
relationship between Jeremy Irons's Humbert and Dominique Swain's
Lolita with enough ambiguity to engage you in Humbert's view of
himself as a beau. The story is told through Humbert's eyes, as the
newly sexual Lolita appears to seduce him, slipping him her tongue
during an innocent kiss, sitting on his lap, knocking her leg
against his on the porch rocker. He's an intellectual boarder in
her mother's house in Ramsdale, but she sees him as a conquest not
too unlike the boys in school. This perspective makes the movie all
the more creepily effective, though that is what probably kept the
distributors away. Humbert, a teacher of French literature, is not
the cliched child-abuser we are accustomed to vilifying, and at
points in the movie he looks quite the victim of love himself, as
Lolita's attentions begin to wander to a mysterious other. ``Who is
it?'' Humbert begs repeatedly during a sexual encounter. Late in
their time together, Lolita offers sex in exchange for a raise in
allowance, and in that moment Humbert appears as debased as his
young lover.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about ``Lolita'' is the extremely fine
performance by Jeremy Irons, who seems born to play this role. If
Lyne and Schiff were trying to bring us inside the twisted mind of
Humbert, they couldn't have found a more skilled actor to do it.
His Humbert is like a schoolboy in a man's body, all vulnerability
to the whims of Lolita and secret plotting to keep her. He allows
us to sympathize with Humbert, to see the humanity within his
distorted consciousness and his selfish acts, to feel his
self-loathing and remorse. His Humbert is a creature of tortured
desperation and compulsion, and not snakelike cool. Irons also
provides the movie with its too few humorous moments, drugging his
new wife, Lolita's mother, so that he won't have to have sexual
relations with her. He then tests to be sure she's asleep by
holding a blaring radio up to her head (it's playing ``I'm in the
Mood for Love'').
</P>
<P>
   At points, the serious atmosphere becomes a little tiresome.
Perhaps because his previous efforts (including ``9 1/2 Weeks'' and
``Fatal Attraction'') have been considered exploitive, Lyne seems
to work overtime not to let his ``Lolita'' seem like anything but a
``literary'' adaptation. He restrains himself from having nasty fun
at the expense of Humbert and his suffering, choosing instead to
dress the movie in an artiness and an excess of melodrama that wear
thin in the last 45 minutes of the movie. As the power struggles
between Humbert and Lolita grow more intense, it's not a far cry
from ``The Young and the Restless.'' One of the defining pleasures
of Kubrick's ``Lolita'' was its ability to deploy Nabokov's black
humor, mostly thanks to the perfectly droll presence of James
Mason. While it's important for Lyne to fully portray Humbert's
romantic feelings for Lolita, it's even more important for him to
take a step back from those feelings with a dose of edginess, or
garishness, or mean laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Lyne also gives his ``Lolita'' an overly sensual look, as the
camera moves along at a languid pace, grazing 1940s Midwestern
landscapes soaked in earth tones and bittersweet sunlight. This
heightened atmosphere feeds into Humbert's dazed, love-struck state
of mind, as he and Lolita motel-hop through the backwash of
America, but it undermines the distortion and agony of Humbert's
passion. It made me think of movies like Louis Malle's ``Damage,''
which also starred Irons, in the way its composed beauty manages to
strip the life out of the torment. It's only when an armed Humbert
confronts his nemesis, Clare Quilty _ the man who stole his Lolita
and then spit her out, the man who is everything awful about
Humbert taken to an extreme _ that the movie rustles up a healthy
sense of ugliness. This violent ending is jarring, but it punctures
the increasingly numbing dreaminess of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   As Lolita, Swain is fine in a very difficult role, as she needs
to be both a seductress and a carefree 12-year-old girl with a
fondness for jawbreakers. Swain effectively manages to merge the
sexual woman and the carefree child, reveling in the vibrating bed
in a motel room, or reading a comic book while having sex with
Humbert. Only Melanie Griffith as Charlotte, Lolita's mother, seems
out of place in the movie, more 1990s than 1940s. Her role is
fairly small, so it doesn't spoil the chemistry between Irons and
Swain, a chemistry that is consistently fascinating, frightening,
and, sadly, believable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
