<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
ASKING 401(k) QUESTIONS CAN PAY OFF LATER 
 
By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In today's world of retirement planning, it pays to make a pest
of yourself.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true when it comes to 401(k) retirement
savings plans offered by employers.
</P>
<P>
   That's because some employers are doing a lousy job of telling
their workers about their 401(k) programs, according to the
Financial Literacy Center in Kalamazoo, Mich., which educates
consumers on the basics of personal finance.
</P>
<P>
   The center said employers make common mistakes when it comes to
401(k) presentations, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Talking over workers' heads and failing to explain basic
concepts of saving.
</P>
<P>
   _ Failing to explain how to save more money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Placing too much emphasis on maxing out contributions to a
401(k), which just discourages poor savers from doing anything,
when employers should be teaching that even a 1 percent
contribution can add up over time.
</P>
<P>
   If this describes your employer, don't give up. It's up to you
to make sure you ask the right questions so that you get the most
out of your 401(k), which for most workers is the foundation for
their retirement savings program. The quality of the answers you
get will only be as good as the questions you ask.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to sharpen your questions is to make a list of
them.
</P>
<P>
   One reason many employees don't participate in a 401(k) plan is
because they feel they can't afford to have a certain amount of
their pay set aside for savings. If you feel that way, ask your
employer if there is a financial adviser you can approach who will
help you find money in your budget that will enable you to save in
the 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   A crucial question is, what are the fees with the company's
401(k) plan and how much of those costs are borne by the employee?
That's crucial because fees take a bite out of your investment
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of plans now _ especially mutual funds _ the employees
are paying all of the expenses,'' said Joel Wehner, head of the
Houston office of Buck Consultants, an employee benefits consulting
firm. ``They may not see it because it's built into the investment
return.''
</P>
<P>
   Other fees pay for administration of a 401(k) plan, a trustee or
custodian to oversee plan assets and for plan audits by
accountants.
</P>
<P>
   Ask whether your company will match your contribution. If so,
how much is the match? For example, is it 50 cents on every dollar
you contribute?
</P>
<P>
   Plans that have a company match are a godsend because it's free
money.
</P>
<P>
   You should always try to contribute enough to get the maximum
match payment from the company. said Theodore Benna, president of
the 401(k) Association in Cross Fork, Pa., an advocacy group for
401(k) participants.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, companies will match your contribution up to 3 to 6
percent of your annual pay, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Matching often doesn't begin when you start a job, so ask how
long you have to work at your company before you are eligible to
receive employer matching of contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Don't stop when you reach the match level because there are
still tax advantages to saving within these plans. Find out what is
the maximum contribution you can make to your 401(k). You
personally can contribute up to $10,000 a year, excluding any
employer contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, you and your employer can contribute up to 25 percent
of your annual pay.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the investment options available for your 401(k)
money. Don't stop with a list of the mutual funds. Before picking
one, ask for copies of their prospectuses and pay close attention
to the investment philosophy of each fund and its risks.
</P>
<P>
   Find out how each fund has performed over at least five years.
The fund's reports to shareholders should have the data. You may
also call the fund or go to the Internet at www.morningstar.net and
get the data from Morningstar, which is a mutual fund research firm
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar publications may also be found at many libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Also see how often you can change your investments and
contributions to your 401(k). Generally, you don't have to pay any
fees when you make these changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequences for employees of not fully utilizing their
401(k) could literally mean the difference between a comfortable
retirement and a much more pinched existence in later life,'' said
Julyette Jacobs, director of 401(k) investor education at the
Financial Literacy Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
