<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !!! ``Un Air de Famille''  Family dysfunction, Gallic-style. More
sweet than bitter, though, even as a fragile truce shatters and the
baggage and recriminations are heaped on the table during an
after-hours birthday dinner at a family-owned bistro. With less
insight, finesse, and compassion, it could grow hard to take _ but
the film sympathizes with its characters, and you likely will, too.
(Unrated)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ! 1/2 ``BASEketball''  &LR; Anyone who's ever watched ``South Park''
knows a little bit of crude comedy goes a long way. More proof
comes in this film starring ``South Park'' creators Matt Stone and
Trey Parker, a sewer of body fluids and gay jokes that just goes on
and on and on. Come back, Chris Farley, all is forgiven! (R) Renee
Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FR)!!! 1/2 ``Ever &LR;   &UR; After''  &LR; Delightful retooling of the
Cinderella story, with gorgeous 16th-century French costumes and
settings and a thoroughly modern sensibility bubbling through its
fairytale romance. Drew Barrymore's Cinderella doesn't wait around
for a prince to rescue her, or a fairy godmother to provide magic.
Anjelica Huston brings surprising faceting to the stepmother,
rescuing her from campy caricature. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! ``The Negotiator''  &LR; Crackling-good fire-and-ice leads _ Samuel
L. Jackson's hostage negotiator turned hostage-taker to clear his
name, and Kevin Spacey's negotiator coolly doing the job Jackson's
cop usually does _ can't save this initially interesting action
thriller from crumbling into punched-up formula that pushes it away
from gritty credibility. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 ``The Parent Trap''  &LR; Glossy, earnest, but not terribly
involving remake of the 1961 original. Lindsay Lohan spunkily
recycles the double role originated by Hayley Mills, playing twin
sisters separated since birth, meeting, then scheming to reunite
their long-divorced parents. Natasha Richardson and Dennis Quaid
bring charm to those roles, but can't do much about the transparent
string-pulling _ not to mention the questionable idea that kids can
get divorced parents back together if they really try. (PG)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! ``Polish Wedding''  &LR; First-time filmmaker Theresa Connelly knows
the territory _ the Detroit Polish enclave known as Hamtramck _ but
can't seem to serve it up in more than overpitched sitcom terms.
That wastes the performances of Lena Olin as a dissatisfied earth
mother and Claire Danes as her daughter, who can't see she's
inherited her mom's unruly DNA. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! 1/2 ``The Saltmen of Tibet''  &LR; An achingly beautiful, if slow,
documentary about a remote, nomadic Tibet community making its
long, tradition-rich caravan to a fabled lake to collect salt
needed to trade for the grain that will ensure the village's
survival. (Unrated) Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``The Well''  &LR; Impressive, highly charged debut from Aussie
filmmaker Samantha Lang. It casts an ever-deepening spell as it
spins a dark story about the shifting dynamic between two women in
an isolated outback setting. Miranda Otto is the naive but sexually
precocious young domestic who quickly sees her effect on Patricia
Rabe's long-repressed single woman, after which they play out an
intense and mutually needy but untenable relationship. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
