<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL RAIN LILIES NATURALIZE EASILY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I was given a schefflera in bad condition. I bought
a large pot, good potting soil and repotted the plant. I started
feeding it 1/4 teaspoon of Miracle Grow every time I watered it. It
was outside in shade three-quarters of the day. I was watering it
every other day, 2 gallons at a time, as the pot was the largest I
could find. All of a sudden, a spottiness appeared on the leaves. I
have flushed out the soil twice with water. I was told to add
coffee grounds, and have done so once a month. Can you tell me what
is wrong and what to do?
</P>
<P>
   A: I know the heat and drought makes us want to water, water,
water. But sometimes we overwater. Make sure the soil is not too
wet, especially in the lower half of the pot. The roots may be in
moist-to-wet soil when you're watering. Test for dryness with your
fingers. An overly wet soil causes leaves to yellow. However,
inadequate water also causes yellow foliage. Scheffleras like a
lightly moist soil.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, city water can contain a lot of calcium, which ties
up the iron in the soil. When we apply a lot of city water and a
plant cannot absorb needed iron, as well as magnesium, the result
is yellowish leaves. A soil on the acidic side will enable some
plants to absorb iron and magnesium. Azaleas are a good example.
Some gardeners use coffee grounds to help acidify soils.
</P>
<P>
   I would try moving the plant to bright shade, avoiding direct
sun if possible. Scheffleras do not like such heat. The ideal
temperature range for these plants does not exceed 70, but wouldn't
we all love that?
</P>
<P>
   Carefully monitor the watering. You might try using softened
water, if possible. And only use diluted applications of a balanced
fertilizer with trace elements. A standard house-plant fertilizer
is good. Do not use one with a lot of phosphorus, the element
represented by the middle number in the fertilizer formula. You
could try a diluted fish emulsion. Every two weeks may prove
adequate. It depends on how frequently you water, since frequent
watering washes nutrients from the soil.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Epsom salt sprinkled around the pot, then watered
in, will boost magnesium levels. Iron chelate, applied according to
package directions, will boost iron supplies, and in turn, help
green up your plant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I bought a beautiful shrub, ``Duranta repens.'' I read in a
garden book that the berries are poisonous. I know that meant
poisonous to humans, but what about birds? I love my birds and will
destroy the plant before bringing harm to wild birds.
</P>
<P>
   A: The berries will not harm the birds. Lantana, too, is a plant
with berries harmful to people, but not so to birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duranta repens,'' or golden dewdrop, is a great shrub with
arching branches that matures to 6 or 7 feet in height, and flowers
in summer. It likes sun to partial sun and good drainage. Flowers
may be lilac-blue or white. The small berries are yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I planted morning glory seed in spring. The vines are thick
and beautiful, but no flowers. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is possible your morning glory has received an abundance
of nitrogen and therefore is putting on a lot of growth at the
expense of flowers. Morning glories bloom best in full sun and in a
soil that's not overly rich in nitrogen and that is on the dry
side. Perhaps yours will come around. Sometimes they flower best in
late summer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a compost pile that provides beautiful dirt. How can I
make mulch, instead?
</P>
<P>
   A: I hope I am understanding your question. The product you make
in your compost pile can be used as a soil additive or as a mulch.
We mix fruit and vegetable scraps, coffee grounds, eggshells,
leaves and some grass clippings in our compost pile. When these
organic materials break down, we have a wonderful dark, crumbly
substance that I use to mix in garden soil to boost nutrients and
improve drainage. I also use the compost as a layer of mulch in
established beds. This works like the bagged pine bark mulch you
buy at garden centers _ it helps modify soil temperature; helps
maintain soil moisture; replenishes nutrients, which in turn
promotes plant health; and discourages weeds. I think a dark, clean
compost makes an attractive mulch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
