<SLUG> BC-FILM-CURTIS-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTIS THANKS HORROR FANS BY REVISITING `HALLOWEEN' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After making five horror films in three years, Jamie Lee Curtis
was tired of being America's scream queen.
</P>
<P>
   She'd screamed through her film debut in 1978's ``Halloween,''
the most successful independent film ever on a budget-to-earnings
basis. (Cost: $325,000; domestic gross: $47 million.)
</P>
<P>
   She'd also shrieked and cringed in knockoffs such as ``Prom
Night,'' ``Terror Train'' and ``The Fog,'' as well as a Halloween
sequel she couldn't stand.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it was time to move on. But now it's time to come back
_ in ``Halloween: H20,'' due in theaters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe my career to `Halloween,''' Curtis said. ``I felt the
audience who'd given me that career deserved this.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, 39, hadn't made a horror film in 17 years. Instead, she
carved a career with riotous comedies (``Trading Places,'' ``A Fish
Called Wanda''), tender dramas (``My Girl,'' ``Forever Young'') and
a costly action romp (``True Lies'').
</P>
<P>
   But old ghosts die hard _ just like ``Halloween'' bogeyman
Michael Myers. So when Curtis saw the film's 20th anniversary lying
dead ahead, she decided to take another stab.
</P>
<P>
   She knows ``H20's'' title can be misconstrued as the symbol for
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Costner's water movie was so successful that we thought
we'd jump on the bandwagon,'' Curtis said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I came up with an ad line that was on the first
poster mock-up _ `Blood is thicker than water' _ tying in
beautifully to the `H20.' But the real `H2O,' obviously, means a
20th anniversary.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the movie didn't take any arm-twisting: It was her idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like they'd been trying to get me back all these
years,'' Curtis said. ``I actually went after this. It was
completely my call.''
</P>
<P>
   She also helped steer the story.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Halloween,'' director John Carpenter introduced Curtis as
Laurie Strode, a baby-sitting teen tormented by Myers, a masked,
mute killer wielding large kitchen knives.
</P>
<P>
   Their saga continued in 1981's ``Halloween II,'' which resumed
the story on the same night and established Myers and Strode as
siblings. (She'd been adopted by another family after their parents
were killed.)
</P>
<P>
   ``H20'' _ the series' seventh film _ ignores four more sequels
that didn't feature Curtis' character. Instead, its story picks up
20 years later, when Strode has become headmistress of a prep
school in rural California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt if we made a movie about Laurie and the horror of
horror films _ that this woman's life was devastated by Michael
Myers _ then we could give her a chance to redeem her life by
facing him,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   She took her idea to Carpenter and his co-writer on
``Halloween,'' Debra Hill. They went to Dimension, which owns the
rights to the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dimension hadn't released `Scream' yet, so we weren't catching
on the coattails of a hit,'' Curtis said. ``Of course, after
`Scream' came out, this went onto a faster track.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike `Scream' and its imitators, `H20' doesn't dote on teens
(though some do arise, including Josh Hartnett as Curtis' son).
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it's an adult's story, with Strode taking center stage,
Adam Arkin as a teacher who's her love interest and LL Cool J as a
security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This film is a thank-you note to my fans who have loved that
movie and supported me for 20 years,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guaranteed (Dimension) that the audience would be with us. I
joked that it was Field of Screams: If you build it, they will
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimension's chiefs were still nervous about the seriousness of
the film, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The redemption of a human soul that's been taken away by a
violent act is a heavy notion for a horror movie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I kept drilling this point to the writers: If you give
Laurie an opportunity to run away, and she runs, she'll be running
for the rest of her life. But if she turns around and faces her
fear, even if she dies, she'll get her soul back.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said Carpenter was unable to make the movie because of
conflicting projects. ``H20'' wound up with Steve Miner, who'd
directed two ``Friday the 13th'' films as well as ``Forever
Young.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``H20'' was finished, test-screening scores went through
the roof, and its release was moved from fall to early August.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz has been so strong that other films have scurried from
``H20's'' release date _ including Curtis' own ``Virus,'' now set
for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Virus'' sounds scary (invading aliens consider humans a
virus), Curtis said it's ``pure sci-fi.'' Between ``Halloween II''
and ``H20,'' her only movie that was even marginally in the horror
genre was 1993's ``Mother's Boys,'' in which she played the
violently possessive mother of a fractured family.
</P>
<P>
   Staying away from the genre ``was very deliberate,'' Curtis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little bit of show-biz savvy I inherited from my family
clearly paid off in realizing, after I'd gotten a very nice
foothold, that if I continued to ply my trade in that field, I'd be
limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents are actors Tony Curtis and Janet Leigh, who divorced
when she was 4.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Lee Curtis has been married for 14 years to actor-director
Christopher Guest; they have two adopted children and live in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis and her mother co-starred for Carpenter in 1980's ``The
Fog,'' and Curtis joined Leigh in Houston in 1977 when Leigh was
filming ``Murder at the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Now mother and daughter are reunited again: Leigh plays Curtis'
secretary in ``H20.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of many nods, homages and tips of the horror hat
sprinkled throughout ``H20.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother apes lines from the first `Halloween' movie,''
Curtis said. ``She also drives a car that's the same kind she drove
in `Psycho.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``H20'' also has audio of the late Donald Pleasence, who fought
Myers in all but one of the movies, and it features Nancy Stephens,
who played Pleasence's nurse.
</P>
<P>
   It includes Carpenter's familiar theme music, is shot in
Panavision like the first film, and shows clips from other horror
films.
</P>
<P>
   In this case it's from ``Scream 2'' _ just as the first
``Scream'' had clips from ``Halloween.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In one line I say, `Drive down to the Beckers,' and that's a
line from the first `Halloween' but uses a name from `Scream'
instead,'' Curtis said. ``You can really have fun with
connect-the-dots on these movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't about milking this. We had this idea before `Scream'
came out. It just so happens the genre was reinvigorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us it was always, `Look, we have one opportunity to make a
20th-anniversary movie, so let's take it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis realizes that horror films often fall into formulaic
ruts, but she still feels the genre should get more respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent 20 years defending my work as an actor,'' she said.
``People don't understand horror. `Halloween' was the `Easy Rider'
of horror films, which is why it has so much resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked really hard on this new movie. The first sequel
wasn't very good at all, but this one is special. It's difficult
work for an actor, and I'm proud of what we did. I hope the fans
will be, too.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
