<HEADLINE>
BE SMART ABOUT TRAVEL SAFETY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As instructed, I donned my life jacket and joined other
passengers at the assigned ``muster station'' on the promenade deck
of a cruise ship a couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The vessel was scheduled to depart from Santo Domingo in the
Dominican Republic in 15 minutes, and those aboard were in a
festive mood. Many arrived for this required drill carrying and
sipping tropical beverages. Others chatted about dinner plans or
exchanged jokes. One teen-ager bounced a basketball on the open
deck; another rocked to an apparent musical beat emanating from
headphones.
</P>
<P>
   As a ship's officer began detailing safety information over the
public-address system, crew members tried gamely to maintain order.
But only a few passengers paid attention. After all, this wasn't
school. Or the office. These weren't teachers. Or bosses. This was
vacation. Party time.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an unfamiliar experience, either.
</P>
<P>
   Next day, I was sitting on the sofa-bed in my stateroom,
mesmerized by dramatic pictures transmitted live by satellite to my
television screen. Pictures of another ship _ Carnival's Ecstasy _
partially engulfed in flames off the Florida coast. Pictures of
passengers, many wearing life jackets and no doubt scared for their
lives, huddled on another open deck.
</P>
<P>
   We know now that all aboard escaped serious injury, that the
blaze was quickly extinguished. But as I watched, my immediate
reaction was to pray that those Ecstasy passengers had taken the
safety drill seriously.
</P>
<P>
   I felt a special bond, too: Only a year earlier, the Society of
American Travel Writers' Editors Council had convened our annual
workshop aboard the Ecstasy. Our meetings were conducted at the
extreme rear of the ship _ now all but obscured by smoke in the
televised footage.
</P>
<P>
   What I didn't feel was fear: I knew that this was a rare
occurrence. I knew that the Ecstasy _ like the vessel on which I
was traveling, like the jetliner that had brought me to the
Caribbean, like the thousands of hotels where I'd stayed over the
years _ had a good track record for safety. Not one passenger has
died in a fire aboard a cruise ship during this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But accidents do happen. And the Ecstasy should serve as a
reminder to all travelers _ on sea and land _ that understanding
and heeding safety regulations are not trivial matters.
</P>
<P>
   How many among us allow our minds to drift when a flight
attendant talks about oxygen masks and emergency exits? Do white
lights lead to red lights? Or red to white? Heard it all before,
you say? Not necessarily. Safety guidelines vary by aircraft. In
any case, how intrusive can a two-minute refresher course be?
</P>
<P>
   How many among us study the fire emergency instructions posted
near the doors of our hotel or motel rooms?
</P>
<P>
   I've never experienced a serious emergency on an airplane or a
cruise ship, but I've been rousted from hotel rooms in the dead of
night by fire alarms from Anchorage, Alaska, to San Diego. Some
were false signals, others real scares. Several rooms in one hotel
_ rooms precariously close to mine _ were reduced to ashes. So,
yes, I do memorize the nearest fire exits.
</P>
<P>
   I familiarize myself with all the controls of a rental car, too,
before starting the ignition. I learned the importance of that
ritual the hard way: Late for an appointment one afternoon in
Birmingham, Ala., I plunged into my rental vehicle, pointed toward
a freeway and suddenly found myself in a torrential rainstorm. No
matter where my frantic fingers fumbled, I couldn't locate the
windshield wipers. Ever experienced the sensation of blindness at
60 mph? It's a miracle the car didn't crash.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us at home respect the importance _ and legal obligation
_ of buckling seat belts in our personal vehicles. But when we go
on vacation and hop aboard a scenic trolley or tour bus or into a
taxi, our sound judgment is too often clouded by a quest for
carefree adventure.
</P>
<P>
   No matter our choice of escape _ frolicking in the surf just off
a remote beach or splashing in a crowded hotel pool; hiking and
camping in an unfamiliar wilderness or roaming the streets of a big
city; drifting on a sailboat in Galveston Bay or dancing on a
cruise ship in the Caribbean _ our safety, and that of all around
us, should be a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   It is top priority with cruise-ship officials. Laws mandate a
passenger fire drill within 24 hours of departure; most occur
moments before or after the initial sailing. Typically, officers
and crew members participate in a separate drill every week.
</P>
<P>
   But effective safety-related communication, like all
communication, requires mutual participation. Our participation.
</P>
<P>
   During this recent cruise, several passengers were joking with
the captain about airlines showing ``Titanic'' on in-flight movie
screens en route to the Caribbean. The Titanic's fate, the captain
assured them, would never happen today, given advancements in
maritime technology. ``But ever since that movie became popular,
more passengers are asking about safety and thinking about safety,
and that's a good sign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive me if I seem to preach; it's not my nature. It's not my
intention, either, to dissuade one person from getting maximum
enjoyment from his or her vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is no need to be paranoid about travel. We just
need to be smart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
