</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS SUMMER, HOLLYWOOD HAS MADE MORE THAN BIG NOISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Overfed and undernourished. That's us culture consumers in the
junk-food '90s, penned up like cattle in a feed lot, blown up on
steroids, delivered numbed to the next pummeling. Or so it could
have been, a summer like any other summer on the way to the
millennium, if you stuck to the assaultive likes of ``Armageddon,''
``Godzilla,'' ``Deep Impact,'' ``Lethal Weapon 4'' and ``The
X-Files.'' Many moviegoers did. ``Armageddon'' is on its way to
selling $200 million worth of tickets in the United States. Even
``Godzilla,'' written off as a disappointment, took in over $100
million, a sum once regarded as significant money.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a message coming from the multiplexes this summer,
too. Drowned out in some quarters, perhaps, by the amped-up
decibels of the high-tech demolition derby of the week, but there
to be heard beneath the noisy clobber of movies that seemed visual
metaphors for big heavy things being dropped on our heads from a
great height: comets, reptiles, marketing campaigns. Unheralded,
but unavoidable, substance staged a comeback at the movies this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it. Two years ago, Hollywood could come up with only
one studio movie to enter in its own Oscar race, and that was a
romantic sports comedy, an enjoyable one, but hardly a pinnacle:
``Jerry Maguire.'' This summer, we have seen no less than four
films worthy of Oscar recognition, including the one that at this
point is the film to beat, Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' Its D-Day scene of the Omaha Beach landing already is an
instant cinema classic. It simply outdoes any previous war movie in
its ability to plunge audiences into the midst of war's carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Esthetically, Spielberg won the battle when he decided to film
``Saving Private Ryan'' in the gritty manner of a World War II
documentary newsreel, draining away color except for the color of
blood, wedding hand-held style to the chaos into which the soldiers
sent to rescue Private Ryan were plunged. Abandoning the usual
storyboarding, Spielberg shot the film in sequence, in
semi-improvisatory style, with a cast consisting largely of actors
who were filmmakers themselves, ranging from Tom Hanks to Edward
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Morally, Spielberg's film has the weight and depth it needs. Its
violence is not only justifiable, but indispensable, given his
determination to present the subject _ in equal parts heroic and
horrific _ truthfully. There's lots of brutal, unsparing death in
``Saving Private Ryan.'' But there's all the difference between the
deaths depicted here and the deaths in, say, ``Lethal Weapon 4.''
In the latter, the pileup of corpses is intended to entertain. The
death in ``Saving Private Ryan'' is depicted with dignity, with
serious intent. Context is everything. Not a special effect in
sight, and who needs one?
</P>
<P>
   Amusingly, it isn't a cadre of young reformers that has been
leading Hollywood away from empty special-effects spectacles and
back toward substance, but veterans who are growing old, yet
thinking young. The most radical film out of Hollywood this summer
may be Robert Redford's ``The Horse Whisperer.'' In a culture of
clamor, it's a 2 1/2-hour film about patience and the need for time
to be part of any healing equation. Stillness is the star of its
most memorable scene, in which Redford's empathetic horse healer
simply kneels in a field for hours and waits for a spooked horse to
calm down and walk back to him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a climate of insufferable cant where lively political
debate should be, along came Warren Beatty's ``Bulworth.'' His
California senator, too zonked-out with self-disgust to bother to
play the game any longer, starts running off at the mouth, refusing
to fall back on the usual cliches, making more sense the closer he
approaches delirium. He's Dostoevsky's Holy Fool, Southern
California style, ripping away the platitudes lying like tarpaulins
over the root causes of society's stacking of the deck against the
disenfranchised. ``Bulworth'' is too radical in its laser-beam
jeremiads to achieve megagrosses, but it remains a blast of fresh,
invigorating air in a climate otherwise drenched in the smug
flatulence of special-interest groups providing the customary wall
of sound that passes for political debate.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ``The Truman Show'' revisits a couple of meaty themes
that Jim Carrey only partly developed in his venturesome but
off-putting ``Cable Guy.'' Ironies pile up like snow in an Alpine
avalanche in ``The Truman Show.'' It's a film about the way TV has
colonized real life, becoming so pervasive and powerful that we
serve it instead of the reverse, taking our cues from it, shaping
our responses to its defining influence, falsifying ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   By becoming the subject of so-called reality-based TV, the life
of Carrey's Truman is removed from reality and rendered synthetic.
With a surprising performance from Ed Harris, who trades in his
usual working-class guy to play god as TV producer, and a chance
for Carrey to layer some emotional appeal into his usual sunny fool
(turned, on this occasion, victim), ``The Truman Show'' is a
brilliant pop-culture fable. It will not be lost upon the observant
that this film inveighs against film's ultimate destination and
profit center. Yup, TV.
</P>
<P>
   Audience embrace of such seemingly retro films as ``The Mask of
Zorro,'' ``There's Something About Mary,'' and ``Out of Sight''
also makes one wonder if there isn't something blowing in the wind
at the multiplexes, something that speaks of rejection of the
merely effects-laden juggernauts. Although ``Zorro'' is animated by
the wit and style of Anthony Hopkins as the old Zorro and the
roguish tongue-in-cheek sexiness of Antonio Banderas as his
sucessor behind the mask, its motor is the exuberant gymnastic
swordplay that Douglas Fairbanks Sr. invented when he filmed it in
1920 _ effects executed by humans, not computers.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``There's Something About Mary'' _ in which Ben
Stiller, Matt Dillon, and Lee Evans play R-rated versions of Larry,
Moe, and Curly as they go into raunchy orbit around Cameron Diaz's
sweet, sunny, oblivious Snow White _ attests to a need to escape
the withering puritanism of current political correctness,
especially as it has been applied to the arena of sex in the era of
AIDS, with enthusiastic prodding from the conservative right. There
are times when base instincts become basic instincts, and while
it's silly to pretend that ``There's Something About Mary'' is more
than a lowlife guy film, its outrageous sex-soaked sight gags
obviously are meeting a widespread need that can't be blamed on El
 &UR; gfspanish &LR; Nino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight,'' in which George Clooney finally seems like a
movie star, relaxed and authoritative in a laid-back way, and
Jennifer Lopez dissolves any lingering incompatibility between
sexiness and toughness, is a throwback to the days of wit and
character and playfulness in crime thrillers, before they were
replaced with stridency. The rush to retro low-tech pleasures is
clear. So is the message it sends. Roller-coaster rides and
jackhammer music videos masquerading as movies are losing their
novelty value, especially if the roller coasters are empty and the
strummers are all playing air guitar.
</P>
</TEXT>
