<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED MESSAGES ON TEEN BEER, TOBACCO USE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sometimes, we give mixed messages.
</P>
<P>
   A cigarette billboard that used to occupy a prominent space
along my normal route to work is no longer there, thanks to Texas'
lawsuit settlement with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of hundreds of tobacco billboards to come down all
over the state in an effort to reduce the temptation for teen-agers
to smoke. The idea is to discourage young Texans from getting
hooked on a dangerous product that is illegal for them to consume
but that thousands of them consume anyway.
</P>
<P>
   These billboards carry other messages now. A handful even
display anti-smoking warnings. Most, however, simply hawk other
products.
</P>
<P>
   The one on my way to work was advertising a well-known brand of
beer last week.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the last time I checked the law, beer also was an illegal
product for teen-agers to consume, and there is absolutely no
reason to think that young people will pay any less attention to
the beer billboard than they did to the cigarette ad that it
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, is that the tobacco industry
voluntarily agreed to remove its billboard advertising in Texas _
and agreed to cough up $17.3 billion _ to settle the state's
lawsuit over public health-care costs associated with smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette makers weren't acting out of the goodness of their
hearts. Their lawyers and accountants simply advised them that it
was better for business to settle than to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Texas didn't sue the alcoholic beverage industry, and beer
companies continue to exercise their right to advertise largely as
they choose. I don't argue with that because there are free speech
considerations inherent in advertising, although the content of
some beer ads, particularly on television, obviously appeals to
teens.
</P>
<P>
   We can hope that removal of the cigarette ads will prove to be
an important step forward in promoting healthy lifestyles and
respect for the law among young Texans. But there also is the risk
that well-intentioned grown-ups may simply be giving teen-agers
another excuse to laugh at them.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think that some young people haven't noticed the
conflicting signals.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lewis, a spokesman for Mothers Against Drunk Driving, said
a number of teen-agers attending a MADD youth camp this summer
detected an inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids were asking why is all the attention being focused on
banning tobacco and tobacco ads, and beer companies are getting by
with no attention at all,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   You can argue that there are some differences in the products,
namely that cigarettes, when used the way they were intended to be
used, can eventually kill you, although tobacco companies have
spent untold millions of dollars over the years trying to hide that
fact from people who got hooked on smoking as teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol, when used in moderation, doesn't pose the same health
risks for most people, but the fact remains that both products are
equally illegal in the hands of minors.
</P>
<P>
   And more high school seniors use alcohol than tobacco, according
to surveys by the Texas Commission on Alcohol and Drug Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on tobacco billboards gave Attorney General Dan Morales,
other anti-tobacco crusaders and the tobacco industry itself a big
publicity splash. It wasn't as big as the size of the tobacco
settlement itself, but then few things are as big as $17.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It will be several years, however, before we know whether the
removal of the billboards and other anti-tobacco education efforts
that may be funded by the settlement money will have any
appreciable effect on teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state government also is attempting to clamp down in
less publicized ways on both underage smoking and drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, before Morales negotiated the settlement of the
tobacco suit, the Legislature already had toughened state law
against teens caught smoking.
</P>
<P>
   People younger than 18 who are caught smoking or possessing
tobacco products can have their driver's licenses _ prized
possessions for most young people _ suspended for as long as six
months. But it also is too early to predict whether that sanction
will be the deterrent that health advocates hope it will be.
</P>
<P>
   A lot will depend on how actively police officers, who have
plenty of other things to do, issue citations to teen smokers. Most
young people, after all, can recognize the difference between smoke
and fire.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers last year also enacted a ``zero tolerance'' law that
allows officials to suspend the driver's licenses of minors caught
driving with even a trace of alcohol on their breath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
