u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SNAKE-EYES-BOS &LR;      08-03 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SNAKE-EYES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARY SINISE AT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After he appeared in ``Forrest Gump,'' one of the
highest-grossing films in movie history, and received his first
Academy Award nomination for his memorable performance as the gruff
but vulnerable Vietnam veteran Lt. Dan Taylor, someone got the
bright idea to call Gary Sinise ``a mainstream movie star.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it was written in at least one magazine, and on a
Web site devoted to the movie biz. True, Sinise has co-starred in
some of the biggest commercial hits of recent years, including
``Ransom,'' with Mel Gibson, and ``Apollo 13,'' with his ``Forrest
Gump'' co-star, Tom Hanks. His latest, ``Snake Eyes,'' is a big
summer crime actioner directed by Brian DePalma and starring
Nicolas Cage.
</P>
<P>
   But is Sinise truly a mainstream movie star, a name, a face, a
Travolta, a Cruise? If he is, well, someone forgot to tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're above the title on a $75 million movie, you're
probably a mainstream movie star, and I believe the poster says,
`Cage: Snake Eyes,''' Sinise joked. ``I feel like I've been in some
mainstream movies, big, fairly accessible commercial films. But
I've yet to be the star in one of them. Besides, I'd probably make
a lot more money than I do if I was a mainstream movie star.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sinise is not a mainstream movie star. He is not in the
rarefied company of those who, in Hollywoodspeak, can ``open'' a
film. He gets the scripts with fingerprints on them, reading for
the parts that already have been considered and rejected by other
actors. (His role in ``Snake Eyes,'' was offered to Will Smith,
then Al Pacino.)
</P>
<P>
   He is also, however, the kind of actor who makes you pay closer
attention to any film simply because he's in it. His performances
are spiced with sinew and authority, and he is a far better actor
than many who command more attention and bigger paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   While his name doesn't garner the biggest type in ads for
``Snake Eyes,'' which opens Friday, he's one of the film's most
compelling characters. Sinise plays Kevin Dunne, a strait-laced
Navy commander assigned to protect the secretary of defense at a
heavyweight boxing match in Atlantic City. There, he hooks up with
his old friend, Cage's Rick Santoro, a cop with his hands in too
many dirty pockets. While Dunne is distracted, the defense
secretary is murdered, and the two friends try to uncover how and
why the assassination occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Sinise became interested in the role because of the names
attached: Oscar-winning Cage and DePalma, who has directed such
films as ``Dressed to Kill,'' ``The Untouchables,'' and ``Mission:
Impossible.'' He also was drawn to the story, a coiling
sleight-of-hand unveiled from multiple viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne is the latest in a series of emotionally complex
characters Si-nise has tackled of late, most notably former Alabama
Governor George Wallace in the TNT miniseries, ``Wallace.''
Sinise's stunning portrayal of the man who once intoned,
``Segregation now, segregation tomorrow, segregation forever,''
earned him an Emmy nomination last month for best actor in a
miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   Sinise has been in his native Chicago recently with his wife,
actress Moira Harris, who is performing in the play, ``Playboy of
the Western World'' at Steppenwolf, the theater company Sinise
cofounded in 1974. That's where he was when he got a call from his
personal assistant informing him about the Emmy nod. Though he's
been nominated for just about every major acting award, he says,
``I should quit if being acknowledged for an award ever becomes
boring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for my friends when they get acknowledged and
they're happy for me,'' Sinise said. ``But really we're all just
trying to stay working actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Before accepting the role of Wallace, Sinise knew little about
the fiery politician from his headline-grabbing moments. He knew of
the man who put his body between black students and their legal
right to an equal education in Alabama; the man who along with
Birmingham sheriff Bull Connor, turned hoses and dogs on black
women and children who dared to say ``enough''; the man put in a
wheelchair by a 1972 assassination attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about Wallace, Sinise slipped into a swampy drawl
explaining the governor's reasoning for using cattle prods on civil
rights protesters:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, suh, you gotta understand,'' he said, arching his back,
perfectly capturing the Wallace of black-and-white newsreels.
``When you have these demonstrations you got to control these
things.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Sinise was compelled by the redemption song of Wallace's
later years, and by the man who went into a black church, bowed his
head, and begged forgiveness from the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film said so much about forgiveness,'' he said. ``That was
a movie to be made. I wasn't interested in just making a film about
a bigoted, racist governor.''
</P>
<P>
   His best supporting actor nomination in 1995 for ``Forrest
Gump'' brought Sinise greater attention, but television has
provided the best opportunity for him to flex his muscles in such
films as ``Wallace'' and HBO's ``Truman,'' with Sinise in an
award-winning performance as the no-nonsense president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still basically a character actor in the business,'' he
said. ``Until you prove yourself as a box office star, you're not
going to get offered those things. But I'm still driven by whether
I connect to the character, and does it make sense to me as a
movie. I've turned down things, possible commercial choices, but
they just didn't feel right. I turned down some starring roles in
features, but nothing I've ever regretted.''
</P>
<P>
   Sipping Evian and sitting in a luxurious Four Seasons suite,
Sinise could be mistaken for a movie star. His personal assistant
is on hand, as is a man who fiddles with Sinise's hair before
photographs can be taken. His suite is enormous _ ``about as big as
my first theater,'' he quipped _ complete with a baby grand piano
and a dining table for eight. With striking blue-gray eyes, Sinise
is as intense in person as on screen, but he also possesses a sly
sense of humor as dry as Texas in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, which has spanned 25 of his 43 years,
Sinise has enjoyed success in film, TV, and theater, which remains
his first love. He has starred in such plays as ``True West,''
``Balm in Gilead,'' and ``A Streetcar Names Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't replace the process of doing theater, and how it
evolves. You have such an extended period of time to absorb a
character, change a character, and sink into one, and I appreciate
that process,'' said Sinise, who is also an accomplished stage and
film director, most notably of an adaptation of ``Of Mice and
Men,'' with John Malkovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go through such an evolution and change in the character,
and you try so many things from night to night, you really feel
you've lived it. You can't replace that,'' he said. ``I did `The
Grapes of Wrath' as a play at Steppenwolf in Chicago for three
months, then we moved it to La Jolla, Calif., for three months, we
went to London for three weeks, we went to Broadway for six
months,'' he said. ``I got to do Tom Joad 400 times; Henry Fonda
did a couple of takes for each scene. He would have been extremely
jealous of me getting to play it that many times in the theater,
because I got to discover so many things along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, 1998 has been ``a year for small jobs,'' Sinise said. He
will play an inattentive father in the upcoming ``Bruno,'' which
marks Shirley Mac-Laine's directorial debut. This year has been
``very slow in terms of what has presented itself, and what has
been available to me, which has been nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that mainstream movie stars do not fret about
such things. But Sinise has never considered himself to be anything
other than a hard-working actor, always eager for his next role,
always concerned his current role may be his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, there's fear and insecurity, but I'm comfortable when I'm
working, when I get started on something,'' he said. ``The down
time I'm getting better at _ you know, `Relax, the right thing will
come along.' But the longer it goes on, the more I worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a possibility that you'll go out of fashion and
things won't work, or you'll make the wrong decisions. Most actors
have such ups and downs, even people at the top of the their
game,'' Sinise said. ``Anybody with any real sense of what it's
like to be an actor would have a pretty straightforward humility
about what the actor's life is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
