<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKING-PLUGOLA-HNS &LR;      08-03 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-PLUGOLA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTING UP ON THE BIG SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NANCY MARSDEN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Until now, little evidence has supported
the theory that tobacco companies use movies as advertising
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has long been aware that the Philip Morris Cos. paid to
``place'' Marlboro cigarettes and signage in ``Superman I and II.''
And lawmakers learned a year after the fact that, in 1988, the same
company shelled out $350,000 to showcase Lark cigarettes in the
James Bond film, ``License to Kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the memos leaked from Brown &AMP; Williamson suggesting
that, back in the early 1980s, A-list movie stars accepted gifts
for smoking in movies. Luxury cars, jewelry, and cash payments of
up to $300,000 were allegedly channeled through a now-defunct
product placement agency, at a cost of $950,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now, evidence subpoenaed in the Minnesota lawsuit against the
tobacco companies is raising new concerns about Hollywood's tobacco
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris document 2025863645 states that ``product was
supplied'' for more than 190 movies during the decade from 1978 to
1988.
</P>
<P>
   The shocking, 14-page list of titles peaks in '87 and '88, when
the company supplied tobacco for 54 films, including youth fare
like ``The Dream Team,'' ``Crocodile Dundee,'' ``Robocop,'' ``Die
Hard,'' and ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit?''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty films, such as ``The Muppet Movie,'' ``Grease'' and ``Jaws
II,'' were rated PG or G.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris calls the placements ``donations'' _ and indeed,
no record of payments has been uncovered. On the other hand, if
embedded advertising went for free, why did the company pay
$350,000 the same year for a role in ``License to Kill''?
</P>
<P>
   Eric Johnson, executive assistant to Minnesota Attorney General
Hubert Humphrey III, thinks that ``evidence may have been
destroyed, or communicated orally to avoid disclosure. Or business
may have been conducted by winks and nods.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, this advertising blitzkrieg belies Hollywood's
standard disclaimer _ that films don't influence behavior. If
movies could not recruit smokers, tobacco executives would not have
risked public censure.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing statistics confirm the power of product placement. Tom
Cruise put on a pair of Ray Ban sunglasses in ``Risky Business''
and the company charted 55 percent gains. Reese's Pieces candy
sales jumped 65 percent after an appearance in ``E.T.'' And when
Fonzie applied for a library card in ``Happy Days,'' library
registration increased.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to calculate the impact of the 190 product
placement salvos listed on Document 2025863645. Many of the movies
have traveled worldwide and are still circulating as favorite
videos. With the re-release of ``Grease'' _ one of the smokiest
films on the list _ the message plays on.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, different tobacco companies ``placed'' products
in the same movies. For example, in ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit?''
the cartoon character, Betty Boop, is a cigarette girl bearing a
tray of Camels _ an R.J. Reynolds brand. Lucky Strikes, made by
Brown &AMP; Williamson, also appear.
</P>
<P>
   And lest anyone tell you it's all about ``realism,'' there are
``generic'' smoking portrayals that look a lot like commercials.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, three boys about 9 years old smoke cigarettes on
the bumper of a bus. When the main character leaps aboard, the boys
award him two of their smokes, which he pockets with a satisfied
smile. The encounter has nothing to do with the plot, but it does
contain a potent, pro-tobacco message geared to youth.
</P>
<P>
   As the children of the 1980s reached adolescence, teen tobacco
use rose dramatically _ 32 percent since 1991. Once addicted (after
about 100 cigarettes) the typical teen will continue to smoke for
16 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, between 1980 and 1998, Philip Morris has climbed from
63rd to 9th in sales on the Forbes 500 list of U.S. corporations.
In assets, the company moved from 87 to 45 and in profits, from 38
to 5.
</P>
<P>
   While smoking may at times be necessary for
``characterization,'' tobacco payoffs are unacceptable because they
provide hidden incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's $6 billion tobacco settlement bars payment _ direct
or indirect _ for cigarette placement in U.S. movies. ``You should
have seen how hard (the tobacco companies) fought it,'' recalls
Eric Johnson. ``Up until the final night, it was the last item they
conceded to.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd, given that Big Tobacco voluntarily banned product placement
eight years ago under pressure from the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both the film and tobacco industries insist that
the practice hasn't occurred since 1990. Why, then, was the product
placement provision so hard to swallow?
</P>
<P>
   The answer may be that the Minnesota ban is legally binding.
</P>
<P>
   According to Humphrey's press release, ``Speculation abounds
whether secret payoffs may have been made to the makers of such
recent, smoking-intensive movies as ``Titanic'' and ``My Best
Friend's Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Secret payoffs would explain the dramatic rise in on-screen
smoking since 1990. Tobacco brands rarely appear in movies today.
But the American Lung Association found that in 133 top films
produced between 1994 and 1995, 82 percent of the lead or
supporting actors smoked.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, only 29 percent of movie characters smoked in the
1970s, according to Stanton Glantz of the University of California
at San Francisco. And only 14 percent of comparable individuals
smoke in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Even Richard Masur, president of the Screen Actors Guild,
reportedly thinks that some smoking portrayals defy credibility. He
cites the example of a cop, ``a heavy smoker, chasing a bad guy
down the street .... and never drawing a harsh breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Also perplexing is the sudden influx of tobacco dialog.
Characters no longer just smoke; they talk about it in lines that
often have the ring of commercial advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Alec Klein of the Baltimore Sun uncovered a piece of
the puzzle. Dicey memos show that the Cigar Association, a trade
group funded by tobacco companies, paid brokers to ``place'' cigars
in recent films and television shows, including the blockbuster,
``Independence Day.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a short leap to speculate that generic cigarette placement
might be promoted in the same manner. Call it ``commodity
placement.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS anchorwoman Leslie Stahl asked the tough question in a 1996
``60 Minutes'' interview that was re-aired in May. Could ``under
the table'' payoffs be going on today?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' replied Disney executive Joe Roth. But he didn't
think so. The public deserves a better answer. Tobacco is the
leading cause of death and disease in the U.S. Forty-three percent
of American teen-agers now use tobacco, and the numbers are
climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Ethical persons in both industries must take a stand and smoke
out the truth. Roth has initiated a policy discouraging smoking in
Disney's ``family'' films. And the Cigar Association announced it
will halt product placement.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture
Association of America, told the Wall Street Journal in March, ``I
don't see a lot of smoking in films, and I see a lot of films.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what they said in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Nancy Marsden is a teacher living in Beverly Hills, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
