<HEADER>
A5260 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-FALLING-BOS &LR;      08-03 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FALLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIRST NOVEL OF FLIGHT, REBELLION, AMID A NEW IRISH REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LONG FALLING 
By Keith Ridgway. Houghton Mifflin. 305 pp. $22. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The disproportionate output of serious young fiction writers by
Ireland seems a puzzle _ the whole country has a smaller population
than that of Massachusetts. It is less puzzling if one thinks of
Ireland not as a country but as a fractious family living on a
single acre. Everyone is related; everyone is in contact with the
same intense, conflicted, ingrown history and the same few richly
seasoned power centers; everything is personal. Irish society is a
perfect petri dish for literature; the wonder is that anyone is not
a poet or novelist.
</P>
<P>
   Dubliner Keith Ridgway's impressive first novel takes up all the
familiar elements: troglodytic patriarchial bullying, the silent
suffering of oppressed women, the rebellion of sons, the crushing
weight of a conservative religious/political/social system. He adds
a new element, homosexuality, but with an ironic twist: Not even
the outcast son, a sexual pariah, escapes an alliance with
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The story is told mainly from two points of view, those of Grace
Quinn, an abused farm wife in her early 50s in County Monaghan, and
of her gay son, Martin. Grace lives alone with her husband, who is
not fully realized as a character but in his few appearances is
presented as a twisted brute. He unjustly blames his wife for the
accidental death by drowning of their firstborn, 3-year-old Sean.
When he learns years later that his second son is gay, he flies
into a violent rage, and Martin leaves home for Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   In the year before the present of the novel, the father, after a
night of drinking, kills a girl with his car on a dark country road
and receives a six-month sentence. He returns home even more
violent toward Grace than before. The night after a particularly
vicious predawn attack, which includes kicking for the first time,
she takes the car and waits at the narrow place in the road for him
to come home from the pub. When he appears on foot, she guns the
engine, runs him down and kills him exactly where he had killed the
girl earlier. At that moment, he is kneeling at the flower-strewn
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Grace washes off the car, sleeps well, then goes to Dublin to
visit Martin. She calls to tell him that his father has been
killed, but not that she was the killer. Arriving in Dublin, she
enters into the complicated personal life of her surviving son. His
lover, Henry, is in Paris on a film project and Martin is tormented
with doubts about Henry's fidelity. Martin and friends take Grace
to a club. Her odd behavior when the subject of her husband's death
comes up arouses the suspicion of Sean, one of Martin's gay friends
and a newspaper reporter. Sean wonders why the police do not regard
Grace as the prime suspect, and smells a good story.
</P>
<P>
   The action of the novel, set in 1992, takes place against the
background of the real-life X case. ``X'' was a 14-year-old girl,
pregnant by a rapist, who was enjoined by an Irish judge against
leaving the country to obtain an abortion. Amid a tremendous outcry
pitting religious traditionalists against a growing secular
sentiment, there were large public demonstrations and parades. In
the end, the High Court set aside the injunction and ruled that in
certain cases abortion was justified. By then, the girl had already
left the country and the pregnancy had miscarried.
</P>
<P>
   In a clever device, Ridgway has the fictional and real-life
stories proceed in concert. In each case, the truth about the
oppressive circumstances of a woman's life is at war with the
established general rules of law and society. Both women want to
get out of the country; both are victims of men but need other men
to help them. Sean is involved in the coverage of the X case, which
is on all lips, while he is thinking about how to crack the Grace
Quinn case and make a name for himself. The denouement of the novel
takes place in the middle of a demonstration against the X
injunction outside the General Post Office _ the site of the 1916
Easter uprising.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertain meaning of the father's gesture, kneeling just
before he is killed _ is it contrition or pious hypocrisy? _ is a
recurrent theme; almost none of the characters in the book are
exactly what they seem or what one expects. Born in Ireland but
raised in England by an Irish father who so hated his country that
he changed his name to Wilson, Grace's identity is ambiguous; her
Monaghan neighbors regard her as English. The local police
detective, representing law and order and the state, nonetheless
knows about the abuse Grace has received from her husband and wants
to help her leave the country. Despite his bitter and violent
rejection at the hands of his father, Martin's response when he
learns what his mother has done is surprising. Henry, suspected by
Martin of unfaithfulness in Paris, turns out to be a voice of
ordinary loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Long Falling'' (the meaning of the title eluded me)
reveals a society and a group of people groaning toward a
refashioning of traditional assumptions. They have their roles, but
they are all trying to break out of them. The novel might have been
titled ``The Great Escape.''
</P>
<P>
   I am not altogether clear as to the reasons, but I found the
novel unsatisfying, even as I admired Ridgway's talent and
ambition. In part, the symbolic background of the X case, and the
clear-cut roles of the characters (even though they strive to
modify them), tend to weigh the book down, to give it a freight of
significance that makes it seem creaky and unduly solemn. The
ironic picture of Sean standing against the bullet-scarred pillars
of the GPO was over the top.
</P>
<P>
   I also found the style heavy going. Ridgway is an able writer
with a fairly plain manner, but he lapses into flights of
unintelligible lyricism: At one point in her wanderings, Grace
``stood at a great height over the land that had taken her and kept
her and killed her child. She saw herself upon it, moving like the
ink of a red pen. Writing herself across the world, telling her
small, thin, story. Her sketch.'' Very pretty, but hard to believe
that an unintellectual, unartistic woman like Grace would ``see''
any such thing. Also, Ridgway frequently presents a clear thought
with a straightforward sentence, then follows it with a volley of
short sentences, or fragments, that muddy things up:
</P>
<P>
   ``Above her the steeple stretched to a point that she could
imagine better than she could see. She wondered how small it was,
how sharp, how still in the wind. She wondered how to get there.
Not literally. In another way, the way in which the steeple got
there, the evolving slate. The higher the smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it has symbolic meaning, but Ridgway's characters
frequently laugh without reason, and they cough so much that one
wonders if there was something going around in Dublin in 1992. And
there is an abundance of dead dialogue:
</P>
<P>
   ```How are you?' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ```Oh, I'm fine. A bit wet.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Here, get under the umbrella. I like the cap.'
</P>
<P>
   ```It's Henry's.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh.'''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps I am an irritable reader. And these are all elements
of craft that might change as this talented writer goes forward.
``The Long Falling'' is an ambitious novel for its small size, full
of characters, Great Themes, and clever plotting. Speaking of
escapes, Keith Ridgway has escaped every cliche and most of the
stereotypes of modern Irish fiction. Without a doubt, he has the
gifts and tools for a long rising as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Mehegan is the book editor of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
