<HEADLINE>
IN AUGUST FRANCE COMES TO A STANDSTILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 News Analysis  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Over the weekend some 5 million French families were on
south-bound highways advancing at a pace somewhat slower than that
of Adolf Hitler's armored columns during their 1940 invasion.
</P>
<P>
   It was the start of the month-long August vacation when all true
French people are ready to endure every conceivable misadventure
and hardship in order to enjoy _ if that's the right word _ four
weeks of paid summer holiday guaranteed them under the law.
</P>
<P>
   Paris and other cities empty out as the French head for the
Mediterranean seaside and, in slightly smaller numbers, for the
countryside. Those remaining in the cities are hard put to find a
doctor, dentist or a butcher. Heaven help you if the plumbing
springs a leak in August. The plumbers are living it up on the
crowded beaches of St. Tropez, where no French celebrity would be
caught dead this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Whole factories shut down. One estimate puts the lost economic
activity resulting from the nation playing for an entire month at
10 percent of France's total production of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to one's vacation destination involves long hours in
traffic jams _ not surprising since nearly everybody goes on
vacation at the same time. Highway mishaps normally quadruple at
this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   The vacationers arrive at their destination worn out and
frazzled, only to begin complaining immediately about the high
prices, as landlords, hoteliers and restaurateurs make a heroic
effort to rake in their year's profit during a single four-week
period.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Apparently, nothing will deter the French from taking
their August vacation all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ~~``There's a mystique about August vacationing that cuts across
all social classes,'' explains Thierry Longet, a history professor
at the University of Paris. ``Somehow, not taking off in August
would be considered a sacrilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Holidays, Longet observes, are more important to most French
than their work. ``(Vacations) have become life's main objective,''
he notes. ``Most French people would rather have more time off than
higher salaries. This is so although they already are entitled to
six weeks off (including two in the winter), more than anyone else
in the industrialized world.''
</P>
<P>
   My friend Pierre and his wife Nicole don't leave town in August
because, he says, ``it is the best time to be in Paris. There is
little traffic and plenty of recreational activities. The only
thing one must do is avoid places frequented by foreign tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pierre, a well-off lawyer, never admits to his French
friends that he and Nicole are staying home. He says they would be
shocked by such iconoclastic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   He has hit on an ingenious method of insuring that nobody finds
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep our windows shuttered,'' he explained. ``Anyone who
happens to know us and passes by thinks that we, too, are away for
the month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5268 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HANKS-PROFILE-HN     08-03 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HANKS-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ROLE IS TOO REGULAR FOR TOM HANKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trim) 
 
By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Tom Hanks is tilting back in his chair, balancing it on
two legs. His left hand is unconsciously playing with the plastic
cap to a water bottle. He's listening.
</P>
<P>
   He's hearing that his friend Steven Spielberg, who directed him
in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' just compared him to James Stewart _
certainly not the first time Hanks has heard himself compared to
the great ``everyman'' actor. But Hanks looks slightly
uncomfortable about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed that it continuously comes up,'' Hanks says.
``I mean, it's the highest praise you can offer to a guy like me.''
He chuckles slightly. ``But isn't it kind of insulting to Mr.
Stewart and his work?
</P>
<P>
   ``You get pigeonholed one way or another. But look, I'm just
this cheesy guy who is making movies now. There is no reason to
compare me to any of the great immortals. I don't think anybody
working right now compares to the great immortals.''
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful the immortal Mr. Stewart would be too insulted by
the comparison. This ``cheesy guy'' has already gotten three Oscar
nominations _ he seems a shoe-in for a fourth this year _ and two
wins. And a Screen Actors Award and a ShoWest Convention Male Star
of the Year Award. A few more years, and Hanks is likely to be
considered one of the immortals himself.
</P>
<P>
   If Hanks is pigeonholed _ stereotyped _ as a common man, it's
not a bad rut to be stuck in. That kind of image offers so much
more leeway than, say, action hero or comedian. In the past five
years it has allowed Hanks to get the serious starring roles other
actors would kill for: a lonely widower dad in ``Sleepless in
Seattle,'' a dying AIDS patient in ``Philadelphia,'' an idiot
savant in ``Forrest Gump,'' an astronaut in crisis in ``Apollo
13.'' And now a citizen soldier forced to make daily life and death
decisions in ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Hanks gets parts based on character is obvious.
People respond to him. They believe and accept him as a genuine
person with deep inner emotions they can relate to. Spielberg
called it ``trust.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something that a performer can't just act. Or can he?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always aware of some degree of countenance I'm going to
bring to anything,'' Hanks says thoughtfully. ``Everybody is.
Robert De Niro has a countenance: It's this weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring something different. You are forced to analyze your
work. Which is uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, I'm not a threatening guy. I don't carry some
massive rough and tumble thing. When I walk into a room, nobody
fears me. The characters I play are not real stand-out flashy
dudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen,'' he says, laughing, ``I'm glad they compare me to
James Stewart rather than Van Johnson, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   And then, perhaps because Hanks is a nice guy, and because he
remembers that Van Johnson is still alive, he adds quickly, ``He
made some fine movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks even looks the part of the common guy. He has a nice
appearance, but with his undefined chin and a tall, thin head that
seems to place his narrow eyes smack in the middle, he looks more
like a friendly egghead than movie star.
</P>
<P>
   His dark curly hair is cut short, though certainly not as short
as it was as a soldier in ``Saving Private Ryan'' or as the social
misfit in ``Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   He's dressed in black jeans and heavy black leather shoes _ like
something left over from ``Private Ryan'' _ and a black jacket. The
only bright touch comes from his plaid shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks is at the peak of his career. Since the disaster of ``The
Bonfire of the Vanities'' in 1990, one of several low points in
what had been a roller-coaster career, his star has risen almost
constantly. Starting with his role as the manager of a women's
baseball team in ``A League of Their Own'' in 1992, all the films
he's done as lead actor have been hits. Even ``Toy Story,'' for
which he did only a voice, was a big success.
</P>
<P>
   Between starring roles, he directed a small movie, ``That Thing
You Do,'' taking a support role. It was a small box-office success
and earned mostly good reviews. And he produced the highly praised
miniseries, ``From the Earth to the Moon,'' for which he directed
an episode and played a small role.
</P>
<P>
   And now ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which has earned $73 million in
two weeks and has gotten the best reviews of the year, is his sixth
starring-role hit in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks' acting was once not taken very seriously because of his
TV comedy background (``Bosom Buddies''), which led to light comedy
roles. In fact, Hanks began his career on stage in the mid-'70s
doing Chekhov and Shakespeare. But his performances do seem to get
richer and better as he goes along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so much respect for Tom,'' said Gary Sinise, who
supported Hanks in ``Forrest Gump'' and ``Apollo 13.'' ``If you
look at his first work in the movies up to the kind of work he is
doing now and the kind of taste and integrity for the projects that
he's choosing now ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him on the phone the other day that I thought his
performance in `Saving Private Ryan' is just sensational. He was
doing emotionally restrained work in `Apollo 13' because the
astronauts are very contained. In `Private Ryan,' he got to play so
many different sides, strength and vulnerability and fear, and he
did it so beautifully. Aside from `Forrest Gump,' it's his greatest
performance I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks gives the impression of not just looking and acting like a
regular guy, but of being one, too. That's certainly the image you
get from his co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great example of whom I would love to be like in every
respect,'' said Matt Damon, Hanks co-star in `Saving Private Ryan.'
``It's something the young guys talked about on the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the biggest star in the world. To see the way he is to
every single person who works with him on a film, to see how
accessible he is, and the demands put on him and the way he handles
it, it gives you no excuse to ever misbehave.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hanks made an impression on Damon as soon as the young actor
arrived on location for ``Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day I walked on the set, this girl was walking
around with drinks for people. I was reaching for a soda, and I
looked over, and there was Hanks sitting in this foxhole, drinking
out of a canteen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who could go to his trailer (between takes) and
order salmon from Alaska, and it would be there, you know? And he
sits in the foxhole and drinks out of the canteen, and that's how
it's going to be done. And he doesn't tell you to do that, he just
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in a very short time, that girl wasn't walking around with
drinks anymore. There was a group of people in their foxholes,
drinking out of canteens. That's just the way he is, and we all
really responded to the part in Tom that absolutely leads by
example and doesn't preach to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is at the top of his game, as successful as anyone could
hope to be, and he handles it with total class, all the time. That
made it great because everybody wanted to follow him on the film.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By now, everyone has heard about the boot camp training the
actors went through before filming ``Saving Private Ryan.'' By all
accounts it was a rough ordeal: sleeping on the ground in the cold
and the rain for only three hours a night, and spending days in
rough training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the 44 days or whatever (was reported),'' Hanks says
with a sigh. ``It was six days. It was really quite miserable and
really humiliating, but it was worthwhile, every second of it. It
was cold, and you could only operate on three hours of sleep for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my own agenda, and I was looking forward to it. Yes, it
was exhausting, but we all became so familiar with not just our
equipment but also the mind-set and the monotony and the
exhaustion, that when it came to shoot the movie, we were cold and
exhausted guys who were sleeping in the grass while they were
setting up the camera shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without boot camp, we would have all been a bunch of goofy
actors running around saying `pow, pow.'''
</P>
<P>
   After the third day of boot camp, most of the actors rebelled
against the indignities they were being put through. A vote was
held, and everyone voted to quit. Except Hanks. So they voted
again, and everyone voted to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important that we treat that as our rehearsal,''
Hanks says. ``And that we not become a fractured unit. We were
going to be together for 65 days making this movie, and if we broke
into some sort a I-don't-want-to-do-this cliche, that is a palpable
thing that shows up on camera at the oddest times. We all had to be
on the same page every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you, now we all look at each other and say thank
God we went through boot camp.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of dedication, along with his astounding
box-office success, that have made Hanks a sought-after actor. But
it has also allowed him the luxury of not doing just any project _
he certainly doesn't need the money _ and pursuing his obsessions,
such as the space program and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   (Asked if he has any other passions waiting to be brought to the
screen, he laughs. ``No, I'd better dig something up.'')
</P>
<P>
   Hanks says he chooses his roles the same way he always has.
Winning the Academy Awards haven't changed his criteria, or made
him look for harder roles. He just wants to do good work that
interests him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest thing in the world is to say yes to something you
want to do,'' he says. ``It's harder to say no because there's a
lot of money involved and a lot of great stuff out there, but you
read it and say, `You know, it doesn't do anything for me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``By now the Oscars are like, ancient history,'' he says,
grinning. ``When did I win? Nine years ago? Five years ago? (1994
and 1995.) Bunch of other guys have won since. I'm just in the
history books. &UR; '' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
