<P>
   LEUKEMIA-OLDER-PATIENTS (Seattle) Treating older patients with
leukemia is an agonizing dilemma for physicians. Doctors can
increase an older patient's odds of a cure with aggressive
treatment, such as a bone marrow transplant, but the treatment
itself can kill the patient. That's the conundrum Seattle School
Superindent John Stanford has faced at each treatment decision
point in his battle with acute myelogenous leukemia. Researchers at
the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center have begun testing a
new-generation bone marrow transplant procedure that could one day
be used for older patients who aren't eligible for traditional bone
marrow transplants, and for others who are too sick to survive the
conventional bone marrow regimen. So far, six people have tried the
new procedure, which is not being done anywhere else in the world.
</P>
