<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COMBAT VETERANS, AVOIDING `PRIVATE RYAN' MAY BE THE BEST
COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ So powerful are the combat scenes in ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' Veterans Administration counselors across the
country are bracing for a possible wave of veterans who see the
film and rip open old emotional wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Loren Pankratz, who spent 25 years treating
patients in the VA hospital in Portland, Ore., says there is
something war vets can do to defend themselves against such pain.
</P>
<P>
   Don't see the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you enjoy action or war movies or you want to see how
Steven Spielberg handles this subject, great. Go,'' Pankratz said.
``But if it's something else _ if you think you should face
something about your past or that unless you see it you're not a
man or that seeing it will in some way help you to chase away the
memories _ think again. A picture like this is likely to do the
opposite. You'll reexperience the trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   While some psychotherapists believe that reliving trauma is
precisely the route to mental health _ especially for patients
suffering from post traumatic stress disorder _ Pankratz is not
among them. Along with his own professional experience in the VA
and in the Psychiatry Department at Oregon Health Sciences
University, he points to a vacuum of clinical proof that such an
approach works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there has never been a treatment shown to be
effective for true post traumatic stress disorder; it has a pretty
rotten prognosis,'' Pankratz said. ``Nobody can show that this
(reexperiencing) method has done any good. Quite the opposite. Two
extensive studies done in Israel in 1996 and Canada in 1997 refute
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli study, essentially a review of the world's research
on treating traumatic stress by focusing on the trauma, found no
significant successes. Treatment that focused the patient on the
future rather than the past did provide some patients some relief.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian study, another review of international research,
found that the most potent weapon against post traumatic stress is
the human animal's natural resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study basically shows that people tend to rise above the
most horrendous experiences and that there is no relation to the
amount of toxicity in the things that happen to you and how you
survive them.'' Pankratz said.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Patients Who Deceive'' (Charles Thomas Press),
Pankratz is convinced that ``post traumatic stress disorder'' has
lost its specific medical meaning and has become a catch-all term
for any number of psychological and emotional reactions. One woman
he encountered insisted that, because she had been told an
offensive joke at work, she was suffering from PTSD.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so eager these days to find pathology, they can't
get their nose out of trauma,'' he said. ``PTSD is not about
occasional nightmares or bad memories. It must follow directly from
the trauma, it's not the result of a bad life or unhappiness or
depression running in the family. It doesn't come and go, it's
persistent and significantly impairs your functioning in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Long a critic of therapy that dwells on previous trauma,
Pankratz says psychological tools like choosing not to talk or even
think about a trauma often help us put needed distance between
ourselves and pain. We ought to be grateful for the tools, not view
them as a weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some pretty good evidence that denial is an effective
mechanism for avoiding trauma stress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So the veteran who has spent decades focusing on post-war life
and turning away from the horror of Omaha Beach, Anzio, Bataan,
Korea or Vietnam?
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds like a healthy, functioning person,'' Pankratz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Should such a person expose his most tender insides to a
three-hour movie that realistically depicts the horrors of war?
</P>
<P>
   Said Pankratz: ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
