<SLUG> BC-OPERA-TRISTAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE OPERA'S NEW $2 MILLION `TRISTAN' IS BOLD, EXTRAORDINARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By R.M. CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In one bold, imaginative leap, Seattle Opera moved
Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde'' from the 19th century to the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Using diverse imagery such as Russian Constructivism,
Pre-Raphaelites and Philip Johnson's architecture, the production
gleams and glistens with brilliant ideas. There is not one ordinary
moment in the nearly five hours it takes to move through this
monumental example of the lyric theater. The extraordinary,
visually and aurally, draws our eyes and ears to the stage and
wholly engages us.
</P>
<P>
   With the notable exception of conductor Armin Jordan, nearly
everyone in the production is doing his or her first ``Tristan.''
That was barely evident Saturday night at the Opera House. Tense
may have been the operative word backstage _ with dozens of critics
in the house along with an international audience _ but the result
was seemingly one, long phrase of music from the famous ``Tristan''
chord at the beginning of the Prelude, to the dying breath of
Isolde in the ``Liebestod'' at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tristan'' is celebrated for its complications and demands, as
well as its rewards. What makes Seattle's ``Tristan'' so
exceptional is its human scale set in a huge universe, the ability
to astonish and persuade, its clarity, intelligence and insight.
Air exists where often it does not. Still lifes of rare beauty are
created, then animated gloriously and provocatively.
</P>
<P>
   There was almost no weakness Saturday in terms of music or
staging or design. Wagner often spoke of the complete art work, or
``Gesamtkunstwerk.'' This production represents such a synthesis of
ideas, musical and dramatic, magnificently realized. Rarely has so
much thought been given to every aspect of a production. A bravo
for Seattle Opera general director Speight Jenkins, without whom
none of this would have occurred. He authorized a budget of more
than $2 million, making ``Tristan'' the largest single production
in the history of company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tristan'' succeeds and fails with the two title characters,
who occupy the stage for so long. Let it be said at the outset that
Jane Eaglen and Ben Heppner are the kinds of singers one dreams of
for these roles but almost never hears. Both were engaged by
Jenkins for major roles at the start of their careers, and they
have repaid the favor by continuing to come here, now that they are
sought throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Eaglen's soprano is one of size and strength, but also one of
lyric beauty. The high B-flats and C's are triumphant, and the
middle part of her voice mellifluous and a wonder by itself. While
her reading of ``Liebestod'' will grow, her portrayal of Isolde _
the longest role in a single opera _ is already one of compassion
and courage, defiance and nobility. She is the Isolde for the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Heppner is one of those rare heroic tenors more tenor than
baritone. What gorgeous sounds he produces, long-limbed and
remarkably sweet. He is still finding his way in this complicated
role, but his accomplishment Saturday was thrilling: the sheer
beauty of timbre he brings to Tristan, instead of worked-over
leather, and powerful expression. His third-act monologue was
riveting and deeply moving.
</P>
<P>
   In her house debut, Michelle DeYoung, was a convincing Brangane,
attractive for the warmth of her characterization and lyricism of
her voice. Greer Grimsley, as the gruff and ready Kurwenal, has
never sung better, more fully, with greater passion. Peter Rose's
King Marke was also compelling, and poignant. I liked the singing
of Doug Jones (the sailor and shepherd) for its purity and
simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan knows the score of this opera, and his knowledge shows in
every bar. His tempos were medium in speed: slower than Karl Bohm
and faster than Wilhelm Furtwangler, closer to Herbert von Karajan.
The Swiss conductor was a rock but not a boring rock. He produced a
ravishing silky sound from the orchestra, one I have never heard
from this pit, silk that is strong yet supple, beautiful but
rigorous. Glen Danielson's long English horn solo in the third act
deserves special praise.
</P>
<P>
   The work of stage director Francesca Zambello, set and costume
designer Alison Chitty and lighting designer Mimi Jordan Sherin was
of one piece.
</P>
<P>
   Zambello, who sought to equalize the human and heroic elements
of the opera, has done exactly that. Every gesture has reason
behind it, and scenes that often go dead in the theater spring to
life in her hands.
</P>
<P>
   To animate this opera with dramatic action is a huge task, but
Zambello has done that without stooping to silliness and gratuitous
action. Well, there is one exception: buff boys from local muscle
parlors, stripped to the waist, hair slicked back pretending to be
sailors in the first act. This almost camp mise-en-scene comes
perilously close to disrupting the intensity and meaning of the
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Chitty's set design is so potent and striking, it will long be
remembered for the way it illuminates the text and the characters
and the way it took advantage of the low, wide Opera House stage.
</P>
<P>
   The ship bearing Isolde from Ireland to Cornwall in Act I is
hardly of medieval design; rather, it evokes Russian Constructivism
in a sleek way: a handsome, luxurious space yet a prison for
Isolde. Panels open to reveal different sections of the ship.
</P>
<P>
   The second act begins not in summer but bleak winter, snow
falling among giant birch trees. This could be Russia again, but
with the handsome glass pavilion center stage, I think more of
Johnson's famous glass house in Connecticut. This act is a triumph
of imaginative design, in which night and day are realized, the
terror and ecstasy of love illuminated. It is a series of coups de
theatre, including burning torches to signify the grim return of
day to the lovers. Chitty's third act is the least striking.
</P>
<P>
   Sherin is a lighting designer with a broad palette of
adventuresome colors and vivid imagination. Every scene she paints
with seeming abandon but in fact is carefully controlled. One
cannot imagine this production without her telling contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The production was intended to be complete. However, after the
dress rehearsal, Jenkins decided to take cuts in Acts 2 and 3,
about 12 minutes, to relieve pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tristan und Isolde.'' Music and libretto by Richard Wagner.
Seattle Opera. Saturday night at the Opera House. Principals were
Jane Eaglen, Ben Heppner, Michelle DeYoung, Greer Grimsley and
Peter Rose. Armin Jordanall was the conductor; Francesca Zambello,
stage director; Alison Chitty, set and costume designer; and Mimi
Jordan Sherin, lighting designer. Performances through Aug. 28
(Gary Lakes sings Tristan Aug. 25-28). Tickets $40-$107;
206-389-7676.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
