<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5337 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-BEEPERSPEAK-ART     08-03 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BEEPERSPEAK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING WITH THE PAGER PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (e and l coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ If etymologists ever feel the need to trace
the origins of beeperspeak, they'll have to research high school
life, circa 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Sweethearts, hoods, stoners, and loners all devised languages
that could be transmitted through their beepers, those sleek
pocket-size message centers religiously worn at the hip. When
paging a friend, they would dial in numeric codes instead of a
return phone number. The most widely known message, for example,
was 143, meaning ``I love you,'' the numbers signifying the letter
count of each affectionate word.
</P>
<P>
   But when beeperspeak surfaced, entrepreneur Norman Beauregard
was well out of high school and well out of the loop. Last year,
the 35-year-old from Attleboro, Mass., came up with what he thought
was a great idea: construct a beeper language in which numbers
could denote everyday words or phrases.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the concept wasn't all that novel. But
capitalizing on that concept was. And business is serving him well.
</P>
<P>
   Beauregard and two friends created ``The Universal Beeper Code
Book,'' a beeperspeak-English dictionary that comes in packages of
two for $4.95. About 22,000 packages have been sold nationwide to
gift shops and drugstores since December. The product also joined
the Web last week at www.thebeeperbook.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Beeperbook creators, Adam Three Inc. of Smithfield, are
banking on the unifying potential of the palm-size book. Sure,
teenagers have been communicating through pagers for years, but
each couple and set of friends had to invent their own esoteric
language. Think Beeperbook, think a united people: ``One book of
codes across the country,'' as Beauregard envisioned it.
</P>
<P>
   Small enough to fit in a wallet, the book assigns 270 words and
phrases to two- or three-digit numbers. Last year, Beauregard
invited to his home a circle of friends _ doctors, firefighters,
police officers, and lawyers _ to compile a list of commonly used
words. After six hours and a few beers, the group made the final
cut, which included terms like ``lunch,'' ``canceled,'' ``tee
time,'' and _ hey, why not? _ ``Beeperbook.'' Anything not
referenced in the book can be spelled out (A(EQ)01, B(EQ)02, etc.).
The last pages are blank, reserving codes 271 to 300 for personal
words and phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the high school codes, there is no method or reason to
the Beeperbook's matching of numbers with words, except that
everything is listed in alphabetic and numeric order. Even
Beauregard has no idea how to read a message unless he has the book
handy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not expecting anyone to memorize the book,''
said &UR;  &LR; Beauregard, who has applied for a patent on his creation.
``You just have to ask people when they're going out, `Do you have
your Beeperbook?'''
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration came to Beauregard when he grew frustrated with
searching for a pay phone every time his wife, friends, or
associates paged him in the car. He would have to pull over, use
his calling card, and learn that his wife, for instance, wanted him
to pick up some milk on the way home. With the Beeperbook, she can
punch in 211-260-123 (``after work/ &QC; 
pick up/milk''). And he doesn't need to stop the car or make the
call _ he just needs to bring home the milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, our slogan was going to be `Saves time, saves
money,' but we had to change it to `It's fun, too,''' said
Beauregard, pretending to read his pager and eagerly flip through
the tiny pages. ``When you get a code, you get your little book
out. It's just fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged the humble surroundings of his Adam Three
office, the basement of the day-care center where he sends his
youngest son. There's no view, of course, and the unfurnished space
next to the office serves as a holding area for shipments. Adam
Three shares the office with Beauregard's partners, John Felici and
David Losardo of Cam Am Sales, a packaging and paper products firm.
</P>
<P>
   But Beauregard is familiar with launching small businesses from
modest means. At 18, the Woonsocket native started Keyboard
Concepts, which makes specialized computer keys.
</P>
<P>
   He fears no threat from the latest alpha-numeric pagers, which
have bigger screens and advanced technology to allow for word
messages. Users can read e-mail, weather and traffic updates, CNN
news, and stock quotes on the screen. But these models usually cost
$100 to $200 with a charge of $12 to $30 a month, whereas numeric
pagers can run as low as $50 with monthly fees under $10.
</P>
<P>
   Pager use in the country tends to skew toward people aged 18 to
34, and 80 percent are the numeric type, said a Motorola regional
spokeswoman, Monique Allen. Fourteen percent of the 50 million
pager users are teenagers. Pager makers are apparently trying to
woo this market by releasing models in leopard-skin patterns and
hot pink. ``The young generation wants the trendiest color,'' Allen
said. ``They're very fashion-conscious, and they want a hip and
trendy pager.''
</P>
<P>
   Beeperbook sales in Pawtucket's Alpha Page beeper shop are ``not
too good,'' according to 17-year-old sales representative Ana
Borges. People in their 30s are buying the books, but Borges's
teenage friends ``haven't even considered it, probably because we
have our own codes,'' she said. ``We have 143, which means `I love
you,' but to them, it means something like, `Pick up the milk.'''
</P>
<P>
   Young people comprise one market Adam Three particularly wants
to target. ``If you put the Beeperbook in their hands, they'll have
a ball,'' said company partner Losardo. In ProCom Wireless shops in
Texas, 14-year-olds to 20-somethings are buying the inexpensive
books because most of them still use numeric pagers, said sales
director Emmett Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   After a hockey or soccer game, Beauregard's 10-year-old son,
Ryan, punches in the scores and ``won'' or ``lost'' when beeping
his dad.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's some fun in store for the zany and creative.
The book's vocabulary can allow sentence constructions like ``Thank
you for the doughnuts'' (176-84-70), ``Sorry, I lost your mother''
(169-104-115-210-128), or ``Just wanted to say, `I love to clean
diapers''' (243-104-247-57-66).
</P>
<P>
   And the old cherished declaration of ``I love you''? According
to the Beeperbook, 143 now means ``pharmacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Quipped Losardo: ``We're breaking tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT THEY'RE SAYING ON THOSE BEEPERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Talk about a generation gap. The numeric codes traditionally used
by teen-agers, according to the Motorola Web site, can carry
completely different meanings in the new Beeperbook. &QL; 
($ used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers $ Beeperbook &QL; 
21 $ Let's go for a drink. $ the letter ``U'' &QL; 
87 $ Running late. $ fun &QL; 
