<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RYAN-VET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATE RYAN' MEANS TEARS, TORMENT FOR VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUILDERLAND, N.Y. _ His gait was slow and measured as he left
the theater, but Harold Ripps' clenched fists and traces of
moisture beneath his eyes revealed his true feelings about the
movie ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   The 82-year-old veteran of World War II had heard about the
film's graphic re-enactment of the D-Day invasion at Omaha Beach in
Normandy. But he wasn't prepared for the way the sounds of bullets
zinging and anguished screams of men dying on the screen brought
back his own memories of fighting in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more realistic than any movie I've ever seen,'' said
Ripps, who served with the 2nd Division of the 38th Infantry Unit
in Germany and France. ``It really struck home.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it opened last month, thousands of moviegoers young and
old have flocked to see director Steven Spielberg's testament to
the brutality of war. The film has struck a chord with veterans _
not only of World War II, but of Vietnam, Korea and the Persian
Gulf, as well _ unearthing long-forgotten or carefully buried
recollections of combat.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, veterans' hospitals have been inundated with
calls from men seeking help coping with disturbing memories
uncovered by the movie's realism. In some cases, the film's stark
portrayal of torn flesh and frightened soldiers watching their
friends die triggered what is called post traumatic stress disorder
in veterans who had never experienced such difficulties before,
counselors said.
</P>
<P>
   Having already experienced such outpourings of emotion from
veterans after the release of Vietnam War movies like ``Platoon''
and ``Full Metal Jacket,'' the Department of Veterans Affairs in
Washington extended the hours of its telephone hot line after
``Saving Private Ryan'' opened at the theaters. The line, which is
normally not staffed over the weekend, received more than 100 calls
in three days, said Laurie Tranter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these movies can be cathartic,'' said James C.
Garrett, a clinical psychologist at the Vet Center in Albany, N.Y.
``We've seen a lot of these kinds of movies cause some people to go
out and get the help they needed. This goes all the way back to
films like `The Deer Hunter' and `Apocalypse Now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Only about 6.6 million of the 16 million men who fought in World
War II are still alive, according to Department of Veterans Affairs
records.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is the opening scene of ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which
depicts the first wave of the invasion at Omaha Beach, that evokes
the most visceral response from many veterans. The 25-minute scene
follows the soldiers as they storm the beach. Scores were mowed
down by German machine gunners, and terrified young men begged for
their mothers as they dodged bullets and cowered in the water
tinged crimson with blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought back my most vivid memories of combat; I could even
smell the gunpowder,'' said John Howe, a Vietnam vet who went to
see the movie in memory of his father and father-in-law, both of
whom fought in World War II. ``The dance of death, we used to call
it. The smoke, the bodies _ it was all there.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe was an infantryman in the 101st Airborne Division, the same
company to which the fictitious Pvt. James Ryan belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Many have lauded ``Saving Private Ryan,'' saying it is a
particularly valuable teaching tool for members of younger
generations who have neither lived during wartime nor fought in a
battle.
</P>
<P>
   But not all veterans are rushing to join the crowds seeing
``Saving Private Ryan.'' For some, who are aging or infirm, the
movie is just not a priority _ particularly because it might
resurrect memories of an experience so horrifying and personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure do think there's a need (for the movie) because it
gives people the idea of the hell us fellows went through,'' said
Thomas J. Callahan, 84, who was a warrant officer on the USS
Yorktown, an aircraft carrier lost during the Battle of Midway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if I want to see it, though. I saw my share of
combat, and I saw guys get killed. I know what they went through _
you never forget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
