to shut down five sex shops under its new zoning laws. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-AIRCON (Rome) _ While America has embraced
air-conditioning, Europe has traditionally just taken summer
afternoons off. Stores in Italy closed for the noontime heat, and
Spaniards took siestas. In the evening, Europe sat outside in the
piazza. In the hottest weeks, the Continent simply shut down. But
the piazza has become polluted by exhaust fumes, and the pressures
of a global economy are increasingly forcing Europeans to work
summers. So people are starting to demand air-conditioning.
Environmentalists are not amused, but there is an effort to make
air-conditioners kinder to the planet. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   ALBERTSON-AMERICAN (Undated) _ Albertson's Inc., the nation's
fifth-largest supermarket chain, will buy American Stores for $8.3
billion in stock and will also assume $3.4 billion in debt. The
deal will create the largest chain of supermarkets and drugstores,
with 2,470 stores, and will strengthen the position of Albertson's,
based in Boise, Idaho, in California and the Southwest. By Dana
Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ The Hang Seng index plunged 4.8
percent as hard evidence emerged of a downtown in the Hong Kong
economy. The market reacted with concern to a report by HSBC
Holdings, Britain's largest bank, that its drop in first-half
profits was worse than expected and that it had taken a charge for
bad loans that was more than four times the charge of a year
earlier. In addition, the government said the economy shrank 2.8
percent in the first quarter, an even worse decline than the 2
percent reported earlier. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   GM-BOARD (Undated) _ Developments as General Motors' board of
directors meets. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHER-TRIAL (Chicago) _ Developments at the price-fixing trial
of Archer Daniels Midland. By Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-IMATION (Undated) _ Turning its attention to increasing
its revenue, Eastman Kodak will acquire most of the medical imaging
business of Imation, the 3M spinoff, for $520 million in cash. By
Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ The yen fell to its lowest level against
the dollar in seven weeks, as currency traders tentatively tested
the new government's resolve to let the market determine the value
of Japan's currency. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-TELECOM (Madrid) _ When the Spanish telephone company
Telefonica came away with the largest single piece of Brazil's
telecommunciations privatization auction last week, the Spanish
carrier instantly doubled its holdings to more than $10 billion in
Latin America, where it was already the dominant ``foreign'' phone
provider.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 53 points at 1:15 p.m. By Sharon R.
King.
</P>
