<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5364 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILITH-OTHERWOMEN-TEX     08-03 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILITH-OTHERWOMEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENTED FEMALE ARTISTS YOU MIGHT NOT SEE AT LILITH FAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN and MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no end to the number of excellent female artists out
there _ and the sad reality is, for every one that sells bunches of
CDs and plays the main stage at Lilith, several others are just as
talented and deserving. Some others you might enjoy:
</P>
<P>
   GILLIAN WELCH: Along with partner David Rawlings, the
California-born Welch makes music that seems to spring to life from
old Walker Evans photographs; they spin tales of dying miners,
morphine addicts, poor farmers, restless ghosts and moonshine
stills up in the hills. Welch's first CD, ``Revival,'' came out in
1995; the follow-up, ``Hell Among the Yearlings,'' was released
last week.
</P>
<P>
   SAM PHILLIPS: In the '80s, Sam (then going by Leslie Phillips)
cut Christian CDs for major genre labels Myrrh and Word. But in
1988, she began making secular CDs, which were more rock-oriented
and arty but still concerned with issues of spirituality.
``Martinis &AMP; Bikinis,'' from 1994, included her two best-known
songs, ``Baby, I Can't Please You'' and ``Strawberry Road,'' but
'96's ``Omnipop (It's Only a Flesh Wound Lambchop),'' is her
masterpiece, a strange and wonderful, richly textured CD. She is
married to Fort Worth-bred singer/songwriter/producer T Bone
Burnett, who has produced several of her CDs.
</P>
<P>
   PATTY GRIFFIN: This thirtysomething East
Coaster-turned-Austinite released one of 1996's best albums,
``Living With Ghosts,'' one of the most hauntingly gorgeous
acoustic discs this side of Springsteen's ``Nebraska.'' A full band
backs on her latest effort, this year's ``Flaming Red''; it's a
rewardingly eclectic album that fluidly moves from pop to lounge to
straightforward rock. She'll tour this fall.
</P>
<P>
   KATELL KEINEG: Born in Wales and now living in Ireland, Keineg
has released two unclassifiable, exotic CDs that blend in
everything from fairly straight-ahead folk-pop to rock to hip-hop
to Middle Eastern touches to Led Zeppelinish orchestration. Last
year's ``Jet,'' her second CD, included the semihit ``One Hell of a
Life,'' and she appeared on Lilith's second stage in some venues
last year.
</P>
<P>
   FREAKWATER: This duo pairs Kentucky natives and high school pals
Janet Beveridge Bean (who also drums in the great Chicago
indie-rock band Eleventh Dream Day) and Catherine Irwin. The two
began playing bars in Louisville and released their first,
eponymous CD in 1989. Since then they've released four more CDs,
all full of rustic, sad back-porch laments, including numerous
songs about dead children. The group's latest effort, the very
impressive ``Springtime,'' came out early this year.
</P>
<P>
   KELLY WILLIS: Record companies and this amazing Austin country
singer simply do not get along. Willis, whose voice echoes the
magical twang of Patsy Cline, has had at least two major labels
sign, then release, her, simply because she refuses to play by
their rules. Still, she perseveres: She collaborated with fellow
Texas musicians like Dale Watson and Asleep at the Wheel on a new
outlaw-country compilation, ``Wandering Eyes,'' and she's shopping
around a new record. Kelly Willis, we pray, will get her day.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
