<HEADER>
A5393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES0     08-03 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes: Proliferation not all bad
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iran has joined the missile club. One of the most testy,
distasteful and unstable of regimes is getting all gussied up to
whack any country, friend or foe, in the Middle East All Iran lacks
is something sufficiently loathsome to top off its missiles _
nuclear, biological or vaporous.
</P>
<P>
   The missile club is not exclusive. Russia, China and North Korea
seem to be dispatching parts as fast as they can ship them to any
griper with hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much to do but fret. I have stolen _ and, I hope,
respectfully advanced _ an idea from Joseph Heller's great war
novel ``Catch-22.'' You will recall that at one point the U.S. Army
Air Corps hires itself out to the Germans to bomb its own bases,
thus saving money and even more inconvenience for the strapped
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   This scenario needs technological updating. How's this: The
missile-club nations agree to accommodate and install one doomsday
device for each country in the club. The devices will be exploded
only after a distinguished international committee determines war
is inevitable. Participating countries will then blow themselves
up, or, as the case may be, gas or sicken their populations. Care
would be taken that no one turns weak-kneed, or sneakily nurture a
``you-go-first'' attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of cash saved would satisfy any freshman Republican.
Additionally, the plan would fashionably exemplify government doing
things to people rather than for them.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
