<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MAXIMUMBOB-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAXIMUM BOB' IS QUIRKY, IF NOT POLITICALLY CORRECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a tropical disturbance roiling in the Gulf, the comparisons
to ``Northern Exposure'' are starting to build. Similarities are
undeniable: quirky script, interesting cast, summer launch. If
``Maximum Bob'' can retain the slice 'n' dice edge of its pilot
episode _ and if ABC has the sense to stick with it as word of
mouth spreads _ we might have a keeper here.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that ABC is committed to only seven episodes of
``Bob'' while it gives ``NYPD Blue'' a late-summer breather.
``Northern Exposure'' had a similar limited run in the summer of
1990 and disappeared for seven months before returning to CBS's
regular schedule in April '91.
</P>
<P>
   'Course, ABC's recent track record with pithy, provocative
programming is not reassuring. Jettisoned titles spring readily to
mind like cherished blasts from the past: ``My So-called Life'',
``Relativity,'' ``Cracker,'' ``Nothing Sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   On the pith meter, ``Maximum Bob'' falls short. But provocative?
Those who know Elmore Leonard's work can assume even a TV version
of ``Maximum Bob'' will be about as politically correct as a burp
in church.
</P>
<P>
   Judge ``Maximum Bob'' Gibbs is the tasteless, tactless,
shoot-from-the-lip kind of full-meal deal TV viewers haven't seen
since Archie Bunker. In these delicately sensitive times, he's
bound to knot the knickers of some group dedicated to the ethical
treatment of something. If a band of Catholics can find fault with
the caring, compassionate priest of ``Nothing Sacred,'' someone is
bound to complain about Bob, who ignores the law, bullies
defendants, stereotypes ethnic groups and, with the help of an
ornery alligator, tries to frighten his semi-estranged and
completely loopy wife into leaving him.
</P>
<P>
   Bob is an all-around despicable guy, and Beau Bridges plays him
with relish and a side of ham. More to the point, Bridges makes him
believable and downright likable.
</P>
<P>
   So consider this fair warning. Pay a visit to ``Maximum Bob''
Tuesday night, and don't worry too much if the TV gets wet. Gibbs
lives in a place called Deepwater, Fla., after all, and he's the
creation of a novelist whose characters are splashier than anything
on ``Shark Week.''
</P>
<P>
   The title character is a flamboyant Florida hangin' judge who is
tough on crime, tougher on common sense. His rulings don't fit the
law of logic, but Bob is a politician, and flouting convention gets
more notice than flaunting congeniality. Living life large also
helps.
</P>
<P>
   Any performer would dive into such a role. In keeping with Bob's
big-boy persona, Bridges' dive of choice seems to have been the
cannonball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be accused of chewing the scenery,'' Bridges
told a group of TV critics recently, ``but when you get the green
light, hey, you know, go for it. You don't have too many times in
your career where you can get that wild and crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, ``Maximum Bob'' was to have been a Barry Sonnenfeld
feature film in the manner of ``Get Shorty,'' another darkly funny
Leonard novel. But Leonard's gift for goofiness prompted Sonnenfeld
to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry decided he really wanted to do it as a television series
because he loved the characters and thought they would endure,''
said Barry Josephson, Sonnenfeld's production partner.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, ABC ordered 12 episodes plus the pilot, then halved
the order when executives decided on the summertime launch. ABC
won't say that it cut back out of fear that ``Bob'' might offend
advertisers, but a summer launch is certainly a lower-profile,
lower-risk option. If it catches on, terrific. If no one watches,
the world will have forgotten it in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, at least, the Sonnenfeld camp seems willing to buy
ABC's reasoning. Though admitting to some hurt feelings when told
of the change order, Josephson said he is now enthusiastic about
premiering the show outside the clutter of fall or midseason
launches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They figured they only had six to seven slots for us and there
was no need to do 12,'' he said. ``Just do six or seven, see what
kind of a response we got, and then hopefully come back
midseason.''
</P>
<P>
   All seven episodes, shot in Florida, have been completed, so
cast and crew can do nothing now but wait for audience response.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges is philosophical about the chances of returning after
the seven-episode teaser. ``I learned a long time ago,'' he said,
``not to have any expectations as far as longevity goes in a
television series.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wouldn't mind another crack at playing Maximum Bob to the
max, even if Bob doesn't set well with the pooh-bahs of political
correctitude. As Bob says early in Tuesday night's episode, ``We do
things a little unorthodox around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridges is happy to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry (Sonnenfeld) encouraged me,'' Bridges disclosed. ``He
said, `You've got an outrageous guy there.' So I can get about as
crazy as I can get because there are a lot of people that live in
Deepwater that can put me in line when I get too crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them is a voluble public defender named Kathy Baker,
played not by Kathy Baker but by Liz Vassey (``All My Children'').
Baker, whose husband has left her for a dental assistant, arrives
in Deepwater on a temporary assignment but stays in town after
deciding there's no reason to go home to Miami and ample reason to
keep somebody like Judge Gibbs on a short leash.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot episode, Vassey is charming and feisty, but the
least convincing of the principal players. She seems unsure if
she's performing in a drama or a comedy, which may have to do with
Sonnenberg's attempt to give TV audiences a lighter version of
Elmore Leonard. (Script writer and executive producer Alex Gansa
has explained that if a cancer were to occur in the book, it would
be malignant, and if there were one in the series, it would be
benign.)
</P>
<P>
   Sam Robards plays the other setup role more effectively, making
it clear that the widowed sheriff, Gary Hammond, is the voice of
reason in Deepwater.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum Bob's wife, Leanne Lancaster, is the opposite of reason.
Leanne is the one-time star of an R-rated underwater mermaid act
whose near-drowning gave her special psychic ability, not to
mention a second personality _ that of a 12-year-old slave girl _
who emerges when Leanne least expects it to. It may be a juicier
role than even Bob's, and an inspired Kiersten Warren squeezes
every drop from it.
</P>
<P>
   Though billed as a humorous drama, ``Maximum Bob'' is broader
and sillier than ``Northern Exposure,'' and it might be more
fitting to classify it as a seriocomedy in the tradition of another
Sonnenfeld film, ``Men in Black,'' and certainly in keeping with
last season's biggest surprise, ``Ally McBeal,'' which is competing
for awards in the comedy category.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it's a refreshing summertime julep that would
improve ABC's lineup in all seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum Bob. Hourlong series about an eccentric judge in an
eccentric Florida town, based on the Elmore Leonard novel, starring
Beau Bridges, Liz Vassey, Kiersten Warren and Sam Robards.
Premieres Tuesday night, ABC. Check local listings. Parental
guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
