<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      08-03 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING MEN DIRECTIONS TO THE ROAD TO BETTER HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (JT)  
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hospitals all over the country are opening women's health
centers, offering breast and pelvic examinations, bone density
tests, blood and urine tests and counseling on nutrition, weight
control, stress management and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason these centers cater to women: Survey after
survey has shown that women pay more attention to their physical
and emotional well-being and are more likely than men to take steps
to protect their health and check out early signs of possible
disease. And once again, a new survey conducted for Men's Health
magazine and CNN has found that American men are behind the
preventive health eight-ball.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted in April among 1,017 men and women by
Opinion Research Corporation International, disclosed that while 76
percent of women had had a physical checkup within the previous
year, only 60 percent of men had done the same.
</P>
<P>
   Extrapolating from another survey's finding, researchers
estimated that of the nation's 87 million men, nearly 7 million had
not seen a doctor for a checkup in 10 or more years _ not since
Ronald Reagan was President. And only one-fourth of the men
surveyed said they were interested in improving their health and
fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Why Bother?
</P>
<P>
   As the population ages and the proportion of people over 50
years old grows, more and more are reaching the age when health
problems develop. Many of these problems can be easily treated and
reversed if detected early enough, which generally happens in a
regular physical examination. This kind of checkup also gives
doctors an opportunity to recommend measures that can help maintain
the health of a patient who has no pressing health problems.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation racing full speed into managed health care,
preventive health measures will assume ever-greater importance.
Under managed care, you can expect a gradual rationing of costly
therapeutic techniques, especially for older people. Insurers in
the not-too-distant future may, for example, refuse to pay for
coronary bypass surgery in people over 75, costly organ transplants
and possibly even certain cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most men and a large percentage of women as well
may be forced to change their health-care ways. The first step will
be to convince men, intellectually and emotionally, of the value of
preventive health practices. The next step will be to overcome what
seems like a gender-specific resistance to paying attention to
health and acting promptly and appropriately at the first inkling
of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   There are many explanations for the fact that women on average
live about seven years longer than men do. Not the least of them is
that many men fail to take the necessary steps to prevent
life-threatening diseases and get treatment while they can still be
readily reversed or cured without budget-blowing therapies.
</P>
<P>
   For men, there is no health professional comparable to a woman's
gynecologist who sees them on a regular enough basis to head off
serious health problems. The survey showed that women well
outnumber men in recognizing the importance of practicing healthy
habits and in believing that such habits can protect their health.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, three-fifths of the men who responded to the survey
confessed to concern about developing heart disease and prostate
cancer. They also worry more than women about colon cancer, AIDS
and liver disease. The time is long overdue for men to act on these
concerns by periodically undergoing certain health checks.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended frequency of such checkups depends on your age,
family and personal medical history and whether you have any
health-threatening characteristics, like smoking or a significant
weight problem.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the Signals
</P>
<P>
   The body often gives warning signs that something is amiss.
Unfortunately, men tend to ignore noticeable signals, thinking they
will go away with rest or time or that it is more manly to suffer
in silence. Only when the signals progress into a health crisis
that can no longer be ignored are they likely to seek medical help.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, the body's signals are not readily apparent
unless checked. For example, without a medical examination, it is
impossible to know if you have high blood levels of artery-damaging
fats, high blood pressure or blood sugar or abnormal substances
spilling into your urine.
</P>
<P>
   Half the men surveyed said they had not been tested for high
cholesterol, a leading and reversible risk factor for heart
disease, and only one-third had had a blood lipid test for
cholesterol and other blood fats in the previous year.
Three-fourths of the men had not been checked for signs of colon
cancer, a leading killer of American men but one that is curable if
detected early. Likewise, among younger men who face the highest
risk of testicular cancer, only 12 percent of those 25 through 34
had been checked for this easily detected and highly curable
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A 32-page pamphlet called ``Men's Maintenance Manual'' developed
by Men's Health magazine in consultation with the American Academy
of Physicians describes the following symptoms as worth paying
attention to:
</P>
<P>
   HEADACHE that persists for more than three days, prevents you
from doing your normal activities or is accompanied by vision or
coordination problems, difficulty talking or thinking clearly,
weakness in an arm or leg, fever or vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   CHEST PAIN that is sudden and severe and lasts more than a few
minutes, gets worse with exertion, radiates to the jaw, neck or
arms or is accompanied by sensations of squeezing or pressure in
the chest and dizziness, fainting, sweating, nausea or shortness of
breath.
</P>
<P>
   SORE THROAT that is severe and gets progressively worse, making
it hard to breathe or swallow, especially if accompanied by swollen
glands or a temperature of 101 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   ABDOMINAL PAIN that is sudden and severe, lasts more than four
days, is only temporarily relieved by eating or standing up or that
recurs with constipation or diarrhea and bloating.
</P>
<P>
   BACK PAIN lasting more than three days that radiates down the
leg or interferes with work and perhaps is accompanied by numbness,
tingling and muscle weakness.
</P>
<P>
   URINATION PROBLEMS, including the need to urinate frequently or
difficulty starting or stopping the flow of urine.
</P>
<P>
   TESTICULAR ABNORMALITY, such as tenderness to the touch or
unusual hardness or unevenness.
</P>
<P>
   SKIN CHANGES, including any sore that fails to heal or a mole or
birthmark that bleeds, develops irregular borders or changes color,
size or texture.
</P>
<P>
   For More Information
</P>
<P>
   To order a free copy of the ``Men's Maintenance Manual'' through
the Internet _ see www.menshealth.com _ or call 800-955-2002 any
time of the day. You can also write to ``Men's Maintenance
Manual,'' 14 East Minor St., Emmaus, Pa. 18098. The manual, which
includes discussions of stress management, sexual health and weight
control, also lists health hotlines' for 23 helpful organizations
that can provide further information on specific health topics,
ranging from aging and allergy to sports medicine and stress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
