<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ White House officials say
they will appeal to the Supreme Court a ruling requiring grand jury
testimony by deputy White House counsel Bruce Lindsey, a longtime
friend and confidant of President Clinton. Clinton's lawyers say
the testimony would violate the sacrosanct privilege of
attorney-client confidentiality. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-MEDICARE (Washington) _ Sixty-eight House members, including
Rep. Nancy Pelosi and House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt,
ask Health Secretary Donna Shalala to define people with HIV as
``disabled'' so they can qualify for Medicaid and obtain expensive
drugs that can delay the onset of AIDS. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ The House prepares to vote on
changes to the campaign finance system that would prohibit
so-called soft-money contributions, or unrestricted donations to
political parties. The Republican-led legislation is likely to
pass. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CIA (Washington) _ The House approves legislation to name
the CIA headquarters for former President George Bush, a one-time
director of the spy agency. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-PACT (Washington) _ The House passes a resolution calling
for a ``fire suppression'' agreement with Mexico to jointly fight
wildfires. In late spring, U.S. firefighters went to Mexico to help
battle scores of fires, so intense at one time dense smoke prompted
health alters in some U.S. cities. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ Martha Phillips, director of the
Concord Coalition, a bipartisan group that lobbies for a balanced
budget, says lawmakers have a rare opportunity to fix Social
Security. Times are good, she notes, and President Clinton
understands the problems of the system and wants to avoid deficit
spending. By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HARRELSON-TRIAL (Denver) _ Charles Harrelson, convicted in the
only murder of a federal judge this century, appears in a Denver
courtroom in a last-ditch effort for a new trial. With a legal team
that includes one of O.J. Simpson's lawyers, Harrelson is
contesting his conviction and two life sentences he received for
the contract slaying of U.S. District Judge John H. Wood Jr. in San
Antonio nearly 20 years ago. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-STANDSTILL (Paris) _ already filed _ Paris and other
cities are emptying out as the French head for a month at the
seashore or countryside. Those remaining in the cities are hard put
to find a doctor or dentist. Heaven help you if the toilet leaks.
The plumbers are living it up on the beaches of St. Tropez, where
no celebrity would be caught dead this time of year. By BERNARD D.
KAPLAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Both the Senate and House are so
obtuse on the subject of gun control that they ignored the recent
violent lesson right under their noses. Although lawmakers grew
emotional last week at memorial services for two police guards
slain in the Capitol, the legislators refused to connect their
hearts with their heads. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
