<P>
   SCI-CHILE-ASTRONOMY (Undated) _ In the oven heat of day on the
high desert, cranes swing over the construction site, loaded trucks
groan up the winding road to the summit and workers in blue
hard-hats bend to their tasks around a gleaming machine anchored
inside one of the new buildings. It is the tableau of a mountaintop
being transformed by builders in the tradition of the Inca at
sacred Machu Picchu, but this time the lofty temples will be put to
the service of a modern scientific: cosmology. The worldwide
building boom in powerful astronomical observatories has now
reached this 8,000-foot mountain in the Atacama Desert of northern
Chile. By John Noble Wilford. (2500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MOTHER-CHILD (Undated) _ Challenging a popular belief about
human development, a researcher claims to have found that the
security of a baby's attachment to its mother does not influence
how well adjusted that child will be later in life. Events like
divorce, disease and accidents are far more important in shaping a
child's well-being at age 18 than early bonding with its mother. By
Sandra Blakeslee. (1650 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MATH-FRAUD (Undated) _ Dr. Theodore P. Hill asks his
mathematics students at Georgia Tech to go home and either flip a
coin 200 times and record the results, or merely pretend to flip a
coin and fake 200 results. The following day he runs his eye over
the homework data, and to the students' amazement, he easily
fingers nearly all those who faked their tosses. There is more to
this than a classroom trick. Hill is one of a growing number of
statisticians, accountants and mathematicians who are convinced
that an astonishing mathematical theorem known as Benford's Law is
a powerful and relatively simple tool for pointing suspicion at
frauds, embezzlers, tax evaders, sloppy accountants and even
computer bugs. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Undated) _ When it first made headlines about
a decade ago, gene therapy seemed the answer to a prayer for
thousands of people with hereditary diseases. The idea is simple
and eloquent. Many inherited diseases are caused by a faulty gene,
which makes the body unable to produce some essential protein or
enzyme. Gene therapy would deliver the needed gene to a person's
cells, which would then begin producing the essential substance.
But gene therapy so far has not worked, mainly because it has been
difficult to get the genes to the desired cells efficiently and
have them produce enough of the needed protein. By Andrew Pollack.
(2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BOTANY-RAVEN (St. Louis) _ A new $146 million plant research
center in St. Louis promises to make the city an agricultural
Silicon Valley, proponents say. And the man largely behind the
city's prominence and the new center is Dr. Peter Raven, for 27
years the director of the Missouri Botanical Garden and one of the
nation's foremost botanists. But says his strength is in
biopoliticking, or networking to make things happen in the plant
world. By Nancy Beth Jackson. (1950 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BURN-MASK (Undated) _ In an Ohio hospital, a group of
engineers, doctors and physical therapists are experimenting with
technology from the movie industry to produce a facial mask that
they hope will help speed the recovery of the 20,000 American
suffering serious burns each year. By Jane Ellen Stevens. (1350
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Twenty-three software makers
responded last week to the issue of a consumer's control over his
own computer and declared ``don't ask, don't tell'' an unacceptable
competitive practice. The policy statement represents an effort to
correct years of abusive practices with a new industry standard
known as ``Ask, Tell &AMP; Help.'' By Rob Fixmer.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions: The moon and its
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: The human line has
emerged from Africa not once but twice. That is the ingenious and
far-reaching surmise proposed in the latest issue of Current
Biology.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-HEALTH (Undated) _ There is a brand new recipe for a
healthy life. The basic ingredients are a low-fat diet, regular
exercise _ and marriage. Countering conventional wisdom that
marriage is bad for women but good for men, a University of Chicago
researcher said she has found that marriage brings considerable
benefits to both women and men. It lengthens life, substantially
boosts physical and emotional health, and raises income over that
enjoyed by single or divorced people or those who live together,
she said. By Hara Estroff Marano. (1450 words.)
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: A new
survey conducted has found that American men are again lagging
behind women in their concern for health. The survey revealed that
while 76 percent of women had had a physical checkup within the
previous year, only 60 percent of men had done the same. And only
one-fourth of the men surveyed said they were interested in
improving their health and fitness. By Jane E. Brody. (1230 words)
(``l'' code)
</P>
