<HEADER>
A5552 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV09-NY     08-03 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUMMER OF THIS CONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 9.)  
 (Eds., items in boldface should be set in italics.)  
 (HLW)  
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In olden times, I used to file  &UR; copy &LR; . A stack of cheap beige
 &UR; copy paper &LR;  was on my desk for this purpose, and to crumple up
satisfyingly when I rejected my own lede, or to make paper planes
out of when the muse was absent. This was when  &UR; copy boy &LR;  was a
coveted job for a kid and not a managerial slur. I used to get into
arguments with the  &UR; copy editor &LR; . (``I don't care if Shakespeare
wrote  &UR; paint the lily &LR; , people say  &UR; gild the lily &LR; .'')
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a movement among upscale copy editors to call
themselves  &UR; language therapists &LR; . Copy paper went out with carbon
copies, and former copy-paper crumplers now float painfully though
the carpal tunnel of love. And I no longer file copy, or even
transmit data; ever at the cutting edge of the pointiest cusp, I
 &UR; provide content &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   If any word in the English language is hot, buzzworthy and
finger-snappingly with-it, surpassing even  &UR; millennium &LR;  in both
general discourse and insiderese, that word is  &UR; content &LR; . Get used
to it, because we won't soon get over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accent is on  &UR; content &LR; '' is an advertising theme that
Conde Nast publications has been running for the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   When Tina Brown, empress of buzz, left Conde Nast's New Yorker
for a Disney affiliate to create a magazine that _ living in
synergy _ would provide nonfiction material to become the basis of
movies, she summed up her future with: ``It's all about
 &UR; content &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   This caused Maureen Dowd, the trend-sensitive Times Op-Ed
columnist, to ask: ``And what in heaven's name is  &UR; content &LR; ? Isn't
it just a pretentious word for substance, which was, anyway, a
pretentious word for ideas? Can  &UR; content &LR;  be synergized the way
milk is homogenized?''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few weeks before, a magazine about the media named
Brill's Content burst upon the scene. ``Steve Brill came up with
the idea of  &UR; content &LR; ,'' says Bill Kovach, its external ombudsman
and my former Times colleague, ``to give the reader the
understanding that the purpose of the magazine was to review the
content of the writing of nonfiction journalism.'' To avoid
litigation with another publisher threatening to seek an injunction
to protect a trademark claim to  &UR; Content &LR; , the proper name was
added.
</P>
<P>
   John P. Noon, who made the earlier claim (his Content World
Publishing applied for the single-word trademark in 1991), says
``we named the magazine Content because it was going to be geared
toward people in the content industry. It covers how different
types of content can make it into digital media.'' (If you're
planning a publication about questions, be careful _ he has
trademarked Query.) Another magazine, published in London, Ontario,
that describes itself as ``paving the way to the information
superhighway,'' is titled Content London and has been in business
since 1996, the same year Canadian Content, a review of software
for educators, was born.
</P>
<P>
   As used narrowly in the computer world,  &UR; content &LR;  means ``the
information on a Web site''; more broadly, it means ``software
rather than hardware'' or ``data or other material to be provided
by online services.'' The phrase  &UR; online service provider &LR;  (OSP) _
used to describe such firms as America Online, Fujitsu Niftyserve,
or Compuserve _ led to the term  &UR; content provider &LR;  (which is not
shorthanded as CP, because some of us remember the Communist
Party). ``A service provider _ Earthlink, Prodigy, AT&AMP;T _ gives you
access, like a pipeline to a destination,'' says Paul Lewis, an
online advertising pioneer. ``A  &UR; content provider &LR;  is the outfit
that offers the stuff you want at the destination.''
</P>
<P>
   First use I can find is in the June 1, 1991, Byte, a McGraw-Hill
print publication: ``Compression will be handled primarily by the
 &UR; content provider &LR; .'' The phrase still requires explanation to the
Great Unwashed: reporting in The San Francisco Chronicle about a
Ziff-Davis venture, Jerry Carroll wrote: ``ZDTV will create 300 new
` &UR; content provider &LR; ' jobs. In case you're wondering what they are,
look no further. I'm a  &UR; provider &LR;  and what you're reading is
 &UR; content &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Nisenholtz, president of electronic media at The New York
Times, recalls the predecessor phrase,  &UR; information provider &LR; , in
the days of videotext in the early '80s. `` &UR; Information provider &LR; 
morphed into  &UR; content provider &LR; ,'' he says, ``in the mid-'80s, when
it became necessary to include entertainment.'' (Martin uses verbs
like  &UR; morphed &LR; , zipping past the New Age types still mired in
 &UR; evolved &LR; .) The  &UR; content absorber &LR;  (that's you, formerly Dear
Reader) is undoubtedly experiencing the rush of insight made
possible by the prism of lexicography. When  &UR; information &LR;  _ the
name of the highway, the society, even the era _ needed a broader
term to encompass or subsume entertainment, the carapace of
 &UR; content &LR;  emerged.
</P>
<P>
   And as the profit-making  &UR; synergy &LR;  _ that combination of fact
and fiction in which the entertaining whole is hoped to be greater
than the informative parts _ attacks the world of journalism, it
has found its identity in the word  &UR; content &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the old, narrow, truth-rutted information
superhighway has morphed into nothing but a country lane, a
tributary of the ever-widening channel of Original Synergy.
</P>
<P>
   Access  &UR; content &LR;  before its stuff accesses you. But beware: this
is no vogue word or Conde Nast usage. The darkly sweeping reach of
 &UR; content &LR;  marks this coinage as a true millennialism. When every
story is partly true, who can then be false to any man?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
