<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-PRIMARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING ON GOVERNOR'S RACE MAY TO PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With newly released records showing that the
California gubernatorial primary cost an unprecedented $72 million,
political experts predict the general election in November might
look cheap in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Lungren, the Republican candidate for
governor, and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic candidate, could
make the final stretch a nickel-and-dime fund-raising affair in
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The two longtime politicians going after contributors, including
wealthy lawyers and owners of McDonald's fast-food franchises. But
in contrast to the largely self-funded primary campaigns of
Democrats Al Checchi and Rep. Jane Harman, Lungren and Davis are
raising money $1,000 at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign analysts believe the general election race between
Davis and Lungren might cost $40 million to $50 million. It could
easily beat the $40 million general election record set by
incumbent Gov. Pete Wilson and challenger Kathleen Brown in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But experts say it will never match June's election, in which
Checchi spent $39 million of his own money and Harman used $13
million of her own cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it costs, it won't be as much as the primary,'' said
Garry South, campaign manager for Davis, who said the campaign
plans to raise up to $20 million for the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy is to raise as much money as possible. You have
to reach a certain threshold or else you're in serious trouble,''
South said.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance filings sent to the secretary of state on
Friday show that both Lungren and Davis come into the race with
relatively meager war chests.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who had to struggle to beat his two wealthy Democratic
challengers in the primary, came out with an unexpected
fund-raising edge over Lungren, who faced only token opposition in
the primary.
</P>
<P>
   For the six-week period between May 17 and June 30, Davis
reported raising $113,500 per day to end up with $4.5 million in
cash on hand. Lungren raised money at only about half that pace,
collecting $55,813 per day, giving him $3.3 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three million dollars isn't exactly chopped liver,'' Southern
California political scientist Sherry Bebitch Jeffe said. ``But I
imagine Lungren would have liked to come out of the primary with at
least as much as Davis had.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll probably both be raising a lot of money. Davis has a
reputation as being one of the most prodigious fund-raisers in the
state. And I've heard Lungren has inherited a golden fund-raising
list from Pete Wilson.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the huge chunks of money that poured into the
primary, fund-raising for the general election is slow going.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day during the May fund-raising rush, Lungren
reported collecting eight $1,000 contributions from owners of
McDonald's restaurants up and down the state. At the same time,
Davis rounded up a $1,500 donation from a union for cement masons
and $2,500 from the International Association of Plumbing &AMP;
Mechanical Officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of the candidates is independently wealthy,'' said
Dave Puglia, campaign manager for Lungren. ``Both of them have to
go to donors and raise money the old-fashioned way. The real
contest is going to be who gets the most votes, not the most money.
I think it's going to be a very tight race.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' edge in the early financial reports comes as a surprise
to some experts, who expected Lungren to emerge from the primary
with a large pot of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Lungren had only token opposition in the primary,
political scientists say California's first open primary _ in which
voters could cast ballots for any candidate, rather than being
restricted to voting within their declared party _ might have hurt
Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Republicans could switch sides to vote in the
highly competitive race for the Democratic nomination meant that
Lungren had to spend money on advertising to avoid the potentially
damaging embarrassment of getting a low number of votes. By June
30, he had spent $7.9 million, while Davis spent a little more than
$9 million to win the three-way Democratic race.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Davis captured 35 percent of the total vote, while
Lungren came with 34 percent. Thirteen percent went to Checchi and
12 percent to Harman.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategist Steve Merksamer dismissed the primary
results and early fund-raising reports as virtually irrelevant to
what will happen in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats were energized because they had a contest in the
primary,'' he said. ``The Republicans were not energized. But
they're getting energized now. The fact of the matter is they're
both going to have enough money to get their message out. Money
alone will not determine this election. If money were the only
factor, Al Checchi would be governor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MOTHER-CHILD-2NDT     08-03 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MOTHER-CHILD-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: high school.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each person was interviewed for an hour at home to measure adult
attachment. Among other things, the teen-agers were asked to
describe early relationships with their parents, to generate
adjectives for each parent and provide memories to support the
adjectives.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews were scored by trained observers who examined how
specific memories were integrated into a general understanding of
the parent-child relationship. A teen-ager was deemed securely
attached if he presented a coherent story about his relationship
with his parents. A teen-ager was considered insecurely attached if
that story was fragmented, ambivalent or incoherent.
</P>
<P>
   Among securely attached infants, 57 percent were considered
well-adjusted at age 18 and 43 percent were found to be
maladjusted, Lewis said. Among insecure infants, 74 percent were
considered secure at age 18 and 26 percent were believed to have
remained insecure.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis asserts that the critical factor in human development is
not security of attachment at age 1 but subsequent experiences in
family life. There are many critical periods in every child's life.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce played a primary role in their adjustment and ``to
understand a child's emotional and social development, you have to
look at his current life,'' he said. He added: ``We don't so much
remember the past as we reconstruct it in the light of present
events. Accidents and chance encounters are a major part of life.
The task is always adaptation to the present.''
</P>
<P>
   The proponents of attachment theory, however, are not ready to
give up on a method that in their view works. For example, Dr. Alan
Sroufe, a leading attachment expert at the University of Minnesota
in Minneapolis, conducted a long-term study several years ago and
found that, in his sample, infant attachment can predict
psychopathology at age 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with Mike Lewis,'' Sroufe said. ``His study is
weaker than ours and he used fewer children. I'm not surprised he
didn't find correlations. I also disagree with him on logical
grounds. Your behavior is always a product of your history and your
present circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing that theme, Dr. Jay Belsky, a professor of human
development at Pennsylvania State University in University Park and
another well-known proponent of attachment theory, argues that
infant day care can disrupt attachment and may harm children in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``To understand the present, you have to understand what the
child brings to the circumstances,'' Belsky said. ``Of course it
matters how development proceeds, but what happens early in life
makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate is over how much of a difference. Critics of
attachment theory, including Lewis, say that most researchers place
far too much importance on what happens in the first year or two of
life. Some proponents of the theory even argue that critical
mother-infant bonding begins at birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, I visited a program in Philadelphia to foster the
social and emotional development of children of teen-aged
inner-city mothers,'' Lewis said. ``The program consisted of
placing the naked newborn child on the naked belly of the mother,
as if early bonding would somehow inoculate the child against all
future problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Irving Lazar, a professor emeritus of child development at
Vanderbilt University in Nashville, is even more critical of
attachment theorists. ``Of course babies need good mothers,'' he
said. ``It's important to feel loved and secure. But the so-called
attachment measure is ludicrous. The one-time observation of a
baby's reaction to its mother's return has no meaningful
consequences.'' All it does is make mothers feel guilty, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cairns said that animal studies mostly supported Lewis. Studies
of other mammals separated from their mothers, including the monkey
experiments of Dr. Harry Harlow in which babies were raised without
mothers, show no permanent damage to the deprived animals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harlow's monkeys treated their first-born babies ``like
basketballs'' and that is what got reported, Cairns said, but
babies born later to those same mothers were well-cared for. The
mothers adapted.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, people on both sides of the debate will say ``of
course both past and present are important,'' Cairns said, ``but
they really don't mean it.'' Many have entrenched ideological
positions which, if confined to an ivory tower, might be amusing.
These arguments, though, have important policy consequences for
American society, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the first year of life is all-important, then why bother
investing huge sums in later intervention programs? But if the
first year of life is not that important, and it is the quality of
your whole childhood that matters, how could we possibly change
things?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
