<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-TOWERS-HNS &LR;      08-03 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-TOWERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKERS WORK TO PRESERVE AN ENDANGERED SPECIES: FIRE TOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RICK KARLIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HADLEY MOUNTAIN, N.Y. _ High above the rocky summit of this
2,675-foot peak, Adam Federman has been trying to paint the wooden
stairs of a fire tower _ the last step in the three-year renovation
of this elegant structure that had been locked up and abandoned in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer, so many people have been visiting the restored
40-foot tower that Federman's paint job hasn't gotten very far. So
many visitors have been going up and down the steep stairway that
the paint wouldn't have time to dry.
</P>
<P>
   Originally built to help spot forest fires, lookout towers are a
part of Adirondack mountain lore. Dozens still dot the peaks in
upstate New York. But rendered obsolete by airplane observers and a
sharp decline in fires, most towers have been abandoned, with some
slated to eventually be torn down by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, a growing band of preservationists is starting to
restore these structures. In a bit of historic preservation akin to
the movement to turn abandoned railroad beds into bike paths, the
fire towers are being restored as mountaintop attractions for
hikers. A few, including the Hadley tower, even have interpretive
``summit guides,'' like Federman, to greet hikers.
</P>
<P>
   The Hadley Mountain fire tower, built in 1917, is just about
fully restored, with new guy wires, concrete footings, and sturdy
plastic windows on top.
</P>
<P>
   Some weekends, Federman, a 19-year-old college student who is
manning the Hadley tower as a summer job, has hosted more than 100
people who have come to climb the tower, which gets them well above
the trees and affords a 360-degree view. He answers questions like
where is Mount Marcy (you can't really see it from here) and he
hands out tiny ``I Climbed Hadley Mountain'' certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Fire towers have come a long way from their workaday origins.
Most were erected around the turn of the century, when the
Adirondacks were a vastly different place, said Jack Freeman,
research director for the Adirondack Mountain Club, a group that
promotes hiking and helps maintain trails in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, vast sections of the Adirondacks had been logged out,
leaving a scarred landscape of tree stumps and dead timber.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, tourists used to travel from the cities to
Adirondack resorts on coal and wood-fired steam trains that left
sparks in their wakes _ a recipe for catastrophic forest fires.
</P>
<P>
   By putting up a network of towers, forest rangers hoped to spot
and put out the fires early.
</P>
<P>
   They were equipped with hand-cranked phones, which usually had a
line to the watchman's home. The state hired local married men,
thinking that their wives would be around to get the phone calls in
case a fire was spotted. At their peak in the 1920s, there were
about 59 towers in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, though, steam trains gave way to automobiles as a
mode of transport and forest rangers began relying on hikers and
pilots to spot fires.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, though, was the regeneration of the logged
areas, which removed the tinderbox conditions. Major fires became
rare events, and by 1990 the last of the fire tower watchmen had
retired, marking the end of an era.
</P>
<P>
   The towers were pretty much abandoned, with only about 30
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Their revival started a few years ago when hikers started
wondering why nothing was being done with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had been complaining,'' Freeman recalled. ``Isn't it a
shame that the state doesn't care enough about these magnificent
structures?''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the complaints to heart, Freeman helped organize local
groups to ``adopt'' and rebuild the towers in places like Hadley.
He also enlisted the Department of Environmental Conservation to
help with labor and other non-monetary support.
</P>
<P>
   So far, towers at Blue Mountain, near Blue Mountain Lake, Kane
Mountain near Caroga Lake and at Hadley have been renovated.
</P>
<P>
   A tower at Goodnow Mountain near Newcomb has also been fixed up
and maintained by the state university's forestry school.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, on Poke-O-Moonshine Mountain in northern Essex
County and Mount Arab in St. Lawrence County, are undergoing
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists also want to restore five towers in the
Catskills, including one atop Hunter Mountain that has been
nominated to the National Register of Historic Places. Similar
restorations are under way in Vermont and other states.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the driving forces for the restoration at Hadley was Roy
Fordham. He's been climbing Hadley Mountain since 1933, when his
parents purchased a summer camp near the foot of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   After a career making topographic maps for the federal
government, Fordham, 70, retired to his parents' cabin. By 1995 he
was involved in a local group working to renovate the tower. The
cost of the project was about $3,000 for material such as Lexan
clear plastic for the windows and new guy wires.
</P>
<P>
   Along with those busy stairs, Fordham's volunteers are painting
the hut atop the tower in a retro-looking aluminum color paint.
</P>
<P>
   On days with low humidity, or when a high-pressure front is
coming in, savvy hikers know the views will be spectacular and they
climb Hadley Mountain in droves.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, 5-year-old Nick Bollinger had his mom's
full attention as he clambered up the steep wooden stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi mom,'' Bollinger said, his voice barely audible over the
steady hum of a 20-mph breeze blowing through the tower's guy
wires.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reason to worry, though, since the tower stairs are
partially enclosed in chicken wire.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hut, the wind noise suddenly stops _ blocked by the
thick plastic windows. The view is a classic Adirondack panorama of
deep green mountains that seem to roll on forever. To the
southwest, Great Sacandaga Lake glimmers in the noontime sun,
cutting through the haze like a signal mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on weather conditions, one can see the Green Mountains
of Vermont to the east, the Adirondack High Peaks to the north and
the Catskills to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts like Steven Engelhart, director of Adirondack
Architectural Heritage, a preservationist group, says there's
something magical about reaching a mountain summit and seeing a
tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are these wonderful sentinels on top of mountains,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
