<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS SAY HUMAN LINE EMERGED FROM AFRICA TWICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The human line has emerged from Africa not once but twice.
</P>
<P>
   That is the ingenious and far-reaching surmise proposed in the
latest issue of Current Biology by Caro-Beth Stewart of the State
University of New York at Albany and Todd R. Disotell of New York
University.
</P>
<P>
   Their conclusion emerges from an attempt to make sense of the
geographical distribution of living and fossil apes and Old World
monkeys. This special branch of the mammalian tree originated in
Africa but spread through Europe and Asia. The orangutan, for
example, is found only in southeast Asia but its close cousins the
chimpanzee and the gorilla live only in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Disotell drew up an evolutionary tree according to
the best current evidence from molecular clocks and cladistics and
then applied Occam's razor to search for the simplest pattern of
dispersal that would explain the known distribution of the species.
</P>
<P>
   Their conclusion is that an early ape-like species dispersed out
of Africa about 20 million years ago, giving rise to the gibbons,
orangutans and other ape lineages. One of these descendant ape
species must then have moved back into Africa about 10 million
years ago, speciating into the gorilla, the chimp and the hominid
line that led to humans.
</P>
<P>
   This scheme, the two scientists note, requires only two
migrations whereas the alternative of keeping the ape line
permanently in Africa postulates six migrations out of Africa and
the implausible condition of a continuously open, forested land
bridge linking Africa and Asia via Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The theory explains the absence of ape fossils in Africa from 12
million to 10 million years ago, and predicts that the Arabian
peninsula would be a good place to explore for ape-like remains.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is not yet gospel, however. Its authors note that in
earlier presentations their ideas have ``aroused vehement
discourse.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said that similar proposals had been made before but had
been ignored. Paleoanthropologists who believed in a direct lineage
between extinct African ape species like kenyapithecus and the
hominids, she said, were deeply opposed to her thesis that ape
evolution was occurring outside Africa at this period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
