<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BURN-MASK-NYT &LR;      08-03 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BURN-MASK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE SPECIAL EFFECTS HELPS SCIENTISTS MAKE A BETTER BURN MASK 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (jt)  
 By JANE ELLEN STEVENS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Vandegrift was savoring his retirement. After three decades
as coach of winning football and track teams at Lebanon High School
in Ohio, he was golfing with friends, planning some long-awaited
vacations with his wife, Rosie, and doing a little farming on six
acres outside town.
</P>
<P>
   One warm afternoon in June 1997, as he was driving his tractor
along a two-lane highway back to his house, the tractor's gas cap
popped off, gasoline sprayed out and soaked VanDeGrift from his
head to the tops of his legs, and a spark turned him into a ball of
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists stopped to help, and 20 minutes later, VanDeGrift was
flown to Miami Valley Hospital in nearby Dayton. There, VanDeGrift
began the long, difficult road to recovery traveled by all burn
patients, with one big difference. He landed in a hospital where a
group of engineers, doctors and physical therapists was
experimenting with movie-industry technology to produce a facial
mask that they hoped would help him heal faster and reduce the need
for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, more than 2 million people suffer burns; between
8,000 and 12,000 die. Of the 75,000 who are hospitalized, 20,000
have major burns involving at least 25 percent of their total body
surface. These burn patients undergo weeks in intensive care,
followed by weeks in a burn unit, followed by years of
rehabilitation and reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest problems is the growth of scar tissue, which
is so hard and unyielding it looks and feels like the tendons of an
Olympic weight lifter. It grows relentlessly for a year or two. If
patients with extensive burns do not fight it every day, by
stretching it, massaging it and wearing tight garments that slow
its growth, their bodies will constrict into a ball.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the scar tissue on facial burns under control, patients
must wear a plastic mask. The mask presses on the scars and
restricts blood flow. Without blood to feed the tissue, scars
cannot grow.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, being fitted for a mask can be horribly painful
and claustrophobic. Patients must lie on their backs as a thick
layer of plaster is smeared over their faces. They must lie still
for 30 minutes and breathe through cocktail straws stuck in their
noses while the plaster sets. Some must be sedated.
</P>
<P>
   The masks made this way do not fit that well, in part because
the face muscle shift between standing and lying positions. Without
a proper fit, the masks do not press on the scar tissue enough.
Burn patients must still undergo several operations to cut away
scar tissue that contorts their mouths or keeps their eyes
permanently open or closed.
</P>
<P>
   But now, a three-dimensional scanning technology best known for
its use in the movie industry is replacing the old method. The
result is a painless process producing better fitting masks.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Whitestone, a biomedical engineer who was among the
original group of volunteers to adapt the mask technology, said:
``Burn patients can be fitted with a high-tech mask months earlier,
before their faces begin building enough scar tissue to withstand
the pain of fitting a traditional mask. The masks fit better, so
that means the growth of the scar tissue can be arrested sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Ause-Ellias, a Miami Valley Hospital physical therapist
with the volunteer group, said, ``Patients are much more willing to
wear these new masks.'' She and Ms. Whitestone have fit six
patients with masks made with the new technology. They believe that
patients who wear the high-tech masks will require fewer operations
than those who wear the traditional masks.
</P>
<P>
   The technology used to make the masks was devised 15 years ago
in Monterey, Calif., when an electrical engineer, Lloyd Addleman,
and his family invented a three-dimensional copier to make
life-size busts of people's heads.
</P>
<P>
   They found a niche in Hollywood's special-effects industry,
scanning dinosaurs for ``Jurassic Park'' and making images for
other films.
</P>
<P>
   Wright-Patterson Air Force Base snapped up the technology to
make more efficient oxygen masks and helmets for pilots. Then, a
group of engineers, physicians and prosthetics specialists
volunteered their time to make the first high-tech masks for burn
patients. Ms. Ause-Ellias led the project with Ms. Whitestone, who
has since launched Total Contact, a company that provides the
software and hardware to make burn masks.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after his accident, VanDeGrift sat on a stool as a
scanner circled his head for 17 seconds and swept his face with a
red laser beam that he could not feel. The scanner's camera
collected 512 profiles, and its computer noted the coordinates of
500 points along each line. VanDeGrift's face appeared on a
computer screen as a wire image with thousands of points.
</P>
<P>
   The next step was to make a mold for the mask. Engineers at
Bastech Inc., an engineering company in Columbus, used computers to
slice the image of VanDeGrift's face into hundreds of cross
sections, each 1/5,000th of an inch thick. A green laser traced the
cross sections on the surface of a vat of liquid polymer and
hardened one thin layer at a time. Each hardened layer was dropped
into the liquid; the masks built layer by layer, from the chin to
the top of the nose. A day later, the molds were ready to be
smoothed.
</P>
<P>
   The final step _ making the mask _ was done at Fidelity
Orthotics, a company that makes prosthetics. Employees placed the
molds on a vacuum stand and heated sheets of clear plastic to 350
degrees until they were soft enough to shrink-wrap over the mold.
Off popped a mask. Holes were cut for eyes, nose and mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a perfect fit,'' said Ms. Ause-Ellias as she put the
mask on VanDeGrift and marked the plastic with a grease pencil to
increase the size of the mouth hole.
</P>
<P>
   Other burn specialists call the technology promising, but at
$1,500 a mask, discouragingly expensive. ``The scanning laser
technology appears to make a previously tedious and labor-intensive
process much easier,'' said Dr. Robert Spence, co-director of the
Baltimore Regional Burn Center and associate professor of plastic
surgery at Johns Hopkins Medical School. ``The primary limitation
currently, in my opinion, is its high cost.''
</P>
<P>
   VanDeGrift wears his mask every day and every night. ``I'll wear
it as long as it takes,'' he said. ``It's pretty comfortable. It
gets itchy when I exercise, and it's hard to talk very well through
it. But I can forget about it.'' The only time he takes it off is
for a haircut, to eat or to announce high school football games for
the local radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ause-Ellias noted that the mask was already beginning to
make a difference. ``He's doing great,'' she said. ``He's healing
much faster than other burn patients.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
