<HEADLINE>
SNOOTY STARTS THE LONG SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday Aug. 5)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While I was away on vacation, Snooty the manatee turned 50.
</P>
<P>
   I usually try to schedule my vacations around Snooty's
birthdays, but this year the lure of Paducah in July was simply too
strong and I left Snooty to deal with this milestone (millstone?)
by himself as best he could.
</P>
<P>
   While I was tweezing Lyme-disease-carrying ticks off my ankles
and swatting horseflies the size of herons, Snooty was celebrating
the big Five-Oh in the comfort of his aquarium at South Florida
Museum in Bradenton, Fla. There was a great deal of press coverage
of the party itself, the birthday card contest, the
save-the-manatee campaign, blah, blah, blah, but nowhere did a find
a single mention of Snooty's state of mind, which just goes to show
what a sorry product American journalism schools are turning out
these days.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who is speeding toward his 50th birthday faster than
a rogue asteroid, I think I have a pretty good idea what Snooty is
going through. When Snooty rolls out of bed in the morning and
looks at himself in the mirror, he sees a much different manatee
than he did 25 years ago. For one thing, he's put on a little
weight. I am no disciple of the cult of thinness, but even so it's
hard to feel good about yourself when you weigh 1,300 pounds, as
Snooty does.
</P>
<P>
   Snooty's weight problem must be especially depressing since all
he eats is lettuce, carrots, apples and other unappetizing stuff
that people gag down when they're trying to lose weight. How would
you feel if you weighed 1,300 pounds and had never had a pepperoni
pizza or a bowl of Cherry Garcia ice cream in your life? Pretty
unhappy, that's how.
</P>
<P>
   Obesity is not the only indignity that Snooty has suffered as he
limps (paddles?) into the twilight years of his life. Last
February, for the first time in his life, Snooty was forced to
share his aquarium with another manatee, a 4-year-old punk named,
of all things, Newton. To say that Newton is annoying is like
saying the Pentagon is wasteful. Newton flits about the tank like a
1,000-pound mosquito, stealing the spotlight from Snooty, whose
dreams of a successful acting career are now pretty much dashed
unless they come out with a movie called ``Grumpy Old Manatees.''
</P>
<P>
   Snooty, without having any say in the matter, has led a
thoroughly chaste life. Now he finds himself confined with a much
younger manatee of the same sex. This is not to imply that Snooty
would ever allow himself to be anything but a model of decorum and
decency, but all of us have read those unfortunate stories about
Catholic priests and people who have been locked up in prison for
long periods of time. Clearly, this is not the kind of
``educational purpose'' that Snooty and Newton were meant to serve.
It is certainly not the kind of legacy Snooty had in mind, either.
He wants to be remembered as our county mascot, not our midnight
cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   If Snooty is typical of 50-year-old males (and there is no
reason to think he isn't) he isn't real amenable to change. Change
is confusing, and life is confusing enough when you're 50, without
added complications.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty is the age when you start thinking about the kids moving
out of the house, not new ones moving in.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty is the age when you feel entitled to slow down a little
bit and you don't want some punk kid zipping under your chin like a
skateboarder wired on Jolt cola to remind you that you're growing
old.
</P>
<P>
   Hang in there, Snooty. It's all downhill from here.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
