<HEADER>
A5683 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-YOUTH-TEX     08-03 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-YOUTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ISN'T YOUR FATHER'S CHRISTIAN OUTREACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Behind the covered windows of a Pipeline
Road storefront in a suburb north of Fort Worth, a room full of
teens, hands in the air, sways to the sounds of young people
jamming on guitars, drums and electronic keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   Flashes of red, green, pink and blue shoot through the darkened
room. The glow of a large video screen offers minimal lighting and
a second glance at the band. A disco ball twirls slowly over the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   More than 85 teens wearing tank tops, body piercings and a
rainbow of hair colors have filed into rows of folding chairs for
an experience that 15-year-old Jeremy Lyne of North Richland Hills
says has ``pretty much changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the scene of Youth WAVE church in Hurst may owe some of
its flavoring to musical grunge gurus, the smell of teen spirit
exudes no sourness here. In this independent church that ministers
to 13- to 25-year-olds, pastors Spencer and Cyndy Nordyke
purposefully channel this teen spirit as an expression of Christian
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reaching out to a group that has their own language,
their own dress,'' Spencer Nordyke said. ``We're not trying to pull
kids out of the church. We are trying to provide a nontraditional
setting for kids to come into.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching out to teens has long been a goal for many church
leaders, who have responded by offering special Sunday school
classes, Wednesday evening prayer meetings and socials. For youth
pastors of many denominations, the goal remains much the same:
provide religious leadership and education for youths who are
making life decisions as they feel their way through the secular
and spiritual worlds.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, church leaders are expanding youth programs
beyond religious education and the occasional ice cream social or
trip to a pro baseball game, youth ministers say. A calendar of
events for youths can include a summer full of eye-opening mission
trips, weekend retreats, volunteer work and leadership training. In
some churches, the result has been a renewed emphasis on youth
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is very definitely a new interest in it,'' said
Philip H. Briggs, distinguished professor of student ministries at
Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The desire for religion geared to youths comes in part from
teens themselves, who appear to be very much included in a national
religious awakening of their baby boomer parents, clergy say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really digging spiritually,'' said Betsy Godbold,
associate pastor of White's Chapel United Methodist Church in
Southlake, north of Fort Worth. ``We are going to have to meet that
challenge to provide programs that meet the spiritual needs of
these kids. It can't be just lightweight stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 350 youths are on the roster at White's Chapel United
Methodist, and about one-third of the ministry during the week is
geared to them, said the Rev. Marty Dunbar, who oversees youth
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the Southlake church, Metroplex Covenant Church in
Colleyville offers a youth group, Crossfire. In addition to a
Wednesday night worship service in which youth pastor B. Marc
Bolling plays the electric guitar with the band, members of
Crossfire can take part in many weekly events. They can join prayer
team meetings, work on the group's Web site, and join the dance or
drama teams. Crossfire also sponsors a concert series of Christian
rock music that can attract a crowd from around the Metroplex.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 2 1/2 years, the Wednesday night Crossfire services
have grown from about 25 teens to an average of more than 65,
Bolling said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not entertainment. It's not a production. It's a
service,'' he said. ``Everything we do is geared toward God.''
</P>
<P>
   At services such as Bollings' or those at Youth WAVE, much of
the emphasis is on helping teens forge an intimate relationship
with Jesus, a relationship that parents or adults may not
understand.
</P>
<P>
   It's a crucial relationship, Briggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``God doesn't have any grandkids,'' he said. ``Every person must
have a personal encounter with a faith pilgrimage.''
</P>
<P>
   But teens are not the only driving force behind new youth
programs. Parents often expect their church to directly minister to
the spiritual needs of children and teens, Briggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we find a church that we may not be totally happy with but
our kids are getting fed, I'm willing to stay in that church for
that benefit,'' said Donna Day of Keller, whose daughter Danyelle
attends services at Youth WAVE.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the needs of the parents is also foremost in the minds
of church leaders, especially in growing areas with young families
willing to travel to the church of their choosing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a consumer society,'' Bolling said. ``Consumers go with
the best product they can find. When parents go to churches ...
they want to go to a church that can meet every need of their
family.''
</P>
<P>
   In a consumer society, Youth WAVE is probably an example of
niche marketing. Spencer Nordyke calls his church ``interest
group-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   He said youths have their own culture and it's his job to meet
their interests. That means keeping up with the latest in Christian
rock and understanding and ministering to the needs of suburban
teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting in a circle singing `Kumbaya' isn't going to do it for
these guys,'' Nordyke said.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeremy Lyne, the result is a place where a 15-year-old can
worship on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more free to be myself here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
