<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5711 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERWATCH04-COX     08-03 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERWATCH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finally, a do-not-call list for telemarketers
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Come Jan. 1, Georgia consumers will have another
weapon to fight unwanted telemarketing calls, especially those made
by Georgia-based telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   The state Public Service Commission is establishing a ``do not
call'' list of consumers who don't want to be called by
telemarketers -- and telemarketers are required to use the list or
face fines.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly passed legislation this year authorizing
the no-call list. The law -- House Bill No. 71 -- became effective
July 1, but the list becomes effective Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Information explaining the list and forms to join it will be
included in October bills mailed by Georgia's telephone companies,
said Shawn Davis, spokesman for the PSC. There is no way to join
until the information is received.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers will have to pay $5 to join the list, which is
expected to stop unwanted calls from most Georgia-based
telemarketing firms. Exempted from the law, however, are companies
that have a current or previous relationship with the customer,
political pollsters and candidates for public offices, and
religious or charity groups.
</P>
<P>
   The state also intends for the no-call list to apply to
telemarketers in other states, although it may be difficult to
enforce the law against out-of-state marketers that say the law
doesn't apply to them.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Reid, administrator of the Georgia Office of Consumer
Affairs, charged with enforcing the no-call list, said he has
``every intention of vigorously enforcing the law,'' including
legal actions in other states when needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also will rely on consumer-protection officials in other
states to help us, and we expect they will,'' Reid said. In recent
years, consumer agencies and attorneys general in various states
have increasingly worked together to resolve interstate consumer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Also a possibility, said the PSC's Davis, is the Direct
Marketing Association might add the Georgia list to its own no-call
list. The DMA is the nation's biggest association of major
telemarketing firms, most of whom honor the DMA's no-call list.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have unsuccessfully lobbied Congress for several
years to pass legislation requiring a national do-not-call list for
telemarketers. Eventually, a national list probably will be
established, but meanwhile a number of states have established
their own lists.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Congress did require telemarketers to establish
their own no-call lists of consumers who say they don't want to be
called. But the consumer has to tell each unwanted telemarketer
that calls -- and there are thousands of telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia consumer affairs office may issue civil fines up to
$2,000 for each violation of the no-call list. The law requires
telemarketers to identify themselves at the beginning of the call,
and not to use equipment that would block caller identification
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's one type of telemarketer that won't pay
any attention to Georgia's no-call list or any no-call list -- the
fraudulent one.
</P>
<P>
   This year the General Assembly passed House Bill 1420 that:
</P>
<P>
   -- Prohibits telemarketers from using couriers to pick up a
consumer's payment unless the goods are delivered with the chance
to inspect before payment is made. Con artists sometimes use
couriers to pick up cash or checks to avoid mail-fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   -- Prohibits telemarketers from requesting advance fees to
remove derogatory information from, or improve, a person's credit
history or credit record.
</P>
<P>
   -- Prohibits requesting or receiving advance payments to help
recover money lost in a previous telemarketing transaction -- the
``recovery room'' scams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
