<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McPhail's speed could eventually win Johnson over
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Spill all the Miami Dolphins running backs out of the
bag and search for the basic parts of the killer running game Jimmy
Johnson hopes to build. Clearly, some assembly is required.
</P>
<P>
   Karim Abdul-Jabbar is good, for instance, with 15 touchdowns to
his credit last season, but he's not great. Bernie Parmalee is
credible, with six 100-yard rushing games as proof, but he's not
incredible.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie John Avery is sensational, but he's also on the sidelines
with training camp slipping away. Ray Nealy is strong but his
professional resume is weak, barely stretching beyond the practice
squad.
</P>
<P>
   Is there something left at the bottom of the bag? Wait, yes,
it's Jerris McPhail, the fastest man on the team, but whether he
qualifies as anything else is a question Jimmy has been asking
himself since spending a fifth-round draft pick on the East
Carolina curiosity two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Already McPhail has been tried as a kick returner, a third-down
specialty back and, during one wildly experimental stretch of
training camp last month, a full-time wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Johnson is a guy who looks after his talent,'' said
McPhail, returned to the backfield on the day Lawrence Phillips was
cut. ``Any time a coach puts a running back at receiver, you have
to wonder what's going on. But he could easily have put me out the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely that would have happened long ago if not for one play.
Last October, on the simple off-tackle groaner that normally nets
Miami runners a migraine but little else, McPhail shot through the
line for a 71-yard touchdown. It was the third-longest run in Miami
history, just 6 yards short of the record shared by Leroy Harris
and Keith Byars, and it reminded Johnson that the only commodity he
loved more than raw speed during the glorious Dallas years was
speed bought cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not much else is remembered from that game, a 36-33
overtime loss to the previously winless Chicago Bears. What a shame
for McPhail, since nobody else in a Miami uniform popped a run
longer than 22 yards all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   In an offense so mundane, each spark of excitement must be
nurtured and preserved like the last torch in a guano-coated
cavern. That is why I point out to you that McPhail rattled off a
22-yard gain in Saturday's intrasquad scrimmage at the Orange Bowl
and that he produced a stubborn touchdown surge on fourth-and-1 and
that he carried the ball 18 times for 57 yards without injuring a
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   All of these accomplishments, fairly simple at first glance, go
so far beyond the Dolphin norm that you have to ask yourself if
McPhail has been paying attention in team meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, there was a knock on me about being able to read my
blocks,'' McPhail said. ``All that is coming together now. When I
get myself mentally prepared to take the ball on every down, I'll
be untouchable.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's running game may yet be fitted together without this
guy, but Jimmy would have to be a little disappointed by that. What
he wants now from Avery, a game-breaking jolt, he once expected
from McPhail.
</P>
<P>
   Put the spare parts of the Miami running game back into the bag
for now, but don't forget this uncatalogued extra. Something tells
me Jimmy will watch the films of this scrimmage and try again,
twisting McPhail a little tighter, hammering him just a little
harder, bending him to the will of a coach who won two Super Bowls
with speed and won't stop until he does it again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
