<SLUG> BC-HIWAY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet service firm to buy rival for $352 million
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Colorado-based Internet service company Verio
Inc. will acquire buy Hiway Technologies in a stock and cash deal
worth $352.4 million, the companies announced.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is made up of $101 million in cash and 8.67
million shares of Verio common stock, with Hiway shareholders
owning about 19 percent of the combined company on a fully diluted
basis after the deal. Hiway also gets to appoint one member to
Verio's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Hiway hosts more than 90,000 Web sites and employs 275, with 175
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Verio has more than 850 employees, hosting more than 60,000 Web
sites and offering Internet access to 100,000 subscribers, mainly
businesses. In the first quarter, its most recent, Verio lost $28.4
million on sales of $21.2 million. Verio (Nasdaq: VRIO) closed at
$29.12 Thursday, up 12 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   For Verio, the Hiway purchase represents the second acquisition
in two months in Palm Beach County. It bought West Palm Beach-based
Florida Internet Corp., another Internet access provider, for
undisclosed cash in June. Englewood, Col.,-based Verio has bought
more than 30 smaller Internet service providers since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It means that Verio's Northern California operation and Hiway's
Best Internet unit _ also based in Northern California _ will
combine, increasing Verio's regional revenue base by more than 75
percent. Verio also gets Hiway's group of 2,000 resellers for its
service around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy for Verio has been to acquire regional Internet
providers so that they could offer hands-on local service,'' said
Steve Silvers, a Verio spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But the Verio and Hiway deal weds companies that together host
more individually registered Web sites than any other Internet
company.
</P>
<P>
   Verio approached Hiway after it had broken into another facet of
the Internet business _ Web-hosting. So far this year, it has
bought two Web-hosting companies other than Hiway _ TabNet of
California three weeks ago and iServer in Utah in February.
</P>
<P>
   For Hiway, the deal ends the company's plans for an initial
stock offering next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Verio brings to Hiway what it was looking for in the first
place, a national infrastructure and high-speed network. They
needed the ability to grow, national accounting and billing
systems, as well as a national (Internet) backbone,'' Silvers said.
</P>
<P>
   Hiway President Scott Adams said there are no plans for layoffs
and Verio expects to keep Hiway basedin Boca Raton in the Blue Lake
center, where it occupies 72,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything we need diverse locations so we can route our
Internet traffic to another location in case of a earthquake in
California or a hurricane in Florida,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Hiway
</P>
<P>
   Technologies
</P>
<P>
   Business: Internet Web-hosting
</P>
<P>
   Employees: 275
</P>
<P>
   Operations: Boca Raton, Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Net sales: $9.7 million (second quarter, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   Operating income: $1.4 million (second quarter, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-30-98 2322E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
