<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5717 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARIS-RECORD04-COX     08-03 2419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARIS-RECORD04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maris' legacy reborn as three near record
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE _ They are among the millions of baseball fans who
grab the sports page first thing each morning to follow the Great
Home Run Chase of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven years ago their father was involved in a similar
chase when he said: ``Records are made to be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Roger Maris Jr., the second of six children in the
Maris family of Gainesville, said: ``My family doesn't want to see
Dad's record broken.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marises have been saying that for years, well before Roger
Maris died of cancer in 1985. Now, however, they see the increasing
vulnerability of his record _ 61 home runs in 1961. It's right
there in fine print every time they open the Gainesville Sun to
check Dad's progress in the Chasing Roger Maris Chart.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what they saw Saturday morning: After 108 games, Mark
McGwire _ 45 home runs, Ken Griffey Jr. _ 41 home runs, Sammy Sosa
_ 42 home runs (after 110 games). Roger Maris _ 41 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean we'd have any ill-feeling toward anyone,''
Roger Maris Jr., 39, continued. ``Dad was proud of that record. We
definitely want him to keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after everything he went through to get it. The
Marises remember the stigma he carried to his grave for achieving
what many baseball fans in 1961 hoped would never be accomplished.
The newspaper's chart doesn't mention any of that.
</P>
<P>
   But Maris' family _ his widow Pat and his brother Rudy and his
mother Connie and his six kids _ and all his old golfing buddies
see it as clearly as the black-and-white photograph of his 61st
home-run swing that frames the chart.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Maris sees the strangers who used to show up on her doorstep
in Kansas City, hoping for a peek of the porcupine-topped New York
Yankee who had sneaked home in late August 1961 to hold his infant
son Randy for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   She sees the patches of skin on the back of her husband's head
where his crewcut was falling out, a reaction to the stress the
26-year-old slugger felt as he closed in on what was then
considered the most sacrosanct of baseball records _ Babe Ruth's 60
home runs in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   Maris' four sons, who have their dad's eyes and chin, were
either too young to remember 1961 or born later. But they remember
how the chase followed their dad to Gainesville, where he moved
after retiring in 1968. Their parents' red-brick house (with a
staircase bannister spoked with baseball bats) overlooks the
seventh green of the Gainesville Golf and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Maris, who coaches a baseball team that plays at Roger
Maris Field, hears his dad on the links as he prepares to sink a
4-foot putt: ``Pressure? I don't know the word.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Maris, an amateur golfer born Aug.21, 1961 (``No home runs
that day''), has studied the old newsreels from that summer. He
sees the reporters around Dad's locker asking questions like, ``Do
you cheat on your wife?''
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Roger Maris Jr. hear the frustration in their dad's
voice as he chats with friends about his stormy relationship with
the New York media, how he thinks it probably denied him what he
always felt was his rightful spot in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 13 years after his death _ with his picture in the paper
every morning and the reporters calling to ask about him every day
and his name mentioned on TV every night _ it's as if Roger Maris
is alive again.
</P>
<P>
   It's like 1961 all over again. Only this time he and Mickey
Mantle aren't chasing Babe Ruth. This time he's being chased by
McGwire, Griffey and Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, the underdog is Roger Maris. It says so right
there in the chart, where Griffey is on a pace to tie, Sosa is on a
pace to beat, and McGwire on a pace to shatter Maris' mark, a
record he held longer than the mighty Babe did.
</P>
<P>
   But it's August now. And Randy Maris knows, ``Dad hit quite a
few home runs at the end of the year.'' He sounds as if he's
certain of the outcome when he says, ``Dad's going to catch up here
pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what he's hoping.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after his father died, Randy Maris met Mark McGwire at
a baseball card show in Orlando. Randy was shopping for memorabilia
to stock the Roger Maris Museum, which is a 70-foot-long display
case next to a pet shop at the West Acres mall in his father's
hometown of Fargo, N.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organizer heard who I was and introduced us,'' Randy Maris
said. McGwire, who hit 49 home runs the year before as a rookie for
the Oakland A's, was at a table signing autographs. ``He drops what
he's doing and comes over and shakes my hand ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't remember what we talked about. Real low-key
small talk. But he was a real classy guy.''
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire complained two months ago that he felt ``like a
caged animal'' because of the reporters who surrounded him during
batting practice, Randy Maris knew exactly what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's team, the St. Louis Cardinals, responded immediately
by limiting access to the slugger. Among the restrictions: all
pre-game interview requests at home must be arranged in advance;
he's available for 30 minutes starting 3 1/2 hours before the first
game only of each road series; and no live-shot TV interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees never did anything like that for my dad,'' Randy
said. ``He would sit at his locker and there would be throngs of
reporters. Then another wave would come in and they'd ask the same
exact questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Maris said her husband ``was probably the guinea pig with
reporters not knowing what questions to ask. I know it used to
upset him when he'd come to his locker and they'd ask him about
`this' home run. They had such a good team at the time and he felt
like the attention should be going to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a reporter asked Maris how the pressure was affecting his
sex life with his wife. ``You,'' Maris replied, rising from his
stool and pointing at the reporter, ``have exactly 10 seconds to
get out of the clubhouse alive!''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, he blew off an interviewer so he could visit a
child in a hospital. ``The writer slammed him the next day, saying
Dad was `unconscionable' and `inconsiderate.' But when the writer
found out where Dad had been, there wasn't anything in the paper,''
Randy Maris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dad was very blunt and he was very honest. The reporters
didn't like that. He was in the New York media market and everybody
wanted Mickey Mantle to break the record.''
</P>
<P>
   After Maris hit No.59, Oliver Keuchle wrote in the Milwaukee
Journal: ``If the record is to be broken, it should be done by
someone with greater stature and public appeal ... Maris is
colorless ... There just isn't anything deeply heroic about the
man.''
</P>
<P>
   That portrayal reflected the thinking of baseball's pro-Ruth
commissioner at the time _ Ford Frick, Ruth's friend and
ghostwriter. On July17, 1961, Frick decided that since the Babe's
record of 60 was set during a 154-game season, Maris would have to
break the record in 154 games _ even though the season had been
expanded that year to 162 games.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling became known as ``the asterisk,'' which was not
removed until 1992. It would symbolize the stigma that would follow
Maris forever.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris and the asterisk became one in the fourth inning of
the last game of the season, when he launched a 2-0 pitch from Red
Sox right-hander Tracy Stallard into Yankee Stadium's right-field
porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran those bases with his head down,'' Randy Maris said.
``Dad didn't want to show up Babe Ruth. He had respect for the
record. He ran straight to the dugout. And when he got there (his
teammates) had to push him out so he could take a curtain call.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Oct.1, 1961. Exactly two years to the day later, Mark
McGwire was born.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris arrived in Gainesville in the fall of 1968. ``I
think it was a Wednesday,'' said retired banker John Jennings Sr.
He was among the first in town to meet the famous Yankee slugger
and his brother Rudy after they had arrived at Gainesville Regional
Airport on the private plane of beer baron August Busch Jr.
</P>
<P>
   As the story passed around town goes, Maris and Busch, who owned
the St. Louis Cardinals, struck an informal bargain during the
Cardinals' clubhouse celebration after their 1967 pennant victory.
</P>
<P>
   Play for the Cardinals one more year, Busch is said to have told
Maris (whom the Yankees had traded to St. Louis after the 1966
season), and I'll give you a beer distributorship.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 1968, after Maris took his final swing in the
Cardinals' World Series loss to the Detroit Tigers, the owner of
the Tampa distributorship had died. That triggered a domino effect
in Anheuser-Busch's Florida operations.
</P>
<P>
   One of those dominos landed Maris in Gainesville, where the
Maris family still lives in near-anonymity among the thousands of
football fans in Gator country. (Today, the Maris distributorship
remains closed while the family battles Anheuser-Busch in court for
control of it.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved the quiet town. He could just be Roger,'' said Azey
Stephens, a Fort Lauderdale distributor who worked and golfed with
Maris.
</P>
<P>
   He kept his familiar crew cut. He ran Maris Distributing from a
warehouse. He drove a white Mercedes. In the side pouch of the
front door, he kept a stack of photographs of his 61st home-run
swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really hounded for autographs,'' Stephens recalled.
``We would be eating breakfast and people would come up to him and
say, `I saw you hit that home run.' But I never saw him turn anyone
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris Field at Oak Hall, the private school that Maris'
kids attended, was built in 1977 _ thanks to a quiet deal Maris cut
with Yankees owner George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Maris held a grudge against the Yankees for the way
he was treated. He rejected annual invitations from the
organization to participate in Old-Timers games at Yankee Stadium.
Not long after Steinbrenner purchased the club, the new owner was
able to persuade Maris to pull on No.9 again. The Yankees retired
his number in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Steinbrenner's name can be found in the school lobby, on
a plaque that says ``$25,000 subscriber.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, who didn't return phone calls for this article,
once said, ``To me, Roger Maris was one of the greatest Yankees of
all time. Roger was a most misunderstood young man. In my mind, the
Yankees treated him shabbily.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the Gainesville links, Maris is remembered for his deft
play and practical jokes. The one locals talk about most was pulled
on Billy Martin, the late Yankees manager who came to town just
after making headlines for a fight with a marshmallow salesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the second tee,'' recalled Paul Costello, a golfing
chum, ``and a guy from the pro shop drives up in a cart. `Package
for you, Mr. Martin.' Billy opens it up ... and it's a bag of
marshmallows!''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs as if the joke has just been pulled. ``Billy chases
Roger all the way down the fairway. Roger fell down laughing and
Billy fell down laughing on top of him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for ``the 61,'' Maris' golfing buddies say they never asked.
Once in a while, Maris would volunteer an anecdote. ``I was
diagnosed with cancer before he was,'' Jennings said. ``And when my
hair started falling out, he said, `My hair fell out, too, once.'''
</P>
<P>
   In November 1983, Maris visited a doctor because of a nagging
sinus problem. It turned out to be lymphoma. After fighting the
cancer with experimental treatments at the M.D. Anderson Hospital
and Tumor Institute in Houston, he spent his final summer at a
house the family owns on a lake outside of Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1985, the same month Maris was buried in Fargo, the
Baseball Dugout opened across the street from the Holiday Inn where
Maris first lived when he came to Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Maris' 1958 rookie card can be bought there today for $425.
That's $315 more than the hottest card on the market _ McGwire's
1987 rookie card. ``Everybody wants the McGwire rookie card because
everyone thinks he's going to break the record,'' said owner Chris
Rodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while someone will ask for a Maris card. But
most of the college kids here have never heard of him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug.16, 1961, Maris hit his 47th and 48th home runs at Yankee
Stadium. It was Babe Ruth Day to commemorate the 13th anniversary
of Ruth's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Ruth had been at the game,'' Maris recalled in his 1962
book Roger Maris At Bat. ``She had been asked what she thought of
the possibility that Babe's record might be broken. She had been
completely honest when she replied: `I don't want to see it broken.
These are two nice boys and they are Yankees, but I don't want to
see either of them erase the record.'''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Maris' widow, who met her husband at a high school
basketball game in Fargo, sounded just like him when she said:
``Naturally, records are made to be broken. And I'm sure it's going
to come down to that. You've got some good hitters out there
between McGwire and Griffey and Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've been through this before,'' she continued, alluding
to other failed chases over the last 37 years. ``We've still got a
little bit of time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he died, Roger Maris managed to get into the Baseball
Hall of Fame: He donated the bat and ball that produced home run
No.61. Today they are the only two items representing Maris in
Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   When Kevin Maris talks about the chase, he is reminded of
another legendary milestone that fell recently. He was watching TV
that night in 1995 when Cal Ripken Jr. broke the Iron Man record of
2,130 consecutive games played by Lou Gehrig, Babe Ruth's teammate.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the outpouring of emotion at Camden Yards when the
game was stopped and Ripken walked the grandstand railings during a
22-minute standing ovation, shaking just about every hand in the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to see him appreciated the way Cal
Ripken was ... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad brought a lot of fans to the game, just like McGwire
has brought a lot of fans to the game. I mean, even if you don't
like baseball you can't help but watch the home-run race,' said
Kevin Maris, who with brother Richard met McGwire on Saturday in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Dad would have definitely appreciated watching McGwire
go for it. I'll tell you one thing for sure: I know he's up there
watching it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
