<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ECONOMY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't bet budget surplus on dry farms, lawmakers warn
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ With sales tax revenues soaring, interests are coming
out of the woodwork to spend an unprecedented budget surplus
expected to top $6 billion by the time the Texas Legislature goes
back to work in January.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some lawmakers are warning against moving too quickly to
spend the money in light of a drought they say can dry up the Texas
economy as surely as it is searing Texas farmlands.
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged drought is hurting Texas' farming and ranching
industry. President Clinton last week declared the entire state a
disaster area. Sen. Bill Ratliff, chairman of the budget-writing
Senate Finance Committee, said this week he will hold hearings soon
to tally the financial damage. And Agriculture Commissioner Rick
Perry has crisscrossed the state, forecasting losses totaling $4.5
billion that he said could severely hurt Texas' booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas economists say they doubt the drought will
significantly affect the state's $641 billion economy because
agriculture makes up 1 percent of the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the sky is not falling,'' said Bernard Weinstein, director
of the Center for Economic Development at the University of North
Texas. ``Unless it (drought) lasts for several years, it won't have
a significant impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic impact largely will be felt by farmers and
businesses directly related to agriculture, said Thomas Saving,
director of the Private Enterprise Research Center at Texas A&AMP;M
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a tractor dealer somewhere in Texas, you're not a
happy camper,'' Saving said. ``You won't even notice it in
Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by a half-dozen other Texas
economists. They said the state's economy is more threatened by the
Asian financial market than the relentless heat and lack of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful thing about the growth in the '90s is it isn't
tied to a single-sector industry,'' said Jared Hazelton, director
of the Center for Business and Economic Analysis at Texas A&AMP;M
University. ``There is no dominant industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture once played a pivotal role in the state economy.
That changed as Texas shifted from a state reliant on natural
resources _ farming and ranching, forests, oil and gas _ to human
resources. Farming and ranching makes up 1 percent of the Texas
economy this year, according to the Texas Department of Economic
Development, which cited figures developed by the state
comptroller's office. That's down from 2.2 percent in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   When related businesses are accounted for, farming and ranching
account for as much as 7 percent of the Texas economy, according to
the state Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   But to hear some politicians tell it, the state economy and the
budget surplus _ if not the sky _ is falling fast in the wake of a
drought that is devastating Texas farmers and ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Perry said, ``There is no doubt that the relentless
heat and lack of rain are not only drying up our crops and our
pastureland, it's drying up the Texas economy.''
</P>
<P>
   No relief, he said, could mean no crops. ``If that occurs,'' he
said, ``we've got major, major economic problems all over the State
of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Perry's campaign spokesman Ray Sullivan clarified those
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he (Perry) was referring to was the impact on smaller and
more rural agriculture-heavy communities in Texas as opposed to the
Texas economy as a whole,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he (Perry) was saying is: Should this drought continue
and should agriculture continue to be hard-hit, the smaller more
rural communities in Texas that rely more heavily on agriculture to
keep their local economies going will be hard-hit.''
</P>
<P>
   If political posturing is high on the issue, it is because the
political stakes are equally high.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, the Republican nominee for lieutenant governor, earlier
this year lost a key endorsement by the Texas Farm Bureau AgFund to
his Democratic opponent, State Comptroller John Sharp. Beating the
drum for farmers no doubt has boosted Perry's posture with farmers
and with a public that still romanticizes farmers despite their
relatively small numbers. They make up less than 2 percent of the
Texas population.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the projected $6.3 billion surplus Sharp predicted
last month? He based the figure on an estimated $3.7 billion
unanticipated sales tax revenue currently on hand, plus another
$2.6 billion by January.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, on Thursday urged teachers'
organizations, which have designs on the surplus for a pay raise,
and others to put the brakes on spending the unprecedented windfall
in light of the drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody ought to calm down so far as this idea that
we might have $6 billion,'' Ratliff said. ``I think we ought to see
if whether after the agriculture industry in Texas has a complete
disaster, whether or not the economy of Texas is going spin off
that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and spend the money, economists say. The surplus is
safe because agriculture losses already have been factored into
Sharp's revenue estimates, said Clyde Walter, a spokesman Sharp.
That the Texas economy as a whole won't be significantly rocked by
the 1998 drought does not mean some areas of the state won't
suffer, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas economy is booming, but we have this one segment of
the Texas economy that is going to be facing significant losses
while the rest of the economy is doing very well,'' said Roland
Smith, economist for the Texas Agricultural Extension Office at
Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-01-98 0022E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
