<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM strike hit employees harder than area economy
 &HT;    By Kristi E. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The most expensive strike in General Motors Corp.'s
history cost the automaker more than $2 billion, slowed the entire
nation's economic output and disrupted the finances for about
200,000 workers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   While the nearly 4,000 workers at GM's Doraville minivan plant
went without a paycheck for about six weeks, the strike's effect on
metro Atlanta's economy was more like a pothole on a busy highway.
</P>
<P>
   Things are just starting to return to normal. Vehicles have been
in the pipeline to dealerships since GM and the United Auto Workers
settled their disputes last Tuesday. Doraville's administrative
employees and maintenance workers went back on the job the next
morning. Parts will be reaching Doraville on Monday, when the two
shifts of assembly line workers come back to the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The strike, with its epicenter in Flint, Mich., had shock waves
felt nationwide. Parts suppliers laid off workers, GM dealerships
saw their inventory and sales shrink, and suddenly out-of-work
employees had to scrape by on unemployment checks.
</P>
<P>
   But in metro Atlanta, the effect wasn't as pronounced as it was
in other parts of the country. For example, the Doraville assembly
plant doesn't even make the list of the area's top 25 employers.
And only about 10 percent of the metro area's 2 million jobs are in
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing to remember is that GM's employment is still a small
part of the portion of (manufacturing in) metro Atlanta,'' said
Roger Tutterow, co-director of Kennesaw State University's
Econometric Center.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the area's economy took a hit. The lost income
from Doraville workers ``cost the area a couple of million dollars
in buying power.''
</P>
<P>
   Local companies said they saw dwindling business but not to an
extreme level.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Knight, manager of Oga's Restaurant on Peachtree
Industrial Boulevard near the Doraville plant, said there was a
slight drop in business, but that it's picked up already since
salaried and maintenance workers began heading back to work last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Peachtree Industrial also is lined with car dealerships -- Audi,
Mazda, Ford, as well as three that sell GM cars. Most dealerships
keep a 60- to 90-day supply of vehicles on the lot, and dealership
managers such as Glen Evans of McNamara Pontiac are looking forward
to receiving new cars in about 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Many were down to a 20-day supply, with some of the more popular
vehicles in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   The Doraville workers were forced off the job because of a lack
of parts from the striking Flint plants needed to build its
Chevrolet Venture, Oldsmobile Silhouette, Pontiac Trans Sport and
Opel Sintra minivans.
</P>
<P>
   Autoworkers like 22-year GM veteran Tina Jackson learned long
ago they need to save money for possible strikes and layoffs. She
said after being laid off in the early '80s, she had to do things
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swore I'd never be in that condition again; I swore I'd
never be a poor rat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who spent all but this past year of her career in a
three-shift, 380-worker parts plant in Michigan, said she was
prepared this time and spent her time off traveling and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Ronald, works for Pillsbury Corp., and together
they support her 10-year-old niece, Amber. Jackson said she spent
$1,600, and ``all the money came from me, (but) my husband wants me
to go back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But other workers were hurt financially by the downtime.
</P>
<P>
   George White Jr. almost got evicted from his $680-a-month
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin N. White Sr., no relation, hopes one last unemployment
check will arrive so he can pay his electric bill. He's lost his
cable service and can't repair his broken-down car.
</P>
<P>
   Purvis Patterson spent his time frugally, frequenting the movies
and taking his daughter to Stone Mountain. He had saved some money,
but he was not making any major expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Doraville workers could file for unemployment benefits starting
June 25 with a maximum payment of $224 a week. The Georgia
Department of Labor issued 3,600 checks to union and salaried
employees starting the following week, said department spokesman
Sam Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Even though workers are heading back to work, their financial
problems may not be completely over. GM has challenged benefits
payments. If it wins its case, workers could be forced to repay the
money they received.
</P>
<P>
   and are not part of general tax revenues to the state. Being
back on the job at Doraville also means being back on the job at
other plants supplying parts for GM autos, including several
hundred workers at Johnson Controls' Suwanee car-seat plant.
</P>
<P>
   Outsourcing -- sending work to other companies, often nonunion,
to save money and increase efficiency -- was a key issue in the
strikes in Flint and is a continuing sore point between the
automaker and the union.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
