<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ernest Holsendolph's Business Commentary: Trust of GM hangs in
balance at Saturn
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It was back in 1983, I think, when I interviewed
Roger Smith, then the boss of General Motors. Or what passed as
boss at GM. Here is what raised some doubts:
</P>
<P>
   I remarked to Smith what a pleasant surprise for General Motors,
to have the splashy success of the sporty little Pontiac Fiero. It
was a wonderful GM story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, isn't it wonderful,'' said Smith. ``I just wish I could
get those guys down at Pontiac to make more of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's what he said. In other words, the chairman and chief
executive of General Motors was reduced to pleading with a division
to step up production, but was refused and had to shrug it off.
</P>
<P>
   It was clogged arteries of that kind that persuaded Roger Smith
and others it was time for an experiment, an attempt to show the
world -- and GM management, that there was a way to do business
differently. A way to be a responsive auto manufacturer. And thus
was born the idea of Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment, which finally took shape in the '90s, has been a
success. Saturn has been ``a different kind of car company,'' as
its marketing slogan suggests. Operating separately from the GM
structure, it has produced a plant in Spring Hill, Tenn., that has
been an American model of management and worker cooperation, with
the workers having a significant say in how things got done.
</P>
<P>
   Incentives and profit-sharing have helped the workers share
financially in the success of the Saturn product.
</P>
<P>
   And Saturn customers like me have fallen in love with the Saturn
style of customer relations -- the no-hassle car purchase, a
careful and caring vehicle service policy, friendly continued
contact with the company, and dealer involvement with the community
and the customers.
</P>
<P>
   It is because a lot of people care about Saturn, almost to the
point of feeling possessive, that made me very interested in labor
troubles that have the small company on the brink of its first
labor strike.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Smith is gone now, and there is evidence elements of the
powerful GM bureaucracy may want to see Saturn brought in from the
warm and friendly world it has created.
</P>
<P>
   Some steps already have intruded on the little Spring Hill
family.
</P>
<P>
   The use of outside components and parts seems to threaten the
job security, part of the fabric of the early Saturn operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customer could care less where we get our McPherson struts
or door hinges as long as it doesn't change the buyer's ownership
experience,'' a GM official told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   I talked with David Ott, general manager of Saturn of Decatur,
about the changing atmosphere as seen from the dealer's level. Ott,
on Thursday, was just returning from a dedication ceremony for a
youth park his store and Saturn of Southlake had built in the
Edgewood community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, this whole topic was what we talked about
most at the annual dealers' meeting late last month in San
Antonio,'' Ott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there is a new plant, a second plant, in Wilmington,
Del., and so operations are no longer just in Spring Hill...
</P>
<P>
   ``And yes, some parts will now come from Europe and other places
if such purchases can help us produce quality products at the right
cost. I firmly believe that the new integration of systems will
benefit Saturn and help us be more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   But how will this change affect the Saturn mystique, style and
marketing -- especially if it is accompanied by labor strife?
</P>
<P>
   ``One GM official after another assured us that Saturn remains
General Motors' best hope of change,'' Ott said. ``They let us know
that it would be corporate craziness to turn our backs on the one
thing that is new and has been exciting at General Motors. They let
us know that, in order to protect what Saturn has become, the
company will never become another GM division. It will always be
like a subsidiary.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Saturn and the customers are concerned, there will
continue to be community projects, Ott said. And those evening
sessions at Saturn of Decatur, where car owners are invited to
spend time in the service shop learning how to do maintenance of
their own and getting to know the experts who care for the cars.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of thing that makes you hope enough civility
remains in the talks between GM and the Saturn UAW to have frank
discussions and an equitable new agreement that restores an element
of trust in Spring Hill. Now that the strike in Michigan has been
settled, GM can focus on Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   Trust always seemed to be the pin that held together Saturn, its
production lines, car dealers and customers.
</P>
<P>
   Trust is a terrible thing to waste, especially with so much good
will hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
