<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5728 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPS-FUTURE04-COX     08-03 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-FUTURE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New units will outshine U.S. package delivery at UPS
 &HT;    with UPS lessons
 &HT;    By Cynthia Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As UPS Vice Chairman John Alden likes to put it, unless and
until scientists figure a way to beam packages from place to place,
UPS will surely always deliver them.
</P>
<P>
   But even now, the chief of long-term business development says
its U.S. package delivery business -- making up more than 80
percent of UPS' $22.5 billion in revenue -- isn't the key to the
company's future.
</P>
<P>
   That lies in UPS Worldwide Logistics Group, which manages the
so-called supply chain for big manufacturers such as Allied Signal
Corp. and adidas. And its international operations, which now serve
219 foreign airports, are finally profitable after $9 billion in
investment and years of patience.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that so-called e-commerce, such as UPS Document Exchange,
which uses the Internet to transmit securely coded documents. And
UPS is using its links to customers' inventories to step into such
services as financing and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This comes from trying to look at where the industry and the
business world are going,'' Alden said. ``The last thing we want in
this business is to become a commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the U.S. package delivery business, where margins are
razor thin and archrival Federal Express has merged with
ground-based package service RPS, that's not likely to happen:
</P>
<P>
   -- In a room inside a UPS warehouse in Louisville, Ky., rows of
technicians repair Gateway 2000 computers. Nearby, the computers'
shells are repainted to look new. While UPS rents the space to a
computer repair company, the relationship is part of a deal in
which Gateway customers send their faulty computers straight to
Louisville, and UPS returns them within days. Thanks to such
innovative arrangements, the Logistics Group's revenue reached $598
million last year, and logistics chief Dan DiMaggio projects it
will reach $900 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   -- During the disastrous opening of Hong Kong's new airport July
8, the airport's computer system crashed, but the one running UPS'
new air hub worked fine. While thousands of containers of cargo
stacked up at the airport, UPS diverted planes from the United
States and operated 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The government asked the company to bail out eight to 10 other
airlines that couldn't process their shipments, said international
chief Ron Wallace, who feels sure many of those customers will wind
up sticking with UPS. Since the crisis, UPS' shipments out of Hong
Kong soared 260 percent. In the first quarter, the unit posted
operating profit of $34.5 million, up from a $31 million loss, and
Wallace expects profitability to continue.
</P>
<P>
   -- On the Internet, the UPS Document Exchange will likely
cannibalize its own overnight letter service. But the company
figures it's better to eat oneself than let somebody else do the
eating. Just launched in June, the company says it's too early to
estimate revenues, but tech marketing manager Dave Ladner says the
opportunity is ``enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Meanwhile, UPS' move into financing and insuring companies'
inventories also won't materialize immediately. But Alden said UPS
is currently testing customer acceptance, and next year, the
company will launch initial tests with two major companies, which
it won't disclose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
