<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5729 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPS-LESSONS04-COX     08-03 2507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-LESSONS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Critics say UPS hasn't improved in its communications and
relations with workers after Teamsters strike
 &HT;    By Cynthia Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- In the year since 185,000 striking Teamsters refused
to sort and deliver truckloads of packages for United Parcel
Service, the company has made its storied ``tightest ship in the
shipping business'' even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   For shareholders, UPS has wrung out every unnecessary dime to
make back the $1 billion in revenue it lost during and after those
15 days last August, posting record profits in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It wooed back its 1.6 million daily business customers with no
less zeal -- calling, visiting, providing incentives, introducing
new services.
</P>
<P>
   But what about those hourly workers? The strikers, whose plea
for more full-time jobs won the battle for public opinion? UPS has
labeled their strike ``irresponsible'' and has told them they need
to put it behind them and focus on customers.
</P>
<P>
   The union that represents those employees? UPS has all but spit
in its eye, continuing to blame former Teamsters President Ron
Carey, who has since been banned forever from the union because of
an illegal campaign financing scheme. And last month, UPS notified
the Teamsters it was moving to nullify its agreement to create
2,000 new full-time jobs this year out of existing part-time
positions, because it's carrying 4 percent fewer packages and now
employs 16,000 fewer people than it did before the strike, some of
whom it says have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
   So on Friday, Teamsters once again toted picket signs and yelled
into bullhorns at parking lot rallies across the country, accusing
the company of reneging on its deal. The dispute raises the
question of whether UPS has learned the hardest and most important
lessons from that billion-dollar textbook laid out before it last
summer:
</P>
<P>
   -- That the notorious loyalty of the company's public
ambassadors, those drivers who deliver the packages, isn't as deep
as it once was -- and may not exist at all in the company's growing
part-time ranks.
</P>
<P>
   -- That it can't afford to underestimate the degree to which the
Teamsters have united employees against the company -- and that a
continued rocky relationship with the union may only strengthen
customers' resolve to never again rely on UPS to the degree they
did before the strike.
</P>
<P>
   -- That how the company communicates with all of its
constituents -- from employees to the public -- isn't a side issue,
but plays a critical role in whether UPS achieves all of its
business goals.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in crisis management, communications and labor relations
firmly believe that if UPS had understood those hard-to-face
realities in the year leading up to last summer's contract
deadline, the company would not have had to endure the strike in
the first place. And they believe the company wouldn't still be
battling the Teamsters -- much less in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm astounded. Do they not understand the game that's being
played?'' said Larry Smith, a consultant with Louisville, Ky.-based
International Crisis Management. ``This is not a matter of being a
little bit pregnant. If you've got relationship problems with your
employees or customers, you need to go all the way to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just step back and hope they'll go away,'' Smith
added. ``If you don't mend your fences and repair your
relationships and get those employees feeling good about coming to
work every day, that could come back and bite you big time.''
</P>
<P>
   And repairing those relationships involves ``communication,
communication, communication,'' says Atlanta attorney Howard
Maverty, who advises corporations on how to deal with labor unions.
``If you've got labor relations or employee problems of any sort,
generally you're going to find it was caused by a breakdown in
communication.''
</P>
<P>
   But the way UPS sees it, no major surgery is needed because last
summer's strike didn't reflect any fundamental problems at the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people had nothing to do with the strike. Their voice was
never heard. It was caused by the union leadership,'' said UPS
Chairman Jim Kelly in an interview earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   What's happened to Carey since, they argue, just proves he's the
culprit. Within days of the strike's settlement last August,
Carey's re-election as Teamsters president was overturned because
of a scheme to funnel Teamsters money into Carey's own campaign
coffers. The federal election overseer later barred Carey from
running again, and last week Carey was barred from the union for
life. Carey has continued to deny any knowledge of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone back and revisited everything from labor relations,
public relations and communications with our people and
shareholders and (looked at) how well we did everything,'' Kelly
said. ``There's always room for improvement, but given the same set
of circumstances, I don't know what could have been done to prevent
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also points to how quickly it's bounced back.
``We're doing as well as we've ever done financially,'' said UPS'
top spokesman, Ken Sternad. ``The first quarter was our best ever,
and there's every reason to believe the second is also very, very
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And where are the Teamsters today? Where are they? Who's
running them? What's their balance sheet look like? What are they
doing for their people? What are their lessons learned?'' Sternad
demanded angrily. ``Our lesson learned is we could do a few
cosmetic things PR-wise, which are important to our image. And it
certainly reinforced the value of communicating internally, of our
strong internal communications program -- all those things. Lessons
learned is we made a lot of good decisions for the long-term, best
interest of UPS.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Sandy Springs-based delivery giant, the stakes remain
high -- just as they were before last summer's showdown. Like it or
not, the Teamsters represent about two-thirds of its U.S. work
force. Those workers are the muscle behind most of its $22.5
billion a year in annual revenue -- as well as the company's
all-important link to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   And given the pain and money the strike cost customers, they're
likely to be much more easily spooked by any sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to have continual conflict, should I as a
customer use this service?'' asks David Weil, a labor relations
professor at Boston University, who thinks the answer will be no.
``You know what they say -- fool me once, shame on you, fool me
twice, shame on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, any effort UPS spends fighting the union takes time
and money away from its hot new growth areas -- logistics services,
international operations and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't concentrate on improving the business and fighting
the union at the same time,'' says Harley Shaiken, a labor
relations professor with the University of California at Berkeley.
``Workers are likely to be less willing to cooperate in any new
endeavor they might want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS also faces two class-action race discrimination suits -- a
sign its employee problems go deeper than its relationship with the
union. One of the cases, a glass ceiling suit filed by black
midlevel managers, has the backing of the federal Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission and is headed for trial.
</P>
<P>
   The other case, which claims black hourly workers are harassed
and consistently get the worst assignments, isn't yet certified.
But it's backed by the NAACP, and the media-savvy president of the
Oakland, Calif., chapter has already staged public events to
pillory UPS and air the plaintiffs' claims. At the least, the cases
make it imperative, PR consultants say, that UPS get better at
anticipating and planning for the potential mines that could erupt,
a la Texaco. If it doesn't, the company could find its reputation
once again being chewed up in the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   All told, UPS' experience provides lessons in employee
relations, communications and crisis management for companies in
any industry -- unionized or not, making widgets or delivering
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS has been, from start to finish, a case study in what not
to do,'' says Robert Dilenschneider, a communications consultant
for companies that operate in politically charged environments.
</P>
<P>
   To those who understand UPS' history and corporate culture, it's
not surprising the company was caught off guard when the Teamsters
turned up the heat last July.
</P>
<P>
   In the 90 years since founder Jim Casey first started delivering
messages on his bike in Seattle, UPS had built a history of
employee loyalty. The way he saw it, those employees were the
bedrock of the company's success -- and they deserved to be treated
like it. Casey actually invited the union to represent his workers
in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   And after that, UPS won favorable and flexible contracts. It got
the green light to start using part-timers in 1962 and didn't have
to raise their starting wage from $8 an hour from 1982 until last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Casey also instilled the company with modesty; it didn't even
have much of a marketing department until the 1980s and didn't have
more than a few public relations people on staff until the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   So as last year's contract negotiations approached, UPS never
dreamed its drivers -- who made $50,000 a year with another $20,000
in benefits, the best in the industry -- would let the company and
its customers down. It also assumed the part-timers couldn't have
much of a beef, either, given UPS paid them full-time benefits,
including pensions.
</P>
<P>
   And while UPS and the Teamsters often had a testy time at the
negotiating table, they always worked it out. At the worst, the
Teamsters would agree to extend the contract and keep bargaining,
or put it out to a vote, at which point if the membership rejected
it, they'd bargain some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't anticipate a strike,'' said Kelly, who himself had
been at the bargaining table for UPS since 1976. ``There was no
logical reason for one to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   But UPS' view of logic and reason didn't necessarily jibe with
what was going on in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1980s, longtime employees say increasingly stringent time
standards started to take precedence over Casey's golden rule of
how to treat employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I started, I always heard it was a real pro-employee
place to work,'' said Robby Hales, a driver based in Rome since
1986 and one of the few who will let his name be used, since many
fear retribution. ``But as profits went up, I guess they've seen
more chances to make even more profits. Since I started back then,
all I've really seen is immense pressure. ... It don't matter how
much you do or how well you work, it's always never good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many drivers, including Hales, are still proud of
steering UPS' trademark boxy brown trucks and wearing their
starched brown shirts. But now, they say it's got a lot more to do
with serving their customers -- many of whom they consider friends
because of their daily contact-- not any allegiance to the
corporation or its managers.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers across Georgia, for instance, have been dismayed about
UPS' strict enforcement of what's known as the ``rural remote''
policy. Rather than deliver a package to a rural area when it
arrived, they were forced to wait a few days to accumulate more of
them, thus making the trip more profitable and cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``l feel like we're cheating the customers,'' said driver Bart
Johnston, whose daily route traverses sparsely populated Eckles
County in South Georgia. He cited several customers whose packages
got pulled from his truck because of the remote policy -- including
a woman waiting on her wedding dress. His loyalty, he said, is
``not to the company; it's to my customers.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the union is right on the money in arguing UPS' 4
percent volume decline and any resulting layoffs have to do with
the remote policy and pushing workers harder.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UPS did more to make it clear it no longer viewed
itself and the unionized employees as being on the same team.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, just a year after a major contract negotiation with the
Teamsters, UPS announced it would more than double the weight of
packages the drivers would deliver, to 150 pounds from 70.
Employees felt betrayed; the union was outraged. No way, Carey
argued, did UPS not know of the plan during negotiations. And even
if it was a brand-new idea, he insisted the contract barred UPS
from unilaterally instituting the policy without the Teamsters'
consent.
</P>
<P>
   UPS rushed to federal court and got a restraining order barring
the Teamsters from striking until the issue had been through
arbitration. But Carey called a one-day walkout anyway, persuading
40 percent of the hourly workers to stay home. UPS and the
Teamsters then hammered out policies to minimize the risk of
handling the packages, known as ``over 70s.''
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters watchers figure UPS misread the turnout as a sign the
rank and file would never fully support Carey. He'd entered office
in 1991 as the man who would clean up the Teamsters' mob-riddled
past, and had spent three years forcing union locals into
trusteeship, stripping the ``old guard'' of their perks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran into a snake pit in terms of the cooperation from the
local unions,'' said Rand Wilson, a Carey campaign volunteer in
Boston who was tapped in 1995 for a key communications post at
union headquarters. ``That really influenced his thinking about how
national negotiations would need to be approached, given the lack
of cooperation he was getting.''
</P>
<P>
   So more than a year before the UPS contract expired July 31,
1997, Carey started appealing straight to the rank and file. And he
figured out how to unite the seemingly disparate needs of full-time
drivers making $50,000 a year and part-time sorters making $8 an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Mathematics required it. Since 1962, the percentage of
part-timers in UPS' unionized work force had swelled to about 60
percent. And more than 80 percent of the new unionized jobs created
since the previous contract in 1993 had been part-time positions.
</P>
<P>
   Management needs ``to see that part-timers are informed and
involved as well,'' Carey explained in an October 1996 newsletter.
``They need to see part-timers wearing buttons, passing out
leaflets, coming to meetings and getting organized.''
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters' education staff fanned out across the country,
showing members how to set up communications networks and talk up
the issues. Videos, newsletters and Teamsters magazines featured
UPS part-timers stressing how their issues affected full-timers,
and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could start a school on what the Teamsters did right
regarding preparing their membership,'' said John Stamm, a labor
relations professor at Babson College in Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-98 2307E
</P>
