<HEADER>
A5732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLSTREET04-COX     08-03 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall Street: August makes for a great time to be optimistic
about the market
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- August is to stock market bulls what October is to
bears.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average hit last year's peak of
8,259.31 in August.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the Dow peaked at 2,722.40 in August -- and crashed two
months later.
</P>
<P>
   August 1982 was also important for bulls but for a different
reason.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of the longest, strongest super-bull market
in history -- one that shows no sign of ending soon. Market
historians date the super bull from Aug. 12, 1982, when the Dow
closed at 776.92.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow closed at an all-time high of 9,337.97 just two weeks
ago. That's an increase of 1,102 percent since August 1982 for the
benchmark index by which most people track stock market trends.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Nasdaq composite of technology and smaller stocks
rose 1,166 percent from August 1982 to its recent high, while the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 1,059 percent and the Russell 2000
small-cap index 715 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers usually trigger the ``if only'' syndrome in
investors -- ``if only'' I had bought shares of Coca-Cola or Home
Depot.
</P>
<P>
   If you had, your shares (adjusted for subsequent splits) would
have risen 5,452 percent and 26,072 percent, respectively, between
August 1982 and Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   The market had dropped to an August low in 1982 in response to
the deepest U.S. recession since the 1930s, accompanied for a time
by the highest inflation rates in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   But the recession, engineered by Federal Reserve Chairman Paul
Volcker, broke the back of inflation, since which prices have
trended lower in a global pattern economists believe will continue
well into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The byproduct of falling inflation and falling interest rates,
which accompanied it, has been rising corporate profits and the
almost exponential rise in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, these trend lines have had their peaks and valleys
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The market suffered its shortest bear market ever in October
1987, when stocks crashed for reasons historians are still
debating.
</P>
<P>
   The next bear market occurred in the summer and early fall of
1990, exacerbated but not caused by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait. The
economy also dipped into a recession in 1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts date the current bull market in stocks from 1990
and the latest expansion in the economy from 1991. Neither the bull
market nor the economy has suffered a serious setback since,
although the S&AMP;P 500 declined 1.5 percent in 1994 when the Fed
raised interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   As for the economy, the government announced Friday that, Asia
and General Motors to the contrary, gross domestic product expanded
in the second quarter by a bigger-than-expected 1.4 percent annual
rate. Some analysts had anticipated a decline.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no mainstream analyst thinks either the bull market or
the economy will suffer anything more than routine corrections or
slumps over the next several years, conditions being what they are.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this long-range optimism is based on factors such as the
large-scale adoption of computer technology, downsizing and other
business restructuring that improved productivity, and the surge of
investment by aging baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody suggests something catastrophic couldn't happen that
would upset all of these upbeat scenarios. But that's always
possible.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, it might be a good idea to keep an eye out for
the next asteroid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-98 2301E
</P>
