<HEADER>
A5733 &Cx1f; tad-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-BJT04-COX     08-03 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BJT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, August 4, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GM _ General Motors Corp.'s board of directors meets today and
is expected to announce that it will spin off 20 percent of its
Delphi Automotive Systems. Delphi is the world's largest maker of
auto parts and employs about 14,000 workers in the Dayton-area. The
spin-off, anticipated for more than a year, is expected to produce
about $1.6 billion for GM. Selling the stake would raise the cash
to offset the cost of the recent crippling strikes in Flint, Mich.
We get reaction from United Auto Workers at our troubled Delphi
plants if the spin-off is approved. (Wagner, Bohman/Dayton Daily
News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GM-RETURN _ Talking to workers at the Doraville GM plant for
fresh quotes fas they end their first day back on the line.
(Swartz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ Delta Air Lines, which has struggled with getting its
planes to arrive on time, now has the second best performance among
top 10 carriers, even tho it has slipped to 75 percent on time,
down from 79 percent, according to the latest DOT figures. (Poole,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ CWA votes to authorize a strike against BellSouth.
(Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BEERMAN _ Elder-Beerman Stores Corp. goes to Wall Street with a
secondary offering of its new stock priced at $22 a share. We tell
what this means. (Bohman, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-WISCONSIN _ Southern Co. plans to build a 300 megawatt
natural gas-fueled electric power plant in Wisconsin in anoither
thrust into nationwaide electricty markets. Terms of a preliminary
agreement with Wisconsin Electric call for Southern to build and
own the plant and sell power to the local utility. Southern's
Georgia Power subsidiary, meanwhile, has agreed to purchase
electricity from two independently owned plants in Georgia. (Quinn,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ABP _ American Business Products, whose stock has slumped
steadily for two years, is in for some changes under Larry
Gellerstedt. Gellerstedt, hired this year from Beer Construction,
is to develop a strategy for a diversified company that has not
appeared to have one. (McNaughton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ ATLANTA _ The people who sell mutual funds keep
coming up with seductive concepts to get you to invest. Some of
those approaches actually work. Some are no more than gimmicks. But
there are others that might well be both a good idea and a good
investment, which brings us to focused, or concentrated funds.
(Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-COMPUTERVIRUS _ As more and more people log onto the World
Wide Web, they become increasingly susceptible to infection from a
computer virus, experts say. And those recent events have left
users wondering how to best protect their machines and files.
(Cocks, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ Despite grumbling from old-time Internet
users, some of the best things on the Net are still free. Better
yet, some things that weren't free in the old days -- e-mail, for
instance _ are available from a number of sources without paying a
penny. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MACNEWS _ Ascend, based on a philosophy of life management, is a
popular personal information manager among PC users. The Mac
version, though, works and feels like an afterthought by the
publisher. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ It was a certain type of clogged
arteries that persuaded Roger Smith and others it was time for an
experiment, an attempt to show the world -- and GM management, that
there was a way to do business differently. A way to be a
responsive auto manufacturer. And thus was born the idea of Saturn.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER-TRADING _ The following insider transactions were
disclosed in the latest reporting period. (List follows.) (Luke,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UPS-LESSONS _ ATLANTA -- For shareholders, UPS has wrung out
every unnecessary dime to make back the $1 billion in revenue it
lost during and after those 15 days last August, posting record
profits in the first quarter. But what about those hourly workers?
The strikers, whose plea for more full-time jobs won the battle for
public opinion? UPS has labeled their strike ``irresponsible'' and
has told them they need to put it behind them and focus on
customers. (Mitchell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   UPS-FUTURE _ even now, the chief of long-term business
development says its U.S. package delivery business -- making up
more than 80 percent of UPS' $22.5 billion in revenue -- isn't the
key to the company's future. That lies in UPS Worldwide Logistics
Group. (Mitchell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HIWAY _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Colorado-based Internet service
company Verio Inc. will acquire buy Hiway Technologies in a stock
and cash deal worth $352.4 million, the companies announced.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is made up of $101 million in cash and 8.67
million shares of Verio common stock, with Hiway shareholders
owning about 19 percent of the combined company on a fully diluted
basis after the deal. Hiway also gets to appoint one member to
Verio's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Hiway hosts more than 90,000 Web sites and employs 275, with 175
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   WALLSTREET _ ATLANTA _ August is to stock market bulls what
October is to bears. The Dow Jones industrial average hit last
year's peak of 8,259.31 in August. In 1987, the Dow peaked at
2,722.40 in August -- and crashed two months later. August 1982 was
also important for bulls but for a different reason. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REYNOLDS-MONEY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Burt Reynolds is on his
way out of bankruptcy. Creditors for the actor ``still have some
terms that we're arguing over but we're substantially in
agreement'' on his plan of reorganization, their lawyer, Bob
Gilbert, said from West Palm Beach. Reynolds declared more than $10
million in debts when he filed for Chapter 11 protection in 1996.
(Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ECONOMY _ AUSTIN _ With sales tax revenues soaring,
interests are coming out of the woodwork to spend an unprecedented
budget surplus expected to top $6 billion by the time the Texas
Legislature goes back to work in January. Yet some lawmakers are
warning against moving too quickly to spend the money in light of a
drought they say can dry up the Texas economy as surely as it is
searing Texas farmlands. (Brooks, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GM-AFTERMATH _ ATLANTA -- The most expensive strike in General
Motors Corp.'s history cost the automaker more than $2 billion,
slowed the entire nation's economic output and disrupted the
finances for about 200,000 workers around the country. (Swartz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERWATCH _ ATLANTA -- Come Jan. 1, Georgia consumers will
have another weapon to fight unwanted telemarketing calls,
especially those made by Georgia-based telemarketers. The state
Public Service Commission is establishing a ``do not call'' list of
consumers who don't want to be called by telemarketers -- and
telemarketers are required to use the list or face fines. (Tharpe,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
