<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5742 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BOTANY-RAVEN-890(     08-03 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BOTANY-RAVEN-890(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY POLITICKING FOR PLANTS, HE MADE HIS GARDEN GROW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By NANCY BETH JACKSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Peter Raven jumps up from the conference table at
midsentence and disappears out the door, returning loaded down with
a stack of fat books. He picks up the conversation as though he
never left.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are my babies,'' he says, patting the latest volumes in
``The Flora of China'' and ``The Flora of North America'' series
chronicling ``survivors and new species.''
</P>
<P>
   While Raven, botanist, evolutionary biologist and director of
the Missouri Botanical Garden, has not been out there picking all
the daisies himself, his ``biopoliticking'' and networking lurk
behind the collaborative projects to catalog and understand plants
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The same biopoliticking behind the ``Flora'' series surfaced
last month with the announcement that the Missouri Botanical
Garden, Washington University, the University of Missouri and
Monsanto Co. would be partners in a new $146 million Donald
Danforth Plant Science Center.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say it will be the largest plant science center in
the world and turn St. Louis _ already renowned among botanists
because of the garden _ into an agricultural Silicon Valley when it
opens in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I specialize in networking,'' Raven said. ``There is an
enormous kind of pleasure in working with people, helping them to
realize what they want to do. I like to link people.'' Jonathan
Kleinbard, a former University of Chicago vice president who
recently became the garden's deputy director, said his boss ``likes
to have 27 balls in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1971, when he left an associate professorship at Stanford
University with no more administrative experience than ``part-time
access'' to a secretary, Raven has turned a rather scuffy patch of
real estate in a decaying urban neighborhood into an international
center of biodiversity research and activism, a community magnet
and one of the nation's four largest herbariums.
</P>
<P>
   And, he quickly added, the fastest expanding collection in the
world, with 120,000 specimens added each year and at least a dozen
staff taxonomists collecting somewhere in the world at any given
time.
</P>
<P>
   When Raven arrived at the garden as a 35-year-old Californian
with no particular plan in mind, he found 85 employees and a budget
of $650,000. Today, he directs a staff of 354, including 55
researchers with Ph.D.s, and oversees a budget of $20 million. The
New York Botanical Garden, by comparison, has a staff of about 100,
including 30 Ph.D.s. Recently, the Missouri garden opened an $8.6
million research center, housing a 122,000-volume library, nearly 5
million herbarium specimens and the TROPICOS database _
http://mobot.mobot.org/Pick/Search/pick.html, which averages over
one million hits a month.
</P>
<P>
   Known locally as Shaw's Garden, the place was created in 1859 by
Henry Shaw, a major landowner who made his fortune selling goods to
traders and pioneers headed west. An amateur botanist, Shaw worked
with George Engleman, a physician and botanist, to create a center
for education, research and horticultural display. Shaw also
endowed a school of botany at Washington University, a link between
garden and university that continues today with the director
holding a tenured seat on the faculty, teaching graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   By the early '20s, the garden had built a national reputation
for research and training, but by the time Raven arrived it was, as
he describes it, ``like an art museum with exhibits only in a few
rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 acres were laid out in gardens _ most of the 79 acres
Shaw had set aside still looked like the treeless prairie it once
was. Raven set to work not only gardening but also building
support. A 1982 election gave the garden access to property tax
revenues, which now make up 28.9 percent of the budget. An
additional 30.4 percent comes from contributions, bequests and
memberships, now over 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Over 250,000 people visit the garden each year, wandering
through the living rain forest, feeding giant carp at the fall
festival in the Japanese Garden, strolling through the Victorian
Garden or the Rock Garden or the English Woodland Garden or simply
admiring sculpture, tucked in everywhere, by Alexander Calder,
Henry Moore, Carl Milles or Frank Stella. Gardeners get tips; jazz
and gospel fans come to concerts. Children troop through on class
outings.
</P>
<P>
   Raven never misses a beat on getting people involved _ in St.
Louis and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Candide, he is not content to cultivate his own
garden. He travels the world _ Washington, Australia, India, China,
the Vatican are ticketed these days _ not to collect plants but to
stir others to action, build human networks and promote
biodiversity in the face of development. He makes speeches, lobbies
politicians and corporate leaders, puts scientists together with
research projects.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, he has been grand marshal of the Veiled Prophet Parade,
a St. Louis institution for some 120 years, and served on the
University of Missouri board of curators. When he was inducted into
the St. Louis Walk of Fame two years ago, he joined Henry Shaw,
Ulysses S. Grant, Josephine Baker, and Stan Musial as famous folk
with roots or other important links to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is any doubt of his local commitment, Raven says
``Missour-ah'' instead of ``Missour-ee.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   On the national level he serves as home secretary of the
National Academy of Sciences, chairman of the report review
committee of the National Research Council, and member of the
committee for research and exploration of the National Geographic
Society. He also serves on the President's Committee of Advisers on
Science and Technology and this year chaired a While House panel on
environmental and economic strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Raven has been a National Science Foundation fellow, a
Guggenheim Fellow , a MacArthur Fellow, belongs to academies of
science in more countries than Thomas Cook has tours , headed the
Botanical Society of America, the Society for the Study of
Evolution, the American Society of Naturalists, the American
Institute of Biological Sciences and then some. He has written 18
books and more than 450 articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the type of personality that likes to be interrupted
constantly,'' he said. ``I like a lot of things in play. I get
rejuvenated by noise and interruptions and have a great power of
recall.''
</P>
<P>
   Raven, born in Shanghai in 1936 into a family of American
bankers, counts as ancestors Mayflower pilgrims and a British
Redcoat, but the strongest DNA may come from the his maternal
grandfather's grandfather: Patrick Breen, who arrived in California
in 1847 after spending the winter snowbound with the Donner Party
in the Sierra Nevada . Of the 87 pioneers, only 46 survived,
including all 9 of the Breens.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 62, Raven is doing what he began doing at age 6:
exploring nature. An only child, he read a book on insects when he
was sick in bed and then began growing caterpillars into
butterflies. That led to exploring vacant lots around San Francisco
in search of plant specimens. At 8, he became the youngest member
of the California Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   By 10, he was comparing field notes with Alice Eastwood, the
grand old lady of California botany, then 90. At 12, he joined the
Sierra Club and ended up sharing a tent with Ledyard Stebbins, who
has been called one of the foremost plant evolutionary biologists
of the century. At 16, he discovered a Clarkia franciscana, a
member of the evening primrose, which had not been seen in Marin
County since 1900; a subspecies, Dr. Ravenii, was later named in
his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly surprising, he chose academic studies in botany,
graduating Phi Beta Kappa from the University of California at
Berkeley and obtaining a PhD from the University of California at
Los Angeles. He was networking even then.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a graduate student,'' he said, ``I had 15 other graduate
students working on the evening primrose. They said I was the only
graduate student to have graduate students.''
</P>
<P>
   At Stanford, after a postdoctoral fellowship, he began looking
beyond botany toward evolution and biodiversity. He and a
colleague, Dr. Paul Ehrlich, came up with a theory of co-evolution,
a process in which species change as the species they interact with
change. But they also became increasingly worried about what was
going on in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began thinking about population,'' said Raven. ``In the
late '60s, we became concerned about plant extinction. We began to
put it all together. The real problem was that the kinds of things
we liked to study were disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   And he started worrying about how many more species were
disappearing than being created and about what was happening to the
rain forest before botanists had even started to find out what was
there.
</P>
<P>
   Ticktock, ticktock. At the Garden's Climatron, a flashing
electronic bank counts down the disappearing acres of rain forest
second by second. Raven also frets about topsoil, the ozone layer,
skin cancer, cutting down forests without replacing them,
industrial wastes, global warming. His warnings often have him
labeled a pessimist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1990s and the first few decades of the 21st century are
likely to be the most tumultuous and destructive of the natural
resources of our planet that we may ever face,'' he has written.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can either decide to be conservative in dealing with
biodiversity _ such species are of such fundamental importance to
us, and their loss is absolute and irreversible _ or we can
recklessly conclude, despite all the evidence to the contrary, that
what we are destroying is not important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone likes the strategies he chooses to try to save
ecological systems. He bets on multinationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it,'' Raven said, ``multinational corporations
are one of the best vehicles to achieve global sustainability.
Unlike governments, which can pretend there is no global warming
because they can live from election to election, the corporations
can't live in fantasy. They have to return value to shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   He and the garden have been criticized by various groups for
working with corporations, particularly Monsanto, which is based in
St. Louis. The garden's new research center is named the Monsanto
Center and Monsanto is a major donor in the new plant science
center, which will explore genetic engineering, leading to
commercial applications.
</P>
<P>
   Raven dismissed such criticism as he spewed out numbers of
things that were disappearing, never to be replaced. A man with a
cause, he can wear out board directors, committee members,
politicians, academics and critics with his enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is after Pope John Paul II. Raven will be going to Rome
three times in the next six months in an effort to persuade the
pope to join his crusade, and he plans to push hard for the concept
of ``sustainability,'' or preservation the earth's resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can get the pope to put sustainability higher on his
agenda, present it as a world problem,'' Raven said as though
talking to himself, ``then I would be very successful and happy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
