<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-WATCH-NYT &LR;      08-03 0257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN AND CAFFEINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn.)   By JOHN O'NEIL (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in this Starbucks-crazed age, children are not big coffee
drinkers. But they do consume a surprising amount of caffeine, in
carbonated sodas and chocolate drinks _ and, a new study reports,
suffer the same symptoms of caffeine withdrawal as adults do.
</P>
<P>
   For the study, whose results are published in this month's issue
of the Journal of the American Academy of Child Adolescent
Psychiatry, researchers focused on decreased attention span, a
symptom of caffeine withdrawal. Led by Dr. Gail A. Bernstein of the
University of Minnesota Medical School, a team of psychiatrists
looked at 30 healthy school-age children who were given four sets
of response-time assessment tests over the course of a month.
</P>
<P>
   The first session established the young subjects' performance on
their regular diet of caffeinated beverages. Next, their caffeine
intake was increased to the equivalent of three cans of cola a day,
twice the average caffeine consumption for American children, and
they were retested a week later.
</P>
<P>
   For the third test, the subjects went cold turkey for a day,
then returned to their regular diet for a week before the final
session.
</P>
<P>
   The students' performance plummeted on cold-turkey day _ and a
week later, there had been little improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to prevent this phenomenon,'' wrote the
researchers, ``is to have children avoid consuming high levels of
caffeinated beverages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
