<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A cold front will bring parts of drought-stricken north Texas
the first chance for showers in over a month Tuesday. However,
scorching heat and dryness will plague most of central and southern
Texas and interior Louisiana for at least one more day until the
cold front and the chance for clouds and rain shift farther
southeast. Additional showers and thunderstorms will precede the
cold front northward into Missouri. Some of the thunderstorms will
be strong to severe with damaging winds. Ample clouds, showers and
embedded thunder will surround low pressure from northern Indiana
to western South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a persistent ridge of high pressure will provide
partly to mostly sunny skies and comfortable humidity levels from
Maine to Alabama. The exception will be the Southeast seaboard,
where low pressure will affect coastal areas with isolated showers.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will develop again ahead of an unusually tenacious
cold front in central and south Florida, though northern Florida
will be mainly dry with lower than seasonable humidity levels. The
leading edge of the afternoon sea breeze will ignite a few showers
along the central Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, thunderstorms will percolate in the Rockies from
Wyoming to New Mexico, while interior regions farther west will
remain drier than they have been recently as the monsoon
circulation temporarily halts. The Pacific Northwest will continue
to be uncharacteristically hot and dry with the reception of
increased clouds along the coast. Interior California and the
deserts of the southwest will also be blistering hot.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Montana Downpour
</P>
<P>
   Downpours dumped 1.2 inches of rain at Billings, Montana, on
Sunday, marking the town's greatest single-day rainfall in over a
year. The availability of moisture in Billings is limited, given
that the Rockies west of the city provide a barrier against Pacific
moisture and that humid air from the distant Gulf of Mexico is
seldom able to reach Montana. On Sunday, a sluggish low pressure
system inched across the state. In turn, Gulf moisture had time to
circulate from the Plains into Montana. With destabilizing cold air
aloft, heavy storms erupted, bringing a month's worth of rain in a
day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
