<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-NAZI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE MUSEUM IS SUED FOR A LOOTED MATISSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The heirs of Paul Rosenberg, a prominent Jewish art dealer who
fled Paris for the United States during World War II, have filed
suit in U.S. District Court against the Seattle Art Museum to
recover a Matisse painting that was confiscated by the Nazis in
1941.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, the first against an American museum over art
stolen by the Nazis from a Jewish family, provides an inkling of
how complicated it may be to unravel such claims, which are just
now surfacing more than a half-century after the war. The museum,
which said it was still researching the Rosenbergs' claim,
essentially asked the family to sue so that it could reach a
comprehensive settlement that would include Knoedler &AMP; Co., the
Manhattan art dealer, which purchased the painting in Paris in
1954, said the Rosenbergs' lawyer, Laura Hoguet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provided the museum with proof that it was stolen from Paul
Rosenberg, and they never told us any reason why that was not
correct, but they concluded that they could not do anything without
a legal proceeding,'' Ms. Hoguet said. The suit was filed late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   John Reed, the museum's lawyer, said in a statement that the
museum had hoped for mediation of the dispute. ``Since a settlement
was not possible,'' he said, ``the museum is pleased that this
matter is now at issue so that the rightful owner of the painting
can be determined and the relative rights and obligations of the
parties, including the Knoedler Gallery, can be decided in one
forum.''
</P>
<P>
   The whereabouts of the painting, ``Odalisque,'' were unknown to
the Rosenbergs until last summer, when a grandchild of the couple
who donated it to the museum in 1996, Virginia and Prentice
Bloedel, a founder of the Canadian timber giant MacMillan Bloedel
Ltd., recognized it in ``The Lost Museum: The Nazi Conspiracy to
Steal the World's Greatest Works of Art'' by Hector Feliciano. The
Bloedels, now deceased, had bought ``Odalisque'' in 1954 from
Knoedler.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Bloedel Wright, their daughter, who is a trustee of the
museum, notified the Rosenbergs. They filed a legal demand for the
painting last October, which was rejected by the museum on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no justification for the Seattle Art Museum's forcing
the Rosenberg family to incur the expense and delay of bringing a
lawsuit,'' said Elaine Rosenberg, the widow of Paul Rosenberg's
son, Alexandre.
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano, who had traced the painting's provenance for his
book, was also mystified by the museum's action. ``This is a very,
very solid claim where you have documents all the way through from
the 1930s through the 1960s showing that the painting belonged to
the Rosenbergs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing guidelines adopted in June by the Association of Art
Museum Directors, in which members pledged to resolve claims
quickly, Feliciano said, ``I believe that if the Seattle Art Museum
applies to the letter all the guidelines of the AAMD, this claim
should be solved very quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
