A5780 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BLACK-JOCKEYS-HNS     08-03 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BLACK-JOCKEYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS, WHO ONCE DOMINATED RACING, GAIN RECOGNITION AT HALL OF
FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GOTTLIEB  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ From the first Kentucky Derby in 1875
through 1911, black jockeys dominated. Winning trainers were black
and, like the riders, some learned the job as slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there aren't more than a handful of African-American
jockeys, trainers or horse owners in professional racing. Centuries
of dominance were snuffed out by racism and economic forces.
</P>
<P>
   Observers see no new surge of interest among African Americans
on the horizon. But history is taking note of the early champion
jockeys and trainers. On Aug. 10, the National Racing Hall of Fame
will induct Ansel Williamson, an ex-slave who trained the first
Kentucky Derby winner in 1875 and in 1873 the winner of Saratoga's
Travers. The honor comes as writers and museums recognize blacks in
horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary story of athletes who dominated
America's first sport and were totally forgotten and written out of
history,'' said Edward Hotaling, who will soon publish his second
racing book, ``The Great Black Jockeys.''
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, a towering man known as ``Old Anse,'' trained
Aristides, the horse that won the first Kentucky Derby. The horse
was ridden by Oliver Lewis, who like 13 of the 15 riders was black.
Black jockeys clenched 15 of the Derby's first 28 runnings. They
dominated because they lived on the farms where they cared for
horses, and often started racing when they were 11 years old and
slightly built. In the 18th and 19th centuries, racing had a bad
reputation and once it became a status sport, whites wanted in,
said Lynn Rinau, a Kentucky author of two books on racing.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Williamson's personal life were never recorded, but
the Racing Musem said he was born around 1806 in Virginia and his
training career dates to the 1850s. He was owned by several people
before being freed by R.A. Alexander in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson trained the unbeaten Norfolk, who won the first
American event called a derby, held in New Jersey in 1864. He
worked for H.P. McGrath, training the horse known as Tom Bowling,
which won the Travers. In 1875 he trained Aristides, the first
Kentucky Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a judge of horses he had very few superiors,'' read
Williamson's 1881 obituary. ``His conclusions were drawn from long
experience and were delivered with a quaintness of expression and a
brevity of style which pleased while it instructed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rinau said blacks were adept riders well before slave ships
brought them to America. In West Africa, they were known as strong
riders, racers and warriors atop nimble Arab horses. By 1700, elite
slaves in the South earned respect from their masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South was a gambling population and they bet heavily,''
Rinau said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who distinguished themselves landed on the front page of
the newspaper and some traveled freely. They were also some of the
best-paid American athletes. Still there were not more than 100
slave jockeys, and the glory could be short lived. ``When they
died, they buried them where they fell,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Civil War, blacks stayed with the sport they were
familiar with. Isaac B. Murphy was the leading rider in 1894. Jimmy
Winkfield won the Derby in 1901 and 1902 and had a lucrative racing
career in Europe. Willie Simms won the Derby in 1896 and 1898, and
won each Triple Crown event.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the century, racism forced blacks out.
Sometimes, Rinau said, they were literally nudged off their horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had the Ku Klux Klan setting the tone and it was a pretty
horrible one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, blacks increasingly moved north. Today, their
participation is small. Troy Lively is a successful steeplechase
rider out of Maryland, and Hank Allen is a long-tenured horse
trainer. Well-known black horse owners include Bery Gordy and rap
star Stanley Burrell, known as ``Hammer.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Anse Williamson is the fourth black in the Racing Hall of
Fame and the first trainer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
