<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAIGHT DROP RAISES SENSES TO THEIR PEAKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASSETTS, Calif. _ Some people get dizzy atop the Sierra Buttes.
Some get nervous, and others seem euphoric. It's the thrill that
makes this one of the best short hikes anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Perched atop the buttes, at 8,587 feet, there is a lookout
station that seems to float on air. It is set on such a small
pinnacle that it seems there is nothing but empty space below the
meshed-grate metal deck. At one spot, if you look straight down,
past your boots and through the grate, it can seem that directly
under you is a straight drop of about 1,000 feet of nothingness.
</P>
<P>
   I looked down, my heart raced and, hey, it was pointed out to me
that my jaw had dropped like an egg from a long-legged chicken.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Buttes is located at the southern edge of the Lakes
Basin Recreation Area, about an hour northwest of Reno, Nev., one
of the Sierra Nevada's prettiest areas, and also one of the best
for summer vacations and camping, hiking, biking and fishing. It is
the Buttes that loom over it all, a series of stunning granite
spires, with an excellent trail right to the top.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the summit requires a 2.5-mile hike with a 1,700-foot
climb, with well-placed switchbacks to keep it from degenerating
into a wheezer of a buttkicker. You park at the Packer Saddle
Trailhead, which also serves as a trailhead for the Pacific Crest
Trail. The trailhead is located near Packer Lake (take the left
fork), with a good road in that even a minivan can handle.
</P>
<P>
   The hike climbs right off, at first gradually, then more steeply
but amid shade in forest. After a short respite at a mountain
terrace, it then climbs the last 700 feet elevation gain more
steeply, but with switchbacks all the way. Finally you emerge above
forest and approach the craggy spires. It takes most well under two
hours to make it.
</P>
<P>
   Then the sensations start. To reach the lookout requires
climbing three sets of metal stairs, two which jut out over open
space, and then finally to the lookout itself. It is positioned
atop the highest crag, on a tiny point of a rock, and it can feel
as if you are surrounded by free-fall on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   The views, of course, extend for miles across the Sierra,
directly below to the Sardine Lakes, across to Volcano Lake,
northeast over the Gold Lakes Basin, to the south to French Meadows
Reservoir and beyond to Grouse Ridge and the Sierra crest. It can
make you want to explore the area for weeks to find all of these
revealed spots.
</P>
<P>
   But what really can get to you is that sensation of nothing but
air beneath your feet. I found myself walking scared, holding the
railing with a lock-grip, peeking looks straight down, with every
sense electrified. For anybody who loves to explore and walk, this
one is an absolute must-do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information: Tahoe National Forest, Downieville Ranger
District, 15924 Highway 49, Camptonville, CA 95922; 530-288-3231.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
