<SLUG> BC-BODYGUARD-PERJURY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODYGUARD OF CONVICTED CARRIAGE OPERATOR CHARGED WITH PERJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM JACKMAN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The bodyguard of a convicted carriage
operator was charged Friday with perjury after investigators
accused him of creating a new identity and lying on the witness
stand.
</P>
<P>
   The charge raised new questions about M.J. L'Donna'sconviction
last month on murder-for-hire charges, as well as the conviction
last year of five Kansas Citians for causing the 1988 explosion
that killed six firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, prosecutors said Friday, Thomas E. Butner took
the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   But in L'Donna's trial, Butner, 27, identified himself as Shawn
P. Butner. Prosecutors allege more perjury occurred in the L'Donna
trial, when they say Butner denied testifying or receiving payment
in the firefighters case. Defense lawyers had asked him about that
case to attack his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Court transcripts, however, show Butner did testify and
prosecutors said he was paid for his testimony in the firefighters'
case.
</P>
<P>
   L'Donna's lawyer, David L. Owen Jr., said Friday that he would
file a motion for a new trial in her case, based on the charge
against Butner. He declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr. said,
``I am proud of the fact we are coming forward with this
information. Rather than wait to see if it comes out randomly,
we're coming forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hill said L'Donna's guilty verdict should stand. ``We
believe that this is not a basis for a new trial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Butner was arrested Thursday afternoon by Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms agents and made his first court appearance
Friday afternoon before U.S. Magistrate Judge John T. Maughmer. He
said very little, and Maughmer ordered him held without bond
pending a detention hearing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Butner declined to answer questions as he left the hearing in
handcuffs and leg shackles. ``I got nothing to say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the five defendants convicted last year of causing
the 1988 explosion that killed six firefighters watched Friday's
developments with interest. Butner and his sister, Cindy Butner,
testified in that case, and the defense lawyers said they would
consider using it in their appeal, which already is pending.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Osgood, attorney for convicted defendant Richard Brown,
said, ``This is characteristic of the type of witnesses, across the
board, that testified against Mr. Brown and his co-defendants.
Nothing that is revealed about these people would surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Robert Switzer, Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms special agent in charge, was asked how the bureau, which
handled both the firefighters and the L'Donna cases, couldn't
notice that the same man was testifying under different names. He
said the only federal agent who dealt with Butner on the
firefighters case was David True, who retired last spring, and
different prosecutors handled the two cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this before,'' Switzer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn'' Butner testified that it was his brother, Tom, who had
testified in the firefighters' case. In February 1997, Tom Butner
testified that Richard Brown had repeatedly confessed his
involvement in the 1988 explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on the witness stand last year why he came forward in the
firefighters' case, Butner said: ``If I do something wrong, I pay
the crime. If they did it, why shouldn't they pay the crime?''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the same man apparently took the witness stand
again, claiming that L'Donna wanted him to kill a carriage
competitor and then her boyfriend. Instead, Butner approached the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and agreed to wear a hidden
microphone and tape his conversations with L'Donna.
</P>
<P>
   Those tapes became the crux of the case against L'Donna. A jury
convicted her on July 16 of providing Butner with a gun to be used
for murder and using a phone to arrange a murder.
</P>
<P>
   L'Donna is being held in a private jail at Leavenworth and could
not be reached for comment. But in a recent letter to The Kansas
City Star she continued to maintain her innocence as well as attack
Butner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a conspiracy,'' L'Donna wrote, ``between ATF, my
business competition and Shawn Butner, mobile phone records proved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   She also criticized his testimony that he made money as a
``street fighter.'' She said that claim ``fell in the lies along
with (his claim) he had four wives and eight children.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Goodale, another carriage operator who a target of the
alleged murder plot, said Friday that ``she's still guilty. ... You
know, he could have said his name was Joe Blow or anybody. It
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hill and Switzer said the government moved quickly to
investigate Butner once it found out his alleged ruse. They said
the tip was e-mailed to the ATF's Web site in Washington on July
18.
</P>
<P>
   The task of investigating Butner's identity fell to Agent Ronald
W. Getty, who had handled Butner from the time he approached the
bureau in January, and wired him for sound before Butner's meetings
with L'Donna.
</P>
<P>
   According to Getty's affidavit in federal court, he found that
Shawn P. Butner, born in January 1969, lives in Denver and is a
cousin of Tom Butner. Shawn Butner said he hadn't seen his cousin
in many years and wouldn't recognize him.
</P>
<P>
   But Shawn Butner of Denver reportedly told ATF investigators
that another cousin visited his family about four years ago, and
some items turned up missing, including a list of all the family's
birth dates and Social Security numbers. Shawn Butner told the ATF
when he applied for a car loan earlier this year, he found his
Social Security number had been used in Missouri to run up credit
card debt of $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Getty also found that another Shawn Butner obtained both a
Missouri and a Kansas driver's license in the winter of 1997, not
long after Tom Butner's testimony in the firefighters case. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
