<P>
   &UR; DEEP THOUGHTS (Hilarious) By Jack Handy &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I can picture in my mind a world without war, a world without
hate. And I can picture us attacking that world, because they'd
never expect it.
</P>
<P>
   If a kid asks where rain comes from, I think a cute thing to
tell him is, `God is crying.` And if he asks why God is crying,
another cute thing to tell him is, `Probably because of something
you did.`
</P>
<P>
   If you ever catch on fire, try to avoid seeing yourself in the
mirror, because I bet that's what REALLY throws you into a panic.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I would have a real tragic love affair and get so bummed
out that I'd just quit my job and become a bum for a few years,
because I was thinking about doing that anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you read a good book, it's like the author is right
there, in the room talking to you, which is why I don't like to
read good books.
</P>
<P>
   I hope that after I die, people will say of me: `That guy sure
owed me a lot of money.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Passed on by Jeff Farnell, Asst. Director Photos/Graphics, NY
Times News Service. (Fancy title that means you work rotten hours
for less money). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says he's looking forward'' to testifying in the
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky case. Sounds like a little perjury right there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Linda Tripp has also given prosecutors her dress,
which is also stained, with spaghetti sauce, beef gravy, custard
pie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You all see Linda Tripp's press conference? The theme of it
was, 'I am you. I am just the average person.' Assuming the average
person tapes their friends and then stabs them in the back.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to say the state of California does not have the
powerball lottery. We don't need it. We have legitimate ways of
earning money in this state. We want money, we spill coffee on
ourselves at McDonald's. We go to Denny's and cry about not getting
service. We marry wealthy women and sue for alimony. We earn our
dough.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As an artist about to leave on a long trip to Italy, I called a
storage company to have someone pack the artwork in my studio. The
packer arrived the next day with stacks of flattened cardboard and
balls of twine. I went back to my easel as he began unfolding the
pieces of cardboard and fitting them to the paintings, tying and
securing. From time to time I watched as he made one neat package
after another, thinking to myself, ``What a monotonous job day
after day.''
</P>
<P>
   After a while, we took a coffee break and he asked me if I was a
painter, either oblivious to what he was packing, or just to make
conversation. I admitted I was, and this provoked a thoughtful
silence. Then he said, ``Do you do this every day?'' I said I did
indeed. Another silence. Then in a sympathetic voice he said, ``It
must be boring.''
</P>
<P>
   _ HENRY S. GILLETTE
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Garcia stopped in at his local Barnes &AMP; Noble to buy
a volume of poetry by Gerard Manley Hopkins. As the salesclerk rang
up the purchase, she said briskly, ``That comes to $10.66.''
</P>
<P>
   Without thinking, he replied, ``The year of the Norman
invasion,'' and was given a blank stare in return.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to explain himself, he said, ``You know, the year the
Normans invaded England, William the Conqueror and all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another blank stare. But as Garcia handed over his money, the
young clerk looked up, somewhat awestruck, and said, ``Wow, can you
do that with any number?''
</P>
<P>
   John Schiff was jogging in Central Park, wearing his Nolan Ryan
T-shirt with a picture of the retired pitcher on the front and
facts of his career on the back. As he jogged along, he realized
someone was pacing behind him. After three minutes or so, the man
behind him put on speed and called out as he passed: ``Thanks for
the information. Good reading.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Grand Opera Company has been giving free Wednesday
evening performances at Central Park's ``Summerstage'' for more
than two decades. Vincent La Selva, the artistic director, answers
the telephone himself in the company's small office.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he began keeping a record of some of the telephone
queries put to him on performance days:
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you people intend to do about the weather?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to go to the free opera in Central Park. How much
does it cost?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If admission is free, do I get a refund in case of rain?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a special cast in case of rain or is it the same
one listed in the newspaper?''
</P>
<P>
   ``At what time will you know if it's raining or not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the performance starts at 7:30, what time does the
conductor come in?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If `Stiffelio' is postponed because of rain, does it change to
`Rigoletto'?''
</P>
<P>
   During an afternoon rush hour, a man boarded the A train at the
World Trade Center. ``Attention, ladies and gentlemen,'' he
intoned, his voice piercing the humid air of the subway car,
``Jesus is coming, Jesus is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The man standing in front of Adam Cohen didn't have to think
twice. He turned to his companion and said, ``I hope he's not
waiting for a train, or he's going to be late.''
</P>
<P>
   As good a definition as any: H.D. Causbie overheard an obviously
relaxed diner addressing a companion at the Boat Basin Cafe: ``This
is delightful. It's a poor man's cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   At 71, I sit down on a bus seat with a sign giving priority to
elderly riders and notice I'm seated next to a younger couple.
Enter a woman my age and the man of the couple immediately gets up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, aren't you nice,'' the woman says, and sits down next to
me.
</P>
<P>
   The man who stood up says, ``Well, that's one advantage of being
elderly.'' The woman my age nods her head.
</P>
<P>
   The young man follows with ``But there must be others.''
</P>
<P>
   I break in and say loudly, ``No, that's about it.'' The whole
front of the bus breaks into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALFRED GESCHEIDT
</P>
<P>
   Craig and Nancy Sobocinski were shopping for mattresses with
their 3-year-old son, Alec. The hours went by, the number of stores
visited increased and Alec became restless.
</P>
<P>
   As he was wandering through the last store, a young salesperson
invited him to try an adjustable bed. He climbed up, and she
proceeded to show him how the control pad lowered and raised the
bed, and even made it vibrate.
</P>
<P>
   Alec was unimpressed. ``Can you make it fly?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   It was New Year's Eve, and West Moss was in a fancy hair salon,
getting her hair styled professionally for the first time. She was
nervous, and not certain that she would be able to explain what she
wanted to the stylist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like my hair like Mary Tyler Moore,'' she said shyly.
Which Mary Tyler Moore, he wanted to know _ ``Laura Petrie or Mary
Richards?''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, returning to the same salon, she asked for the
same stylist. He didn't recognize her but she felt a surge of
warmth when he came over and asked what she'd like. ``Audrey
Hepburn,'' she said. ``Holly Golightly or Sabrina?'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   William D. Harney telephoned to make a grooming appointment for
his French bulldog. He was asked for his name. ``Bill,'' he
replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``And your dog's name?'' ``Simon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The voice at the other end sounded surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funniest thing,'' it said. ``The call before yours was
also to groom a French bulldog _ but the man's name was Simon, and
his dog's name was Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia E. Noonan, walking along Madison Avenue with a friend,
encountered what must be the city's most enterprising panhandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, ladies,'' he chirped. ``Have you any spare credit cards?''
</P>
<P>
   While I was living in Manhattan and on my way to the Museum of
Natural History, an approaching pedestrian and I simultaneously
spotted a $10 bill on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The man, closer to the bill than I was, picked it up and put it
in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   As we passed, he handed me a five! What a town!
</P>
<P>
   _ DIANE PECK
</P>
</TEXT>
