<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODYGUARD-PERJURY-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ the firefighters case.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit states that Getty then took the fingerprints of
Shawn Butner and Tom Butner to a police fingerprint examiner. The
prints matched, the affidavit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Hill acknowledged that Butner had been paid for his testimony in
both cases. He would not say how much Butner received for his
participation in the firefighters case.
</P>
<P>
   In the L'Donna case, court records showed Butner was paid
$4,116.
</P>
<P>
   At trial, defense attorney Owen tried to attack Butner's
credibility by alleging that Butner had claimed to have testified
in the firefighters' case, when he hadn't. When Butner denied
participating in that case, Owen argued to the jury that Butner
learned from his ``brother Tom,'' how to make money by testifying _
by approaching the ATF, rather than Kansas City police.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Owen asked Butner, ``Did you know the ATF
paid for testimony from witnesses?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Butner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much did Tom and Cindy (Butner, his sister) get paid (for
their firefighters testimony)?'' Owen asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Butner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever tell anyone you testified in the firefighters
case?'' Owen asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not,'' Butner replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever tell anyone you turned in the people responsible
for the firefighters case?'' Owen asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Butner said, then added, ``only Don Crumpley,'' a
co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't tell him you had been paid?'' Owen asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Butner said.
</P>
<P>
   Crumpley later testified that Butner told him he had been paid
for his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Butner spent much of his time on the witness stand listening to
the tapes he secretly made of his talks with L'Donna, and
explaining the background and context of each conversation. The
tapes appear to show L'Donna agreeing to pay Butner $5,000 to kill
her boyfriend, John Encell.
</P>
<P>
   But L'Donna's comments were somewhat guarded, and never
explicitly direct Butner to commit murder. She did hand Butner a
loaded pistol during one meeting and she paid him $500 cash.
</P>
<P>
   In the firefighters case, Butner admitted on the witness stand
that he offered to wear a secret recorder in 1995 to capture
Richard Brown making admissions. Police and ATF agents declined
Butner's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Getty said he was disappointed with Butner's apparent
identity change. He said Butner reportedly obtained new driver's
licenses after being named on warrants in Clay County.
</P>
<P>
   Clay County Sheriff Bob Boydston confirmed Friday that Thomas
Butner is wanted for a January 1997 moving violation and for
leaving the scene of an accident. Shawn Butner has no criminal
record, authorities said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
