<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5799 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MYSTERY-MAN-KAN &LR;      08-03 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-MAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S IDENTITY STILL A MYSTERY AT HIS FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the end, Chang Ho Chang's life remains as
much a mystery as when he was found two years ago wandering in
front of an Olathe, Kan., social service agency.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 11, 1996, the then 64-year-old Korean man was found
carrying a bag of clean clothes and a note that said: ``Please take
care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The note identified the man as Chang Ho Chang. He had no other
papers, and efforts to identify him in the area's Korean community
hit dead ends.
</P>
<P>
   Chang died Thursday at 8:55 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we are no closer to finding out who he was than we were
years ago,'' said Young Lee, former president of the Korean
American Society of Greater Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really unbelievable and impossible to think this could
happen. It is a sorrowful time.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 Korean-American business leaders on Friday attended a
45-minute service for Chang in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders solicited funds to buy Chang a new shirt and
flowers for the viewing, and the funeral home cut $100 off the $600
funeral as a gesture of condolence. Traditional Christian hymns
were led by the Rev. Park Jee Yong.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's death certificate is littered with unknowns, but here is
what is known.
</P>
<P>
   After he was found two years ago, Chang was taken to the
University of Kansas Medical Center in Kansas City, Kan., where he
was diagnosed with a degenerative brain condition that causes a
disoriented state much like Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Some people thought that Chang may have had two or three grown
children in the area and that his wife may have died the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   One interpreter thought Chang said he originally was from Seoul,
South Korea, and that his surname might be Suh. Publicity generated
about 50 phone calls and tips to KU campus police while Chang was
at the medical center, but nothing materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Campus police forwarded Chang's fingerprints to the FBI's
national identification center in Washington and the Kansas Bureau
of Investigation headquarters in Topeka, where the case was given
low priority.
</P>
<P>
   With no official name, official efforts to identify Chang
failed. Without solid leads, all appeals for help were rebuffed by
government agencies, including the federal offices of Immigration
and Naturalization, Medicaid and Social Security and Missouri's
Division of Family Services and Division of Aging.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculated that fear of prosecution silenced those in
Chang's ethnic community, a culture that prides itself on stoic
individualism.
</P>
<P>
   Chang spoke only rarely, and then in Korean, particularly when
he was hungry. Because of his mental state, he was unable to
communicate effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a big smile that would come out of the blue,'' said
Carla Berkel, the director of the Alzheimer's unit at Oakwood Manor
Nursing Home in Kansas City, where the man eventually came to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would rub his cheeks and out would come that smile,''
Berkel said. ``We never had any trouble with him.''
</P>
<P>
   A family ``adopted'' Chang, visiting once a week. Family members
spoke with him in Korean but never once got a clue to his identity.
</P>
<P>
   Korean business leaders gathered in Overland Park on Friday
after the funeral service to try to make sense of Chang's death.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter with a Korean newspaper, a tax collector, a preacher,
a senior citizens representative and a member of the Federation of
Korean Associations all spoke of individuality, respect and the
importance of family.
</P>
<P>
   For Kiutae Bae, president of Bae Brothers Co. of Overland Park,
Kan., the day was one of mixed emotions.
</P>
<P>
   There was shame in the fact that the Korean community would
abandon one of its elders in such a public way. There also was the
pride he expressed in the American social service system that cared
for Chang.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is a system in place to better communicate so
this does not happen again,'' he said. ``There is no shame in
asking for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Lee wore black on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to know we will never give up,'' said Lee. ``We
will never give up trying to find this man's family. I'm sure
they're out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
