<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WHITE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMMY HILFIGER HAS ARRIVED IN THE WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Tommy Hilfiger arrived on the fashion scene
waving the American flag and he can't seem to ease his grip.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the apparel mogul was discovered by rappers and rock
and sports stars and well before he opened a glitzy celebrity store
in Beverly Hills, he had a flag-like logo. His shirts and boxers
with red, white and blue patriotic motifs were winners with middle
aged men in suburbia. And his book, published last year, was called
American Classic: A Style Book.
</P>
<P>
   He is still playing the Americana theme. His upcoming
advertising campaign uses a White House mockup as back drop for
photography. ``We wanted to use as a theme what the White House
represents to the American people _ a symbol of hope,'' says a
Hilfiger quote in the press release.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes, shot in Los Angeles with models such as Tyra Banks
and Jason Shaw, evoke images of the White House Lawn, the Oval
office, the Roosevelt room and the rose garden. The sets in L.A.'s
Griffith Park were from movies such as ``Dave'' and ``American
President.''
</P>
<P>
   A tie for the sky?
</P>
<P>
   Who else but Nicole Miller, the fashion designer best known for
pop culture print ties, sexy dresses and a penchant for parties,
would design the decor of the airplane that will airlift the
winners of Harrah's Entertainment Inc. casino promotions later this
month?
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen couples, including two people chosen in Kansas City,
will be flown on a tour through Atlantic City, Lake Tahoe and Las
Vegas. Milller says she is using lemon yellow and cherry red in
casino icons such as roulette cards and slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   It's got to be a yawn for her. Her irreverent statusy tie prints
decked with the likes of champaign bottles, theater tickets and
dice during the '80s conversational tie rage put her business on
the map. She only has to turn to her archives.
</P>
<P>
   Skip the wrestler look.
</P>
<P>
   How does a man choose a swimsuit? Let us count the ways: A slim
man should wear a slim suit (so his trunks don't balloon in the
water) says the August GQ. A flat front trunk will deemphasize a
stomach. A short guy looks best with short shorts. And if you are a
bit round and a few pounds over on the scales, an unbuttoned sports
shirt around the pool is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   It's better to look as if you're going to a barbecue, says GQ.
And puleeze, unless you're in top, triathlete shape, just say no to
Speedo briefs.
</P>
<P>
   A TV moment.
</P>
<P>
   The recent couture shows in Paris have gotten more attention
than usual, in part because they were featured in a prime time ABC
special and in part, because some were so way out there in lavish
opulence and theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   As for the television show, it seemed to be a good idea gone
awry. Couture, of course, is the old-world, ultimate in clothing
luxury. The clothes are made to order and costs easily run in the
$30,000-to-$40,000 and up range. Customers include maybe 200 to 300
Americans at most and some Eastern princesses.
</P>
<P>
   But cable television has traditionally framed fashion in lively,
high-speed terms. And by comparison, ABC hosts Anne Archer and
Isabella Rossellini seemed stiff, stilted and burdened with a slow,
academic script. The guests looked uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   As for the clothes, there may be some signals of things to come
to the mainstream. For instance, industry observers believe the
feathers and Christian Dior's play on Pocahontas may inspire a new
wave of Western and American Indian derivatives on the fashion
scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
