<HEADER>
A5807 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-MINIMALIST-KA     08-03 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MINIMALIST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MINIMALIST LOOK IS BEING AUGMENTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: What will you be adding to your closet come cold
weather?
</P>
<P>
   A feather boa? A choker necklace Kate Winslet would envy?
Earrings long enough to bounce against your neck when you toss your
head? An embroidered jacket? With sequined lining?
</P>
<P>
   If your shopping list was weighted more toward sweaters, mittens
and boots, some revisions may be in order.
</P>
<P>
   Serious fashion trend trackers are veering a bit from the basics
these days to follow a new wave of decorative ornamentation.
Subtle? Yes. But it's more exuberant than anything seen since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, philosophical shifts are fuel for the fashion arena.
Within the 1970s alone, bell-bottomed, hot-panted women morphed
into no-nonsense, conservative preppies. The overdone pouf-skirt
excesses of the '80s gave way to a clericallike austerity in the
early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The simple, minimalist style that emphasizes shape and fabric
over detailing, trims and other distractions has long dominated the
world of designers and apparel manufacturers. Noted names like
Calvin Klein and Helmet Lang have been in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   A backlash in part to the '80s, it coincided with the dressing
down of America when even business executives adapted knit shirts
for the office and the best restaurants were challenged to enforce
a dress code. It also came at a time when books on simplifying
one's life were creeping up the best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of the accessories industry, designers dropped
jewelry and eventually hosiery from runway shows. The biggest trend
in accessories in recent years has been toward subtlety. (Remember
Y necklaces?) And celebrity observers at events such as Oscar
ceremonies nodded off at the ongoing parade of simple slip dresses.
</P>
<P>
   But recently such embellishments as embroidery, contrasting
trims and touches of glitz have begun to resurface. ``It's a
happening thing,'' says Dana Buchman, the designer best known for
her business suits. ``It's all over,'' says Hal Rubenstein, the
fashion director for InStyle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Trend forecaster and retail consultant David Wolfe says the
trend is on the way up. ``It has a foot in the door. I know because
so much of what has been successful now has been embellishment,''
says Wolfe, fashion director with the New York-based Donegar Group.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly viewers of ABC-TV's haute couture special late last
month took in lavish doses of extravagant ornamentation through the
visions of such designers as Christian Dior's John Galliano and
Alexander McQueen. While the shows were theatrical and exaggerated,
they showcased miles of feathers (Dior featured Pocahontas), rich
colorful embroidery and sumptuous textiles, all of which will have
a trickle-down impact. ``I kept thinking just a piece of that
fabric could be a lapel on a jacket,'' Wolfe says. Donatella
Versace appeared to have woven feathers into some fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   On a more realistic planet for fall, the new thinking is
manifested in, say, fur boas, a feather collar, fur trims, new lacy
chokers, embroidered handbags, embroidered scarfs and a velvet
appliqued pattern snaking up a shapely jacket.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a drop-dead jeweled skirt tempered with a sporty
cashmere sweater as shown by Badgley Mischka design team, or it's a
metallic-patterned jacket softened with a simple white shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more discreet'' than in the 1980s, says Gina Tovar,
the Chicago-based fashion director of Nordstrom stores. It may be a
texture, she says, the glimmering lining of a coat or a metallic
rim around a hem. As for herself, she is envisioning a new fur boa.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Reynolds, the buyer for Halls Plaza, a Kansas City
specialty store, added a feather boa to her own wardrobe earlier
this year. And she is upbeat about jackets and sweaters with fur
cuffs or maribou trims and glimmering patterns. It's ``fun and
lighthearted. It's like having a new palette.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchman, the designer, says, ``women are tired of totally plain,
slightly masculine, hard-edged clothing'' and ready for feminine
softer styles. For her, it can be jackets with touches of beading
and, in one case, her navy velvet decorated with steel gray
embroidery. Both can be worn for day into night. ``It's almost like
private embellishments only you know you're wearing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   On a more opulent note, Todd Dean has bought Alexander McQueen's
ready-to-wear for his Kansas City store, Loma Vista Hardware, where
the fall stock will include McQueen's long skirt decorated with a
red sequin Asian pattern on one side and a man's jacket decked with
a sequin cherub motif.
</P>
<P>
   He says people who want to be out front are ready for change
after fashion's generic mode. ``Everyone wants this burst of
energy. Everyone wants to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   To Marylou Luther, the syndicated fashion columnist, the shift
may be in part triggered by the millennium. ``Traditionally fashion
always goes baroque at the end of the century,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But more likely, credit goes to the fashion pendulum that
routinely swings from one extreme to another and the ongoing search
for something new. After designers ``have exhausted minimalism,''
Luther says, ``what do they do other than maximalism?''
</P>
<P>
   InStyle magazine's Rubenstein sees the shift as a natural
evolution after people tired of minimalism. ``Once you buy it, you
own it. There is nowhere to go'' with it.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly another boost comes from the media. Decorative clothes
``frankly make better pictures,'' Luther says. And designers want
the attention of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Finally _ and ultimately the key to acceptance _ ornamentation
gives women an opportunity to set themselves apart from the pack.
``We have been living in the minimalist trend for too long. Women
have lost the ability to create our own identity,'' says Irenka
Jakubiak, the editor in chief of Accessories magazine, a trade
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Embellishment, Rubenstein says, ``helps women individualize
their look. It personalizes a wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the idea will start for many women with jewelry.
Jakubiak predicts increased popularity for long earrings and
choker//bibs, especially in dark metal with stones, along with
feather pieces and decorated bags.
</P>
<P>
   Will more decorative clothing mean higher prices? Not
significantly in Buchman's view. ``If you have hand embroidery,
it's going to add something, but I don't think they are out of
line,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Steele, the fashion historian at New York's Fashion
Institute of Technology, says manufacturers and designers will
simply seek alternative, less costly resources. ``It doesn't mean
you're adding more value. Ultimately it's costlier to buy simple
fabric from Italy than to have embroidery done in Asia,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile no one expects the stylish simplicity of the moment to
go away. Minimalism ``is easy to take care of. It shows how well
the clothes are cut,'' Rubenstein says. ``But women want to look
pretty. It just comes down to a nice balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
