<HEADER>
A5821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GI-FORUM-0804-COX     08-03 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GI-FORUM-0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS GRANTS LONG-AWAITED FEDERAL CHARTER TO HISPANIC
VETERANS GROUP
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. House of Representatives voted Monday to
bestow a federal charter on the American G.I. Forum, an advocacy
group for Hispanic veterans that had waited almost 30 years to
receive the same charter as other veterans' groups and national
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The voice vote in the House broke a six-year-old moratorium on
federal charters and delivered a symbolic but meaningful honor to
the G.I. Forum, as its members gather for their national convention
this week in Corpus Christi, Texas, and mark the group's founding
there 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to get what you've been after for 50 years,'' said
Gil Rodriguez of Austin, a Navy veteran who was elected last month
as first vice commander of the G.I. Forum's Texas organization.
``It's a good beginning for the second'' 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The federal charter, approved Friday in the Senate, places the
G.I. Forum on the same plane with Disabled American Veterans, the
American Legion, Jewish War Veterans Inc. and other veterans'
groups. Those groups earned a federal charter earlier because their
members are primarily veterans, while the American G.I. Forum from
its beginning has comprised groups of veterans, women and youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three are considered equal,'' said Arthur Solis (Note:
accent over the ``I'') of San Antonio, legislative liaison for the
G.I. Forum. ``Our organization is a veterans' family
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   After Congress balked 30 years ago at recognizing the group,
founder Hector P. Garcia and other leaders ``decided we weren't
willing to change our organization,'' Solis said, so the charter
drive was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Congress decided that it was issuing too many
federal charters, which convey no benefits. By the time an informal
moratorium was imposed in 1992, such groups as Little League
Baseball Inc., the American Symphony Orchestra League and the
Society of American Florists and Ornamental Horticulturists held
federal charters on the same par with the veterans' groups. A
formal moratorium, with a tiny window for exceptions, took effect
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the G.I. Forum decided to seek out one of those
exceptions: ``As the organization has matured, it has become more
and more involved in veterans' issues,'' Solis said. ``We felt the
need to have a federal charter to recognize our work on behalf of
veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   The G.I. Forum was also looking for a tribute to its founder,
Dr. Garcia, who died two years ago. Garcia, a decorated veteran of
World War II, formed the organization in 1948 in Corpus Christi to
help Mexican-American veterans obtain treatment from veterans'
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal charter is seen as honoring Dr. Garcia, and it
would be a fitting tribute to his sacrifice and tireless work,''
Solis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had many well-deserved awards and accolades,'' including
the Presidential MeDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
