<HEADER>
A5822 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-FIREWORKS-COX     08-03 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FIREWORKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bergman introspection meets Woo's violence
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a ``Death Wish'' movie directed by Ingmar Bergman, or a
Harold Pinter play directed by John Woo, and you'll have some idea
of Takeshi Kitano's remarkable ``Fireworks'' (``Hana-bi'').
</P>
<P>
   Winner of the top prize at the Venice Film Festival _ the first
Japanese picture so honored since Akira Kurosawa's ``Rashomon'' in
1950 _ ``Fireworks'' arrives stateside with Quentin Tarantino's
seal of approval. That's become less of a recommendation to those
of us weary (and wary) of his film-geek penchant for the too-cool
movie.
</P>
<P>
   But this film, which Kitano wrote, directed and stars in (under
his acting alias, ``Beat'' Takeshi), is something quite special.
It's cool, all right, but it's so much more. Scenes of
contemplative tenderness or deadpan humor alternate with furious
explosions of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Kitano's fondness for fractured chronology renders a simple plot
summary the most difficult thing about ``Fireworks.'' But here are
the basics (consider this summary as you would opera notes,
incomplete but a leg up): Nishi (Kitano) is a hard-boiled,
tough-guy detective whose beloved wife (Kayoko Kishimoto) is dying
of leukemia. While he's visiting her in the hospital, he briefly
abandons his longtime partner, Horibe (Ren Osugi), on a stakeout.
</P>
<P>
   Horibe is badly wounded and paralyzed for life. His family
leaves him and he sits alone in his wheelchair thinking about
suicide. Meanwhile, another cop Nishi cares about is killed in the
line of duty, leaving his young widow penniless. Finally, some
thuggish yakuzas from whom Nishi borrowed money are calling in
their loan. Overcome with remorse and guilt, Nishi sets out to make
things right. Or at least as close to right as they'll ever be
</P>
<P>
   The outbursts of violence are as bloody, brutal and unexpected
as a chopstick in the eye (don't laugh; it happens). But when Nishi
isn't killing or maiming someone, the movie is suffused with comic
pathos and a sweet melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   Visually rich and formally paced, the picture as a whole echoes
Kitano's on-screen self-assurance and meditative bravado. Rarely
without his shades and radiating the stoic macho of Charles
Bronson, he occasionally suggests an Asian John Garfield with his
measured intensity and opaque eyes.
</P>
<P>
   What's astonishing about ``Fireworks'' isn't how very cool it
is, but how very human it is. The vicissitudes of life _ nasty or
funny, reflective or heartbreaking _ have rarely been expressed so
eloquently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fireworks''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring ``Beat'' Takeshi. Directed by Takeshi Kitano.
Subtitles. Not rated but there is extreme violence.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Eloquent and original mix of tenderness and
brutality, of poignancy and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
