A5823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN04-COX     08-03 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: It's nice to open doors others can't go through
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I worried that I'd have to present my transcripts at the door.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't terrible, but they weren't going to get me in here.
They didn't get me in when I graduated, and I could imagine the
people at the sign-in desk looking them up and down, looking at
each other, looking at me and, having sized me up, saying, ``Get
lost, pal.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a social gathering, but not open to just anyone. I was
along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you do,'' my wife said as we pulled into the parking
lot of the Capital City Club, ``just keep your mouth shut.''
</P>
<P>
   She'd do the talking. She had the key.
</P>
<P>
   In Phi Beta Kappa, the key is the proof you made the grade. Or,
I should say, the grades.
</P>
<P>
   I was not Phi Beta Kappa. I was Phi Delta Theta. Rather than a
key we had a secret handshake.
</P>
<P>
   That handshake hasn't done me much good since I graduated, and
it wasn't going to help me here. This was a meeting of the Atlanta
alumni chapter of Phi Beta Kappa. My wife is a member; I was the
barbarian at the gate. You can let him in, but you don't want to
give him the run of the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I introduce you,'' she said, ``just nod and smile. You can
say hello, but don't get drawn into any conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   I've played the part before, the swizzle stick in my wife's
drink. When we lived in North Carolina, she belonged to something
called Alliance Francaise, a talky group of Francophiles who'd get
together and speak French. I'm not much for cocktail parties in any
language, but I went once, nodding on cue and nibbling on the
cheese and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they ignored me, but I could have told them that I'd read
Sartre, too. In the English translation, of course. I could have
told them I'd read most of ``Being and Nothingness'' _ what I took
to be the nothingness part _ and I knew all about Proust and his
cork-lined room. But I wasn't a part of anyone's conversation. And
somehow I didn't think they were talking about Sartre or Proust.
</P>
<P>
   Here, at the Capital City Club, my instincts told me the bar was
set a little higher. The first thing I heard upon being admitted
(``He's with me,'' my wife said) was one person saying to another,
``Yes, I taught him internal medicine at Emory.''
</P>
<P>
   We darted the other way, toward the cheese and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why, but Phi Beta Kappa seems to follow me
everywhere. The small handful of significant women in my life,
every one of them, has been Phi Beta Kappa. They couldn't have been
too smart. But they had that key. I couldn't show 'em much more
than a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best editors I'll ever write for was also a Phi Beta
Kappa, and she found it deeply amusing that the Raleigh alumni
chapter, desperate for a speaker, invited me of all people to
address it one year. We shared an office and shared confidences,
and I like to think there was a mutual admiration. There was on my
end anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked you?'' she said with a smirk I still miss. ``Remind
me to bring in my key tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marion,'' I said, ``they didn't ask me to join them. They
asked me to instruct them.''
</P>
<P>
   But as I stood mute and muzzled at the Capital City Club, I had
the distinct feeling there would be no petitions for enlightenment.
It was just as well. I was starting to feel almost comfortable.
Everyone was speaking English, and no one grilled me on my GPA.
</P>
<P>
   More than just intelligent, they were open and friendly, none
more so than Angelika Pohl, Christina James and Carolyn Weber. I
was the tag-along spouse, not quite up to snuff on his transcripts
but well-trained and generally presentable. Unless somebody's set
the curve beyond reasonable reach, you could give me a solid B.
</P>
<P>
   And I had always thought these people grade-grubbers. I left
wishing I had grubbed for one or two more A's myself. That key is
rather nice.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
