<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A new Spin on white rappers
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Choose your Beastie. The September issue of Spin ($3.99) is
giving single-issue purchasers their choice of the three Beastie
Boys on the cover. The redesigned magazine, with expanded coverage
of fashion and music, profiles the beer-chugging, groupie-grabbing
white boys and asks how the group became the elder statesmen of
hip-hop. Good question.
</P>
<P>
   Newsmags urge the Prez to tell the truth
</P>
<P>
   The nation's biggest soap opera (``As Monica Turns''?) heats up
this week, and magazines from Newsweek to The New Yorker weigh in
with their spin on what President Clinton should do. Perhaps the
best advice comes from former Clinton aide George Stephanopoulos:
``If he's shaded the truth, it's time to amend the record,'' he
writes in Newsweek ($2.95). ``If he's lied, he should tell all,
apologize and hope for the best.'' In another development, Newsweek
reports that Linda Tripp and literary agent Lucianne Goldberg
plotted to get the ``evidence-stained'' dress from Monica Lewinsky
either by theft or deception.
</P>
<P>
   Time ($2.95), meanwhile, explains why Lewinsky decided to
testify (to get immunity for herself and her mother) and offers the
up sides and downsides of Clinton's options. The preferred option,
of course, is to tell the whole truth, Time says. Especially if the
DNA tests are incriminating.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.79) agrees with Stephanopoulos that
truth is the best defense, but hard-liners _ namely Hillary Rodham
Clinton and lawyer David Kendall _ reportedly favor continued
denial.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clinton gets caught in a lie, there still may be hope,
Jeffrey Rosen writes in an intriguing article in The New Yorker
($3). Citing previous political sex scandals, Rosen says
heavy-handed attempts to prove guilt sometimes spark public
outrage. In 1820, for example, Queen Caroline of England was
accused of adultery. Prosecutors trotted out bodyguards and
chambermaids to testify and even produced semen-stained sheets. A
vote to impeach the queen was shelved at the last minute because of
angry demonstrations in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   A PERFECT 10: Editors at Men's Health ($3.50) expect readers to
flip over their 10th anniversary issue. Literally. The September
issue features an upside-down ``flip cover'' that offers two
magazines in one. The regular cover has the usual half-naked guy
with six-pack abs, while the flip cover has the same guy in an
Armani suit. Part of the magazine includes such articles as ``99
Best Health Tips Ever'' and ``The Baldness Pill.'' On the flip
side, men can learn how to build the ultimate wardrobe and get the
best haircut. Though not as flashy as some of its counterparts,
Men's Health has quietly built a circulation of 1.5 million readers
_ more than that of GQ and Esquire combined.
</P>
<P>
   MORE FOR MEN: Bob Guccione Jr., son of the Penthouse publisher,
launches some slick competition for Esquire and GQ this week with
Gear ($2.99), a men's magazine sans centerfold. There's lots of
good reading here, from an article on ``La Femme Nikita'' star Peta
Wilson to an interview with Matt Damon before he became famous. But
the most interesting _ and most inexplicable _ piece is Guccione's
interview with rival Hugh Hefner of Playboy. Interviewed in his
trademark silk pajamas, Hefner discusses everything from the merits
of Viagra to his ``almost-date'' with Gloria Steinem when she was
an editorial assistant at Help magazine. According to Hefner,
publisher Harvey Kurtzman tried unsuccessfully to fix them up. ``He
was convinced we were made for each other romantically,'' Hef says.
Shortly after that, Steinem went undercover for Show magazine to
write her first-person account as a Playboy bunny.
</P>
<P>
   MAY-DECEMBER MATCH-
</P>
<P>
   UPS: Judging from the latest spate of Hollywood films, you would
think there are no actresses ``of a certain age'' to be found. Jack
Nicholson, Harrison Ford and Michael Douglas have been paired with
Helen Hunt, Anne Heche and Gwyneth Paltrow _ women young enough to
be their daughters. People ($2.79) talks to older actresses such as
Jane Fonda, Bette Midler and Meryl Streep about Hollywood's
generation gap. Fonda, 60, says it's a battle that can't be won.
``You know, in a big close-up on a big screen, seeing wrinkled lips
kissing wrinkled lips, it's not as appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
