<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    St. Louis singer finds success in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The attention now coming to R&AMP;B singer Wendell Brown, a St.
Louis native and now an Atlantan, is proof once again that working
hard enough at the grassroots level can pay off. His ``Sing a Song
for You'' video single is, according to Radio &AMP; Records magazine,
the most-added on the Urban Contemporary and Urban Adult playlists,
and it's gotten there without a big-bucks, major-label campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Credit for Brown's success goes to Raw Deal Records of College
Park, Ga., a fledgling label created by T.C. Payton and Thom Mueed
because they felt Brown's talent deserved a spotlight. They
produced his just-released album, ``Make It Good for You'';
introduced Brown to Atlanta at a listening party; finagled him some
airtime on BET; booked him on a cerebral palsy telethon, and gained
additional exposure by getting his music played in theaters via
Movie Tunes. Brown says it ``took a trip to Atlanta'' to make his
music begin to happen, because here's where he found someone else
who believed in him.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gloria Estefan, ``Gloria!'' (Epic/Sony). Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   -- Vince Gill, ``The Key'' (MCA). Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   -- Emmylou Harris, ``Spyboy'' (Eminent). Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gerald Levert, ``Love &AMP; Consequences'' (Eastwest). Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   -- Squirrel Nut Zippers, ``Perennial Favorites'' (Mammoth).
Grade: B-.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``There's Something About Mary'' soundtrack (Capitol). Grade:
B+.
</P>
<P>
   -- Luther Vandross, ``I Know'' (Virgin). Grade: B-.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
