<HEADER>
A5826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER04-COX     08-03 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV series based on best seller doesn't show much
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Maximum Bob'' is a condescending insult to insult comedy. It's
smart enough to know better _ based on Elmore Leonard's best
seller, the premiere of tonight's summer series (10 p.m. EDT on
ABC) stars Beau Bridges and is directed by Barry Sonnefeld (``Men
in Black,'' ``Get Shorty''). But it quickly out-smarts itself and
takes the low road, winking and smirking the whole way, just to let
us know it's in on its own joke.
</P>
<P>
   But where's the joke? We're deposited in Deepwater, a Florida
swamp burg billed as ``The Biggest Little City in the South.''
You'll recognize it: no southern cliche goes unturned. Citizens not
married to first cousins are married to brothers or sisters.
Everybody's either possum-vittle skinny or Goo Goo Cluster plump.
Women are there to be leered at. And did we mention everybody's
really, really stew-pid ?
</P>
<P>
   Running things is Judge Bob Gibbs (Bridges), a politically
ambitious, politically incorrect bench sitter who revels in
endless, lawless sentencings. 'Course, most locals love him, at
least until pretty public defender Kathy Baker (Liz Vassey) arrives
from Miami and is appalled by what she finds (after Gibbs sentences
her client to the electric chair for drinking a beer, then hits on
her, Baker wonders if he's late for his ``golf date with Rush
Limbaugh'').
</P>
<P>
   But Baker isn't that appalled: by the end of the hour, she's
decided to relocate to Deepwater. What at first repulsed her turns
out to be merely colorful (``One thing I'll say for him, he sure is
horny for a man his age,'' she admits of the judge) and, what the
heck, without her it's goodbye series.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other shows that successfully set themselves in Oddville,
USA (``Northern Exposure,'' ``Twin Peaks''), making us feel
deficient for not being eccentric, ``Maximum Bob'' cruises its
streets to point and laugh at the weirdos. It starts out
promisingly _ tourists watching a trio of underwater mermaids
eating bananas and drinking sodas _ and it has a bright, neon look
that perfectly captures both Florida and the irony that's promised
and never delivered. Kiersten Warren is memorably flaky as a
mermaid turned Gibb's mystic wife Leanne; you could drop her in
Cicely, Alaska, and she'd get along just fine.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing here adds up, and it's clear nothing is meant to.
``Maximum Bob'' is smart, but it never takes the time to think.
This is a series that knows it's gone in seven weeks _ if it isn't
killed off first.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
