<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: RETURN ENGAGEMENT; SIGNS OF OUR TIMES; DENNEHY PLAYS
LOMAN;   HEAVY DUSTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Md.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The director Andrei Serban, late of the Romanian
National Theater and now the head of Columbia University's graduate
acting program, returns to the Public Theater after a 16-year
hiatus with Shakespeare's ``Cymbeline,'' at ``Shakespeare in
Central Park.'' The production stars Michael Hall as Posthumus
Leonatus and Liev Schreiber, seen recently in the films
``Twilight'' and ``Sphere,'' as the nasty Iachimo. ``Cymbeline''
begins previews Tuesday night and runs through Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Out
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Talk about life imitating art. Just minutes before
``Civil Disturbances: Battles for Justice in New York City,'' an
installation by the activist collective Repohistory, was scheduled
to open on May 19, the city prohibited the use of lampposts to
display public art. On July 23, the city reversed itself and
granted a permit to the collective.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning in St. Andrew Plaza in Foley Square,
Repohistory will install the last 12 of 40 street signs. No mere
pedestrian aids, these: The 21-by-36-inch metal signs present
visual histories of landmark issues in public-interest law. A red
background frames a T-shirt-clad woman to honor Berkman vs. FDNY,
which opened the door for women to become firefighters in New York
City; ``R' You Looking at Me?'' floats above a figure of a child in
a sign referring to Marisol vs. Giuliani, the pending class action
suit about child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The signs line the sidewalks near the courthouses in which many
of these cases were heard. A favorite of Repohistory: a tribute to
Bery vs. City of New York, the 1996 ruling that secured public art
as a form of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Together Again
</P>
<P>
   Brian Dennehy will play Willy Loman in ``Death of a Salesman''
at the Goodman Theater in Chicago, with Robert Falls directing. The
two teamed up at the Goodman on ``The Iceman Cometh,'' ``Galileo''
and ``A Touch of the Poet.'' Previews for ``Salesman'' begin on
Sept. 29; the play runs through Nov. 8. Dennehy's current project
is ABC's miniseries of Tom Clancy's ``Net Force,'' with Scott
Bakula and Kris Kristofferson.
</P>
<P>
   2001 Odyssey
</P>
<P>
   The Walters Art Gallery in Baltimore can finally dust off much
of its renowned Egyptian art collection, thanks to an award of
$325,270 from the National Endowment for the Humanities. The award,
to be used for the reinstallation of the collection in the wing
known as the 1974 Building, which is undergoing an $18.5 million
renovation, will provide display space for artifacts not seen since
the early part of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The new space will leave visitors with the sense of being
transported back 5,000 years to an ancient Egyptian temple, a
museum spokesman said. But time travelers must wait: The wing won't
reopen until the spring of 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
