<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-ARTHUR-ART-NYT     08-03 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-ARTHUR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AARDVARK GETS TO THE TOP (LITERALLY) AT A MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pierre Bonnard is the big draw at the Museum of Modern
Art in New York City this summer. The National Gallery of Art in
Washington is celebrating Mark Rothko. The Children's Museum in
Boston, meanwhile, has mounted its own blockbuster, starring Arthur
Read. As just about anyone age 8 or so and under knows, Arthur Read
is not a painter. Arthur is a smart, sweet, slightly neurotic,
8-year-old aardvark whose family life, adventures and problems are
chronicled in the best-selling children's book series by Marc Brown
and in the spinoff public television show.
</P>
<P>
   True to his last name, Arthur loves to read. The son of an
accountant and a caterer, he has a gutsy, pesky 4-year-old sister
named D.W., a baby sister named Kate, a gang of loyal friends and a
taskmaster of a third-grade teacher named Ratburn. Arthur was a
natural for the Children's Museum, said Lou Casagrande, the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to find kids' cultural icons whose values and
message we can get behind,'' Casagrande said. ``We want to be hip
and relevant to kids and families. We don't want to be dealing with
esoteric topics all the time, but yet we don't want to go to the
other extreme of just being total fun because we are in the
educational business.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Children's Museum is not Disneyworld. ``We
would not do Pocahontas,'' Casagrande said. ``We would not do
anything related to Disney movies. Disney creates a presentation
standard that we aspire to. We just don't think their message is
deep enough and rich enough for children.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the crowds of families that have been lining up for
``Arthur's World,'' as the exhibition is called, children don't
require the museum to be Disney. Arthur opened in May, and
attendance is up 40 percent this summer over last summer. The show
is to run for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's partner in ``Arthur's World'' is WGBH, the Boston
public television station, which produces the Arthur series. Brown,
who is 51 and lives in Hingham, Mass., is a consultant. He dreamed
up the aardvark in 1976 when his young son asked him for a bedtime
story about ``a weird animal.'' Arthur is a worrier. He worries
that his nose is too long. He worries that his friends will make
fun of his new glasses. Despite his obvious talent, he worries that
he is not a good writer.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a lot like Arthur. And while his books have sold more
than 10 million copies, he says it was a bit overwhelming to show
up at the opening and see a 22-foot-tall inflatable Arthur seated
on the museum roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the strongest desire to shout, `Arthur, what are you
doing up there?''' Brown said. ```Arthur, get away from the edge,
get back!'''
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Museum, which was founded in 1913 by science
teachers, is considered a pioneer in the hands-on, object-based
approach to learning. It is not a place for standing in front of
works of art and speaking in hushed voices.
</P>
<P>
   With few exceptions, the staff has made the decision not even to
hang children's artwork on the walls. Children aren't particularly
interested in that sort of thing, says Joanne Rizzi, the museum's
cultural program director, who developed the Arthur exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum is not intended to be about children but for
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Part school, part community center, part playground, it is a
place where children can float handmade boats along a 28-foot,
800-gallon tank that is a model of the Fort Point Channel outside
the museum's window. They can put on life jackets and climb aboard
the Minnow, a life-size boat. As part of an exhibit about
construction, they can design and build skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   The other afternoon boys and girls from about age 2 to 8 were
hanging out in the Read Family Kitchen, reading Arthur books in the
Town Library, and lining up to meet Arthur (a stoical, unidentified
museum staffer sweating in a heavy costume). They were racing
through the Backyard Sleepover, with tents and flashlights and
sound effects, modeled on the one in the book, ``Arthur's First
Sleepover.'' And they were joining in a 25-minute play produced by
the museum's resident theater company, Citystage Company, about
Arthur's pet business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is, `Here's this great character,''' said Ms.
Rizzi, who was touring the exhibit. ``Use this place to explore.
Play in it, have a good time in it. And read, read, read.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Ferguson, who was accompanied by his mother, Fran
Ferguson, was at a table in the library, writing Arthur a note:
``Hi, Arthur. I like you because we have something in common. We
are both in third grade and are 8 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all. ``I have teacher trouble, too,'' said
Russell, who has 20-20 vision but often wears a pair of plastic
glasses in homage to his spectacled aardvark hero.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Carbonneau and her three children, Daniel, 8, Michaeala,
6, and Colleen, 4, were visiting from New Hampshire. ``We love
Arthur,'' said Mrs. Carbonneau, an occupational therapist. ``He's
like my family. The dad works, the mom works, they have problems,
they figure them out.''
</P>
<P>
   While other museums don't necessarily have to consider children
in creating exhibitions, the Children's Museum can't afford not to
think about adults. They are the ones, after all, who bring
children to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Arthur is that adults like Arthur, too,'' said
Leslie Swartz, vice president for development. ``He's not annoying.
He's a sympathetic character.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the museum's best-known shows, ``The Kids Bridge,''
developed by Ms. Rizzi and Aylette Jenness, was about cultural
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Being that he is an aardvark whose friends include a rabbit
named Buster and a bear named Brain, Arthur certainly transcends
race and ethnicity. ``It's purposefully designed to do that,''
Brown said. ``That's why I use different animals. You immediately
eliminate skin tone and any relationship to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur has plenty of problems, but one thing he does not have to
deal with is divorce. The Reads are happily married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't ready for his family to divorce, too,'' said Brown,
who went through a divorce shortly after he began the Arthur
series.
</P>
<P>
   But the author and his second wife, Laurie Krasny Brown, have
written ``Dinosaurs Divorce'' (Little, Brown), a catalog of divorce
information for families. And Brown says he would like his next
show at the museum to deal with divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to use Arthur's celebrity to do other things that
aren't as sexy,'' he said. ``Life is a series of problems, and this
is one of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
