<HEADLINE>
CONCORD GROUP SAYS NOW IS THE TIME TO FIX SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Martha Phillips, the director of the
deficit-fighting Concord Coalition, said Monday that a rare
combination of factors makes this a ripe time to repair the Social
Security System, which says it faces financial difficulties in
coming years as the number of retirees rises sharply.
</P>
<P>
   She said those factors include a relatively small retired
population, a relatively large working population, plus a strong
economy and a president who understands Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, we've got a window of opportunity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security analysts say the retirement program will run out
of money in the 21st century as baby boomers retire and outnumber
workers, who contribute to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is exploring different solutions to the funding
problem, including a boost in Social Security taxes and cuts in
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips made her comments during a debate over whether to make
changes in the Social Security System. The debate was sponsored by
the Preamble Center, a nonprofit economic research organization.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., another participant, said Congress is
too willing to postpone consideration of Social Security's future.
Lawmakers need to find a solution while the current system is
financially secure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of Social Security has been based on confidence,''
he said, and changes should be made while Americans still believe
in the system.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to solve the problem, Kolbe and Rep. Charles
Stenholm, D-Texas, last month introduced legislation that would
allow individuals to invest two percentage points of the current
12.4 percent payroll tax in private markets instead of paying the
entire tax into the system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5844 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-IMMIGRANT-HNS &LR;      08-03 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-IMMIGRANT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALANDER WITH AIDS SEEKS RETURN TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A New Zealand AIDS patient who lived and worked
in San Francisco for most of the 28 years he spent in this country
plans to risk arrest by returning this week in defiance of U.S.
immigration policy barring HIV-infected foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Christopher Arnesen, 56, say the move could provoke
a confrontation with Immigration and Naturalization Service agents.
The man is scheduled to arrive at the San Francisco International
Airport Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'm extremely concerned,'' Arnesen said in an
interview Friday from Christchurch. ``But there are principles
involved here and if I back down now, it would be a disappointment
to the people who have supported me.''
</P>
<P>
   INS District Director Thomas Schiltgen declined comment on the
case Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Arnesen is a one-time tour guide and photographer who lived in
San Francisco from 1966 to 1994 as a permanent resident under
federal law. He said he contracted the human immunodeficiency virus
_ which has since developed into AIDS _ from a 1984 blood
transfusion in Rwanda, following a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   He has paid nearly $200,000 in Social Security taxes, he said,
and now wants to claim a monthly disability benefit of $726 owed to
him, he said, since March 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Catch-22, however, and only federal authorities _ or a
judge _ can cut through it: The Social Security Administration
requires one month of residency in the United States every six
months before it pays benefits to foreigners who have worked here.
</P>
<P>
   But the INS won't let Arnesen back in under a federal
``loathsome or contagious diseases'' law barring many visitors who
have AIDS or other communicable illnesses, or who are HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
   Arnesen, who has no relatives in the United States, said he
returned to New Zealand after being diagnosed in 1993 to be near
his family and because a Social Security representative said he had
to apply for disability benefits from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was patently false. But Arnesen's attorneys
acknowledge they have no proof he was misinformed because he hasn't
been able to provide the name of the Social Security representative
or the date he met that person.
</P>
<P>
   Growing more and more ill, he was unable to return to the United
States to renew his permanent residency status within the required
12-month period.
</P>
<P>
   A dispute arose as to whether Arnesen had legally ``abandoned''
his permanent residency status. Eventually, he won that part of the
battle, but now that he is better because of improved AIDS drugs,
the INS won't let him back in because of his medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``These policies are just wrong,'' said one of Arnesen's
lawyers, Kristen Jensen of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. policy excluding foreigners with AIDS is the harshest and
most restrictive of virtually any country. The other issue is that
Chris completely embraced this country. He paid into the system the
way every citizen and permanent resident does. He did everything
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then when he became too sick to contribute any more and was
entitled to get something back, this gauntlet was thrown down for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Social Security spokeswoman Linda Claramo said her agency had
reviewed Arnesen's case, determined he is eligible for benefits and
felt ``very sympathetic'' to him. But it can find no exception to
the law requiring residency, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has reciprocity agreements on pension and
disability benefits with 14 nations, but no agreement with New
Zealand. As a result, attorneys said, there are 18,600 non-U.S.
citizens in New Zealand and other nations who are entitled to
Social Security benefits but can't get them without fulfilling the
two-months-a-year residency requirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
