<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-DIRECT-SALES-ART     08-03 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-DIRECT-SALES-ART-790(2TAKES)-NYTRNG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL WINE MAKERS CHALLENGE LAWS AGAINST DIRECT SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., Ga., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic showing wine-shipping laws in different states is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES W. SWEENEY   NYT Regional Newspapers  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Small wine makers, increasingly cut off from
joining the point-and-click world of Internet commerce, are turning
from statehouses to courthouses in their feud with the wholesalers
who control much of the United States' $90 billion alcohol trade.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past half-dozen years, direct wine sales quietly
blossomed into a $300 million a year business and many wineries say
their only entree into some states is by mail order and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But they collided with a government-sanctioned system where
licensed wholesalers control the flow of wine, beer and liquor
between manufacturers and retailers. Direct shipments violate state
laws and threaten to carve profits from the powerful middlemen who
have dominated the industry since Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen states have made it a felony to sidestep the
hour-glass-shaped system. Several others are considering similar
measures and Congress also may act soon. Altogether, 44 states
place some restriction on direct shipments.
</P>
<P>
   In a counterattack, the wine industry has won five straight
legal skirmishes with opponents of direct wine shipments. And its
strategists are discussing a more ambitious challenge to the entire
system with an eye on the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mind set in the wine industry has been to go at this
legislature by legislature, but we haven't had enormous success,''
said Bill Nelson, vice president of the American Vintners
Association. ``Ultimately, it may not be possible to get the states
to drop the barriers that protect local wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may require a court test,'' Nelson said. ``My personal view
is leaning that way.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more California wine makers share Nelson's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is our mission,'' said Bill MacIver, president of
Matanzas Creek Winery in Santa Rosa, California, and the Coalition
for Fair Trade, an industry organization in the forefront of the
direct-shipping fight.
</P>
<P>
   Wine makers say that they're fighting for survival in a
competitive market and that wholesalers, with a near-monopoly
stranglehold on distribution systems, are unable or unwilling to
stock inventories from the nearly 2,000 small wineries across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But the wholesalers have a distinctly different view.
</P>
<P>
   They present themselves as an efficient collector of state
excise taxes on alcohol _ and the final bulwark against underage
drinking, citing well-publicized sting operations in New York,
Maryland and elsewhere that tracked Internet wine orders by
teen-age decoys.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesalers are trying to enlist anti-smoking groups in the
fight against direct shipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes on their radar, I can't see them doing anything
else,'' said Doug Metz, executive vice president of the Wine and
Spirits Wholesalers Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesalers group represents 200 of the largest wine, beer
and spirits distributors in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating their lucrative position in the alcohol trade, the
largest wholesaler, Miami-based Southern Wine and Spirits, which
does business in California and seven other states, had revenues of
$2.3 billion in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Both the wine industry and the wholesalers finance large
lobbying operations in Washington and all 50 state capitals, and
they are among the most generous campaign contributors, accounting
for more than $1.1 million in donations to congressional candidates
in the 1997-98 election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over direct shipping involves a 65-year-old regulatory
scheme that grew out of Prohibition and stands on three legs:
politics, policy and profits.
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, alcoholic beverages were prohibited by the U.S.
Constitution. But the dry years were anything but dry in many parts
of the country. New York, Ohio and some other states virtually
ignored the law and some California vintners used a
sacramental-wine loophole to make millions.
</P>
<P>
   Prohibition ended in 1933 when the 21st Amendment was ratified
and Congress passed the Webb-Kenyon Act. Between them, these gave
states the authority to regulate alcohol sales, leading to a
present-day patchwork of wet and dry counties and the lone
exception to federal authority over interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Through the three-tier system, manufacturers are required to
sell their beer, wine and liquor to licensed wholesalers, who are
the sole suppliers for stores, bars, restaurants, sports arenas and
other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone except these small wineries consider that question
closed,'' said Art DeCelle, general counsel of the Beer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The system is lucrative. In 1996, the most recent year for which
estimates are available, Americans spent $96 billion on alcoholic
beverages _ almost all of which passed through a licensed
distributor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   California, which produces more than 90 percent of the wine in
the country, is one of several states that have created exceptions
to the three-tier system to allow vintners and craft brewers to
sell wine or beer that they produce in tasting rooms or brew pubs.
The system is hardly universal: Visitors to the Jack Daniels
distillery in Tennessee, for example, can't buy samples there. It's
a dry county.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 100 wineries in the country produce more than 150,000
gallons a year, according to the American Vintners Association.
With their inventory, they have plenty to supply wholesalers across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most wineries produce much less and can't provide enough to
supply wholesalers that don't want to deal with odd lots of a few
dozen cases. For them, vintners say, the only way to expand their
market is to sell a few bottles at a time by mail order or the
Internet to customers outside the area.
</P>
<P>
   The 12,000-case Brutacao Winery in California's Mendocino County
has arrangements with distributors in about 15 states but makes
additional sales via direct shipment. It had to cancel deliveries
to Georgia after the state declared such imports a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is another state that has made direct shipments a
felony. Brutacao, which used to ship about four cases a year on its
own, has signed up with The Great House of Wine, a Web site
designed to comply with the state law by aligning itself with a
licensed wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's four cases of wine that we would ordinarily not be able
to sell,'' said Steve Brutacao.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesalers, however, have challenged some of those arrangements
in court. So far, those efforts have failed, most recently last
week in Massachusetts where a judge ruled that wholesalers could
not use federal courts to block direct shipments by Virtual
Vineyards through Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesalers have had some successes in state legislatures,
pressing the felony measures that passed in Florida, Georgia,
Tennessee, North Carolina, Indiana and Kentucky. And even in
wine-friendly California, they bottled up a resolution opposing
federal legislation against direct shipping.
</P>
<P>
   The federal proposal, which would authorize federal courts to
enforce state criminal statutes against direct shipments, is
stalled in the House Judiciary Committee but wholesalers believe
they may be able to push the measure through the U.S. Senate by
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Also pending in Congress is a bill to make it a federal crime
for courier companies like United Parcel Service to deliver alcohol
to a minor. One courier, Airborne Express, quit shipping alcohol
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several widely publicized sting operations, vintners
insist that shipments to minors aren't a significant problem, and
their view is shared by Manny Espinoza, chief of the California
Alcoholic Beverage Control Board.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wine Institute, which represents many of the largest
vintners, direct shipment is given a high priority. But officials
there are reluctant to drop lobbying efforts in favor of lawsuits.
``We still think state-by-state is a smart way to go, but it's hard
sailing,'' said Bobby Koch, senior vice president of the
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   It would cost more than $1 million and take as long as five
years to get a challenge to the U.S. Supreme Court, but looking at
the mixed record in state capitals and recent successes in court,
others say the time is ripe for a legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our only chance,'' MacIver said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (James W. Sweeney is a staff writer for The Press Democrat in
Santa Rosa, Calif. This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times
News Service.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
