<HEADER>
A5848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-LABELS-HEALTH-NY     08-03 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-LABELS-HEALTH-NYTRNG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 LABELS STILL CAN'T SUGGEST WINE'S HEALTH BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES W. SWEENEY   NYT REGIONAL NEWSPAPERS  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A four-month standoff over labels touting the
health value of sipping wine shows little sign of ending any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of wine-industry lobbying, federal regulators
were prepared to approve labels distinguishing wine from beer and
other alcoholic beverages earlier this year but postponed action
indefinitely following complaints from Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Some vintners are optimistic about a breakthrough this fall, but
Thurmond vowed to prevent any relaxation of the warning that
currently appears on all wine bottles.
</P>
<P>
   He also has introduced legislation to make the warnings more
explicit.
</P>
<P>
   Like the regulatory decision, Thurmond's bill is bottled up and
unlikely to move before the Senate adjourns for the year in early
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may or may not move,'' Thurmond's spokesman John DeCrosta
said. ``But if it doesn't move, it will be one of the first bills
introduced next year.''
</P>
<P>
   DeCrosta added, ``The only change he's willing to see is for
that warning label to get tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's less the legislation than the ability of a single
senator to tie up business that creates leverage for Thurmond, who
sponsored the 1988 measure that required labels warning that
alcohol consumption during pregnancy can cause birth defects and
that it can impair driving ability.
</P>
<P>
   Before any new labels can be used, they must be approved by the
U.S. Treasury Department, which regulates alcohol at the federal
level. Treasury also has three appointees awaiting Senate
confirmation, any one of which could be blocked by Thurmond if the
new labels are authorized over his objections.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 6 letter to Thurmond, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
flatly stated that the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
``plans to approve the use of these labels'' but an ATF spokesman
said it's unclear when _ or if _ final action will be taken on the
request.
</P>
<P>
   ``No final decision has been made,'' ATF spokesman Art Resnick
said.
</P>
<P>
   Vintners, who want to separate themselves from the beer and
liquor industries, have spent the past several years trying to
persuade federal regulators to add labels to wine bottles
encouraging people to consult their physicians or Food and Drug
Administration dietary guidelines about the benefits of wine
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   FDA guidelines say that moderate consumption of wine can reduce
the risk of coronary disease for some people. They also warn,
however, that heavy use can contribute to cancer, heart attacks,
liver disease and other maladies.
</P>
<P>
   But lobbyists for the wine industry, who were confident of
approval as recently as March, now say they don't know when a
decision will be forthcoming. ``This has been going on too long for
me to make a prediction,'' said Bobby Koch, senior vice president
of the San Francisco-based Wine Institute.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (James W. Sweeney is a staff writer for The Press Democrat in
Santa Rosa, Calif. This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times
News Service.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
