<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWPORT-FOLK-FEST-705     08-03 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWPORT-FOLK-FEST-705&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: NEWPORT FOLK, HOW IT'S CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Newport Folk Festival tour, which presented nine
singers and songwriters at the Jones Beach Theater on Sunday,
invokes an illustrious name.
</P>
<P>
   The Newport Folk Festivals of the early 1960s, held in Newport,
R.I., were watersheds of the folk revival, the postwar movement
that brought ``hootenanny'' into the American vocabulary and put a
guitar in every dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   While the current Newport festival continues (ending in Los
Angeles on Sept. 20), the Film Forum begins a weeklong engagement
on Friday for ``Festival,'' Murray Lerner's documentary of Newport
Folk Festivals from 1963 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the film and the festival in the same week _ with Joan
Baez in the lineup of both _ leads to one conclusion. While the old
Newport might recognize and appreciate its descendant, it would
certainly be surprised at what the young whippersnapper is up to.
</P>
<P>
   Between Newport then and Newport now, the notion of folk music
has been transformed. It was already happening in the years that
``Festival'' documents, when sacred-harp hymn singers and Delta
bluesmen shared lineups with pop hit-makers like Peter, Paul and
Mary (who, unfortunately, dominate the film).
</P>
<P>
   During the 1960s Newport festivals, the divergent strains of
tradition, protest, personal statement and pop ambition were all
revolutionized by Bob Dylan. ``Bob really created a whole mess,''
Loudon Wainwright III said admiringly at Jones Beach. When the dust
cleared, what emerged as ``folk'' was a gentle strain of pop.
</P>
<P>
   At Jones Beach, the word ``folk'' designated a texture _ music
centered on acoustic guitar, or piano in a pinch _ and a style of
songwriting that prizes introspection, storytelling and literary
touches. Sincerity prevailed, though not entirely; Wainwright and
the Violent Femmes had their own kinds of irony, sly and wild-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   The current folk audience expects to hear memories, character
sketches and hints of philosophy; it expects to share intimate
thoughts and reflections shaped by a songwriter's gifts. And the
voices were generally earnest, though John Hiatt cut loose with
soul-style whoops and hollers; two of his songs cited a figure the
old folk singers tried to ignore, Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   Current folky songwriters reveal private preoccupations. At
Jones Beach, Suzanne Vega sang with breathiness and precision about
desire _ illicit, remembered, new _ and about power differences,
between David and Goliath or a child and his abusive parents. Marc
Cohn sang hymnlike ruminations about history's aftermath in the
present.
</P>
<P>
   Nanci Griffith, whose group reconstitutes the sound of the Band,
sang about journeys, lost love and a halcyon past; the chirpiness
is weathering out of her voice, though she still has a taste for
saccharine messages.
</P>
<P>
   At the old Newport, and in much of the 1960s revival, folk was
used in its more academic sense, designating music created and
transmitted by nonprofessionals. Most of the performers in
``Festival'' weren't telling their own stories or singing their own
songs; their material is by Traditional, Anonymous and
half-remembered blues and gospel sources.
</P>
<P>
   They presented themselves as preservers and disciples of
venerable styles, holding onto music that was homemade and proud of
its distance from the machinations of commercial pop. Performers
certainly had egos, but they were careful to preach their humility
and loyalty to roots.
</P>
<P>
   David Bromberg, making a rare appearance, was a partial echo of
the old Newport. He played embittered my-baby-left-me blues and
picked light-fingered, curlicued leads on his acoustic guitar. He
adds his own tangent to tradition: garrulous rants that land
halfway between Bible Belt preaching and Borscht Belt comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Violent Femmes, meanwhile, honored tradition by twisting it
completely. Harking back to the influential ``Anthology of American
Folk Music,'' the 1958 collection of rural performers singing
harrowing stories of death and misfortune, the Violent Femmes used
the sounds of Celtic ballads and skiffle blues to carry tales of
sociopaths and drug casualties; Tony Trischka, a banjo virtuoso,
sat in with the Femmes while Gordon Gano sang about a father
throwing his daughter down a well.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Part of the folk revival _ a part that would echo through rock,
punk and hip-hop _ was the idea that everyone could be a musician.
``Festival'' shows crowds arriving at Newport carrying not just
guitars but also banjos and setting up at the campgrounds to plunk
washtub basses and tap along on junk percussion. When Bob Dylan
asks an audience to lend him an E harmonica, at least three are
heard as they land on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Baez pops up often in ``Festival'' to add a harmony, and
she did the same at Jones Beach, singing with Bromberg and with Ms.
Griffith, who returned the favor during her set. Still, the
audience didn't seem to be carrying any instruments, and when Ms.
Vega cued it to sing along on ``Tom's Diner,'' they couldn't carry
a tune either.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the 1960s, folk was starting to divide. But topical
songwriters papered over their differences with pure archivists by
using old melodies to carry new agitprop. Bruce Cockburn held onto
that legacy, playing a Bo Diddley beat on a bodhran and singing
about land stolen from indigenous people. But the core of his set
was musical, not verbal: intricate, resonant guitar patterns that
were inextricable from his meditations on trouble and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baez tried to squeeze current songs, like Richard Shindell's
``Reunion Hill,'' into didactic categories like anti-war; she also
sang the oldest song in the program, the union anthem ``Joe Hill.''
But the way she sings it now, it's not a rallying cry. It's a
tribute to an individual: one more sign of folk music's
metamorphosis from the people's music to music that gets personal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
