A5856 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     08-03 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE MAKERS OFFER TO HELP ... THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)   (af)  
 By ROB FIXMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With great fanfare, 23 software makers last week issued a policy
statement titled ``Ask, Tell &AMP; Help,'' promising to end a problem
that has frequently infuriated Windows 95 users _ programs that
automatically install themselves as ``default applications,'' the
software the operating system calls upon to open all files of a
certain type.
</P>
<P>
   A closer examination of the policy suggests that it might be
less a sincere effort by the developers _ including Netscape
Communications, Novell, Real Networks and Sun Microsystems _ to
restrain their own practices than an attempt to restrain Microsoft
from absorbing their products into the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, default applications are a great convenience
because they allow you to open a file by simply clicking on it.
</P>
<P>
   Most users want control over which program opens each type of
file, but some applications commandeer this responsibility without
notifying you.
</P>
<P>
   The companies that signed on to the policy statement pledged to
forgo such sneak attacks. But Microsoft Corp. is missing from the
list and it is Microsoft's Windows operating system _ specifically
the Windows registry _ that regulates which application opens any
given file type.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, a major reason that default applications are a
problem is that Windows makes changing such defaults mind-numbingly
complicated. For example, three years after the release of Windows
95, millions of users are still trying to figure out how to get
that persistent digital barnacle, the Inbox, off their desktops.
</P>
<P>
   The policy is a declaration of restraint, promising that
henceforth each program will do three things:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask the user for permission before becoming a default
application.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tell the user of any limits on its ability to read and/or
write the types of files it is proposing to handle by default.
</P>
<P>
   _ Help users find other applications to open files that the
program itself cannot open.
</P>
<P>
   The third point is especially interesting. It states, ``If we
encounter a specific file that we cannot read or play, and if there
are other programs (freely downloadable over the Internet) from
other vendors that do play that file, we will point the user to
information on how he or she can download the third-party
program(s).''
</P>
<P>
   Has a wave of altruism rushed over the software industry? No.
What is really happening here is that these companies want
Microsoft to point you to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   From a technical standpoint, the pledge will work only if each
application obeys rules in the way it interacts with the operating
system, and those rules, for better or worse, are established by
Microsoft. But Yusuf Mehdi, the marketing director for Windows,
said on Friday that Microsoft had never been told of the principles
or consulted about them, much less asked to sign them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sneak attack on Microsoft,'' said Albert Lill, vice
president and research director of the Gartner Group, a management
consulting firm in Stamford, Conn. ``It sounds really great on
paper. Who could argue with it in principle? But it's untenable.''
</P>
<P>
   The declaration's timing is also interesting. It came one week
after Robert Glaser, the chairman of Real Networks, complained to
the Senate Judiciary Committee that Microsoft's Windows Media
Player, a program that aggregates video and audio programs and then
acts as the default application for all of them, ``broke'' the
latest test version of his company's software.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that Glaser was misinformed. A quick examination
by several independent companies revealed that a bug in Real
Networks' own software had caused the problem.
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely that the declaration is an attempt to steer
attention away from Glaser's false accusation and back to the
larger issue: Microsoft's assertion of the default rights over
multimedia files.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that this and other examples of unauthorized
defaults ar a real issue, Lill pointed out that Microsoft ``owns
the guts of the system,'' that is, the Windows application
programming interfaces, which set out the rules for how any program
must interact with other programs and files.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Real Networks had played by the rules and wrapped its
player around Media Player, this wouldn't have been an issue,''
Lill said.
</P>
<P>
   So should software developers simply roll over and let Microsoft
dictate all the terms? No, Lill said, but the solution is a
dialogue rather than a statement of principles that he insists are
``technical nonsense'' and ``pure PR.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehdi is more diplomatic, describing the statement as ``a pretty
narrow view of a much broader and complicated issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that ill-conceived Windows defaults like Inbox are
``bumps along the learning process,'' Mehdi nonetheless insists:
``We're learning, and we're eager to cooperate with developers to
solve these problems. We couldn't survive if other companies
stopped developing programs for Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which leaves Windows users frustrated for want of a
solution, stranded somewhere between Mehdi's assurances of good
will and the perception on the part of 23 developers that they had
to make a public assertion of principles, however unworkable, to
get Microsoft's attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
