<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5865 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-03 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLASTING AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even when members of Congress appear to be all
heart, they don't use their heads _ because they have their hands
out.
</P>
<P>
   They still love guns and those hefty campaign contributions from
the gun lobby despite a graphic lesson right under their noses of
the violent consequences of uncontrolled access to weapons that can
kill.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional leadership presided last week over moving
ceremonies honoring two brave police guards who were slain
protecting others from a berserk gunman in the Capitol. Emotions
ran high. Tears were shed. Genuine humility in honor of courage was
displayed.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this touching sentiment extended into the
legislative chamber, where the hard-nosed business of gun
protection went on as usual. The stark contrast between what the
legislators were saying and what they were virtually simultaneously
doing demonstrated once again that the gun lobby owns a majority of
Congress, or has at least a long-term lease on it.
</P>
<P>
   Mere hours before the eulogies in the Capitol Rotunda, the
Senate voted to block a proposal to ban imports of large-capacity
assault weapon ammunition clips that hold more than 10 rounds.
Assault weapons with large-capacity clips were used to mow down
children in recent schoolyard shootings in Arkansas and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Only five Republicans joined the Democrats in favor of the ban,
which would have closed a loophole that keeps aging assault weapons
armed and circulating despite a 1994 ban on further manufacture of
the guns themselves. The timing of the vote was a dramatic
coincidence even though it seems like a deliberate insult to the
dead policemen.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more, lots more. Just days before the police
officers were killed with a .38 caliber pistol, more than 60
senators voted to kill two amendments that would have tightened
control of handguns.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment would have required new guns to come with trigger
mechanisms that would serve as child safety locks. Sounds sensible
to me, but not to the gun-lovers in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The other amendment would have made parents who left their
weapons where children could find them responsible for any crime
committed by those children with those weapons. Russell Eugene
Weston Jr., accused of killing the Capitol Hill police officers,
stole the pistol from his parents. He was not a kid, but he was a
prohibited from owning, purchasing or possessing a gun because he
had been committed to a mental institution in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also recently passed a third amendment pushed by the
National Rifle Association that is designed to hobble efforts to
make it harder for criminals to buy guns. Shades of the Wild West.
Everyone hit the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would prohibit the FBI from funding a new instant
crime-record check by imposing a fee on gun purchases, as
originally proposed. The database is supposed to be up and running
by Dec. 1, but putting its financing in doubt is a political
setback.
</P>
<P>
   The practical effect may be to kill the proposed checking system
outright by starving it for money. Alternatively, it means raising
taxes in general or taking funds from some existing program, making
it much more difficult to pass a bill financing the crime-record
check.
</P>
<P>
   Such a centralized checking system is meant to supplant the
Brady law _ named after White House Press Secretary James Brady,
who was wounded in the attempted assassination of President Reagan
_ which will expire in November unless extended. The Brady law
requires a five-day waiting period between buying a gun and
actually taking possession of it. The instant-check system would
allow licensed gun dealers to quickly determine whether a customer
has a disqualifying criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate amendment, of course, is perfectly compatible with
Majority Leader Trent Lott's recent call for ``a well-armed
public.'' He supports a pilot project to turn police stations into
``citizen self-defense centers'' where the cops would train anybody
who comes in off the street in the use of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP House and Senate leadership thinks as one on the gun
control issue. Since the Republicans took over both houses, there
have been no new gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, whose office Weston was
headed for and whose personal guard was one of the victims, has
fought for two years to repeal the ban on assault weapons. He
opposed the Brady law when it passed in 1991 and still does. After
the school shootings, he said, ``This has nothing to do with gun
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the Capitol shootout, the House was set to hold
hearings on extending the legal right of all citizens to carry
concealed weapons. The bill would create a national standard
allowing those with a permit to carry a firearm in one state to use
that same permit in the 29 other states that allow concealed
weapons. But members did have the sensitivity to temporarily cancel
the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA needn't worry, however. The hearings will be
rescheduled. The public safety be damned. There are elections to be
financed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
