<SLUG> BC-GLIMMER-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLIMMERGLASS OPERA: TWO TALES MOVED UP TO MODERN TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ During intermissions at the Glimmerglass
Opera one hears with surprising frequency how remarkable it is to
find an opera company, let alone a successful and adventurous one,
``in the middle of nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the shores of Otsego Lake are far from the opera
world's traditional corridors of power, but now that the
23-year-old company is allied with the New York City Opera _ they
share administrative and artistic staffs, singers and productions _
the real question is whether Glimmerglass is a farm team for the
New York company, or the tail that wags the dog.
</P>
<P>
   Shared new productions are staged first at Glimmerglass, where
they benefit from luxurious rehearsal time. And the productions are
unquestionably seen to better effect in the attractive, comfortably
intimate 912-seat Alice Busch Opera Theater than at the cavernous
New York State Theater.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's festival runs through Aug. 24, and all four of its
productions will make their way to City Opera: Puccini's ``Tosca''
and Handel's ``Partenope'' arrive in the fall; Verdi's ``Falstaff''
and Virgil Thomson's ``Mother of Us All'' are due in future
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Glimmerglass has long cherished the notion that excavating the
psychological truths within a work, or presenting a director's
conception of them, is what a contemporary production should do. If
the director's insights clash with the text of the piece, or with
the spirit and conventions in which the composer worked, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Clashes of this sort occur in both of the works that are
destined more immediately for the City Opera stage, but they weigh
on each work differently.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lamos has wrenched ``Tosca'' from its original setting,
during the Napoleonic wars, to World War II. Making Scarpia and his
henchmen jackbooted Nazis may sharpen the sense of good vs. evil
for a postwar audience. But don't the libretto and the music
(starting with the ominous opening chords) make that clear enough?
</P>
<P>
   The libretto's references to the political landscape of
19th-century Italy dangle awkwardly in this setting. Nor is the
idea particularly fresh: It was first explored in a 1947 Italian
film, ``E Avanti a Lui Tremava Tutta Roma.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Michael Yeargan's stark, sleek sets, Constance
Hoffman's costumes and Robert Wierzel's harshly atmospheric
lighting make for some striking stage pictures, and although
Stewart Robertson's orchestra played scrawnily through much of the
show, the second act was electrifying. The production could work if
not for Lamos' character exaggerations.
</P>
<P>
   Scarpia, for example, crosses himself regularly during the first
act, but after he declares that Tosca makes him forget God, he
grabs his crotch, drops to his knees and masturbates while all
around him nuns and boy choristers sing the Te Deum that ends Act
I.
</P>
<P>
   Provocative tastelessness that makes a point is one thing; here
it is juvenile, even a bit insulting in its implication that
audiences might not apprehend Scarpia's depravity and lust for
Tosca without being batted over the head.
</P>
<P>
   Other touches _ making the Sacristan a spastic, or having Tosca
take a compact from her purse and check her makeup after murdering
Scarpia _ were moves one might expect in a parody by the Gran Scena
Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Vocally, the production's drawing card is Amy Johnson, who sang
Tosca's music with a touching fervency and a strong, attractive
timbre. Michele Bianchini's Scarpia was dry but serviceable in the
Saturday afternoon performance, and Ian DeNolfo's heldentenor
approach to Cavaradossi worked only intermittently, as did his
ability to keep on pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Handel's rarely heard ``Partenope'' is a long, involved comedy
in which the title character, the founder and queen of Naples, is
surrounded by suitors. Arsace, her favorite, has ditched Rosmira
for her, but when Rosmira turns up disguised as a man, Eurimene,
Arsace realizes he is still in love with her. Armindo is too shy to
declare his love to Partenope, and when Emilio, the prince of a
neighboring city, offers the choice of marriage or war, Partenope
fights and wins.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Negrin's production, heard on Friday, moves the action
to the present, more or less: Partenope moves and dresses like a
1920s flapper and is portrayed as sex-obsessed, but Paul Steinberg
has dressed the others in various shades of downtown trendiness,
and Negrin has them behave like Generation X-ers.
</P>
<P>
   John Conklin's sets are beautiful and efficient. As in
``Tosca,'' temporal displacement raises questions: Contemporary
culture doesn't really accommodate the relationships Handel
presents here, yet the result is so entertaining that one willingly
suspends disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   The production has an extraordinary cast: David Daniels'
countertenor is fully supported, flexible and irresistibly
transparent, and he uses those qualities to bring depth and scope
to Arsace's music. David Walker's countertenor is nearly as lovely,
and he conveyed Armindo's combination of modesty and nobility
affectingly.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Saffer's high-spirited portrayal of Partenope was
dramatically and vocally commanding, and Jennifer Dudley as
Rosmira, John McVeigh as Emilio, and Eduardo Chama as the oracle
Ormonte made strong contributions. Harry Bicket, an English
conductor who specializes in early opera, drew a stylish
performance from the orchestra.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
