<SLUG> BC-US-COLOMBIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, COLOMBIAN PRESIDENT MEET AT WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton welcomed Colombia's
president-elect, Andres Pastrana, to the White House in a friendly
meeting Monday that signaled a significant change in US anti-drug
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would help Colombia end a 30-year-old guerrilla
war while pursuing cocaine and heroin traffickers who have paid off
the country's congress, courts, and police.
</P>
<P>
   While aides said Clinton did not promise a specific aid package,
the meeting itself was a reward for Pastrana, a free-market
advocate who was seen as Washington's favorite in Colombia's June
21 elections. The White House rarely invites a Latin American
president-elect in for a talk, and officials said Monday's visit
followed a sharp debate between the State Department and law
enforcement agencies about how to deal with disorder in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting marked a reversal of Washington's relationship with
Bogota and a rebuff of Colombia's current president, Ernesto
Samper, who has been denied entry to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Samper took office four years ago amid accusations by Pastrana
and others that he took millions of dollars in donations from the
Cali drug cartel. After Samper failed to crack down on drug traffic
and corruption, the State Department revoked his travel visa in
1996 and twice rejected, or ``decertified,'' Colombia's anti-drug
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today marks a new beginning in the US-Colombian relations,''
Pastrana told reporters as he left the White House and headed to a
luncheon with Attorney General Janet Reno and other high-ranking
officials, hosted by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. ``The
years of mistrust are now behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Until a few days ago, the administration had simply planned to
send a group of State Department officials to see Pastrana in
Bogota before his inauguration Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But a lobbying effort by Colombia persuaded the White House that
Pastrana should be invited, according to officials who requested
anonymity. They said the State Department's Latin American
specialists have urged the White House to cooperate fully with
Pastrana as he tries to forge peace, while the Pentagon and drug
policy adviser Barry McCaffrey have argued that he is too eager to
make concessions to guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very mixed message going to Colombia because we
have some people in the US government supporting peace but Colombia
has the largest US military aid program in the hemisphere,'' said
Coletta Youngers, an Andean expert at the non-profit Washington
Office on Latin America. Washington gives Colombia about $100
million a year in aid and anti-drug assistance.
</P>
<P>
   US officials agree that Colombia _ the second-largest
Spanish-speaking country in the hemisphere after Mexico _ is an
imporant ally to woo. Colombia is the world's leading producer of
cocaine and leads the hemisphere in kidnappings and per capita
homicides. While the country is not in danger of collapsing,
Colombian guerrillas and traffickers have plagued neighboring
countries, including Ecuador and Venezuela, in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombia is under more pressure than most any other country in
the hemisphere,'' said Viron P. Vaky, senior fellow at the
Inter-American Dialogue in Washington. ``It's facing the most
difficult security problems and it's central to any worldwide
global drug strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   As the administration decided how to deal with Colombia,
officials have disagreed over who should head the US delegation to
the inauguration. Pastrana's cooperation is considered so important
that some officials wanted Albright to attend, but she will be in
Italy for the wedding of her spokesman, James P. Rubin. McCaffrey
demanded that he head the group, officials said, but the White
House thought that would send the wrong message to a country that
already feels bullied by US anti-drug policies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's friend and former Latin American envoy, Thomas
``Mack'' McLarty, will lead the delegation. McLarty, who is far
more interested in talking about increasing trade than cracking
down on drugs, is expected to assure Colombian business leaders
that Washington wants to ``de-narcotize'' its dealings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that the way to strengthen our relationship on
narcotics is to strenghten our relationship on other things,'' said
Arturo Valenzuela, director of the Center for Latin American
Studies at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana will return for a state visit later this year, the
White House announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
