<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CIA-HNS &LR;      08-03 0263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES NAMING CIA HEADQUARTERS AFTER BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ronald Reagan got his airport and now George Bush
has his CIA headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The House gave its unanimous approval Monday to a measure naming
the Langley, Va., building housing the nation's premier
intelligence organization the George H.W. Bush Center for Central
Intelligence. The Senate is expected to pass the same measure when
it returns from its summer recess in early September.
</P>
<P>
   In a tribute to the former president who resides in Houston, his
congressman, Rep. Bill Archer, called Bush ``a man of unblemished
integrity'' and said it was fitting that the CIA building should be
named after the only president to serve as head of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 74, served as director of the CIA for a year during the
Ford administration. He has also served as vice president, United
Nations ambassador, envoy to China, Texas congressman and chairman
of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   President Ford named Bush as director of the CIA in 1976 when
the agency was being investigated by Congress. While in charge,
Bush helped draft orders to prevent violations of CIA regulations
as well as federal and international laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``He created strength and stability in the intelligence
community, and he is widely credited with restoring (CIA staff)
morale,'' said Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va. ``What better way to honor
George Bush than to place his name on CIA headquarters?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1850EDT &QL; 
