<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT &LR;      08-03 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER SALES EXCEED 200,000 FOR 6TH STRAIGHT MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Chrysler Corp. announced Monday that its sales of cars
and trucks in July were up slightly from levels a year earlier but
down from the brisk pace of the previous two months.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler's sales totaled 206,018 cars and trucks, up 3 percent
from the level in July 1997. In both May and June this year, when
incentives to buyers were in place, Chrysler sales hit 250,000
units, reaching that level for the first time ever, and inventories
were lowered on dealer lots. Still, July marked the sixth
consecutive month of sales exceeding 200,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of Chrysler's sales is derived from healthy demand
for its trucks, particularly the Dodge Durango and the Jeep Grand
Cherokee, Cherokee and Wrangler. The automaker sold 146,503 trucks
in July, up 9 percent from levels a year earlier. It sold 59,515
cars, down 8 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota reported a 13 percent gain over July 1997, with its
Toyota and Lexus divisions together selling 122,550 cars and
trucks. The Toyota division, led by its best-selling Camry,
recorded sales of 107,877, up 8 percent from a year earlier,
marking the first time in its 41-year history that its sales topped
100,000 vehicles in each of three consecutive months. Lexus
reported its best-ever sales month with July sales of 14,674, up 58
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Honda reported that July gave it the second-best month ever.
Honda and Acura sold 92,820 cars and trucks, up 6 percent from a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz of North America reported a 53 percent increase
from a year earlier with July sales of 10,310 cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Subaru of America's sales totaled 13,071 cars and trucks, up 16
percent from July 1997, for Subaru's best July since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Saab, which has introduced two new models in recent months,
announced sales of 15,977 cars, an 11 percent rise from July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi sold 15,474 cars and trucks in July, a decrease of 8
percent from the level a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   July sales for the industry, some of which remain to be reported
over the next few days, are expected to be off overall from last
year's strong July and from the extraordinarily brisk pace of May
and June, when sales were the highest since the mid 1980s, thanks
to attractive consumer incentives that expired at the end of June
and in early July.
</P>
<P>
   A six-week strike by the United Automobile Workers union at two
General Motors parts plants, which forced the closing of nearly all
of the GM's North American plants, also weakened sales of cars and
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the early reports suggest that auto sales in July may
come in stronger than some analysts had predicted. ``Industry sales
will be off about 6 to 7 percent from strong year-ago levels, but
not bad given the problems at GM,'' said David Healy, an auto
analyst for Burnham Securities Inc., New York.
</P>
<P>
   Healy predicted that the seasonally adjusted selling rate, which
reached 16.7 million cars and light trucks in June _ the highest
level since 1986 _ would be about 14.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict that Ford sales, which are to be announced
Tuesday, will be flat.
</P>
<P>
   GM reports sales on Wednesday. Ronald Zarrella, vice president
in charge of GM's North American Vehicle Sales, Service and
Marketing Group, said a month ago that GM's July sales would be
down as much as 40 percent because of the strike, causing GM's
market share to slide to an all-time low of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some competitors picked up share from GM customers not willing
to wait,'' Healy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
