<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5889 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-GOV-HNS &LR;      08-03 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISSUE-ORIENTED DEBATE HIGHLIGHTS DIFFERENCES IN CALIF. CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY-COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Despite all the sniping between Attorney General Dan
Lungren and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the first of a series of debates
in the race for governor was surprising in its focus on issues.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the primary campaign, which was dominated by
mudslinging often dished out in expensive television ads, the
Republican and Democratic nominees for governor clashed in an open
forum over critical issues such as taxes and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that struck me was that they really laid out their
agendas,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, political analyst at the
Claremont Graduate University. ``They really went out there and
laid out their ideas. The question now is, what are they going to
do in the next four debates?''
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong debate, held Friday night at the San Diego
Convention Center, underscored some of the deep ideological
differences between the two candidates, especially on abortion,
affirmative action and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The debate also provided an early peek at the issues the
candidates believe they can use against each other to sway
undecided voters before the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the Democrat, repeatedly talked of his support for
abortion rights and his plans to reform California's ailing public
education system. Davis' advisers believe both themes will have
strong appeal with women, who early polls show are leaning heavily
toward the former two-term controller.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the core issue (of abortion), we are in fundamental
disagreement,'' Davis said. ``I trust a woman, who in concert with
her own God, her own doctor and her own conscience comes to a
decision on the most personal and delicate thing that involves a
woman's health. You (Lungren) don't trust a woman to make that
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, the Republican candidate, painted his opponent as
outside the mainstream for voting against bills to expand the death
penalty and for opposing ballot initiatives to end affirmative
action and to cut benefits to illegal immigrants. Both measures
were passed by California voters.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren leaned most heavily on the two issues political analysts
say are his strongest: taxes and crime. The two-term attorney
general said crime rates, which soared to record levels in the
1980s, dropped to 1967 levels during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has tried to blunt his opponent's perceived advantage on
the tax issue, proposing an investment tax credit and a cut in the
vehicle-license fee that Lungren and Republican Gov. Pete Wilson
want to abolish. Lungren warned voters not to trust Davis on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bring taxes down a lot more than Gray will,'' he said.
``Just look at our records.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus on issues after a primary election that was dominated
by personalities was welcomed by members of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to see they're going to stick to the issues,'' said
Gene Block, a Los Angeles resident who works in construction.
</P>
<P>
   The debate at times wandered off course. A discussion on
improving relations with Mexico drifted off into a dispute over
whether Davis eschewed his state responsibilities by missing a 1996
conference on trade issues south of the border. Lungren said Davis
was in New York City raising money at the time.
</P>
<P>
   During a discussion of the death penalty, which both candidates
support, Davis praised Singapore's hard-line criminal justice
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Singapore is a good starting point in terms of law and
order,'' Davis said. ``I think there ought to be clear rules. You
can't punish people enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said his comments were limited to the country's penalties
for violent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The frank tenor of the debate was in part a reflection of the
format, which allowed the candidates to question each other as well
as respond to questions from a panel of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The head-to-head format allows candidates to get under each
other's skins,'' said Barbara O'Connor, a communications professor
at Cal State Sacramento. ``I think it's great for the viewer. I
think he or she can make up their minds about how the candidates do
under pressure, how they do when they're under fire, and how their
tempers hold.''
</P>
<P>
   The next televised debate is set for Aug. 18 in Fresno, followed
by debates in San Francisco, Los Angeles and Sacramento.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
