<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-MEDICAID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS URGE MEDICAID COVERAGE FOR HIV-INFECTED PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sixty-eight House members asked the Clinton
administration on Monday to designate people with HIV as
``disabled'' so they can qualify for Medicaid and get drugs that
can delay the onset of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Donna Shalala, the secretary of the Department of
Health and Human Services, the lawmakers urged that Medicaid be
expanded to cover HIV-positive recipients so they can afford the
expensive HIV-fighting ``protease cocktail.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug cocktail, which can cost $12,000 to $15,000 a year, has
been shown to reduce the amount of HIV in a person's blood stream.
HIV _ the human immunodeficiency virus _ causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid _ the federal-state health insurance program that
covers low-income individuals and people with disabilities _ now
covers individuals with HIV only if they are sick or disabled. In
effect, this precludes them from getting early treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The 68 letter signers included House Minority Leader Richard A.
Gephardt, D-Mo., and Reps. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., Jim Turner,
D-Texas, Nick V. Lampson, D-Texas, Pete Stark, D-Calif., Jim
McDermott, D-Wash., Lois Capps, D-Calif., Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., Ellen
Tauscher, D-Calif., Anna Eshoo, D-Calif., Vic Fazio, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unconscionable to deny people living with HIV the drugs
we know can help keep them well simply because they have no health
insurance or are not yet sick enough to qualify for Medicaid,''
Gephardt said in statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said new HIV treatments should be available to all who
need them.
</P>
<P>
   ``While government researchers issue hopeful statements about
the benefits of early therapy and news reports herald a new age for
people with AIDS, Medicaid trails the science,'' she said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., wrote a similar letter
following the June 25 U.S. Supreme Court ruling that federal laws
barring discrimination against disabled Americans applied to
HIV-positive individuals, even though they were without obvious
symptoms. The case involved a HIV-positive woman who was refused
treatment by a Maine dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli argued that HHS should follow the Supreme Court's
example by ``reinventing Medicaid'' so that low-income HIV-positive
people can benefit from drugs that postpone AIDS symptoms.
Torricelli is considering legislation that would require Medicaid
to pay for drugs for HIV-infected people.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore also has endorsed the proposed Medicaid
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal Medicaid statutes, Shalala has the authority to
expand the program to cover HIV-infected people if she can show
such a step would be cost neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt and Pelosi argue that would be the case here because,
they contend, people receiving earlier therapy would stay healthy
longer, avoiding some infections that can require costly
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   They also argued that early HIV treatment would result in a
savings to the Supplemental Security Income program, which provides
benefits to disabled people, including those with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   HHS spokesman Richard Sorian said the administration ``is
examining all of the more recent data to see whether or not a
change in policy is called for.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Zingale, executive director of the Washington advocacy
group AIDS ACTION, says the current HHS policy is badly flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that under the current Medicaid rules, you have
to have full-blown AIDS before you can have access to AIDS
preventing drugs,'' Zingale said. ``If traffic safety regulations
followed this approach you'd put the airbags in the car after it
crashes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
