<SLUG> BC-FIRE-PACT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES RESOLUTION URGING FIRE PACT BETWEEN U.S., MEXICO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House gave unanimous approval Monday to a
resolution calling for the United States and Mexico to negotiate a
cooperative fire suppression agreement similar to the one that has
existed between the U.S. and Canadian governments since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, said that reaching an agreement would
allow U.S. and Mexican authorities ``to respond more quickly and
efficiently'' to wildfires, such as the ones this spring that
devastated more than 1 million acres along the U.S.-Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen, joined by Rep. Kevin Brady, R-Texas, said a fire
suppression agreement could help prevent the kind of situation this
spring when more than 10,000 fires in Mexico created a heavy layer
of smoke over much of Texas. The smoke, combined with the heat,
forced officials in Houston and elsewhere across the state to
declare a series of health alerts to keep people indoors,
especially the elderly and young school children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is real and as we have seen from the fires from
southern Mexico, you don't have to live next to the fire to be
affected by it,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials are engaged in negotiations
with Mexico to finalize an agreement that would allow firefighters
from both countries to assist one another in fighting wildfires
that break out within 125 miles of the border.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
