the foster care system, showing how child welfare officials have
not made much progress improving the plight of foster children. In
death, Elisa Izquierdo became a national symbol of all that was
wrong with child welfare in New York City, exposing the sloppy
investigations that allowed her to suffer and die under the city's
watch. And in some ways, her siblings' long journey through the
child welfare system highlights a less sensational, but far more
common problem: the experience of thousands of children who
languish in foster care for years without finding permanent homes.
