<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUNS-TAYLOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SIGN TAYLOR TO ONE-YEAR STINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins and veteran center Tim Taylor, scheduled to
meet in a hearing Monday in Toronto, averted arbitration when they
agreed on a one-year contract Sunday. The club didn't release the
salary figure, although it's likely that Taylor, who made $425,000
last season, will now pull in something in the $750,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's best for both sides,'' said Taylor. ``No one's a loser
and everyone is a winner. I think this all could've been avoided if
we'd sat down earlier but I'm relieved to get it over with. Now I
feel a part of the team again. I feel a sense of responsibility to
prepare for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 29, made the 75-minute drive from his home in Stratford,
Ontario, to Toronto for the hearing, but rather than sitting
through a tense hearing Monday, he went with a friend to the Hockey
Hall of Fame and for the first time saw the Stanley Cup with his
name engraved on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really great,'' said Taylor, who was on the Red Wings'
championship club in 1996-97. ``There also were a couple of
pictures up that I was in and I saw the video clips and the
highlights.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor even participated in the interactive shooting gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend told me he'd give me 10 shots to hit nine targets,''
said Taylor. ``It took me 14 so I guess I'd better keep
practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who is scheduled to become an unrestricted free agent at
the end of the 1998-99 season, is thrilled to have the distraction
of thinking about a contract removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was constantly wondering what was going to happen,'' said
Taylor, who had a career-high 20 goals and 31 points in 79 games
last year. ``I was pretty anxious about it. It really was a
distraction. At times I was taking it kind of personal. But looking
back on it, I had to keep in mind that it is a business. If they
can get me for the cheapest price, then they're doing their job. My
agent and I are trying to get the most we can get. After reading
their brief, they were pretty honest. They didn't cut me up. In all
fairness, they were responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said the sides
weren't that far apart to start with. O'Connell, reached by
telephone in Nashville, where he is scheduled to attend GM meetings
today, said after the sides exchanged briefs it was clear that a
deal could be struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really drove this is that Tim really wanted to be in
Boston,'' said O'Connell. ``He likes the city, he likes the
environment. What averted this was that the position the club took
and the one Tim presented were so similar. Both were realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Boston,'' said Taylor. ``I like the coaching staff. I
think I've established myself as a good, solid, checking center.
It's a great situation. I think this team has a really good chance
to grow together.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the sides have kept the door wide open for further
negotiations that would lock him up rather than allow him to reach
total free agency next July 1. O'Connell said the team thought the
salary demands for a three-year deal were high but he told Taylor
he would be willing to reopen talks at midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Bruins have hearings scheduled for next week. Forward
Dmitri Khristich is due for his next Tuesday while goalie Rob
Tallas is scheduled for next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he had some positive discussions with Bob Gerow,
the representative for free-agent center Jason Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we'd get back to him with a proposal,'' said
O'Connell. ``Maybe next week. It was a good dialogue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
