<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BILLS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT     08-03 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLS COUNTING ON JOHNSON-FLUTIE TANDEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDONIA, N.Y. _ Next door to the Buffalo Bills' training camp
at Fredonia University is an intriguing setup that lets fans of
nearly any age try their hand at some NFL-type football drills.
</P>
<P>
   So on a recent day there was the engaging sight of a 5-year-old
boy struggling to toss a football through a big hole in a huge
wooden board. The boy would toss the football. Clunk! The football
would bounce off the board. The boy would try again. Clunk! Again.
Again. Again. Clunk! Clunk! Clunk!
</P>
<P>
   Sort of like the Bills' passing game last season.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo ranked 25th in passing yards gained among the National
Football League's 30 teams (the team's rushing offense was a
respectable 14th). In a league in which 17 teams produced 20 or
more passing touchdowns, the Bills had only 14. Only one team _ San
Diego, with 12 _ was worse.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the Bills' quarterbacks _ Todd Collins, Alex
Van Pelt and Billy Joe Hobert (now with New Orleans) _ were not
ready to replace Jim Kelly, the club's leading career passer who
retired after the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Bills did something about it. In camp are two newcomers
at quarterback with vastly different games and backgrounds. The
Bills traded with Jacksonville for Rob Johnson and then looked to
the Canadian Football League to swipe Doug Flutie. It is Johnson
and Flutie now, and Johnson gets first crack.
</P>
<P>
   Has Buffalo found an answer?
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we do know is that Jim Kelly is not here anymore,''
said Wade Phillips, who has replaced Marv Levy as the head coach
after serving as the Bills' defensive coordinator for the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not the Super Bowl Buffalo Bills,'' he said. ``This
team was 6-10 last year. We'd love to have some new tradition; we
can't live off the past. We think Rob is a quarterback who can do
it all. He throws the long ball and looks downfield a lot. He has
command and presence. He's not a rookie, so he knows the speed and
size of the game. Doug is a great leader, and he's mobile. He will
learn the entire offense, know everybody's job, and he's like
having a coach on the field. Because he moves so well, we'll have
to use him differently from Rob. He will bootleg and roll out and
throw on the run and scramble some. He'll give us another dimension
at the position.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is not exaggerating when he says that the Bills are not
the same team that, under Levy, made four straight appearances in
the Super Bowl this decade. Only four players _ Thurman Thomas,
Bruce Smith, Mike Pike and Andre Reed _ remain from those four
teams. Thirty-three of 84 players on the Bills' roster are either
rookies or players with only one year of pro experience, and 64
have four or fewer years of pro experience.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 25, has three years, all with Jacksonville. He and the
Jet receiver Keyshawn Johnson were a dynamic twosome at the
University of Southern California, but in Jacksonville he was a
backup to Mark Brunell. Johnson threw seven regular-season passes
in 1995, none in '96 and 35 last year. He is sort of a
known-unknown quantity.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Brunell was hurt during the preseason, Johnson
started a Monday night game against San Francisco and torched the
49ers' pass defense with the nation watching. He played well the
following week against Atlanta and then started the season opener
against Baltimore. Jacksonville won, 28-27, and this is what
Johnson did: 20 of 24 passing for 294 yards with two touchdowns and
a rushing touchdown. His completion percentage of 83.3 for that
game set a Jacksonville record, and it was the best by a first-time
starter since the 1970 merger of the NFL and the American Football
League.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Johnson missed the next game with an injury and then Brunell
returned the following week. Johnson sat for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But on the strength of his three-game audition, Johnson earned
plenty of interest, especially from the Bills, who traded first-and
fourth-round draft spots for him and then signed him to a
five-year, $25.5 million contract with an $8.5 million signing
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought my time would come,'' Johnson said. ``I knew
I had the physical tools to play in this game and I had the two
things it takes to be successful at quarterback _ toughness and
smarts. I don't have the Brett Favre arm. I don't have Mark
Brunell's feet or elusiveness. I'd like to think I'm in-between on
those things. I pride myself on accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Bills figured I was a young quarterback who had
been in the league and was worth the chance, as opposed to a rookie
quarterback coming straight out of college _ that's a crap shoot.
I've played and been around. But I know that fans here are like
fans everywhere. You don't perform well, and they boo you. You
don't perform well often enough, and they will help get rid of you.
I've got thick skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is 6 feet 4 inches, 214 pounds. He is from Newport
Beach, Calif. He is all beach, sun and surf. The problem is, there
is little to none of that in Buffalo in November and December, when
the weather turns brutal and game conditions are often ugly.
Johnson said he can handle it, though. The Bills think he can, but
no one knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   But Flutie certainly can.
</P>
<P>
   He has played in blizzards in Canada and has succeeded. He
played eight CFL seasons and won the most valuable player award six
times, along with five passing titles and three Grey Cup
championships. Before that, Flutie, 35, played four NFL seasons,
splitting time with Chicago and New England from 1986 through 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his mobility, the Bills can use him as a change of
pace, inserting him for six to eight plays a game to ruffle the
opposing defense. And maybe Flutie, at 5-10 and 175 pounds, will
play more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athleticism and experience is my game,'' Flutie said. ``I'm
thrilled to be back in the NFL. I don't look at this year in
Buffalo as rebuilding. We want to win, and we have a nucleus of
veterans and youth to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo defense ranked No. 9 overall last season. Antowain
Smith and Thomas are anchors of the running game. The receivers
include Reed and Quinn Early and the former Dallas Super Bowl
champion Kevin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Bills, it all starts at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kelly is not there anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what people expect and I accept that,'' Johnson said.
``The Buffalo fans want the Bills to win at least a couple of Super
Bowls. I'd take one _ and we'd go from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
