<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL SET TO RELEASE PALESTINIAN PRISONERS IN EFFORT TO REVIVE
TALKS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Apparently in an effort to rescue imperiled peace
talks, Israel was reported on Monday to be preparing to free dozens
of Palestinian prisoners whose release had been urged by
Palestinian negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, first reported by Israel Radio, was discussed on
Monday by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's aides, although a
formal meeting on the subject was postponed until Tuesday. And
while Netanyahu's two top security advisers have disagreed over the
timing and wisdom of the proposed step, aides to Netanyahu said
they expected the plan to be carried out in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The idea gained prominence Monday after Palestinian officials
warned starkly on Sunday that they were prepared to call a halt to
meetings between the two sides unless Israel used a meeting that
was taking place Monday night to propose new ways to break a
16-month deadlock in their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   A prisoner release would not address the Palestinians' chief
concern: Netanyahu's rejection of an American-backed plan calling
for Israel to pull back its troops from an additional 13 percent of
the West Bank as part of a long-overdue troop withdrawal. And
because Israel would still hold 3,000 Palestinian prisoners, some
Palestinian officials dismissed the idea of a new prisoner release
as an empty gesture.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared, though, that such a gesture might be enough to
dissuade the Palestinians from calling an immediate halt to the
talks, which Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's Cabinet described
on Saturday as having been ``a waste of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have a keen interest in portraying Israel as
the obstacle to progress, and as word of a possible prisoner
release began to spread Monday afternoon, a top Palestinian
official, Saeb Erekat, appeared to back away from the threat to
break off talks if Monday's working-level talks were not decisive.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Monday's meeting would be the last, Erekat said,
``I don't want to make any prejudgments.'' He said that Arafat and
other Palestinian leaders would review the session's outcome and
then decide what steps to take next.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Netanyahu called on the Palestinians ``to stop
using the language of ultimatums.'' He added: ``I think the
Palestinians would be ill-advised to create artificial crises.
That's not going to lead anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Within Netanyahu's government, the main champion of a new
prisoner release has been the public security minister, Avigdor
Kahalani. Kahalani heads the moderate Third Way party, which has
threatened to pull out of the government unless Netanyahu reaches
an accord with the Palestinians. He characterized the plan as one
bound to be welcomed by Arafat as a show of Israeli good will.
</P>
<P>
   Yitzhak Mordechai, the defense minister, had reportedly opposed
the plan on grounds that such a step should be taken only as part
of a broader accord, which he has said should be hammered out as
quickly as possible. But an Israeli official who spoke on the
condition of anonymity said he understood that Mordechai had shown
a new willingness to relax that objection.
</P>
<P>
   Some strong opposition was voiced, however, from the far right
of Netanyahu's Likud Party. Conservatives, including Michael Eitan,
an outspoken member of the party's right wing, said that any
decision to release more Palestinian prisoners at this juncture
could be dangerous and foolhardy.
</P>
<P>
   The release would probably include as many as 100 Palestinians,
most of them ill and none seen as a security threat, Israeli
officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As reports of the Israeli plan began to circulate Monday, the
Palestinian authorities submitted their own list of 120 prisoners
they said they want freed. At the same time, dozens of Palestinians
staged a demonstration outside Arafat's office in Gaza in which
they held aloft photographs of relatives held prisoner in Israeli
jails and demanded that the Palestinian leader secure their
release.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves appeared to suggest that freeing more Palestinians
from Israeli jails might well help to shore up Arafat's standing
among Palestinians, who are growing angry because his quest for
peace has produced so few tangible dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Palestinian officials have shown no sign of backing away
from what they have made their bottom-line demand: that Netanyahu
carry out the 13 percent troop withdrawal that American officials
have called the minimum that the Palestinians could accept. Since
the plan was presented to the two sides in March, Netanyahu's
government has said repeatedly that it cannot envision ceding so
much territory to the Palestinians and has offered only what the
Palestinians have rejected as unacceptable alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the Israeli party to say yes to the American
initiative,'' Erekat, the Palestinian negotiator, said in an
interview published Monday. ``The issue does not need negotiations
but needs decisions, and we are waiting for the Israeli
government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
