<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCE MINISTER'S COMMENTS DRIVES YEN DOWN AGAINST DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The yen fell to its lowest level against the dollar in
seven weeks on Monday, as currency traders tentatively tested the
new Japanese government's resolve to let the market determine the
currency's value.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. on Monday, one dollar could buy 145.63 yen, up from
144.79 yen when trading opened Monday morning and from 144.70 yen
late Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Many currency traders and economists expect the dollar to test
this year's high of 146.75 yen any day, although few have forgotten
being burned by intervention by the United States and Japanese
governments after that high was hit on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   Kiichi Miyazawa, the newly appointed minister of finance, caught
the markets' attention last week when he suggested that markets,
rather than governments, should determine the appropriate
dollar-yen exchange rate, although he hedged his comments by saying
intervention was ``all right'' in an ``extreme situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The comment by Miyazawa when he said he would leave the market
to determine exchange rates was what got the most interest in the
market, and now they're speculating about whether he will be as
committed as his predecessor to capping the market,'' said Robert
Alan Feldman, senior economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman has set a target of 160 yen to the dollar by the end of
this year based on continuing gloomy economic fundamentals. On
Monday, the Japan Automobile Dealers Association said domestic
vehicle sales fell 8.4 percent from a year earlier, the 16th
consecutive month that sales have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding mini-vehicles, however, sales climbed 13.5 percent
from the previous month, and two of the country's five largest car
makers, Honda and Mazda, reported a 3.5 percent and 4.5 percent
sales increase, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The financial markets have been skeptical of new Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi's ability to address Japan's weak economy and shaky
banking system quickly and comprehensively.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's new economic team _ including Miyazawa, Taichi Sakaiya,
the head of the Economic Planning Agency, and Toyoo Gyohten, who is
the prime minister's special adviser on financial issues _ has won
some grudging respect from the markets, but doubts still linger.
</P>
<P>
   As yet, they have not articulated a single philosophy on what
economic changes they will pursue, and Miyazawa is blamed in some
quarters for doing little to rein in the speculative growth that
created Japan's economic bubble in the 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1918EDT &QL; 
