<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BOB-REVIEW-440&AMP;ADD     08-03 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BOB-REVIEW-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAXIMUM BOB': ELMORE LEONARD'S JUDGE TRANSFORMED INTO A QUIRKY
GOOD OLD BOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at the end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Please check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1991 novel ``Maximum Bob,'' Elmore Leonard wrote that the
title character, a crackpot Florida judge guided more by whim than
law, looked like the actor Harry Dean Stanton. Things change. Now
Judge Bob Gibbs shows up on television looking like the actor Beau
Bridges. Not only that, his chilly nastiness seems to have warmed
into good-old-boy quirkiness. He's nearly cuddly.
</P>
<P>
   That may be disappointing for Leonard's devotees who enjoy
skulking along the moral fringes with his losers. (They're
sometimes winners, rarely heroes.) But the judge's transformation
holds promise for viewers.
</P>
<P>
   How much promise depends on the progress of ABC's ``Maximum
Bob'' series, which begins a seven-week trial run Tuesday night at
10. The executive producers include Barry Sonnenfeld, the film
director who authentically conveyed Leonard's cockeyed netherworld
in ``Get Shorty,'' and Alex Gansa, whose television credits include
a stint as supervising producer of ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   The network provided advance tapes of two hourlong episodes: the
show's pilot, to be broadcast Tuesday night, and the third
installment, scheduled for Aug. 18. The former is a goofy
curiosity. The latter has an offbeat charm that could grow on you.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's hour, directed by Sonnenfeld and written by Gansa,
crams in many of the plot elements from the novel while sowing
seeds for the series. We meet Bridges as the judge and Kiersten
Warren as his wife, Leanne, who spouts a lot of kooky spiritualism,
sometimes in the voice of a long-dead black girl named Wanda Grace.
(Leanne, like the other characters, is white.) Bob, who was
otherwise married when he spotted the much-younger Leanne when she
was a mermaid in an underwater show, has grown tired of her and
decides to scare her out of his life with the aid of an alligator.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the book's other major figures have been transformed.
Kathy Baker, Leonard's tough but vulnerable newly divorced young
probation officer, has become a tough but vulnerable newly divorced
public defender, played by Liz Vassey. Bob still makes a pass at
her. Her romantic interest, a suave police officer named Gary
Hammond, has become the not so suave Sheriff (Sam Robards),
fulfilling his late wife's wish that he learn the tango.
</P>
<P>
   The show flies by in a blur of bright lights and not so bright
grotesque minor characters, one of whom holds Leanne hostage and
seeks her help in writing a ransom note. ``How do you spell
orels?'' he asks, as in ``Do what I say orels I will put her in the
wood chipper.'' Stick with it. Before the final fade-out, those
exploding fireballs in the sky are explained.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   What isn't explained, at least not yet, is what happened between
the pilot and the show to be seen in two weeks. We've now come
pretty far from Leonard's territory, but this new place has charms
of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Bob has become even more warm and fuzzy. He and Leanne, who has
deep-sixed the voice from the great beyond, seem to have fallen
back in love. She takes organic fruit to the women her husband has
thrown into the local jail. One of them is Bob's ex-wife, Rosellen
Fortenot (Lee Garlington), to whom he declares, ``You are to
cynicism what Vermont is to syrup.''
</P>
<P>
   May she return, along with Rudolfo Esquival (Miguel Sandoval),
the sheriff's tango teacher, who has more than dance steps on his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   The episode, written by Theresa Rebeck and directed by Marc
Buckland, prime-time veterans, has an off-the-wall plot that
includes Fidel Castro, smuggled cigars, poisoned darts, an NBA
franchise and the state tango championship, not necessarily in that
order. There are also a pair of mysterious government agents with
black suits and dark glasses, an obvious but deft poke at
Sonnenfeld's film ``Men in Black.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Bridges, grinning under his redneck's buzz cut,
looks as if he's having a wonderful time. If ``Maximum Bob'' can
maintain its off-kilter inventiveness, it could build a following.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   MAXIMUM BOB
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Tuesday night at 10
</P>
<P>
   Barry Sonnenfeld, Barry Josephson and Alex Gansa, executive
producers. A Sonnenfeld/Josephson production in association with
Warner Bros. Television. Sonnenfeld, director of the pilot; Gansa,
writer of the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   With: Beau Bridges (Bob Gibbs), Liz Vassey (Kathy Baker), Sam
Robards (Sheriff Gary Hammond), Kiersten Warren (Leanne Lancaster),
RaeVen Larrymore-Kelly (Wanda Grace), Lee Garlington (Rosellen
Fortenot) and Miguel Sandoval (Rudolfo Esquival).
</P>
</TEXT>
