<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER TREATS ONSTAGE AND OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 9.)  
 (JT)  
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blockbuster events along the routes of summer travel tend to
find you: fireworks on the Fourth, state fairs, major festivals.
But sometimes news of events that families remember forever is
encountered by accident, in a flier at a rest stop, or a free local
summer-events publication.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a peek at choice events in museums, on college campuses
and at outdoor amphitheaters. On campuses, the schedule is skinnier
in August to give the schools a chance to get ready for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, information is given on a new service for parents
of high school students who want to visit any of 15 colleges in the
Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alfresco Plays &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor dramas are major attractions in the United States, with
about 100 scheduled. Around half are on historic themes, and many
of the others are Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Snow Camp Outdoor Theater,  &LR; Snow Camp, N.C., between
Greensboro and Chapel Hill, is presenting William Hardy's ``Sword
of Peace,'' about the Cane Creek Society of Friends and the
difficulties that adherents of nonviolence encountered in the
Revolution. This alternates with ``Pathway to Freedom,'' about
antislavery efforts in North Carolina before the Civil War.
Performances are 8:30 p.m. from Wednesday to Saturday until Aug.
15. Admission: $10, senior citizens $8 and children under 11 $5.
Call (800) 726-5115.
</P>
<P>
   Several plays tell of white settlers who were captured by
Indians and escaped or remained to start a different life. The
musical ``Blue Jacket,'' written by W.L. Mundell and composed by
Michael Rasbury, is about an Ohio Valley man who became a Shawnee
chief. This story is presented by  &UR; First Frontier  &LR; in Xenia, Ohio,
30 minutes east of Dayton. Performances Tuesday to Sunday at 8 p.m.
until Sept. 6; admission is $8 to $14, $6 for children under 13.
Information: (937) 376-4318.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legend of Jenny Wiley'' is a musical drama about a white
woman who fled captivity by Indians in the 1780s and whose story
became a legend. It is presented until Aug. 23 by the  &UR; Jenny Wiley
Theater  &LR; in Prestonsburg, in eastern Kentucky, in rotation with
``Smoke on the Mountain'' and ``Cinderella.'' Performances at 8:15
p.m. Tuesday to Sunday, with ``Jenny Wiley'' usually on Thursday
and Friday. Admission is $15, $13 for seniors and $8 for students
under 18; (606) 886-9274.
</P>
<P>
   In Alturas, nearly surrounded by a national forest in northeast
California, the  &UR; Modoc County Arts Council  &LR; will present ``Lost
River: the Story of the Modoc Indian War,'' by Ben Van Meter. In
the 1872-73 war, Indians refusing to leave their homes held off the
Army for nine months before fleeing and being tracked down and
tried. Performances are Aug. 27 to 29 at 8 p.m. and Aug. 30 at 3
p.m. Admission is $8, $6 for children and seniors. Call (530)
233-5454.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Institute of Outdoor Drama &LR;  maintains a Web site:
unc.edu/depts/outdoor. An annual directory costs $5 by mail: CB
3240, Nationsbank Plaza, University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill,
N.C. 27599.
</P>
<P>
   Campus offerings often provide a showcase for summer-session
arts students.  &UR; Bates College  &LR; in Lewiston, Maine, is holding a
dance festival through Aug. 16, with visiting companies on the
schedule. ``Different Voices,'' on Aug. 13, for example, includes
dances by Japanese, Javanese, Cape Verdean, South African and
Australian artists who have been part of an international
residency. Admission is $12. ``Young Choreographers/New Works''
will be offered Aug. 14 and 15 at the Schaeffer Theater, for $6
admission. The student finale, free admission, is on Aug. 15.
Information: (207) 786-6381.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Skidmore College  &LR; in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., a major tourism
area, stays busy all summer with writing classes and jazz
festivals. In August, the 250 members of the Boys Choir of Harlem
are at their summer camp. On Aug. 18 at 7:30 p.m., the choir will
offer a concert for its own benefit at the outdoor Saratoga
Performing Arts Center. Seats are $15, $8 for children; lawn
admission is $8, free for children under 12. Skidmore: (518)
580-5590.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 21, the modern dance students of the New York State
Summer School of the Arts in Saratoga Springs offer a final
performance at the dance theater at Skidmore. This is free. Until
this performance, the students are in residence at the National
Museum of Dance on South Broadway in Saratoga Springs, where two
daily rehearsals, from 10 a.m. to noon and 2 to 4 p.m. are open
Tuesday to Saturday. The admission prices are $1 for children under
12, $2.50 for students and senior citizens and $3.50 general
admission. Information: (518) 584-2225.
</P>
<P>
   At the  &UR; University of Western Washington  &LR; in Bellingham, 80
miles north of Seattle, the student theater will present ``Hay
Fever'' by Noel Coward, ``The Fantastiks'' and ``My Fair Lady'' in
repertory rotation until Aug. 20 with performances Tuesday to
Sunday at 7:30 p.m., and Sunday at 2 p.m. Admission to the first
two plays is $13, $12 for seniors, $11 for students and $9 for
youths; ``My Fair Lady'' is slightly higher. Call (360) 650-6146.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Underwater Camping &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Aquariums, as any parent of a Scout knows, are providing
entrancing opportunities: Sleep with the fishes! Now at least three
of these are offering overnights to parents and children who are
not part of a group. It sounds wonderful to put a sleeping bag down
by the Coral Reef tank, as they do in Tampa, but Betty Kay Swanson,
who directs the program at the  &UR; John G. Shedd Aquarium  &LR; in Chicago,
says that the absolute best thing in the kids' eyes is to be in the
aquarium after hours and to talk with the staff who watch the
place.
</P>
<P>
   These programs all require reservations; participants bring
their sleeping bags and pillows and pay a fee for meals and special
programs. The Shedd has been doing these programs for seven years
for members, but now offers them for others, too, with as many as
350 people participating. The minimum age is 5; all children must
be accompanied by an adult. The next night is Sept. 25. The cost is
$45, $40 for members, with dinner, a bedtime snack and Continental
breakfast. Information: (312) 692-3333. The  &UR; Florida Aquarium  &LR; in
Tampa has been offering regular family overnights; the September
date is pending. Information: (813) 273-4176. The  &UR; New England
Aquarium  &LR; in Boston is offering two to the general public this
year; the next is Nov. 13. Call (617) 973-5206.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New College Try &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For those already looking toward life as a freshman in the fall
of '99, checking out Boston universities has been made easier by an
organization called Campus Visit. The organization says that
100,000 students take a look at the Boston area, so 15 colleges set
up a consortium to provide information to potential visitors. A
magazine, Campus Visit, 1998, is available from the colleges or on
the Web at campusvisit.com. Sheets on any participating college may
be ordered by touch-tone phone through (888) 998-4748, and an
affiliated travel agency can make reservations for hotels, air
travel and a car. Participating schools are: Bentley, Berklee,
Boston University, Brandeis, Emerson, Harvard and Radcliffe, MIT,
Northeastern, Regis, Simmons, Stonehill, Suffolk, Tufts, Wellesley
and Wheaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
