<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5942 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-AIRLINE-ALLIAN     08-03 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AIRLINE-ALLIANCE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES TEAM UP, RAISING SOME HACKLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 9.)  
 (JT)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The airline industry has always been a good breeding ground for
copycats, so when Northwest Airlines and Continental Airlines, the
country's fourth- and fifth-largest carriers respectively,
announced a ``global strategic alliance'' in January, the other
major airlines immediately began circling one another.
</P>
<P>
   By April United Airlines, the country's largest carrier, and
Delta Airlines, the third largest, announced their own alliance as
did No. 2 American Airlines and No. 6 US Airways. The airlines say
that the three alliances, which together cover about 70 percent of
all domestic passengers, will give consumers more choices, lower
fares and improved service.
</P>
<P>
   But critics have denounced the proposed linkups, arguing that
any benefits they may bring will be far outweighed by the lack of
competition that is likely to result.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume that members of an alliance are not going to compete
strenuously with one another,'' said Alfred Kahn, who presided over
the deregulation of the airline industry 20 years ago and is now
professor emeritus at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   In June the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, released a preliminary assessment of the deals. It found
that the alliances would reduce the number of competing airlines on
1,836 of the 5,000 busiest routes, which account for 90 percent of
total domestic traffic. Historically, the GAO said, when
competition declines, fares rise. It estimated that 100 million of
the 396 million passengers who fly each year faced potential
disadvantages, compared with potential benefits for about 30
million passengers on 338 routes.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have announced the deals at a time when they are
reporting record profits and their best customers _ business
travelers _ are complaining about high fares and overcrowded
planes.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing a potent election-year issue, members of Congress have
denounced the high fares, proposing a half dozen bills to promote
competition. But it is unclear what the government can do to stop
the alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the proposed linkups is slightly different. Northwest
and Continental plan to code-share _ meaning that each carrier will
sell its partner's flights as if they were its own _ forming a
global network from Asia to South America. The deal requires the
approval of the antitrust division of the Justice Department
because Northwest proposes to buy a controlling stake in
Continental. The department has also asked for information from
United and Delta, which plan to code-share but will exclude their
European operations and will not invest in each other.
</P>
<P>
   American and US Airways plan only to open up their
frequent-flier programs and airport lounges to each other's
members, something planned in the two other alliances also. That
does not require government approval, although the Department of
Transportation does have the power to intervene if it believes that
passengers are being adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, linking frequent-flier programs appears to be a
consumer boon. For example, as of Aug. 1, holders of US Airways'
Dividend Miles can use their miles to fly American to Hawaii, a
popular destination that US Airways does not now serve. But adding
US Airways' 20 million frequent-fliers makes the competition for
the limited number of seats reserved for free tickets that much
fiercer. Many passengers already complain that seats are not
available when they try to redeem their miles. A recent Consumer
Reports study found that domestic airlines last year booked 152,000
fewer free seats on routes most popular with frequent-fliers than
they did in 1996. (Several airlines said they actually gave away
more seats last year and accused the magazine of using misleading
data.)
</P>
<P>
   More troubling is the prospect that the alliances will reduce
competition among the major airlines and strengthen their already
strong hold on large metropolitan hubs.
</P>
<P>
   United, Delta, Northwest and Continental all say that there is
little overlap in their route systems and that by combining them
they will be able to offer service to cities they currently do not
serve. For example, someone living in Lincoln, Neb., which is now
served by United, will be able to book a ticket straight through to
Sarasota, Fla., which is served by Delta.
</P>
<P>
   But only a small number of passengers fly such routes each year,
compared with the millions who travel between United's hub in
Denver and Delta's base in Atlanta. The two carriers now dominate
air service between those cities, and critics say that they will
have little incentive to compete once they are allied.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO also said that the alliances will strengthen the hold
that the major airlines have at the four airports where the number
of landings and takeoffs are strictly controlled _ Kennedy and La
Guardia in New York, O'Hare in Chicago and National in Washington.
That would make it even more difficult for small carriers to expand
service at these key airports. Indeed, the GAO and other critics
say that the alliances threaten the major achievement of
deregulation, which has been the competition introduced by new
discount carriers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
