<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBIL-AD-COLUMN-500&AMP;A     08-03 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBIL-AD-COLUMN-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PEGASUS FLIES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 77 years of serving as the symbol of Mobil gasoline, motor
oil and other automotive products, the flying horse is now being
brought to life as part of a comprehensive image campaign.
</P>
<P>
   An animated, 3-D version of Pegasus, the classic red flying
horse icon, is the star of television commercials that are meant to
evoke warm, fuzzy feelings in consumers. The glitzy spots, which
feature the Grammy award-winning song ``I Believe I Can Fly,'' by
R. Kelly, stand in marked contrast to Mobil's traditionally bland,
product-focused pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Pegasus campaign is indicative of attempts by marketers of
products bearing valuable, though venerable, trademarks to reach
today's consumers. In many instances, the presentation is, like
Mobil's, retro-chic, updating familiar fare to take advantage of
fond memories of an idealized past.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples include the return of the contoured bottle and
red disk in advertising for Coca-Cola Co. and the redesigns of such
ad characters as Sailor Jack and Bingo, the boy and dog featured on
packages of Cracker Jack snacks, now owned by the Frito-Lay unit of
Pepsico Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pegasus is a way to emotionalize our relationship with the
customer,'' said Kevin Jeter, vice president for global fuel
marketing at Mobil Corp. in Fairfax, Va., and ``provides us with a
way to talk about anything we sell, whether it be our
convenience-store products, gas or service.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegasus _ a classical mythological creature associated with
strength, power and beauty _ is coming alive after consumers, in
focus groups, told Mobil executives how appealing the symbol was in
several different campaign formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The research demonstrated how powerful the Pegasus icon is,''
Jeter said. ``It confirmed that there is a strong relationship
already between Pegasus and the consumer. The campaign only serves
to enhance that relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegasus is the centerpiece of the extensive campaign, titled
``Take Wing,'' which began running in mid-May. The goal, Jeter
said, is to depict Mobil as a trusted brand with products that
``empower customers to live more productively'' and to celebrate
``the sense of power, energy, speed and service customers can
expect from the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is an unusual joint effort of the Mobil roster
agencies. The lead agency, DDB Needham Worldwide in New York and
Chicago, part of Omnicom Group, handles general market advertising
for fuels and services. Arnold Communications in Boston, a unit of
Snyder Communications, handles advertising for convenience stores.
Ornelas &AMP; Associates in Dallas handles ads aimed at
Spanish-speaking consumers. And Burrell Communications Group in
Chicago handles campaigns for black consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is looking for ways to draw attention for their brand
and find something that separates them from the pack,'' said Ed
Hogikyan, management supervisor on the Mobil account at DDB Needham
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Though spending for the campaign was not disclosed, trade
publications are estimating the budget at more than $30 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jeter, who joined Mobil a little more than a year ago, said he
came up with the idea to give Pegasus a much more prominent role in
the brand's pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The symbol has been in continuous use since it appeared on the
gas pumps of Standard Oil Co. of New York, which was eventually
renamed Mobil. But sometimes it has been played up, as when it
appeared on the giant signs that identified Mobil stations, and
other times it has been played down, particularly after a reworked
Mobil logo (with a red ``o'') became the primary identification for
the brand.
</P>
<P>
   Early versions of Pegasus signs are in demand among collectors
of advertising memorabilia and nostalgic Americana. Nowadays,
Pegasus has been on display on the pumps as well as in large
outdoor lighted panels at the service stations.
</P>
<P>
   Creators of the campaign decided, Jeter said, that the Kelly
song would be an integral part of the commercials for TV and radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music is key,'' he said. ``It was so appropriate, and it
provides a memory device.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, ``I Believe I Can Fly'' comes from ``Space Jam,''
the 1996 movie featuring Michael Jordan and Bugs Bunny that was
based on the ``Air Jordan/Hare Jordan'' commercials for Nike Inc.
by Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore. That means that a song
written for a movie based on commercials is now being used in other
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the Mobil TV spots, a child is shown looking out a car
window at the flying horse. Pegasus soars through the skies over
city and country locales until landing at a Mobil station. An
announcer's voice says: ``Do you believe man was meant to fly? We
do.'' The voice adds that at Mobil, ``everything we do lets you
take wing.'' The spot closes with the theme ``Mobil. The energy to
make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Another commercial depicts Pegasus charging through a maze of
outdated gas pumps as a car tails behind. The announcer says: ``Do
you believe the old way of buying gas is dead? We do.'' That spot
is centered on the Mobil Speedpass system, which allows a customer
to use a tag to buy gasoline, with charges automatically billed to
a pre-selected credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Pegasus is back in a big way, it is Mobil's intention
``to stay the course,'' Jeter said, ``by building equity
long-term.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer we stay with Pegasus,'' he added, ``the more
beneficial it will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
