<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5959 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-APPRECIATION-LA     08-03 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-APPRECIATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HER LESSONS MORE THAN CHILD'S PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; For most of her 64 years, kids came first for
Shari Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Since the '50s, Lewis slipped her hand into a sock to entertain
_ and, more importantly, educate and enlighten _ millions of
children.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the ventriloquist behind Lamb Chop, Charlie Horse and
Hush Puppy died at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles,
succumbing to pneumonia, which she contracted while undergoing
chemotherapy for her recently diagnosed uterine cancer. She was 64.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis turned her sock puppets into a cottage industry that
spawned books, videos and, of course, a television show. Earlier
this year, her Charlie Horse character got its own series, ``The
Charlie Horse Music Pizza'' (7:30 a.m. weekdays on KCET), a show
stressing the importance of preschool music education. Three new
episodes already have been taped, to be mixed in with reruns
scheduled to run through the fall. After that, her publicist Maggie
Begley speculated that the show will go off the air.
</P>
<P>
   No story was crafted without a suitable lesson, and Lamb Chop, a
6-year-old girl in sheep's clothing, was an easy character for
young girls to identify with.
</P>
<P>
   All of Lewis' ventures encouraged kids in the viewing audience
to participate. She was not interested in ratings or raising a new
breed of couch potatoes. She was not interested in being an
electronic baby sitter, rather more of an at-home, after-school
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' interactive approach to children's television taught,
rather than simply mesmerized, generations of American youth. Her
gentle presence on television also paved the way for a new batch of
children's show hosts, such as Soupy Sales and Pee-wee Herman, both
of whom she outlasted.
</P>
<P>
   Using fun sing-alongs, games and jokes, Lewis would make sure
her followers learned something _ whether they realized it or not.
And, she didn't go about it in a haphazard fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In conceiving ``The Charlie Horse Music Pizza,'' for instance,
Lewis drew upon her background as a musician who graduated from New
York's High School of Music and Arts and conducted symphonies in
the United States, Canada and Japan. She worked closely with the
Music Educators National Conference to build the new show.
</P>
<P>
   Her impeccable reputation led to actors such as Dom DeLuise
signing on to her projects and musicians such as Ray Charles
playing along.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' work, including ``Lamb Chop's Play-Along,'' has been
recognized with 12 Emmy Awards, the John F. Kennedy Center Award
for Excellence and Creativity, seven Parents' Choice Awards and the
Action for Children's Television Award. But more importantly, her
shows, videos and specials have been there for parents, their
children and their children's children.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis herself was a pistol. Born Shari Hurwitz in New York City,
she was an entertainer since age 2 and a singer, dancer, author,
actress and ventriloquist during the following 62 years. Sure, she
took children and her work seriously, but Lewis had a sensational
sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1997 interview with the Daily News, she patiently got
into her Lamb Chop character and answered a few touchy questions:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sheep have been in the news a lot. What's your view on
cloning?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``If they clone me? If Shari had two of me, she'd really have
her hands full.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, you're against cloning then?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I'm not against it. I mean I feel sheepish saying it, but
why clone me? Why mess with perfection?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, when Lewis stayed at the l'Enfant Plaza Hotel in
Washington, D.C., the management took lamb chops off the menu in
deference to her. She told the Wall Street magazine, ``Actually,
rack of lamb is my favorite _ if for no other reason than to
horrify the waiter.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely her legacy will live on through her books, videos and
reruns of her television show. And if they aren't careful, future
generations of kids will have so much fun that they won't even
realize they are learning something. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
