<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KASHMIR-TERROR-ART-47     08-03 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-TERROR-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KASHMIR REBELS SLAY 34 INDIAN WORKERS, INDIA CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(js) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Indian officials said on Monday that Muslim
rebels contesting Indian rule in Kashmir had crossed into a
neighboring Indian state overnight and shot and killed 34
construction workers who were sleeping in two remote construction
camps.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the workers, most or all of them Hindus, was one
of the worst of its kind in the nine years of guerrilla warfare in
Kashmir. It followed days of escalating artillery battles between
Indian and Pakistani troops along the confrontation line that
separates the two armies in Kashmir, and prompted fears of a more
general escalation of the fighting over the divided territory.
</P>
<P>
   Since the underground nuclear tests that India and Pakistan
conducted in May, the United States has led a chorus of concern
around the world at the risks of Kashmir's becoming the flashpoint
of a new war between India and Pakistan that could prompt the use
of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the slaying of the construction workers began at
about 2 a.m. on Monday, when a group of assailants with automatic
rifles burst into a shed used as a dormitory by the workers at
Kalaban, 10 miles from the town of Chamba in northern Himachal
Pradesh. The fighting that followed killed 26 workers and wounded
eight, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, there was a similar attack on another
construction camp at the village of Shatrundi, along a remote
mountain road leading back into Kashmir, the police said. In the
second attack, eight workers were killed and three wounded.
Although the police accounts did not specify how the Indian
authorities could be sure the killers were Muslim guerrillas, the
inference seemed to be that only the guerrillas would have the
weapons and the motive for such attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The area of the two attacks is about 270 miles north of New
Delhi and only a few miles from the border between the Indian
states of Jammu and Kashmir and Himachal Pradesh. Although attacks
by the guerrillas outside Kashmir have been rare, Indian officials
said they had received intelligence reports for some weeks
suggesting that the rebels might strike in Himachal Pradesh, a
usually peaceful state where the rebels would not face the heavy
Indian troop and police concentrations that confront them in
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   News of the killings came as artillery battles in Kashmir
appeared to be intensifying. A report by Reuters news service from
Islamabad, the Pakistani capital, put the number of civilians
killed on both sides in the artillery duels in the last five days
at 60. Other accounts placed the total closer to 80. The toll
appeared to be among the heaviest in years in the sporadic battles
that India and Pakistan have fought along the 550-mile line that
divides the larger part of Kashmir held by India from the smaller
part in Pakistan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indian military commanders played down the significance of the
artillery exchanges, saying similar upsurges occurred every summer
when melting snow in the Himalayan mountains opened passes through
which Muslim rebels infiltrate from bases in Pakistan-held Kashmir
to the Indian side. ``This is a seasonal feature, and there is
nothing to be alarmed about,'' said Air Chief Marshal S.K. Sareen,
chief of staff of the Indian Air Force, who spoke on a visit to
Srinagar, summer capital of Indian-held Jammu and Kashmir state.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody was so hopeful about the deteriorating
situation in the divided territory, especially after news broke of
the attack on the construction workers in Himachal Pradesh. A
frosty meeting last week between the Indian and Pakistani prime
ministers in Colombo, the Sri Lankan capital, did little to allay
the anxieties over Kashmir and the potential for using nuclear
weapons. The two leaders, Atal Bihari Vajpayee of India and Nawaz
Sharif of Pakistan, met while attending an annual conference of
South Asian heads of government.
</P>
<P>
   They were unable to agree on a formula for resuming diplomatic
talks on Kashmir and other contentious issues, including measures
to reduce the risk of a nuclear confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for both governments said Kashmir was the cause of the
deadlock, with Pakistan insisting Kashmir be the focus of the
discussions and India holding to its demand that Kashmir could be
discussed only in the context of a broader dialogue about security
issues.
</P>
<P>
   When the regional meeting ended on Friday, the delegations
returned home and blamed each other for the deadlock using harsh
language that suggested neither side was in the mood for
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Sharif told reporters in Islamabad that India was
responsible for escalating the artillery exchanges along the
border, which Pakistani officials said had caused at least 30
civilian casualties. Many of the victims were said to have died as
a result of Indian barrages on villages in the Neelum Valley area
of Pakistan-held Kashmir, northeast of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   ``India is indulging in irresponsible behavior, and I fail to
see any logic in this,'' Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
   Giving an account of his meeting with Sharif to the Indian
Parliament on Monday, Vajpayee said his government favored ``a
direct, composite dialogue'' with Pakistan, but not one that dealt
with tensions between the two countries in ``a narrow, segmented
fashion'' that focused on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Vajpayee said, he had admonished Sharif about
Pakistan's role in the territory, telling him that ``instigation of
terrorism was incompatible with our common desire for friendly and
peaceful relations and that these activities must cease
immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
