<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HEPATITIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS LAUNCHES HEPATITIS IMMUNIZATION PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts public health officials launched a
campaign Monday urging residents to immunize themselves against
hepatitis B, a liver-damaging disease that in its chronic form
afflicts more than 1 million Americans and annually kills about
6,000.
</P>
<P>
   The officials enlisted Congressman Joe Moakley of Boston, who
exhorted others to avoid the ``horrors'' he endured after he was
infected by the virus in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became jaundiced, my eyes were yellow,'' he said. ``I had no
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors told me I had two months to live.''
</P>
<P>
   A liver transplant saved his life. But a series of three
vaccines over six months could have spared him the agony.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the most common types of hepatitis are A,
B, and C. Type B and C are spread through blood and bodily fluids,
according to a state Department of Public Health fact sheet. Type A
is spread through food or water contaminated with feces. Vaccines
protect against Types A and B only, although work on a vaccine for
hepatitis C is under way.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine against Type A is particularly recommended for
day-care center workers, and anyone who comes into close contact
with an infected person, travels to geographic areas that have poor
sanitation or lives in an area where there has been a recent
outbreak of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis B is 100 times more infectious than the HIV virus, and
can cause primary cancer of the liver or liver failure in chronic
cases, which comprise about 10 percent of all hepatitis B
infections. In these cases, people can carry the virus for decades
and infect others with it.
</P>
<P>
   As in Moakley's case, about 40 percent of hepatitis B cases stem
fron unknown causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can live for three weeks in a drop of dry blood,'' said
Linda Keller, hepatitis B coordinator for the state immunization
program. It can spread through nosebleeds or open sores, or through
sharing toothbrushes, razors, washcloths, needles or nail clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic hepatitis B affects 1.2 million Americans. Each year
200,000 people develop new infections, according to the American
Liver Foundation. Massachusetts doctors reported 1,200 chronic
cases in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Every infant, child and adolescent in the state is at risk and
should be immunized, Keller said. Public health programs provide
free vaccines. More information is available at 617-983-6800.
</P>
<P>
   Adults should get tested and immunized if they are at high risk:
if they come from Asian or African countries, live with hepatitis B
infected people, are health care workers, use dialysis or IV drugs,
or engage in unprotected sex, or have multiple sex partners.
</P>
<P>
   About 88 percent of the infants born in the state are immunized,
Keller said, giving Massachusetts one of the highest rates in the
country. About 50 percent of schoolchildren are immunized now,
largely thanks to a federal and state funded program that, starting
in 1995, required vaccinations for sixth graders and made them
voluntary for older students.
</P>
<P>
   A new phase of the program will begin in 1998 requiring
immunizations for seventh graders.
</P>
<P>
   But very few adults _ even those at high risk _ are vaccinated.
For adults with high or low risk, Keller said, ``it's foolish not
to be vaccinated.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller said that, if successful, the childhood immunization
programs could eradicate the disease in about 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   State public health commissioner Howard Koh agreed. ``We believe
in the power of prevention. We have a vaccine and we're making
tremendous progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a totally preventable form of suffering,'' Koh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
