<SLUG> BC-GAYS-RESEARCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR DECRIES ANTI-GAY USE OF RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lambasting a national anti-gay advertising campaign
that draws on his research, a Boston doctor Monday accused
conservative religious groups of distorting his work to support
their own theory: that homosexuality can be ``healed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Garofalo, a Children's Hospital pediatrician who
authored a study of gay teenagers last spring, is cited at the
bottom of full-page advertisements featuring a group of smiling
``ex-gays,'' in a conversion campaign launched last month by a
coalition of Christian groups.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo's survey, which found high levels of substance abuse
among gays, is presented in the ads as footnoted evidence that
homosexuality is self-destructive. The ads contend that substance
abuse and other high-risk behavior among gays are the ``visible
response to a broken heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garofalo says he found nothing of the sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete misrepresentation of what the research
actually says,'' he said. ``It was taken completely out of context.
It comes to the complete opposite conclusion of what the paper
actually concluded.''
</P>
<P>
   His paper _ titled ``The Association Between Health Risk
Behaviors and Sexual Orientation Among a School-based Sample of
Adolescents'' _ was published in May in the medical journal
Pediatrics, based on a 1995 survey of 4,300 adolescents in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   It found that teenagers who consider themselves gay, lesbian, or
bisexual in high school also report ``disproportionate risk'' for a
number of other troubles _ especially suicide, violence, and
substance abuse. Garofalo believes the abuses are the result of the
alienation that gay teenagers face in a ``culture that is often
unaccepting.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ad campaign _ which was launched July 13 in seven
newspapers nationwide, prompting an immediate outcry from advocacy
groups _ shifts the cause of the problem onto homosexuality itself.
And conservative officials offered no apology Monday for their
interpretation of the medical research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homosexual behavior itself is a symptom of deeper, unmet
emotional needs,'' said Robert Knight, director of cultural studies
at the Family Research Council, a conservative think tank that is
helping fund the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in their heart knows the behavior is wrong,'' he
added. ``People who are caught up in it often cover their emotional
distress by abusing substances.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad mentioning Garofalo by name, the ``Standing for Truth''
campaign, was printed in the Washington Post on July 14, then
reprinted 15 days later in the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Some ads invoke the names of prominent opponents of
homosexuality, such as Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, and
others feature repentant former gays, such as Anne Paulk, who in
one full-page advertisement is billed as a ``wife, mother, former
lesbian.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing Garofalo as a pawn of political correctness, Knight
said there is no substance to the theory that alienation can
produce self-destructive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like saying, if we could just understand adulterers
more, they wouldn't drink to cover up their guilt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo said he was ``horrified and angry'' about the
misappropriation of his work, calling the interpretation by the
religious right a ``divisive and destructive forum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an awful and very destructive message,'' he said
Monday. ``It alienates them, makes them further feel isolated and
alone. That's the very thing that leads to suicide, and leads to
the behaviors that were reported in my paper.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign, which has sparked a renewed debate about
homosexuality, followed incendiary remarks last month by Lott, who
described homosexuality as a behavior that can be controlled, and
compared it to kleptomania. Advocacy groups have responded in kind,
taking out advertisements of their own to counter such allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The medical community has raised some of its own objections. Dr.
Elizabeth Goodman, an assistant professor of pediatrics at Harvard
Medical School, said Monday that the causality implied in the ads
is scientifically impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've gone beyond the data,'' she said. ``I think
Dr. Garofalo's work shows us youth who have sexual identity issues
are at greater risk. But I think the importance of that is fixing
how our society views sexual orientation _ not fixing the sexual
orientation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENEMY-THEATER-REVIEW-     08-03 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENEMY-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ENEMY OF THE PEOPLE': DOCTOR VS. MOB IN POISONED ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dr. Tomas Stockmann has thrown off the last traces
of self-control, and the results are not pretty. He has been
addressing the citizens of the coastal Norwegian town where he has
been known for years as a benevolent if eccentric physician and
scholar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he's unrecognizable at the moment, his features engorged
with contempt, his voice loud and scalding. He has climbed a chair
on the speaker's platform; he is imitating a rabid monkey,
scratching himself. He is also, he makes it very clear, imitating
the people who are watching him.
</P>
<P>
   That's Ian McKellen, the great English classical actor, who is
playing Stockmann in the Royal National Theater's production of
Ibsen's ``Enemy of the People,'' and he has fully turned up the
volume of his natural stage presence, which is never exactly a
whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Because other performers, playing townspeople, have been planted
throughout the audience of the Ahmanson Theater here, where the
traveling production runs through Sept. 6, theatergoers themselves
may feel vulnerable. There's a direct, uncomfortable intimacy
between you and the fulminator center stage. You may be infected by
all the anger and want to shout back. The question is on whose
side?
</P>
<P>
   This scene, part of the famous fourth act of Ibsen's 1883 drama
of political corruption and mob mindlessness, is the pinnacle in
this shrewd, carefully thought out and cleanly executed production,
directed by Trevor Nunn from a new translation by Christopher
Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt, objectively speaking, that Stockmann is in the
right, as he tries to convince his fellow citizens that the waters
to be used in the town's new bath and spa center have been
poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   But who can be clearheaded in a crowd, especially one charged
with fear and confusion? The sheer ugliness of the doctor's rage
and disdain prohibits unconditional sympathy, and McKellen's crafty
performance has set up motives that go deeper than moral
indignation for this descent into fury. His Stockmann remains the
work's hero, but none of the characters emerge untainted from their
involvement in small-town politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Enemy of the People'' is the play Ibsen wrote, with unusual
dispatch, in response to the public outcry against his previous
work, ``Ghosts.'' It reflects the dramatist's belief that the
so-called ``solid majority'' of democracy is made up largely of
slow-thinking ``serfs''; it's the enlightened few, ``attuned to the
future,'' who by rights should rule.
</P>
<P>
   Of the iconoclastic, defiant Stockmann, he wrote, ``We are alike
in so many ways.'' The play is more crudely polemical than most of
Ibsen and for obvious reasons is not among the most frequently
performed. But as Anthony Page's revival of ``A Doll's House'' with
Janet McTeer demonstrated, Ibsen's characters are seldom as simple
as one might have come to think.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn and McKellen uncover the conflicted soul of the leading
man. The play's broader elements of preachifying aren't disguised:
the moral inadequacy of everyone other than Stockmann and his
immediate family is broadly rendered.
</P>
<P>
   But McKellen also creates a portrait of a manic, brilliant naif
conditioned by a life of rivalry with his brother, Peter (Stephen
Moore), the town's mayor, and of being indulged and admired by
those around him. He expects a torchlight parade for his discovery
that the baths, which are expected to revive the town commercially,
are polluted.
</P>
<P>
   That what happens instead suggests the torch-wielding vigilante
villagers of ``Frankenstein'' prompts in Stockmann a childlike
astonishment and a savage sense of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn sustains a double vision throughout the production, a sense
of public and private lives headed toward collision. John Napier's
revolving set, a gray 19th-century townscape that already seems
painted by industrial grime, is directly reminiscent of his work
with Nunn on another study in mob rule, ``Les Miserables.''
</P>
<P>
   It shifts constantly between interior scenes and those of street
life, with lots of people (some of them locally recruited actors)
milling around, a bit unconvincingly.
</P>
<P>
   The searing fourth act aside, it's the private moments that have
the greater impact. McKellen is in his well-known extroverted mode,
as opposed to the more subtle, inward-looking style of his
brilliant ``Macbeth'' and ``Uncle Vanya,'' but the expansiveness is
appropriate here.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor is, after all, a bit of a showoff, enchanted by the
affection his absent-minded-professor persona and boyish enthusiasm
inspire in others and given to taking over any room he inhabits.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
