<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5985 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-FIGHTING-ART-NY     08-03 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-FIGHTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTINOUS TROOPS PLEDGE TO OUST CONGOLESE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ Rebellious troops seized control of
several cities in eastern Congo Monday, and fought gun battles in
the capital, as the alliance that brought President Laurent Kabila
to office last year unraveled, threatening his hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio announcement from the eastern city of Goma, a man
claiming to be the rebels' leader, identifying himself as Sylvain
Mbuchi, commander of the country's 10th battalion, said the army
``had decided to remove President Kabila from power.'' He denounced
what he said was the government's ``nepotism, corruption and bad
governance.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats, aid workers and the Congolese government suggested
that in both the east and the capital, Kinshasa, the mutinies were
led by members of Congo's small Tutsi minority. Kabila's relations
with the Tutsis have been marked by mounting tension ever since he
seized power 15 months ago at the head of a rebel force largely
composed of Tutsi fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila now faces the problem that bedeviled his predecessor,
Mobutu Sese Seko: keeping the Congo whole. But he does so with far
fewer friends within Africa and abroad that he had a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-governmental troops appeared to have restored order in
Kinshasa, where the situation was quiet for most of the day Monday.
But by all accounts the situation in the country's interior remains
far more confused, with communications with some cities, such as
Goma, cut off entirely, and mutinous troops in several other
eastern cities reportedly making common cause with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tension is very high right now throughout this region, and the
situation is not at all clear,'' said one aid worker in the city of
Uvira, where there was scattered gunfire. ``There are all kinds of
rumors of mutinies and of troop movements.''
</P>
<P>
   International aid workers reported Monday that the rebellion in
Goma had inspired copycat movements in Bukavu, Uvira, Baraka and a
number of smaller eastern cities, where Tutsi populations are
relatively large, and where Tutsi troops are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   In Bukavu, on Sunday, rebellious troops attacked a prison and
freed people jailed in a previous mutiny, and then announced their
intention to remove Kabila from power.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration of mutiny came after a night of intense mortar
and machine gun fire in Kinshasa mounted by Tutsi elements of the
country's armed forces, against units of the Congolese army loyal
to Kabila. The Congo government contends that Rwandan forces helped
the Tutsi rebels, but Rwanda denies that.
</P>
<P>
   By midmorning, when the gunfire had died down, witnesses in
Kinshasa reported seeing numerous bodies, presumably of combatants,
in the vicinity of Camp Tshatshi, one of two main barracks in
Kinshasa where Tutsi forces are known to be garrisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's government responded to the unrest Monday by closing
the country's borders and imposing a three-day dusk-to-dawn curfew
in the capital. He also appealed, in a communique broadcast on
national radio, ``for all of the security forces as well as the
entire population to collaborate in rooting out and denouncing the
enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Congolese, after a week of bitter public recriminations
between Kabila's government and that of Rwanda, its eastern
neighbor and former ally, the talk of ``the enemy'' will inevitably
be interpreted as a denunciation of Rwanda, and of the Tutsi
themselves, an ethnic group that many Congolese consider
essentially Rwandan, rather than Congolese.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently fearing a witch hunt against the Tutsi, two of
Kabila's top aides, Foreign Minister Bizima Karaha and Deogratias
Bugera, presidential affairs minister, both Tutsi, reportedly fled
the country Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After defeating Mobutu's army in May 1997, Kabila took power
with strong support to overturn long-held policies that had
impoverished a country full of natural resources. His popularity
quickly dissipated, however, as Congolese saw that the new
government had little experience and had quickly lost its
international good will.
</P>
<P>
   Within months of taking power, the east of the giant country,
which had spawned Kabila's rebellion and had long been among the
country's most unstable regions, was already posing a serious
security challenge to the government. Tutsi and other troops there
complained that the country was on the wrong track and that they
had fought for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The open conflict between Kabila's loyalists and Tutsi marks an
ironic reversal of the situation that brought Kabila, a longtime
guerrilla fighter lost in the obscurity of the mountainous eastern
bush country, to power in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwandan government picked Kabila to head a hastily concocted
coalition of eastern political forces that overthrew the aging
dictator, Mobutu Sese Seko, after a seven-month rebellion. The
fighting, in what all but amounted to a rout, was done by Rwandan
army elements and Tutsi soldiers trained and armed by Rwanda and
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   By backing Kabila, Rwanda's Tutsi-led government hoped to break
up huge refugee camps in eastern Congo, then known as Zaire. The
camps housed more than a million members of the country's Hutu
majority, which used Congolese territory to mount attacks on the
Rwandan government.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to government accusations that regular Rwandan troops
were involved in the unrest, Rwandan officials Monday denied that
any of their soldiers had stayed behind in the Congo after Kabila's
order, last Tuesday, for them to leave the country immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our soldiers left the Congo last week, approximately 500 of
them, and they are rejoining their respective units,'' Gen. Kayumba
Nyamwansa told the French news agency. ``They are very happy to be
back in their country.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether it is actively encouraging the mutiny against Kabila
or not, diplomats and Congolese political analysts say that Rwanda
feels anything but sympathy toward its former allies in the Congo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
