<HEADER>
A5986 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-FIGHTING-ART-2N     08-03 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-FIGHTING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast: the Congo. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The falloff between the two countries, which has been unfolding
for months, has a complex history. On the Congolese side, Kabila is
said to have resented bearing international blame for the massacre
of thousands of Rwandan Hutu refugees by his own troops _
essentially Tutsi forces trained by or on loan from Rwanda _ during
the seven-month rebellion that brought him to power.
</P>
<P>
   With elections promised for next year, the Congolese leader,
never strongly popular since taking power, has played a nationalist
card, asserting his independence from his sponsors, the far smaller
neighbors in Rwanda and Uganda, whose highly visible presence in
the country has been a source of widespread resentment.
</P>
<P>
   He began doing this by weeding out senior ethnic Tutsi from
important military positions and replacing them with his own ethnic
kinsmen from southern Congo, and consummated the gambit by
expelling Rwandan soldiers from the country altogether.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Rwandan and Ugandans have been embarrassed
by what they see as Kabila's political ineptitude, which has led to
frequent diplomatic gaffes. More seriously, Kabila's former
sponsors are believed to have invested heavily in the rebellion
that brought him to power because they expected that having a
strong ally in Kinshasa would deny numerous rebel groups use of
Congolese territory as a base for their activities.
</P>
<P>
   But in a year marked by skirmishes, mini-rebellions and ethnic
purges, Kabila's army has had its hands full with its own internal
problems and has been able to accomplish little to secure the
country's long borders with its eastern neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   When the first signs of trouble between Kinshasa and Rwanda and
Uganda began cropping up, within weeks of Kabila's overthrow of
Mobutu, Kabila began to lean heavily on another ally, Congo's
southern neighbor, Angola.
</P>
<P>
   But even that relationship has become strained, African
diplomats say, over reports that Angolan rebels have reactivated
arms-running and gem-running networks that filter contraband
through Congo's porous territory.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even if Angola wanted to back Kabila against his new
foes in the east, these diplomats say, fresh hostilities between
the Angolan government and its longtime rebel enemies in the Unita
movement would make an intervention in Congo unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who proclaimed that the problems of Congo were
simple questions of management and that by installing Kabila all
could be settled,'' said one African diplomat with long experience
of Central Africa. ``What we are seeing is that this country is the
most complicated of African puzzles, and holding the capital is a
far cry from governing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
