<HEADLINE>
EX-PROSECUTOR PASSED OVER FOR U.S. ATTORNEY IN SAN DIEGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Charles La Bella, former head of the Justice
Department's campaign finance unit, has apparently lost out in his
effort to be named U.S. attorney in San Diego, where he long worked
as a federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella returned to San Diego two weeks ago to fill in as U.S.
attorney temporarily, hoping to land the job on a permanent basis.
He departed after delivering a confidential report to Attorney
General Janet Reno that concluded she should seek an independent
prosecutor to investigate how the Democrats financed the 1996
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although his advocacy of an independent fund-raising inquiry
placed him at odds with Reno, who has refused to seek an outside
prosecutor, La Bella still hoped to be appointed the top federal
prosecutor in the volatile border region of California.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the job appears likely to be filled by Gregory Vega,
another longtime federal prosecutor in San Diego. Vega, president
of the Hispanic National Bar Association, sought the job in 1993
after Bill Clinton was first elected president, but Clinton instead
chose a fellow Rhodes scholar, Alan Bersin.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella was rejected in favor of Vega through a system in which
home-state senators recommend nominees for U.S. attorney before the
president formally sends their names to the Senate for
confirmation. Vega was the choice of Sen. Barbara Boxer, a Democrat
running for re-election this year.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing her recommendation of Vega on Friday, Ms. Boxer
said he was qualified because of his personal involvement in the
problems of the area and because, as a longtime assistant U.S.
attorney there, he is well regarded by colleagues and judges in San
Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
