<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIBSON-ARLINGTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURIAL OF SLAIN CAPITOL GUARD IN ARLINGTON PROTESTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Backed by some prominent veterans groups, the
chairman of the House Veteran Affairs Committee has raised
objections to the burial last week of Capitol Police Detective John
M. Gibson in Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Bob Stump, an Arizona Republican, refused to
support the request from House Speaker Newt Gingrich and House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt to the Secretary of the Army to
grant a special burial waiver for Gibson, a Waltham, Mass. native
who was not a military veteran.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of controversy over special burial rights at
Arlington granted to non-veterans last year, Stump successfully led
the House in March to pass a bill that would end all exceptions to
the rule that only veterans can be interned there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the speaker that this waiver was contrary to the bill,
which passed 417-0,'' Stump, a World War II veteran, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while Stump and groups such as the Non-Commissioned
Officers Association of America have criticized the waiver granted
Gibson, as first reported Monday in Roll Call, a Capitol Hill
newspaper, the outpouring of public grief and support for the two
officers killed during the July 24 shooting at the US Capitol has
strengthened efforts to keep the door open for special exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an example of why the law should allow for waivers in
circumstances of extraordinary merit or, in his case, heroism,''
said John Ullyot, a member of the Republican staff of the Senate
Veteran Affairs Committee, which will take up the no-waivers bill
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington National Cemetery is regarded as a national shrine
honoring individual and collective acts of bravery and selfless
public service. It is also a living memorial to history, the site
of the Tomb of the Unknowns and the final resting place of veterans
from all the nation's wars. More than 240,000 Americans, including
President John F. Kennedy, are buried there.
</P>
<P>
   Burial space is limited to certain veterans who are highly
decorated or life-long service members, and to particular members
of their family.
</P>
<P>
   Although space is highly restricted, Stump said more than 60
waivers were granted last year to non-military individuals. Burial
rights became a political issue after it was revealed that M. Larry
Lawrence, a former US ambassador to Switzerland and a Democratic
donor, had lied about his military record. His widow had his body
exhumed.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of such waivers, Stump proposed his legislation to
stop the president or Secretary of the Army from issuing exceptions
to non-veterans. A few months later, Gibson was shot to death and
the Secretary of the Army granted his waiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no equitable way to justify burying civilians in
Arlington Cemetery when you are denying burial to veterans,'' said
Richard Johnson of the Non-Commissioned Officers Association, which
represents 160,000 members. ``You could have a guy who served three
years in Vietnam with a bronze star who is denied because a bronze
star isn't high enough to qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   Most veteran groups, however displeased they were with the
Gibson waiver, were reluctant to publicly announce their objections
in the face of such an emotional outpouring of support for the
slain Capitol Police, said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hard-pressed to say where we stand in this particular
climate,'' explained Bill Smith, a spokesman for the Veterans of
Foreign Wars, which has 2 million members.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans groups, however, were not united in their opposition to
Gibson's Arlington burial. Phil Dughan, a spokesman for the
American Legion, which represents 2.5 million veterans, neither
opposed nor endorsed the exception, but the group did recognize
Gibson's bravery.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Muller, president of the Vietnam Veterans of America
Foundation, an organization dedicated to promoting international
peace efforts, called those opposing Gibson's burial ``idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You think I have any problem with a national hero being buried
in Arlington Cemetary?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a South Boston Democrat whose
niece was married to Gibson, echoed Muller's point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I known the chairman is a strong supporter of veterans, but
I'm surprised that he would come out that strongly because for
every rule there's an exception,'' he said. ``These people weren't
just run over by a truck, they jumped in front of other people to
save lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
