A5999 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PROBE-BOS &LR;      08-03 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LOOKS TO SUPREME COURT AGAIN IN LEWINSKY PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House Monday said it would ask the
Supreme Court to block prosecutors in the Monica S. Lewinsky case
from questioning a close confidante of President Clinton, and held
out little hope that Clinton will offer, as some of his allies have
urged, a fuller public accounting of his relationship with the
former intern.
</P>
<P>
   As the high stakes legal struggle continues to intensify, the
testimony of Deputy Counsel Bruce R. Lindsey remains one of the few
unresolved battles between the White House and Independent Counsel
Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court appeal, which could delay Starr's probe, comes
at a time when even congressional Democrats have been urging the
White House to be more cooperative with Starr so he can wrap up his
case.
</P>
<P>
   White House Counsel Charles Ruff said the White House also has
no desire to see the case drag on, and that was one reason he had
decided to take the question of whether Lindsey must testify
directly to the Supreme Court rather than ask the full appellate
court to to rule on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would ask the Supreme Court to reverse a lower court
ruling that Lindsey's conversations with Clinton were not protected
by attorney-client privilege because he was a government attorney.
Ruff said he would ask the appeals court to keep Starr from calling
Lindsey to testify until the Supreme Court has a chance to act.
</P>
<P>
   Those latest legal moves come as Clinton and Lewinsky both are
preparing to testify before Starr's grand jury and as FBI
technicians analyze stains on a blue dress belonging to Lewinsky
that might hold possible genetic material linking it to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of the dress and a blanket immunity deal that
Starr gave Lewinsky and her mother, Marcia Lewis, has heightened
the political and legal pressure on Clinton. Clinton has agreed to
testify Aug. 17 by videotaped to the grand jury, but, so far, he
has not said whether he will explain his relationship with Lewinsky
publically.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, after promising to testify ``completely and
truthfully,'' Clinton said he would have no further comment between
now and his testimony. One White House aide said Clinton doesn't
plan a public statement before Aug. 17, but said that could change
and left open the possibility that the president would speak out
after he his closed-circuit television testimony before the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for Clinton to tell the public what he will tell the grand
jury have come from several of his former advisers, including
former chief of staff Leon Panetta, consultant Dick Morris and
press secretary Dee Dee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this matter is important enough that he should sit
down, stare the American people in the eye and do it directly from
the Oval Office,'' Panetta said Sunday on ``Late Edition'' on Cable
News Network.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said Clinton was aware of the
advice being offered by some of his former aides and Democratic
loyalists who have been using the airwaves to urge him to come
forward and explain what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll receive all kinds of advice from people inside, from
people outside, from outsiders who were insiders, insiders who were
outsiders,'' Toiv said. ``We'll hear it all, take note of it.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides have stressed that they are as much in the
dark as the public and cannot be sure whether Clinton will stick by
his earlier denials of never having sexual relations ``with that
woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has told the truth about this and will continue
to do so,'' Toiv told reporters Monday morning. ``I'm not in a
position to tell you what the president's testimony is going to be.
The only thing I can tell you is that he has said that he has told
the truth, and that he will continue to tell the truth,'' Toiv
said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House used Clinton's upcoming testimony to support its
argument that questioning of Lindsey was no longer essential to
Starr's investigation ``The fact that the president is going to be
testifying certainly, in our view, lowers the significance of this
testimony and that of other attorneys,'' said one White House aide.
</P>
<P>
   The administration insisted Monday that the battle to prevent
Lindsey's testimony was being pursued solely on grounds of
principle, and not as part of an effort to delay Starr's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney-client privilege is a bedrock priniciple of our
legal system,'' said Ruff, the White House counsel in a statement.
``The attorney-client relationship is no less important in
government than in every other context where it exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a three-judge panel rejected the White House
argument that Lindsey's tesimony was protected by attorney-client
privilege. ``Because of the importance of this principle for this
and future presidents, as well as the Executive Branch, we are
seeking review'' of that decision, Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who was in Toronto for a speech to the American Bar
Association, did not comment specifically on the latest stumbling
block to his investigation other than to say he was seeking to
``move forward very quickly'' with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   He also signaled that he would show respect to Clinton when the
time came for the president to testify. ``One of the things that I
want to make clear is that it is very important we respect our
institutions of government and seek to discharge the duties that we
have... in a way that is very respectful of the institutions of our
government,'' Starr told reporters after his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the White House, Toiv said he did not know whether
Clinton had received a request or a subpoena from Starr to provide
DNA samples that investigators might need to determine if the stain
on Lewinsky's dress came from the president.
</P>
<P>
   Some DNA experts have reportedly said that the analysis is not
extremely time consuming and that by now the results should be
known. But Ron Van Vranken, a spokesman for the FBI, refused to say
whether the analysis was completed and if so, why the results had
not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are analyzing it. We're not in a position to talk about
how long they (investigators) will take,'' he said. ``We'll just
have to wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
