<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6001 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HICKS-LADN     08-03 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HICKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLIDING UP THE CHART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FROSTBURG, Md. _ While watching a recent Washington Redskins
practice here in the rolling Appalachians, a father asked his young
sons which first-year players would make the final roster.
</P>
<P>
   One of the boys asked about former UCLA tailback Skip Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, Hicks,'' the father said. ``I think he's just
about a sure thing.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the Redskins drafted Hicks, they called him a
third-round pick (69th overall) with first-round talent. Through
the first 10 days of training camp, he has done nothing to alter
their opinion. When coach Norv Turner was asked to name the most
impressive newcomers after last week's scrimmage against
Pittsburgh, Hicks was the first name mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of ability,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has the size to run inside, the speed to run outside and a
sense for the end zone that produced 48 rushing touchdowns at UCLA.
He has excellent hands, an unflappable demeanor and young legs _
something Washington's starting tailback, nine-year veteran Terry
Allen, does not possess.
</P>
<P>
   If early form holds, Hicks will challenge third-year pro Stephen
Davis for the second-string spot. Because of Allen's knees, No.2
could quickly become No.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is the Redskins' offense is identical to the
one we had at UCLA, only there are a lot more plays,'' Hicks said.
``If anything, this one's easier. At UCLA, there was a lot to
memorize. Here, they tell you what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks' resume is not without blemishes, however. He fumbled in
the scrimmage. He made a slew of mental errors _ ``Hopefully, that
was just nerves,'' he said _ and he hasn't learned to hit the hole
with ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   Turner can accept Hicks' gliding style, as long as the fumbles
vanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of backs have different styles,'' Turner said. ``When I
was at USC, we had Charles White, Ricky Bell and Marcus Allen, and
they each had different styles. When I was with the Rams, we had
Eric Dickerson, and he had a unique style. In Dallas, it was Emmitt
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to coach them, of course, but you also have to give
them the freedom to have their own style. When we looked at film of
Skip, he was awfully powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   __ NOTE: Former USC quarterback Brad Otten, who had major knee
surgery after college, is contending for the Redskins' third-string
job with veteran Trent Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been inconsistent,'' Turner said of Otten. ``He has days
when he does real well, and he has days when I'm disappointed with
him. It's taken a while for him to get comfortable with the knee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
