<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL BILL FOLLOW TINA TO HOLLYWOOD?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the flotsam and jetsam had paid their money and said
hello, and the fund-raising party was over, &UR; Bill &LR;  and  &UR; Hillary &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR;  and their hosts,  &UR; Alec Baldwin  &LR; and  &UR; Kim Basinger &LR; , dined
in an East Hampton restaurant on Saturday night with a select crew
of insiders. The president sat between Basinger and  &UR; Kate &LR; 
 &UR; Capshaw &LR; ,  &UR; Steven Spielberg &LR; 's wife, and ate hush puppies, chicken,
ribs, shrimp and puffer fish, a local delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed particularly close to Spielberg, observed  &UR; Neil &LR; 
 &UR; Travis &LR;  of the New York Post. ``In fact, they are such good
friends,'' wrote Travis, ``that I'm starting to believe those
stories that Clinton will go to work for Spielberg's DreamWorks
company when he leaves the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAVING A GOOD TIME IN THE PARKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An old-fashioned accordion-style postcard folder produced for
the Golden Gate National Parks Association uses some new- &LR; fangled
text. Created pro bono by the San Francisco ad agency Goodby,
Silverstein &AMP; Partners, each of the seven postcards pictures a
place along the 70-mile-long stretch of coastline parks.
</P>
<P>
   On the reverse side of an image of Muir Woods, for example:
``Among the 500 miles of hiking trails in the Golden Gate National
Parks, the shadiest can be found under these redwoods. Hike through
trees over 2,150 feet tall and over a thousand years old. Every few
years, a mighty redwood falls down all by itself. But don't worry _
you'll hear it coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The folder aims to attract members to the association, which
supports the parks. Membership ($35 a year) includes a quarterly
newsletter, invitations to hikes and events, merchandise discounts,
free admission to the Hyde Street Pier and free audio tours of
Alcatraz and Fort Point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABC GOES BANANAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Those wild and wacky folks at ABC, a company owned by Disney,
are starting an ad campaign this week utilizing stickers on
bananas. This is logical, said network officials, because ABC's
``We Love TV'' campaign, which began last year, used the color
yellow as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   The small oval stickers will say either ``TV. Zero Calories'' or
``Another Fine Use of Yellow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is increasingly more difficult to impact consumers,'' said
 &UR; Brian Fox &LR;  of Santa Monica's Fruit Label Co., the brains behind
the campaign. ``And the banana labels are a very novel medium to
cut through the clutter.'' (Clutter Patrol to Fox: ``Increasingly
more'' and ``very novel'' must go.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WATCHING AND LISTENING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Watching the Goodwill Games women's beach volleyball final,
 &UR; Nancy Gehlke &LR;  wondered if the label ``BRA'' on the backs of the
``top portions of two players' skimpy uniforms'' was an effort ``to
teach English to the international TV audience.'' The players were
from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   _ The trendy Bar 89 in Manhattan has a unisex rest room with
five stalls with see-through doors. These portals become opaque
when someone's inside, says SOMA magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Bar 89 manager &UR; Kirk Lieske  &LR; explained that the opacity, affected
by motion sensors, is complete when they're not turned on. Thus,
users need not worry about modesty during power failures.
Presumably they wouldn't be worried anyway because it would be
dark.
</P>
<P>
   _ When MTV's ``The Real World'' shot its new episodes in Seattle
this spring, unfriendly natives wore ``The Real World Sucks''
T-shirts, mooned the cast and crew at a rock concert and threw
vegetables at them when they were visiting the Pike Place market,
reports the Seattle magazine Media Inc. Producer  &UR; Matt &LR; 
 &UR; Kunitz &LR;  called this reception ``a little annoying'' and hard to
understand, ``since we were paying money to the artists and
craftsmen of Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle producer,  &UR; Rod Shelton &LR; , says word was out that the
locals made little profit. ``They took a majority of the work back
to L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Pat Shareck &LR;  was listening Thursday night when Berkeley FM
station KALW carried a report on sports in the Middle East: Yemeni
Cricket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to kind of live like a bum to be a successful
stand-up. But the bigger you get, the less free time you have to
let your mind just wander. In order for me to be a good stand-up, I
got to pretty much do nothing all day.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Rock in The Cable Guide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
