</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vets say Gulf War probe won't go far enough
 &HT;    (EDS: ``...spokeswoman Dian Lawhon....'' is CQ)
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gulf War veteran advocates say they are concerned that
an expanded testing program for depleted uranium contamination that
the Pentagon will announce today does not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon will announce that about 300 soldiers identified by
the Department of Defense as having come into contact with depleted
uranium (DU) during the 1991 Gulf War will have their urine tested
for the toxic heavy metal. The Pentagon has been conducting medical
tests on 33 soldiers who came into significant contact with the
radioactive material, which is used in armor-piercing shells and to
reinforce armor on tank bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medically, there is nothing that ties any Gulf War illness to
depleted uranium,'' said Pentagon spokeswoman Dian Lawhon.
``However, because some veterans are expressing conce
</P>
