<SLUG> BC-ABP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CEO remodeling American Business Products
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ American Business Products may never be the same again
_ which is the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything here is sacred,'' said Larry
Gellerstedt III, chief executive officer of the company since March
30 and chairman since May 8. Gellerstedt said he has a mandate to
``produce a clear strategy'' for a 116-year-old Atlanta company
with a mix of businesses from printing to office supplies to
specialty coatings used in packaging. Institutional investors and
analysts ``don't see any direction to the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have they seen much lately in the way of stock performance.
The shares closed 1995 at a high _ $28.50 _ and with a gain of 92
percent for the year. Since then, they have lost 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things they do very well,'' said analyst Steven
Margulies of Brean Murray. ``It's a cheap stock, and they do make
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But the performance of its five units has been mixed, said
Burnham Securities analyst David Leibowitz. ``The big question is
whether those performing below average have the potential to show
the type of improvement shareholders have come to expect, and if
so, what steps are needed to bring that up,'' Liebowitz said.
Gellerstedt, who replaced Robert W. Gundeck after leaving Beers
Construction, has already pulled the plug on a joint venture in
Europe that made envelopes, and on an in-house effort to develop a
computerized order entry system. But the most radical changes, if
they are made, are likely to be in the Curtis 1000 subsidiary, the
forerunner of American Business Products and producer of about 40
percent of total revenue. Curtis makes custom-order envelopes,
labels, forms and other products.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis 1000, started in St. Paul, Minn., in 1882, ``is back to
making money,'' Gellerstedt noted. A restructuring reduced the
unit's plants from 17 to five, including one in Duluth with 346
employees, and those left are running at only 50 percent capacity,
he said. Gellerstedt, who hopes to deliver a strategic plan to
directors this fall, sees several options for Curtis 1000:
</P>
<P>
   Keep it intact; form a joint venture, perhaps with an office
supply chain, to keep the plants running at a higher capacity; sell
the production part of the business, and sell and distribute
another company's products; or sell the unit.
</P>
<P>
   Another business, BookCrafters, which prints small runs of
books, continued to show ``weakness'' in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given up on BookCrafters,''Gellerstedt said, while
acknowledging he does not have an answer to the problems. Discount
Labels, International Envelope and Jen-Coat, on the other hand, are
doing well, and Gellerstedt hopes to transfer technology and
operating advantages among them and other parts of American
Business Products.
</P>
<P>
   Discount Label produces and delivers custom-order labels to
30,000 distributors within 24 hours, across the nation, from a
plant in Louisville, Gellerstedt said.
</P>
<P>
   International Envelope makes light, tough envelopes, almost
impossible to open without scissors. Gellerstedt sees the potential
to expand into packaging, perhaps supplying mail-order companies.
</P>
<P>
   Jen-Coat supplies specialty coatings, including those used in
the packaging of chewing gum andartificial sweetener.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Leibowitz thinks it's ``probably premature'' to guess
what changes Gellerstedt will make.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they are, Gellerstedt has a multi-million-dollar
incentive to make them translate into a higher stock price. He
could wind up with 2 percent to 2.5 percent of American Business
Products stock as a long-term incentive, according to a filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission. At Monday's closing price
of $18.12 1/2, that's worth about $5.9 million to $7.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
