<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If talks fail, BellSouth workers may strikeBy Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Members of the union representing more than half of
BellSouth's workers have voted overwhelmingly to authorize a strike
should talks fail to produce a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   With the deadline for a deal only days away, about 93 percent of
Communications Workers of America voters gave union leaders the
right to call a strike if negotiators fail to hammer out a deal by
the time current contracts expire at 11:59 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very iffy at this point,'' said Jimmy Smith, CWA vice
president for District 3, which includes the nine Southeastern
states in which BellSouth provides local service. ``If the contract
expired today, there's no question there would be a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   CWA represents about 48,000 of the 86,188 BellSouth employees.
The company, created by the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T, has never faced a
strike and neither side seems anxious for a walkout now.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth officials say they remain optimistic that an accord
can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with the progress of the talks,'' said
BellSouth spokeswoman Deborah Spicer. ``We are absolutely committed
to reaching an agreement by Saturday. We need to let that real work
happen at the table.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth views the authorization vote as ``standard operating
procedure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are working on contracts for six BellSouth units.
Key issues are the company's ability to force employees to work
overtime, the contracting of jobs to non-union workers and pension
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   CWA officials declined to say how many members voted. However,
the turnout was greater than that three years ago when members
ratified pacts with BellSouth, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the distance between the two sides, the negotiating mood
can shift, he said. ``It's like the weather _ it can change in 15
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
