</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Cincinnati Reds
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Tonight, Wednesday and Thursday at 7:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Turner Field, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: TBS will telecast tonight and Thursday night. Fox Sports
South will telecast Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, RHP John Smoltz (9-2,
3.18; 14-10, 3.00 lifetime vs. Reds) vs. RHP Steve Parris (1-2,
5.45; 1-1, 5.68 lifetime vs. Braves). Wednesday, LHP Denny Neagle
(11-9, 3.53; 8-3, 4.45 lifetime vs. Reds) vs. RHP Brett Tomko
(10-7, 4.19; 0-1, lifetime vs. Braves). Thursday, RHP Greg Maddux
(14-5, 1.61; 13-11, 3.33 lifetime vs. Reds) vs. LHP Mike Remlinger
(6-11, 4.63; 1-2, 4.40 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: Atlanta trails the all-time series 251-293 but
has won 14 of the last 17 games between the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Braves are 5-1 against Cincinnati and took
three of four at Cinergy Field last week. The Reds scored 23 runs
in those four games and still won just once. Atlanta is batting
.292 with nine homers against Cincinnati this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reds leaders: Avg. _ Dmitri Young (.309); HR _ Willie Greene
(13); RBI _ Eddie Taubensee (55); SB _ Barry Larkin (17). Wins _
Brett Tomko (10); ERA _ John Hudek (0.00). Saves _ Danny Graves
(3). Strikeouts _ Pete Harnisch (109).
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: The Reds are coming off a three-game weekend sweep at
Florida and have won five of nine after coming out of a eight-game
losing streak. The bad news: Three of those four losses came
against the Braves last week in Cincinnati. . .. The Reds have been
in last place since July 20 and have been no higher than fourth
since Opening Day. . . . The recent Braves series was a disaster
for Cincinnati. Infielder Pokey Reese tore ligaments in his right
thumb and may be out for the year. Right-hander Pete Harnisch was
forced out of a start because of a tricep strain, and second
baseman Bret Boone might get back into the lineup only now after
spraining his left ankle. . . . The Reds have scored five or more
runs in five of their last nine games. . . . Since closer Jeff Shaw
was dealt to Los Angeles July 4, Cincinnati's bullpen has not blown
a save and designated closer Danny Graves is 3-for-3 in
conversions. . . . Parris, tonight's starter, is in a rematch with
Smoltz, after their last meeting was spoiled by Smoltz's ejection.
Parris pitched well early, taking a no-hitter into the fifth when
the Braves, enraged by Smoltz's ejection by umpire Hunter
Wendelstedt, nailed him for seven runs in their next 11 at-bats.
The big blow was Tony Graffanino's three run homer. . . . On the
DL: C Brook Fordyce (bruised left shoulder), LHP Steve Cooke (left
elbow tendinitis), INF Pokey Reese (torn ligaments, right thumb),
RHP Marc Kroon (right elbow tendinitis), RHP Keith Glauber (right
shoulder surgery), RHP Mark Hutton (strained right groin).
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's hot: OF Reggie Sanders is hitting .333 in his last eight
starts. OF Pat Watkins has a home run and is hitting .333 since his
call-up from Class AAA Indianapolis last week. RHP John Hudek has
yet to allow a run in his first 11 appearances (15 2/3 innings) as
a Red.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's not: C Eddie Taubensee is hitting .190 in his last six
games. OF Dmitri Young is hitting .227 over the last 10 days.
</P>
