<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burrough in the pits this offseason
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're looking for a future lawyer, accountant or
executive on the Atlanta Falcons current roster, then John Burrough
probably isn't your man. But if you want somebody who will get down
and dirty, he's the guy.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-year defensive end grew up in Wyoming, tending horses
and feeding cattle. After his pro football career, he aspires to
work in the oil industry, which is why he went back to school at
Wyoming to get his degree in geophysics.
</P>
<P>
   And this spring, he worked on the pit crew for NASCAR driver
Kyle Petty in races at Atlanta, Bristol and Talladega. The NFL
Players Association is one of Petty's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it's not where you expect to find a 6-foot-5, 275-pound
professional football player, but Burrough couldn't help himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became a NASCAR fan two years ago when I went to a race with
(former Falcon tackle) Antone Davis,'' he said. ``A lot of guys
went to the race in Daytona, but I wanted to get my hands dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   Burrough, who was used mostly as a backup to right end Chuck
Smith last year, spent his offseason getting dirty in Suwanee,
where coaches have worked on building his strength.
</P>
<P>
   In training camp this year, he's working behind left end Lester
Archambeau, but he'll probably play both ends, at least until
someone claims the fourth end spot.
</P>
<P>
   Burrough, who has had one start each of the last two seasons,
has played in all 48 games in his Falcon career. Last year was his
best statistically, with 30 tackles and his only career sack.
</P>
<P>
   But the shortage of sacks is not the Falcons' chief concern
about the former late seventh-round pick. Burrough sometimes gets
pushed too easily out of the way on running plays. So most of his
offseason work with strength and conditioning coach Al Miller has
been on holding his ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on the point of impact and sturdiness on run
blocks,'' he said. ``We've worked on power and explosion, and a lot
of that comes in the offseason. I had a good offseason, and as a
team we had a great offseason. The camaraderie of the guys was
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Team officials hope that offseason pays off for Burrough and his
teammates. In the meantime, he practically glows when talking of
his work in the Petty's pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't let me go over the wall,'' he said. ``What I did
was catch tires. As the tires come off the car, they throw them at
the wall, and I'd bring them over the wall. I also worked a sign
board, which brings Kyle in to the pit at certain times. Once I
went to a NASCAR race and worked in the pits, I was a fan for
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
