</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-POLLS-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fingers point to Ohio State
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1998 season ended on a particularly sour note for the Ohio
State Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 22, Ohio State was 10-1 and ranked No. 4 when it played
No. 2 Michigan for the Big Ten championship and a spot in the Rose
Bowl. The Buckeyes, however, could not stop Michigan's Charles
Woodson and lost 20-14. That dropped Ohio State to 1-8-1 against
Michigan in nine years under coach John Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, Ohio State fell to Florida State 31-14 in the Sugar
Bowl in a game that wasn't that close. Cooper's bowl record at Ohio
State fell to 2-7.
</P>
<P>
   But if we are to believe the preseason magazines, 1998 will be a
year of redemption for both Cooper and the Buckeyes. Six of the
eight magazines surveyed by The Journal-Constitution have Ohio
State No. 1, and the composite poll has the Buckeyes No. 1 overall,
just ahead of Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State has been in the national championship race for most
of this decade, but something always has gotten in the way _
usually Michigan. In fact, Ohio State's last national title came 30
years ago. But with 17 starters returning and a schedule that has
Penn State, Michigan State and Michigan coming to Columbus, the
scribes say this finally will be the Buckeyes' breakthrough season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in NFL history, Ohio State didn't get
anybody drafted this year,'' said Charlie Miller, the managing
editor at Athlon, which has the Buckeyes No. 1. ``That tells us
they didn't lose anybody from what was a bowl-alliance team. And
John Cooper's jinx against Michigan has to end sooner or later.''
Others have not jumped on the Ohio State bandwagon. They look at
the fact that in 11 of the past 14 seasons, Ohio State has ended
the season with a loss to Michigan. They look at Ohio State's
opener at West Virginia (11th in the composite poll) on Sept. 5,
and see an upset in the making. They see a Florida State team that
has gotten even faster in the offseason and has all of its tough
games, including Florida, at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida State was one play away from playing Nebraska for the
national championship last season,'' said Tom Deinhart of The
Sporting News, one of two magazines that picked the Seminoles No.
1. ``If Chris Weinke works out at qua rterback, they are certainly
good enough to run the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bobby Bowden's team was No. 1 in the coaches' poll last
season when it fell 32-29 at Florida. The Seminoles are hungry
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``With us, you have to ask, `Can they put it all together?'''
said Bowden, whose teams have finished in the top five for 11
straight years. ``If we do, we'll be as good as we have been. We
certainly have the pieces to be that kind of team.''
</P>
<P>
   While Florida State and Ohio State got all the first-place
votes, several other teams could jump into the national
championship race, which will end Jan. 4 in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Florida finished No. 3 in the comtion's most versatile players
in tailback J.R. Redmond, and the Sun Devils don't play UCLA. LSU
looks for a breakthrough season with the return of tailback Kevin
Faulk. But the Tigers must play at Florida on Oct. 10. UCLA brings
a 10-game winning streak and quarterback Cade McNown into the
season. Tennessee will be very good on offense again.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a real darkhorse, try West Virginia, which
returns a ton of starters, including quarterback Marc Bulger and
tailback Amos Zereoue. The Mountaineers will find out if they are
for real on Sept. 5, when Ohio State visits.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
