<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-WISCONSIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern negotiating to build, operate Wisconsin generating
plant
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co., expanding its network of electric power
plants outside the Southeast, is negotiating with a Milwaukee-based
utility to build and operate a $125 million natural-gas-fueled
plant in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Electric said the Atlanta-based utility holding
company will build the plant in Herman, Wis., then sell the
Wisconsin utility all but 50 megawatts of the plant's 300 megawatts
of electricity capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern offer was the top bid among 20 proposals. Final
details of the eight-year power purchase agreement are still being
negotiated, and a final decision on the plant site is yet to come.
The preferred location is a 30-acre site Wisconsin Electric owns in
Sheboygan County.
</P>
<P>
   David Mould, a spokesman for Southern, said the company is
optimistic final details can be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facility is scheduled for operation by June 2000 and will
strengthen electric reliability in the region,'' said Richard
Grigg, president and chief operating officer of Wisconsin Electric.
</P>
<P>
   The utility said the plant would provide enough electricity to
meet the requirements of 100,000 homes. That's about one-tenth of
Wisconsin Electric's 1 million customers in the eastern part of the
state and Michigan's Upper Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The plant would be owned by Southern Energy Inc., a Southern
subsidiary that presumably would be free to market surplus
electricity in wholesale markets.
</P>
<P>
   Southern is moving to establish footholds in electricity markets
around the country as deregulation expands in the industry. In most
cases, it is building or operating plants and agreeing to supply
power back to local utilities for set periods with rights to sell
surplus power in wholesale markets.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Southern has announced plans to sell
electricity from four upstate New York plants owned by Sithe
Energies and to acquire a network of small Massachusetts plants
from Commonwealth Energy System for $537 million.
</P>
<P>
   Southern last year acquired an antiquated coal-fueled plant in
Hammond, Ind., for $68 million. The plant caught fire last week,
injuring 14 workers. Southern also has a 50 percent stake in a
small plant in King George County, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Southern is seeking approval to build a $175 million plant in
southern New Hampshire and is part of a consortium bidding about $1
billion for plants now owned by Cajun Electric Power Cooperative, a
bankrupt Louisiana utility cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Southern's Georgia Power Co. subsidiary has
made long-term agreements to purchase electricity from two Georgia
power plants owned by out-of-state companies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
