<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside pro tennis
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Davis Cup captain Tom Gullikson was thrilled that Milwaukee
was chosen as the site of the semifinal against Italy in September,
saying, ``This is a proud day for me, being a native of
Wisconsin,'' but that selection apparently cost the team Andre
Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you right now, me and (Jim) Courier would have
rather played in Southern California,'' Agassi said. ``What about
what the players think? I was hoping it would be down there (in San
Diego) or we could pull it off in (Las) Vegas. I could've played in
San Diego, but now I can't play in Milwaukee.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi had already committed himself to attending a dinner for
the Andre Agassi Foundation in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the U.S.-Belgium Davis Cup quarterfinal last month
in Indianapolis drew just short of 12,000 for the three days. The
first-round match against Russia at Stone Mountain Park attracted
over 14,000 despite a rainout.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open preview for women
</P>
<P>
   The best event before the U.S. Open hardcourt probably will be
this week's Toshiba Classic in San Diego, where the field includes
Martina Hingis, Monica Seles, Venus Williams, Steffi Graf and Anna
Kournikova. ... Seles on her first meeting against Williams, a
semifinal loss last week in Stanford, Calif.: ``She does a very
good variety on her serve. I really love that part of her game. I
wish I had that serve and that athletic ability.'' Williams won
6-3, 6-4 and hit 12 aces, including the first and final points of
the match. ... Graf, who lost to Lindsay Davenport in the Stanford
semifinals, was asked how her injury layoff affected her personal
life. ``I have to approach people more,'' she said. ``I think I'm a
more open person. Maybe it is something of a coming of age. I used
to be very quiet, I know. But I have had to make major changes.''
</P>
<P>
   TeamTennis
</P>
<P>
   Four Atlanta players are competing in World TeamTennis this
summer. T.J. Middleton is ranked fourth in singles at 59-51 for
third-place Springfield and beat Jimmy Connors of Kansas City 6-3
in Connors' debut. Richey Reneberg is 16-11 in limited singles duty
for second-place Sacramento. Luke and Murphy Jensen are 50-51 in
doubles for last-place Delaware. Luke is 14-30 and Murphy 20-25 in
singles. The league is at midseason break and will resume Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Loose points
</P>
<P>
   Rod Laver's recovery from a stroke is only beginning, according
to Dr. Neil Martin, co-director of the stroke center at UCLA
Medical Center. ``He's going to have a substantial job in front of
him, as far as physical therapy,'' Martin said. ``We're talking
months of therapy.'' ... Pete Sampras' plantar's wart was good
fortune to the du Maurier Open in Toronto. Sampras, who pulled out
of Los Angeles last week after the minor foot surgery, took a wild
card into Toronto this week instead and will play there for the
first time since 1990. ... During the first round of the Fed Cup,
Davenport said U.S. team members were on a mission to win back the
championship. Just days before the second round last month, she
begged off because of mental fatigue, prompting a late
substitution. ... Thomas Muster's injured left shoulder could keep
him out of the U.S. Open. ... Brad Gilbert says NCAA singles
champion Bob Bryan's game reminds him of his own. ``I didn't think
my game is that ugly,'' Bryan responded. ... Atlanta's Doug Flach
won three matches to qualify for the du Maurier Open in Toronto.
... Suspicious of tax evasion, German tax agents have raided about
30 locations linked to Boris Becker, including offices and
apartments of friends and the German Tennis Federation, according
to a Munich newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
