<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-APPRECIATE-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS REWROTE THE RULES IN A HIGH-TECH MEDIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (IDs Beth Potier in 14th graf; a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a high-tech medium, television usually requires effects more
special than a talking sock.
</P>
<P>
   But Shari Lewis was so gifted a puppeteer, ventriloquist, and
entertainer that she was able to rewrite the rules and win 12 Emmys
before dying Sunday at age 65 of complications from uterine cancer.
</P>
<P>
   However, the diminutive, red-haired dynamo also experienced
television's fickle side, and was absent from the tube for long
periods as cartoons took over children's programming.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis will forever be identified with her most indelible
creation: a cantankerous little puppet named Lamb Chop. As much of
a high-maintenance prima donna as Miss Piggy, Lamb Chop was
nobody's sheep. Her screechy voice was even heard in the halls of
Congress. On programs such as ``Lamb Chop's Play-Along,'' she made
the sort of mischief that gave a vicarious thrill to millions of
children watching at home _ while demurely professing her innocence
all the while.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Lewis means that yet another reassuring figure from
television's early years is gone from the scene. In the past month,
Robert Young of ``Father Knows Best,'' Buffalo Bob Smith of ``The
Howdy Doody Show,'' and singing cowboy Roy Rogers also have passed
away.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis seemed both ageless and tireless. It was easy to forget
that she had introduced Lamb Chop as far back as 1957, on ``The
Captain Kangaroo Show,'' before going on to create and star in such
shows as ``The Shari Lewis Show,'' ``Lamb Chop's Play-Along,'' and
her latest, ``The Charlie Horse Music Pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was someone who seemed to get younger as she got older,''
said children's TV activist Peggy Charren, a friend of Lewis's.
``She had more energy than anybody I know. She was Charlie Horse
and she was Lamb Chop, and some of those conversations between the
two of them were achingly funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The ebullient Lewis filled her shows with music, comedy,
riddles, puns, and easy-to-digest lessons about life. The
educational impulse was present off-camera too; Charren said Lewis
was as much activist as entertainer, ever concerned about expanding
the array of choices for children on television.
</P>
<P>
   During a memorable day in 1993, Lewis brought Lamb Chop to
Capitol Hill to make an impassioned plea to broadcasters to improve
children's television programming. ``We need the best you grown-ups
have to offer,'' Lewis had the puppet say. ``If you give it to us,
we will give you the good stuff back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis herself had a broad definition of ``the good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Lewis noticed that few TV programs seemed geared
toward Jewish children, so she came up with such primetime specials
as ``Lamb Chop's Special Chanukah'' and ``Shari's Passover
Surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Conscious that television seldom tried to foster an appreciation
of music, Lewis created a show designed to do just that, ``The
Charlie Horse Music Pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What she did was look at what was missing on television and
try to fill the gap,'' said Charren.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Potier, a spokesperson for WGBH-TV in Boston, which carried
Lewis' shows, recalled seeing Lewis perform last year in Dallas at
a PBS meeting. ``She did a song-and-dance with Lamb Chop, very fast
back and forth, singing the whole time,'' said Potier. ``She had to
change her voice each time, and throw her voice. It was
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis began astounding spectators at an early age. She first
pulled a rabbit out of her hat at the age of 4, appeared on her
first TV variety show at age 13, and starred in ``Facts 'n' Fun''
on NBC at 18. &UR;  &LR; She cemented her status as a leading children's
entertainer with ``The Shari Lewis Show,'' which ran Saturday
mornings on NBC from 1960 to 1963 before being canceled as
children's television shifted its focus to animation.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a half-hour syndicated puppet show called ``The Shari
Show'' in 1975, it would be three decades before Lewis regained a
prominent place on television. A resilient trouper, she took her
act to Las Vegas, appeared on game shows, and even conducted
symphony orchestras. She also wrote more than 60 children's books,
and in 1986, entertained children from around the world at a White
House Christmas party.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis returned triumphantly to television with ``Lamb Chop's
Play-Along,'' which premiered on PBS in 1992. Before Lewis stopped
production on it last year, the show had won five Emmys. Then, in
January, Lewis introduced ``The Charlie Horse Music Pizza'' on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   In June, however, she was diagnosed with uterine cancer. She cut
short production on the show six weeks ago when she began
undergoing chemotherapy treatments. Among the events she had to
miss was the ``Charlie Horse Music Pizza Jam Session,'' an event to
celebrate PBS' children's programming, at the Children's Museum in
Boston on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After developing pneumonia during chemotherapy, Lewis died
Sunday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center. She leaves her husband,
Jeremy Tarcher; her daughter, Mallory Tarcher; and many grateful
parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew what parents would like for their kids, and
fortunately, the kids liked it,'' said Charren. ``She had that
magic touch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
