<SLUG> BC-DELTA04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta receives higher rating in quest for happy customers
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines' push to improve its customer service
paid off in June with the Atlanta-based carrier ranking No. 2 among
the 10 major airlines in on-time arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, which ranked No. 4 in May on arrivals within 15 minutes
of schedule, also improved with fewer baggage-handling problems and
fewer complaints from customers, according to the latest Department
of Transportation figures available.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good indication of the focus we are putting on
reliability and on-time flights,'' Delta spokesman Bill Berry said
Monday. ``We are definitely committed to improving customer service
across the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is upgrading its fleet, installing new technology
and software to improve passenger traffic flow through its gates
and last month promoted 25-year Delta veteran Vicki Escarra, a
native Atlantan who started as a flight attendant, to executive
vice president-customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT's monthly Air Travel Consumer Report shows 75.4 percent
of Delta's flights arrived on time in June. The leader in the
category remained Southwest Airlines, which had 81.4 percent of its
flights arrive on time.
</P>
<P>
   While Delta came in second, its performance was actually below
the 79.5 percent of flights that were on time in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weather is a big variable,'' Berry said. ``You can have a bad
month or a good month depending on what the weather does for you in
your major hubs.'' Delta services 80 percent of the flights at
Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of this year, Delta ranked No. 4 in
on-time performance, compared with No. 10 a year ago, according to
the DOT report.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the nation's 10 largest carriers had an on-time arrival
record of 70.4 percent in June, down from May's 77.5 percent rate
and below June 1997's market of 76.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another key indicator of service is mishandled baggage. In June,
Delta jumped from No. 5 in May to No. 1 in June with 3.99 reports
for every 1,000 passengers. America West had 4.27 complaints per
1,000 passengers, putting it in the second spot.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also improved with fewer customer complaints in June,
rising to No. 3 from No. 4 in the ranking. It had .60 complaints
per 100,000 passengers, compared with the carrier with the worst
results: Northwest with 2.34 complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Among all airliens in June, consumers filed 709 complaints about
airline service, 22 percent fewer than the 914 filed in May and 6
percent below the 758 percent in June a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT results did not include second quarter figures on
``bumping,'' or passengers who were either voluntarily or
involuntarily denied boarding. Delta ranked No. 6 in the first
quarter, January through March, with 1.14 bumpings per 10,000
passengers, compared with 2.23 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
