<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN EXILE ASSERTS HE DELIBERATELY MISINFORMED THE NEW YORK
TIMES  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Cuban exile who conducted violent operations against the Cuban
government has asserted that he deliberately misinformed The New
York Times when he said in a series of interviews that leaders of
the most influential exile organization in the United States had
provided him with financial support.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, a cable news station in Miami broadcast
excerpts from an interview in which the Cuban exile, Luis Posada
Carriles, said he had lied because The New York Times had
information about financial backers in the United States whom he
wished to protect. He said that he had misdirected the newspaper by
asserting that he had received money from Jorge Mas Canosa, who,
until his death, was the leader of the Cuban-American National
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newspaper had a lot of information about people that could
be adversely affected, people that were alive, that could get into
federal problems,'' Posada said in the interview with CBS
Telenoticias, a Spanish-language station. The interview was
conducted in Spanish and translated by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say what pressures Mr. Posada may have felt to change
his story, or what second thoughts he may have had after seeing the
furious reaction among anti-Castro Cubans, or even what motivated
him to give us the interview in the first place,'' said Bill
Keller, the managing editor of The New York Times. ``As we made
clear in the original articles, he is a tricky character who lives
in a shadowy world. We presented him as an interesting figure from
history, not a paragon of truth and virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller added: ``What we can say with confidence is that he said
the things we quoted. We can say that some of what he said _
including the fact that he had a longstanding relationship with Mr.
Mas _ was corroborated by other interviews and documents. And where
we could not corroborate his claims, we said so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday night broadcast was the second interview with Posada
that has been aired in Miami since The New York Times published
three articles about his activities and his ties with Mas.
Immediately after The New York Times articles were published, the
foundation called a news conference to condemn the articles and
showed a videotaped interview with Posada in which he said the
articles were lies. In that interview, Posada asserted that The New
York Times had misquoted him.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times quoted Posada as saying that over the years,
Mas and other leaders of the Cuban-American National Foundation had
sent him more than $200,000. Posada admitted that he had been
responsible for a number of violent acts, including several
attempts on the life of Fidel Castro and the bombing of hotels last
year in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Posada was quoted in The New York Times as saying that all
payments were made in cash and that he did not know whether the
money came from personal, business, or foundation accounts. He said
the money was used for his living and operating expenses. Posada
said that Mas did not want to know the details of Posada's
activities and he did not tell him.
</P>
<P>
   In tracing the relationship between Mas and Posada, The New York
Times drew on recently declassified government documents, including
a 1965 Central Intelligence Agency cable that asserts that Mas had
paid Posada $5,000 to place mines in a Cuban or Soviet vessel in a
Mexican harbor. The articles also included a deposition by Mas'
brother, Ricardo Mas, who said that his brother had used the money
to pay for Posada's escape from jail and his transportation from
Venezuela to Central America.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent interview, Posada said that all of his
comments about the foundation and Mas were deliberate pieces of
disinformation intended to lead The New York Times away from his
true sources of financing in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times asked Posada in the interviews several times
about a document that indicated he was receiving money for the
hotel bombings from four Cuban Americans in Union City, N.J., one
of them a member of the foundation with close ties to its leaders
in Miami. He confirmed the authenticity of the document but
declined to explain it.
</P>
<P>
   In the television interview on Sunday, Posada said that it had
been ``15 years, 12 years since I last had contact with Jorge
Mas.''
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, Posada had said that it was eight to 10 years
since he had contact with Mas. He told The New York Times that they
had last spoken about a month before Mas' death in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent interview, Posada was asked if the Cuban
foundation had sent him money to finance subversive actions. ``They
have never sent me any to finance subversive acts, never given me
money to pay my expenses, not for any other type of activities,''
he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times article did not say the foundation had given
money to Posada.
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiography, however, Posada wrote that foundation
leaders had helped pay his medical and living expenses and
transportation from Venezuela to Central America after he escaped
from jail in 1985. Posada told The New York Times that Mas had
coordinated the flow of money to him.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Mas said in the deposition that his brother had paid for
Posada's escape from jail after he was arrested for bombing a
Cubana airliner in 1976, killing 73 people. Mas testified that his
brother said ``he needed me to go down and bring back $50,000, that
it would be used to get Luis Posada Carriles out of jail, that
Carriles wanted out, that he might start talking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
