<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAS-VEGAS-MAYOR-ART-715(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAS VEGAS MAYOR RUNS FOR GOVERNOR, WITH BREAST CANCER HELD HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Jan Jones is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ After Jan Jones, this booming city's two-term
Democratic mayor, entered the Nevada gubernatorial race just over
two months ago, she had plenty on her mind and on her plate. There
were dollars to be raised, hands to be shaken, pitches to be honed.
</P>
<P>
   But first and foremost, there were chemotherapy and radiation
treatments to be endured. In tandem with her quest to become the
state's first female governor, Ms. Jones was trying to overcome
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, she still is. Although Ms. Jones says that the
surgery she underwent in February was successful and that the odds
that she is cured are better than 90 percent, doctors are still
pumping toxins into her body, in case there is any residual cancer
to be vanquished.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones capped off perhaps the most turbulent, eventful few
days of her campaign more than a week ago with a chemotherapy
session. She has one more to go.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that she has made no effort to conceal any of this _
her husband, Richard Schuetz, a gambling industry consultant, wrote
a front-page article for The Las Vegas Sun in which he described
lying beside her in bed and welcoming her snoring as a sign that
she was sleeping well _ has lent a fascinating, unpredictable
dynamic to the Nevada gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   But it has also underscored the extent to which candidates and
elected officials have in many cases come to expose the most
intimate corners of their lives, including illness, to public view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in an era when politicians look to humanize themselves
and talk about these things much more often,'' said Stuart
Rothenberg, editor of The Rothenberg Political Report.
</P>
<P>
   It is in many ways a bold contrast to the past, when politicians
like Franklin Delano Roosevelt and John F. Kennedy sought to
conceal or at least soft-pedal health problems: polio in
Roosevelt's case and Addison's disease, a degeneration of the
adrenal glands, in Kennedy's. The prevailing wisdom and worry were
that voters might be concerned by any suggestion that a candidate
or elected official was not in robust health.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking appeared to influence Paul Tsongas, a Democratic
candidate for president who in 1992 trumpeted what he called a full
recovery from lymphoma by allowing news photographers to take
pictures of him in his bathing suit at the pool where he swam laps.
It was later learned that Tsongas' prognosis was more problematic,
and he died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been many signs in recent years that the
political climate is changing, at least at the level below the
presidency. Lawton Chiles was elected governor of Florida in 1990
despite an admission that he had taken anti-depressant medication,
and Ms. Jones, 49, is one of several candidates around the country
this year who have been remarkably open about health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill., who is 46, has spoken candidly about
having Parkinson's disease, a degenerative nerve disorder, as has
70-year-old Rep. Joe Skeen, R-N.M. Both are running for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts said this openness is part of a
confessional culture in America that has inevitably influenced
politics and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Al Gore and the trials and tribulations of every family
member,'' said Rothenberg, referring to the vice president's
frequent public comments about his sister's lung cancer and a
nearly fatal accident in which his son was hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg said it was impossible to know how much, if any,
calculation goes into these confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Other political analysts said that politicians may simply be
anticipating scrutiny from reporters and beating them to the punch.
Both Evans and Skeen had faced speculation about their health
before revealing they had Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones said she could easily have kept her breast cancer
secret, but did not do so in part because she felt she could help
educate people about the disease and the importance of the early
detection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've often said I could be the only governor candidate who
could save women's lives,'' said Ms. Jones, adding that her busy
public schedule and obvious vim should reassure voters that she is
fine, and that her honesty could help her at the polls. Many
political analysts agree.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it could play out differently, says Aaron Russo, one of
several Republicans in the race. Russo, a movie producer running a
somewhat offbeat campaign, said bluntly that voters should be wary
of Ms. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if, God forbid, something happened to Jan when she was
governor?'' Russo asked in an interview. ``If she's sick, I don't
know that what she's doing is best for the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' volubility about her breast cancer is only the latest
surprising chapter in a political career that has pegged her as one
of the most interesting up-and-comers in the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscally conservative but socially liberal, she has an
undergraduate degree from Stanford University, a personal worth of
millions, a generous nimbus of frosted hair, a penchant for
extremely high heels, eight cats, four dogs and three children,
ages 18, 14 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   Before she was elected mayor of Las Vegas in 1991, she was best
known to Nevadans for her campy shenanigans in a string of
television commercials for the car dealerships owned by her second
husband. The couple later divorced and Ms. Jones was married in
January to Schuetz, her third husband.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones said that she was not merely an actress in the
commercials, in which she was cast as Little Red Riding Hood and a
gangster's moll, but a principal force in their creation, correctly
anticipating that consumers, traditionally suspicious of car
salesmen, would find a woman more trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, there was no other woman on TV selling cars,''
she said over a long dinner several weeks ago. ``Today in Las
Vegas, every car dealership has a woman spokesperson. I think I set
the trend.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughed. ``Politics was the only job I could have found
where I didn't step down from selling cars,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones is considered the front-runner to win the Democratic
gubernatorial primary in September, but political analysts said
that she would clearly be the underdog in a match-up in November
with Kenny Guinn, 61, the former president of the University of
Nevada at Las Vegas, who is expected to win the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge before her may have grown a bit tougher a week and
a half ago, when the state's Ethics Commission decided to
investigate whether there was any impropriety in a vote by Ms.
Jones, who sits on the Las Vegas City Council, that appeared to
benefit one of her political contributors. Ms. Jones has denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger hurdle she faces may be financial. While she has
raised about $800,000 so far, Guinn has raised about $3.5 million,
which is one reason why many Nevadans consider Guinn's election a
foregone conclusion. Ms. Jones has taken to referring to herself as
the ``fly in the anointment.''
</P>
<P>
   That she is a woman could work to her advantage. In recent
years, Nevada has elected more women proportionally to state and
national offices than most other states, and this election season
could be the best test of that progressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Jones, the Democratic front-runners for attorney
general and lieutenant governor are women, an all-female lineup
that political insiders have taken to calling ``the estrogen
ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Ralston, the publisher of a nonpartisan political newsletter
in Nevada, also noted: ``The more Jan Jones plays up the breast
cancer thing, the more she plays up her gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of her opponents conceded quietly that the public sympathy
created by her openness about breast cancer makes campaigning
against her a more delicate endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's helping her, but the whole thing can be
overplayed,'' Ralston said. ``There's a slight danger of her doing
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
