<SLUG> BC-MARKET-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW FALLS 96.55; NASDAQ INDEX TAKES BIGGER HIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks fell Monday as investor concerns that Asia's
economic crisis will continue to erode the profits of U.S.
companies depressed share prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 96.55 points, to 8,786.74,
a 1.09 percent decline. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
dropped 8.23 points, to 1,112.44.
</P>
<P>
   But once again the technology-laden Nasdaq composite index took
a greater hit, declining 21.29 points, to 1,851.10, a 1.14 percent
drop. Microsoft, Worldcom, MCI Communications and
Tele-Communications Inc. were the leading decliners in the index,
which lost more than 3 percent of what its value was last week.
That compared with last week's 0.6 percent drop in the Dow and 1.8
percent fall in the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Asia pushed the dollar higher against the yen, to
145.60, closer to its June 16 high of 146.75 yen _ its highest
level in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds gained as the strong dollar made Treasury issues an
attractive safe-haven investment for foreign buyers. Treasury
securities were also buoyed by a larger-than-expected decline in
the July National Association of Purchasing Management's index.
</P>
<P>
   The key indicator of domestic manufacturing activity fell to
49.1 in July from 49.6 in June, its second consecutive decline
after 22 months of being above 50, the dividing line between a
manufacturing sector that is expanding and one that is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fairly strong consumer demand and tame inflation in the
United States, analysts are concerned that Asia's woes will crimp
earnings, especially for large multinational companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on second-quarter earnings, it's clear there's a
meaningful slowdown in profit growth,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief
investment officer at First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson noted that even companies with limited operations in
Asia, like Computer Associates International, were being affected
by the malaise. This is because some of the company's customers _
with greater exposure to Asia _ may delay spending on the software
developers' products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find a safe haven or avoid being hurt by what's
going on in Asia,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to his more bearish sentiment, Johnson on Monday
lowered his earnings forecasts for the S&AMP;P 500. He now expects
operating earnings for the S&AMP;P 500 to be $46.73 a share this year,
down from $48.57, and $49.48 in 1999, down from $52.21.
</P>
<P>
   His forecasts are slightly below the consensus estimates of
$47.20 and $49.70, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the declines and a strong bearish market sentiment,
Johnson and several other analysts believe the declines simply
signal a market correction and are not the beginning of a severe
market decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this short-term setback as a reality check, however,
rather than the start of a meaningful move to the downside,''
Elizabeth Mackay, investment strategist at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co.,
wrote in a recent market report.
</P>
<P>
   Declines should be limited to a 7 percent to 10 percent decline
for the major market indexes from their recent highs, Ms. Mackay
wrote. At Monday's close, the Dow was down about 5.9 percent from
its July 17 record close of 9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
   But if the index falls below its recent low of 8,627.93
investors may begin to worry more about whether the declines will
end soon.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's losses left the Dow 158.81 points away from its recent
low of 8,727.93 on June 15. A close below that would signal an
almost 8 percent decline from the July 17 high.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the market, the German software developer SAP began
trading on the New York Stock exchange Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The company, with a market capitalization of about $73 billion,
is the world's second-largest technology company behind Microsoft.
It is also the largest new listing ever on the Big Board, a
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Its size is one reason SAP chose to list on the New York Stock
Exchange, as opposed to the Nasdaq, said Kevin McKay, chief
operating officer and chief financial officer of SAP Americas. ``We
don't characterize ourselves as a high-tech start-up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company favored a recent change in the
exchange's policies that allowed SAP to select the specialist, or
dealer, who is assigned to maintain fair and orderly trading in the
stock. Generally, specialists are assigned securities by the
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The company's American depository receipts fell 1 15/16, to 59
9/16. One ADR represents one-twelfth of a preferred share of SAP
stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
