<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-LIGTENBERG-COX     08-03 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-LIGTENBERG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ligtenberg doesn't fit mold, but has been unstoppable
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson and Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His are not classic closer credentials.
</P>
<P>
   You think Robb Nen is one course shy of a degree in chemical
engineering? Trevor Hoffman neither walked on at the University of
Minnesota nor attended college on a student loan. Rod Beck didn't
go undrafted, then play for a minor-league team called the Loons
and endure all-night, 26-hour bus rides through the Canadian
wilderness to pitch. Mariano Rivera wasn't traded for a bunch of
bats and balls. John Wetteland doesn't have ``90210'' sideburns.
Jeff Shaw's father didn't pressure him to abandon his baseball
dreams and take that job offer in a 3M lab.
</P>
<P>
   Only baseball's other Kerry did all that. Only Kerry Ligtenberg.
That, and reassert himself again and again whenever others doubted
him. And now look. Ladies and gentlemen, the new closer on
baseball's team of the '90s, the NL's Luke Perry Luke-alike _ Kerry
Ligtenberg?
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg, Mr. October closer? Yes. Yes indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the (expletive) story of the century for me,'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said. ``The guy's a chemical engineer coming out
of an independent league, and he's closing for a team that's won
more games than any team in the major leagues the last eight
years.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Ligtenberg merely hoped to throw well enough in
Double or Triple A to get to spring training '98 as a non-roster
invitee. Then he was abruptly promoted to Atlanta last August.
``That was a dream,'' Ligtenberg said. ``I was shocked, but happy.
I thought from now on, everything I do from here on out is icing on
the cake. Nobody expected me to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Ligtenberg needs a steam-shovel-sized spatula to
spread all the icing. Ever since Mark Wohlers hurt his side, then
lost his control, Ligtenberg has not only assumed the closer's
role, he's commanded it. Since July 1, the day after Wohlers was
optioned to Richmond to rediscover the strike zone, Ligtenberg's
been lights-out.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 appearances, he's allowed just one earned run in 14 2/3
innings, an ERA of 0.61. He's converted nine straight save
opportunities (10 in a row overall), the last two coming Saturday
and Sunday against St. Louis. Ligtenberg is 16-for-18 in save
situations and has lowered his ERA from 4.16 at the end of June to
3.14. And with the July 31st trading deadline having passed without
Atlanta acquiring a reliever, Kerry's the closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What hasn't he done?'' asked Cox. ``There's no criticism of
Kerry Ligtenberg. Can't be. The guy throws strikes, throws 94, 95
miles an hour, can hit the black with his slider. He's been
dynamite. The guy's a pretty well-kept secret around the league
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With his portfolio, who wouldn't be? In 1989, upon graduation
from Park High School in the Minneapolis suburb of Cottage Grove,
Ligtenberg was 6-1, 150. ``School was easy for me,'' said
Ligtenberg, who was in all advanced-placement classes in high
school. His best buddies weren't nerds, ``but nobody was into
baseball.'' When four of them _ all good math students _ decided to
attend Minnesota, Ligtenberg did, too. Only one, David Hall, made
it through the chemical engineering school rated No. 1 in the
country. ``He's into polymers,'' Ligtenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball walk-on, Ligtenberg was told by his college pitching
coach, Rob Fornicere, that he'd never make it as a professional
pitcher. As a junior, he was 7-6, with two shutouts. His senior
season began with a trip south and three straight losses: At
Georgia Tech, where Jason Varitek beat him with a three-run homer;
at FSU, where Paul Wilson out-dueled him; and at Miami, where
Ligtenberg was shelled.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he regrouped, pitching well enough to make third-team
All-Big Ten and get the Gophers into the NCAA Regionals. When
Ligtenberg wasn't drafted, though, he considered going to a
major-league tryout. But his head coach, John Anderson, advised,
``Don't do that. You have some ways to go. Why don't you go talk to
this guy Olson about playing?''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Olson, the Braves' catcher from 1990-93, was then the
general manager/manager of the Minneapolis Loons of the
now-defunct, independent Prairie League. Ligtenberg auditioned for
the Loons and Olson offered him a contract: $650 a month. Norm
Ligtenberg, a chemical engineer at 3M, urged his son to consider a
3M job offer. Kerry had considered that career path until an
internship at 3M. ``I always wanted to work in a lab,'' he said,
``but when I started to, it sucked.''
</P>
<P>
   So he'd started taking management courses. When Olson offered a
$650-a-month alternative, Ligtenberg jumped at it. The caliber of
play was ``a couple of steps down from Minnesota,'' he said. The
20-man roster included one ex-major leaguer: Senor Smoke, Juan
Berenguer, a reliever on the Braves' pennant winners of 1991-92.
``But he was just fat,'' Ligtenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Road trips were pure Prairie League, especially one bus ride to
Saskatoon after a day game in Minneapolis. ``We drove the whole 4th
of July,'' Ligtenberg said. ``We watched fireworks as we're
driving. We got stopped at (Canadian) customs.'' Finally, 26 hours
later, the Loons hit Saskatoon. ``We ended up getting to the park
at six o'clock,'' he said. ``The game was at seven. We never took
BP. We just played.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg loved it, finishing 5-5. ``The first year, I wasn't
real good,'' he said. ``But I was having fun.'' When his father
again pressured him to go back to school and get his degree,
Ligtenberg went to Olson and said he needed more money to assuage
his dad. Done. A raise from $650 to $1,100. Ligtenberg remembers
pitching a no-hitter somewhere in North Dakota, in front of 50
people. By then, he was a two-pitch pitcher: A fastball that was up
to 90 mph and a slider. His changeup was ``awful.'' In the
off-season, he worked for UPS.
</P>
<P>
   After a second season of Loon-iness, Ligtenberg was invited to a
Cincinnati tryout camp. ``Don't do that,'' Olson told him. ``You
shouldn't have to. I want to get you invited to a spring-training
camp.'' In January 1996, three months after the season and since
Ligtenberg had last thrown a baseball, he went to an unheated
high-school gym one morning and threw for two Braves scouts. The
new scout wasn't impressed; the older one, Brian Kohlscheen, was. A
month after signing a contract, at $850 a month, a $250 pay cut
from the Loons, Ligtenberg went to West Palm Beach for his first
Braves' minor-league spring training camp.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Ligtenberg weighed 210 and threw in the low '90s. But
when a Class A Durham Braves coach called him aside shortly before
the last cut, he thought, ``I'm gonna get shafted.'' Nope. He had
eight saves by the All-Star break before blowing five-straight
saves in late June. But he bore down, threw 12 scoreless innings in
a row, finished with 20 saves and thought, ``I might be pretty good
at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, it was important to prove all the doubters
wrong, all those who thought he wasn't any good at Minnesota. Yet
his father persisted, saying, ``You're wasting your time.'' John
Anderson, though, told Ligtenberg, ``If you quit now, you'll never
know how far you might have gotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the minor-league camp in the spring of '97, Ligtenberg
was something of an enigma to Bill Fischer, the crafty,
curmudgeonly pitching coach at Richmond. ``Fisch and I really
didn't see eye to eye at first,'' he said. ``He's an old-school
guy. He liked me at first because I threw strikes, didn't walk a
lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer, however, hated Ligtenberg's appearance. The Braves have
a systemwide ban on facial hair, but Ligtenberg rarely shaved and
grew a huge shock of hair and long sideburns. ``To see how far I
could take it with the manager,'' said Ligtenberg, who was not
inspired by Luke Perry on ``Beverly Hills 90210.'' ``No, I thought
that guy looked like a dork,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Ligtenberg was finally called up to Atlanta last Aug. 12
and made his first appearance in a televised game, Olson called the
next day and said, ``You've got to get a haircut.'' When Ligtenberg
sat in the barber's chair, the barber recognized him from the
sideburns. So Ligtenberg lost the long hair but kept the sideburns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leo (Mazzone, the Braves pitching coach) always says, 'You can
grow 'em as long as you pitch like that,' `` Ligtenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   He's pitching with superb control (just two walks since July 1),
a splitter he learned from Bryan Harvey last season in Greenville
and an implacable sense of purpose. In his last outing in the
spring of '97, Ligtenberg walked four batters, drew Fischer's wrath
and then told off the old coach. He figures that's why he started
that season in Greenville, not Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Later that season, after being promoted to Richmond, Ligtenberg
gave up a game-losing, 13th-inning homer to Toledo, then walked off
the field and said, ``Hey, I'm fine.'' Later, he told Fischer,
``Come on, Fisch, that stuff's gonna happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, even here, Ligtenberg doesn't get flustered. ``He
always looks the same,'' Cox said. ''He looks like Fred McGriff
walking off the mound. You can't tell if he won or lost the game.
He's got the right makeup for it.''
</P>
<P>
   For closing. The toughest moment? Blowing a three-run lead five
weeks ago for Dennis Martinez, temporarily denying him a historic
242nd career win. ``I thought it was going to be easy and took it
for granted,'' Ligtenberg said. ``I overcame that. And if I can
overcome that, I can overcome about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, he already has. ``I don't think I'll ever take this
for granted,'' Ligtenberg said. ``From where I was three, four
years ago, this is about as far away as I can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
