<HEADER>
A6039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLADEMS-COX     08-03 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLADEMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's Democrats foundering
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jeb Bush's smile was as wide as the
Everglades as he worked the crowd of 250 people in a posh private
club overlooking the playground of America's upper classes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican front-runner in the Florida governor's race
wasn't addressing the rich, mostly white socialites and captains of
industry who own the oceanfront mansions of Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The audience was peppered with prominent business owners and
local politicians, but most of them happened to be black.
</P>
<P>
   Their polite _ even enthusiastic _ response to a Republican
candidate signaled the surge of another big wave in what has become
a watershed year in Florida politics.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the waves are crashing over the bow of the once-dominant
Florida Democratic Party, caught in a racial controversy that could
sink its campaign to hold onto its last remaining high-profile
state office: the governorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a headless horse,'' said University of South Florida
political scientist Susan MacManus, who tracks state politics.
``They haven't had any leadership. If they lose the governor's
chair, they've lost Florida for the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   So bad is the crisis that Vice President Al Gore will jet into
the state Friday to meet with the party leadership to try to sooth
the roiled waters. Gore isn't just providing a selfless boost to a
state party in trouble: He needs Florida in 2000 for his
presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' debacle began as a slow erosion in the 1980s,
when Republicans started making significant gains in voter
registration. Florida also voted Republican in several national
elections, like several other Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   But as recently as 1990, the Democrats still had the upper hand,
retaining majorities in both houses of the Legislature and
controlling most county and city offices.
</P>
<P>
   The relentless Republican tide, however, finally crested in
1992, when the GOP won exactly half the seats in the state Senate.
They followed up in 1994 by taking the Senate outright, then won
the House in 1996, making Florida's the first Southern statehouse
in GOP hands since Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats didn't do their homework,'' said Richard Scher,
a University of Florida political scientist who follows state
politics. ``The handwriting was on the wall in the late 1980s, but
since 1992, the collapse has been prodigious.''
</P>
<P>
   Voter registration records show the Democrats still maintain a
precarious edge over their GOP rivals, 45 percent to 40 percent.
The Democrats' tally is down from 66 percent just 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they have watched their power base erode, the party
has managed to exacerbate the crisis by alienating one of its most
loyal constituencies, African-American voters.
</P>
<P>
   In January, state Rep. Willie Logan, a black Democrat from
Opa-Locka, was in line to become the party's leader in Tallahassee.
At the last minute, Logan was deposed by 31 white Democrats who
said he hadn't raised enough money for the party and wasn't
providing the leadership they needed.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks were outraged. In the months since the coup, Logan has
teamed up with U.S. Rep. Alcee Hastings, an outspoken black
Democrat from Fort Lauderdale, to create a political action
committee that is working against the white Democrats who voted
against Logan.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have gleefully aided their cause. At one
high-profile fund-raiser this summer in Tallahassee, Republican
Party Chairman Tom Slade theatrically served lunch to Logan, then
gave his PAC $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 10 of the white Democrats who voted against Logan have
either retired from politics, switched parties or changed the
office they are seeking. The biggest casualty came last month when
State Rep. Anne Mackenzie of Fort Lauderdale, once a rising party
star who took over when Logan was ousted, suddenly retired from
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Mackenzie had done no better than Logan in raising money for the
party and couldn't smooth over the crisis created by the coup. All
this has happened just as the campaign between Bush and the
presumed Democratic nominee, Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay, is hitting full
stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like a nuclear blast,'' MacManus said of the Logan
debacle. ``It was the last straw that broke a coalition that had
been eroding for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKay desperately needs black support. The most recent poll in
late July showed him trailing Bush by 22 points. He also lags
dangerously in the race to raise campaign money. As of July,
Republicans had raised $8 million to the Democrats' $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is a formidable opponent. In 1994, he came within an
eyelash of defeating Lawton Chiles, one of the most popular
politicians in Florida in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, a longtime Democratic congressman from Ocala, ran for
the U.S. Senate in the late 1980s and lost to a Republican
congressman, Connie Mack. He then became Chiles' running mate and
has served two terms as lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   According to the polls, Logan's campaign to extract revenge from
his foundering party appears to be working. The July survey found
16 percent of blacks would vote for Bush _ a giant stride over the
5 percent he received in the 1994 race and clearly enough to turn
the tide in a close race. Observers say there is already a surge of
change bubbling among black voters nationally, with the traditional
unquestioning loyalty to the Democratic Party wavering. In Florida,
the Logan affair has accelerated that change and could prove a key
turning point in the history of the state's politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although MacManus and Scher believe MacKay still has time to
salvage his campaign and run competitively against Bush, both say
it will take the Democrats years to recover, even if MacKay wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warning signs have been there for a long time,'' MacManus
said. ``But it has happened very quickly. It caught the old-line
Democratic leadership with their pants down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
