<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWITCHED-COX     08-03 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWITCHED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Families working on solution of switched babies
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The families of two Virginia girls who were switched in the
hospital shortly after their births in 1995 are working out an
agreement that would keep the children with the people who
currently have custody, a relative said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The switched children, Rebecca Grace Chittum and Callie Marie
Johnson, are now 3 years old. Callie has been raised in
Ruckersville, Va., by Paula Johnson. Ninety miles away in Buena
Vista, Va., Rebecca had been raised by Kevin Chittum and his
fiancee, Whitney Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Chittum and Rogers died July 4 in a traffic accident that killed
five other people. Rebecca lives with her grandmother, Rosa Lee
Chittum, who is Kevin Chittum's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Paula and my sister will work it out,'' said Mary
Watts, Callie's biological great-aunt, in a telephone interview
Monday. ``There will be no court fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What an intelligent bunch of people, if that's the way it
turns out,'' said Elizabeth McCulloch, a family law expert at the
University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Watts said the child-switch surfaced after Paula Johnson filed a
dispute over child support and a DNA test showed Callie was not her
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never knew anything about it,'' Watts said. Officials from
the University of Virginia Medical Center in Charlottesville showed
up in recent weeks ``to take blood from Rebecca'' for tests,
providing the first hint that something was amiss.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said she doesn't want to take Rebecca from the family
that has raised her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This girl has already experienced so much tragedy in her three
years,'' Johnson told USA Today. ``I just wanted to know her name,
to see what she looked like and to know my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Johnson, 30, said, ``Words cannot express the
way I felt. This last month of not knowing has been agony for my
family and for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the news media have swept into Buena Vista, a
mountain town of 6,300 supported by the manufacture of space
heaters and drainage supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy. It's wild,'' said Watts, who has had reporters
from as far away as London tramping through her front yard.
</P>
<P>
   Buena Vista City Attorney W.T. Robey asked reporters to give the
Chittums and others space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grandparents dearly love this child they have and they
very much want for her to stay right here where she has been loved
and raised with the only family she has ever known,'' Robey said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A picturesque community in the lap of the Shenandoah Valley, the
town barely has emerged from its mourning for Chittum and the
others killed when the car they were in hit a patch of water on
I-81 near Buena Vista and slammed head-on into a tractor-trailer
truck. Almost 800 people attended the funeral. Some people still
light candles in the windows and vigils still have been seen in the
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town has been very supportive of the family,'' said Mayor
Harold Kidd. ``The accident was very devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   At Todd's, a downtown bar and restaurant known for a laid-back
atmosphere and barbecued ribs, the tragic crash was a topic at
nearly every table. ``Almost everyone knows everyone in the area,''
said Tonia Carpenter, 34, a waitress at Todd's.
</P>
<P>
   What is not yet known is the how and why of the baby switch that
occurred three years ago at the University of Virginia Medical
Center and only served to intensify the tragedy of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an internal investigation determined the switch could not
have happened by accident, and university police are investigating
the incident as a criminal act.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of their births, the girls and parents were
``banded'' with matching identification bracelets, hospital chief
of staff Thomas Massaro said in a statement. ``Banding was
documented, and the documentation was corroborated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No human enterprise can be perfect, and we are doing
everything we can to improve the process further,'' Massaro said
Monday through the hospital's media relations department.
</P>
<P>
   McCulloch, the family law expert, said courts ``strongly
prefer'' natural parents in custody cases unless ``strange
circumstances'' prevail. The longer a child lives with a
non-parent, the weaker the natural-parent argument becomes,
McCulloch said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Kimberly Mays, a Florida girl switched at birth
in 1978, Mays sued to ``divorce'' herself from her biological
parents. In 1993, a judge ruled in her favor. Within a year, Mays
changed her mind and moved in with her birth parents.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Rights Council in Washington, which lobbies to
``demilitarize divorce,'' urged the court to keep Mays with the
family that raised her _ a position it also takes with Callie and
Rebecca.
</P>
<P>
   David L. Levy, president of the Children's Rights Council,
declared that both birth parents and adoptive parents should be
involved in raising such children. ``You can't have too many
children loving the child,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
