</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-HOUSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE ACCEPTS BIPARTISAN CAMPAIGN FINANCE BILL
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted overwhelmingly Monday for a
bipartisan bill that could curb the flow to political parties of
the large contributions that were at the heart of many of the
scandals in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming months of delays by the Republican leadership, the
House voted 237-186 to accept the sweeping campaign-finance
overhaul co-authored by Rep. Chris Shays, R-Conn., and Martin
Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Their bill, which had been endorsed by the Democratic leadership
and President Clinton, had the support of 185 Democrats , 51
Republicans and one independent. The Republican leadership managed
to round up 175 Republicans and 11 Democrats to vote against. Two
Republicans and 10 Democrats missed the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters still face new struggles to defeat substitute bills
and obtain final House passage this week, and then to obtain
approval next month by the Senate, where GOP filibusters have
blocked final action on similar legislation twice within the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a generation, members of Congress take it upon
themselves to change our campaign finance laws,'' Meehan said.
``That day has arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, led the assault on the bill he
described as ``unilateral disarmament'' by the Republican Party,
because it contains a ban on unregulated ``soft money'' gifts to
political parties. The bill would no longer let the parties take
contributions of any size from the treasuries of corporations or
unions, or of more than $25,000 a year from any person.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18 months that ended June 30, the Republican Party
reported $70 million and the Democratic Party reported $45.8
million in soft money receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zach Wamp, R-Tenn., took exception to DeLay's description
of the bill as ``unilateral disarmament'' by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, this bill is as fair to Republicans as it is to
Democrats. It's the same to Wall Street as to the labor unions.
It's the same to the Christian Coalition as to the ACLU,'' Zach
said. ``Isn't that fair?''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay grumbled that he was unable to prevent votes for the
Shays-Meehan bill by Republicans seeking to please newspaper
editorial writers in their districts. He said the members told him,
``Since the Senate will never support the bill, they can afford to
vote yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., doesn't plan to schedule a
vote on the bill when the Senate reconvenes in September for the
final month of this session of Congress. Sens. John McCain,
R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold, D-Wis., whose version of the bill
was blocked by a GOP filibuster earlier this year, said the wide
victory margin in the House would help their plans to try again
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   They can offer the bill as an amendment or hold up action on
other vital legislation in an attempt to change Lott's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``No side can get 60 votes,'' which would be enough to end a
filibuster in the 100-member Senate, Lott's spokesman, John
Czwartacki (CQ), said. ``It would be a big waste of time.''
</P>
<P>
   However, supporters said they rescued the bill from similar
death threats many times in the past. In addition to forcing House
GOP leaders to keep their promises to allow votes on the
Shays-Meehan bill, they defeated 15 ``poison pill'' amendments that
they believed would have weakened the bill too much or made it too
strong to pass by such a large margin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to banning soft money, the Shays-Meehan bill would
tighten regulations for pre-election ads and financial disclosures,
and would create a nonpartisan commission to recommend further
reforms to the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all probability, the (Supreme) Court will hold parts of the
bill unconstitutional,'' said Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif. A leading
opponent of Shays-Meehan, he asked House members to vote by an even
larger margin later this week for a milder bipartisan substitute
sponsored by a group of freshman members.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan supporters will fight hard against that.
</P>
<P>
   After the nine remaining substitutes for the Shays-Meehan bill
are withdrawn or voted upon, only the version with the most votes
will be presented to the House for final passage. That final action
will take place before the House adjourns Friday for its month-long
summer vacation, promised Majority Leader Richard K. Armey,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
