<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-RETURN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM workers put in a full day, plus some OT
 &HT;    By Kristi E. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DORAVILLE, Ga. _ General Motors is starting to make up for lost
time.
</P>
<P>
   As the first shift in more than six weeks ended Monday, workers
rolled out of General Motors Corp.'s assembly plant after a full
workday, plus an hour of overtime. Most said morale inside was high
after settlement of strikes in Flint, Mich., that forced layoffs at
Doraville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's business as usual,'' said Kelvin Dennis, who spent his
time away from the plant fishing and taking vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is the same, and we're glad to be back,'' said Toni
Kemp, a 21-year GM veteran.
</P>
<P>
   All 4,000 workers were sent home in June after the plant ran out
of parts because of strikes by United Auto Workers at two parts
plants on June 5. GM and the UAW came to an agreement last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt really great to be in there,'' said Gary Christian.
``Six weeks without a paycheck isn't good.''
</P>
<P>
   Some workers and plant management headed back last week to
prepare for Monday's 6 a.m. start.
</P>
<P>
   The next few days will be spent heating up paint ovens, turning
on machines and making sure no problems occur before they start
churning out the Chevrolet Ventures, Oldsmobile Silhouettes,
Pontiac Trans Sports and Opel Sintras, said GM spokeswoman Marsha
Hall Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to start up in a controlled manner, from a quality
standpoint,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It will only be a matter of days before the plant is operating
at capacity, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Workers likely will have nine-hour days and overtime on
Saturdays for the rest of the year. Schedules are determined
weekly, however, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to try and make up for production losses,''
Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike idled more than 190,000 workers at 27 of GM's 29
North American assembly plants and cost the world's No. 1 automaker
an estimated $2.2 billion in profits.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
