<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-NOTEBOOK04-CO     08-03 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NOTEBOOK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons notebook
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the second Monday in a row, you needed a roster to
keep up with moves on the Atlanta Falcons' offseason line, as
several players were moved around, some because of an injury to
starting right tackle Corey Louchiey, and others by plan.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries, in fact, caused coach Dan Reeves to scrap morning
practice as the team went just once, at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Louchiey pulled a groin in the afternoon scrimmage Saturday in
Jacksonville, and Reeves said he might not play in Friday night's
preseason opener against Tennessee in the Georgia Dome. Backup left
tackle Nate Miller was moved to Louchiey's spot with the No. 1
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Other moves: backup rookie right tackle Ephraim Salaam moved to
No. 2 left tackle; No. 2 rookie right guard Bob Hallen was moved to
No. 2 left guard; No. 3 rookie right tackle Jose Portilla moved to
No. 2 right tackle, and No. 2 left guard Scott Adams moved to No. 2
right guard.
</P>
<P>
   Louchiey was one of six players who did not practice, and one of
10 on the injury report. His injury is significant. The Falcons
struggled at that spot last season, chiefly with departed Tim
Willig, and when Louchiey was signed as a free agent after starting
13 games in three seasons in Buffalo, he was inserted as the
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Salaam was backing him up, but since he and Portilla are
rookies, Reeves said the move of Miller to right tackle gives the
Falcons a veteran at that spot. He also said the Falcons had
planned on Salaam and Portilla working both sides, as any reserve
lineman will need to play multiple positions.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was an undrafted free agent defensive tackle out of LSU
in 1995. He spent most of '95 and most of '96 on the practice
squad. He did not dress for the first three games last season, and
saw limited reserve duty the final 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Louchiey on the sidelines were backup CB Randy Fuller
(ankle), starting CB Ronnie Bradford (hamstring), backup LBs David
Brandon (foot arch) and Ruffin Hamilton (hamstring), and DE Barry
Mitchell (groin). It was the first practice missed for Brandon and
Hamilton, and the ninth straight for Mitchell, a member of last
year's practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had six or eight guys who couldn't go this morning, and we
thought some of them might go this afternoon,'' Reeves said. ''We
were a little short with secondary receivers, and at cornerback.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Keith Crawford, who missed four straight practices with
a hamstring, was able to practice, as was receiver Mercury Hayes,
who missed the afternoon scrimmage in Jacksonville. Also, rookie
cornerback Elijah Williams, who sprained an ankle Saturday morning
in Jacksonville, was able to go Monday. Fuller (10 practices
missed) and Bradford (nine) both looked a lot better, running
during practice.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the injury report from Monday: DT Mark Campbell (knee
sprain), G Jeremy Akers (shoulder, elbow), LG Calvin Collins
(wrist) and Hayes (hamstring).
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   Reeves wasn't sure whether the team would practice once or twice
today, but the Falcons almost surely will practice just once
Wednesday and once Thursday. Should there be two practices today,
they'll likely be at 9 a.m. and 3 p.m. It's possible Thursday's
practice will be at the Dome, a sort of walk-through prior to
Friday's preseason opener. Coaches may also experiment on the
sidelines with headsets. This will be the first year the NFL is
using wireless communications systems, although coaches will have
the option of using the old system. Today, it's possible the
Falcons will stage a full-go, tackling-included drill for just the
second time in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Turning down the heat
</P>
<P>
   It was more like late October Monday, as it was a 82 degrees
with 50 percent humidity. It was obvious after practice it had been
cooler because just a handful of players got in ice barrels to cool
down their legs. Normally, there's a waiting line.
</P>
<P>
   QB watch
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at what's going on with the quarterbacks:
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler - Threw in drills and worked with the No. 1
offense ''red zone'' drills and regular 11-on-11 sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graziani -- Ditto, except with the No. 2 offense. Also had
holding dutes with placekickers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve DeBerg -- Ditto, except with the No. 3 offense. Also had
holding duties with placekickers. Took some snaps with the No. 1
and No. 2 offenses in 9-on-7 running game sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Brennan -- Threw in drills, and took some snaps with the
No. 1 and No. 2 offenses in 9-on-7 running game sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The good, bad, and ugly
</P>
<P>
   Good: In full-go field goal drills, reserve cornerback Juran
Bolden blocked a 35-yard attempt by backup kicker David Akers. He
knifed through on the right side, squeezing between outside man Ed
Smith and end Travis Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Bad: Starting cornerback Ray Buchanan got beat deep down the
middle by rookie free agent receiver Octavus Barnes in one-on-one
passing drills. Buchanan ran him down about 30 yards later and
tackled him.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly: In the 11-on-11 session, Chandler rolled out right under a
heavy rush and threw a perfect 21-yard pass to Terance Mathis near
the right sideline. Mathis dropped it, screaming in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   What he said
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's confidence. We went down to another training
camp, and beat up on a good team like Jacksonville (in a pair of
Saturday scrimmages). We're beat up, but it was pretty obvious.
That's an 'A-line,' and people say they got a chance to win the
Super Bowl, but we banged them up and that's a fact. You can say
what you want, and in a game situation things (ITAL might (END ITAL
be different, but that was a good confidence-booster for a lot of
guys.'' _ Defensive end Chuck Smith, when asked to explain the
general good mood players seemed to be in Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   Falcons video director Tom Atcheson and his crew usually
generate about 80 tapes per practice. Many of these are copies, as
every coach gets a copy of nearly every drill. At every practice,
there are cameras on two mobile, three-story towers, and a
hand-held unit used for placekicking. Each drill is on a seperate
tape, and most of the tapes are re-used a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   What about next year?
</P>
<P>
   Coaches from Middle Georgia College, which is among parties
interested in playing host to Falcons training camp next year if
construction in Suwanee mandates a move, were at practice. The
group included head coach/athletics director Randy Pippin, whose
proposal is in the Falcons' hands of Falcons. Furman officials, who
also are interested in having camp on their Greenville, S.C.
campus, may attend a practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams
</P>
<P>
   The first kickoff team worked half-speed on staying in lanes.
That unit, from left to right, was CB Michael Booker, CB Lenny
McGill, LB Craig Sauer, S Chris Bayne, CB Juran Bolden, RB Gary
Downs, LB Ben Talley, LB Eddie Sutter, S Devin Bush, and FB Bob
Christian. Later, kicker Morten Andersen hit two onsides kicks,
each bouncing more than 30 feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
