<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOUBLE-LIVES-DRAG-ART     08-03 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUBLE-LIVES-DRAG-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE LIVES: PINSTRIPES BY DAY, SEQUINS BY NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scene I: Late afternoon, offices of a large Manhattan law firm.
Stanley Bojarski, a tall, animated man, hunches over a computer
terminal. He wears a gray pinstripe suit, retro-ish geometric tie,
black tasseled loafers. At his right elbow is a stack of papers,
legal briefs or depositions, which he periodically leafs through.
</P>
<P>
   Scene II: Some hours later, a 199-seat West Side theater. A
mermaid in a blue wig and bosomy nude fishtailed body-mold cavorts
onstage, to crowd guffaws. It is ... Stanley Bojarski!
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Such is the bipolar life of Bojarski, legal assistant
by day, actor and comic female impersonator by night.
</P>
<P>
   By juggling a so-called survival job at the sedate midtown
offices of Dewey Ballantine with a prime role in the exuberantly
gay-themed musical revue ``Howard Crabtree's When Pigs Fly'' on
West 42nd Street, Bojarski is doing what actors have long done to
eat and pay the rent. There are countless Stanley Bojarskis off and
on Broadway waiting tables, modeling, driving taxicabs, painting
apartments and spraying cologne on shoppers in Bloomingdale's.
</P>
<P>
   Few, however, have their feet planted in two such contrasting
worlds. T.S. Eliot was a bank clerk. Wallace Stevens and Charles
Ives sold insurance. But they, so far as is known, did not perform
in drag after dark.
</P>
<P>
   Bojarski, 48, spends his days sorting through lawsuit papers of
Ciba-Geigy vs. Liberty Mutual Insurance Co., and his nights vamping
onstage in dresses, high heels and outlandish costumes.
</P>
<P>
   The campy roles were created for him by Crabtree, an acclaimed
designer who died of AIDS in 1996, shortly after finishing work on
the hit show, now winding up a near-record two-year run.
</P>
<P>
   (The title of the revue is taken from a school counselor's dire
prediction that young Howard would make something of himself ``when
pigs fly.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Gemini _ it's a perfect situation,'' Bojarski said the
other day in a running interview that began in his cubicle at work
and wound up in front of a makeup mirror in his cluttered backstage
dressing room at the Douglas Fairbanks Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Another cast member in ``When Pigs Fly,'' James Heatherly,
undergoes a similar daily transformation, from a business-suited
preparer of client presentations in the private banking division of
Republic National Bank to extravagantly costumed women, Cupid and a
smitten gay lover singing satiric torch songs to conservative icons
like House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Sen. Strom Thurmond and radio
commentator Rush Limbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my day job, this is my real job,'' said Heatherly,
sitting in the darkened theater before his nightly metamorphosis.
``This is what I care about, this is what my passion is.'' He said
his bosses at the bank were culture-minded and understanding of his
complicated schedule, allowing him now, for example, to take some
time off for the final weeks of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Some jobs that actors juggle are more of a stretch than others.
Terry Richmond, who performs in the ensemble of ``The Scarlet
Pimpernel'' on Broadway, holds yoga classes for her fellow actors
at $5 a session. Another cast member, Bill Bowers, teaches
pantomime to colleagues and children with physical and learning
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Liz McConahay, on leave from the cabaret revue ``Secrets Every
Smart Traveler Should Know,'' is a dog walker.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Garner, an aspiring actor from Kansas who performs
stand-up in drag at ``The Web,'' a gay cabaret in midtown, is an
assistant publicist promoting shows for the theatrical publicity
agency Boneau/Bryan-Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most encyclopedic inventory of an actor's survival
jobs was provided by Claudia Shear in her 1994 one-woman Off
Broadway show ``Blown Sideways Through Life,'' which chronicled the
64 jobs that took her from an artist's modeling studio to Bear
Stearns to the telephone reception desk of an East Side brothel.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Bojarski fell into his law firm job between stage roles. Growing
up in Fonda, N.Y., west of Albany, where his parents owned a
restaurant, he acted in amateur productions and majored in
literature at Marist College in Poughkeepsie. He performed in
musicals in dinner theaters and summer stock, toured with road
companies of ``Annie'' and ``Me and My Girl'' and played in ``West
Side Story'' in Berlin. He also had a prime role in Crabtree's
earlier show, ``Whoop-Dee-Doo!''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, looking for steady work between parts, he applied to a
temporary employment agency, Career Blazers. He was placed at Dewey
Ballantine on a team of legal assistants helping prepare for the
civil trial of a lawsuit brought by the firm's client, Ciba-Geigy,
against its insurance company, Liberty Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree, meanwhile, was writing prime parts for Bojarski into
his new musical ``When Pigs Fly.'' The show opened in August 1996,
with Bojarski playing multiple roles, among them the Queen of
Diamonds; a sailor-suited, dippy suburban arts presenter, Carol Ann
Knippel of the Melody Barn (pronounced ``Bern''); a garden supplier
(one of the jobs the school counselor suggested for Crabtree) with
the sassiness of a streetwalker and a grotesquely bewigged
18th-century courtesan whose gown is her entire vanity table.
</P>
<P>
   But Bojarski had one condition. ``I was not going to jeopardize
my day job,'' he said. ``It's nice when you're 22, you can call
Mommy and Daddy. Not when you're in your 40s.'' Accordingly, the
show schedule took his law firm routine into account.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical recent weekday, Bojarski worked on his legal papers
at his desk until just after 5:30 p.m. Then, with a cheerful
``g'night'' to his co-workers, answered by a chorus of ``good
night, Stanley,'' he clicked off his computer and headed out.
</P>
<P>
   He passed his project manager, Douglas Briggs, who praised
Bojarski's work and said his unusual schedule ``probably keeps him
happy in some strange way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oooh,'' said Bojarski, beaming, ``I'm asking for a raise
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his associates at Dewey Ballantine have been to the
show, which is closing on Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Walking toward the theater, he said he could feel the burdens of
his law work dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk out that door and that all gets shed away,'' he said.
``You can't take it with you.''
</P>
<P>
   En route, he stopped at a deli. ``I get something to eat for
after my nap,'' he said, adding, ``Ugh, it sounds so pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   He emerged with a small bag. ``Tonight's chicken, tomorrow's
pizza,'' he said. ``You got to vary it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the theater he went backstage, took off his suit, changed
into a black robe and sequestered himself for an hour's restorative
nap. When he got up, he ate his chicken sandwich and began applying
his makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Heatherly, meanwhile, had arrived from his job. A former boy
soprano from Tennessee, he grew up around the country following the
postings of his father, a Secret Service agent. He came to New York
at 25 in 1991, with a degree in musical theater from West Texas
State University in Canyon. That qualified him to be a proofreader
in a publishing house, manager of a restaurant at the Bridgehampton
Tennis and Surf Club, telephone receptionist for a construction
company and now a banker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good about letting me take time off,'' he said. ``They
hired me knowing I had a life on the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Garner, 21, the actor who works days as a theatrical publicist,
has found a creative way to stretch his dollars. By traveling from
his apartment in Brooklyn to his engagements in drag, he said, he
is sometimes not charged by taxi drivers. ``They think they're
taking a beautiful blonde,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bojarski said actors were often compelled to dwell in two
separate worlds. ``I live two lives,'' he said. But he has no doubt
where he belonged, he said. ``The real me is what you see
onstage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
