<HEADER>
A6061 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PORN-SHOPS-ART-600     08-03 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PORN-SHOPS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY SEX INDUSTRY STRAINS TO COMPLY WITH NEW LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By DAN BARRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The bang of hammers and the buzz of power drills
muffled the come-hither cooing of the women working at Show World
on Monday, as the flagship for New York City's sex industry
frantically sought to strike a balance of compliance under a city
government no longer tolerant of its brand of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Miniature Statues of Liberty, not rubber sex toys and leather
handcuffs, now fill the ground-floor display cases, while the Big
Top Theater upstairs offers old movies, not nude entertainment.
Such recent changes were enough to convince a Supreme Court judge
Monday to block, at least for a few days, the city's plan to
padlock the sex emporium.
</P>
<P>
   The on-going renovations do not reflect any Saul-like conversion
by Show World's owner, Richard Basciano, a reclusive businessman
who lives in an apartment above his empire of sexual illusion, on
the corner of 42nd Street and Eighth Avenue. Instead, they are
Basciano's way of complying with a new zoning law that prohibits
establishments in restricted areas from having more than 40 percent
of their inventories dedicated to sex.
</P>
<P>
   Now at Show World, customers can buy a New York Police
Department souvenir T-shirt, watch a pornographic video in a
peep-show booth, catch the Cary Grant film playing upstairs, shoot
some pool, then spend $15 and more to peer through Plexiglas to
watch a woman remove all her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Judge Stephen Crane cited these changes
Monday in denying the city's motion to close Show World, saying
that the renovations had sufficiently complicated the matter of its
compliance to require another hearing, scheduled for Thursday.
Judge Crane also declined to permit the closing of three other
Manhattan businesses and reserved judgment on a fourth, but allowed
the city to shut down the Harmony Theater in lower Manhattan last
night.
</P>
<P>
   After the court hearing, Herald Price Fahringer, the attorney
representing businesses, expressed confidence that Show World would
remain open, saying that only 33 percent of its floor space is set
aside for the sex business. But Steven Fishner, Giuliani's criminal
justice coordinator, disagreed; he predicted the city would
demonstrate that Show World is a threat to the public welfare that
needs to be padlocked immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The city argues that Show World is within 500 feet of both a
school and the Roman Catholic Church of the Holy Cross, and
therefore is in violation of a new zoning law that prohibits sex
shops from operating near places of worship, residences, schools,
day-care centers and each other. During Monday's court hearing, the
city's lawyers introduced the affidavits of inspectors to support
their argument that Show World continues to violate the law,
renovations notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Those affidavits reflect the change in what is considered
acceptable behavior during the tenure of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, as
well as the city's determination to shut down establishments like
Show World through vigorous enforcement of the new law. During one
week in late July, five inspectors paid a total of six visits to
Show World.
</P>
<P>
   One inspector, Raymond Dowd, visited Show World on two
consecutive nights, dropping tokens in 10 different video booths.
In his affidavit he employed the exact language of the zoning law
to report having seen ``specified sexual activities'' and the
exposure of ``specified anatomical areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Another inspector, Srigiajaharan Chellah, bought $3 worth of
tokens at Show World. He visited the peep-show booths and watched
eight pornographic videos, each one lasting a minute, each one
costing a quarter. He then went into the lounge and, his affidavit
said, watched ``one (1) female performer on the stage, dressed in a
bikini suit, and dancing to pre-recorded music.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors estimated that as much as 90 percent of Show
World's floor space was dedicated to adult entertainment, although
these estimates were based on measurements by eye, not by tape.
None reported seeing live nudity.
</P>
<P>
   The experiences of these inspectors were markedly different from
those who ventured into the Harmony Theatre, an establishment at
279 Church St. Those city employees reported seeing mutual groping
between naked women and male customers; one inspector said, simply:
``I observed one female who appeared to be having sexual
intercourse with one of the male patrons.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports like these offended Tom Simmons, the property manager
for the Show World Organization. ``To have Show World lumped
together with some of these other establishments is,'' he said,
struggling for a moment to find the appropriate word, ``really
insulting.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Such sentiments arise from a prevalent attitude at Show World
that it is somehow superior to other peep shows and sex shops. For
a quarter-century it has stood like a gaudy fortress across from
the Port Authority, withstanding occasional attacks from community
groups, thwarting city inspectors with diligent health code
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Basciano, who is believed to be in his early 70s, used to have
several partners, including one man, Robert DiBernardo, who was
murdered by the Mafia several years ago for offending John Gotti.
Now he operates alone, employees say, aware of the great value of
his real estate, but determined to fight Giuliani in the name of
the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   `` Basciano's concerns here are over the consitutional rights
that he fought for in both theaters of World War II,'' Simmons
said. ``How far are they going to take this law? Is the Shubert
Theatre next, with `Chicago?'''
</P>
<P>
   But the sex industry's fight over the legality of the city's new
zoning law has been all but lost. After three years of court
arguments and appeals, the industry's dim hopes now rest with the
U.S. Supreme Court, which is unlikely to overturn the law. In the
meantime, Basciano has decided to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   He has preserved the curious circus motif that includes clown
heads and merry-go-round horses, as well as the stairwell that
includes a different flashing sign on each step: ``private
booths''; ``nude dancing;'' ``safe and clean.'' But gone are the
barkers who once stood at the theater's portals, urging passersby
to check out the show; the posters of scantily dressed women; the
advertisement depicting a man with tophat and cane and announcing
that couples were welcome.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOSTERCARE-PLIGHT-NYT     08-03 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTERCARE-PLIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE YEARS AFTER SISTER'S DEATH, SIBLINGS LANGUISH IN FOSTER
CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The five children watched helplessly as their parents
forced their sister, Elisa Izquierdo, to drink ammonia and eat her
own feces. They looked on as their parents sexually assaulted her
and beat her until the white bones gleamed through her brown
fingers. The children survived the violence that killed Elisa, but
they landed in foster care with shattered lives and damaged
psyches.
</P>
<P>
   Child welfare officials, who investigated 6-year-old Elisa's
death in November 1995, suggested that the city sever ties between
the abusive parents and their surviving children, and have the
children adopted so they could begin to recover from the severe
psychological trauma in stable, nurturing homes.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly three years after Elisa's death, her mother,
imprisoned for the killing, still retains the legal rights to her
five surviving children, who are 5 to 13 years old. Four of the
five siblings have bounced through more than four foster homes as
city officials have fallen months behind their own timetable in
setting the children on the road to adoption.
</P>
<P>
   In death, Elisa Izquierdo became a national symbol of all that
was wrong with child welfare in New York City, exposing the sloppy
investigations that allowed her to suffer and die while under the
city's watch. And in some ways, her siblings' long journey through
the child welfare system highlights a less sensational but far more
common problem: the experience of thousands of children who
languish in foster care for years without finding permanent homes.
</P>
<P>
   While the median stay in foster care has declined from four
years to three years since 1996, which both city officials and
advocates for children say is still too long for many children to
wait for stability. The city wants to reduce it even further, to
below 2.4 years.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Elisa's siblings also reflects the legal and
bureaucratic barriers that often prevent child welfare officials
from quickly severing the bonds between parents and their children,
even when a parent has killed a child.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, officials had to wait 12 months before starting
the court process to terminate the parental rights of Awilda Lopez,
Elisa's mother, and Carlos Lopez, her stepfather. Laws protecting
the rights of parents are so strong that the waiting period was
necessary even though Ms. Lopez had pleaded guilty to murder and
Mr. Lopez was serving a sentence for attempted assault.
</P>
<P>
   After that, child welfare officials had to prove to a judge that
the couple had also abused the surviving children, in a trial that
took several months. Even after a formal finding of abuse was
granted, it took 11 months for the city's office of Family Court
Mental Health Services to complete the psychological evaluations
needed to prove the children should never be returned to the
Lopezes, child welfare officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, finding foster parents capable of coping with the
psychologically damaged children was difficult. Less than 10
percent of all child welfare cases involve abuse, and many foster
parents were unprepared for Elisa's siblings, who had been exposed
to such extraordinary violence.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed by the needs of the traumatized siblings, some
foster parents simply gave up on the children, saying they could no
longer care for them, city officials familiar with the case said.
As a result, the four youngest children, who are still struggling
to erase the painful memories of the torture they witnessed, found
themselves forced to move over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only the three youngest siblings, who are 5, 6 and 7,
live together. The older children, 12 and 13, live in separate
homes, city officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the children say the obstacles to finding
permanent homes for children who have lived through extreme abuse
are so great that they do not blame child welfare officials for the
lack of stability in the siblings' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were any other case, I would be arguing that the
system was working too slowly,'' said Ronald E. Richter, the deputy
director of the Manhattan office of Legal Aid's Juvenile Rights
Division, which represents the siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't believe that the system has failed these
children,'' said Mr. Richter, who declined to discuss the details
of the case or the lives of the children he represents. ``I believe
the system has responded as well as it can to these children with
extraordinary needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Richter declined to describe the homes or the permanency
plans for the children, saying only that the siblings are safe and
happy in their current foster homes. But unfortunately, he said, in
the quest for stability, even explainable, understandable delays
often wreak havoc in children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Besharov, a child welfare specialist who investigated
Elisa's death as a member of the city's child fatality panel and
pushed for her siblings' adoption, said he fears that their
unstable lives in foster care may ultimately have a devastating
impact on their psychological and social development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of permanency is the biggest threat to the welfare
and the safety of foster children,'' Mr. Besharov said. ``Temporary
and haphazard placements hurt children. Their emotional and
physical situations deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective ought to be to halt the emotional and physical
deterioration of abused and neglected children,'' he said. ``But
for too many children coming in contact with New York City's child
welfare system, the system doesn't arrest their downward spiral. It
sometimes accelerates it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
