<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NGA-HOLYFIELD-COX     08-03 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NGA-HOLYFIELD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield speaks to governors at convention
 &HT;    (EDS: This story will move on (a) national and (s) sports
categories.)
 &HT;    By Debra Jasper
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ You can't mentor troubled children without also
helping their parents because children always return home,
heavyweight boxing champion Evander Holyfield told a group of
governors Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success starts at home,'' Holyfield said. ``Everything starts
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, a three-time heavyweight champion and the youngest of
nine children, spoke about fatherhood to the National Governors'
Association Committee on Human Resources, where he and governors
spent the morning discussing how states can promote programs that
emphasize responsible fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   According to NGA figures, four out of 10 children in the United
States are not living in the same home as their biological father,
and nearly half of all children being raised in mother-headed
families are living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   During the committee meeting, governors outlined ways their
states are helping men learn parenting skills through mentoring
programs and other initiatives. Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson said
one of the most difficult hurdles such programs face is finding
mentors who will work with children long enough that children don't
feel abandoned when the mentor moves on.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, the father of eight children ages ``14 on down,''
said a program he backs in Atlanta encourages mentors to teach
children how to be independent and make the right choices for
themselves. Mentors must make it clear to children that they are
giving them information, and how they use that information is up to
them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield also said he would like to see fatherhood classes
taught in schools. ``They teach people how to get a job but not how
to raise a family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said too many children today grow up without fathers or male
role models to show them how to raise children properly. They also
aren't taught how to control their aggression, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he told a group of teen boys heading to prison who
thought he was ``real bad'' that he was actually good because he
only uses his aggression in a boxing ring. He said children don't
know how to deal with their aggression productively and respect
others because they simply aren't trained.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, he said, parents just aren't around. There are
plenty of kids today wearing ``a $150 pair of tennis shoes who are
still upset'' because their parents give them money but don't give
of themselves, Holyfield said. ``It's not the money that solves the
problems, it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Debra Jasper writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
