<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICASSO WORKS INSTALLED AT BIRTHPLACE IN MALAGA  
 LORIKEETS, MEERKATS AND KOALAS IN ST. LOUIS  
 VALET PARKING INTRODUCED AT KENNEDY  
 EUROPEAN LINKS TO U.S. ARE FOCUS OF NEW GUIDE  
 BLIMPS AND BALLOONS TO FILL OTTAWA SKIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Aug. 9) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The house in Malaga, Spain, where Pablo Picasso was born on Oct.
25, 1881, and lived for 17 months before his family moved next
door, reopened on June 22 as a small museum for Picasso's work. The
five-story building, which had been open to visitors from 1988 to
1996, has been transformed into the first of two Picasso museums
planned for Malaga, on Spain's southern Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
   The permanent collection of 200 Picasso artworks, mainly
engravings, was donated by his daughter-in-law, Christine Ruiz
Picasso. Currently on display are some 20 of Picasso's engravings
inspired by the sonnets of the Spanish writer Luis de Gongora y
Argote. The museum will also have rotating monthly exhibits, which
started with a loan of 30 of the artist's engravings from the 1930s
to the 1970s from the Reina Sofia National Art Center in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   The Pablo Ruiz Picasso Foundation, run by Malaga's city hall,
operates the museum. A library occupies the upper floors, with
thousands of Picasso-related books, press clippings and
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, at 15 Plaza de la Merced in the city's historic
quarter, (34-95) 221-5005, is open Monday to Saturday from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. and 6 to 9 p.m., and Sunday from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.,
through mid-September. The schedule then changes to 11 a.m. to 2
p.m. and 5 to 8 p.m. Monday to Saturday, and 11 a.m. to 2 p.m. on
Sunday. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   The second, larger museum, also in the city's historic district,
is expected to open next year, with a display of works donated by
Christine Ruiz Picasso and the artist's grandson Bernard Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   Lorikeets, Meerkats and Koalas in St. Louis
</P>
<P>
   Children's zoos have gone far beyond a few pens of sheep or
goats that will nibble food from kids' hands. The St. Louis Zoo,
for example, has recently redone its Children's Zoo to include a
slide that goes through a pool of otters, an aviary alive with
dozens of little parrots called lorikeets, and hourly shows like
``Pets and Consequences'' in a special amphitheater for live animal
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The Emerson Electric Children's Zoo, as the new
three-and-a-half-acre area is called, also has installations of
koalas; meerkats (like Timon from ``The Lion King''), which stand
on their hind legs to look around; and big-eared fennec foxes,
which run down crickets at snack time. In the Just Like Me area,
children can mimic animals by swinging like a monkey, climbing on a
web like a spider or digging like an aardvark.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the St. Louis Zoo, in Forest Park, (314) 781-0900,
is free; admission to the children's zoo is $3 a person (under 2
free), though it, too, is free for those who enter between 9 and 10
a.m. The zoo is open daily from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; to 9 p.m. on
Tuesday until Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Valet Parking Introduced at Kennedy
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Passengers driving to Kennedy International Airport
who are in a rush to make a flight and don't want to waste too much
time parking (and waiting for the van that invariably seems to stop
at every other terminal before theirs) now have an alternative:
valet parking.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey began
a service that allows motorists to get off at the Federal Circle
exit of the Van Wyck Expressway inside the airport, drop off their
cars and be driven in a 14-seat van that goes directly to the
passenger's terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority promises that customers should not have to
wait any longer than a few minutes for the van, which will include
free newspapers and bottled water. The passenger's car will be
parked in a lot accessible only to the valets. The cost is $18 a
day (compared with $7 a day in a long-term lot and $24 a day in a
daily lot). A similar service was introduced at Newark (N.J.)
Airport on July 1, and is eventually planned for La Guardia, too.
</P>
<P>
   Returning customers will call for pickup at the passenger
terminal, either at the ground-transportation desk or by using a
special telephone number, and will be taken back to the valet
parking area, where their cars will be waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The new service also offers a last chance at redemption for any
traveler who has forgotten to buy a gift for those left at home.
Customers who call at least six hours ahead can arrange to have
roses, a box of chocolates or other gifts _ including a teddy bear
_ waiting along with their vehicles. Information: (877) 535-8253.
</P>
<P>
   European Links to U.S. Are Focus of New Guide
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who want to trace their roots in England, France and
the Netherlands can find information in a 24-page booklet issued by
a new organization, Exporting Cultural Heritage Overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet, titled ``Europe's Best Kept Secret,'' offers
background and travel information about the cities of Bournemouth,
Poole, Portsmouth and Southampton in England, Cherbourg and Le
Havre in France and the province of Flevoland in the Netherlands,
places that hold interest for Americans because of their
connections to emigration beginning in the 17th century and, more
recently, the Normandy landing on D-Day in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet, sponsored by the European Regional Development Fund
of the European Union, is available free from the British Tourist
Authority at (800) 462-2748 or the Western France Tourist Board at
(202) 659-7779. More information is offered at
www.saturnus.nl/vvvf/go2europe.
</P>
<P>
   Blimps and Balloons to Fill Ottawa Skies
</P>
<P>
   A fleet of airships and hot-air balloons _ including a
150-foot-tall rabbit with a magician's hat _ will fill the skies
over Ottawa during the sixth World Hot Air Airship Championships
between Sept. 2 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen airships, each about 100 feet long and 45 feet high,
from the United States, Canada and 11 countries in Europe and Asia
will be competing in speed and navigational events for the first
time in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The championships were previously held in Italy, France,
Luxembourg and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The Gatineau Hot Air Balloon Festival, host of the competition,
stages its own annual event in La Baie Park in Gatineau, within a
10-minute drive of Ottawa. All the competitions will be held over
the 20-acre park.
</P>
<P>
   Oddities among the festival's 100 hot-air balloons from eight
countries include a Statue of Liberty, a Yellow Pages directory, an
eagle, a tiger and a cow. The Canadian government has three
entries: a constable on a horse, a maple leaf and a Canadian flag.
</P>
<P>
   The events are part of the Paris-based Aeroclub of France's
100th-anniversary celebration of the first manned flights in
France.
</P>
<P>
   Concerts, fairground rides and a fireworks display (Sept. 5) are
also scheduled. Hours are 6 a.m. to midnight Wednesday to Sunday,
until 11 p.m. on Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for six days bought before Aug. 28 are $15.75,
calculated at $1.45 Canadian to the U.S. dollar; daily passes sold
at the entrance are $10.25. Children under 4 feet are admitted
free.
</P>
<P>
   There will be food kiosks in the park, and wheelchair access to
restrooms. Visitors may also take one-hour balloon tours for $89.75
a passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (819) 243-2330.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
