<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6072 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIALS-AZREPUBLIC     08-03 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIALS-AZREPUBLIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA REPUBLIC EDITORIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONE BED, ONE LIFE: GOOD REASONS TO CHEER
</P>
<P>
   When the need is great the good people of the Phoenix area know
precisely what to do.
</P>
<P>
   They have opened their hearts to the victims of domestic
violence because it is a tragic subject that cannot help but touch
a heartstring.
</P>
<P>
   Women running from an abusive mate in the early morning hours,
clutching an infant and wondering if there is help, wondering if
there is a bed for a safe haven. Anything. Just to get away and out
of harm's way and to get help.
</P>
<P>
   It is a scene from hell.
</P>
<P>
   And it happens with an alarming frequency.
</P>
<P>
   But often out of view. The secrets of a particular family. Maybe
a neighborhood. Police blotter information that's not usually
disseminated.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the horrific death and tragedy of Laura Munoz
(EDITORS: There is a tilde over the `n' in MUNOZ) did the Phoenix
area take notice and begin to understand the crying need. Munoz, a
mother of six, was one of the unlucky ones, a stabbing victim who
had been repeatedly turned away from crowded domestic shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of beds is so dire that only about one in six can
be admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the outrage if hospitals had to turn so many away?
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix City Council took matters into its own hands and
authorized $1 million for the building of new shelter beds for
women fleeing from abusive situations. But there was a catch.
Shelters couldn't apply for the money unless they demonstrated an
ability to meet the match.
</P>
<P>
   That's where you came in. That's where you came through.
</P>
<P>
   In only two months, a fund-raising campaign has raised an
additional $1 million in the ``One Bed, One Life'' campaign,
sponsored by The Republic, Channel 12 (KPNX), KMLE-FM (107.9) and
Bank One.
</P>
<P>
   That means that $2 million can be put to incredibly good use.
The grants are expected to be given out by the city's Committee on
Domestic Violence in September.
</P>
<P>
   It also means that the odds of another tragedy like the one that
befell Laura Munoz might be lessened by a considerable margin.
</P>
<P>
   But the work is not done, and another important proposal has
been endorsed by the Phoenix committee headed by Councilwoman Peggy
Bilsten. The idea is to establish in Phoenix a ``one-stop-shop'' to
help victims of family violence, whether they are in need of
medical attention, police assistance, counseling or an order of
protection.
</P>
<P>
   This is a far more humane and efficient way to treat victims who
now must endure the pain of telling their stories several times in
many different locations.
</P>
<P>
   Bilsten's committee has suggested that $1.2 million would be
required to bring a comprehensive domestic violence center on line.
Donations of furniture, computers, phone lines and the like could
lower the cost.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good idea, another response to a problem that's out of
the closet. If the convenience of so many services under one roof
encourages just one adult to seek help, it will have served its
purpose. In September, the City Council should make another strong
statement against domestic violence and approve a family center. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLARENCE THOMAS' SPEECH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Justice Clarence Thomas spoke to 2,000 members of the National
Bar Association last week, and for a fleeting moment, the First
Amendment seemed a tiny bit more secure.
</P>
<P>
   An introspective, thoughtful speech by the nation's
highest-ranking black official to the nation's largest group of
black attorneys and judges may seem about as unusual as jam and
bread. But in fact, his appearance over the shrill objections of
NBA directors, including - incredibly - judges charged with
dispensing fair and impartial justice, represented a notable
victory for free speech regardless of race.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has been a lightning rod for controversy and vilification
in civil rights circles since he ascended to the high court in 1991
for one reason - he holds views out of sync with self-anointed
black leaders, a `betrayal'' of the conventional liberalism of his
predecessor, Thurgood Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   He explained his ``primary problem'' among black brethren `is
that I have no right to think the way I do because I'm Black.'' But
his views, he added, are ``not necessarily illegitimate if held by
non-Blacks. They are exempt from this kind of criticism because
they are not Black.''
</P>
<P>
   An exaggeration? Imagine demonstrators picketing Justice Sandra
O'Connor because her views aren't `White'' enough. Or Black leaders
objecting to her views on affirmative action. They don't; she's
exempt.
</P>
<P>
   It's only Thomas who is so honored. He must be made to toe the
line.
</P>
<P>
   But it is precisely this demagogic groupthink notion that all
members of a racial minority must be of one mind which, in Black
economist and writer Thomas Sowell's words, has `already poisoned
race relations and misdirected a whole generation of young
Blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in this context that Justice Thomas' assertion of the
right to `think for myself,'' and to ``refuse to have my views
assigned to me...because I'm black'' represents a triumph of free
speech, and a threat to the hegemony so many civil rights leaders
seek over their followers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it also signifies a moderation of the thought
regimentation among that leadership remains to be seen. It was not
a hopeful sign that as soon as Thomas finished speaking, the
lawyers put on a special seminar to dump on those views whose
independence scares them so. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
