A6073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-ECON-550&AMP;ADD     08-03 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-ECON-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS FALL AS HONG KONG'S ECONOMIC SLUMP WORSENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The stock market fell sharply here on Monday, as two
new reports laid bare the depths of the Asian financial crisis and
its impact on this former British colony.
</P>
<P>
   First, Hong Kong's government reported that the economy shrank
2.8 percent in the first quarter of 1998. The contraction was even
sharper than the provisional figure of 2 percent the government
released in June. And it confirmed that Hong Kong is headed into
its deepest recession since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corp., the leading bank
here, announced that earnings fell 41 percent, to $791.16 million,
in the first half of 1998 because of a huge charge taken to protect
it from bad loans. HSBC Holdings PLC, the bank's London-based
parent, said it took a $1.14-billion charge _ a jump of $889
million over a charge in the first half of 1997. As a result, HSBC
said net profit for the first half fell 16 percent to $2.402
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The provision for bad loans is one yardstick of how severe HSBC
believes the financial crisis will be. Analysts said its size
indicated that the bank expected many Asian companies to tumble
into financial hardship as the crisis wears on _ with a good number
defaulting on their loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the market has to realize is that this is not the end,
but the beginning,'' said Roy Ramos, a banking analyst with
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. in Hong Kong. ``There will have to be more
provisions for bad loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Although HSBC and the government made their announcements after
the stock market here closed, investors had anticipated the bad
news. The benchmark Hang Seng index of 33 leading issues fell
383.43 points, or 4.8 percent, to 7,552.77, worsening a market
decline just over 8 percent in the two preceding weeks. HSBC, which
accounts for about one-third of the weighted index, also slid
nearly 5 percent Monday, to $179(Hong Kong), or $23.25(U.S.) a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said on Monday that Hong Kong's economic
performance in the first quarter was worse than first thought
because declines in consumer spending and in tourism revenue were
steeper than expected. K.Y. Tang, a government economist, said the
rapid onset of the financial crisis had made it all but impossible
to accurately forecast economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Tang acknowledged that _ with the latest trade and retail
sales figures showing continued declines _ he expected the second
quarter to be ``somewhat worse'' than the first. Private economists
said Hong Kong's output would probably decline 3 percent in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only bright spot I can see is the normal seasonal pickup
in trade in the fourth quarter,'' said Ian Perkin, chief economist
of the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce. ``But then we get
into the problem of what happens in the first and second quarter of
1999.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like many economists, Perkin said he worried that Hong Kong and
other Asian economies faced several years of recession. Hong Kong's
economy has been sapped by all the usual symptoms of the Asian
economic ailment _ like an erosion of exports to its neighbors and
a loss of consumer confidence _ and a few symptoms unique to this
city. The trouble-prone opening of the Hong Kong airport disrupted
cargo shipments, costing several hundred million dollars in
exports.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Perkin estimated that Hong Kong's gross domestic
product would decline by 2 percent this year _ its first full year
of contraction since the territory began keeping records in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Hongkong and Shanghai Bank is taking a similarly bleak view. It
said it could not predict when Hong Kong or other markets would
claw themselves out of their current trough. Executives at HSBC
said the bulk of the $1.14 billion in bad-loan provisions was
intended for loans to companies in Indonesia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos noted, though, that the bank still needed to deal with
loans to companies here and in South Korea, Malaysia and China.
``We take a very strong premise that it is going to get worse in
all these markets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, HSBC's nonperforming loans account for only 1.7
percent of all its loans in Hong Kong, and 6.9 percent of loans in
the rest of Asia. But Ramos said he expected that the ratio of
nonperforming loans could easily double in Hong Kong, and in some
Asian markets _ like Thailand _ it could rise to as much as 30
percent of the bank's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, we've been taken aback by how severely economies
in Asia have contracted,'' Ramos said. ``And we've been taken aback
by how high the ratio of nonperforming loans has risen.''
</P>
<P>
   HSBC executives noted, somewhat plaintively, that their
underlying business was performing well. The bank's operating
earnings before the bad-loan provision increased 13 percent, to
$4.76 billion, in the first half. And HSBC's British and U.S.
operations both had solid profit gains.
</P>
<P>
   But the bankers found it hard to accentuate the positive.
Addressing a news conference in the bank's architecturally striking
Hong Kong headquarters, John Bond, the group chairman of HSBC
Holdings, said of the Asian crisis, ``I think the speed and
severity has caught everybody by surprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
