<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA MILITARY EXAMINES SUHARTO-ERA ABUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia's military began an investigation
Monday into the kidnapping and torture of political opponents under
Suharto, the former president, and the possible involvement of his
son-in-law and other members of the military.
</P>
<P>
   The Armed Forces chief, Gen. Wiranto, said that Lt. Gen. Prabowo
Subianto, Suharto's son-in-law, and two other officers connected to
the military's Special Forces unit would be called before a special
military council while 10 others below the rank of colonel would
face court-martial charges.
</P>
<P>
   The military is attempting to improve its image following local
and international pressure to find 14 political opponents of
Suharto who are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto said the council had been formed ``to put an end to the
case of the missing persons'' but that punishment would be meted
out according to military procedure behind closed doors. The
maximum penalty is dishonorable discharge.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian public's perception of the military has fallen to
its lowest point in years after reports of the military's
involvement in kidnapping Suharto's opponents and shooting four
university students last May and accusations that it may have been
behind rioting that claimed nearly 1,200 lives the same month.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the National Commission on Human Rights said the
military was taking the right steps by forming the review body but
called for the results to be open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0405 </DOCNO>
