<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6082 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV09-NYT     08-03 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Aug. 9)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Rembrandt, by Rembrandt &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have heard that there will be an exhibit of Rembrandt's
self-portraits next year, both at the National Gallery in London
and the Maurits-huis in The Hague. Do you know the dates? _ Jim
Graham, Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   A. Rembrandt wrote his autobiography with a paintbrush, creating
60 self-portraits _ the first at age 20 or 21, the last at 63,
shortly before his death in 1669. The paintings, drawings and
etchings help trace his stylistic development, from youthful
self-confidence to the searching portraits of old age.
</P>
<P>
   Rembrandt painted himself in many roles: as artist, in
extravagant dress, as the Apostle Paul and at the feet of Christ
during the raising of the Cross. This exhibit, which will first be
shown in London before moving to The Hague, will study the
significance of these varying depictions as well as the facial
expressions the artist chose. It will include numerous paintings
and about 30 of his etchings and drawings. In addition, a small
selection of works by Rembrandt's students will show how their
self-portraits were influenced by their teacher. The works will be
on loan from the Netherlands, Britain, Germany, France, Italy, the
United States and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The show is first scheduled to run at the National Gallery on
Trafalgar Square in London from June 9 through Sept. 5, 1999. Early
plans are for 40 paintings and 35 etchings and drawings by
Rembrandt to be on display. There will be an admission charge to
the exhibition (the permanent collections are free), to be called
``Rembrandt by Himself,'' but it has not been set yet. Information:
(44-171) 747-2885.
</P>
<P>
   The Mauritshuis, 8 Korte Vijverberg, The Hague, has chosen the
simpler name ``Rembrandt Himself'' for the show, to run from Sept.
25, 1999, to Jan. 9, 2000. This exhibition will feature 25
paintings, fewer than the number at the National Gallery. Tickets
for the Mauritshuis show will be available beginning June 1, 1999,
and will be sold for specific entry times. Visitors will have a
one-hour window in which to arrive and will be able to stay as long
as they wish. For information, call (31-70) 302-3456.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buenos Aires Hotels  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I will be staying in Buenos Aires in November.
We saw that one major American chain hotel costs $390 a night. Can
you suggest something more moderate? _ Mary Jane Baker, Portland,
Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A. Here are three possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Plaza Francia, 2189 Schiaffino, telephone and fax
(54-1) 804-9631, has 50 smallish but cozy rooms in the elegant
Recoleta district. Nearby are trendy shopping centers, outdoor
cafes and major museums. Rooms at the front of the hotel offer
views of the pretty tree-lined streets below. A double room is
$152.46 to $175.45, including tax and Continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooking the Libertad Plaza and two blocks from the Teatro
Colon is the Hotel Bisonte, 1207 Paraguay St., (54-1) 816-5770, fax
(54-1) 816-5775. The 87 rooms are not overly elegant, but they are
comfortable and are particular favorites for business travelers,
with their computer ports and 24-hour room service. A double is
$169.40, with tax and buffet breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to go higher on the amenity (and price) scale, the
Hotel Claridge, 535 Tucuman Street, (54-1) 314-7700, fax (54-1)
314-8022, is a traditional English-style hotel in the middle of the
financial district. The 161 rooms are large and well--appointed,
and there is an outdoor pool. The Claridge Grill is one of the
city's better-known restaurants. Doubles: $290, with tax but no
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Airport Parking &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently left my car in the Kennedy Airport long-term lot
for a week. The cost was reasonable, but after leaving the lot, I
noticed that my license plate number was on my credit-card receipt.
How is this done and why? _ Leonard A. O'Connor, Watertown, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. How your license-plate number gets on your receipt is fairly
simple _ the cashier in the booth can see it thanks to a mirror
(it's also recorded by a video camera) and enters it in the
register. But the background is a little more complex.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cahill, a spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey, the agency that operates La Guardia, Kennedy and Newark
airports, said that in 1991 the authority installed a computerized
revenue-control system for the daily and long-term lots at each
airport. One problem at these lots in the 1980's was car theft, but
the new system has helped reduce that. Each night, an employee with
a hand-held computer records the license plate number and location
of each car parked in these lots. Besides helping to reduce auto
theft, it also helps the authority to find out where travelers like
to park and for how long, data that can be used to improve customer
service. If a customer has a complaint about a cashier, that
employee can be identified. And if you come home from your trip
with so many great memories that you forgot where you parked your
car, the computer can find it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill also said that by the end of the year, the Port Authority
planned to have at least one lot at each of the three airports that
accepted payment with EZ Pass, the system now used at the
authority's bridges and tunnels to automatically record toll
charges for drivers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nevis Runway &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I really enjoy the island of Nevis in the Caribbean, but it
takes the better part of a day to get there since I must first fly
to San Juan, then to St. Kitts, then switch planes for Nevis. The
runway at the island's airport is being lengthened. How soon can I
expect direct flights from, say, San Juan? _ John Wellenbach,
Narberth, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. The runway, which is being extended to 4,000 feet to
accommodate larger jets, was originally scheduled to be completed
this month, said Christine Walwyn of the St. Kitts and Nevis
Department of Tourism, but the target is now early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, neither American Airlines nor its subsidiary,
American Eagle, plans to provide more direct service to Nevis after
the project is completed. ``It wouldn't make economic sense for
either one of the airlines to do it at this time,'' said Mitch
Baranowski, an American Airlines spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   So for now, you will just have to keep taking those 10-minute
flights from St. Kitts (there's also a 45-minute ferry trip
instead), or try the longer flights from Anguilla, Antigua, St.
Barts, St. Croix and St. Maarten.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
