<HEADER>
A6083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAID-WORKRULES-NY     08-03 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-WORKRULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO EXPAND MEDICAID FOR SOME OF THE WORKING POOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET EMBARGO for
electronic media.) 
(JT) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday will announce new
policies making it easier for states to provide Medicaid to adults
in two-parent families who work at low-wage jobs for more than 100
hours a month.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the changes would help 135,000 to
200,000 people in 20 states. Thirty states had already received
permission from the federal government to dispense with the
100-hour-a-month rule.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will make the changes by regulation, having concluded
that he does not need to ask Congress to change the laws governing
Medicaid and welfare, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The old rules, in effect, penalized work effort, cutting off
Medicaid to adults in many low-income families who worked more than
100 hours a month.
</P>
<P>
   The rules also penalized marriage, cutting off Medicaid for many
single mothers who married, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, to be issued this week, states may
eliminate the 100-hour limit if they wish, or they could set a
higher limit. And states will have a financial incentive to do so,
because the federal government pays 50 percent to 77 percent of
Medicaid benefits. The federal share is larger in states with low
per capita incomes.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to be delivered on Tuesday, Clinton describes the
100-hour limit as ``the last vestige of the old welfare system.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps ``no aspect of the welfare system did more to defy
common sense and insult our values than the so-called 100-hour
rule,'' Clinton plans to says. ``Instead of rewarding work, it took
away health care from people who secured a full-time job.''
</P>
<P>
   In conclusion, Clinton says, ``the 100-hour rule was wrong, and
now it's history.''
</P>
<P>
   The president will announce the changes at a White House event
reviewing what has happened to low-income families since he signed
legislation revamping the welfare system on Aug. 22, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent data, for March of this year, show 8.9 million
people on welfare. The number has declined by 37 percent since
Clinton took office in January 1993 and by 27 percent since he
signed the welfare bill in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Jocelyn Guyer, a policy analyst at the Center on Budget and
Policy Priorities, a research and advocacy group, described the new
rules as ``a wonderful policy change'' that could help many people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If states take advantage of this new option,'' Ms. Guyer said,
``low-income parents can increase the number of hours they work
without fear of losing Medicaid coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Baxendell, a health policy analyst at the National
Governors' Association, said state officials would also welcome the
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the new rules give states an option for more flexibility,
that's something we would support,'' Ms. Baxendell said. ``Some
states could view this as a nice complement to efforts to help
parents move from public assistance to work while keeping their
health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of all working poor parents have no health
insurance. Typically, their jobs do not offer health benefits, and
low-wage workers often cannot afford to take advantage of the
coverage if it is offered to them. Moreover, while many states have
expanded Medicaid to cover the children of low-income families in
recent years, the parents are often ineligible for Medicaid and
other public health insurance programs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old welfare system, people who received cash
assistance were automatically eligible for Medicaid. But, Ms. Guyer
said, as parents move off welfare into low-wage jobs, they
frequently lose their health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In 20 states including New York and New Jersey, an adult in a
two-parent family can ordinarily qualify for Medicaid only if the
principal wage-earner in the family works fewer than 100 hours a
month, federal officials said. This restriction prevents states
from expanding Medicaid to two-parent families in which the
principal wage-earner works 100 hours a month or more.
</P>
<P>
   The other 30 states had received waivers under the old welfare
law allowing them to eliminate the 100-hour rule.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Department of Health and Human Services said
the 100-hour limit was added to federal welfare regulations in
1971, and it restricted Medicaid eligibility as well because the
two programs were closely linked.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 welfare law gave states new freedom to set eligibility
rules for cash assistance, but it froze in place most of the
Medicaid eligibility rules that prevailed in July 1996. States
could liberalize eligibility for welfare, but not for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   One result, officials said, was a disincentive for poor people
to work. They could keep Medicaid coverage if they worked 90 hours
a month, but, in many states, they would lose Medicaid if they
worked 110 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In most states, healthy adults of working age are eligible for
Medicaid only if they have children. While Congress and the states
have established more generous criteria for children and pregnant
women, the income limit for parents seeking Medicaid is generally
far below the official poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
