<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6086 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-COX     08-03 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gramm joins call for speeding farm aid
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Sen. Phil Gramm Monday joined the chorus
of national leaders calling for help for farmers and ranchers
hurting from the drought that is killing crops and parching
pastures from the Gulf Coast to the Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, a Republican member of the Senate Agriculture Committee,
urged the U.S. Department of Agriculture to speed up applications
for emergency loans from farmers and ranchers who face severe
losses because of the drought.
</P>
<P>
   The low-interest loans were triggered last month when
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman declared that the entire state
is an agricultural disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, President Clinton issued a statement acknowledging
that while the nation's capital can't make it rain, it can help
farmers and ranchers who are hurting ``through no fault of their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   In separate trips to Texas last month, Glickman and Deputy
Secretary of Agriculture Richard Rominger visited farms and ranches
for a first-hand look at the effects of the severe dry spell.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm was scheduled late Monday to visit a drought-damaged
pasture in Brazos County after meeting with state agriculture
officials at Texas A&AMP;M University. He complained that it can take
up to 18 months for agricultural producers to receive money from
disaster loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems plain that requiring farmers and ranchers to wait a
year and a half to accommodate the processing of paperwork will
pile a policy disaster on top of a natural disaster,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   In urging the USDA to assign more employees to local Farm
Service Agency offices to handle the expected crush of disaster
applications, Gramm echoed a plea made in July by Texas Agriculture
Commissioner Rick Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to help pay essential living expenses or to refinance
existing loans, the ``last-resort'' government loans carry an
interest rate of 3.75 percent. To be eligible, farmers and ranchers
must have suffered at least a 30 percent loss in normal revenues
and have been turned down by two private lenders.
</P>
<P>
   After the drought of 1996, 306 Texas producers received disaster
loans totaling $17.8 million, for an average of $58,000, according
to the Farm Service Agency, which administers the program.
</P>
<P>
   While that's a relatively small number, agriculture experts say
most farmers are able to get help from banks where they have
borrowed money for many years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, about 110 of 254 counties were eligible for the
disaster loans.
</P>
<P>
   Separately from drought aid, Congress, responding to a severe
drop in farm income, sent President Clinton a bill Monday to
accelerate $5.5 billion in payments already due farmers in the year
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, farmers who had been receiving subsidies
prior to the 1996 ``Freedom to Farm'' law would get transition
payments in two installments next year. The payments, which are
gradually declining and would end in 2002, are intended to wean
farmers off the old subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, given voice vote approval in the House on Monday and
the Senate last Thursday, would let those farmers receive all or
part of their transition payment Oct. 1, the first day of the new
federal fiscal year. President Clinton has indicated he will sign
it.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
