<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-1STLD-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Repeating; moves CLINTON-STARR to lede; adds reefers.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, Aug. 4.The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927; e-mail,
patryan(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Taking a defiant stance toward
prosecutors and political critics, White House officials say that
President Clinton would continue to maintain that he had no sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky and would appeal a court decision
ordering a top aide to testify in the case. By James Bennet. (We
plan to move the story by 9:45 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center:
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ Republicans join Democrats in
endorsing a campaign finance bill. (We plan to move the story by
9:15 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) The story runs next to a 3-column
photo. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead stories:
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-FIGHTING (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ Rebellious troops seize
control of a series of border cities in eastern Congo, and fight
overnight gun battles against government forces in the capital,
Kinshasa, in the most serious uprising against the country's
president, Laurent Kabila. By Howard W. French. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
