<SLUG> BC-GOVERNORS-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CRISIS SETS TONE OF GOVERNORS' MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., S.C., Mich., Nev., Colo.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ When the 90th annual meeting of the National
Governors' Association convened here on Saturday, its leaders
hailed the gathering as ``an exceptional opportunity to spotlight
what unites America and propels us into the 21st century.'' But
what has been spotlighted instead is rapidly growing worry among
top Democrats and rapidly rising hopes, if not glee, among top
Republicans about the outcome of the Clinton-Lewinsky
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's right up against it now,'' Gov. Lawton Chiles of Florida,
a Democrat, said of President Clinton's impending grand jury
testimony. Then, with a downcast shake of his head, Chiles said:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing left for him except to tell the truth. That's
what he's said he will do. He says he's done nothing wrong. OK.
That's what he's got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tommy Thompson, the Wisconsin Republican who is official
host of the four-day conference here, used similar words in
discussing the president's problems. But he wore a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, it's easy,'' said Thompson, who has sometimes been
mentioned as a presidential contender. ``Just give his speech and
get it over with. But just make sure it's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all Republicans here, Thompson hedged his comments so as
not to convict the president prematurely. Still, he and other
Republican governors left no doubt that they felt that Clinton's
difficulties, wherever they might come out in the end, had already
seriously damaged the Democrats and would greatly benefit
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good about Republicans in 1998 and 2000, and why
not?'' Thompson said. ``The Democrats are confused, all over the
map, and they've got a leader who's got big troubles. Of course
we're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican governor, David Beasley of South Carolina,
predicted that the Lewinsky matter would hurt Democrats ``in a lot
of ways.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the one I want to mention,'' he said, ``is that the
president will be less able to get out and energize voters.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, such comments come mostly in corridor talk here, not
in the official seminars and plenary sessions. In those, the talk
has been solely about matters like welfare reform, health care,
education programs, environmental cleanup and any number of other
state initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end it is corridor talk that has set the tone of the
Milwaukee meeting, because at this juncture it seems that the
political hopes and fears of Democrats and Republicans both will
more likely turn on the president's grand jury testimony than on
child care or education reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just let him tell what he said he will tell, and that ought to
take care of all this,'' said Gov. John Engler of Michigan, often
mentioned as a Republican presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic governors have put the best face they can on things,
with many saying, mantra-like, that the president has denied any
wrongdoing and that there is no reason to question his denial
pending proof to the contrary. Still, like the congressional
Democrats who have recently begun to call on the president to be
more forthcoming about the Lewinsky matter, the Democratic
governors no longer insist that there is nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   None have made bold predictions here about expanding their ranks
this fall _ they are already outnumbered by Republicans, 32-17,
with one independent _ and they have no great expectation that
their party will be regaining control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ending the election with the same numbers would probably be
good for us,'' Gov. Bob Miller of Nevada lamented when asked about
Democratic hopes for cutting the Republican hold on governorships.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, said word that Clinton had agreed to give
testimony had brought a renewed focus on the investigation not only
from leading Democrats and Republicans but also from typical
Americans well outside the Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   What was once just a sideshow beyond the nation's capital, Romer
said, has become a ``serious sideshow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
