<SLUG> BC-ARCHER-TRIAL-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEOTAPES TAKE STAR ROLE AT ARCHER DANIELS TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Top executives from two of the world's most powerful
food companies sat at a conference table, snacking on orange juice
and steak sandwiches as they spoke. The meeting, in a private room
at the Marriott Hotel in Irvine, Calif., was terse and
businesslike. But the topic of discussion, the government says, was
a crime.
</P>
<P>
   For several hours, the four men _ two from Archer Daniels
Midland Co. and two from Ajinimoto Co. of Japan _ haggled over
volume production numbers, arguing over the accuracy of data they
were providing each other about their companies' sales of a feed
additive. It was, prosecutors say, the critical stage in conspiracy
that had lasted more than a year to fix prices of the additive.
</P>
<P>
   And unknown to all but one man in the room at that meeting in
October 1993, every word was being videotaped.
</P>
<P>
   More than three years after government raids disclosed the
existence of a huge price-fixing investigation, prosecutors played
that videotape Monday to a federal jury that is hearing the
criminal price-fixing case against three former Archer Daniels
executives. All three men have pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   If the government is right in its claims, the videotape offers
an unprecedented look into what the government contends was a
price-fixing conspiracy on a giant scale, involving every major
company in the business of producing the additive, which is called
lysine. It shows the executives of the two largest companies in the
business discussing how they would dictate the annual growth in
production to the other lysine makers, and debating the tactical
benefits of simply lying to the others about certain data.
</P>
<P>
   But the tape has already played a critical role in reshaping the
future of Archer Daniels, the politically powerful grain giant. For
it is the crucial evidence against one defendant, Michael Andreas,
the son and former heir apparent to the powerful company's
chairman, Dwayne Andreas.
</P>
<P>
   Also charged in the case are Terrance Wilson, the former head of
the company's corn-processing division, and Mark Whitacre, the
former head of its bioproducts unit, which produces lysine.
</P>
<P>
   The government has already secured guilty pleas from some of the
executives involved in the conspiracy and each of the companies;
Archer Daniels agreed to pay $100 million in 1996 to settle
price-fixing charges.
</P>
<P>
   Since the investigation was first disclosed, much of the public
attention has focused on Whitacre, who served as a government
informant during the inquiry and secretly recorded his colleagues
over more than two years. But he became a defendant in the case
after the government learned he had violated his cooperation
agreement by illegally taking millions of dollars from Archer
Daniels through a complex fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of the defense centers on Whitacre. Lawyers for
Andreas and Wilson have argued that he manipulated investigators
and Archer Daniels officials to create evidence of a conspiracy.
The defense lawyers have argued that many of the conversations
captured on the recordings either involve innocent business
discussions or were elaborate efforts to trick Asian competitors
into providing information that would allow Archer Daniels to gauge
the size of the lysine market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the hearing Monday focused solely on the price-fixing
allegations that began the investigation. Early in the day,
prosecutors played an audiotape recorded by Whitacre in 1993 during
a meeting at Archer Daniels' headquarters in Decatur, Ill., between
senior executives with the company and officials with Ajinimoto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a saying at this company,'' James Randall, then the
president of Archer Daniels, told the Japanese executives. ``Our
competitors are our friends and our customers are our enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting in Irvine came some months later. According to
testimony in the case, efforts among the five lysine producers to
fix prices were failing because the companies were unable to reach
an agreement to limit production. So, the government contends, a
meeting between top decision makers at the two largest producers _
Archer Daniels and Ajinimoto _ was arranged.
</P>
<P>
   In the videotape, which was made by a camera hidden in a lamp,
the men appeared to be discussing various possible agreements to
allocate how much lysine each company could produce in 1994. At one
point, they decided to use their 1993 sales as a base; they then
appeared to attempt to allocate a predicted growth in market demand
of 14,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how do we share the growth,'' Andreas said.
``What would we be willing to accept and what would you be willing
to accept?''
</P>
<P>
   The men spent some time haggling over production numbers while
standing at an easel. At one point on the tape, the Ajinimoto
executive said that other lysine producers would not believe Archer
Daniels' sales figures. The Archer Daniels executives replied that
the two companies should instead offer lower, false numbers to the
other competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Andreas appeared to propose an allocation of the
projected lysine market growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can each have 2,000 tons more in 1994,'' Andreas said of
the other lysine producers. ``And we get the rest between you and
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the video, Andreas, who is now on leave as vice chairman of
Archer Daniels, said that if an agreement was not reached, Archer
Daniels could simply run up its production far more. ``If they
don't agree and there becomes a free-for-all,'' he said, ``Our
numbers are liable to be a lot larger.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he specified what that meant. ``Their choices are that
we'll agree to only grow five if everything is good,'' he said,
``Or 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parts of the conversation indicated that the senior
management at Archer Daniels kept a close handle on developments in
its businesses, particularly divisions like bioproducts. ``Myself
and my father and Randall,'' Andreas said. ``We all know all the
time what is going on, especially with new businesses that need our
attention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
