u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-TALKS-NYT &LR;      08-03 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. ARMS INSPECTOR'S TALKS WITH IRAQ BREAK DOWN IN BITTERNESS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Crucial talks in Baghdad on the remaining
issues blocking the lifting of sanctions on Iraq collapsed in
rancor on Monday, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis, returning to the belligerent tone that heralded an
international crisis last fall, rejected a plan for settling issues
proposed by the U.N. chief arms inspector for Iraq, Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, the Iraqi delegation leader,
accused Butler, an Australian, of using ``old tricks'' and
following an American policy of continuing sanctions no matter what
progress is made.
</P>
<P>
   Butler told reporters in Baghdad after Monday's session that he
had not made the progress he had hoped for. ``I made a proposal for
further acceleration of work and it was rejected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Danilo Turk, the Slovenian delegate to the Security Council and
its current president, said that Butler would cut his trip short
and return to brief the council by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials here and in Baghdad said that they had no further
information on the stalled discussions and declined to speculate
whether the show of obstinacy by the Iraqis was a ploy to rally
support against Butler, whose frank style they dislike.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis once again staged a funeral procession for 35 Iraqi
children outside the building where Butler and Aziz met. Their
parents told reporters that the children had died because of
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis accused the United States of ``wrecking'' the program
under which limited oil sales are permitted to pay for food and
medicine. U.N. officials countered that a loosening of the
sanctions has increased oil sales sharply and has allowed hundreds
of millions of dollars in medical supplies to reach Iraq. They said
it was the Iraqi government that recently reduced a U.N. proposal
to raise caloric intake in food distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis have been encouraged by Russia, France and China to
hope for a phasing-out of sanctions should the Security Council
acknowledge that every detail about Iraqi weapons will never be
known and that enough progress had been made to warrant a
relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Butler, under pressure from the Security Council,
provided Iraq with a ``road map'' of steps to take to meet his
disarmament requirements. Aziz, repeating that Iraq had no more
weapons or information to provide, strongly indicated then that
there would be no more cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Butler did not go to Iraq this week with high hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of this round of talks would leave little room for
averting tensions when the sanctions are reviewed by the Security
Council in October. Iraq has significant questions to answer and
has provided no new information since May.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis have, in fact, lost some ground because of the
discovery of VX nerve gas on shell canisters and a less upbeat
assessment than expected last week by the International Atomic
Energy Agency on accounting for nuclear programs. Iraq also refused
to hand over a document found by inspectors last month.
</P>
<P>
   President Saddam Hussein has threatened unspecified retaliation
if the embargo on oil sales is not lifted this year. Last year, his
government expelled American inspectors, put large presidential
compounds off limits and threatened to freeze all inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam's defiance of arms inspectors led to a massing of
American and British forces in the Persian Gulf early this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2125EDT &QL; 
