<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS &LR;      08-03 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BANS UNREGULATED `SOFT MONEY' CONTRIBUTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Champions of overhauling campaign finance laws
prevailed against the odds in the House on Monday, passing a bill
that bans unregulated and unlimited ``soft money'' contributions to
political parties and dramatically changes the way national
elections are paid for.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of campaign finance reform still face an uphill
battle, not only in the House but in the Senate, where Majority
Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi and other Republican opponents say
they will continue to block the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bipartisan bill sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., and Marty Meehan, D-Mass., managed to overcome stiff
opposition led by House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas. The vote
of 237-186 was a hard-fought victory for Shays and Meehan, who had
worried over several months of debate that their measure would be
watered down or killed outright by several hundred amendments
designed to siphon off support.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than losing steam, the bill seemed to pick up more
supporters in recent weeks as Republican leaders tried repeatedly
to bring it down with some 60 ``poison pill'' amendments and
warnings that it would violate the constitutional guarantee of free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the vote, Shays attempted to persuade a number of
members still uncommitted by dubbing the campaign finance issue
``the most important vote'' of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope and pray we will do our job and send it to the
Senate,'' Shays said, calling the vote ``a historic opportunity to
restore integrity to the campaign finance process.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, modeled after legislation first introduced in
the Senate by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold,
D-Wis., would ban soft money contributions to state and national
political parties from corporations, individuals and special
interest groups. It would beef up disclosure regulations for any
contributions more than $50 and require the timely posting of
contributions on an Internet site once a candidate's report is
filed with the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would regulate so-called anonymous special
interest ``issue ads'' that masquerade as negative campaign ads run
on radio and television during the closing days of a campaign.
Finally, the bill would force labor unions to refund any dues or
payments from members used for political purposes if members
object.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bill for which under the scrutiny of daylight
support has grown,'' said Rep. Michael Castle, R-Del, who called it
one of the ``finest pieces of legislation'' voted on by the House
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents led by DeLay trashed the Shays-Meehan bill,
calling it a ``fiasco'' that violates the Constitution's First
Amendment protection of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It violates our most precious freedom _ the freedom of
speech,'' said DeLay, who warned that the Supreme Court would
likely overturn the measure if it becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay also said the bill amounted to ``political disarmament''
for Republicans, who normally outraise and outspend their
Democratic opponents by a margin of 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not reform. This is not good government. This is
political disarmament,'' DeLay declared, imploring his GOP
colleagues to vote it down.
</P>
<P>
   But his arguments against the measure only fueled the intensity
of support for it among many of its Republican backers, who labeled
DeLay's comments about it benefiting Democrats more than
Republicans ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that this bill is as fair to Republicans as
Democrats. The truth is that it affects any outside group the same.
It's the same for Wall Street or the labor unions. It's the same
for the Christian Coalition and the ACLU,'' said Rep. Zach Wamp,
R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Wamp called on his fellow Republicans to ``do the right thing
for the American people and send the signal that we have gone the
distance on reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the moment of truth,'' he said. ``Will you please put
the public interest above your personal interest? Will you please
put good government above your political party?''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Shays-Meehan bill received a majority of House
votes, it still could be stopped under a ``king of the hill'' rule
governing the campaign finance debate. The Shays-Meehan measure is
just one of several campaign finance reform bills the House will
vote on this week. The one that gets the most votes will be the
bill that gets forwarded on to the Senate for possible
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill, however, is expected to emerge at the end
of the week as ``the top dog'' legislation, as House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., put it recently.
</P>
<P>
   In his floor speech in favor of the bill, Gephardt said passage
of the measure would be ``the first real step in the process of
reform this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote on Shays-Meehan was a setback for the Republican
leadership, which had sought to prevent a vote on the measure. In
the end, 51 Republicans, 185 Democrats and one independent voted
for the legislation and 175 Republicans and 11 Democrats voted
against it. Party leaders had predicted only a few weeks ago, that
no more than two dozen Republicans would support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got kicked pretty good,'' said one Republican leadership
aide. ``But it'll never get through the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, both Lott and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., have vowed
not to allow the legislation to be considered again in the Senate
this year. The McCain-Feingold version was blocked earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked last week if the Senate would be under pressure to
pass campaign finance reform if the Shay-Meehan measured prevailed
in the House, McConnell just laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the position of Lott and McConnell, Shays said he has no
plans to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been resurrected from the grave,'' he said of the vote on
his measure. ``This bill won't die.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a letter to House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
R-Ga., called the Shays-Meehan measure a ``tough, fair'' bill that
would make ``a genuine difference in the way we conduct
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called on the Senate to take up the issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
