u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      08-03 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES CAMPAIGN FINANCE REVAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House, in a rare snub of the Republican
leadership, Monday night passed a landmark plan for the most
sweeping changes in the way money is spent and raised in the
nation's elections since the wake of the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   After months of political pressure, parliamentary pitfalls and
``poison-pill'' amendments, a bloc of 51 renegade Republicans broke
with House Speaker Newt Gingrich and helped the Democratic minority
pass the overhaul plan, 237-186. Only 11 Democrats voted against
the high-stakes measure.
</P>
<P>
   All 24 House members from New England voted for the proposal
except Representative John E. Sununu, a New Hampshire Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would ban the large, unregulated contributions known as
``soft money'' that were at the center of campaign-finance abuses
in the 1996 elections. The bill also would prohibit the type of
anonymous attack ads that proliferated in 1996 and influenced the
outcomes of many congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a generation, members of Congress take it upon
themselves to change our campaign-finance law,'' said
Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, who
sponsored the bill with Representative Christopher Shays, a
Connecticut Republican. ``That day has arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has vowed to sign the measure into law if
it reaches his desk, issued a statement calling the vote a
``breakthrough in the fight for bipartisan campaign finance
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin of victory, Clinton said, ``showed that reform is an
idea whose time has come.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the legislation's torturous journey is far from over,
despite the plan's remarkable resurgence since foes declared it
dead several months ago amid stern opposition from Gingrich and his
leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   Although the measure faces challenges from several alternative
proposals this week in the House, supporters said it appears likely
to prevail and be forwarded to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a Senate version of the Shays-Meehan bill has failed twice
in the last year, even though it was supported by a simple majority
of the 100-member body. In each case, the effort failed when
supporters fell eight votes short of the 60 votes needed to end a
Republican-led filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the measure's chief sponsor, Senator John McCain,
an Arizona Republican, said little has changed since the last
setback in February.
</P>
<P>
   The House action ``might change some votes in the Senate and
persuade a super-majority of senators that the time is finally at
hand to reform a campaign finance system that a clear majority of
Americans believe is corrupt,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   But the lingering opposition and dwindling number of days in the
current legislative sessions make ``another attempt at passing a
Senate bill an exceedingly difficult task at best,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said
another attempt at passing the campaign-finance bill this year
``would be a big waste of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The House vote was part of the 14th major effort in Congress to
change the campaign-finance system since 1979. Every previous
attempt failed, as legislation died in the House, the Senate or the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   During the 19-year struggle, the House and Senate agreed only
once to an overhaul plan. But when they sent it to the White House,
in 1992, the measure was vetoed by President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a historic opportunity to restore integrity to
the political process,'' said Shays, who has endured a backlash
from GOP colleagues for defying Gingrich's opposition to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said the bill's soft-money ban would benefit
Democrats. Both parties spent a total of $270 million in soft money
in 1996. And in the 18 months after Jan. 1, 1997, Republicans
raised $70 million in soft money while the Democrats raised $46
million.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's foes also argued that the proposed restrictions on
special interest advertising were unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just violates our most precious freedom, freedom of
speech,'' said Representative Tom DeLay, the House majority whip.
``The supporters of this bill believe there is too much information
about our government and that Americans are too stupid to sort out
what is true from what is false.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for banning soft money argued that political leaders
expose themselves to the appearance of possible corruption in
pressuring corporations, labor unions and wealthy individuals for
the six-figure contributions they use to fund their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the allegations about wrongdoing at the White House
involved soft-money donors sharing coffee with Clinton in the
executive mansion or sleeping in the Lincoln bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican Party, whose leaders engineered the recent
attack against antitobacco legislation, have opened themselves to
criticism, for example, by accepting more than $1 million from the
cigarette maker Philip Morris in the 18 months after Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Several House Democrats portrayed Gingrich's opposition of the
bill as a symbol of the influence of big money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Months of delay, poison pills, death by amendment: The
opponents of reform have done everything they can to kill off
campaign finance reform and keep the spigots of special interest
money flowing,'' said House Democratic whip David Bonior of
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from a group of moderate Republicans, Gingrich
ended months of resistance and permitted debate to begin in May on
the Shays-Meehan bill and 11 competing proposals. Debate on the
Shays-Meehan plan began June 19, with much of the action relegated
to late-night sessions over the 45-day span.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shays-Meehan supporters defeated more than 40
amdendments, including many aimed at gutting the measure, they were
unable to fight off 23 others.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 23, however, only two were so problematic that they
threatened to break apart the majority coalition supporting
Shays-Meehan. Both amendments would prohibit non-citizens,
including all non-military legal permanent residents, from
contributing to election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic members of Congress assailed the measure as
discriminatory to individuals who work in the United States, pay
taxes and, in the vast majority of cases, are enmeshed in the
lengthy process of attaining citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The House is scheduled to vote on most alternatives to the
Shays-Meehan plan this week, although several sponsors have said
they may withdraw their proposals in order to keep alive the
Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the competing sponsors are Representatives John F.
Tierney, a Salem Democrat, and Charles F. Bass, a New Hampshire
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney said he had yet to decide if he will withdraw his
proposal, which would provide free and reduced-rate broadcast time
to candidates who abide by spending limits. But he indicated he did
not want to be seen as obstructing progress. ``I don't want to be
part of the delay,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
