the shoreline vistas in Laguna Beach are magnificent. In this city
long known as an artist colony, there's plenty to take in - surf,
sand, art galleries, shopping, restaurants - and through the end of
August, live performances nightly of the Pageant of the Masters.
(Natalie Haughton/Los Angeles Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- NY-MEN'S-FASHION-3, 8-3 --
The blending of street wear and tailored clothes seems organic to
Tommy Hilfiger. At right are his batik pants with a sheer shirt in
shades of blue. While at left he shows a wide-cut pant in a greem
floral print paired with an athletic cut, short-sleeved shirt in
lime green. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- NY-MEN'S-FASHION-2, 8-3 --
Reclaiming the dashiki from cultural oblivion, John Scher proposed
this white poplin version of it, left. (Ruby Washington/New York
Times Photo) Maurice Malone's signature line of sleek suits and
seperates with multiple-flap pockets and contrasting shirts.
(Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- NY-MEN'S-FASHION-1, 8-3 --
Maintaining the whimsy that is her style, Cynthia Rowley's shows
her multicolored, diagonally striped sweaters, left, and a shocking
pink suit with shot, wide-cut pants. (Ruby Washington/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- DOUBLE-LIVES-2, 8-3 --
Stanley Bojarski plays a sassy garden supplier in ``When Pigs
Fly,'' but at his paralegal job he sports a different look. By
juggling a so-called survival job at the sedate midtown offices of
Dewey Ballantine with a prime role in the exuberantly gay-themed
musical revue, Bojarski is doing what actors have long done to eat
and pay the rent. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- DOUBLE-LIVES-1, 8-3 --
Stanley Bojarski slips on panty hose while getting ready to play a
sassy garden supplier in ``When Pigs Fly.'' By juggling a so-called
survival job at the sedate midtown offices of Dewey Ballantine with
a prime role in the exuberantly gay-themed musical revue, Bojarski
is doing what actors have long done to eat and pay the rent.
(Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- BOSTON-ARTHUR, 8-3 -- Marc
Brown, in cap, with Arthur Read - the 8-year-old aardvark whose
family life, adventures and problems are chronicled in Brown's
best-selling children's book series and in the spinoff public
television show - and young visitors to the Children's Museum in
Boston. ``I love to use Arthur's celebrity to do other things that
aren't as sexy,'' he says. ``Life is a series of problems, and this
is one of them.'' (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ISLAND PARK, N.Y. -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- SCI-GENE-THERAPY-2,
8-3 -- Adam Cohen, 17, who suffers from Hunter syndrome, receiving
physical therapy from Anthony DeCicco as his mother, Joan Cohen,
looks on. ``It's like a time bomb,'' she says of her son, Adam, who
is just 4 feet 11 inches tall and suffers from leaky, enlarged
heart valves, respiratory problems, and deteriorated hearing. ``I'm
sitting here with a kid that I know is going to die and there's
nothing I can do that will stop it.'' (Vic DeLucia/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ISLAND PARK, N.Y. -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- SCI-GENE-THERAPY-1,
8-3 -- Adam Cohen, 17, who suffers from Hunter syndrome, is still
waiting for a gene therapy treatment he was told would be available
5 years ago. Even in its mild form, the disease often kills people
by the time they reach 35. But gene therapy so far has not worked,
mainly because it has been difficult to get the genes to the
desired cells efficiently and have them produce enough of the
needed protein. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ST. LOUIS -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- SCI-BOTANY-RAVEN, 8-3 -- Dr.
Peter Raven is the director of the Missouri Botanical Garden, which
grows by 120,000 specimens a year. ``I specialize in networking,''
says Raven, who directs a staff of 354, including 55 researchers
with Ph.D.s, and oversees a budget of $20 million. ``I like to link
people.'' The new $146 million plant research center promises to
make the city an agricultural Silicon Valley, proponents say. (Bill
Stover/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SMITHFIELD, R.I. -- Aug. 3, 1998 --
BOOKS-BEEPERSPEAK-BOS, 8-3 -- Norman Beauregard holds the book
which he and two friends created that has a beeper language in
which numbers denote everyday words or phrases. ``The Universal
Beeper Code Book,'' a beeperspeak-English dictionary comes in
packages of two for $4.95. About 22,000 packages have been sold
nationwide to gift shops and drugstores since December. The product
also joined the Web last week at www.thebeeperbook.com. (Bethany
Versoy/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DURHAM, N.H. -- Aug. 3, 1998 -- FUTURE-GAMES-BOS, 8-3 --
Dennis Meadows, the director of the Institute for Policy and Social
Science Research at the University of New Hampshire poses on the
wall of a chimney at the Browne Center on the UNH campus. ``I've
been creating a series of games to serve as models and metaphors to
help get people thinking about resource development and the limits
to growth,'' Meadows explains. (Wendy Madea/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
