<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBERTSON-AMERICAN-AR     08-03 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBERTSON-AMERICAN-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBERTSON'S TO BUY CHAIN OF STORES FOR $8.3 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on total revenues of top supermarkets is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Albertson's Inc. said Monday that it would acquire American
Stores Co. for $8.3 billion in stock, in a deal that will create
the nation's largest supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction _ the latest in a round of deals announced in
the grocery industry recently as supermarket operators have sought
to form regional strongholds _ would create a chain of nearly 2,500
stores in 37 states with more than 200,000 employees and pro forma
1998 revenues of about $36 billion. The purchase would also
establish Albertson's, which had been the fifth largest chain, as
the industry leader, vaulting past Kroger, which has nearly 1,400
stores in 24 states.
</P>
<P>
   Albertson's is strong in the West, Midwest and South and will
now have a larger presence in the Southwest and on the West Coast,
where American Stores is a large competitor. The acquisition would
also move Albertson's into drug store retailing because American
Stores has 750 free-standing drug stores that operate under the
Osco Drug and Sav-on names.
</P>
<P>
   In all, American Stores, which is based in Salt Lake City,
operates 1,558 stores in 26 states, including 269 food and drug
combination stores and 539 supermarkets that operate under the
names Acme Markets, Jewel Food Stores and Lucky Stores.
</P>
<P>
   Albertson's, which is based in Boise, Idaho, operates 916 retail
stores in 23 states. Both chains' stores will retain their names,
and the company headquarters will remain in Boise.
</P>
<P>
   Albertson's chairman and chief executive, Gary Michael, will run
the combined company, and American Stores' chairman and chief
executive, Victor Lund, will be vice chairman of the combined
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a strategic standpoint, this transaction will strengthen
our presence in many of our existing markets across the country _
particularly in Northern and Southern California and the Southwest
_ and enables us to enter important urban markets like Chicago and
Philadelphia for the first time,'' Michael said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to paying the $8.3 billion in stock, Albertson's
will assume $3.4 billion in debt. American Stores shareholders are
to receive 0.63 shares of Albertson's common stock for each share
of American Stores stock. Based on Albertson's closing price on
Friday of $48 a share, the deal is worth $30.24 a share for
American shareholders, who would then own 41.3 percent of
Albertson's. Also, Albertson's will issue about 170 million
additional shares in the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Albertson's said it expected to save $100 million in costs the
first year from buying and distribution efficiencies and $200
million in the third year from reducing overhead and advertising
expenditures in overlapping markets. Part of the lower overhead
cost will come from eliminating some administrative jobs, although
the number has not been determined. Albertson's said it would take
an undetermined one-time charge related to the transaction, which
it expected to add to earnings per share next year.
</P>
<P>
   American Stores' stock rose $5.3125 Monday to $28.50.
Albertson's shares, meanwhile, were nearly flat, edging up just 50
cents, to $48.50. Shareholders' lukewarm reception may indicate
that they consider the price of the transaction a bit rich or that
they have concerns about how easily the companies can be combined.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``because of our consistent business philosophies and
similar corporate cultures, I am confident the integration of these
two companies will go smoothly,'' Lund said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Analysts said the combination could be more difficult than the
companies anticipate because of the numerous geographical regions
in which they operate and because of the number and type of stores
they run. The deal, which has been approved by both companies'
boards, could also run into antitrust problems in such areas as
California, where Albertson's stands to dominate the market.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission is likely to mandate some
divestitures where there is overlap, said Debra Levin, an analyst
who follows the supermarket industry for Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``They will have to sell some stores, but I don't think
that will prevent this from working.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the industry's merger trend is being driven by the
benefits of size, namely, greater purchasing clout, a larger bang
for the advertising buck and additional stores from which to
compete with Walmart, the warehouse clubs and other nontraditional
retailers that now sell milk and eggs.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in May, Royal Ahold NV said it was buying the
Giant Food Inc., a supermarket chain, for $2.6 billion, adding 177
stores to its 830 domestic stores. And last year, Fred Meyer Inc.
purchased Quality Food Centers Inc. and Ralphs Grocery Co. in
separate deals worth about $2 billion that created a chain with
more than 800 stores in 14 states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
