</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDES TAKE DEFIANT STANCE ON LEWINSKY MATTER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BENNET and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking a defiant stance toward prosecutors and
political critics, White House officials said on Monday that
President Clinton would continue to maintain that he had no sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky and would appeal a court decision
ordering a top aide to testify in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is not scheduled to testify until Aug. 17, and his
advisers cautioned that only he and a small cadre of lawyers are
privy to his deliberations. But several Clinton aides on Monday
dismissed pleas from Republican congressmen and some former
officials that Clinton acknowledge an affair with the former White
House intern to blunt and perhaps end the six-month-old
investigation by Kenneth Starr, the independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has told the truth about this and he will
continue to do so,'' said Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, in
response to questions. ``I have no reason to think that that has
changed in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials expressed annoyance over what they called a
presumption that the president was lying when he denied a
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky in the Paula Corbin Jones sexual
misconduct suit. They said that Clinton's agreement to testify,
despite White House suspicion of Starr's motives, proved that he
had nothing to fear. ``It is a little insulting to turn on the
television and see people come up with the brilliant idea that he
should tell the truth,'' one official said. ``Do you think anyone
here is going in and saying, `Sir, you should lie'?''
</P>
<P>
   The White House also served notice on Monday that it would ask
the Supreme Court to overturn a lower court's decision compelling
Bruce Lindsey, a White House lawyer who is the president's closest
adviser, to testify to the Lewinsky grand jury. Lanny Breuer,
another member of the White House Counsel's office, was subpoenaed
last week to testify on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic scientists at the FBI crime laboratory completed a
first set of tests on a blue dress that Ms. Lewinsky turned over to
prosecutors. Prosecutors are trying to determine whether the dress
was stained during a sexual encounter with Clinton. The first test,
performed under extremely tight security, was intended to determine
whether the stain was caused by semen, but the result was being
very closely held.
</P>
<P>
   In a mixed decision for the White House and Starr, the U.S.
court of appeals here ruled on Monday that an investigation may
continue into whether Starr's office has illegally leaked grand
jury material. The investigation is being conducted by Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson, who presides over the grand jury hearing the
Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But, overruling part of a decision by Judge Johnson, the appeals
court found that the president's lawyers may not on their own
depose Starr's prosecutors or demand documents from them, according
to a lawyer familiar with the ruling, which was sealed. Instead,
Judge Johnson must first review and approve any documents that are
to be turned over by Starr's office, to insure they do not reveal
grand jury secrets.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, one of the president's lawyers, has accused
Starr's office of illegal slipping information to reporters and
sought sanctions against it. Starr's office has denied any such
leaks.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced on Monday that it would appeal a
ruling by a three-judge appeals panel that compelled complete
testimony from Lindsey. Lindsey, who has said that he knows of no
wrongdoing or criminal conduct, cited attorney-client privilege in
declining to answer some questions before a grand jury here.
</P>
<P>
   In its divided ruling last week, the panel of the U.S. court of
appeals found that no such privilege could protect a government
lawyer from testifying in a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Although one of the three judges argued, in dissent, that the
decision would chill discussions in the executive branch, the
majority wrote: ``When an executive branch attorney is called
before a federal grand jury to give evidence about alleged crimes
within the executive branch, reason and experience, duty and
tradition dictate that the attorney shall provide that evidence.
Their duty is not to defend clients against criminal charges and it
is not to protect wrongdoers from public exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House filed a motion with the appeals court here to
block testimony by its lawyers while it awaits Supreme Court
action. It was not clear whether that motion would prevent Breuer's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The White House counsel, Charles F.C. Ruff, said that the
appeals court decision would undercut any president's ability to
get honest advice by removing the attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``This privilege ultimately serves the public interest by
insuring fully informed decision-making through open and candid
discussions between clients and attorneys,'' he said in a statement
on Monday. ``The confidential nature of the attorney-client
privilege relationship is no less important in government than in
any other context where it exists.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Aides to the president said on Monday that he betrayed no sign
of nervousness about his prospective testimony. ``The most
comforting thing in the White House now is that the president seems
totally comfortable,'' said one Clinton aide who is not part of his
damage-control team.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing to publicly ignore his legal and political
predicament, Clinton confined his public comments on Monday to
other legislative matters than talk of potential impeachment
hearings. In a speech to summer jobs workers in Cheverly, Md., he
warned Republican leaders that he would not accept a ``bare-bones''
budget from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House Republican plan puts politics ahead of people and
puts your future in the back seat,'' he said. ``That is wrong.''
With veto threats hanging over seven appropriations bills, the
White House is on a collision course with Congress over the budget,
though that dispute has been obscured by the furor over Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also gave a speech on Monday, appearing before a lawyers'
group in Toronto, Canada. He reviewed the Supreme Court's
performance this year, calling it ``quite impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had learned from a defeat he suffered this year
before the Supreme Court, which ruled he could not have access to
notes taken by a lawyer to Vince Foster, the former Clinton
official who committed suicide during Clinton's first term. The
court ruled that a client's death did not weaken the
attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said that ``the court reminded us that there are other
considerations, there are other values,'' besides the pursuit of
truth. ``The law, embodying the wisdom of the ages, has seen fit to
protect relationships, even at the expense of truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Starr told reporters that he was pursuing his
investigation while ```being respectful of the institutions of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the president's advisers have doubts about his
truthfulness regarding Ms. Lewinsky, and some suspect that by
changing his story now he could bring an end to a drama that has
transfixed Washington and stunted progress on Capitol Hill. But
many Clinton allies also believe that any admission by Clinton
would be turned against him by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's advisers said that his team of political and
legal aides was nervously awaiting test results on Ms. Lewinsky's
dress, which was bought at the Gap. If DNA testing links the dress
to Clinton, this adviser said, White House thinking on his
testimony may change. ``Whatever anyone is saying becomes
inoperative depending upon the results,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike lab findings in most high profile cases, which are widely
distributed through the upper echelons of the law enforcement
agency and the Justice Department, the Lewinsky lab tests are being
provided only to a handful of lab technicians and senior FBI
officials. They in turn reveal the findings directly to Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
