<HEADLINE>
MARINE FLIERS ARE ARRAIGNED IN CRASH CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif., N.Y., Italy)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. _ The pilot and the navigator of a Marine
Corps surveillance jet that cut the cables of a ski-lift gondola in
the Italian Alps, killing 20 people, will enter not guilty pleas as
their cases move closer to trial, their lawyers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, the pilot from Mission Viejo, Calif.,
and Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 30, of Westbury, N.Y., were arraigned
in a courtroom at Camp Lejeune on Monday, their first court
appearance since the Marine Corps commandant, Lt. Gen. Peter Pace
decided last month that they would be tried on charges of negligent
homicide and involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   They are also charged with damaging military and civilian
property and dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on all of the charges, they would face up to life
in military prison.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by their lawyers in separate hearings, the fliers sat
quietly and answered only ``Yes, sir'' or ``No, sir'' when prompted
by the military judge, Lt. Col. Robert Nunley. Although the
officers were asked in the hearing how they would plead, their
lawyers said later that Ashby and Schweitzer would enter pleas of
not guilty at the appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
   The two will be tried separately, with Ashby's court-martial
scheduled to begin Dec. 9, while Schweitzer's case is scheduled to
be heard in January.
</P>
<P>
   The two rear-seat equipment operators, against whom charges were
dropped last month, are likely to be called to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The four crew members were charged after the Feb. 3 accident
near Cavalese, Italy, where their EA-6B Prowler plane severed two
lift cables that were holding up a gondola carrying skiers. The
accident provoked strong protests in Italy and strained relations
with the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
