NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, AUGUST 4
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-IRELAND-KENNEDY-SMITH-NYT (moved on Saturday, July 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, July 25,
about Jean Kennedy Smith's expected departure from Dublin in
September after more than five years as United States Ambassador to
Ireland described her longevity in that post incorrectly. She is
not the longest-serving American ambassador in Dublin; John D.J.
Moore served six years, from 1969 to 1975.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MEXICO-VOTE-NYT (moved on Sunday, August 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, August 2,
about state elections in Mexico misstated the number of state
governorships held by the Party of the Democratic Revolution,
founded by Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, the Mayor of Mexico City.
It is one, not none. (The party won in the state of Zacatecas on
July 5.)
</P>
<P>
   BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT (moved on Monday, July 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 27,
about whether a President can be prosecuted described Leon
Jaworski's status as a Watergate special prosecutor incorrectly.
Mr. Jaworski, who was special prosecutor when President Nixon
resigned, was the second of four men to hold that post, not the
last. He was followed by Henry S. Ruth Jr. and Charles F.C. Ruff.
</P>
