<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-TELECOM-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH PHONE UTILITY EXTENDS LATIN AMERICAN LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ When Telefonica, the Spanish telecommunications
company, came away with the largest single piece of Brazil's
telecommunications privatization auction last week, the Spanish
carrier doubled its holdings to more than $10 billion in Latin
America, where it was already the dominant foreign phone provider.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica's immersion in the region, its main foray outside
Spain, started in 1990 with a $468 million investment to run
Chile's phone company, and spread to control of the leading
telephone companies in Argentina and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   And Telefonica's chairman, Juan Villalonga, said that after last
week's successful bid for a third of the $19 billion selloff of
most of Telebras, as the Brazilian carrier is widely known, his
company was now the ``undisputed'' leader in Latin America and any
competitors there are now just ``niche operators.''
</P>
<P>
   In the auction, which the Brazilian government held to bring
private enterprise and competition to its former state monopoly,
Telefonica agreed to spend $5 billion for control of the phone
company that serves the Sao Paulo region and $1.2 billion for the
wireless carrier that serves the regions of Rio de Janeiro and
Espirito Santo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telefonica means growth,'' Villalonga, 45, said in a phone
interview on Friday from the Washington headquarters of one of his
company's international allies, MCI Communications. He flew in from
Brazil, and was meeting with MCI's chairman, Bert C. Roberts Jr., a
member of Telefonica's board.
</P>
<P>
   The Telefonica group, based in Madrid and fully privatized only
last year, reported 1997 profit of $1.2 billion on revenue of $15.5
billion, an 18 percent increase from 1996. The results continued
the company's steady growth of the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign revenue accounted for 16 percent of company sales last
year and is expected to climb to 27 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although its overseas revenue so far is almost exclusively from
Latin America, Telefonica is counting on international alliances to
give it a foothold in the rest of Europe and the United States. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, it and MCI have been poised to build a fiber optic
network in Latin America and to provide customized
telecommunications products for Hispanic customers in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   It announced business deals in April 1997 with MCI and its
then-ally, British Telecommunications PLC. To do so, Telefonica
bowed out of membership in the European telecommunications
consortium, Unisource, in which AT&AMP;T, the largest phone company,
had also shown interest.
</P>
<P>
   But the planned acquisition of MCI by Worldcom, announced later
in 1997, knocked British Telecom out of the picture for Telefonica.
In March, it announced a series of MCI deals _ one of which would
make Telefonica a distributor for the combined company's European
business network. Villalonga said he is to take a seat on the
merged company's board after the deal is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The companies plan to include in their alliance Portugal
Telecom, which along with MCI made significant, separate purchases
in last week's Brazilian auction.
</P>
<P>
   Investment and mutual funds from the United States own about 35
percent of Telefonica, whose shares trade in Madrid, London, Paris
and Frankfurt and as American depository receipts on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The ADRs rose sharply last Wednesday on news of the Brazilian
auction, nearing a 52-week high of $158.125, then drifted back,
ending the week at $145.50. Monday, they eased a bit further, down
50 cents, to $145.
</P>
<P>
   Three Spanish financial institutions, Banco Bilbao Vizcaya,
Argentaria and La Caixa, hold about 15 percent of the company's
stock among them.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica's overseas expansion has been spurred by the phased
introduction of competition into the Spanish telecommunications
market that began in 1994. The once-cozy monopoly, then Telefonica
de Espana, was founded in 1924 by International Telephone and
Telegraph and nationalized in 1945 under Franco. By the mid-1990s,
it no longer had the field to itself.
</P>
<P>
   Airtouch Communications of the United States has been part of a
cellular phone company competing domestically with Telefonica and
winning nearly 30 percent of that market.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance calls from fixed lines were opened to competition
only this year, and already Telefonica's rival for that business,
Retevision, says it has captured about 6 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga was appointed Telefonica's chairman by the Spanish
government, which still held nearly 21 percent of the company, in
June 1996, a month after his boyhood friend, Jose Maria Aznar, was
sworn in as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga, who had previously worked at Bankers Trust and
Credit Suisse First Boston in Spain, has been pushing Telefonica's
Latin American expansion while trying to protect its position as
Spain's largest company by market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Villalonga said his priority would be to build upon
the Brazilian acquisition. He pledged to double the existing six
million fixed phone lines in the Sao Paulo area within two years
and reduce years-long waiting lists for phones there.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica assumed extra debt in the Brazil deal, and Standard &AMP;
Poor's last Thursday downgraded its credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   But James Downie, an analyst with ABN Amro in London, said: ``We
are fundamentally positive on Telefonica. Debt now is relatively
cheap, and it was a one-off opportunity to get into Brazil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
