<HEADLINE>
SEC ACCUSES DAIN RAUSCHER OF FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Idaho, Texas, Minn.)  (lb) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Securities and Exchange Commission has accused
Dain Rauscher Inc. and two former employees of fraud for their
roles in underwriting bonds connected to the 1994 bankruptcy of
Orange County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Monday in U.S. District Court, is the second
SEC action against a brokerage firm stemming from the bankruptcy.
In the first action, Credit Suisse First Boston and two former
employees agreed in January to pay $870,000 to settle SEC charges.
In addition, the commission is negotiating a settlement with
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. that is reported to be for a fine of less than
$3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC actions are distinct from lawsuits filed by Orange
County itself. Those suits, several of which have been settled
recently, generally accuse brokerage firms of selling risky
securities to the county. The SEC is concentrating on the adequacy
of disclosures made by underwriters who sold bonds issued by the
county or its municipalities to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Dain Rauscher, a major participant in municipal finance,
underwrote or was the financial adviser for 13 bond offerings,
totaling more than $980 million, by cities and school districts in
Orange County in 1993 and 1994, according to the SEC complaint. The
proceeds from the offerings were invested in an investment pool run
by Orange County's treasurer, Robert Citron. The pool suffered
heavy losses in 1994, precipitating the bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC accuses Dain Rauscher of misleading investors by not
disclosing in the offering documents that the sole purpose of the
bond sales was to obtain money to invest in the Orange County pool
in the hopes of making profits.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the commission contends, Dain Rauscher did not
disclose the riskiness of the pool's investments, which were highly
leveraged and subject to big losses if interest rates rose.
</P>
<P>
   Dain Rauscher, which is based in Los Angeles, strongly denied
all charges. ``We do not understand how the SEC can allege fraud in
these circumstances,'' the company said. It said it was not
involved with the investment pool. It also said it knew less about
the pool than the credit-rating agencies, which gave the pool their
highest ratings, and the SEC, which reviewed the pool at that time
and took no action.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the company said, all the investors who held the bonds
it underwrote were paid in full. Michael Missal, a lawyer for Dain
Rauscher, said it was common practice at the time not to disclose
that the proceeds of a bond offering were going to the investment
pool. But, he said, ``Every investor knew where they were going.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the two former Dain Rauscher employees, who were the
investment bankers in charge of many of the offerings in question,
also denied the charges. The former employees are Virginia Horler,
57, of Moraga, Calif., and Kenneth Ough, 45, of Post Falls, Idaho.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dain Rauscher was formed in January through the merger of Dain
Bosworth of Minneapolis and Rauscher Pierce Refsnes Inc. of Dallas.
It was Rauscher Pierce that was involved in the Orange County
underwritings.
</P>
<P>
   The action taken Monday was not a surprise. Rauscher Pierce
disclosed in a quarterly filing last year that it was a focus in a
federal enforcement action related to Orange County. But talks
aimed at a settlement broke down.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, the SEC in January accused Rauscher Pierce
of defrauding investors and the state of Arizona by engaging in
``yield burning,'' in which Treasury bonds are sold to state or
local governments at artificially high prices. The company denied
any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC also brought an administrative action against Ms.
Horler, the former Rauscher investment banker, charging inadequate
disclosure on bonds issued by Nevada County, Calif. Ms. Horler
denies those charges, according to Missal, the lawyer. Rauscher
Pierce is also being sued by Orange County.
</P>
</TEXT>
