<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES SWEEEPING CAMPAIGN-FINANCE REFORM BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Monday succeeded where the Senate has
repeatedly failed.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives approved sweeping campaign-finance reform that
would rein in the two most criticized tools of the election
business - ``soft'' money and third-party attack ads.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort to reform the money system of U.S. elections is
not expected to get through the upper house, where Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz. has been the chief sponsor of campaign-finance
reform legislation. McCain's bill was killed by a series of
procedural maneuvers in the Senate last February, and he said
Monday that the votes are still not there to break it loose.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain said in a statement issued after the vote, the
House action is a hopeful sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The vote) might change some votes in the Senate and persuade
a supermajority of senators that the time is finally at hand to
reform a campaign-finance system that a clear majority of Americans
believe is corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 237-186, the House approved a measure that would
ban soft money _ that is, contributions to political parties that
are then redistributed to candidates at the party's discretion
</P>
<P>
   The House measure also would impose restrictions on election
advertising by third parties and require random audits of
campaigns. It would require that campaign-finance information be
posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The strong majority vote for the proposal, which was sponsored
by Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Rep. Martin Meehan,
D-Mass., seems to guarantee that it will triumph over nine other
campaign-finance measures pending. House leaders decided to allow
whichever proposal had the most votes to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Those other measures will be debated this week, with the final
results expected before the House goes on a month-long break on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders strongly opposed the Shays-Meehan bill,
as did McCain's fellow Republicans in the Senate. On Monday, 51
Republicans defied those leaders to approve the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   None of those mavericks were in the Arizona delegation, however.
All five Republicans voted against the legislation. Rep. Ed Pastor,
the state's sole Democratic congressman, was the delegation's only
vote in favor.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Shadegg, R-Ariz., who handled campaign-finance matters
when he was an assistant state attorney, said the Shays-Meehan bill
has at least two strikes against it.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the bill likely will increase the cost of
campaigns, as restrictions passed in earlier years in Arizona did,
Shadegg said. For another, it impedes constitutionally guaranteed
free speech with its restrictions on third-party ``issues''
advertisements, more often called attack ads.
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg did manage to amend the bill. His change allows
complaints about election-law violations filed 90 days or less
before an election to go to federal district court, where judges
would be ordered to decide the issue quickly.
</P>
<P>
   As it now stands, there is no pre-election punishment for a
candidate who violates the law that close to an election. &QL; 
You can reach Adrianne Flynn at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
