<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO SEEK RELIEF FOR HOME-HEALTH AGENCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US Representative James P. McGovern is expected to unveil
Tuesday a compromise bill to grant financial relief to hundreds of
home-health care agencies that have bitterly complained about
cutbacks in Medicare reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, co-sponsored by US Representative Thomas Coburn
(R-Okla.), was quietly filed Friday and has gained support from
eight Republicans and 20 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, a Massachusetts Democrat, hopes his bill will blunt
the financial blow dealt to the home health care industry when
Congress last year rolled back Medicare reimbursement for
home-health care to 2 percent less than 1994 levels. The cuts were
passed as part of the Balanced Budget Act of 1997 in an attempt to
rein in fraud and spiraling health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Home-health care agencies in Massachusetts and senior advocates
say the cuts must be re-examined because of their tendency to
punish states that have tried to be efficient and maintain lower
costs. New England states spent an average of $4,400 in home-health
care for each patient in 1995, about $73 lower than the national
average that year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the cuts have forced some agencies out of business
and caused others to shun sicker patients with more expensive
needs.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern's bill proposes three changes in reimbursement:
</P>
<P>
   _Agencies would be paid based on an equal mix of the national
average and the regional average costs of providing care. Under
current law, agencies are paid based on each agency's historical
costs, plus some adjustment for geographic differences.
</P>
<P>
   _States would receive a combined $1 billion in temporary block
grants over four years to pay agencies that care for sicker,
high-cost patients. The amount would depend on each state's share
of Medicare patients and on its use of home health services.
Massachusetts would receive roughly $30 million over four years
under that formula.
</P>
<P>
   _Medicare reimbursement rates to agencies would be raised by 3
percent over current rates. Medicare currently pays agencies 105
percent of the agency's average cost of delivering services to
patients. The bill would raise that rate to 108 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
