<SLUG> BC-NY-MEN'S-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN'S WEAR JUST FOR THE FUN OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Kay Thompson, playing a character inspired by
Diana Vreeland in the movie ``Funny Face,'' declared, ``Think
pink!'' she certainly didn't have men in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it shows how far men's wear has come that designers
are now suggesting that their customers do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Meyer, John Bartlett, John Scher and, unexpectedly, Tommy
Hilfiger saved the New York spring 1999 shows from being a
lugubrious procession of mealy suits and shorts by injecting
colorful pants, fancifully printed shirts and a mix of jackets with
surfer jams. It turns out that the designers are not so far ahead
of the men they aspire to dress this time, for the shows presented
a meeting of street wear and high fashion that was not so much
revolutionary as realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett's whimsical but grounded show encapsulated the spirit
of the week. He cast lime-green hibiscus prints, a homage to Lilly
Pulitzer, in frolicky pants and sleeveless jackets, which he paired
with relaxed trousers of waxed cotton. Slipped over a pink polo
shirt bearing the designer's monogram _ he's becoming a name brand
_ was a hot-pink windbreaker and matching crisp trousers. His
jodhpurs were slimly tailored cotton trousers, which he showed
beneath crushed shirts, body-conscious ribbed sweaters or khaki
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Scher, although not as important a designer as Bartlett, lived
up to the all-but-forgotten promise of his first collections nearly
a decade ago. To see his concise, impressive line was like betting
on a sentimental favorite and watching that horse come in. Scher
showed navy-blue shirts with the full collars of a sailor's
uniform. Sailor pants invoked both the manliness and carefreeness
of sailors on shore leave. And a pink zip-front shirt jacket played
against the pale blue of rugged pants.
</P>
<P>
   The designers who consider themselves avant-garde are adding a
sparkle to men's wear, literally. Gene Meyer sprinkled sequins
across the midriff and in small circles on shirts and knit tops.
Meyer is in better control of his work than last season, when he
was oblivious to the perilously thin line between slouchy and
sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   Many men's wear designers are becoming more like their
counterparts in women's wear, in that they are the customers they
design for. Interestingly, when Meyer, Bartlett and Scher came out
to take their end-of-show bows, each dressed and carried himself
like one of the mannequins on his runway.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is more convincing in this role than the attractive,
reed-thin Sandy Dalal. On any given day, Dalal seems not so much
like a designer about to take over the world as a customer for his
young, eclectic vision of pistachio-green floral shirts and
matching skinny pants, or sleeveless, V-neck sweaters paired with
pants cropped at the ankle. Like Cynthia Rowley, Dalal is not
afraid of hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Rowley offered a sweet, affecting show,
complete with bright beach towels thrown over guest chairs. She
mixed buffalo-check trouser shorts with multicolor, diagonally
striped sweaters. Suits _ traditionally the most difficult aspect
of men's wear for new designers to tame _ have come along nicely in
Ms. Rowley's hands since her first outing last season. The
collection as a whole was less clownish, yet retained her whimsical
imprimatur.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the uninhibited joyfulness of collections like
Ms. Rowley's and Dalal's, Marc Jacobs struck a somber note, working
in a palette of white, khaki and mushroom gray. Still, Jacobs'
collection put him in the same casual camp as more joyful
contemporaries like Ms. Rowley. For the message among all the
seemingly effortless pairings of shirt and pants, sweater and jams,
by these designers, is that the yen for dressing up has vanished.
</P>
<P>
   What looks modern is ease. The suit has by no means breathed its
last, but as a defining element it has become the incredible
shrinking suit. As shorthand for success, the suit is a visual cue
from another era belonging to Ivan Boesky or Donald Trump. The
current cover of Fortune magazine boasts Mickey Drexler, the chief
executive of the Gap, in a white polo shirt. The previous issue
showed Bill Gates and Warren Buffet in the same uniform. To
consider this evolution is to understand Jacobs' offhand show of
lush cashmere T-shirts, camouflage pants and secretively detailed
trousers.
</P>
<P>
   Post-grunge would be a name for the change; tech fashion is
another _ clothes for the young barons of Silicon Valley and the
every-day-is-casual-Friday culture they have influenced.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, designers like Donna Karan, Ralph Lauren,
Joseph Abboud and the Hugo Boss company are still arguing for the
suitability of the suit. Ms. Karan introduced tailored suits for
the first time in her DKNY line. In her signature collection, she
layered ultraluxurious, lightweight fabrics in a jacket or a
sweater; the effect is not so evident in the look of the garment,
but in its feel. Her crinkled white suits and pants radiated ease.
And Ms. Karan has loosened her basic jacket by removing the
structured lining but retaining a sculptured shape with double
facing.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren certainly did not move the needle of men's wear by
inventing the shawl-collar sweater _ despite what his brother,
Jerry Lauren, suggested to a group of startled fashion editors last
week. But Lauren has been evolving on at least two fronts. He was
among the first to loosen up the rigid Savile Row-tailored suit.
Unquestionably more interesting is the designer's delving into
relaxed luxury in his top Purple Label line with opalescent fluid
pants, finely wrought white T-shirts and taupe suede jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren has inspired many a designer, and one who clearly aspires
to follow his footsteps is Maurice Malone. Malone had guests view
his collection as though at a museum show. With headsets attached
to a Walkman, the audience meandered through the presentation,
listening to a narrator. First came Malone's signature line of
sleek suits with multiple-flap pockets and contrasting shirts;
next, his underwear on models at a breakfast table, and finally,
his casual oversize jeans shorts and plaid shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult challenge for men's wear designers in this
moment of transition from businesslike to casual is closing the gap
between pink shirts and suits. The best in the business for now is
Hilfiger, who made as convincing a case as has ever been put on a
runway for a meeting between the sartorial, the athletic and the
romantic.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger is emerging a mature designer, with no need to
genuflect to Lauren. Blending street wear and tailored clothes
seems organic to Hilfiger. He showed great mixes of slim floral or
batik pants with sheer shirts; long athletic nylon shorts under a
tailored jacket and emblem shirt; aerodynamic-looking zippered
jackets and drop-crotch jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger has realized that he need look no further than his own
playground for respect, and for what's next.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2147EDT &QL; 
