<SLUG> BC-GOSMAN-RESIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOSMAN SAYS HE'LL RESIGN AS MEDITRUST CHAIRMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abraham Gosman, a wily and highly successful dealmaker, will
resign as chairman and chief executive of Meditrust Cos., &UR;  &LR; his main
investment vehicle, amid a sharp stock slide at the Needham, Mass.
company.
</P>
<P>
   Gosman, 69, said Monday he would be replaced on an interim basis
by Thomas Taylor, an investor with close ties to the Bass family.
The Basses were leading investors in La Quinta Inns, a chain that
was purchased by Meditrust in a $2.65 billion transaction that
closed last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for me to smell the roses,'' Gosman said. ``I was
not pushed out of the company. I could have stayed as long as I
wanted to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the Bass family could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gosman has made a fortune building, selling, and
sometimes repurchasing companies, he will step down at Meditrust at
a time when the real estate investment trust's stock has stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Meditrust shares closed at 22 9/16 Monday, down 42 percent from
a high of 39 in December. Analysts have blamed the performance on
this year's broad decline in real estate stocks and on a lukewarm
reaction to an aggressive plan expanding and reshaping Meditrust's
business.
</P>
<P>
   Meditrust, which had focused on health care-related real estate
holdings, paid $478 million in November to buy Santa Anita Cos., a
company that owned a famous horse track and special tax status.
Santa Anita was one of only four ``paired-share'' real estate
investment trusts, &UR;  &LR; or REITs, that could own property and operate
businesses on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   Most real estate investment trusts pay no federal income tax as
long as they pass most of their earnings on to shareholders every
year. But they are prohibited from operating a business, such as a
hotel, in buildings they own.
</P>
<P>
   Meditrust paid a steep premium, at least $200 million, for Santa
Anita's special tax status and quickly moved to buy other
properties that could make the most of it. Gosman began to build a
golf course business and then purchased La Quinta.
</P>
<P>
   The Bass family agreed to take Meditrust stock for their La
Quinta shares and became important investors in Gosman's company.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress moved to close the paired-share loophole this
spring, just months after Meditrust had paid dearly for the
advantage. Restrictions were included in the Internal Revenue
Service bill signed into law by President Clinton two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gosman, who owns about 2 million shares of Meditrust, said he
would keep all his stock. He agreed Monday that the Santa Anita
deal had hurt the company, but said the poor REIT stock market was
mostly responsible for the Meditrust slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not disappointed the Street,'' Gosman said of investor
expectations and Meditrust's operating performance. ``The company
is making its earnings and will pay dividends for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for someone else to take it to another level,'' he
said. ``I have done all the things I want to do with the company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
