<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   When a Company Offers You `Voluntary' Health Screening  
   
 By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
The staff at one Bay Area technology firm recently learned the new
meaning of ``voluntary'' participation in a company-sponsored
health survey.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A staffer _ who begged me not to name them or their firm _ sent
me a letter that invited workers to fill out confidential health
surveys with an independent research outfit.
</P>
<P>
   The company said this health data wouldn't become part of any
employee's file, and that the questions were only being asked to
give workers an outside assessment of their health risks.
</P>
<P>
   To get 100 percent participation in this health inquisition, the
company said all employees would have to pay $25 a month more for
their HMO coverage. But people who participated in the survey would
get a $25-a-month credit, leaving their HMO premiums unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Wohl, an employee benefits attorney with Orrick
Herrington &AMP; Sutcliffe in San Francisco, said he hadn't heard of
any such company-wide health survey before, but could imagine some
good and legal reasons why it was being done.
</P>
<P>
   The company could be trying to get a lower group rate by giving
potential insurers an aggregate look at the firm's health risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is that although they're presenting this as
voluntary, the raising and lowering of &UR;  &LR; the fees makes it
suspect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much a legal issue, as an employee relations
issue,'' he added. ``Why not just do it with the carrot instead of
with the stick?''
</P>
<P>
   This whole process sounded so Dilbert to me that I had to wonder
whether other tech firms have come up with the same bright idea of
putting their staffs through ``voluntary'' health screenings.
Please let me know.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Proud as a peacock? &LR;  NBC's multi-million stake in the Snap!,
the Internet directory, gave that C/Net spinoff a financial and
prestige boost.
</P>
<P>
   But the affiliation also puts the San Francisco-based service
under extra scrutiny, as was the case yesterday when Wired News
skewered Snap for quietly opening an adult directory _ the day
after NBC announced that it would promote Snap on network
television.
</P>
<P>
   Snap executive producer Katharine English said her staff began
reviewing sex sites months before NBC entered the picture, and that
the network had neither been consulted nor complained about Snap's
new, X-rated content.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  She said the decision to add porn to the directory, which
started July 21, was taken in recognition of the fact that 35 to 40
percent of Snap's daily queries are for ``adult content.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that level of interest, she said Snap felt it had to
address sex searches, but wanted to do so responsibly. When you
type ``sex'' into the Snap search line, the first page that comes
up lists several sex education sites, along with links to filtering
software parents can use to keep cyber-kids from the smut.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-core sites _ like Naked 4 U _ &UR;  &LR; start turning up on the
second of Snap's 25 page sex-listings.
</P>
<P>
   Infoseek, the other Web site with a network partner (Disney/ABC)
was the target of a separate smut barb in a recent edition of
TheStreet.Com. The on-line financial service got a ``no comment''
from Disney and Infoseek when it asked whether the search engine
would still accept ads from hard-core porn sites _ which are said
make up more than 5 percent of online ad revenues.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Split Personality? &LR;  I can't be the only person who thinks it
odd that Wired magazine, which considers itself the paragon of Web
culture, isn't allowed to put its own name on a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the state of affairs that exists three months after
publishing magnate S.I. Newhouse acquired Wired magazine. But the
sale did not include Wired's on-line properties, Wired News, the
HotWired how-to site, and the HotBot search engine &UR; , &LR;  which remain
under the control of Wired's founders Louis Rossetto and Jane
Metcalfe.
</P>
<P>
   What few outsiders understand about the sale agreement is that
it specifically prohibits Wired magazine from using the ``wired''
brand name on-line _ and Wired Digital isn't allowed to put the
valuable word on any broadcast or print property.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Wired _ be they print or digital _ cared to discuss
the irony of two corporations sharing one brand. Conde Nast,
Newhouse's magazine subsidary in New York, also declined to talk
about this delicate topic.
</P>
<P>
   But if you pumped the Wired building at 520 Third St. full of
sodium pentothol, someone would have to say what one insider told
me privately: ``This situation is untenable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
