</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NAZI-DEPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SEEKS TO EXPEL EX-SALESMAN ACCUSED OF ROLE IN NAZI KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Justice Department accused a 79-year-old retired
businessman Monday of lying about his past as a Nazi war criminal
to enter the United States more than 40 years ago, and asked a
federal judge in Manhattan to revoke his citizenship, the first
step to his deportation.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the man, Jack Reimer, a former potato chip salesman
and restaurateur, sharply criticized the government's evidence and
said that his client, who was born in Ukraine and came to the
United States in 1952, was a prisoner of war during World War II
who had never lied to the American authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But a Justice Department lawyer, Edward A. Stutman, told Judge
Lawrence M. McKenna that Reimer had been a skilled and highly
decorated commander at a Nazi SS training camp in Trawniki, Poland,
who participated in the mass execution of 50 to 60 Jews there, and
who led his men in missions to liquidate Jewish ghettos in Poland
between 1941 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government will show,'' Stutman said, ``that the Trawniki
training camp was in every respect imaginable a training ground for
persecution and murder, and the defendant was one of its first
teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the lawyers presented sharply contrasting accounts of his
past on the first day of his trial in federal district court,
Reimer sat impassively at the defense table, dressed casually in a
blue and gray sweater and sneakers, beside his lawyer, Ramsey
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a former attorney general in the Johnson administration,
suggested that the government had wildly exaggerated Reimer's
status in the SS, and he attacked both the accuracy and reliability
of the witnesses and historical documents Stutman said he would
introduce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government speaks as if the documents are overwhelmingly
clear on these subjects, and they are just the opposite,'' Clark
told McKenna, who is hearing the case without a jury.
</P>
<P>
   During a break in the proceedings before McKenna, Clark told
reporters that there would be no comment from his client, whom he
described as a friendly, cheerful and religious man. ``His feeling
as a religious person is that we are all tested and this is his
test,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized the Justice Department's decision to
prosecute Reimer after so long, saying, ``Perhaps they're running
out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Reimer's varying accounts of his role have long been an issue of
contention. The government has introduced a transcript of a 1992
interrogation in which he acknowledged, without a defense lawyer
present, that he shot at one man in the mass killing of 50 to 60
Jews near Trawniki, and agreed with a prosecutor's suggestion that
he had ``finished him off.''
</P>
<P>
   In court, Clark, who has sought to have that testimony
suppressed, told the judge that government lawyers interviewing
Reimer ``badgered him and badgered him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reimer gave a new account in a 1997 interview with government
investigators, saying that by the time he had arrived at the pit
where the Jews had been herded for execution, all appeared to be
already dead. Reimer said that he fired one shot, directing it away
so that it would not hit any of the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Stutman said that the government would present detailed evidence
_ including the statements of two of the Trawniki guards at the
scene _ to prove that Reimer was not only in command of other armed
Trawniki guards there but that he and the others all fired their
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer's new version, ``in which he changes the trajectory of
his bullet, does not diminish his personal role in this process of
persecution,'' Stutman added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
