<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Does Your Net Provider Eavesdrop?  
   
 By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
   Q: We live in a small town. I know my Internet service provider.
Can he easily ``eavesdrop'' on my Internet activities? Does he know
which Web sites I visit? Can he read my incoming and outgoing
e-mail?
<TEXT>
<P>
   A: Dear paranoid: Yes, he can. According to the Electronic
Privacy Information Center in Washington, D.C., it's not hard
technically for an ISP to track the Web wanderings of customers.
But EPIC Policy Director David Banisar said most ISPs _ even small
ones _ are unlikely to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average ISP probably isn't doing it just because it's
fairly burdensome,'' said EPIC policy director David Banisar. ``It
would take up a lot of space and slow down their systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have had Windows 98 since the day it was released and find
it to be absolutely no improvement over Windows 95. Actually, I
feel I was better off with Windows 95 and would like to uninstall
the 98 version. But after warnings from friends that I could lose
other needed items or create new problems by uninstalling, I am
really afraid to do it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Fear not. Uninstalling Windows 98 is a quick, painless
experience that restores your system to the way it was before you
upgraded. However, to remove the new system, you must have saved
the old one. If you selected the Save Your System Files during the
upgrade process, you're in business. Go to Start/Settings/Control
Panel and double-click Add/Remove Programs. Scroll down until you
get to the option for uninstalling Windows 98. Select it, and click
Add/Remove.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of other situations that prevent you from
uninstalling Windows 98. You can't do it if the operating system is
installed on a compressed hard disk. And if you converted your disk
to FAT32 after installing Windows 98, you're also out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I hate being on somebody's Buddy List in America Online. I
find the interruptions extremely annoying when people send me
instant messages. How can I stop receiving messages from my
so-called buddies?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's what to do: Use the keyword ``Buddy'' to go to the
Buddy List Setup box. Then click Privacy Preferences at the bottom.
Here you'll find a number of options letting you keep people from
adding you to their buddy lists. You can filter out just specific
users you don't want as buddies, or if you really feel anti-social,
you can block everybody. By the way, I agree with you, there's
nothing as irksome as getting an unsolicited greeting from someone
online.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm the only one who uses my computer, and I neither need nor
want a Windows password. So I'd love to get rid of that Password
box that always comes on the screen before Windows 95 boots up. Is
there any way to eliminate this minor but persistent irritant?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure. Here's how. First, delete the file that stores your
password. It has the same name as your user name, followed by the
extension .pwl. So if your user name is Jodie, the file will be
named Jodie.pwl. Go to Windows Explorer in the Windows Program
menu, and you'll find the .pwl file in the Windows folder.
Right-click it, and choose Delete from the pop-up menu.
</P>
<P>
   Now restart the computer. This time, when you see the Windows
Password dialog box, don't enter anything into the space for the
password. Just click OK. This will assign a blank password, and you
should not see the password prompt again.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I send a resume to a company by e-mail without having
to type it into the message itself? And how can I be sure they'll
be able to read it?
</P>
<P>
   A: What you want to do is send the resume as an attachment. All
e-mail programs let you attach files to e-mail messages. To make
sure the file is readable at the other end, the best thing is to
create it in Microsoft Word for Windows _ the word processor used
by the majority of companies.
</P>
<P>
   By sending the resume as an attached Word file, you can fire off
a resume that looks just like one you'd send in the mail or deliver
in person, complete with boldfacing, underlining, italics and
special margins.
</P>
<P>
   Tip of the Week &QC; 
PalmPilot users: Wouldn't it be great if you could see today's (and
even tomorrow's) appointments plus your To-Do list each time you
started your PalmPilot or Palm III? Well, you can with TealGlance,
a $12 shareware program from TealPoint Software. You can get it at
 &LR; www.pilotgear.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
