<HEADLINE>
CHARGES OF FRAUD IN MEXICAN GUBERNATORIAL BALLOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Deletes second graph, which stated that details of how the
PRD would challenge the vote are unknown, and adds new 6th graph
with information on how the PRD will challenge the election
results. No other changes.)  (js) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ On Monday, a day after voting in the southern
state of Oaxaca, the leftist Party of the Democratic Revolution
challenged preliminary returns that showed its candidate for
governor had come in second, saying the balloting was marred by
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 90 percent of the ballots counted Monday by
Oaxaca's State Electoral Institute, the official returns showed
that the candidate of President Ernesto Zedillo's governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, had received 48.5
percent of the votes. The Party of the Democratic Revolution, or
PRD, had 37.5 percent, and several other parties had a total of 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those official returns approximated the results of two exit
polls conducted on Sunday by Mexican television networks. The PRI
candidate, Sen. Jose Murat, claimed victory late Sunday and
celebrated with mariachi music in the central plaza of Oaxaca's
state capital.
</P>
<P>
   But Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, the PRD president, challenged
the PRI's victory claims. He cited a third exit poll, conducted by
the private Rosenblueth Foundation, which predicted on Sunday that
the PRD would defeat the PRI by 38.1 to 36.9 percent. He also said
the Oaxaca balloting had been marred by vote buying and
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say there was a free election in Oaxaca,'' Lopez
Obrador said. ``We don't accept the results.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his party would challenge the results before Mexico's
electoral tribunals. But he did not call for the type of popular
protests that the party has used in other cases to challenge
election results.
</P>
<P>
   Oaxaca's 3.2 million people speak a dozen indigenous languages
and are atomized into 570 townships, far more than any other
Mexican state. Many villages are in remote mountain passes or rain
forests with primitive communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinarily difficult to establish modern voting
methods in a state like Oaxaca,'' said Sergio Aguayo, a college
professor who has worked to prevent vote theft in many states.
``There are still wide margins there for electoral fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the official results' similarity with the networks'
exit polls bolstered their credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Ponce, who helped organize the Rosenblueth exit poll,
said his foundation had interviewed 25,000 Oaxaca voters, a broader
sample than that consulted by the two networks.
</P>
<P>
   But Roy Campos Esquerra, who organized the Televisa network's
exit poll, said, ``I'd put my hands in the fire for our results.
They were very well done.''
</P>
<P>
   In other elections Sunday, the PRI won the governorship of the
Gulf Coast state of Veracruz, and the National Action Party won in
the central state of Aguascalientes, where the PRI had never
previously lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
