<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Ascend Seals Deal For Stratus  
   
 By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Ascend Communications made a bid yesterday in the high-stakes poker
game to help create the next-generation network that will carry
both voice and data communications.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shrugging off Wall Street's skepticism, the Alameda company made
its second cross-country acquisition, with an $822 million
stock-swap deal for Stratus Computer, a Marlboro, Mass., maker of
telephone switching systems.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend, which manufactures networking equipment used by
telephone companies and Internet service providers, said the merger
will accelerate its move to create a combined voice-data network.
</P>
<P>
   Observers predict that such a network could cut costs for
telephone chatters, Internet surfers and users of demanding
applications such as video-conferencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transaction opens up a $10 billion new market opportunity
for Ascend's products now served almost exclusively by traditional
telecom-equipment suppliers,'' said Mory Ejabat, Ascend president
and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was considerably less enthusiastic when rumors
surfaced about the deal last week. On Friday, Ascend's shares
plunged $7, or nearly 14 percent, to close at $44.47, largely
because of fears that the acquisition could slow down Ascend's
strong growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market said the same thing when we acquired Cascade last
year,'' Ejabat said yesterday. Ascend's shares plunged 22 percent
in one day on news of its 1997 deal to buy Cascade Communications,
which makes networking equipment. But the deal turned out to be a
winner, accounting for some major contracts this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Ascend's shares rose $2.34, more than 5 percent, to
$46.81. It was the most active U.S. stock, with volume of 20.4
million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Stratus' shares jumped $4.75 yesterday to close at $33.63.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend itself has been considered an attractive takeover
candidate, possibly by telecom equipment vendors like Lucent of New
Jersey or Ericsson of Sweden. Rumors of Ascend being acquired were
heightened by the merger in June of telecommunications giant
Northern Telecom and Bay Networks, a Santa Clara data networking
company.
</P>
<P>
   That deal also was designed to provide the technology to create
a combined voice-data network _ considered essential to compete in
the telecommunications business, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, there was talk of data-voice convergence.
Now, the rubber is hitting the road here,'' said John Armstrong, an
analyst with Dataquest in San Jose. ``Either you keep up with the
pack or you're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Having someone like Stratus or someone else who knows
telecommunications is the opening bid'' in the game,'' said Michael
King, an analyst with Meta Group in Burlingame.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts questioned whether Stratus was the right choice
for Ascend. The Massachusetts company has been struggling with weak
demand in Asia. Last month, it said it will cut 350 jobs, or 15
percent of its workforce, and it reported a second-quarter loss and
a 20 percent drop in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend said it will sell off all of Stratus' businesses that
don't have to do with telecommunications, including its
financial-services software business. It plans to absorb only about
400 Stratus employees.
</P>
<P>
   Ejabat said he expects the Stratus purchase to boost Ascend's
earnings in 1999 to $1.70 a share next year on combined revenue of
$2.3 billion. Analysts expected $1.60 a share, according to First
Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the transaction, expected to close in the fall, each share of
Stratus will be exchanged for .75 shares of Ascend, based on
Ascend's closing price last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend will take charges of $300 million to $350 million for
research and development and $80 million to $100 million for
acquisition expenses in the fourth quarter related to the purchase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
