<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   `Cybercards' Are Long on Action But Longer on Downloading  
   
 By Amy Doan  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
A new batch of trading cards hit the market this year, but they are
a far cry from the cardboard kind that come attached to a pack of
bubble gum.
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't store them in a shoe box, either.
</P>
<P>
   Complete with sound, full-motion graphics and multiple pull-down
stats windows, these are digital trading cards _ computer files you
download from the Web _ from New York-based CyberAction.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech collectibles actually are multimedia applications,
ranging in size from 200 to 800 kilobytes, that can only be viewed
with the company's free CyberViewer program. They cost $3.95 per
four-card set.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the cards struck CyberAction founder Marty Marion
in the middle of a plane flight to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting across the aisle from this 7-year-old kid, and
he was playing with his Supermonster trading card as if it was real
_ making growling noises and pretending the card was flying,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just got me thinking how much you could do with sound and
video to make trading cards more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is something that Marion has dubbed ``cybercards.''
</P>
<P>
   CyberAction has struck a wide range of image-licensing deals, so
there already are dozens of cybercards. You can collect digital
cards for Major League Baseball players like Ken Griffey Jr. and
Mark McGwire, and for Major League Soccer stars including Carlos
Valderrama. There's even a set for Xena: Warrior Princess and her
one-time rival Hercules.
</P>
<P>
   Sets featuring NFL players and Star Trek characters will be
available later this year, according to Marion.
</P>
<P>
   CyberAction has been selling about four or five sets of cards a
day since their January launch, Marion said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the cards can be downloaded from  &LR; www.cybercards.com.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The required site registration, which includes a name, e-mail
address, ZIP code and gender, is fairly straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the download process is not.
</P>
<P>
   The company is trying to make the cybercards difficult to copy,
resulting in a very tedious download process.
</P>
<P>
   Every time you buy a new cybercard, you also have to download a
``key file,'' which lets only a user who knows your password and is
working on your computer open the card.
</P>
<P>
   You also have to download, and then execute, an application to
install each card on your system. If you don't have Apple QuickTime
2.12 on your system, you have to download that. Finally, you have
to install an ``update key'' file every time you subsequently view
the card.
</P>
<P>
   So even armed with a Chronicle computer systems manager and a
corporate T-1 line, the download process for a single card took
this reporter almost an hour _ considerably longer than
CyberAction's estimate that downloading one card should take about
10 to 15 minutes with a 28.8 Kbps modem.
</P>
<P>
   The company currently is working to simplify the process so that
the key file downloads automatically, according to a spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Once the cards and their accompanying files finally were
downloaded, the four sampled by The Chronicle were impressive. All
had good-quality, well-selected graphics.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Xena: Warrior Princess card features a
20-second clip from the show in which the heroine kickboxes and
fences her way through a group of marauders on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   The Don Mattingly card shows Mattingly swinging away in
slow-motion, accompanied by real crowd sounds and an announcer
shouting, ``In '87, the records fell ... a homer in eight-straight
games and six grand slams on the season.''
</P>
<P>
   When you click on the lower right-hand corner of any of the
cards, it flips over and you can choose from menus like ``lifetime
statistics,'' ``trivia game'' or, for Xena, ``legend'' and
``lore.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why the products would be especially appealing
to kids, a fact which might concern some parents, given how simple
it is to buy them (if not download them) off the site. You don't
need to enter a credit card, just a phone number.
</P>
<P>
   The site does have a prominent message that flashes, ``Hey
Kids,'' then tells them to get their parents' permission before
buying anything.
</P>
<P>
   It also directs the young collectors to a form letter they can
print and give to their parents to help their cause.
</P>
<P>
   (It starts out ``To the World's Greatest Parent'' and ends with
a list of potential bribes like ``being nice to my brother/sister''
and ``cleaning the kitty-litter tray.'')
</P>
<P>
   Although nobody can download more than two sets of cards a week
using just a phone number, a kid could rack up a pretty high phone
bill ($32 a month) before the extra charges attracted adult
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Marion's response: ``That's better than an extra $1,000.''
</P>
<P>
   To give kids a more honest way to get the cards, Marion is
setting up a program that would let parents prepay for a kids'
``card allowance'' on a credit card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
