u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATSKILLS-DANCE-HOST-     08-03 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATSKILLS-DANCE-HOST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE LADIES FEEL LIKE GINGER ROGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The problem with what Victor Aviles does is that when
people hear about it they think one word: gigolo. This may be
because of the tender circumstances. You hold a woman in your arms
_ a succession of women, actually; Aviles estimates in the hundreds
_ and with the moon and the music people assume what they consider
to be the inevitable, while in truth, doing the inevitable will get
you put off the ship at the next port. (In the Catskills, one
hears, they are more understanding.)
</P>
<P>
   Aviles is a dance host.
</P>
<P>
   And while Aviles has had women put room keys and phone numbers
and cash into the pockets of his white dinner jacket, he sees his
job as taking care of the ladies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to love it,'' Aviles says. ``You can be taking on an
impossible task. There were 50 single ladies on my cruise and two
single guys _ of course those two guys had a wonderful time _ and
six dance hosts, and I believe all the ladies left that cruise
saying, `Wow, I had a great time with these guys!' I'm not saying I
took this on by myself, but if I had to, I would have. There are so
many beautiful ladies you can spend time with, no problem. But what
about the others? If you don't like that, it's going to be a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Aviles saying he could have done more? Should have done more?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never say I could have done more,'' Aviles says. ``I say I
did a lot more than I thought I could do. On a cruise you start at
5 o'clock cocktail parties, then we go until midnight. On dance
weekends in the Catskills, the only meal you don't dance through is
breakfast. I have the piece of chicken next to my mouth, a lady
comes over and says, `Vic, dance the mambo with me.' I'm thinking:
`Lady, give me a break. At least let me swallow the chicken.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If life were fair, there would be sufficient men to dance with
the ladies when they went on expensive vacations, but as it is not,
there are dance hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Aviles, age 53, a former New York City police detective.
Aviles spends his summer as the recreation director and dance host
at Sunny Oakes hotel in the Catskills; last April, Aviles worked as
a dance host on the liner Rotterdam, from New York to Lisbon. For
this, Aviles receives a free cruise, but he has to pay $25 a day to
the agency that books him.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise ships have rules. Hosts must be single. ( Aviles is
divorced.) Hosts must sign an agreement not to have a romantic
relationship with the guests. It is doubtful this agreement is
always honored _ hosts average four cruises before quitting, Aviles
says, either because they cannot take having to be continuously
``on'' or because they find someone.
</P>
<P>
   Aviles, who admits to having dated women he met while working in
the Catskills, has not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of women have tried to buy him, offered him trips,
offered him apartments, but he can't be bought,'' says Evelyn
Meier, who has taught and danced with Aviles for 12 years. ``He's
always got a girlfriend, sometimes two, but he's not a player in
that sense. For him, it's about something else. He always watches
to see who isn't dancing. I've seen him dance with women who have
never danced in their lives, who are shy or pudgy. He takes them
out on the floor and presents them and for one moment, they're
Ginger Rogers.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes a dance host? Aviles, who grew up in East Harlem,
credits a movie _ and the Police Department. It is possible that
being responsible for his mother also contributed. Aviles' father
was absent. Aviles worked from the time he was 10. He also joined a
gang. At 15, Aviles says, he saw ``West Side Story'' being filmed
in his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sharks and the Jets,'' Aviles says. ``They're dancing and
snapping their fingers. I remember walking down the street trying
to copy it. Unfortunately, dancing was something tough guys do not
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Aviles married and joined the police department. After five
years on the force, he was tapped by internal affairs to get close
to two policemen. The officers were taking dance lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first dance was the tango,'' Aviles says. ``They give me
this beautiful dance instructor. She says, `Vic, this dance is all
in the body _ we have to have close, close contact.' I'm thinking,
`Where have I been?' ''
</P>
<P>
   After 21 years on the force, Aviles retired. Determined that his
next career would be ``totally nonviolent,'' Aviles spent 12 years
as a massage therapist. Four years ago, Ms. Meier said, Aviles was
approached by agents for the cruise lines to be a dance host. He
declined because his mother was ill. Last year, after his mother
died, Aviles took his first cruise job. He lives in a modest,
rent-controlled apartment on the Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Aviles enjoy more, dancing or making the ladies
happy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a combination, but if I had to choose, I would
say making the ladies happy,'' Aviles says. ``To make her feel and
look as if she is more beautiful than she is, a better dancer than
she is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if I'm a drug and I'm giving them this high. A woman
is sitting there with a frown on her face like the heavens have
fallen and I just extend my hand and say, `May I have this dance?'
and I bring her on to the dance floor, she's smiling, it's like a
miracle. I think, `Wow, that's unbelievable I can do this.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
