<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GRENADA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WELCOME TO GRENADA, CASTRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 4:
</P>
<P>
   A dictator who rules a country as long as Fidel Castro has
governed Cuba sometimes gets to edit the history he helped create.
Castro did just that over the weekend when he visited Grenada, the
tiny Caribbean island the United States invaded almost 15 years ago
in the name of preventing Cuban contamination in the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Castro clearly savored the irony of his warm official greeting
by the democratically elected government of Prime Minister Keith
Mitchell. He was welcomed with steel bands, a 21-gun salute and an
official thank-you for Cuba's help in building the airport that
Washington once viewed as a dangerous extension of Cuba's military
reach into the eastern Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban leader also got positive welcomes in Jamaica and
Barbados, the first two stops in his tour of the English-speaking
Caribbean. Six of the area's prime ministers have visited Havana in
the past year and a half, and many of them are now pressing for
Cuba's admission to the 16-nation Caribbean Community, a regional
trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Further straining American ties with the Caribbean is a 90
percent drop in U.S. aid for the region between 1985 and 1995. Cuba
has been quick to move into the breach with modest but appreciated
programs of medical and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Congress continues to treat Cuba as though the Cold
War had not ended. The Helms-Burton law of 1996, even though the
Clinton administration has been able to waive some of its most
noxious provisions, denies the White House needed flexibility to
modify America's 36-year-old economic embargo against Cuba to take
account of changing circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   That embargo has failed to shake Castro's hold on power and
hurts ordinary Cubans. It also runs counter to a theme of American
foreign policy today, namely that increased trade and investment
can be a useful mechanism for encouraging democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   Despite harsh persecution by the Castro dictatorship, democrats
within Cuba are pressing to expand the narrow legal boundaries of
permitted political expression. The United States should reinforce
their efforts to open up Cuban society by increasing its own
official and unofficial contacts with the Cuban people. Isolation
does not work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
