<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIELBERG SHOOTS ERNIE'S WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A long, slow tracking shot in the movie ``Saving Private Ryan''
shows Omaha Beach in the aftermath of the D-Day invasion. It's a
picture of horror and waste and sacrifice, painted in heartbreaking
detail. If you've read the dispatches of Ernie Pyle, you know what
it looked like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong, swirling tides of the Normandy coast line shifted
the contours of the sandy beach as they moved in and out,'' he
wrote. ``They carried soldiers' bodies out to sea, and later they
returned them. They covered corpses of heroes with sand, and then
in their whims they uncovered them.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . .There in a jumbled row for mile on mile were soldiers'
packs. There were socks and shoe polish, sewing kits, diaries,
Bibles, hand grenades. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``There were toothbrushes and razors, and snapshots of families
back home staring up at you from the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . .As I plowed out over the wet sand, I walked around what
seemed to be a couple of pieces of driftwood sticking out of the
sand. But they weren't driftwood. They were a soldier's two feet.
He was completely covered except for his feet; the toes of his GI
shoes pointed toward the land he had come so far to see, and which
he saw so briefly.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg's film is as good as the critics say it is, but
it's not the first time World War II has been presented honestly.
Pyle did that.
</P>
<P>
   He did it for millions of readers, six days a week, year after
year, in Africa and Europe and the Pacific. He did it by
transforming the charts and graphs of war into a map of the human
heart.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Capt. Miller, played by Tom Hanks in ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' could be Capt. Henry T. Waskow from Pyle's most
famous column. The fictional Sgt. Horvath, played by Tom Sizemore,
could be Sgt. Frank ``Buck'' Eversole, about whom Pyle wrote, ``The
years roll over him and the war becomes his only world, and battle
his only profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The other characters in the movie _ Ryan and the soldiers sent
to save him _ are all there in Pyle's columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't warriors,'' he wrote. ``They were American boys
who by mere chance of fate had wound up with guns in their hands,
sneaking up a death-laden street in a strange and shattered city in
a faraway country in a driving rain. They were afraid, but it was
beyond their power to quit. They had no choice. They were good
boys.''
</P>
<P>
   A scene very much like that is in Spielberg's movie. The
difference being, Pyle's soldiers was real.
</P>
<P>
   And they were ``good boys,'' too, but not perfect ones.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote once, ``They had been fighting and moving constantly
forward on foot for nearly three weeks without rest _ sleeping out
on the ground, wet most of the time, always tense, eating cold
rations, seeing their friends die. One of them came up to me and
said, almost belligerently, `Why don't you tell the folks back home
what this is like? All they hear about is victories and a lot of
glory stuff. They don't know that for every hundred yards we
advance somebody gets killed. Why don't you tell them how tough
this life is?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Pyle did. Steven Spielberg did, too, though with a lot
more gore than Pyle included in his columns, partly because it
wouldn't have made it past military censors and partly because he
didn't need it. His message got through.
</P>
<P>
   Pyle was killed by Japanese machine gun fire Apr. 18, 1945, on a
Pacific island called Ie Shima. He left behind books like ``Here Is
Your War'' and ``Brave'' ``Men.'' I found my father's generation in
them. I know how lucky I am. There's also a fine biography called
``Ernie Pyle's War'' by James Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   Among the personal papers discoved after Pyle's death were notes
for an unfinished column about V-E Day. He writes that ``in the
joyousness of high spirits it is easy for us to forget the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   A movie like ``Saving Private Ryan'' may help some people to
remember. But it's not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Not as long as there's a library in town. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
