<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN'S MISSION IS A HOME ON GIANTS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gary Brown walked alone through the campus at the
Giants' training camp, still feeling his way around at SUNY-Albany
and feeling his way around the third franchise he has found himself
with in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be unfair to term Brown a journeyman just by
looking at the stops he has made in his career, not after he rushed
for 1,002 yards and an American Football Conference-best 5.1 yards
per carry with the Houston Oilers in 1993, and not after he
accumulated 945 yards on the ground for the San Diego Chargers last
season. But even Brown is unsure just how a player like himself has
been unable to find a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, because you see guys who have had success and they
seem to stay with the same team for years,'' Brown said after the
morning session Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that wasn't my thing, so I just have to go out and make
the best of my situation. Hopefully, I can play well again this
year. I look forward to playing well this year, and then maybe I
can play here for a couple more years and maybe even retire here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants would be pleased to see the 29-year-old running back
find a home. They signed him to a one-year, $400,000 contract as an
unrestricted free agent on April 21 after making their way through
the draft without finding a running back. With Rodney Hampton set
free, Brown could become the primary running back with his strength
and skills running between the tackles.
</P>
<P>
   A Cinderella story like Brown's never would make the silver
screen. There are too many twists and turns and disappointments
scattered throughout the story.
</P>
<P>
   An eighth-round draft pick out of Penn State in 1991, he carried
the ball just 27 times in his first two seasons and had only 16
carries in the first eight games in 1993. Then an injury to another
player provided him with his first start, and Brown responded with
166 yards rushing, earning AFC offensive player of the week honors.
</P>
<P>
   He followed that up with a 194-yard performance the next week
and AFC offensive player of the month honors.
</P>
<P>
   But his production slid to 648 yards rushing in 1994 and 293 the
following year. Overweight, overconfident and undermotivated, he
was waived by the Oilers on April 19, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than growing inspired by the turn of events, Brown sat
home and sulked, ballooning to nearly 40 pounds over his playing
weight of 225. When the 1996 season began, Brown was at home in
Williamsport, Pa. He remained there in a funk all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat around the house,'' Brown said. ``I took the wrong
attitude. I blamed the Oilers. I'd sit around watching TV and
eating. Finally, I was watching the AFC playoff games and I
realized I wanted to be back there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered sometimes if I would be back. But once you decide
you're going to play, you have to have total confidence. When you
decide you're going to go back, you have to change your whole life
style completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do this, can't eat that. I couldn't hang out
anymore. So my whole life style had to change. If I hadn't done
that, I wouldn't have been able to make it back. Once I decided I
was going to do it, I had no doubt I was going to make it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown made it back, signing with the Chargers and turning in
another successful season. But in the final game of the season, one
that Brown does not enjoy talking about, he was kept on the bench
against his wishes, falling short of the 1,000-yard plateau and a
$200,000 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   When the Chargers re-signed his predecessor there, Natrone
Means, Brown realized his days were numbered there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The San Diego thing is something I had no control over,''
Brown said. ``Those things happen. I wanted to go for a thousand.
But it's in the past. I don't want to talk about it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brown opted to accept the Giants' offer, placing opportunity
ahead of money, believing that he could earn playing time in a
backfield already crowded with Tiki Barber, Tyrone Wheatley and
Charles Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I proved myself,'' Brown said. ``I think at this
point, I wanted to be in a good situation where I can go out and
just continue to do the things I can do. I took a lot less money
than I could have had somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that is better for me. It's a situation where I
have to prove myself and a situation where I can go out and play
well and contribute. You feel a little uncomfortable being here at
first. But the guys help and I'm feeling really good with how I'm
playing. I want to learn. If I just go out and play hard and do the
things I do, that's the only thing I can control.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
