u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COP-SHOT-535&AMP;ADD-N     08-03 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COP-SHOT-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORHOOD THAT HE TENDED SAYS FAREWELL TO SLAIN OFFICER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While dignitaries, friends and family members
gathered behind the closed doors of the First Central Baptist
Church on Monday to mourn the death of Police Officer Gerard
Carter, a small group of children formed a tight circle outside the
Staten Island church and bowed their heads in silent prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in T-shirts and shorts, they were not nearly as orderly
or solemn as the thousands of uniformed officers who lined Wright
Street six and eight deep as far as the eye could see. But their
grief was in some ways more tangible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how to play baseball before I met him,'' said
Cortne Daniels, 10, a member of the Stapleton-Parkhill housing
police unit softball team, part of a league to which Carter
dedicated a great deal of his spare time. ``I'm going to remember
how he was a good coach and how he never lost his temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, 28, died early Friday, four days after he had been shot
by a local youth, police say, while patrolling the same streets he
had grown up on. While it is common these days for New York City
police officers to go home to the suburbs after pounding a beat,
Carter chose to stay in his old neighborhood, and colleagues and
fellow Staten Islanders said his love and knowledge of his home
turf showed in his work.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dr. Calvin Rice, pastor of the First Central Baptist
Church, recalled the times he gazed across the street into the
Carters' backyard and watched as Gerard Carter grew from a
6-year-old learning how to ride a bicycle into a strapping
teen-ager playing football for the Port Richmond High School Red
Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then it was like it happened overnight _ and he started
watching over me,'' said Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said Carter had chosen to become a police officer in part
because his father, Gaston, had been an officer for 23 years, but
also because ``he realized that the city needed a cop with heart, a
cop with feeling and emotion for the people he served.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew him wept to think that a man who worked
tirelessly to teach good citizenship to children from the projects
would die at the hands of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We honor him as a true hero because he was always doing and
giving more than what was expected,'' Police Commissioner Howard
Safir said. ``The brutal violence of one man cannot take away from
his legacy. And not far from here there are children who will grow
up to be better people because of the example left by one man,
Officer Gerry Carter.''
</P>
<P>
   It was while patrolling the West Brighton Houses on the night of
July 26 that Carter and his partner approached a teen-ager, Shatiek
Johnson, 17, who they believed was wanted for murder. According to
police, Johnson drew a gun and shot Carter through the windshield
of his patrol van. He was the third New York City police officer
killed in the line of duty this year.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors plan to file a second-degree murder charge against
Johnson, who was paroled in April after serving two years of a
three-year manslaughter sentence for beating a homeless man to
death when he was 15. Johnson also faces second-degree murder
charges in the July 16 shooting death of another man on Staten
Island.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Police Officer Larry Olinsky, a member of the Staten Island
housing unit, touched the mourners when he tearfully addressed
Carter's 6-year-old son, Louis. ``I know you can't understand this
now,'' he said. ``But your father was a hero. And all those
superheroes that I know you like to play with, even if you put them
all together, they would be nothing compared to what your father
meant to all the people in this room.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that while Carter had been on the
police force for only five years, he had accomplished more than
some officers can hope to in a 20-year career. In his time on the
police force, Carter was responsible for 76 arrests, received two
commendations and was named outstanding officer of the year by the
Staten Island Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, Lydia Roman, a family friend, said that she
appreciated Giuliani's call to overhaul the state's parole system
to keep felons like Johnson in prison for as long as possible but
that much more needed to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more of what Gerard was doing, working with them when
they're young,'' she said. ``And we need more officers like him
stationed in their own neighborhoods. He knew the streets, he knew
the problems and he was trying to make a difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
