<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      08-03 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES: WHO DESIGNED THAT DRESS?  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to correct dateline)   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mystery has emerged in fashion, where millions of
dollars are spent on publicity and no buzz-generating moment goes
unclaimed. Why has no designer come forward to take credit for that
dress? Yes, the one belonging to Monica Lewinsky and undergoing
tests at an FBI laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine has reported that it was a Gap dress, but a Gap
spokeswoman said Monday she could not confirm it. Experts in public
relations differed on whether the designer should come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Weisenfeld, the vice president for public relations at
Barneys New York and a former aide to Ann Stock, formerly Hillary
Rodham Clinton's social secretary, said: ``Monica is the epitome of
the bridge customer, and I can't believe a bridge designer hasn't
jumped forward to claim it for their own. What are they waiting
for?''
</P>
<P>
   But Pierre Rougier, the owner of Pierre Rougier Public Relations
Consultants, whose clients include Hermes, Narciso Rodriguez and
Richard Edwards, said: ``I would say, `Keep quiet.' If I'm a
designer, I don't want to go down as the designer who designed the
stained dress. There's something yucky about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Treifus, the senior vice president for global
communications at Calvin Klein Inc., says the industrywide silence
is easily explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't you know that all the fashion houses have received
talking points?'' he said. ``We're not quite sure of the source of
the talking points _ whether they are direct from Monica Lewinsky
or from some other source _ but the first of these talking points
is, `Don't admit anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   A SUCCESSOR AT TOCCA
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tocca, the company whose lines were created and
designed by Marie-Anne Oudejans, who abruptly left it three months
ago, has hired Alexandra White, a stylist and contributing editor
at W magazine and Italian Vogue, as its creative director.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oudejans, who has not publicly discussed in detail her
reasons for leaving Tocca, did not have a role in selecting Ms.
White, though she remains a partner in the business, said Edoardo
Mantelli, the chairman of Tocca. Ms. Oudejans could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for a creative director, not a designer,''
Mantelli said. ``Tocca is a concept. It has a lot to do with our
vision. We want someone who can help us strengthen our business and
expand globally.''
</P>
<P>
   Stylists have come to exert a visible and important role in
fashion, helping to shape designers' collections. Prominent
stylists include Melanie Ward, who works with Helmut Lang; Carine
Roitfeld for Gucci, and Victoria Bartlett for Versace.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is rare for a stylist to head a design company. Ms.
Oudejans, herself, was an exception. Once a stylist, she came to
see her fashions for Tocca sold in stores like Bergdorf Goodman and
Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   CONTROLLING NOVA'S CROWD
</P>
<P>
   NEWS YORK _ It's not every fashion show that draws the police.
But that is who showed up at the presentation for Nova by Tony
Mellilo on Thursday night at the close of the men's shows for
spring 1999. They arrived when a crowd of pedestrians joined
fashion editors and retailers blocking the street outside the
unusual show.
</P>
<P>
   The passers-by stopped and stared through glass windows into an
empty store at 100 Stanton St., part of which was decorated like a
bedroom. Inside, a lone model dressed and undressed in the line's
25-or-so soft knit sportswear pieces. The space is the site of a
Nova USA store scheduled to open this month.
</P>
<P>
   Kal Ruttenstein, the corporate fashion director of
Bloomingdale's, and Holly Adam, the fashion director for men's wear
at Bloomingdale's, cooled themselves on a bench outside the store.
Ruttenstein has ordered the collection for his store.
</P>
<P>
   The police asked Mellilo to clear a path on the sidewalk. One
confused guest spread the word _ wrongly, it turned out _ that
Mellilo was being shut down for operating without a cabaret
license.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
