<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6176 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     08-03 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-1STLDWRITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CONTINUES FIGHT TO BLOCK LINDSEY TESTIMONY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to include latest developements from court of appeals) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House announced plans Monday to continue
efforts to block prosecutors from questioning President Clinton's
longtime confidant Bruce Lindsey about an alleged presidential
affair and cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   As aides brushed aside talk of a nationally televised mea culpa
by the president, his lawyers scrambled to buy enough time for the
Supreme Court to consider whether the attorney-client privilege
shields Lindsey, a deputy White House counsel, from questions about
his conversations with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia turned down an effort by the White House to keep Lindsey
from being summoned before independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
grand jury until the nation's high court decides whether to get
involved in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers immediately asked Chief Justice William
Rehnquist to issue a stay that would block Lindsey's appearance
before the grand jury until the court rules on the substance of the
administration's appeal. Rehnquist, who last month denied a similar
motion regarding testimony from Secret Service agents, could rule
on the motion for a stay or turn it over to the full court.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, a three-judge appeals panel of the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit rejected the White
House argument that Lindsey was shielded from testifying. The panel
upheld a lower court order for Lindsey to answer prosecutors'
questions about the president's relationship with former intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey, whose friendship with the president dates back to the
beginning of his political career in Arkansas 30 years ago, has
unmatched knowledge of Clinton's activities in Little Rock and
Washington. Among Lindsey's assignments is defending Clinton
against allegations involving women.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff issued a statement Monday
saying that a review by the Supreme Court is needed ```because of
the importance of this principle for this and future presidents, as
well as the executive branch'' of government.
</P>
<P>
   If the courts agree, Lindsey's testimony would be postponed at
least until the Supreme Court begins its next term in October.
</P>
<P>
   The justices previously refused to consider an appeal of a
similar ruling from the St. Louis-based 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, which held that government lawyers cannot hide behind the
attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, special White House counsel Lanny Breuer was prepared
to appear at the federal courthouse Tuesday after efforts to block
a subpoena for his testimony was turned down by the courts. Breuer,
a New York lawyer who joined the White House staff in early 1997,
heads the team of attorneys overseeing various scandals involving
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who was appointed four years ago to investigate Clinton's
business dealings in Arkansas, broadened his inquiry in January to
include whether the president lied under oath and urged others to
lie in Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit against him.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Clinton testified that he did not have sexual
relations with Lewinsky. The former White House intern issued a
similar denial under oath, but last week reportedly reversed course
and told Starr's deputies _ after she was promised immunity from
prosecution _ that they did engage in sexual activities.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the president has agreed to testify Aug. 17 via
closed-circuit television before Starr's grand jury, which puts him
a position of recanting his earlier denial or contradicting
Lewinsky's most recent description of their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, presidential aides dismissed talk of Clinton
changing his story, insisting such discussion implies that Clinton
lied under oath early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically whether Clinton would continue to maintain
that he had no sexual relationship with Lewinsky, White House
spokesman Barry Toiv told reporters that the president ``told you
that he is going to testify truthfully . . . he's already spoken to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed about whether Clinton's version is the truth, Toiv
replied that he is ``not in a position to tell you what the
president's testimony is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can tell you is that he has said that he has
told the truth, and that he will continue to tell the truth,'' the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Starr's prosecutors interviewed Lewinsky in
preparation for her appearance _ possibly late this week _ before
the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the FBI is expected in the next week to determine
whether a stain found on a blue cocktail dress turned over to Starr
by Lewinsky contains DNA material indicating any sexual contact
with the president. Lewinsky told prosecutors she wore the dress
during a sexual encounter with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's press briefing, Toiv was repeatedly hit with
questions about whether the president has provided investigators
with DNA samples to compare with any material found on the dress or
whether Starr had requested DNA samples from the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I'm aware of,`` Toiv said, referring questions to
Clinton's private attorney, David Kendall, who did not respond to
telephone inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the U.S. Court of Appeals issued a
sealed ruling Monday that reportedly permits U.S. District Judge
Norma Holloway Johnson to proceed with a hearing to determine if
Starr improperly leaked grand jury evidence, which is prohibited by
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Unnamed sources cited by The Associated Press and CNN said the
ruling addressed Starr's concerns that evidence crucial to his
investigation of the president might be obtained by Clinton's
private lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The legal sources said the court ruled the leaks investigation
could proceed but that any evidence should be turned over to
Johnson, who is overseeing the grand jury investigating the
Clinton-Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall has accused Starr of illegal leaks and requested that
the prosecutor be sanctioned for contempt of court. Starr`s office
has denied releasing any information improperly. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-98 2214EDT &QL; 
