<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM announces plans to privitize Dayton plant
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton will no longer be a GM town heading into
the next century.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. on Monday said it will turn its Delphi
Automotive Systems unit into an independent company by next year _
a move that will leave the Miami Valley with only one factory
solely operating under the world's largest automaker.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi , currently a division of GM, employs 15,000 workers in
seven Dayton-area plants. While they will no longer work directly
for GM, th os e workers could emerge from the deal with a brighter
future.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive experts believe an independent Delphi could mean more
business for local plants that supply parts to most of the world's
automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, the company will offer up to 20 percent of
Delphi in a public stock offering, then turn over the remaining
part of the company to GM shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Once the spin-off is complete, the Moraine Truck Assembly plant
will be the only factory out of nine local plants operating solely
under the world's largest automaker. A new diesel engine plant in
Moraine is expected to be a joint venture between GM and Isuzu
Motors. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   GM has been discussing a plan to spin off Delphi since early
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker said it will work closely with the United Auto
workers, which settled two devastating strikes against GM last
week. As part of the strike settlement, GM promised not to sell or
close two Delphi brake plants in Dayton before January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   UAW officials in Dayton said they weren't familiar with details
of the spin-off and were unsure how it would affect local plants.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the spin-off, Delphi officials said Monday they would
honor the GM settlement and not sell or close the Dayton brake
plants during the next 17 months. The two troubled plants on
Needmore Road and Wisconsin Boulevard employ 3,400 workers and have
been suffering from massive financial losses.
</P>
<P>
   The spin-off will better position Delphi, the world's largest
auto-parts maker with annual sales of $31 billion, to do business
with companies other than GM, the automaker said. It also will
eventually free GM to buy parts from the least expensive supplier,
whether Delphi or someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``An independent Delphi would become even more competitive than
Delphi is today,'' said J.T. Battenberg III, president of Delphi
and a GM vice president. ``While General Motors would continue to
be an important customer, Delphi's independence would substantially
help it attract additional business from automotive companies other
than GM.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate Delphi's market value at $11 billion to $13
billion. Delphi, based in Troy, Mich., has 204,000 employees and
plants in 36 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Delphi officials said the spin-off will add another
major company to the community's business resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Dayton we will have another Fortune 500 company,''
said Alan Dawes, general manager of Delphi's Chassis division,
adding that Delphi would already be about 25th on the list, based
on current sales. ``We have a lot of opportunity to grow our
business with non-GM customers at a faster rate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether GM's decision to sell off Delphi would lessen
the long-term threat of plants being sold or closed, Dawes would
only say, ``This is not a facility-specific announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of GM's employees strolling through a parking lot at the
Wisconsin Boulevard plant said they knew GM wouldn't be their
employer forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for some good to come out of this, though,'' said Ben
Lewis, a 13-year employee and a senior plant engineer. ``This move
will help (lead to) a better relationship with the UAW and Delphi.
Success is not a dirty word. Corporation is not a dirty word. We
need to be successful and (now) the union can help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Beach, an employee of Delphi for nine years, said that word
of the split is ``news to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was coming. I've always considered myself an
employee of Delphi, not GM,'' Beach said. ``See that sign above the
door (that says Delphi) . . . it doesn't say GM does it?''
</P>
<P>
   Several Dayton city officials called the GM-Delphi split a
positive move for the local community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dayton area workforce has always been very competitive
both in quality and commitment,'' Dayton Mayor Mike Turner said.
``We certainly look forward to success in this new venture.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Kettering, where Delphi operates a suspension parts
plant that employs 3,000 people, were also optimistic about the
business deal. The Kettering plant has been targeted for sale or
shutdown by GM unless it can overcome huge financial losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delphi officials seem optimistic that financial problems can
be worked out to keep the Dayton area plants open,'' said Kettering
Assistant City Manager Pete Horan.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had expected the spin-off decision on Delphi at a GM
board meeting on Monday. ``It's what everyone was waiting for,''
said Credit Suisse First Boston analyst Nicholas Colas.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes a week after GM settled the two costly
strikes in Flint, Mich., including one at a Delphi plant triggered
in part by the company's efforts to farm plant work out to other
parts makers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe GM will come close to making up its
strike-related losses of $2.5 billion by selling its initial 20
percent stake in Delphi.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. downgraded its outlook on GM debt to
negative from stable following the Delphi announcement. S&AMP;P cited
``the significant challenges GM faces'' in completing the
divestiture without worsening its already poor relations with the
UAW.
</P>
<P>
   But in the long run, shedding Delphi could help GM eliminate the
high costs stemming from its Delphi ownership and close the
efficiency gap with its competitors, S&AMP;P said.
</P>
<P>
   Battenberg, who has pushed for a public offering, will be
chairman and chief executive of Delphi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delphi has proven its ability to compete,'' said Jack Smith,
GM's chief executive, in a letter to shareholders. ``But the fact
is, for competitive reasons, many manufacturers simply refuse to
buy components from Delphi as long as it's part of General
Motors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. is expected to sell a public stake in its Visteon
parts unit, with $17 billion in annual sales, for similar reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
