<SLUG> BC-HARRELSON-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRELSON'S DEFENSE CHIPS AWAY AT WITNESSES IN SEEKING NEW TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Stands for Harrelson-Conviction) 
 
By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Lawyers hoping to win Charles Harrelson a new trial for
the 1979 shooting of a federal judge in San Antonio sought Monday
to show that one of his defense attorneys was once implicated in
the murder himself.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, hired by actor Woody Harrelson on behalf of his
father, chipped away at two witnesses in the first of what is
expected to be a three-day evidentiary hearing. Through painstaking
testimony, they revealed that Harrelson's main attorney sought the
help of San Antonio defense lawyer Alan Brown after a convict had
linked Brown to the assassination of U.S. District Judge John Wood.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers, including David Michael of San Francisco, and _
before he was called as a witness in the case _ Harvard law
professor Alan Dershowitz, appeared stymied in their attempts to
show that Harrelson's case was indeed one where the criminal
justice system went awry.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio lawyer Tom Sharpe, who defended Harrelson at his
murder trial, testified Monday that while he once sought Brown's
help as an investigator, Brown never did any work on the case.
What's more, Sharpe said, the convict who implicated Brown was a
self-serving liar who had been ``vaccinated with a polygraph
needle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Brown was a ghost in this case,'' Sharpe said. ``He knew
nothing about the murder of Judge Wood other than what he read in
the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown himself has called the allegations ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years later, the emotions swirling around the case
still seem raw. The hearing was moved to Denver from San Antonio by
U.S. District Judge Fred Biery because of security concerns and
because holding the proceeding in a courthouse named after the
murdered judge would be unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Maximum John'' for his lengthy sentences in drug
cases, Wood was shot once in the back with a hunting rifle outside
his San Antonio townhouse on May 29, 1979. Harrelson, now 59,
claims he was in Dallas at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Wood is the only federal judge to be killed in modern times and
his murder is the stuff of Texas legend.
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter called it an ``assault on our very system
of justice.'' U.S. Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez labeled Wood's murder the
``crime of the century.'' And Griffin Bell, then attorney general,
described the killing as a ``dark time'' in U.S. history and
pledged a fierce manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities indicted Harrelson, a card player and
hustler who was previously convicted for a 1968 contract murder in
South Texas. In 1982, he was found guilty of murdering Wood for a
$250,000 payment from an El Paso drug smuggler known as Jimmy
Chagra.
</P>
<P>
   The Chagra link provided fresh intrigue. Chagra was the middle
son of a colorful, if tragic, El Paso family. His two brothers,
both now dead, were attorneys who mixed drugs and law. The elder,
Lee Chagra, was known to have had an intense dislike for Judge Wood
because of his harsh sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was no death penalty at the time, Harrelson
received two life sentences. He was moved to a maximum-security
prison dubbed ``Supermax'' in Florence, Colo., after he tried to
escape from a federal penitentiary in Atlanta on July 4, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, spurred by a son who never really knew his
father, a legal dream team filed motions aimed at winning a new
trial for Harrelson. At the same time, son Woody, who made his fame
on the television show ``Cheers,'' was in the running for a best
actor Oscar for ``The People vs. Larry Flynt.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the younger Harrelson was in the courtroom, dressed
in black Armani jeans and a lime green Patagonia shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the actor has said that his father is innocent in
the Wood killing. But on Monday, he focused his comments on
``government wrongdoing and cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to know about my father's guilt or innocence,''
he said during a break, his wife and two brothers beside him. ``But
I don't think he had a fair trial.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Lawyers are hoping to prove that federal prosecutors hid
evidence that could have shown that a group of five men with loose
ties to the Chagra family killed Wood. One of them, they have
argued, is Brown. The hearing is to air the evidence the lawyers
have gathered regarding Brown's alleged role.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the lawyers argue that Sharpe failed to give
Harrelson adequate legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   Their task is not easy. In their opening statements, prosecutors
told Biery that Brown had been dropped from the FBI's probe long
before he was approached to help in the Harrelson case. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Without a doubt,'' said John DePue, a Justice Department
lawyer, ``Alan Brown was conflict-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson's lawyers called as a witness Jack Compton, police
chief in the South Texas town of Alice and one-time Customs agent
who early on investigated the Wood killing. Much of his testimony
centered on Robert Riojas, a convicted killer who linked Wood's
murder to five other suspects. But Compton said he's still
convinced Harrelson was the triggerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed it then and I believe it now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors portrayed Riojas as a conniving outlaw who was
desperate to make any kind of deal he could for leniency. Later,
Sharpe bolstered this portrayal, saying that Riojas had led
investigators on a ``rabbit trail'' that came to a sudden dead-end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not subpoena Mr. Riojas to testify,'' Sharpe said. ``I
would not attempt to convince a judge or a jury that Mr. Riojas is
believable.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Sharpe contends that Harrelson does deserve a new
trial, but not because he received ineffective counsel. He said the
convicted killer should not have been tried in San Antonio, nor in
a courthouse named after the assassinated judge, nor before a judge
who was a pallbearer at Wood's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Harrelson and Brown are expected to testify when the
hearing resumes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
