<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS CONTINUE TO DECLINE ON CONCERNS ABOUT PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Investor concerns about the economic crisis in Asia and its
impact on the earnings of U.S. companies continued to send
stock-market gauges lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell more than 1 percent, or
96.55 points, to 8,786.74. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
dropped 8.23 points, to 1,112.44. The technology-laden Nasdaq
composite index decreased 21.29 points, to 1,851.10.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong stock market fell sharply before a report showed
that the economy shrank 2.8 percent in the first quarter of 1998.
The effect of the Asian crisis on Hong Kong was also reflected in a
sharply weaker earnings report from Hongkong and Shanghai Banking.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, the yen fell to its lowest level against the dollar in
seven weeks _ 145.63 to the dollar. The yen ended in late New York
trading at 145.60 yen to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER'S SALES ROSE 3 PERCENT IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler reported a 3 percent increase in July vehicle sales, to
206,018, but that was below May and June sales. Its truck sales
rose 9 percent, but car sales fell 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ASCEND CONFIRMS DEAL FOR STRATUS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Stratus Computer have increased in the last week amid
speculation that it was being acquired by Ascend Communications.
The $822 million stock deal, which was officially announced Monday,
values Stratus at $33.35 a share, 15 percent higher than Friday's
closing price.
</P>
<P>
   BROKERAGE FIRM SUED BY THE SEC
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has accused Dain Rauscher
and two former employees of fraud for their roles in underwriting
bonds connected to the 1994 bankruptcy of Orange County, Calif. The
suit is the second SEC action against a brokerage firm. The first
was settled in January when Credit Suisse First Boston and two
former employees agreed to pay $870,000.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK BUYS A MEDICAL IMAGING UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak will buy Imation's medical-imaging business for
$520 million in cash. The deal signals a turnaround for Kodak,
which has been shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER SPENDING ROSE IN JUNE
</P>
<P>
   Spending by consumers rose a strong 0.6 percent in June, even
though incomes posted the smallest gain in three and a half years.
In another report, the National Association of Purchasing
Management said its composite index retreated in July to 49.1 from
49.6 in June.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG DOLLAR BOLSTERS BONDS
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices rose, helped by a stronger dollar, weaker
commodities prices and an announcement by the Treasury that it
would retire $45 billion in debt through September. The yield on
the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.65 percent, from 5.71 on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   MOBIL REVIVES FAMILIAR FLYING HORSE
</P>
<P>
   Pegasus, the classical mythological creature associated with
strength, power and beauty and the red flying horse used by Mobil
gasoline for 77 years, is making a comeback. It is the star of TV
commercials depicting Mobil as a trusted brand.
</P>
<P>
   A SPANISH COMPANY GAINS OVERSEAS
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish telecommunications company Telefonica doubled its
Latin American holdings to more than $10 billion last week after it
successfully bid for a third of the Brazilian carrier Telebras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
