<DOCNO> NYT19980803.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6202 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-LADN     08-03 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT AT HOME IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Born and reared in Los Angeles, educated at
Crespi High and UCLA, Shaun Williams scoffs at the suggestion he
hasn't spent much time outside Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to Las Vegas,'' he said with the ease of a world
traveler. ``And to Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   He's no Phineas Phog. But it didn't take Williams longer than a
New York minute to get comfortable in Albany, the Empire State
capital, where the New York Giants are holding their training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had an excellent camp,'' Giants defensive coordinator
John Fox said last week. ``He's a sharp guy and he's picked things
up quickly. He's been very impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   What else would you expect from a man who was born Oct. 10, 1976
_ the day Giants Stadium opened.
</P>
<P>
   New York selected Williams with the 24th pick in the April
draft, then signed him to a reported four-year, $4.4 million
contract shortly before training camp. Projected as a safety, his
natural position, Williams has shown enough speed and coverage
ability to merit a look at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be an added bonus,'' Fox said. ``It's a compliment
to him we're even giving it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have one of the best young secondaries in the NFL,
with cornerbacks Jason Sehorn (USC) and Phillippi Sparks, and
safeties Sam Garnes and Tito Wooten. The unit is as stable as it is
talented, with a reserve corps returning intact.
</P>
<P>
   Given the competition, Williams figures his best chance for
immediate playing time is at nickel back _ the fifth defensive
back, used primarily in passing situations. His grueling
double-days (morning and afternoon practices) are spent learning
techniques and defensive schemes for both cornerbacks and safeties.
It's a full load and Williams is careful not to burden himself with
unrealistic demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``At UCLA, I was used to the defense,'' he said. ``But here, I
have to think about what I have to do and what my responsibilities
are. Once I get the defense down, I'll be able to line up and
play.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got plenty of support. The Giants' secondary coach, Johnnie
Lynn, played for UCLA in the late '70s and is familiar not only
with Williams but with all the great Bruins defensive backs, from
Kenny Easley to Eric Turner. And Williams, Lynn believes, has to
tools to extend the legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easley was the prototype,'' Lynn said. ``He was used in a lot
of (schemes) to create plays. You had to account for him, and Shaun
Williams is the same way. He can dominate a game with tackling,
blitzing and making plays on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Bruins linebacker Jason Nevadomsky signed a free-agent
contract with the Giants this spring. If his troublesome shoulder
holds, he has the requisite size and speed to challenge for a
roster spot. If nothing else, Nevadomsky and Willliams have each
other during the toughest days (and most boring nights) of training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   And in a refreshing twist, Williams' closest competitors, Garnes
and Wooten, are also his staunchest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been surprised at how welcoming the guys are,'' Williams
said. ``It's a total team atmosphere and that's made the transition
easier. The guys are always giving me helpful hints on techniques.
They're willing to share information. On some teams, the vets would
be skeptical about giving a rookie valuable tidbits but not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they teach Williams the ropes, they'll teach him the roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for a house in New Jersey as close to Giants
Stadium as possible,'' he said. ``That way, I won't get lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
