<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-TRISTAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TITANIC `TRISTAN' IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE &LR;   &LR; _ It was the biggest high-stakes operatic gamble in
years, and for the most part it paid off gloriously.
</P>
<P>
   With opera lovers from all over the world on hand for the
occasion, the Seattle Opera hosted a landmark double debut Saturday
night: Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde,'' with two of the most
important young Wagner singers of the day _ English soprano Jane
Eaglen and Canadian tenor Ben Heppner _ undertaking the grueling
title roles for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   On one point, at least, there was no doubt: Eaglen's Isolde was
a triumph, a richly detailed, vocally unstoppable portrait of a
princess in the throes of uncontrollable passion.
</P>
<P>
   Heppner's Tristan, on the other hand, was considerably less
steady until the marathon third act, when he finally let loose with
the kind of vocal splendor that has made his name.
</P>
<P>
   But with some truly magnificent singing in the secondary roles
and a provocative, alluring production by director Francesca
Zambello and designer Alison Chitty, this ``Tristan'' made for an
enthralling night in the opera house _ almost as glittering a
success as the optimists were hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to overstate just how important this event was in the
far-flung but tightly linked community of opera buffs. When it's
done right, Wagner's sweeping tale of doomed, adulterous love
between a Cornish knight and the Irish princess betrothed to his
king is about the headiest, most intoxicating brew opera has to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   No other composer has ever come so close to encapsulating in
sound the seductive pull of love, that tempestuous struggle of
pride, fear, rage and pure erotic longing that we all know but
rarely experience at such a heightened, unbroken pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In the otherworldly harmonies, searing vocal lines and heated
Romantic poetry of this score, Wagner inscribed a vision of
unquenchable love that continues to work its magic nearly a century
and a half later.
</P>
<P>
   The only catch is that the opera is almost impossible to cast
satisfactorily. It requires two performers capable of incredible
feats of vocal agility, power, stamina and interpretive subtlety,
singers who can command the stage for most of a nearly five-hour
span while singing above the heavy orchestral textures that swamp
the average voice. Such singers appear once or twice in a
generation, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   In Eaglen and Heppner, who are appearing together for the first
time in this production, Seattle has assembled the duo that
represents the current generation's best hopes for ``Tristan.''
Both have proven themselves to be among the leading Wagnerians of
the day _ Eaglen as Br &LR; u &LR; nnhilde in the ``Ring,'' and Heppner in
San Francisco and elsewhere in performances of ``Lohengrin'' and
``Die Meistersinger.''
</P>
<P>
   For Eaglen, at least, returning to the stage where she made her
memorable 1994 U.S. debut as a last-minute replacement in Bellini's
``Norma,'' Saturday's performance made good on every promise.
</P>
<P>
   Hers is a voice that seems to know neither fear nor ordinary
wear and tear, a pure, soaring tone that is as fresh and tireless
at the end of a long evening as at the beginning. It rides
effortlessly above the majestical din of the Wagnerian orchestra,
not only in the clear, forthright upper register but also in her
richly colored middle range. And if one or two high notes emerged
with a touch of strain, there were always more right behind them to
bring the performance back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Most striking, though, for a singer who has sometimes seemed a
wooden dramatic presence, was how much she made of the role's
emotional drama. In Act 1, as Tristan's ship takes her to the
arranged marriage with King Marke, Eaglen registered the fury and
wounded pride of a woman betrayed (as she thinks) by the man she
loves. The surges of emotion during the lovers' Act 2 tryst were
almost heartrending in their intensity, and the ``Liebestod,'' that
amazing stretch of vocal transcendence that concludes the opera,
rang out with a limpid blend of ardor and serenity.
</P>
<P>
   Heppner's success as Tristan was more mixed _ for the first two
acts, in truth, it would not have been appropriate to speak of his
success at all. During that time, Heppner tiptoed gingerly around
his part like a deer caught in the headlights of an oncoming semi
truck.
</P>
<P>
   In Act 1, he seemed intent only on making as few waves as
possible, and in the extended Act 2 love duet (from which a sizable
cut was taken after the final dress rehearsal), he could barely be
heard over the sound of the orchestra and Eaglen's singing. Only in
the most intimate moments, such as his feeble reply to King Marke's
reproaches (``O K &LR; o &LR; nig, das kann ich dir nicht sagen''), did the
sweet tone and thoughtful phrasing that are his trademarks really
come through.
</P>
<P>
   The semi that was bearing down on him, of course, was Act 3,
surely the longest and most harrowing death scene in opera. Yet
when the crunch arrived, Heppner suddenly came into his own. Here
at last were the vigor, freedom and vocal clarity that had been
missing, deployed thrillingly and at great length. Singing a superb
Act 3, of course, isn't quite the same as singing Tristan, but
perhaps it's a start.
</P>
<P>
   Although Eaglen and Heppner were the headliners, they were by no
means the only important singers on the stage. Some of the
evening's most extraordinary singing came from mezzo-soprano
Michelle DeYoung, as Isolde's nurse Brang &LR; a &LR; ne, in a performance of
unremitting force and tonal splendor.
</P>
<P>
   Baritone Greer Grimsley was a charismatic, vocally heroic
presence as Tristan's sidekick Kurwenal, rising to particular
strength in Act 3. And English bass Peter Rose brought gravitas and
palpable pain to King Marke's sorrowful Act 2 monologue after
discovering the lovers in flagrante. Armin Jordan's conducting was
solid but rarely vivid; the Prelude and other orchestral passages
went by without raising the ambient temperature at all.
</P>
<P>
   Zambello's staging featured a few silly, arty touches that were
easily overlooked (a corps of naked crewmen in the hellish lower
deck of Tristan's ship, a blood-red Nike swoosh when he is wounded
at the end of Act 2), but other than that it managed to keep the
lovers' predicament to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   Chitty's set for Act 1 is the side of a huge ocean liner, as
overt a homage to ``Titanic'' as it could be, with the action
playing out resourcefully both on deck and below. The second and
third acts are staged in an attractive but mysterious glass house
that looks something like an extremely upscale bus shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The best touches come at the flash points of the drama _ the
beautiful starlit night sky that lighting designer Mimi Jordan
Sherin has created for the Act 2 assignation, and most memorable of
all, the subtle but unmistakable shift in lighting when the
principals first share the fatal love potion.
</P>
<P>
   These are the moments when this ``Tristan'' comes closest to the
dark, unruly passion Wagner knew all too well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
