<SLUG> BC-MORELAND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family granted more visitation with surviving children while
custody date pushed back
 &HT;    By Wendy Hundley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Moreland family will have more visitation
with their four children but will have to wait at least six weeks
to learn whether the youngsters will remain in foster care or be
allowed to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's hearing on a motion to change the custody arrangements
was continued until Sept. 15. Defense and prosecutors agreed to the
continuation.
</P>
<P>
   It's the third time Montgomery County Juvenile Court Judge
Michael Murphy has postponed the custody hearing in order to allow
investigators more time to examine the deaths of four other
children in the family.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy had earlier said that he wanted more information before
he ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want their children back but visitations are going to be
increased,'' said family attorney, Anthony Van Noy, after a
closed-door meeting with Murphy, prosecutors and child welfare
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The children were removed from the home of Phillip and Regina
Moreland on Dec. 24 following the death of Danatta Moreland, the
third child in the family to die.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 20, the children were placed in the care of their
maternal grandmother, Cecile O. Marshall
</P>
<P>
   The children were removed from Marshall's home on June 26, one
day after the death of a fourth child - Kelab Moreland, 2.
</P>
<P>
   All deaths have been ruled homicides by suffocation or
asphyxiation. Police say they have a suspect but have not said who
it is.
</P>
<P>
   Family members have said that police are focusing their
investigation on a child in the household. Some family members have
rejected that conclusion and have been accused of not cooperating
with police.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Juvenile Prosecutor Jim Cole said the family is now
cooperating fully with authoritie, and attorney Van Noy praised
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police are doing their job and doing a good job,'' Van Noy
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Murphy's decision to delay the custody hearing once
again tends to suggest that police are having a hard time making a
solid case against a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had someone,'' Van Noy said, ``charges would have been
filed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Hundley writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
