<SLUG> BC-OPERA-SEATTLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE IS FOR WAGNER LOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (with OPERA-TRISTAN-SFCHRON)  
 By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If anybody was going to make a splash with a new
``Tristan,'' it would have to be the Seattle Opera. No other
company in the United States has been so indelibly associated with
Wagner's music.
</P>
<P>
   An ``emphasis on the work of Richard Wagner'' is even included
in the company's mission statement.
</P>
<P>
   Under founder Glynn Ross, and since 1983 under Speight Jenkins,
the company's garrulous, affable Texan general director, Wagner has
been a central part of Seattle's operatic life.
</P>
<P>
   For years it was the place to go for the full ``Ring'' cycle,
that dauntingly ambitious four-opera pinnacle of Wagner's art.
Every summer from 1975 to 1984, the company mounted the cycle in
both German and English. Jenkins introduced a new ``Ring''
production in 1986, and a third production is planned for August
2001.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``Ring'' is only the most prominent aspect of Seattle's
Wagner fixation. In the past decade alone, Jenkins has introduced
notable productions of ``Die Meistersinger,'' ``Tannh &LR; a &LR; user,''
``The Flying Dutchman,'' ``Lohengrin'' and now ``Tristan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done every major opera now except `Parsifal,''' Jenkins
says. ``And that's slated for 2003.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
