<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IN LINE AT BASEBALL'S STAR MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Canada)  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene played out pretty much the way Mark Grudzielanek and
Carlos Perez always imagined it would. Felipe Alou, the classy
manager who had raised them as major league pups, called their
names in the Montreal dugout. First Grudzielanek. Then Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been traded,'' Alou said. Then the players waited for
Alou to divulge the really good news. ``The Dodgers. Work hard.
Good luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The sports highlights caught these exchanges, with Alou's arm
affectionately on each player's shoulder, and the players standing
there awkwardly, not knowing whether to stay or go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to say or do,'' Grudzielanek said in the
Dodgers' clubhouse before Monday night's game with the Mets. ``I
mean, I wanted to just yell out, `Yes!' or jump up and down like a
kid. But Felipe has been my only manager. People talk about what
happened in Florida, but Felipe's been dealing with that the last
five years, losing guys he helped develop. I respect the guy so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Money doesn't buy respect, just some of the best players in the
game. Pedro Martinez. Henry Rodriguez. Larry Walker. Andres
Galarraga. John Wetteland. Marquis Grissom. They all walked out of
Felipe Alou's dugout as free agents or before demanding the big
money the indigent Expos have been in no position to pay. Alou has
solemnly shaken the hands of a virtual all-star team that included
his son, Moises. He knows the downsizing drill better than anyone,
including Jim Leyland, the Florida manager who is undeservedly
baseball's most pitied.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, a 1996 all-star shortstop, and Perez, the Expos'
best remaining pitcher after Martinez was dealt to Boston last
winter, were just the latest to push through customs at last Friday
night's major league trading deadline, which was an actual deadline
in the manner of the first edition of your daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   There will be more trades this season via the miracle of
waivers, or whatever, because the reality of baseball's class
society is that its supermarket for rich teams is open 24 hours a
day, seven days a week, 52 weeks a year. A well-heeled owner can
always walk in, peruse the aisles and lay claim to the latest stars
on the shelves, unless he is beaten to the draw and can't get his
checkbook out of his pocket fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   This is important to remember with the Mike Piazza saga into a
bizarre disaffection stage _ the catcher not hitting his weight
with runners in scoring position, the Shea fans booing his every
breath, and the grand plan of co-opting Piazza's Hall of Fame bat
for the next half-dozen years looking more like a seasonal rental
every day.
</P>
<P>
   I don't understand why anyone expected Piazza to come here and
suddenly exchange wedding vows with the Mets this summer, before he
becomes a free agent, after he rejected $84 million from the
Dodgers, the team with which he had spent his entire career. No
matter how many times he dispassionately claims to like New York,
Piazza must have some other agenda, for as Carlos Perez said:
``When you get drafted by a team and spend all these years with the
same guys, you usually don't want to leave. You just want that team
to give you the big money and a long-term contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The desired organizational outcome, of course, would be for
Piazza to start hitting long balls in the clutch, get the fans off
his back and get the Mets onto his shoulders and into the playoffs.
If he has already decided he is going elsewhere, the Mets will have
opportunities to survive the failed experiment, believe me, as long
as they are out there with the same money they presumably have set
aside for Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   They can make a run at Mo Vaughn, or Bernie Williams. How much
longer before Ken Griffey Jr. wants out of Seattle? If recent
history tells anything, it is that baseball's stars inevitably
move, and big ones, too. Rather than spend the whole $12 million
Piazza pie on one player, maybe the Mets slice that sum in half,
pursue strong hitters at third base and in the outfield, and move
Todd Hundley out of his worst nightmare, left field, and back
behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   For teams with money, there is always a spender's chance, a star
to steal, especially from the likes of Montreal, where it is now
Vladimir Guerrero's turn to count down the days until the Expos'
next fire sale. Guerrero, named National League player of the month
Monday, is an impressive 24-year-old slugger who, according to
Grudzielanek, has already rejected a rare long-term offer from the
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's eligible for arbitration after next season, they'll
trade him,'' Grudzielanek said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets should get in line right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
