<HEADLINE>
NO SERMONIZING ON THE PRESIDENT  
 BOOK HAS EXTRAS  
 LIFE WITH SALINGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A postscript on President Clinton's visit to East Hampton, N.Y.:
The title of the sermon at the First United Methodist Church on
Sunday was ``Mercy and Judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation that the president and Hillary Rodham
Clinton might attend. (Mrs. Clinton is a Methodist.) And the
minister, the Rev. David Parker, wanted to dispel the idea that the
sermon title was an editorial comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some might have suspected that this sermon topic was chosen
with the eye to a possible presidential appearance,'' he told the
congregation. ``Nothing could be further from the fact.'' He said
his topic had been governed by the morning's Scripture readings,
which in turn were determined by a calendar used by most Protestant
and Catholic churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were here,'' Parker added, ``the worst thing a preacher
could do under such circumstances when you have a captive
presidential audience is to pretend to play Nathan to the rule of
David.''
</P>
<P>
   The service began with the hymn ``For the Beauty of the Earth,''
which is often sung at times of thanksgiving. The president was
giving thanks, but not in church. He went to an East Hampton
restaurant, Babette's Feast, and thanked the owner, Barbara Layton,
for a petition she circulated in February attacking what was
described as the ``muckraking witch hunt at taxpayers' expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Book Has Extras
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jonathan Ames was wearing a seersucker jacket, just
like the hero of his new novel, ``The Extra Man.'' And Blair Clark,
a former executive at CBS News, was denying that Ames had learned
anything about ``extra men'' (a k a ``walkers'' who escort wealthy
women to Broadway shows and dinner parties) from him.
</P>
<P>
   The things they talk about at those midsummer book parties.
</P>
<P>
   This one was set in a garden behind Clark's townhouse on the
East Side. Ames wrote much of ``The Extra Man'' in an extra room in
the house; he has known Clark and his wife, Joanna, for nearly 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ames' 84-year-old great aunt, Doris Klein, has known him even
longer. ``He devoted a whole chapter to me and he makes me out to
be much older than I am,'' she said. Ames laughed. ``I've had a
character in each of my books loosely based on my aunt,'' he said,
``and they're always her age.''
</P>
<P>
   Life With Salinger
</P>
<P>
   She called him Jerry. He signed his letters to her ``love.''
</P>
<P>
   He was J.D. Salinger, the famously reclusive author of ``The
Catcher in the Rye,'' writing to 18-year-old Joyce Maynard, an
undergraduate at Yale who had never read a word he had written. It
was 1972, and an article of hers had just appeared in The New York
Times Magazine. They became pen pals. Five months later she moved
in with him in Cornish, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maynard is breaking 26 years of silence about her
relationship with Salinger in a book that is scheduled to be
published next month. Vanity Fair magazine is running an excerpt in
its September issue that presents Salinger as someone who could be
``moody and cranky.'' Ms. Maynard portrays him as a devotee of
homeopathic medicine and an ardent fan of television programs like
``The Andy Griffith Show.''
</P>
<P>
   She also described two sexual encounters, saying that he told
her to move out after nine months, when they went to Florida to see
a ``naturopathic practitioner'' who performed acupuncture to make
sex less painful.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said Ms. Maynard would not give interviews until
the book was published. The magazine said the book chronicles ``her
44 years, through her confrontation last year with Salinger.''
(``She did confront him last fall, but they would not allow us to
use that,'' said Beth Kseniak, a spokeswoman for Vanity Fair,
referring to the book's publisher, Picador USA. ``They did not want
us to give everything away, I guess.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
