<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ARTISTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSICIANS WITH VISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
    (With MUSIC-PFUNK-SFCHRON)  
 By JAMES SULLIVAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Clinton is hardly the first pop-music performer to fancy
himself a visual artist. Rolling Stones guitarist Ron Wood has sold
dozens of his colorful portraits of fellow stars, John Lennon's
estate has made a cottage industry of the late Beatle's dashed-off
cartoons and Tony Bennett has turned out almost as many paintings
as recordings over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other pop artists and their milieus:
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; David Bowie _ gaunt, blue-in-the-face portraiture
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Perry Farrell of Jane's Addiction _ orgiastic dioramas.
``Art is the ultimate drug''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Joan Baez _ charcoals and watercolors of puppets and cats
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; John Cougar Mellencamp _ freakish, medieval-style portraits
(what, no ``Pink Houses''?)
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Jerry Garcia _ trippy designs, many reproduced for his line
of silk ties
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Carly Simon _ placid impressionism
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Don Van Vliet (Captain Beefheart) _ trailer-park madness;
now a full-time painter hidden away in rural California
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Cat Stevens _ pre-mystical street scenes (``Teaser and the
Firecat'')
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Miles Davis _ headstrong abstraction, a fusion of styles
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Donna Summer _ bronze work, painting, lithography. Recurring
title: ``Driven by the Music''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Judy Collins _ watercolors and acrylics of fine-china
patterns
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Cris and Curt Kirkwood, Meat Puppets _ heat-stricken
absurdity (sample title: ``My, You Have a Nice Kitchen'')
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Ringo Starr _ finger-paintings
