<HEADER>
A6349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LAROCCA-PROFILE-82     08-03 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAROCCA-PROFILE-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CANDIDATE WITHOUT CASH OR FLASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOWVILLE, N.Y. _ Most people watching the Lewis County Fair
parade had no idea who the man in the monogrammed shirt was or why
he had joined the procession of baton twirlers, beauty queens and
Boy Scouts marching through town on a steamy summer night.
</P>
<P>
   He was politely shaking hands, and occasionally introducing
himself as Jim Larocca, a Democratic candidate for governor. But he
was not urging people to support him in the Democratic primary on
Sept. 15. And unlike other politicians marching in the parade, he
had no zealous campaign aides passing out buttons and shouting his
name to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   James Larocca, a former state official from Huntington, N.Y., is
the most understated of the four Democrats hoping to oppose Gov.
George Pataki in the fall, and his campaign has by far the least
cash. But what he lacks in money and flash, he makes up for in
doggedness. Larocca registered as a gubernatorial candidate more
than a year ago, long before any of his better-known competitors _
Peter Vallone, the New York City Council speaker, Lt. Gov. Betsy
McCaughey Ross and Charles Hynes, the Brooklyn district attorney.
And he has traveled the state ever since, courting Democratic
leaders with a quiet intensity that has earned him a surprising
amount of support, considering that Larocca, 54, has few ties to
the Democratic Party establishment, has never held elective office
and is barely known outside Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim is just a super guy,'' said Charles Merrell, the Lewis
County Democratic chairman, who invited Larocca to the upstate
parade. ``There's a lot to like about him. He'd make a great
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, have Merrell and other party leaders who gush about
Larocca thrown their weight behind other candidates? Why is
Larocca, admired by everyone from upstate dairy farmers to urban
advocates of gay issues, considered the longest of long shots?
</P>
<P>
   Because the other candidates have more money and name
recognition, factors that party officials said count more than good
ideas when the Republican incumbent is soaring high in the polls.
Larocca has raised only $845,000 and spent all but $3,600, which
leaves him miles behind Vallone and Ms. McCaughey Ross, each of
whom has raised more than $3 million. Hynes has raised $500,000 and
still has $200,000 on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going with Peter Vallone because he's got money and, let's
face it, more people know who he is,'' Merrell said. ``I just think
he's got a better chance at it than Jim.''
</P>
<P>
   Larocca is the only Democratic candidate who has worked in state
government, as transportation commissioner under Gov. Mario Cuomo
and energy commissioner under Gov. Hugh Carey. He was also
president of the Long Island Association, the island's largest
economic development group, for eight years. Demographically,
Larocca is a political consultant's dream: Roman Catholic,
Italian-American and the only candidate not from New York City. He
and his wife, Dale, have three grown children. And he looks
gubernatorial, with silvery hair, perfect posture and an earnest
gaze.
</P>
<P>
   His platform is broad enough to appeal to both upstate moderates
and urban liberals. He supports abortion rights, affirmative action
and gay marriage, yet he also calls the death penalty
``appropriate.'' Larocca would cut tuition at public colleges and
universities by 25 percent, ban corporate contributions to
political campaigns and push the State Legislature to allow casinos
in economically depressed regions.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to create regional partnerships involving
businesses, universities and local governments to assist economic
development. He encouraged such partnerships when he was running
the Long Island Association, and he said they helped the region's
economy when the military contracting industry collapsed in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly large stumbling blocks have made political life
difficult for Larocca in recent months. The biggest came in May,
when the Nassau County Democratic chairman, Stephen Sabbeth,
switched his support from Larocca to Ms. McCaughey Ross. As a
result, Larocca did not win enough delegate votes at the state
Democratic Convention to get an automatic spot on the primary
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Larocca turned to a more laborious way of getting on the ballot:
collecting at least 15,000 signatures from registered Democrats
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   These recent complications have hurt his fund-raising efforts,
Larocca said, as would-be supporters have decided his campaign is
doomed. He complains bitterly about his fund-raising disadvantage,
saying Vallone and Hynes can easily raise money as elected
officials, and pointing out that most of Ms. McCaughey Ross' money
comes from her husband, a wealthy banker. But he also attempts to
make an asset of his relative poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proving that it's not about money, but about the vision
and independence and integrity of the candidate,'' Larocca said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The absence of a political record and his relative obscurity
have meant that he has not attracted much campaign criticism yet,
but on Long Island, some civic and business leaders complain that
he has failed to take a strong stand on the state's takeover of the
Long Island Lighting Co.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics say his insistence on staying in the race with no
money is a sign of arrogance. Sheldon Sackstein, the chairman of
Action Long Island, a nonprofit business and civic group, said
Larocca was more focused on advancing his career than on solving
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Larocca's distaste for old-style politicking shows on the
campaign trail, where he spends more time huddling with small
groups than working rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to his credit that he's not a back-slapping type of guy
and likes to have deep conversations with people instead,'' said
Assemblyman Eric Vitaliano, D-Staten Island, who has known Larocca
for years. ``Jimmy's got quiet strength, and that's an asset in
this time of superficial sound bites.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who believe Larocca does not have a prayer said his
soft-pedal approach was winning him a loyal support base that could
make him a strong candidate in 2002. John Zogby, a pollster in
Utica, N.Y., said that although Larocca's better-known opponents
would suffer from a primary defeat, he has nothing to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's young, he's attractive, he is making the kinds of
contacts he needs and he is not hurting himself by attacking the
other candidates,'' Zogby said. ``My guess is that Larocca is the
only one of these four who's got legs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
