<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-APOLLO-THEATER-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EX-BOROUGH PRESIDENT'S CONTRACT FOR APOLLO THEATER TV SHOW UNDER
INVESTIGATION  (js) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The private foundation that controls the financially
troubled Apollo Theater decided Monday that a company owned by
Percy Sutton, the former Manhattan Borough president, could for the
sixth year in a row retain the syndication rights to a popular
television show broadcast from the Harlem landmark.
</P>
<P>
   But another company that had been seeking the syndication rights
complained that the Apollo Theater Foundation had wrongly allowed
Sutton's company, Inner City Broadcasting, to change its bid at the
last minute.
</P>
<P>
   And the state attorney general's office, which is already
investigating the financial relationship between the foundation and
Sutton's company, said it would immediately subpoena records from
the meeting at which foundation members awarded the one-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton rebuilt the Apollo Theater in the 1980s, but it lost
money, and in 1992, he turned its management over to the nonprofit
foundation. The theater fell into disrepair and, in May, state
officials announced they would withhold $750,000 in loans and
grants from the foundation until serious questions about its
finances had been answered. The foundation manages the theater for
the state, which owns it.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, state officials are questioning whether the
foundation's board _ whose chairman is Sutton's close friend, U.S.
Rep. Charles Rangel _ allowed Inner City Broadcasting to
significantly underpay it for control of the popular television
show, ``It's Showtime at the Apollo,'' which it had retained under
a five-year licensing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, Rangel said he and the other board
members had voted 7-4 to let Inner City Broadcasting keep the
syndication rights for another year. Although Rangel would not say
how much the company had offered for the rights, state officials
said it had originally offered $1.5 million _ the same amount that
the other bidder, the African Heritage Network, was offering. But
last Friday, the state officials said, Inner City changed its bid
to $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Wurzell, a spokesman for Attorney General Dennis Vacco,
said Monday that an assistant attorney general had recommended in a
recent letter to the foundation's lawyer that Rangel excuse himself
from the vote because of his friendship with Sutton. Wurzell would
not say exactly why the attorney general's office wanted to know
the specifics of the vote, but he suggested that state
investigators considered it suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue for us is whether the board members' actions today
were in the best interest of the foundation,'' Wurzell said. ``We
will, in the next 24 hours, issue a subpoena to the foundation
requesting all the pertinent documentation of today's meeting and
the board's action.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton was traveling Monday and could not be reached for
comment. Calls to Chuck Sutton, his nephew and spokesman, were not
returned. But Rangel defended the vote, saying it in no way
reflected a bias toward Inner City Broadcasting. He said the
African Heritage Network would have been allowed to change its bid,
too, if it had asked.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rangel would not say how he or any other board member voted, and
would not discuss why they chose Inner City Broadcasting over the
African Heritage Network. But he said representatives from the
attorney general's office, whom he has talked to periodically since
the broader investigation began, never asked him to refrain from
voting.
</P>
<P>
   Under the five-year licensing agreement, Inner City Broadcasting
was supposed to pay the foundation $2,000 per taping or 25 percent
of the show's profits, whichever was greater. But according to
officials at the Empire State Development Corp., the state agency
that owns the Apollo, the foundation's executives told its
directors this year that Sutton owed at least $3 million under the
agreement, which expired at the end of last year. When the board
pressed for payment, it received only $200,000, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton and Rangel both say the foundation received all it was
owed. In an interview in May, Sutton said the television show, now
in its 10th year, began to make a profit only two years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
