<HEADLINE>
THEATER PRODUCER WINS BID FOR 42ND ST. BUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rejecting a more lucrative bid for a theme restaurant
run by the World Wrestling Federation, the officials behind Times
Square's redevelopment have agreed to lease 42nd Street's last
unclaimed historic theater to the Canadian company that produces
``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Livent Inc., the company that built the Ford Theater on the
north side of 42nd Street, home to ``Ragtime,'' is expected to sign
a memorandum of understanding on Tuesday to lease the long-dormant
Times Square Theater next door. If a final deal can be struck,
Livent plans to create a 500-seat theater, a two-story restaurant
and office space in the 88-year-old building, one of eight that
hark back to the glory days of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Livent, New York state officials and the New 42nd
Street, a nonprofit redevelopment agency, rejected a higher offer,
which they did not disclose, by the World Wrestling Federation and
a partner to build a restaurant and retail store with a wrestling
theme. The group wanted to broadcast professional wrestling,
including its popular Wrestlemania championship matches, and
interviews with stars like Stone Cold Steve Austin, the Undertaker
and Hunter Hearst Helmsley of D-Generation X.
</P>
<P>
   Livent also outmaneuvered developers seeking to open a
restaurant called Empire!, with a Roman gladiator theme, and a
comedy club called the Laugh Factory, real estate executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Cora Cahan, the president of New 42nd Street, confirmed that her
group expected to sign an agreement Tuesday with Livent. She said
that the opportunity for another live theater on 42nd Street was
too good to pass up. Two of the biggest hits on Broadway today,
``Ragtime'' and ``The Lion King,'' are housed in newly restored
theaters on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   James Bell, senior vice president of licensing and merchandising
at the World Wrestling Federation, said the wrestlers would have
been good company for Madame Tussaud's Wax Museum, also planned for
42nd Street, and the Mickey Mouse and Bugs Bunny cartoon characters
at the nearby Disney and Warner Brothers stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offer was substantially higher and more lucrative than the
one they chose,'' said Bell, who estimated that 60 million people a
week watch wrestling matches, based on pay-per-view and cable
television ratings. ``We would have brought a good element to that
location. And our fans spend money,'' he said _ about $300 million
annually on action figures, video games and T-shirts licensed by
the World Wrestling Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were compatible with Disney and Warner
Brothers,'' Bell said. ``But the board really wanted a traditional
theater versus, quote unquote, another entertainment type.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
