<HEADER>
A6362 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIR-COX     08-03 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A hair-raising experience: Stylists compete in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge and Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The gloves came off in a hurry Monday night during the
fast-paced ``Hair Battle Royale '98'' at the Georgia World Congress
Center downtown. As more than 3,000 Bronner Bros. International
Hair Show attendees applauded their favorites, 12 hairstylists from
across the country competed for a grand prize of $10,000 or a 1998
Jeep Cherokee. The only rules: a 10-minute time limit and unlimited
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   First up in the large black-draped boxing ring stage: Washington
D.C. stylist Miki Wright vs. LaMesa, Calif.'s Tesa
Breaston-Holiday. While Wright's three tulle gowned and
ringlet-adorned models suggested romance, Breaston-Holiday went
Asian flash complete with a thumping ``X-Files'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   As the models onstage were being sprayed, styled and spritzed,
Northwest Atlanta stylist TEE White was busy backstage readying his
secret weapon _ men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there will be a lot of women out there and I'm looking
for some screams,'' White, 30, explained as he put the finishing
touches on his buffed shirtless models' body art with matching
primary hair colors.
</P>
<P>
   College Park stylist Felisha Gatlin, meanwhile, was looking to
the future for her inspiration, complete with time capsules and
silver space suits. ``I'm using a `frozen in space' look,'' Gatlin,
27, said, whose hands were cooperating with the chosen theme.
``This is a tremendous honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, Norcross stylist Maurice Beaman was busy staging
the history of black hair care. ``My goal is to show where we've
been and where we're going,'' Beaman, 34, explained.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
