<HEADER>
A6365 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-W     08-03 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDES TAKE DEFIANT STANCE ON LEWINSKY MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Changes made throughout story for clarification and further
detail.)  (lb) 
 By JAMES BENNET and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking a defiant stance toward prosecutors and
political critics, White House officials said on Monday that
President Clinton would continue to maintain that he had had no
sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky and would pursue another
Supreme Court showdown, this time over an appeals court decision
ordering a top aide to testify in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is not scheduled to testify until Aug. 17, and his
advisers cautioned that only he and a small cadre of lawyers are
privy to his deliberations. But, in what appeared to be a concerted
effort, several Clinton aides on Monday dismissed pleas from
Republican congressmen and some former officials that Clinton
acknowledge an affair with the former White House intern to blunt
and perhaps end the 6-month-old investigation by Kenneth Starr, the
independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has told the truth about this, and he will
continue to do so,'' said Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, in
response to questions. ``I have no reason to think that that has
changed in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials expressed annoyance over what they called a
presumption that the president was lying when he denied that he had
had a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky in the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct suit. They said that Clinton's agreement to testify,
despite White House suspicion of Starr's motives, proved that he
had nothing to fear. ``It is a little insulting to turn on the
television and see people come up with the brilliant idea that he
should tell the truth,'' one official said. ``Do you think anyone
here is going in and saying, `Sir, you should lie'?''
</P>
<P>
   Each weekday morning, the president's political advisers and
spokesmen, who are generally in the dark about his legal strategy,
meet with members of the White House counsel's office for guidance
on how to respond to the day's developments in the investigation.
Aides who spoke about the president's position appeared to have
based their comments on such discussions.
</P>
<P>
   As the White House affirmed Clinton's denials, forensic
scientists at the FBI crime laboratory completed a first set of
tests on a blue dress that Ms. Lewinsky turned over to prosecutors.
Prosecutors are trying to determine whether the dress was stained
during a sexual encounter with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The first test, performed under extremely tight security, was
intended to determine whether the stain had been caused by semen,
but the result was being very closely held.
</P>
<P>
   On a day of rapid-fire legal motions and court decisions the
White House also served notice on Monday that it would ask the
Supreme Court to overturn a lower court's decision compelling Bruce
Lindsey, a White House lawyer who is the president's closest
adviser, to testify to the Lewinsky grand jury. After that
decision, Lanny Breuer, another member of the White House Counsel's
office, was subpoenaed last week to testify on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House filed a motion Monday with the Court of Appeals
here seeking to block testimony by its lawyers while it awaits
action by the Supreme Court. That motion was rejected, but the
White House immediately filed the same request with Chief Justice
William Rehnquist, according to The Associated Press. It was not
clear whether the maneuvering would affect Breuer's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey, who has said he knows of no wrongdoing or criminal
conduct, cited lawyer-client privilege in declining to answer some
questions before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In its divided ruling last week, a three-judge panel of the U.S.
Court of Appeals found that no such privilege could protect a
government lawyer from testifying in a criminal investigation. It
ruled that the lawyers' ``duty is not to defend clients against
criminal charges and it is not to protect wrongdoers from public
exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House counsel, Charles Ruff, said the appeals court
decision would undercut any president's ability to get honest
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This privilege ultimately serves the public interest by
ensuring fully informed decision-making through open and candid
discussions between clients and attorneys,'' Ruff said in a
statement Monday. ``The confidential nature of the attorney-client
privilege relationship is no less important in government than in
every other context where it exists.''
</P>
<P>
   In another running legal contest between Starr and the White
House, the Court of Appeals handed down a mixed ruling Monday,
deciding that an investigation may continue into whether Starr's
office has illegally leaked grand jury material. The investigation
is being conducted by Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, who presides
over the grand jury hearing the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But, overruling part of a decision by Judge Johnson, the appeals
court found that the president's lawyers may not on their own
depose Starr's prosecutors or demand documents from them, according
to a lawyer familiar with the ruling, which was sealed. Instead,
Judge Johnson must first review and approve any documents that are
to be turned over by Starr's office, to ensure they do not reveal
grand jury secrets.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, one of the president's lawyers, has accused
Starr's office of illegal slipping information to reporters and
sought sanctions against it. Starr's office has denied such leaks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the president said on Monday that he betrayed no sign
of nervousness about his prospective testimony. ``The most
comforting thing in the White House now is that the president seems
totally comfortable,'' said one Clinton aide who is not part of his
damage-control team.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing to publicly ignore his legal and political
predicament, Clinton confined his public comments on Monday to
other legislative matters than talk of potential impeachment
hearings. In a speech to summer jobs workers in Cheverly, Md., he
warned Republican leaders that he would not accept a ``bare-bones''
budget from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House Republican plan puts politics ahead of people and
puts your future in the back seat,'' he said. ``That is wrong.''
With veto threats hanging over seven appropriations bills, the
White House is on a collision course with Congress over the budget,
though that dispute has been obscured by the furor over Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also gave a speech on Monday, appearing before a lawyers'
group in Toronto, Canada. He reviewed the Supreme Court's
performance this year, calling it ``quite impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had learned from a defeat he suffered this year
before the Supreme Court, which ruled he could not have access to
notes taken by a lawyer to Vince Foster, the former White House
deputy counsel who committed suicide during Clinton's first term.
The court ruled that a client's death did not weaken the
attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said that ``the court reminded us that there are other
considerations, there are other values,'' besides the pursuit of
truth. ``The law, embodying the wisdom of the ages, has seen fit to
protect relationships, even at the expense of truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Starr told reporters that he was pursuing his
investigation while ``being respectful of the institutions of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the president's advisers have doubts about his
truthfulness regarding Ms. Lewinsky, and some suspect that by
changing his story now he could bring an end to a drama that has
transfixed Washington and stunted progress on Capitol Hill. But
many Clinton allies also believe that any admission by Clinton
would be turned against him by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's advisers said that his team of political and
legal aides was nervously awaiting test results on Ms. Lewinsky's
dress, which was bought at the Gap. If DNA testing links the dress
to Clinton, this adviser said, White House thinking on his
testimony may change. ``Whatever anyone is saying becomes
inoperative depending upon the results,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike laboratory findings in most high profile cases, which are
widely distributed through the upper echelons of the
law-enforcement agency and the Justice Department, the Lewinsky lab
tests are being provided only to a handful of lab technicians and
senior FBI officials. They in turn reveal the findings directly to
Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
