<SLUG> BC-BBA-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' SUCCESS ENHANCES VALUE OF CABLE CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Each Yankees cable telecast should rightly be
preceded by a notice like the ones that accompany public TV
programs: ``This game has been generously underwritten by a grant
from the Madison Square Garden Network.''
</P>
<P>
   The MSG Network has made the Yankees flusher than flush since
the start of their landmark $486 million cable TV contract in 1989.
As the deal nears its end, MSG will pay the Yankees $53.3 million
this year, $54.25 million next year and $55.25 million in 2000,
according to people who have read the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Most baseball teams survive on $45 million or $50 million a
season less in cable cash. The entire National Hockey League gets
less in its rights deal with Fox Sports.
</P>
<P>
   But with the deal's expiration two years away, can the Yankees
expect a new one to maintain such exorbitant payments _ or go even
higher? When the deal was negotiated in 1988, it was the subject of
rabid bidding among MSG, which wanted to become more than a
six-month Knicks and Rangers service; Sportschannel New York, which
had held the Yankee cable rights from 1982 to 1988, and
WPIX/Channel 11.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Cablevision Systems owns MSG and Fox Sports New York,
the former Sportschannel. WPIX is part of the WB Network and could
not carry more than the 50 games it carries now under a subcontract
with MSG.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably less, as the WB expands,'' said Michael Eigner, who
oversees WPIX as an executive vice president of Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   So does Chuck Dolan, chairman of Cablevision, hold all the
leverage? Can he dictate to George Steinbrenner, the team's
principal owner, a significant cut in payments? Will Steinbrenner's
cash wad shrink in the new millennium until he gets a new stadium?
</P>
<P>
   No. No. And unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' value has expanded in the past decade, almost
making us forget the leanness of their 288-359 record from 1989 to
1992, the first four years of MSG's deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were 77-28 before Monday night's game in Oakland,
and MSG's 3.88 rating after 63 games is up 51 percent from last
year and 33 percent ahead of 1996' full-season MSG peak.
</P>
<P>
   There are several scenarios that offer competition to
Cablevision:
</P>
<P>
   _ Steinbrenner could create his own Yankee Network. For that he
would have to set up an administrative structure to sell the rights
to individual cable systems and commercial time to advertisers. He
would get no cash up front, but would get all the cable system fees
and advertiser payments. To execute the plan, he would need to make
a deal with Cablevision, which owns systems totaling 2.6 million of
the metropolitan area's 4.6 million cable homes. Dolan can be a
tough negotiator, but any attempt to bar the Yankees from his
systems would surely engender widespread viewer reaction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steinbrenner could go into a partnership with Time Warner,
which could create a sports channel on its New York City cable
system, reaching 1.1 million subscribers. Time Warner would also
have to deal with Cablevision to gain full local exposure beyond
its environs. Tough as Cablevision can be, can you imagine someone
else starting a Yankee network and Dolan saying, ``Nah, sorry,
that's not for me''? Cable systems need the Yankees, even Dolan's.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN could launch a sports channel. Until recently, ESPN
contemplated creating ESPN West to carry games of the Anaheim
Angels and Mighty Ducks, the teams controlled by its parent,
Disney. When cable systems balked at carrying ESPN West, ESPN made
10-year deals to keep the Angels on Fox Sports West and the Ducks
on Fox Sports West 2, two of the 22 regional sports outlets under
the Fox Sports Net. A drawback to an ESPN New York is that it would
remain a one-team service until other teams' rights became
available. The Yankees plus college hoops and lacrosse is not a
powerhouse channel. Josh Krulewitz, an ESPN spokesman, said, ``We
will consider regional opportunities if they make good business
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   _ New technologies, like digital television or satellite TV,
could play a role in a non-Cablevision scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Dolan must realize George Steinbrenner has many options
to work things out for himself,'' said Andrew Zimbalist, a
professor of economics at Smith College and an expert on sports
finance. ``Steinbrenner has put an emphasis on developing a winning
team in anticipation of negotiating a new package. He's played his
cards right. I see this as a $50 million-a-year contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolan realizes all this and knows that not having the Yankees'
cable rights would hurt more than the defection of any other team.
If Yankees games were broadcast on the Yankee Network, you could
expect that cable systems would, if necessary, pre-empt whatever
was being shown on MSG to carry the Bronx Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan knows this, which is why he tried to buy the Yankees last
year. If he had bought the team, he would have acquired the cable
rights to eternity, which the Fox Group did by buying the Dodgers.
If he bought a chunk of the team, it would come with a continued
cable deal. The talks never yielded a sale. But if there exists a
price that would make Steinbrenner bite, it has risen thanks to the
successful juggernaut the Yankees have been through 105 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
