<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SQUANDER 4-RUN LEAD, LOSE TO DODGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Piazza turned jeers to cheers against his former
team with a run-scoring single and a two-run home run for the Mets
Monday night at Shea Stadium. But there was no stopping the boos
directed at Greg McMichael when he pitched in relief for the Mets
against his former team. McMichael allowed five unearned runs and
two home runs in just two-thirds of an inning, as the Mets blew a
four-run lead to the Dodgers and suffered a crushing 8-5 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was especially demoralizing because the Mets (58-51)
looked as if they were going to pull within two games of the
Chicago Cubs in the National League wild-card race with what would
have been their 11th victory in the last 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   But then McMichael (2-4) came on in relief for Hideo Nomo _ the
pitcher he was originally traded from the Mets to the Dodgers for _
to begin the seventh inning. And the right-hander could not hold a
5-2 lead, as Raul Mondesi and Eric Karros each belted long home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Jim Eisenreich began the Dodgers' rally with a
one-out single to left. Eric Young followed with a grounder to
short, but Rey Ordonez was charged with a throwing error as the
shortstop and second baseman Carlos Baerga were trying to turn an
inning-ending double play. Ordonez appeared to throw the ball too
hard, and it shot past Baerga's glove and into right center field.
Eisenreich took third on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after Mark Grudzielanek hit a lazy fly to Todd Hundley in
left, McMichael _ who was traded back to New York for Brian Bohanon
_ allowed a three-run home run to Mondesi and a two-run shot to
Karros, both with two out.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, the Mets were down two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's homer, his second of the game and 25th this season,
bounced off the top of the fence in center field, off the speakers
in back, and back onto the field to tie the game at 5-5. Karros'
shot to deep left center followed a single by Gary Sheffield and
gave Los Angeles a 7-5 lead, its first of the game. After McMichael
surrendered a two-out double to the next batter, Roger Cedeno, the
once and current Met, was all but booed off the field.
</P>
<P>
   It was a passion usually reserved for Piazza of late.
</P>
<P>
   But not Monday night, after Piazza had two hits in his first
three times up and three runs batted in. There were also plenty of
cheers for Nomo, who went six strong innings, allowing three hits,
two runs, two walks and striking out six. He looked like a lock to
win his fourth consecutive start.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' defense _ so steady most of the season _ was
shaky, committing three errors.
</P>
<P>
   The misplays hurt Nomo most in the sixth. He allowed a one-out
solo home run to Mondesi and had to work overtime in the inning
just to leave with a 5-2 lead. A two-out third strike to Karros
skipped past Piazza for a wild pitch and enabled Karros to take
first base. Cedeno then reached on an error by Baerga, before Nomo
retired Adrian Beltre on an easy comebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it looked as if the Mets were on their way to an easy
victory. Tony Phillips doubled to lead off the first and Edgardo
Alfonzo walked before Piazza and Brian McRae delivered run-scoring
singles off Dave Mlicki, the pitcher traded to Los Angeles with
McMichael on June 4 for Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   And then, after the Dodgers had clawed back for a run in the
third on a two-out, run-scoring single by Grudzielanek to make it
2-1, Nomo singled home a run off Mlicki in the fourth, and then
Piazza drilled his 19th homer of the season in the fifth for a 5-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   But McMichael and the Mets let it all slip away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
