<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BURNEY-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEROY BURNEY, FORMER SURGEON GENERAL, DIES AT 91 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind., Ohio, Ga., Pa.)  (lb) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Leroy Burney, who as surgeon general of the U.S. Public
Health Service in the Eisenhower administration was the first
federal official publicly to identify smoking as a cause of lung
cancer, died Friday at a hospital in Park Ridge, Ill. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   On July 12, 1957, after organizing a group of scientists to
appraise 18 studies on smoking and health, Burney, himself a
smoker, issued a report saying, ``It is clear that there is an
increasing and consistent body of evidence that excessive cigarette
smoking is one of the causative factors in lung cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scientific Advisory Board to the Tobacco Industry Research
Committee immediately rebutted Burney's statement, saying that it
``adds nothing new to what has been known about the cause of lung
cancer'' and reflected the opinions of a small number of
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the evidence against smoking was mounting.
</P>
<P>
   Burney's first statement, and a stronger one in 1959, paved the
way for Luther Terry, surgeon general under President Lyndon
Johnson, to issue a landmark report on smoking and health in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Burney was not the first surgeon general to discuss the hazards
of smoking. Last year, in the journal Public Health Reports, Dr.
John Parasandola, the Public Health Service's historian, wrote that
in 1929, Surgeon General Hugh Cumming ``warned that smoking could
lower the `physical tone' of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Journal of the American Medical Association in 1959,
Burney expanded on the link between smoking and lung cancer, now
saying smoking was ``the principal'' causative factor in lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the use of tobacco can be made safe, the individual
person's risk of lung cancer can best be reduced by the elimination
of smoking,'' he wrote, adding ``stopping cigarette smoking even
after long exposure is beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   But the American Medical Association, which for years had
investments in tobacco, said in an editorial in 1959 that there was
insufficient evidence ``to warrant the assumption'' that smoking
was the principal factor in the increase in lung cancer. ``A number
of authorities who have examined the same evidence cited by Burney
do not agree with his conclusions,'' the Journal's editor, Dr. John
Talbott, wrote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Leroy Edgar Burney was born on Dec. 31, 1906 in Burney, Ind.,
then a town of 300 that had been founded by his great-grandfather,
William Burney.
</P>
<P>
   After attending Butler University in Indianapolis for two years,
Leroy Burney received a bachelor's degree in 1928 and a medical
degree in 1930 from Indiana University. After an internship at the
U.S. Marine Hospital in Chicago, he earned a degree in public
health from Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   Burney joined the Public Health Service in 1932, starting at its
Marine Hospital in Cleveland. In 1937 he set up the country's first
mobile venereal disease clinic, in Brunswick, Ga. At the time, he
wrote that effective control programs had been created for white
people in Northern states but ``no such programs for the Negro was
in progress in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Burney helped control sexually transmitted diseases for the Navy
during World War II. From 1945 to 1954 he was Indiana state health
officer. In 1956, he became the eighth surgeon general of the U.S.
Public Health Service, replacing Dr. Leonard Scheele, who resigned
after a number of children developed polio from being injected with
Salk vaccine because of a manufacturing problem.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Burney approved the Sabin oral polio vaccine for use in
the United States after the vaccine had been used on millions of
people in South America and the Soviet Union. Burney defended the
long delay in endorsing the vaccine by saying that he had ``no
apologies to make for conservatism, which is justified in an issue
as important as this.''
</P>
<P>
   As surgeon general, Burney worked to improve health care for the
elderly, particularly in nursing homes. Concerned about the
indiscriminate use of X-rays in health care, Burney set up a
division to unify radiation-related activities in the Public Health
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Burney also championed improving environmental health and
cleaning up pollution. He helped create the National Library of
Medicine, the National Center for Health Statistics and a national
influenza-surveillance system at the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The day before leaving the White House in 1961, Eisenhower wrote
Burney, praising his efforts to control air pollution, raise the
quality of water and improve health internationally. A week later,
Burney retired as surgeon general and became vice president for
health sciences at Temple University in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, at a meeting of former surgeons general of the U.S.
Public Health Service, Burney spoke about the effects of managed
care on the health care of Americans and said the patient often was
losing out. ``Some people, particularly the elderly, need the
warmth and friendliness of a personal physician's touch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, the former Mildred Hewins; a son,
Robert, of Washington; a daughter, Kay Butler of Lake Forest, Ill.;
five grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
