<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-TECH-NCAA-HNS &LR;      08-03 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TECH-NCAA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NCAA verdict 
regarding Tech 
due out today
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DANNY ROBBINS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LUBBOCK _ The NCAA report on the Texas Tech infractions case, more
than 90 days in the making, is in the hands of university officials
and will become public today.
</P>
<P>
   The report, prepared by the NCAA's Division I Committee on
Infractions, will be released to the media at 9 a.m., according to
an NCAA news release. Two hours later, Bonnie Slatton, the
committee's acting chairperson, will discuss the document via
conference call, the release said.
</P>
<P>
   Slatton, who chairs the University of Iowa's Department of
Physical Education and Sports Studies, led the committee during the
Tech case in the absence of the panel's chairman, David Swank, a
law professor at the University of Oklahoma. Swank recused himself
as a result of his ties to the Big 12 Conference. The committee has
eight members, all but two affiliated with NCAA schools or
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Tech chancellor John Montford said the university received a
copy of the committee's report late Monday afternoon. Citing NCAA
policy, he said he could not comment on the document until it is
released publicly. He said Tech likely would issue a written
statement after Slatton's news conference and would not hold a
formal news conference of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The report will mark the end of a waiting game that began when
Tech officials spent two days in front of the panel during its
April meeting in Cleveland. The committee's job is to determine the
validity of allegations turned up in NCAA investigations and, if
necessary, assess penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Tech has acknowledged several rules violations stemming from
university audits and a lengthy NCAA investigation and instituted a
series of self-imposed penalties, including scholarship reductions
and forfeitures. The committee's report will state how the panel
ruled on those matters in which Tech and NCAA enforcement personnel
were at odds and whether more sanctions are warranted.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA enforcement staff initiated a preliminary inquiry of
the Tech athletic program in February 1996. The inquiry focused on
issues relating to football and men's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Questions regarding how Tech basketball players Gracen Averil
and Deuce Jones were certified as eligible for the 1996-97 season
prompted Tech to conduct an audit of its eligibility-certification
procedures. The audit determined that 76 athletes in eight sports,
including football and men's basketball, had been improperly
certified as eligible from 1991-92 through 1996-97 as a result of
administrative errors. Further checking by Tech increased the total
to 81.
</P>
<P>
   Another Tech audit found that a misunderstanding of NCAA rules
had caused the university to award improper financial aid to
athletes in baseball and other sports.
</P>
<P>
   A letter of official inquiry prepared by the NCAA enforcement
staff and submitted to Tech last October included the two matters
detailed in the university audits as well as 16 areas of alleged
wrongdoing developed by enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
   In its response to the letter, Tech acknowledged that several of
the NCAA's allegations were correct. The university agreed with the
charge that it lacked institutional control in the operation of its
athletic program. It also acknowledged that former Tech assistant
football coach Rhudy Maskew likely engaged in academic fraud in his
efforts to help ex-defensive lineman Stephen Gaines obtain
correspondence-course credit from Southeastern College of the
Assemblies of God in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Among the charges disputed by Tech were two stating that the
university's longtime faculty athletics representative, Robert
Sweazy, and other personnel were negligent in investigating
potential rules violations. A particularly thorny issue involves
former receiver Malcolm McKenzie, who, enforcement personnel
allege, was allowed to continue playing after Tech officials had
reason to believe he had been improperly readmitted to the
university in the fall of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Tech removed its football team from bowl consideration last fall
after receiving the letter of official inquiry and added a series
of other penalties in April. Those penalties included three years'
probation, scholarship cuts in six sports, and the forfeiture of
all games in which ineligible athletes participated.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Tech's self-imposed penalties, the Red Raiders
football program gave up eight initial scholarships this year and
will lose six in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the infractions committee has chosen to do little
more than rubber-stamp schools' own actions. In the Baylor
University basketball case in 1995, the committee went a step
further and gave the school permission to lighten its self-imposed
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Other schools have not been so fortunate, however. The
University of Miami, facing charges of doling out impermissible
financial aid and other administrative-related impropriety, went
before the committee in 1995 having stripped itself of seven
football scholarships for one year and was handed a punishment that
included a bowl ban and the loss of 24 additional scholarships over
a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Tech can accept the committee's report as the final word in the
case or appeal any element of it to the NCAA Infractions Appeals
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Should the university accept the report without appeal, it will
mark the end of an investigation that began three years ago when
Tech became enmeshed in the national scandal that emerged after
Baylor basketball coaches were found to have helped four recruits
receive phony correspondence-course credit from Southeastern
College.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other schools have received institutional penalties from
the NCAA for various infractions relating to basketball players
having obtained credit for correspondence courses offered by the
Lakeland, Fla., Bible college. A finding of academic fraud in the
Gaines case would make Tech's football program the first tied to
wrongdoing involving Southeastern College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
