<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6381 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-U.S.-SPAIN-HNS &LR;      08-03 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-U.S.-SPAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
U.S. solidifies under fire
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans come from behind to knock off Spain
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ It looked for the longest time like a classic
case of the Americans getting sandbagged.
</P>
<P>
   The same opponent they had hammered by 17 points in a
meaningless exhibition two weeks ago was about to rub out the U.S.
squad in a game that not only meant something, but would go a long
way toward deciding the Americans' ultimate fate in the FIBA World
Championship of Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when they needed it most, the shots started to fall, the
defense made a critical stand and Rudy Tomjanovich's team found
itself pulling off a pulsating 75-73 win over Spain on Monday at
Olympic Stadium. It was one of many strange twists on a day that
left the World Championship with no undefeated teams and no clear
favorite for the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   This, it would seem, is exactly what the tournament should be
like with the ``Dream Team'' of NBA players absent. Six teams have
only one loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That says it right there,'' said Jimmy King, who came off the
bench to help the Americans overcome an 11-point second-half
deficit. ``That's how competitive this tournament is. We didn't
come out here and expect to blow anybody away.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is going to be work. We can't expect to come out here
and breeze through any game. We have to work at it. To me that's
the fun part. They're giving us great competition out here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Americans learned a long time ago they don't necessarily
qualify as favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is unbeatable in this tournament,'' said Jimmy Oliver,
who had 17 points, including a 3-pointer with 1:18 to play that put
the U.S. ahead for good at 72-71. ``Everybody has their Dream Team
here, even though we don't have our NBA players here. Anybody can
be beat. You just can't expect to go out and win every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we lost, some people probably think they're the
favorites. I still say we're the favorites. So we got to play like
we're favorites. We got to go out and work for everything. We got
to be a working-class team. We're not all highly paid individuals
who can go out and expect something to come to us. We got to go out
and take what's ours. And I think this gold medal should be ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But they have a lot of ground to cover between now and
Sunday, when the medals will be decided.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Americans is that they are assured of
making the quarterfinals. Even a loss tonight to Australia wouldn't
knock them out of medal contention.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that they could finish anywhere from first to
fourth in the six-team Group F when the second round is completed
today. Obviously, the higher they finish, the lower-seeded team
they will see from Group E when the quarterfinals are played
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In other action Monday, Italy upset Yugoslavia 61-60 to throw
Group E into a frenzy. With Greece losing to Russia, three teams
are 4-1 in Group E (Yugoslavia, Greece and Russia). Italy is 3-2
and Puerto Rico is 2-3. Canada already has been eliminated at 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   In Group F, Lithuania beat Brazil and Australia outlasted
Argentina. That left the U.S., Lithuania and Spain at 4-1, with
Australia 3-2 and Argentina 2-3. Brazil already has been eliminated
at 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday, the Americans simply are glad to be 4-1. They were
getting manhandled much of the way by Spain and it took a defensive
twist, along with better teamwork offensively, to get them back in
the game after trailing every step of the way until Oliver's
3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the 95-78 whipping the U.S. put on the
Spaniards on July 19 in Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches told us that was because their main guys only
played about 10 minutes when we saw them in Monaco,'' King said.
``So that wasn't really their true team.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously. The Americans had to prove they could win a game
under pressure and, after faltering in the late moments against
Lithuania last week, they came through this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great, character win for us,'' Tomjanovich said.
``I can't tell you how disappointed I was in this team in the first
half. We were not a team. All the work we had put in, I told our
guys we could get five guys off the street and played about the
same kind of game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope a really big lesson was learned about the team concept.
It would have been ugly if we had continued to play like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we made a defensive adjustment that took a
lot of communication. And offensively, we started sharing the ball.
Kiwane Garris came in and made some big shots and we put him on
their star player and he did a good job of staying in front of him,
even though he was giving up some inches.''
</P>
<P>
   Garris was giving away four inches to Alberto Herreros, Spain's
top player who finished with 27 points. But Garris pushed Herreros
to his left and got help from his teammates down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to make an adjustment because they were shooting the
ball so well,'' King said. ``We decided to trap the guy with the
ball and make him make the decisions. We had to do something
because we didn't play any defense, really, in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trailed 69-64 with three minutes to play before Brad
Miller (12 points) got loose for a dunk. After a Spain turnover,
Wendell Alexis hit a 3-pointer to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Herreros and Ignacio de Miguel each missed one of two free
throws. That set up Oliver's trey.
</P>
<P>
   Free throws by both teams made it 75-73 with 10 seconds left,
giving Spain time to tie or win the game. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But when Ignacio Rodriguez and Jose Paraiso missed just before
the buzzer, the Americans had won a game in spite of only leading
for two of the 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they were the right minutes,'' Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Miller: ``We got a chance to get the No. 1 seed now, which
is important because the four teams that will come out of the other
bracket are all real good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
